<HEADLINE>
FORBES BATTLING IN LONG ISLAND; FIRST LADY WINS EASILY 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photos NYT11, 12, 17 and 27 are being sent to photo
clients. Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JONATHAN P. HICKS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Attacked from all sides, Congressman Michael Forbes,
a Republican-turned Democrat from Long Island, was locked in a
dead-even struggle with his primary challenger on Tuesday night and
was one of the few incumbents in the state who had not prevailed in
congressional and legislative contests that were unusually marked
by rancor.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes acknowledged on Tuesday night that his race against
Regina Seltzer, 71, was too close to call. With Republicans
clinging to a narrow majority in the House, both national and state
party officials had channeled money and advertising into the
district early on, to sway even Democrats to vote against the man
who infuriated the GOP by switching his party affiliation in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   This primary election also featured for the first time the name
of a first lady on the ballot for an elective office, with Hillary
Rodham Clinton easily winning the Democratic nomination for the
U.S. Senate against Mark McMahon, a little known Manhattan
orthopedic surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   With 76 percent of the vote counted, Clinton received 80 percent
of the vote, with McMahon receiving 20 percent. Aides to Clinton's
Republican opponent, Rep. Rick Lazio, had forecast that Clinton
would be viewed as a particularly weak contender for the November
general election if her opponent in the Democratic primary received
30 percent of the vote. Still, the 20-percent showing indicated
that Clinton must contend with a group of voters, even Democrats,
who carry a strong dislike for her.
</P>
<P>
   Primary day began in Chappaqua with votes by Mrs. Clinton and
her husband in their new hometown of Chappaqua, N.Y. The two
arrived at 7:15 a.m. to a waiting throng of photographers and
reporters to cast their votes in the sole voting booth in the
school's lobby.
</P>
<P>
   After signing photographs and shaking hands with residents
outside the school lobby, Mrs. Clinton went into the aqua blue
booth first, followed by her husband. Asked afterward how it felt
to see Mrs. Clinton on the ballot for the first time, President
Clinton said, ``It was a thrill. After all these years of her
helping me, it was a thrill. I loved it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton was more demure, saying only that it felt ``great''
to vote for herself. But later, talking to reporters at a nearby
delicatessen, she elaborated somewhat on the occasion. ``I stood
there for a minute,'' she said, ``staring at my name.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
