<HEADLINE>
MOST N.Y. INCUMBENT DEMOCRATS DEFEAT PRIMARY CHALLENGERS
</HEADLINE>
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Several New York lawmakers fended off challenges in
the Democratic primary on Tuesday, once again demonstrating that
when it comes to elections, the state Legislature is usually an
incumbent's paradise. But there were a few exceptions, notably an
East Harlem assemblyman who was defeated by a former councilman,
Adam Clayton Powell IV, a son of one of the most famous politicians
in city history.
</P>
<P>
   Powell, making a comeback after an unsuccessful run for borough
president in 1997, ousted a two-term assemblyman, Nelson Antonio
Denis. Powell charged during the campaign that Denis was neglecting
the district, while Denis retorted that Powell's candidacy was
based solely on his name recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Denis backed an attempt this year to overthrow the Assembly
speaker, Sheldon Silver of Manhattan, and Silver exacted revenge in
the primary, refusing to give Denis the financial or organizational
support that incumbents typically receive from the speaker.
</P>
<P>
   In Buffalo, the longest serving Assembly member, Arthur O. Eve,
was locked in a tight race with Crystal D. Peoples, majority leader
of the Erie County legislature. An incumbent in the Bronx, Edward
Griffith, was also in a close contest, against Diane Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   In the state Senate, in a continuing feud between Bronx party
leaders and the Espada family, a former state senator, Pedro G.
Espada, appeared to be headed for a victory over the incumbent,
David Rosado. Rosado defeated Espada in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Most other Democratic incumbents facing tough challenges
survived easily. Among the Assembly members who won _ tantamount to
retaining the seat in overwhelmingly Democratic districts _ were
Clarence Norman Jr., Roger Green and Darryl C. Towns of Brooklyn;
and Catherine Nolan and Pauline Rhodd-Cummings of Queens. In the
Senate, Olga A. Mendez of Manhattan kept her seat.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, many incumbents did not face primary challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, a Republican, and former Mayor Edward
Koch, a Democrat, had sought to rally support against some
Democratic incumbents in New York City, particularly Nolan, because
they voted to repeal the income tax on commuters last year, but
those appeals appeared to have had little impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of charges hurled my way, but in the end, my
neighbors felt that I was the person who served them and worked
hard,'' said Nolan, who handily turned aside a challenge from
Patrick T. O'Malley, a former Queens prosecutor whose brother,
Martin, is the mayor of Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Incumbents in Albany have long maintained an iron grip on their
seats, in large part because they have name recognition, the
support of party committees, the authority to dole out projects and
the ability to raise political money from contributors with an
interest in legislation. Most turnover in the Legislature stems
from open seats.
</P>
<P>
   In one such open Assembly district in Astoria, Queens, Michael
N. Gianaris, a counsel for the Democratic majority in the Assembly,
was leading in early returns against Kimon C. Thermos, a lawyer who
had unsuccessfully sought the seat previously. Both men were vying
to become the first Greek-American Assembly member from New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   On Staten Island, John W. Lavelle, the county party chairman,
who had pledged not to seek elected office and then changed his
mind, was in a close race against Raymond G. Jorgensen for seat
held by Assemblywoman Elizabeth A. Connelly, who is retiring.
</P>
<P>
   Liz Krueger easily won a Democratic Senate primary on the Upper
East Side, seeking to dislodge the longtime Republican incumbent,
Roy M. Goodman. Krueger, on leave from the Community Food Resource
Center, defeated Robert J. Bellinson, a lawyer who has run against
Mr. Goodman in the last two elections.
</P>
<P>
   In another contest to take on a longtime Republican senator,
Lorraine Coyle Koppell, a lawyer who is the wife of a former state
attorney general, beat Michael R. Benedetto, a public elementary
school teacher who is a Bronx Democratic district leader.
</P>
<P>
   And in a Brooklyn Republican primary, former State Sen. Robert
J. Dicarlo narrowly defeated Charles Capetanakis for the right to
take on the incumbent Democrat, Vincent Gentile.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
