 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Young quarterbacks take over in NFL
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN McCLAIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
When it comes to playing quarterback in the NFL, youth is being
served.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as five years ago, the NFL was in a panic over a
shortage of young, talented prospects at quarterback. Fifteen of
the 30 teams employed starters who were at least 30 years old.
</P>
<P>
   After a youth movement at one of the highest-profile positions
in pro sports, 11 teams have starting quarterbacks who are 25 years
old or younger. Only eight starters have turned 30.
</P>
<P>
   With such star QBs as John Elway, Dan Marino, Jim Kelly and
Steve Young, who combined to start 13 Super Bowls, leaving the
game, it was out with the old and in with the new.
</P>
<P>
   The youth movement began in 1998 when Peyton Manning (Colts) and
Ryan Leaf (Chargers) were the first two picks in the NFL draft.
Charlie Batch (Lions) and Brian Griese (Broncos) were selected in
the second and third rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, six quarterbacks were drafted in the first two
rounds, including five No. 1 picks.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Couch (Browns), Donovan McNabb (Eagles) and Akili Smith
(Bengals) were the first three picks. Daunte Culpepper (Vikings)
and Cade McNown (Bears) were the 11th and 12th picks in the first
round. But the only second-rounder, Tampa Bay's Shaun King, has
been the most successful. As a rookie, he was forced into the
lineup when Trent Dilfer was injured, and he has a 7-2 record as a
starter, including 1-1 in last season's playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   This season, Culpepper and King are the only starters from that
group who are 2-0. Couch and McNabb are 1-1. Smith is 0-1 and
McNown is 0-2.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Buccaneers have such a dominant defense, they play a
conservative offensive style, which takes pressure off King.
Although the offense gets a lot of criticism in the Tampa-St.
Petersburg area, King is the only one of the six quarterbacks not
to throw an interception this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``All Shaun does is win,'' says Bucs receiver Keyshawn Johnson,
who was acquired in a trade with the Jets in the offseason. ``I
don't know what the big deal is. He's the guy. He was the guy for
seven or eight games last year, so what's the big deal?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a quarterback. He's going to throw the ball. I'm going to
catch it. And other guys are going to catch it.''
</P>
<P>
   Add Jake Plummer (Cardinals), a second-round pick in 1997, to
that group of starting quarterbacks drafted in 1998 and 1999, and
the list of 11 who are 25 or younger is complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you're seeing a lot of teams go with younger guys more
than usual,'' Buccaneers coach Tony Dungy says. ``Usually, you like
to let a guy learn for a few seasons, but it seems like more and
more we're going with the younger guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL hopes 1999 will be remembered as the ``Year of the
Quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, this quarterbacks class will be talked about
throughout the history of the game,'' Culpepper says. ``Hopefully,
we'll go out and consistently show what we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   The class of '99 will have to lead its teams to Super Bowls and
set NFL records in the process before it can supplant 1983 as the
``Year of the Quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway (Broncos), Marino (Dolphins), Kelly (Bills), Tony Eason
(Patriots), Ken O'Brien (Jets) and Todd Blackledge (Chiefs) were
first-round picks. Only O'Brien and Blackledge failed to lead their
team to a Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Of the six quarterbacks drafted in the first two rounds of 1999,
four are black _ McNabb, Smith, Culpepper and King. It was the
first time three black quarterbacks went in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a natural progression because there are so many more
black quarterbacks starting on college teams,'' says Kansas City's
Warren Moon, a 17-year NFL veteran who turns 44 on Monday.
``Because defenses are devising so many ways to put pressure on the
quarterback, you need as much athleticism at the position as you
can get.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these young guys are doubly dangerous because they
can throw and run. There's such a demand for young quarterbacks who
can do both.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the six quarterbacks drafted in the first two rounds of 1999,
only Culpepper didn't throw a pass. He watched and learned behind
veterans Jeff George and Randall Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   At this early junction of their careers, if there is a common
characteristic it's that all but Couch and King are exceptional
runners.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening game of the season, McNown rushed for 87 yards.
Last season, only Cincinnati's Jeff Blake (99) rushed for more in a
game.
</P>
<P>
   In two games, McNown has 136 yards rushing. Culpepper has rushed
for 110 yards and scored three touchdowns. McNabb has run for two
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the new breed of athlete,'' Minnesota coach Dennis
Green says. ``They're very talented players. They have young legs,
and they have a lot of courage.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other offensive coordinators, Minnesota's Sherman Lewis is
trying to take advantage of Culpepper's running ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``It adds a different dimension to the offense,'' Lewis says.
``It keeps the chains moving and keeps you on the field. You can't
coach that.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
