<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-MELBOURNE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
U.S. track stars recall special '56 Olympics
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By DAVID BARRON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SYDNEY, Australia _ As the athletes prepared for the 1956 Olympics
in Melbourne, legend has it the chefs at the Soviet Union's
fenced-off enclave within the Olympic Village baked 24 giant
victory cakes _ one for each men's track and field event.
</P>
<P>
   When an unnamed U.S. athlete heard about the bakefest, the story
goes, he snapped, ``Let them eat bread.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the Soviets ended up eating crow.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Soviet Union won the overall medal count for the
'56 Games, which in those Cold War days was a major source of
propaganda points, the U.S. men's track team won its private war
against the Soviets _ and everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. men won 15 of 24 gold medals in Melbourne, including
four 1-2-3 sweeps, and 28 of 72 total medals. It was, quite simply,
one of the most dominant performances by any team in the history of
the modern Games.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. champions included a lanky Texan named Bobby Joe Morrow,
who won the 100 and 200 meters and anchored the 400-meter relay;
Bob Richards, whose second gold medal in the pole vault launched
his career as the longtime pitchman for Wheaties; Al Oerter, who at
19 won the first of what would become four consecutive golds in the
discus; and Harold Connolly, who won not only the hammer but the
heart of Czech discus champion Olga Fikotova.
</P>
<P>
   Oerter returns this week to Sydney, where the Olympics return to
Australia after a 44-year absence. Morrow will watch on television
from his home in San Benito and Richards from his home near Waco.
Theirs was the last Olympics not to appear on television in the
United States, but the memories remain in widescreen,
high-definition, crystal clarity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Melbourne was the greatest Olympics ever,'' Richards said.
``There were 150,000 people there every day, filling every seat and
every standing-room position. The roars were incredible. The
Australians were the most devoted fans of the Olympics ever. I'll
never forget the Closing Ceremony and the entire crowd singing
Waltzing Matilda. It was just fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Melbourne Games remain in legend as the
``Friendly Games,'' they unfolded at a time of geopolitical
tension. The Soviets had just smashed the Hungarian revolution, and
the athletes from both countries were not immune to bitter
feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a 19-year-old kid when I made that team, and what did I
know about international politics?'' Oerter said. ``But I remember
two Soviet athletes and two Hungarian athletes approaching one
another on the sidewalk, and you had to watch to see who was going
to move. The Hungarians moved aside, but not before one of them
spit on the ground in the Russians' path.''
</P>
<P>
   But that was the exception. Oerter remembers the relaxed,
friendly atmosphere throughout most of the Olympic Village and the
excitement that built as the U.S. team exerted its dominance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were living in Air Force barracks, and as the athletes
finished their events and started coming back with medals, you got
to experience their feeling about what they had just done,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   A native of West Babylon, N.Y., Oerter never had heard of the
Olympic trials until his coach at the University of Kansas signed
him up in 1956. He made the team and set an Olympic record of 184
feet, 11 inches with his first throw at Melbourne, beating
world-record holder Fortune Gordien for the gold. Desmond Koch was
third, completing the U.S. sweep.
</P>
<P>
   Richards came to Melbourne as the defending champion in the pole
vault and, in the preliminaries, nearly squandered his chance to
repeat. Running on a sore left Achilles' tendon and competing on a
windy day on a sandy approach track, he missed his first two jumps
at the qualifying height of 13 feet, 1{ inches and was on the verge
of fouling out of the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my own stupidity,'' he said. ``Back in those days, you
would put your pole up against the crossbar to measure it. But on
the low heights, I figured I could just fly over it and I didn't
bother. But what I didn't know is that they had moved the crossbar
forward, and twice I hit the bar going up.''
</P>
<P>
   He probably would have missed a third time but for a tip from
teammate Bob Gutowski, who pointed out Richards' miscalculation of
where the standard had been placed. Richards went on to qualify
with ease.
</P>
<P>
   Richards and Gutowski cleared 14-10\ in the finals, but Gutowski
suffered a pulled stomach muscle and was unable to go higher.
Richards cleared 14-11{ to set an Olympic record and win the gold _
and therein lies a story.
</P>
<P>
   Vaulting on the aforementioned sandy runway into the
aforementioned wind, Richards hit the crossbar on the way down and
lay poised in the pit for more than 30 seconds as the crossbar hung
on the edge of the standards before finally slipping back.
</P>
<P>
   Legend has it Richards, a deeply religious man who was known as
the ``Vaulting Vicar,'' tented his hands in prayer as the crossbar
hung on the edge. Richards said, it wasn't quite that dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did look up and point to the bar, but it wasn't a prayer,''
he said. ``It was more like, `Oh, Lordy, is that thing going to
fall off?''' Richards said. ``I can see how people thought it was a
prayer, but it wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Richards went on to work 13 years as the spokesman for Wheaties,
making dozens of commercials, thousands of personal appearances and
hundreds of television appearances.
</P>
<P>
   And none of it would have happened but for Gutowski's help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the story of John Landy, the great Australian
runner who broke the four-minute-mile barrier after Roger
Bannister,'' Richards said. ``In one race, Landy was on the way to
a world record when he lapped a high school boy who fell down as
Landy was going into the closing curve.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stopped and picked up the boy, whose name was Ron Clarke
(who went on to set more than 20 world records as a long-distance
runner). Everybody criticized Landy and said he didn't have the
killer instinct, but he said, `I would stop every time to pick up a
fallen runner. Records don't mean that much to me.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I've thought about that a lot and about the way that Bob
helped me.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years after setting the world record in 1957, Gutowski was
killed in an auto accident. He was 25 years old.
</P>
<P>
   If Richards' 1956 story was of friendship, Connolly's was of a
romance that breached the Iron Curtain. His romance with Fikotova
culminated in their wedding before a crowd of 40,000 at a civil
ceremony in Prague.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of the U.S. gold haul in Melbourne, at the top of
the heap was Morrow, the sprinter from San Benito by way of Abilene
Christian College who kicked up a cloud of red dust on the brick
cinder track en route to victories in both sprints plus the relays.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had just built the track right before the Games and it
was loose. It was like running on loose dirt,'' he said. ``Of
course, I grew up running on dirt tracks. They even had one when I
went to Abilene Christian in 1954. I was used to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as they remember the greatness of the 1956 team, thoughts
of friends and colleagues share time with the warmth of the
Australian fans _ memories the 2000 U.S. team no doubt will share
when they look back on the Games of Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just love the people there,'' Morrow said. ``They're so
sports-minded and such great supporters of the athletes and the
Games. It's a great place to visit and a great place to compete.
They really love it there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an absolutely superb place,'' Oerter said. ``I don't see
how they can keep from having great Games there. The people are so
open, so gregarious, slap you on the side of the shoulder _ they're
warm, wonderful people, and that will come through.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
