<SLUG> BC-OLY--DREAM </SLUG>
 TEAM-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Column: Whole world to see Carter's coronation
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By FRAN BLINEBURY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Alonzo Mourning throws around praise and
compliments like they're manhole covers. So when he starts to gush
more than an open fire hydrant, you tend to sit up and take notice
of his subject.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you can't help but notice Vince Carter anyway.
</P>
<P>
   As the Dream Team barnstormed its way across the Pacific en
route to Down Under, dancing on heads all the way, Carter was doing
the fanciest steps.
</P>
<P>
   He has caught lob passes from Jason Kidd and slick
behind-the-back shuffles from Gary Payton for rim-rattling slam
dunks. He has filled the lanes on the fast break with Kevin Garnett
in what looks like a greyhound race. He has dropped in 3-pointers
right in the faces of defenders and he has dropped jaws in the
stands from Hawaii to Tokyo to Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
   If the novelty of the Dream Team as conquering heroes in the
Olympics has worn off, Carter's exploits have given us a reason to
watch again.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are, by the time the Games are over, Carter's reputation
and fame will have taken a kangaroo's leap from North America to
every basketball-playing country on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   But more than provide footage for the nightly highlight reels,
what Carter has done with his efforts every day in practice is to
give even his hard-to-impress U.S. teammates reason to make bold
comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   Step aside, M.J.
</P>
<P>
   You know the one: Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the second coming,'' said the normally tactiturn
Mourning. ``I played against M.J. for a lot of years. I've seen
M.J. at his best. I watched him and tried to stop him throughout
his career. What I'm telling you now might sound crazy or
outrageous. But Vince Carter probably has more talent, more natural
ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``M.J. definitely didn't jump as high as this guy, even in his
younger days. The things I've seen him do over the last few weeks,
this is the one that everybody has been waiting for to take the
game to the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   Kidd has been relishing each trip down the floor on the fast
break with Carter, throwing passes that even he doesn't know are
catchable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like playing Frisbee with one of those trained dogs,''
Kidd said. ``You just throw it up there high and see if Vince can
go get it. For a point guard like me, this is the most fun you can
have on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Going into the preliminary round of the Olympics, Carter leads
the team in scoring and plays that make even the coaching staff and
his peers stop to shake their heads.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that not only wasn't he an original selection for
Dream Team 2000, but Carter was not even the first alternate chosen
when Tom Gugliotta was injured and scratched from the lineup. The
nine-man selection committee went for Ray Allen by a 6-3 margin.
</P>
<P>
   Carter didn't get the call until just a few months ago when
Grant Hill opted out of Sydney duty to get married. Now Carter is
on the verge of burning brighter than the Olympic flame. He's
making most of the big plays and setting the tone, getting involved
in the early scuffle with Australia's flag-bearer Andrew Gaze on
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The question is how far can he take it on the NBA stage?
</P>
<P>
   A jury of his peers
</P>
<P>
   What separates Carter from Jordan in full bloom is, of course,
those six NBA championships. But if you're going to make the
comparison, the only fair way is to go back to Jordan's early years
when he was still learning what it took to go from merely a scoring
machine to becoming a hungry, relentless predator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael was a better defender, no question,'' Mourning said.
``That is an area that I think you learn about as you get a few
years under your belt. It's the work ethic that M.J. had that kept
him improving and eventually made him the player he was.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I see all of the other similarities and I think there are
a lot of things that at this stage in his career, Vince can do
better than Michael. He can elevate and maybe shoot better. He can
get up and down the floor like nobody I've ever seen and he can go
straight up and make a play from a situation that doesn't look like
it exists.
</P>
<P>
   ``His talent and ability are electrifying. You can't stop him.
You just can't.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the kind of comparison that would be regarded as hyperbole
if it came from anyone other than these teammates.
</P>
<P>
   They are, after all, among the best in the game and have watched
Carter up close now long enough to make valid judgments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can sit here and say I have seen the second coming,''
Mourning said. ``When M.J. retired, I really didn't think I'd see
another one like him in my lifetime. But I have now. Vince is it.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time they hand out the gold medals, the whole world will
know it.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
