<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1526 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-PREDATOR-AZR &LR;      09-13 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PREDATOR-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-PREDATOR-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    PANEL SHOOTS DOWN BAN ON HUNT CONTESTS(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By JUDD SLIVKA(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Phoenix) - A proposal to ban predator hunting contests was
shot, skinned, gutted and thrown out by a state panel Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   There will be no resurrection.
</P>
<P>
   The Governor's Regulatory Review Council not only tossed the
Game and Fish Commission's proposed ban on contests where hunters
compete to see who can kill the most nuisance creatures in a set
amount of time, it also questioned whether the commission had the
legal authority to manage wildlife in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The five-member commission is appointed by the governor with
confirmation from the Senate. It oversees the Game and Fish
Department, which does the actual wildlife management.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the meeting was over, Game and Fish employees were
shaking their heads, wondering what it all meant.
</P>
<P>
   After all, a poll paid for by a pro-ban group but conducted by a
firm used by the hunting industry said that nearly 70 percent of
Arizona residents are against the practice. The Game and Fish
proposal wouldn't have banned predator hunting, even among groups.
It merely would have banned contests, where people would pay to
compete and receive a prize at the end.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the council struck it down unanimously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you have to look at it as a process,'' said Deputy
Director Steve Farrell of the Game and Fish Department. ``This
process is done.''
</P>
<P>
   It had taken three hours and eight minutes. Twenty-four people
spoke against the proposal, only nine spoke in support.
</P>
<P>
   The council's decision, which was based, its members said, on
vague wording in the proposed rule as well as Game and Fish's lack
of specific authority from the Legislature to make the rule at all,
brought to light a greater threat.
</P>
<P>
   Will the Game and Fish Commission, charged with managing
wildlife in Arizona, be allowed to manage wildlife?
</P>
<P>
   Much of the council's recalcitrance came from an opinion issued
by its attorneys that the commission doesn't have the legal
standing to regulate wildlife contests in the state, especially
because the impact of predator contests is biologically minimal,
and thus, a social issue the commission doesn't have the power to
address.
</P>
<P>
   Game and Fish officials objected to the reasoning, arguing the
Legislature appointed the commission to act in its stead to manage
all wildlife in the state. The agency, its officials argued,
dictates when hunting seasons begin and end, what types of weapons
can be used in a hunt and has barred such things as people hunting
from cars, all ``social'' issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Arizona Game and Fish Commission has never said these
contests have a biological impact,'' Commissioner Joe Carter said.
``What it did say is that they have a tremendous, tremendous social
impact. No one doubts the authority of the commission to manage
wildlife in Arizona. Without the ability to manage social impacts
of wildlife, this commission's ability to manage wildlife at all
will be compromised.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter's words had no impact. And council Chairman Tim Boncoskey
ended the meeting with a reminder to Game and Fish:
</P>
<P>
   ``The public needs to know the rulemaking process does not end
with a commission or at the Attorney General's Office. That's why
we're here.''
</P>
<P>
   The predator-ban controversy has been around for several years,
and a similar proposed rule had gone before the review council in
February. That proposal also was thrown out as too vague. The new
version, with two words added to it in an effort to better define
what constitutes a coyote-hunting contest, was introduced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But far from clarifying the issue, it weakened the Game and Fish
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would vote to send it back to the commission with the
following advice,'' said council member Chuck Roach, who spent the
morning sparring with proponents of the ban, once leaving after an
angry exchange with a pro-ban biologist. ``Find another way of
doing it without an outright ban. And get clear and convincing
evidence from the Legislature, in the form of a legislative
initiative, that you have the power to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   The ban opponents whooped in celebration. The Game and Fish
staff left carrying hundreds of pages of papers and rules now made
worthless.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at judd.slivka(a)arizonarepublic.com or
(602) 444-8097.
</P>
