<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1528 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-BAYLOR-NEWHOUSE-H     09-13 1277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BAYLOR-NEWHOUSE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Baylor's Newhouse inherits father's work ethic
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By TERRY BLOUNT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WACO _ From the neck up, Reggie Newhouse looks a lot like his
famous father. From the neck down, the similarities end.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime University of Houston and Dallas Cowboys fans will
remember Robert Newhouse as a short and stocky running back with
thighs like tree trunks. He was a powerful and punishing runner,
and bringing him down was like trying to tackle a boulder rolling
downhill. Reggie, a 19-year-old sophomore receiver for Baylor,
doesn't fit that physical mold.
</P>
<P>
   If Robert was a bulldog on the field, Reggie is a gazelle. At
6-2, 195 pounds, Reggie is taller and leaner than his dad. Reggie
relies on his speed and cunning moves, whereas Robert relied on
strength and power.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I get my genetics from my mom's side,'' Reggie
Newhouse said. ``Her brothers are all in the 6-2, 6-3 range.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert and Reggie are much different physically, but Baylor
coach Kevin Steele said father and son are carbon copies in other
ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have the same disposition,'' Steele said. ``I've talked
to guys who were with the Cowboys when Robert was a player, and the
way they describe Robert really describes Reggie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reggie is tough. He doesn't miss practice, and he doesn't get
tired. Since two-a-days started, I guarantee you he's run from here
to El Paso and back, but he never says a word except `yes sir.'
Everyone tells me Robert was the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   For those too young to remember, Robert Newhouse was one of the
best players in UH history and went on to have an outstanding
12-year NFL career with the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   The Hallsville product left East Texas and played for the
Cougars from 1969-71. He ranks No. 2 behind Chuck Weatherspoon on
the all-time UH rushing list with 2,961 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Newhouse was a second-team All-America running back in 1971 when
he rushed for 1,757 yards, which was second in the nation that
season (Ed Marinaro of Cornell set an NCAA rushing record that
year) and the second-highest total in NCAA history at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Newhouse rushed for more than 100 yards 16 times, including 245
yards against Mississippi State as a sophomore. He was drafted in
1972 by Dallas in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've watched a lot of highlight films on him to see the things
he did,'' Reggie said. ``I would have been a big fan if I was
watching him play in those days.''
</P>
<P>
   Now an attorney, Robert Newhouse also works for the Cowboys in
player development. Steele thinks so much of Robert that he's had
him come to practice and speak to the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robert talks to them about patience and work ethic and being
coachable and teachable,'' Steele said. ``He tells them not to feel
like they have all the answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He tells them to go about their business and good things will
happen. And his son lives that way. That's the way he raised him,
and let me tell you, the apple doesn't fall far from the tree.''
</P>
<P>
   Steele said there is a humble nature about both men that comes
through immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Reggie, you would never know his dad was a great NFL
player right up the road,'' Steele said. ``Some youngsters in his
position would make a big issue out of it. If you didn't know, they
would tell you. But Robert is just Dad to Reggie.''
</P>
<P>
   Steele knows Reggie is close to his father, who attends most of
the Baylor games and will be at the Minnesota game Saturday. But
Steele quickly found out who the real disciplinarian is in the
Newhouse home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reggie is an ideal young man,'' Steele said. ``But the first
time he got a little rambunctious about something in practice, I
said, `Well Reggie, I guess I will call your daddy.' That didn't
faze him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next time I said I was going to call his momma (Nancy). He
piped up and said, `Oh no, coach. Don't call my momma.'''
</P>
<P>
   Reggie said the advice he gets from his father rarely has
anything to do with the techniques and fundamentals of football.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad helps me more as a father,'' Reggie said. ``He tells me
to stay focused and do what is asked of me in football, in school
and in life. He talks to me more about the moral part of things
than football. Besides, he can't relate to the receiver position.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert and Reggie aren't the only athletes in the family.
Reggie's 21-year-old twin sisters _ Dawnyel and Shawntel _ run
track at Abilene Christian.
</P>
<P>
   But being a football player meant Reggie would be compared to
his dad. Still, he said he never has felt like he had to live up to
his father's accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say I've ever felt pressure about it,'' Reggie said.
``It was great to grow up with a dad that people knew. Old Cowboys
like Drew Pearson were always coming over to the house, and I got
to go to three Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   ``But other than that, I always kind of did my own thing. My dad
and I are two different people, and he always told me I had big
enough shoes to pave my own way.''
</P>
<P>
   Reggie's chance to shine is just beginning. After a stellar high
school career at Lake Highlands in Dallas, Newhouse played in all
11 games for Baylor last year as a true freshman, catching seven
passes for 77 yards.
</P>
<P>
   But he showed his potential in the season opener two weeks ago
at North Texas by catching five passes for 105 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt good about my performance and feel like it's something
I can build on,'' Newhouse said. ``I had a lot to adjust to last
year, and I had my ups and downs. But it's starting to be second
nature to me now.''
</P>
<P>
   Newhouse never played wide receiver until he arrived at Baylor
last year. He was following in his father's footsteps as a running
back in high school, but college recruiters believed his lanky
build better suited him to be a receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Steele, the Baylor receivers coach and Kevin's brother, was
the first person on the Baylor staff to see Newhouse play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dale saw in Reggie a very intelligent young man with a lot of
character,'' Kevin Steele said. ``Reggie also displayed a lot of
athleticism. He has real good body control, and he makes the hard
catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the thing that excited us the most is his height. Before
Reggie got here, our coaches were taller than all our receivers, so
Reggie was a good fit for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Steele knew Newhouse had a lot to learn about being a college
receiver, but he is amazed at how quickly Newhouse has adapted to
the position.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of technical things about running pass
routes,'' Steele said. ``People think it's just run upfield 12
yards and do an out, but it's not. You have to counter what the
defense does, and there are different line splits depending on the
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of stuff. One year later, not only does Reggie know
all three receiver spots, but he is telling the freshman receivers
where to line up.''
</P>
<P>
   Steele believes Newhouse will do a lot of good things at Baylor
before his college career is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reggie is strong now,'' Steele said. ``But I really believe,
as he matures and gets stronger in the hips and legs, he's just
going to get better and better. He understands the game, and he has
a great desire to be the best he can be.''
</P>
<P>
   And Steele knows the one thing people really want to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to know whether Reggie possesses the skills to do
what his dad did, but at a different position,'' Steele said.
``Reggie has the athleticism, he has the mind, and he has the work
ethic. If he continues to improve as much as he has since he first
got here, it wouldn't surprise me a bit for him to reach that
level.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
