<HEADER>
A1529 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-A&AMP;M-TOOMBS-HNS &LR;      09-13 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-A&AMP;M-TOOMBS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Toombs doing his duty as Texas A&AMP;M fullback
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By NEIL HOHLFELD &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
COLLEGE STATION _ One block by a fullback during a game in which an
offense racks up 51 points and 490 yards normally isn't something
that would go into the memory bank.
</P>
<P>
   But the fullback was Ja'Mar Toombs, and the devastating block
led to a rushing touchdown for Texas A&AMP;M, so it was indeed
something to note.
</P>
<P>
   Toombs, the Aggies' 275-pound erstwhile tailback, cleared the
way for Richard Whitaker's 23-yard run early in a 51-3 win over
Wyoming last Saturday. As the game developed, Robert Ferguson's
seven catches for 174 yards and quarterback Mark Farris' 14-of-21,
two-touchdown game deserved to be the focal points.
</P>
<P>
   Toombs also bulled his way into the end zone twice during the
rout. Three days after the game, however, Toombs wanted to talk
more about his head-on block that sent Wyoming strong safety Lamar
James flying into the air like a Pop-Tart coming out of a toaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``That (block) was my favorite play,'' Toombs said Tuesday.
``I've thought about that more than the touchdowns. It's just good
to know that my block helped Richard get into the end zone. I guess
if I had messed it up, he wouldn't have made it.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Whitaker: ``Once I saw that guy's legs go up in the air, I
didn't see anything but the end zone. I could have run forever. If
Ja'Mar keeps that attitude up the whole season, he's going to be
something.''
</P>
<P>
   For several reasons, Toombs' block was something to behold. Its
precision and ferocity offered an indication that Toombs has become
serious about improving the weak link of his game.
</P>
<P>
   Toombs came into the season knowing he had to improve his
blocking. Out of necessity, Toombs was shifted to tailback in the
Aggies' final three games of 1999, and he gained 273 yards. Toombs
lobbied to play there this season, but the Aggies thought Whitaker
and Joe Weber were more suited to tailback because of their
breakaway potential.
</P>
<P>
   Toombs went back to fullback and was given orders to improve his
blocking. Aggies offensive coordinator Steve Kragthorpe said Toombs
was ``a below-average blocker'' last season.
</P>
<P>
   After two games, Kragthorpe likes what he's seeing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were rolling the ball down the alley, that one (the
block on James) was a strike,'' said Kragthorpe. ``He sent the guy
flying. I think Ja'Mar has improved as a blocker, and I think he
has accepted his role.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows he's going to get the ball in some situations, but in
other situations he's a glorified offensive guard. He knows there
are times when his role is to block for the guy who has the ball in
his hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Through two games, Toombs' statistics are hardly eye-popping. He
has rushed 13 times for 25 yards and has three receptions for 30
yards. Against Wyoming however, Toombs had touchdowns of five and
one yard and rushed two other times for first downs in
short-yardage situations.
</P>
<P>
   After the touchdowns, the Kyle Field fans unleashed their
droning ``Toooooooombs'' chant. Because of his off-field problems
last winter, Toombs wasn't sure he'd be part of that scene again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great to hear that again, because I know some people
were against me,'' said Toombs. ``I was thinking about it. I was
wondering if they were actually going to chant it. I was wondering
if the `Toombs' were going to turn to boos. One good thing is I
guess I couldn't tell the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   During the winter, Toombs didn't have much time for levity. He
was arrested for driving under the influence in February, and since
he already was on probation from a marijuana possession conviction
in 1999, there was speculation Toombs would be dismissed from the
team. Instead, Aggies coach R.C. Slocum decided to give him another
chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a coach,'' Slocum said when fall practice started, ``I have
to balance whether the young man is somebody that can salvaged, if
what he did is something that can be corrected, if he is showing
some accountability for his action. He's done all those things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, his rope is shorter now than when he came here, and
he knows that. I don't anticipate any future problems out of
Ja'Mar.''
</P>
<P>
   Some fans believed Toombs got off easy. Perhaps, but he spent
four days in Brazos County jail and is restricted to a 10 p.m.
curfew through December 2001. Toombs understands he has only one
more last chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm maturing because of what I've been through,''
he said. ``One thing the people who turned on me maybe didn't
realize is that I'm 20 years old. Maybe I'm doing the same things
they did when they were 20. There's just more focus on me because
I'm at a big-time university playing big-time football. I know I
have to become more of a man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to my family, my coach, my probation officer. I'm
going to get through this, and it could turn out to be a good
thing. I'm abiding by the rules now. (The curfew) is going to keep
me out of trouble. When it's over and done, going through this _
getting into trouble and getting out of trouble _ is going to help
me as a person.''
</P>
<P>
   From early indications, Toombs is winning all the on- and
off-field battles so far this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's taking tremendous pride in becoming a better blocker,''
said guard Chris Valletta. ``When you watch him tear into people,
it's almost scary. He can hurt you. He's a 275-pound guy with a
full head of steam taking out 180-pound guys. He's going to win
that battle.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
