<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1531 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-CSUN-ROBERSON-LAD     09-13 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUN-ROBERSON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE'S ROBERSON MAKING MOST OF SECOND CHANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JILL PAINTER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Joseph Roberson sat in the locker room at Air
Force's Falcon Stadium before the season opener and couldn't help
but laugh.
</P>
<P>
   The Cal State Northridge senior found it difficult to accept
reality: He was playing college football ... at 28 ... as a
starting defensive end ... in a stadium packed with more than
50,000 fans.
</P>
<P>
   It really was laughable in light of the road he took to get
there, a road he said included physical and mental abuse as a
child, countless street fights, a stint in jail, the birth of his
daughter and no football experience at the high school level.
</P>
<P>
   That's also how his friends (whom he calls associates) reacted
when he told them five years ago that he wanted to go to college to
earn a degree and play football.
</P>
<P>
   They're not laughing now: Not only does Roberson have a
sociology degree _ which he earned in the spring _ he's working
toward his master's in either sociology or psychology and plans to
earn his doctorate.
</P>
<P>
   He also earned a partial athletic scholarship for the first time
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first it was a challenge for me,'' Roberson said. ``When I
first told my peers _ many of whom are locked up now _ they laughed
at me and told jokes. They thought it was funny. They thought it
was a passing idea _ that it was flighty.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberson is anything but flighty.
</P>
<P>
   His 3.85 grade-point average is the highest on the football team
and no one doubts he'll complete his education with that doctorate.
However, he has something more important that keeps him focused:
namely, his 6-year-old daughter, Kyla.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a great daughter,'' Roberson said. ``I'll do anything
with her. I'll play with Barbies and stuff. I go to the park with
her and get on the swings. I didn't have the opportunity to do
those things as a kid. Even now, I'm just a kid at heart.''
</P>
<P>
   He's no kid on the football field.
</P>
<P>
   Roberson, who's 6-foot-2 and 240 pounds, played sparingly last
season but has blossomed into a solid pass rusher. He had five
tackles, including a sack, in Air Force's 55-6 victory and no
tackles in CSUN's 19-13 overtime win over Southwest Texas State on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive line coach Dave Robinson attributed Roberson's
emergence in part to his age.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brings a maturity to the team because he's older,''
Robinson said. ``He's been through life a little bit. He
understands. He listens. He does what the coaches ask him to do. He
doesn't do any free-lance stuff. He works hard and gets everyone
else to be better.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberson has to work hard, particularly at the little things,
because of his relative lack of experience. For example, he asks
Robinson to translate terminology after practice sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from two seasons at Pierce College, his experience in
athletics pre-CSUN was limited to pickup basketball games _ in
which Roberson said he earned quite a reputation.
</P>
<P>
   He said circumstances simply made it impossible for him to play
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family situation really didn't allow for it,'' Roberson
said. ``I had five little brothers and sisters and I had a lot of
responsibilities and had things to do around the house. Finances
didn't allow for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Finances didn't allow for food sometimes. And he said he never
had new clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as food, it seemed normal at the time,'' Roberson said.
``Now I understand what's reasonable. (It happened) quite often.
But that's life. I'm not hungry now.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberson's problems started early in life with the abuse, he
said, while he lived in Buffalo. N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many years it made me bitter,'' Roberson said. ``I still
have a lot of emotions inside tied up to it. It probably had a lot
to do with me picking psychology and sociology as my major _ trying
to understand the behavior of certain individuals and what
influence society had on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberson moved to California when he was 19. He lived with an
aunt he didn't know well but he didn't stay long. He wasn't
comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   It was the beginning of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``To give you an idea of the people I chose to associate with:
One is now on death row, one has 23 years, one has nine years, one
got life, I think, and one is married,'' Roberson said. ``Those
were my associates.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was just the environment I put myself in. I was 19. I
didn't have any direction and no guidance. That's the environment I
felt most comfortable in. I was more comfortable on the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberson said he was convicted of grand theft auto and forgery
and spent several months in jail, a situation in which he says
he'll never again find himself because of Kyla, who lives nearby
with her mother, Ginger Beebe.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughter is the greatest blessing in the world,'' Roberson
said. ``My relationship with her does more for me than anything
I've ever done for her. She gave me something to miss. After I came
(to California), I was very detached. I didn't have direction.
There was nothing I enjoyed about life or being here.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberson married Beebe shortly after Kyla was born but they
recently divorced. Beebe has temporary custody of Kyla and Roberson
has visitation rights while the two battle in court for permanent
custody.
</P>
<P>
   Beebe declined to comment, other than to say: ``I wouldn't be a
good person to say anything good about him right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberson has another custody hearing Sept. 25. He has no
attorney because he said he can't afford one.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN coach Jeff Kearin offered to testify as a character witness
for his player and he wrote the judge a letter. Kearin said
Roberson told him his life story first before he asked whether he
could join the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is what this program aspires to be,'' Kearin said. ``He's a
hard worker and he graduated. Joseph Roberson is doing it the right
way. He's taking care of school and he's taking care of his family.
He has had life experiences I'll never have.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberson's experiences in court are ones he'd rather not endure.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it's traumatic every time I walk into that court
house,'' Roberson said. ``There's a man sitting here (Beebe's
attorney) who's intent is basically to disparage me. And I
understand that. That's his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I walk in with my cornrows and I don't have a suit. I
understand the reality of that situation. But no matter what people
say, it doesn't justify their stereotypes. ... I don't think I've
slept one good night while this thing has been going on.''
</P>
<P>
   His story is one that hasn't gone unnoticed by his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He works harder than a lot of people here and they don't even
have the situations that he has,'' said linebacker Cos Abercrombie.
</P>
<P>
   Roberson is proud of the choices he's made to get his life back
on track. He doesn't know what he wants to do for a living, only
that he wants to help people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has their problems,'' Roberson said. ``Mine was low
self-esteem. I want to help people and tell them that somehow, some
way they can accomplish their goals. There is a way for every
person. They don't have to give up. If I did it, anyone is capable
of doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he laughed again. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
