<HEADLINE>
SUSPENDED TROJAN INJURED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC defensive end John Cousins remains suspended
from the team, but the junior college transfer is also recovering
from having the tip of a finger cut off in a ``non-football
related'' injury.
</P>
<P>
   According to sources, Cousins hurt his finger when a door
slammed on his hand the weekend of the USC-Penn State game. The
fact he suffered the injury clearly irritated USC coach Paul
Hackett.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't go off and do your own thing,'' Hackett said. ``When
we come back from the game, all of a sudden he's injured.''
</P>
<P>
   Cousins' suspension was related in part to missing appointments
following the injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to get his act together and get cleared to come
back,'' Hackett said. ``There's nothing that's preventing him from
coming back to the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Cousins was not on the sideline during USC's victory over
Colorado. It's also usual policy for injured players to watch
practice from the sideline, but Cousins has not been present.
</P>
<P>
   NO SECOND GUESSING: Hackett said he did not regret going for a
field goal on fourth-and-1 in the first quarter from the 13-yard
line against Colorado. Kicker David Newbury badly missed his
attempt and the Trojans came away empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   ``My thing was we had played extremely hard and extremely well
and I didn't want to come away with no points after two drives,''
Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   USC's previous drive ended when a sure touchdown pass was
dropped by Kareem Kelly and intercepted by Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never occurred to me we would miss the field goal,''
Hackett added. ``I think I would make the same decision again.''
</P>
<P>
   USC failed to convert a third-and-1 play before the missed field
goal. On that play, it did not use its short-yardage offense
featuring tackle Faaesea Mailo at fullback, an attempt to fool
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   SECONDARY SHUFFLE: Cornerback Kris Richard (sprained knee) said
he expects to play in the San Jose State game Sept. 23, but whether
he is cleared to play by team doctors or coaches is yet to be
decided.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be ready, but how they'll feel, I don't know,'' Richard
said.
</P>
<P>
   If Richard can't play, sophomore Kevin Arbet will start at left
cornerback with Darrell Rideaux and Chris Cash continuing to split
time at right cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not afraid to play Kevin. He's earned the right to
play,'' secondary coach Dennis Thurman said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
