<SLUG> BC-LIFE-JACKETS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 DAVIS SIGNS MANDATORY LIFE JACKET MEASURE  &HT;     By GREG LUCAS 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Water-skiers, personal watercraft users and boat
passengers 11 years of age or under will be required to wear life
jackets starting Jan. 1 under a bill signed Tuesday by Gov. Gray
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   The mandatory life jacket bill is a big change. Water-skiers and
personal watercraft users don't have to wear flotation devices now,
and only kids 6 or younger are required to wear them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've ever been on a jet ski you know how dangerous it
is,'' said the bill's author, Assemblywoman Marilyn Brewer,
R-Newport Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was one of dozens signed by the Democratic governor,
who has 17 days to dispose of roughly 1,000 measures sent to him by
the Legislature in the days before its August 31 adjournment.
</P>
<P>
   Personal watercraft users also will be able to take a voluntary
safety course the state will develop under another bill signed by
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   And in a nod to the state's small wineries, Davis signed a bill
allowing them to peddle their wares at farmers' markets.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer's life jacket bill prohibits anyone from operating a
motorboat, sailboat or a vessel 26 feet long or smaller unless
every person age 11 or under is wearing a life jacket.
</P>
<P>
   All water-skiers and personal watercraft operators must wear
life jackets.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the state Department of Boating and Waterways said that
30 of the 58 victims of boating fatalities were not wearing life
jackets.
</P>
<P>
   Like California, 33 states kids to wear life vests. Forty-three
states already order personal watercraft users to wear life
jackets. Nineteen require them for water-skiers.
</P>
<P>
   Of the more than 954,000 vessels registered in California, some
171,000 are personal watercraft.
</P>
<P>
   The safety course is aimed at reducing accidents among the
growing number of personal watercraft users.
</P>
<P>
   Various voluntary boater education programs are already
available in California. The boating and waterways department will
place its new safety course on its Web page.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone convicted of one boating violation would be required to
pass the course to qualify for a license.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Davis vetoed a bill that would have required all
boaters to pass a written safety test.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is little evidence that a written test alone will
improve the piloting skills of motor boat operators or reduce
boating accidents,'' Davis said in his veto message.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S Coast Guard has found that 80 percent of the boat
operators involved in accidents have no boater training.
</P>
<P>
   The National Transportation Safety Board has recommended that
California and other states approve mandatory boater education to
decrease the number of accidents.
</P>
<P>
   In signing the voluntary training bill, Davis reiterated his
opposition to universal boater safety tests.
</P>
<P>
   Another law signed by Davis makes it illegal, in those cities or
counties banning alcohol in public parks, simply to possess an
alcoholic beverage.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, the law only outlawed drinking the alcohol.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
