A1539 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n BC-YOSEMITE-KILLING-SFCH     09-13 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOSEMITE-KILLING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLEA BARGAIN IN SLAYING OF YOSEMITE NATURALIST
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By KEVIN FAGAN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cary Stayner has struck a deal to plead guilty Wednesday to the
grisly slaying of a Yosemite naturalist in exchange for being
spared a federal execution _ but that doesn't preclude the
possibility of a death sentence if convicted of the earlier,
separate killings of three sightseers.
</P>
<P>
   The 39-year-old motel handyman agreed to life in prison without
parole in exchange for the plea he will enter in federal court in
Fresno this afternoon, said sources close to the case.
</P>
<P>
   Stayner originally pleaded not guilty in August 1999 to federal
charges including murder, kidnapping and attempted aggravated
sexual abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Members of both Stayner's family and that of the woman he
allegedly beheaded last year, 26-year-old Joie Armstrong, were
reportedly eager for the plea deal. They want to avoid the ordeal
of what promises to be a months-long trial at best, complete with
sordid details of Armstrong's killing and the possible necessity
for relatives from both families to testify, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors, investigators and Stayner's attorneys said they
could not discuss details of the plea, but they promised a press
conference Wednesday after the court hearing before federal Judge
Anthony Ishii.
</P>
<P>
   Stayner's plea bargain won't be made final until a formal
sentencing hearing is held before the judge, probably about two
months from now. After that, the case can proceed on state charges
accusing him of killing Yosemite sightseers Carole Sund, 42, her
daughter Juli,CQ &LR;  15, and their friend Silvina Pelosso, 16, of
Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   And though no pleas have been entered or court dates set in the
Sund-Pelosso case, prosecutors are anxious to get going the moment
the federal matter is resolved, said Mariposa County Sheriff's Lt.
Brian Muller. The Armstrong killing is federal because it occurred
inside Yosemite, but the others happened just outside the park
border.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time the federal government is ready to release Mr.
Stayner into our custody, we believe we will be fully ready for
trial,'' said Muller, spokesman for the county sheriff's and
district attorney's offices.
</P>
<P>
   He said the plea deal has no bearing on county prosecutors'
plans to seek the death penalty. Relatives of the Sund and Pelosso
families vary on whether they want Stayner executed or locked away
for life.
</P>
<P>
   The handyman reportedly confessed to a reporter and
investigators to killing all four women after he was captured by
police at a Sacramento-area nudist lodge.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, who took children on nature hikes in Yosemite, was
killed in the national park a few hundred feet from her cabin. She
evidently put up a ferocious fight, and her head was found about 40
feet from her body, according to court records.
</P>
<P>
   Carole Sund's mother, Carole Carrington of Eureka, said Tuesday
that she was not surprised by the plea deal.
</P>
<P>
   `'He didn't seem to have much choice,'' she said. ``I think it's
probably a good thing for Joie's family. We're good friends with
them, and I know her mother, Leslie, was not looking forward to the
trial.''
</P>
<P>
   A memorial fund in Armstrong's name established at the Yosemite
National Institutes has raised $177,000 so far, and this year
funded its first group of 10 young women to do wilderness study at
the park, said spokeswoman Tanya Grasser. She said the mood was
calm but somber among Armstrong's many friends and co-workers
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just really focusing on the positive, keeping Joie's
legacy going,'' said Grasser. ``In her time here she touched so
many children, and we try to remember that all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Long before his name was connected with the murder spree that
filled Yosemite with terror during the spring and summer of 1999,
Cary Stayner's family had made other national headlines. His
brother, Steven Stayner, was kidnapped in Merced as a young boy in
1972 and dramatically resurfaced seven years later after escaping
his abductor.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Stayner died in 1989 at 24 in an auto accident, but Cary
Stayner was said to have never fully recovered from roiling
emotions associated with the disappearance and subsequent
glorification of his brother.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
