<DOCNO> NYT20000913.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 00:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1540 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-ZERO-TOLERANCE-KAN &LR;      09-13 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZERO-TOLERANCE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI DRUNKEN-DRIVING LAW LETS MINORS KEEP LICENSES, COURT
RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JOE LAMBE  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A Missouri law designed to get tougher on
minors who drink and drive actually allows young offenders to keep
their licenses in some instances, an appeals court ruled Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   And if that ruling stands, critics said, it would allow drivers
under 21 protection from police stops that adults who drive drunk
do not have.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an absurd result,'' said Springfield Rep. Craig Hosmer,
``a strange reading of the statute.'' He sponsored Missouri's 1996
zero-tolerance law, aimed at stopping underage drinking and
driving.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court ruling dealt with the fine distinction between
how the state enforces drunken-driving laws for minors and adults.
</P>
<P>
   The zero-tolerance law allows the state to use a civil action to
suspend licenses of minors who drive with alcohol contents above
0.02. But it also says police must have probable cause such as a
driving violation to stop the underage driver.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1998 case under appeal, the judges ruled there was no
probable cause to stop the young driver, who was legally
intoxicated.
</P>
<P>
   Adults who drive drunk can lose their licenses through civil
actions when stopped for any reason, lawyers said. The civil action
is intended to provide sure punishment to many who escape
drunken-driving convictions because of plea bargains or evidence
problems.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court in Kansas City reversed a Gentry County judge.
Albany police in 1998 stopped Jimmy D. Ballard, who was 20 at the
time, for squealing his truck tires and found he was drunk. His
blood alcohol content was 0.135 _ above the legal limit of 0.02 for
minors and 0.10 for adults.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the reason for the stop _ the squealing tires _ was not
sufficient for police to stop Ballard under the zero-tolerance law,
the appeals court ruled. Another state law allows a similar stop
for adult drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Attorney General Jay Nixon said his office would appeal
the three-judge panel's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The decision raises questions about whether drunken minors could
even be arrested at sobriety check points, Nixon said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers have always intended to punish drunken minors more
because they are drinking illegally and driving illegally, Nixon
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that breaking two separate laws would get you a
benefit is not what anyone had in mind,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce B. Brown, Ballard's attorney, said the ruling was the
right interpretation of the law and is a good test case for the
Missouri Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court ordered the Missouri Department of Revenue to
reinstate Ballard's license, but Ballard has already served a
30-day license suspension on the civil action. Brown wants the
suspension off Ballard's driving record.
</P>
<P>
   Records show that Ballard, now 22, did not receive a criminal
conviction for drunken driving. Ballard could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas, state officials said they know of no legal challenges
to a law intended to crack down on teen-age drinking and driving.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas law applies to drivers under age 21. If they are
caught driving with blood-alcohol levels of 0.02 percent to 0.08
percent, their licenses are suspended for one year. Under the law,
the basic drunken-driving limit standard is 0.08 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri authorities do not know how many cases may be affected
by Tuesday's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Waylene Hiles, an attorney with the Department of Revenue, said
the ruling would not change the department's position that regular
laws for adults apply to underage drivers with blood alcohol
contents of 0.10 or above.
</P>
<P>
   Her office will wait for the Missouri Supreme Court to clarify
the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, action could come in Jefferson City. Hosmer said he
would introduce legislation next year to fix the problems caused by
``strained readings'' of the zero-tolerance law.
</P>
<P>
   The system will work as intended, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court corrects our mistakes,'' Hosmer said, ``and we
correct the court's mistakes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-00 0026EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
