<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 00:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1541 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w BC-SCOUTS-CONGRESS-SFCHR     09-13 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOUTS-CONGRESS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BILL TO SANCTION BOY SCOUTS FACES LIKELY DEFEAT  &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republican leaders will bring Rep. Lynn
Woolsey's bill to revoke the congressional charter of the Boy
Scouts of America to a vote Wednesday, fully expecting its
resounding defeat.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Tex., blasted the California
Democrat's bill Tuesday, calling it an ``an unjustified, despicable
attack'' that was ``part of a campaign by radical extremists to
intimidate the Boy Scouts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I scheduled this bill to demonstrate the lack of support for
those who have declared open season on the Boy Scouts,'' Armey
declared.
</P>
<P>
   Woolsey introduced her ``Scouting for All Act'' after the
Supreme Court ruled 5 to 4 on June 28 that the Constitution permits
the Boy Scouts to ban gays from leadership positions, under the
First Amendment's protection of ``expressive association.''
</P>
<P>
   Woolsey's measure would revoke a congressional charter for the
Boy Scouts dating from 1916. Such honorific charters are given to
distinguish organizations with a patriotic, educational or
charitable purpose.
</P>
<P>
   In introducing the bill, Woolsey said ``there is nothing
charitable or patriotic about intolerance,'' adding that she wanted
to ``send a message to the Boy Scouts and to all Americans that the
Congress of the United States does not support intolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   She noted that revoking the charter would not cut off federal
funding for the scouts or change the organization's tax status.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contrary to what some on the other side of the aisle claim,''
she said, ``I'm not saying the Boy Scouts are bad; I'm saying
intolerance is.''
</P>
<P>
   Woolsey's bill has just eight co-sponsors, down from nine after
civil rights icon John Lewis, D-Georgia, removed his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty confident that we'll have an enormous vote
opposed to this bill,'' said Armey spokeswoman Michelle Davis.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court ruling has unleashed a torrent of debate over
the public role of the Boy Scouts. This week, the Lafayette City
Council discussed whether members should appear officially at
Scouting events, and in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., the city commission
refused to grant the Boy Scouts $10,000 of public money after five
hours of emotional discussion.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy has also spilled over to the presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Woolsey sent a letter to President Clinton, signed by
Bay Area Democrats George Miller of Martinez, Barbara Lee of
Oakland and Nancy Pelosi of San Francisco, urging him to resign his
position as honorary head of the Boy Scouts to protest its policy
against homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did not respond to the letter.
</P>
<P>
   But in August, the Interior Department began examining whether
Boy Scout Jamborees held on federal lands violated an executive
order from Clinton _ issued just five days before the Supreme Court
decision _ banning discrimination against gays in federal education
and training programs.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, the Republican presidential nominee, called on
the administration to drop the probe. Democratic nominee Al Gore's
spokesman, Doug Hattaway, said that ``in a Gore administration, Boy
Scouts will be allowed to use federal land.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 1, Attorney General Janet Reno issued a statement
finding that the federal government does not have to sever its ties
with the Boy Scouts, because the executive order applied only to
programs run by the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   The Boy Scouts are working in national parks _ including Point
Reyes National Seashore in Woolsey's district _ to help eradicate
exotic species, remove litter and improve trails and campsites.
</P>
<P>
   Woolsey took the name for her bill after Boy Scouts for All, a
group founded by Petaluma teenager Stephen Cozza that sought to
change the organization's policy toward gays.
</P>
<P>
   About 90 nonprofit groups currently hold congressional charters,
including the American Legion, the Daughters of the American
Revolution and the National Ski Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional charters convey no benefits and do not signify
government approval, but they are often used by organizations as a
badge of prestige. Congress placed a moratorium on new charters in
1992, although that moratorium has been bypassed several times in
recent years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
