<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BE CAREFUL OPENING THAT BUBBLY  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Napa, Calif., is standing on shaky ground,
according to a geophysicist named John Boatwright, which raises
some questions. Such as:
</P>
<P>
   How is it that a guy who studies the ground has a name like
Boatwright? Isn't that like being a sailor named Farmer?
</P>
<P>
   In Tuesday's paper, Boatwright said that Napa's soil is loose,
and that a magnitude 7 quake could ``shake up Napa to pieces ...
This should be a wake-up call for people here.''
</P>
<P>
   Wake-up call? With that kind of news, who in Napa will ever
sleep again?
</P>
<P>
   It sounds more like a move-out call. It's hard to imagine what
kind of structure could withstand a quake on those shaky grapy
acres. Except ... a boat!
</P>
<P>
   Sure, you dig your swimming pool a little larger, drop in a
live-aboard yacht, and turn the house into a B and B.
</P>
<P>
   Boatwright. Suddenly it all makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   I'VE SEEN fire and I've seen rain.
</P>
<P>
   No, that's not a lead-in to another clever item about Firestone
tires.
</P>
<P>
   The item is this: James Taylor the singer has bought a condo on
Jones St. and will be moving in, at least part-time.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet Baby James is a good pal of Robin Williams. About two
years ago, superstar tenor Andrea Bocelli was booked to sing at a
big fight-cancer fund-raiser in San Francisco. He scratched at the
last minute with a sore throat.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Williams got the 911 call and agreed to help fill in, and
he persuaded Taylor to fly in and sing with Bocelli's symphony
orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Williams and Taylor were a smash, James fell in love with the
city, and here he is.
</P>
<P>
   I hope James rides Muni a lot, and sings. It would do a lot to
cheer up the troops.
</P>
<P>
   CAN'T WAIT for the movie that's sure to be made about that
Colombian cocaine-smuggling submarine that authorities stumbled
upon in mid-construction.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the submarine scheme was worth taking seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why worry?'' Randy Elwood wonders. ``As the article points
out, the sub was being built from Russian plans.''
</P>
<P>
   The theme music for the movie, of course, would be the Beatles'
``Yellow Submarine.'' Or ``Let It Snow.''
</P>
<P>
   Reader Doc flashes back to ``Run Silent, Run Deep'' and can
almost see ``Burt Lancaster and Clark Gable and 11 tons of blow,
headin' for the Bongo Straits.''
</P>
<P>
   I've got two working titles for the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Run Silent, Run Deep, Run Nose.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, ``Das Toot Boot.''
</P>
<P>
   BLENDING SMOOTHLY into the next sea-worthy item:
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' ticket department is under siege for playoffs and
World Series ducats.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Sullivan, the team's ticket czar, got a phone call from a
woman who runs a party-planning business in Marin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have any games in early October?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   The woman explained that the aircraft carrier Constellation will
be steaming into the Bay around that time for Fleet Week and she
would love to arrange for some of the sailors to take in a
ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh, how many?'' Sullivan asked, warily.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 5,500,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan spit out a mouthful of Coke, the official drink of the &QL; 
Gigantes.
</P>
<P>
   For a World Series game, the giants  &UR; might  &LR; be able to squeeze
an admiral or two into the bleachers.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan suggested to the woman that maybe the ship could tie up
in McCovey Cove and the sailors could sit on deck and watch the
game from over the ballpark's right-field wall.
</P>
<P>
   AND CAN you imagine what McCovey Cove will look like if the
Giants make it to the Series?
</P>
<P>
   Traffic will be barnacle to barnacle.
</P>
<P>
   BE CAREFUL today, please.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday is the 101st anniversary of the first
death-by-automobile accident, and you don't want to mess with fate.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 13 of 1899, Henry Bliss was helping a woman step off a
trolley in New York City when he was killed by a speeding taxi.
</P>
<P>
   The stunned citizens learned a valuable lesson. Henry's act is
the last known instance of anyone being courteous on a New York
City street.
</P>
<P>
   But seriously, did you know that there has not been a day
without a traffic fatality in California in more than 10 years?
</P>
<P>
   LESS SERIOUSLY, Buffalo Bills' quarterback Rob Johnson got
slammed around Sunday, suffered a concussion and later said, ``I
was clear-headed, I was just seeing different colors.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey. Is it possible that all the red-light runners in San
Francisco are present or former 49ers quarterbacks?
</P>
<P>
   SOMETHING for Willie and the Supes to ponder:
</P>
<P>
   In Finland, relates reader Kevin Friel, the size of a traffic
fine is dictated by the offender's income.
</P>
<P>
   A dot-com millionaire (in other words, just starting out) who
was cited for driving his Ferrari recklessly through Helsinki was
fined $44,100.
</P>
<P>
   Only problem with that law here: Some of these dot-com firms are
losing millions a day. Huge losses can be the sign of major
success.
</P>
<P>
   But if one of these guys runs a red light, the city might have
to pay  &UR; him &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   WHY CAN'T adults enjoy pinatas, too? That was a philosophical
question posed here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A woman caller says that such objects do exist. She says that a
woman she knows had a penis pinata at her bachelorette party.
</P>
<P>
   And I suppose that's someone's idea of humor?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
