<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KC-CONDOS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVELOPER PLANS LUXURY CONDOS IN DOWNTOWN KANSAS CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 MARK P. COUCH  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A Kansas City architect on Tuesday announced
plans to convert the Kansas City Club building downtown into a
luxury condominium complex.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would save the 14-story, Tudor Gothic structure from
mothballs and would add a dash of luxury living to downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Architect Thomas R. Nolte said he would lead an investment
group, which plans to buy the building at 1228 Baltimore Ave.,
renovate the entire structure and convert five floors into as many
as 20 upscale condominium units.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is truly one of the jewels in the crown of Kansas City,
and we intend to keep it that way,'' Nolte said.
</P>
<P>
   The renovation program could cost $12 million, but Nolte does
not plan to ask for tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   The condominiums would carry a minimum price of $300,000, with
the ultimate cost depending on how fancy the buyer wants to get.
Improvements could add at least $100,000 to the price, Nolte said.
</P>
<P>
   The building would continue to house the Kansas City Club, but
the private dining club on the top floor would be replaced by a
public restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   A restaurant operator has not been selected, Nolte said.
</P>
<P>
   Nolte's renovation plan would rescue the Kansas City Club from a
costly prospect: spending a fortune to restore its building while
coping with a declining membership.
</P>
<P>
   E. Wynn Presson, vice chairman of Health Midwest and president
of the Kansas City Club, said the club's membership had shrunk to
900 from its peak of 2,200 in the 1980s. Membership dues average
$90 a month, club officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Club has been caught in the same vise as many
other private clubs across the country that have suffered big
declines in membership.
</P>
<P>
   As the club's membership declined, its building's problems were
swelling. The building has outdated plumbing and air-conditioning
systems, it doesn't comply with laws regulating access for the
disabled and it has asbestos in some nooks and crannies.
</P>
<P>
   The building, which had been a bastion for executives for nearly
80 years, had become a financial sinkhole for its members.
</P>
<P>
   Presson said the club's board had concluded it would need as
much as $5 million to cure the ailments afflicting the old
building.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the club needed to spruce up the 65 hotel rooms
that the building offered to members for wedding parties and for
out-of-town guests. That would push the total renovation cost to
$12 million.
</P>
<P>
   Spending that much on the rooms didn't make sense because
occupancy was 17 percent in 1999, club officials said. As a
nonprofit group, the club doesn't advertise its hotel space, so
filling it was difficult, Presson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``With declining membership and prohibitive costs and rather
limited resources, the only other alternative was to seek another
location in downtown,'' Presson said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the club had begun to scour downtown for new
space when Nolte's surprise proposal came, Presson said. The
architect said he would convert the hotel space on floors seven
through 11 into luxury condominiums.
</P>
<P>
   Nolte's group would buy the building for $1. The Kansas City
Club would then lease the health club, administrative office and
lobby space for 20 years with options that could extend its
occupancy for up to 100 years, Nolte said.
</P>
<P>
   With the low-cost purchase, Nolte inherits the high-dollar
headaches of renovating the building. Nolte estimates that the
renovation of the basic systems in the building could cost as much
as $7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Nolte and the club are still negotiating the final terms of the
agreement and have set a six-month deadline to complete the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The plan to save the building would not rely on incentives or
tax credits from local or state governments, Nolte said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes too long to get them,'' said Nolte, who is a member
of the Lenexa (Kan.) City Council. ``And we don't want the
government as partners in the project, and we don't need the (tax
breaks).''
</P>
<P>
   The housing would add a dash of flair to the downtown market,
which is primarily focused on apartments for young professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a thing whose time has come,'' said Roger
Buford, who has developed hundreds of apartments downtown. ``To
those people who would spend $1 million for a house in Hallbrook, a
$500,000 condo in downtown is a pretty good deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The downtown housing market, powered by loft conversions, has
exploded during the past several years.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Lebofsky, a development specialist for the City Planning
and Development Department, said 398 loft units had been added
between 1995 and 1999. And developers have 406 units under
construction for the area bounded by the Missouri River, Union
Station, Broadway and Troost Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Nolte said he had not presold any of the units proposed for the
Kansas City Club building. He said he had strong interest from one
potential buyer.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Kay Barnes said the project would be good for the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been a strong proponent for increasing housing
opportunities in downtown,'' Barnes said. ``I'm very grateful for
this exciting new venture.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
