<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHMID UPSET WITH GALAXY'S ATTITUDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid, fed up with the
players' effort in Monday's workout at the Rose Bowl, cut practice
30 minutes short. Schmid then held a team meeting before heading to
Tampa Bay for the opening of Thursday's first-round, best-of-three
playoff series against the Mutiny at Raymond James Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Game 2 is next Wednesday at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   For a team that lost its last two games, home-field advantage
and the Western Division regular-season title to Kansas City, it's
no time to start losing focus as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone has to bring an effort and they're not
bringing it,'' said Schmid. ``We have to train better than this or
we're not going to be around very long.''
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy goalkeeper Kevin Hartman was upset he didn't get a full
workout in. Hartman didn't mention names, but it appears that Cobi
Jones and Luis Hernandez _ the players expected to lead this team
to a championship if it's going to happen _ are the focus of their
teammates' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Jones hasn't scored since July 8 and has been criticized by
Schmid for his shoddy play. If Jones is going through the motions,
it's probably because he has his sights set on playing in France
next season if the MLS doesn't agree to the five-year, $5 million
contract he asked for earlier in the year.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, who has scored only four goals in 17 MLS games, seems
eager for the season to end. When it's over, he will be loaned to
Club America of the Mexican first division.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have to show their pride because I get pretty
disappointed about losing games,'' said Hartman. ``It seems people
are looking toward the future, the future and future. As a
professional, you have to come out and perform every day. We
haven't had that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad Sigi is having this meeting. There is going to be a
lot of stuff people don't want to hear, but it's time they hear it.
Maybe it will wake us all up.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of Jones' problems developed when he returned to midfield,
but with striker Sasha Victorine gone to the Olympics, Schmid
paired Jones and Hernandez on the front line during training
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Cobi and Luis have to get themselves involved,'' said
Schmid. ``And it's not so much the rest of the team getting them
involved, they need to be aggressive and get themselves involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could be the key to this series. If they're active, they
will create problems for Tampa's defense. But it's up to them. They
need to bring it.''
</P>
<P>
   NO SHOOTOUTS: There are no more shootouts in the playoffs to
decide games that end in ties. MLS decided to use the points system
_ the same system used in the regular season. Teams get three
points for a win and one for a tie.
</P>
<P>
   The first team to compile five or six points (win and two ties,
or two wins), advances to the next round. If the series ends even
on points, the two teams will play two 10-minute sudden death
overtime periods following the conclusion of the third game. If the
game is still tied, penalty kicks will decide the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously the MLS likes the idea of third games,'' said
Schmid. ``Personally, I think if you tie and win in your first two
games you should (advance).'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
