<HEADLINE>
REFINERS ARE KEY FACTOR IN FUEL PROBLEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Although the industrialized world's attention
is mostly focused on the rising price of oil, the bigger problem
for American consumers promises to be the tightness of refining
capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Media coverage and policy pronouncements imply that if the
Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries would just
increase oil production enough, the threat of higher prices for
gasoline and heating oil would be ameliorated.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, it's not that simple.
</P>
<P>
   Those who follow developments in the trade and financial
journals get a more comprehensive picture. It's a picture showing
that no matter how much OPEC boosts output, there doesn't seem to
be enough slack in the refining system to create much relief for
U.S. consumers. Even if there were, Big Oil's stockpiles wouldn't
be adequate to produce enough additional gasoline or heating oil to
affect prices.
</P>
<P>
   A recent analysis in The Wall Street Journal, for example, noted
that so far this year the average weekly output of U.S. refiners
has been at 96 percent of industry production capacity. Meanwhile,
the behavior of crude prices this year has discouraged stockpiling
of extra petroleum.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the seeds of the current situation actually were
sown late last year. Kyle Cooper, who follows the market for
Salomon Smith Barney, explained the situation this way: After
OPEC's earlier production cuts began to translate into a price
spiral, U.S. refiners worked on the assumption that it was a
temporary phenomenon. Thus, they opted not to accumulate
substantial crude inventories, preferring to wait for the expected
price decline, which didn't come. All the time, they were content
to produce only enough finished product to meet demand.
</P>
<P>
   The irony here, Cooper noted, is that even as U.S. interests
pressure OPEC to increase production, an oil glut seems more likely
than an oil shortage. How so? With so little excess refining
capacity to work with, U.S. refiners are limited in how much of any
extra OPEC production they'd be able to process.
</P>
<P>
   Although the summer driving season is over, which should relieve
some of the pressure, any refining capacity not needed for gasoline
must be shifted to heating oil. That market already is responding
as if it were expecting a worst-case winter scenario, as futures
prices flirt with record highs.
</P>
<P>
   The area most threatened by soaring heating-oil prices will be
the Northeast, but as refiners divert as much capacity as possible
to meeting heating-oil demand, this means gasoline supplies can be
expected to remain relatively lean. Translation: The odds of rising
gas prices are much greater than declining gasoline prices in the
weeks ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing lasts forever, though. It's an election year, which
means Big Oil will come under political pressure to eat some of the
higher production costs imposed by market conditions. Moreover, if
surging energy prices slow the economy, this may flatten demand,
and thus prices.
</P>
<P>
   As one analyst put it recently, a combination of market
fundamentals and political pressure probably will combine at some
point to cap the market. Meantime, things probably will get worse
before they get better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-00 0038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
