<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 00:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1555 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-HOLLYWOOD-VIOLENCE-SF     09-13 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLYWOOD-VIOLENCE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 DEMOCRATS PUSH FOR LIMITS ON VIOLENCE IN TV, MUSIC  &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Democrats chortled when Dan Quayle went after
television's Murphy Brown. They rolled their eyes when Bob Dole
railed against such movies as ``Natural Born Killers'' and ``Money
Train.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Democrats not only are voicing their own concerns about
the entertainment industry, but making them a centerpiece of their
2000 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   When vice presidential candidate Joe Lieberman testifies
Wednesday morning before a Senate committee on the dangers of
Hollywood's violence and the virtues of curtailing it, it will be
another milepost in the party's steady march toward the
conservative position on cultural values.
</P>
<P>
   Once seen as the more free-living, more free-speech-loving and
hipper of the two major parties, Democrats now are presenting
themselves as concerned _ some would say uptight _ mothers and
fathers.
</P>
<P>
   First there was Tipper Gore's crusade against obscene music
lyrics. Then President Clinton demanded that TV-makers include
V-chips that would allow parents to block children from watching
certain shows. This week, Vice President Al Gore and his running
mate have taken the issue beyond even the GOP's most strident
rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   The two Democrats, in a move that has many supporters raising
their eyebrows, have proposed government intervention to force the
industry to stop marketing violent products to children.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not censorship at all,'' Gore said of his threats to
regulate the makers of music, movies and video games. ``It's about
parenting.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also about polls.
</P>
<P>
   Many Baby Boomers who laughed at their parents' concerns over
the evil influences of rock 'n' roll now worry about the effects of
misogynist and violent lyrics on their children's CDs.
</P>
<P>
   Strict parenting may be good politics.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic pollster Stanley Greenberg writes in a recent edition
of the American Prospect that after rescuing Clinton from the
Monica Lewinsky scandal, ``Democrats again were identified with
1960s-style irresponsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg, who signed on with the Gore camp earlier this summer,
says ``voters want political leaders who put the family at the
center of political discussion and ... are drawn to Democrats who
respect the public's religious faith and belief in personal
responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Most politicians agree that the reduction of violence and
improved family life are admirable goals. But the idea of using
government to regulate the arts _ or even the marketing of artistic
products _ makes many cringe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I praise (Gore) for his call for self-regulation and
self-restraint, but I do not believe it would be constitutional for
the government to start policing ads,'' said Sen. Barbara Boxer,
D-Calif., who also will testify at this morning's hearing before
the Senate Commerce Committee. ``It might work in China or Cuba _
but they don't have (our) Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Boxer, taking a more traditional Democratic line, suggested that
domestic violence and guns contribute to moral decay and crime
rates far more than movies and raunchy CDs.
</P>
<P>
   It is a line of reasoning that Gore himself advanced in many
speeches. Until this week, when Gore spoke about violence among
children, he focused on solutions such as restricting guns, adding
new police officers, providing V-chips and seeking voluntary
restraint from the makers of movies, music and video games.
</P>
<P>
   His selection of Lieberman as a running mate may have been the
first indication of a change.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman has long been an advocate of using government to stem
``the impact that all of the violence, vulgarity and degradation
flooding into the public square is having on our children, our
culture, and our common values.'' He proposed legislation with Sen.
John McCain, R-Ariz., to require the entertainment industry to come
up with a uniform rating system and new laws to prohibit the sale
of certain materials to children.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Gore proposed giving the entertainment industry six
months to stop marketing violent and obscene products to children
or face sanctions from the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   If current law does not permit the Federal Trade Commission to
go after the industries' marketing plans as ``false advertising,''
Gore said, he will work on writing new legislation to provide the
authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I am entrusted with the presidency,'' he told the New York
Times, ``I am going to do something about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Some are finding this hard to stomach, coming from a man who has
taken millions of dollars in Hollywood contributions. Democrats
have received $13.6 million from the entertainment industry this
election cycle, according to the Center for Responsive Politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The change is that in the past, Al Gore has not overtly
threatened the First Amendment with government intervention,'' said
Howie Klein, president of Reprise Records.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see Gore trying to latch onto this to show he is a tough
guy,'' Klein said. ``This is his way of showing paranoid parents _
and in some cases legitimately worried parents _ as well as the
anti-civil libertarian right-wing fanatics, that he is as tough as
the Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   Klein said warning stickers that recording companies place on
CDs containing graphic lyrics do more than alert parents. They also
prevent many stores in shopping malls from carrying the product, he
said, and have a chilling effect on the artistic process.
</P>
<P>
   ``My problem isn't that parents don't have a right to be
concerned,'' Klein said. ``My fear is that government shouldn't
have a role in it.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a position long held by many Democrats. It is no longer
the position held by the party's presidential nominee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
