<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASINO-FIGURES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATION EDGES PAST HARRAH'S IN AUGUST MARKET SHARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 RICK ALM  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Station Casino Kansas City didn't appear to
lose any business over its state licensing troubles, according to
the latest financial report by the Missouri Gaming Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Station led all Kansas City riverboats in August with $14.69
million in revenue and a 33.82 percent market share, according to
the report, which was released this week. That performance inched
past Harrah's North Kansas City Casino &AMP; Hotel, which closed the
month at $14.67 million and a 33.77 percent share.
</P>
<P>
   While the market leaders slugged it out, Flamingo Hilton Casino
posted its lowest numbers of the year. In August the Kansas City
casino temporarily shut down 490 slot machines as part of an
extensive remodeling and rebranding to an Isle of Capri casino.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's called being under construction, and it's going to get
worse before it gets better,'' said General Manager Dan Weindruch.
</P>
<P>
   With almost half its slot machines and floor space out of
action, the Isle-operated Flamingo is going through ``an identity
crisis'' and a painful period for employees, Weindruch said.
Workers' hours have been cut, he said, but he promised, ``There
will be no layoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Employees aren't happy, and the timing couldn't be worse.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City Local 64 of the Hotel Employees and Restaurant
Employees union had been gathering signatures at the casino for
more than a year, hoping to collect a majority and force an
election to establish a collective bargaining unit at the
riverboat.
</P>
<P>
   The organizing effort bogged down in 1999 when it became clear
that Hilton Hotels Corp. was selling the casino, said Beverly
Alery, secretary-treasurer of the local. That effort has resumed
with the emergence of Mississippi-based Isle of Capri Casinos Inc.
as new owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a union town,'' Alery said Tuesday. ``We are not going
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Alery said the culinary workers' Local 74 in St.
Louis probably would mount a similar effort at Isle's other
Missouri casinos in development in Boonville and Kimmswick.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Boone, Isle vice president for human resources, said the
company would fight to keep its rapidly growing chain of 12 casinos
in five states union-free.
</P>
<P>
   Isle has won all but one certifying election over the years,
Boone said. And that lone defeat was turned around after only a
year when workers voted to decertify from the union.
</P>
<P>
   Last month Weindruch formally rejected Alery's request that Isle
negotiate with Local 64, and this month letters went out to
employees over his signature urging them to refuse to sign union
cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``If union organizers come to see you, our advice is to tell
them you are not interested,'' Weindruch wrote in one letter
obtained by The Kansas City Star. ``Signing a union card can
obligate you to pay large sums of money to the union for regular
dues and fees...and give the union the power to make decisions for
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Flamingo employees have long been in a cross fire.
</P>
<P>
   Political scandal kept the casino's fate uncertain for years as
the riverboat struggled just to maintain its market share, which
has long trailed the other boats.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Isle's estimated five-month construction project is sending
workers home each week with less than full paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came down from 40 hours a week to a 30-hour week, and
they're still sending me home early some of the time,'' said one
Flamingo card dealer who is looking for another job and asked not
be identified. ``People can't afford to have their hours cut. I
think they're trying to make us quit.''
</P>
<P>
   Weindruch insists the difficulties are temporary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to be as fair as possible in reducing hours,'' he
said. ``We're trying to minimize the pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is still working and still has their full benefits.
We hope by the first of the year, or even sometime in December when
the renovation is close to completed, business will pick up, and
hours will increase.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Weindruch said, the company is spending
additional development money on preliminary design work for a hotel
and banquet facility on the grounds. If all goes according to plan,
Weindruch said, construction could begin in the spring and the new
facilities could open in summer 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the company on Monday announced a deal with Children's
Choice Learning Centers Inc., of Dallas, to provide on-site day
care for employees' children at all its casinos.
</P>
<P>
   Weindruch said the child-care center in Kansas City probably
would be part of the hotel project.
</P>
<P>
   Last month the Gaming Commission held a two-day inquiry in
Kansas City into events surrounding a former Station lawyer's
guilty plea this year in federal court. Michael Lazaroff admitted
committing several felonies, including misappropriation of law firm
funds that included a questionable $500,000 bonus payment from
Station.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry found no casino wrongdoing linked to that money. But
when Station executives refused to honor the commission's subpoenas
and testify under oath, the commission voted 5-0 to revoke the
company's state gaming licenses in Kansas City and St. Charles.
</P>
<P>
   Las Vegas-based Station is expected to appeal that action. Its
riverboats would remain open until those issues are resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Harrah's also might encounter construction blues before the end
of the year. Inside remodeling and expansion to a second deck
aboard Harrah's Mardi Gras is to begin in November. Exterior work
already has begun.
</P>
<P>
   The project is to be completed July 4, 2001, said General
Manager Michael St. Pierre.
</P>
<P>
   Upon completion of the Mardi Gras work, the smaller North Star
riverboat will be shut down and moved to another Harrah's location,
probably in southern Illinois, St. Pierre said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
