<HEADLINE>
AGENCIES MADE $20.7 BILLION IN ERRONEOUS PAYMENTS, GAO REPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   By KEVIN MURPHY
</P>
<P>
   Knight Ridder Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Taxpayers lost $20.7 billion last year on bills the
federal government paid but didn't owe, according to a General
Accounting Office report released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO found that 12 federal agencies in 1999 made payments
erroneously or fraudulently in 20 programs. The biggest share of
the $20.7 billion was $14.1 billion in Medicare fees paid for
services not rendered, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, there was $19.1 billion in improper spending. This is
the second year the GAO has studied the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Figures for each year would be much higher, but most agencies do
not have systems to determine how much money is being improperly
spent, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare's improper payments grew from $12.6 billion in 1998 to
$14.1 billion last year. Several years ago they lost more than $20
billion _ before steps were taken to crack down on the problem,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides overpayments from Medicare, improper amounts paid
included $1.3 billion for food stamps, $1.6 billion in supplemental
security income, $1.3 billion for old age and survivors insurance,
$1.1 billion for disability insurance and $935 million in housing
subsidies. The rest was spread among other programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stockholders do not tolerate such mismanagement in the private
sector,'' said Thomas Schatz, president of the nonpartisan group
Citizens Against Government Waste. ``Taxpayers should be equally
outraged at such neglect of their investment in Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Schatz said the $20.7 billion would be enough to give every
family in America $300 or could be used to finance programs that
may have to be left out of the budget this year.  &LR; tag1:To reach
Kevin Murphy, a Washington correspondent, call (202) 383-6009 or
send e-mail to kmurphy &LR; krwashington.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-00 0047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
