<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETURN OF POLI-DIXON SHOULD HELP BRUINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ While the play of quarterback Ryan McCann has been
the focus of much of the talk concerning UCLA's uneven offensive
performance against Fresno State, the return of split end Brian
Poli-Dixon could have a big impact on the Bruins' offense Saturday
against No.3-ranked Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Poli-Dixon, who had tightness in his right hamstring prior to
the season opener against Alabama, felt a twinge in the muscle
early in the second half of that game and didn't return. The muscle
felt tight in light running last Monday so the coaches decided to
hold him out against Fresno State.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poli gives you a serious big-play threat,'' offensive
coordinator Al Borges said of the junior whose only catch this
season was a 31-yard scoring pass from flanker Freddie Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can run by you or take the ball underneath and run through
people. Any time you lose a player like that, you're going to
notice. (Jon) Dubravac (four catches, 32 yards) did a great job,
but now we're in a position where we can have both of them out
there (in three-receiver sets).''
</P>
<P>
   Poli-Dixon spent much of last week getting whirlpool treatments
and said Tuesday that he hasn't run full out yet. Missing a week of
conditioning could be a concern, but so is blowing out his
hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to go back to square one,'' Poli-Dixon said.
``This is a huge game. You only get so many opportunities to play a
team like Michigan. This could set us up for the Pac-10 and our
ranking. We can make a statement to the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   KOCHER HEALING: Defensive tackle Ken Kocher (left ankle sprain)
is also expected to return after missing the Fresno State game, but
he won't start and will likely be limited to 15 to 20 plays.
</P>
<P>
   RANKINGS: After UCLA moved ahead of Alabama in the writers' poll
this week _ the Bruins were 14th and the Crimson Tide 15th _ Bruins
coach Bob Toledo felt vindicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's fair,'' he said. ``I wasn't saying we should be No.1.
It's only right. Why should somebody be ranked ahead of you if you
beat them this early in the season?''
</P>
<P>
   The coaches, apparently, don't agree. They kept UCLA 17th and
moved Alabama up a spot this week to 13th. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
