<SLUG> BC-FBC-ANGELS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAFT PICK BOOTCHECK FINALLY ARRIVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ A mere three months after being selected by
the Angels with the 20th overall pick in the draft, pitcher Chris
Bootcheck finally made it to Edison Field on Tuesday afternoon for
a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   It took so long because Bootcheck, a 6-foot-5, 195-pound client
of agent Scott Boras, would not agree to terms on a signing bonus.
Last Friday, the two sides finally agreed on $1.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of anxiety during the process,'' said
Bootcheck, who skipped his senior year at Auburn to sign with the
Angels. ``Baseball is a sport I love. I was anxious to get started.
I couldn't wait for the opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the negotiating process took so long, Bootcheck was
unable to pitch in the organization this season, unlike Joe Torres,
who also was taken in the first round (No.10 overall).
</P>
<P>
   Torres, pitching for Single-A Boise, went 4-1 with a 2.54 ERA in
11 games (10 starts). Bootcheck will pitch in the Arizona
Instructional League beginning Oct. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Angels director of scouting Donny Rowland said it's not out of
the question for Bootcheck to begin next season as high as
Double-A.
</P>
<P>
   ``If things go well, we will not hold him back,'' Rowland said.
``But we're not in a position to rush anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Bootcheck has a four-pitch arsenal _ fastball (clocked at 94
mph), cut fastball/slider, curveball and changeup. But what the
Angels like equally is his intelligence and what they call an
ability to ``quickly absorb information.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I was tested in the conference I was in (Southeastern
Conference) and the opponents I faced,'' Bootcheck said. ``I feel I
proved myself the last couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Boras said he believes Bootcheck has the ability to reach the
majors faster than any other college pitcher in this year's draft.
He is also impressed with 17-year-old Torres.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the Angels could have come out of this draft
with two better pitchers than they have,'' Boras said.
</P>
<P>
   Bootcheck went 9-2 with a 3.76 ERA for Auburn last season and
was 25-10 with a 4.73 ERA in his three years at the school.
</P>
<P>
   COACHES RE-SIGNED: The Angels announced they have renewed the
contracts of the entire major-league coaching staff for the 2001
season.
</P>
<P>
   Returning are pitching coach Bud Black, hitting coach Mickey
Hatcher, third-base coach Ron Roenicke, first-base coach Alfredo
Griffin, bench coach Joe Maddon, bullpen coach Bobby Ramos and
bullpen catcher Orlando Mercado.
</P>
<P>
   PLAYOFF IMPLICATIONS: A series of coin tosses were conducted to
decide the sites of potential one-game playoffs should the AL West
or wild-card race end in a tie.
</P>
<P>
   If the Angels tie with Seattle for the division crown, the two
teams will play at Edison Field. If the Angels and A's tie for the
division, they will play in Oakland. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
