<HEADLINE>
INJURED VALDES DROPS APPEAL OF SUSPENSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Right-hander Ismael Valdes dropped an appeal of his
six-game suspension and began serving it Tuesday, but it's possible
he's already made his last start with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are contemplating keeping Eric Gagne and rookie
right-hander Luke Prokopec in the rotation to prepare for next
season. With Valdes eligible for free agency after the season, the
club might place him in a long-relief role, a club official said.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes can return Monday against Arizona, but the Dodgers want
to get Gagne as many starts as possible. They also want to see more
of Prokopec, who made his first major-league start Tuesday, so they
can evaluate his standing.
</P>
<P>
   Gagne and Prokopec are slated to start this weekend against
Colorado and they could remain in the rotation for the final two
weeks of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``With (17) games to go, decisions about personnel and whatever,
to me, are very important,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said.
``Until you're mathematically eliminated, I'm never giving up. But
there are also questions (for which) you want to get some
information to help you answer for the future of this
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Valdes was scratched from his start Monday because of numbness
in his right pinkie and was replaced by Gagne. Even so, Valdes said
he could have pitched Monday, but team doctors urged him to sit out
so he didn't further aggravate the injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a plan before (Monday), but circumstances changed the
plan,'' Valdes said. ``We were going to wait until the appeal. I
could have pitched, but they didn't want to take a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' future plan, at this point, doesn't involve Valdes.
But he said he wanted to pitch again this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to finish this year and prepare myself for next year as
best I can this winter,'' said Valdes, a combined 2-7 with a 5.64
ERA with the Dodgers and Cubs this season. ``I have to get ready
for next season, because next season is going to be a very, very
important season for me.''
</P>
<P>
   GREEN STILL BLUE: It's been a season of adjustment for right
fielder Shawn Green, who's had a miserable time of it offensively
for the past three-plus months.
</P>
<P>
   He got off to a hot start and batted .337 through May, but since
the All-Star break Green's batting .239 with 11 homers and 36 RBI.
It's not easy to blame his struggles on the general pitfalls of
returning home under a big contract. Green, who grew up in Orange
County, is batting .308 at home but .239 on the road.
</P>
<P>
   While Green's power numbers _ he has 24 homers _ have
dramatically dropped from the last two seasons, when he hit 35 and
42 homers, he's still within five RBI of his third straight 100-RBI
season.
</P>
<P>
   ODDS AND ENDS: Second baseman Mark Grudzielanek was held out of
the lineup because of a bruised right thumb and because he's 5 for
31 (.161) in his career against Curt Schilling. Grudzielanek is
listed as day to day. Jeff Branson started at second in his place.
... Tom Goodwin's bunt single in the sixth pushed his hitting
streak to 13 games, tying a career high. It also matches the
highest for a Dodgers player this season. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
