<SLUG> BC-BKW-UTA-COACH-RESIGNS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UTA WOMEN'S BASKETBALL COACH CHANGING PROFESSIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DARRIN SCHEID 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Mike Dean said he still loves basketball, but
he hates worrying about recruiting, next year's schedule and how
the heck you beat Southland Conference rival Stephen F. Austin.
</P>
<P>
   UT-Arlington's women's coach for the past eight years resigned
Tuesday to pursue a business opportunity in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   He said basketball coaching and the job's anxiety not only takes
time he would spend with from his wife, Lisa, it consumes his mind
every minute for 365 days a year. Most of all, Dean said, it was
not making him a better person.
</P>
<P>
   Dean's resignation is effective Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I've been thinking about for about two years,''
Dean said. ``Basketball is hard on me. Your job can't be more
important than your life, and for me, my life was my job. I don't
want it to be like that any more.''
</P>
<P>
   In the search for a replacement, UTA athletic director Pete
Carlon said he would consider assistant coaches Kim Dowell and
Robert Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Carlon said he wants to fill the position by Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Dean, 37, has spent the past 16 years coaching basketball,
including a four-year stint as an assistant coach at Arkansas State
before taking his first NCAA Division I head coaching position at
UTA. He walks away from a $67,500 salary without much knowledge of
the job he is about to take.
</P>
<P>
   Dean said he is going into a start-up investment business with
two friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really know anything about what I'll be doing, but I
plan to learn, and I'm excited about starting over and doing
something different,'' Dean said. ``I'm ready to be a regular guy.
I want to spend time with my wife. I want us to be together and not
necessarily have basketball rule my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Dean is the second coach in UTA history to reach more than 100
victories in a career. He was 115-105 overall and had five winning
seasons. UTA's 1998-99 team was invited to the Women's National
Invitation Tournament, the Mavericks' only national postseason
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Dean's teams became known for playing stingy defense, and the
Mavericks were consistently ranked among the Division I leaders in
fewest points allowed. The 1997-98 squad gave up 56.7 points per
game, No. 7 nationally.
</P>
<P>
   He informed his players in a meeting Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all pretty shocked,'' said UTA junior forward Patrice
Sims, a transfer who did not play last season. ``Coach Dean stood
by me the past year and I really looked forward to playing for him.
I guess that won't happen. It's time for us to pull together as a
team and get through this.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
