<HEADLINE>
BAYLOR SEEKS ANOTHER TASTE OF '96 AGAINST MINNESOTA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Having won their season opener for the first time
since 1996, the Baylor Bears now welcome the challenge of making it
two in a row ... also a feat last accomplished in '96.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, sure it would be a big step for us,'' says second-year
coach Kevin Steele, whose team will play host to Minnesota (1-1) at
11:30 a.m. Saturday. ``And yes, if you asked the players, they
would probably say this is a big game. But really, we're just
trying to take it week by week. We know that at some point we will
win two straight, then three, then four ...''
</P>
<P>
   Steele did note, however, that while beating North Texas two
weeks ago was great fun, beating the Gophers would be a step up.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're big, strong, coming off a bowl year, playing with a
lot of confidence, very physical,'' Steele said of the Gophers.
``They average about 308 pounds across the offensive line, and all
of those guys are about 6-\Rfoot\S-6 to 6-7.''
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota did, however, lose Saturday to Ohio University, 23-17,
at home. Steele attributed that loss to the Gophers' difficulty
handling Ohio's wishbone offense, which rolled up 363 yards
rushing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also have an option package, which we practice every week,
but it's not the same thing, and it's something Minnesota can
probably handle,'' Steele said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gophers also can mount an impressive pass rush, led by SMU
transfer Karon Riley, whom Steele describes as ``basically your
sleek, get-off-the-ball-quick, relentless type of guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Which leads to the obvious query of quarterback Greg Cicero,
about to start his second NCAA Division I-A game: Can that good ol'
Baylor line give him enough time to throw the ball?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not my job to worry about it,'' Cicero said, smoothly.
``That's the offensive line's job, and if we're having a problem,
the coaches will make an adjustment.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, Cicero's jaunty self-confidence might be the key
ingredient separating the Bears from their recent predecessors, but
he is quick to add that this is indeed a big test for Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Minnesota is a Big Ten team, and they draw a lot more
attention than North Texas and have a lot more national prestige,''
he said. ``It would really be a big thing for us if we could knock
them off. To do that, we have to control the ball and avoid
turnovers, because they live off turnovers. That's all I want to
do, win the game. I'm not going out there to try to be Superman.''
\Nsubheds:Briefly Saturday's game will be televised as the regional
Big 12 Game of the Week and shown locally on KDFI/Channel 27.
</P>
<P>
   Karon Riley, who played two years at SMU, led the Big Ten with
16 sacks last season and is a preseason All-American. Receiver Jack
Brewer is also an SMU ex who was the Mustangs' leading receiver in
'97. Brewer, from Grapevine High School, is the cousin of running
back Tellis Redmon, who played at Grapevine and Colleyville
Heritage. Redmon has rushed for 168 yards in two games.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, the Bears' main concern is stopping the home run.
``They throw the deep ball very well, and they do it often enough
that they'll probably hit one for a score sometime during the
game,'' Kevin Steele said. ``The concern is to make sure they don't
do it two or three times.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
