<SLUG> BC-FBC-TCU-NORTHWESTERN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROGS LOOK TO AVENGE TOUGH '99 LOSS TO NORTHWESTERN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ARTHUR GARCIA 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The Horned Frogs circled this game coming
into the season. Going up against a Big Ten foe in the home-opener
is a measuring stick, sure, but it's also an opportunity to make
amends for last season.
</P>
<P>
   Northwestern's 17-7 victory in Evanston, Ill., doesn't sit well
with the players, who believe they gave the game away in the fourth
quarter. The Frogs had several chances to at least tie the score in
fourth quarter, including a drive inside the Northwestern 10-yard
line that ended in a fumble.
</P>
<P>
   TCU coach Dennis Franchione said Tuesday at his weekly news
conference that coaching mistakes leading up to the game had as
much to do with the outcome as on-field miscues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not play well in this game last year and I had told the
guys, and I'm not trying to discredit Northwestern's victory, that
last year's loss was my fault,'' Franchione said. ``Totally my
fault. I take the responsibility, burden for it.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU played Arizona on Sunday night, six days before a Saturday
morning game at Northwestern. TCU lost to Arizona, 35-31, and the
loss was not only physically draining, but emotionally exhausting,
as well.
</P>
<P>
   Playing on Sunday eliminated more than a day of practice time to
prepare for the Wildcats, and left Franchione with a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a head coach, you've got a decision to come \Rand
practice\S Monday, because you don't have Sunday and then a day
off,'' he said, referring to the team's normal Monday off-day.
``So, you have to make a decision about how you're going to go into
this next week. Here's what you have to weigh: You're supposed to
improve from Game 1 to Game 2. But if you don't practice, how do
you improve? On the same token, \Rthere is\S almost a day-and-half
less preparation.
</P>
<P>
   ``A day-and-a-half in a football player's week is quite a bit in
\Rlost\S recovery and preparation time. So, I probably pushed them
too hard in Week 2 to improve and maybe went into the game a little
dead-legged, a little tired.''
</P>
<P>
   Franchione said that if given the chance, ``I'd probably do it a
little different.'' On the other hand, he firmly believes ``it
helped us in the long run become a better football team.''
</P>
<P>
   Not one to help the Wildcats prepare for the No. 20 Frogs,
Franchione kept it close to the vest Saturday against Nevada. The
game plan was simple: wear down the Wolf Pack at the point of
attack with both the offensive and defensive lines. More than 300
yards rushing and 15 sacks, and a 41-10 victory, safely
accomplished that mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could we have done some other things? Probably. Did we need
to? Nah,'' Franchione said. ``We don't need to show anymore than we
need to show ... The first game you're never quite sure what to
think about yourself. I'd like to think with the number of seniors
and starters \Rback\S, I had a little bit of an idea, but you can
always be fooled. I did not know if Nevada could beat us. I did
know we could lose to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Northwestern goes into Saturday's game 2-0 for the first time
since 1975 and gunning for its first 3-0 start in 38 years. The
Wildcats, 3-8 last season, downed Duke, 38-5, behind a career-high
187 yards rushing from Damien Anderson and Zak Kustok's 197 yards
passing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any doubt they're better'' than last
year, Franchione said. \Nsubheds:Injury update Defensive end Aaron
Schobel (bruised right hip), linebacker Shannon Brazzell (right
knee sprain) and safety/returner LaVar Veale (right ankle sprain)
practiced Tuesday. Schobel and Veale did light work, while
Brazzell, closer to 100 percent, went at it harder. Franchione
expects all three to play Saturday.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
