<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-SOCCER-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELECTING BEST, WORST IN MLS SEASON HAS UPS AND DOWNS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BLANE BACHELOR 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With Major League Soccer's regular season wrapping up over the
weekend, here are some of the ups, downs, bests and worsts of the
league's fifth year:
</P>
<P>
   League MVP: This is a tough one to pick. Tampa Bay striker
Mamadou Diallo lit up the stats with 26 goals in 28 games in his
first season in MLS, though his bruising, physical style of play
has slightly tainted that production. Teammate and legendary
Colombian midfielder Carlos Valderrama makes a strong case with a
league-record 26 assists. MetroStars midfielder and forward Clint
Mathis flourished after a midseason trade from Los Angeles, scoring
13 goals and adding 13 assists in 20 games with New York/New
Jersey. Kansas City goalkeeper Tony Meola registered a
league-record 15 shutouts and posted an 0.89 goals-against average.
</P>
<P>
   Gotta give it to Diallo, despite the outcry over his style.
Nearly a goal a game is impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Coach of the Year: Kansas City's Bob Gansler. In his first full
season with the Wizards, Gansler has brought the franchise
unprecedented success. The Wizards won the Western Division title
after missing the playoffs for three consecutive seasons.
</P>
<P>
   A close runner-up is the MetroStars' Octavio Zambrano, who
guided a team with a 7-25 record a year ago to its first division
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Top newcomer: Toss-up between Kansas City defender Nick Garcia
or Chicago defender Carlos Bocanegra. Both left early from college
and have adjusted perfectly to the professional level, playing
critical roles in their team's respective successes.
</P>
<P>
   Good news for the league is that this year's influx of
youngsters such as Garcia, Bocanegra and Bobby Convey of D.C.
United has started to move MLS into the ranks of other professional
leagues in which bypassing college or leaving early is a viable
option.
</P>
<P>
   Biggest letdown: Midfielder Lothar Matthaus, the aging German
superstar who was supposed to help lift the MetroStars. But the
rise of the team had little to do with Matthaus, who made more
headlines with his bratty behavior and weak excuses than he did
with his play. San Jose's Khodadad Azizi, the highly touted striker
who became the first Iranian player in MLS, also is a candidate.
Unfortunately, injuries kept him from playing much. And D.C.
midfielder Marco Etcheverry, ``El Diablo,'' was ejected in the
season opener and remained virtually invisible this season for
struggling United.
</P>
<P>
   With his $1 million price tag, Matthaus gets the nod.
</P>
<P>
   Best rivalry: Hands down, the Burn and the Chicago Fire. Fitting
names for teams that put on heated battles any time they meet. They
have played an astounding 17 times in only three seasons, and after
last season's bruising first-round playoffs series, you can bet
both teams were probably breathing a sigh of relief when Chad
Deering scored the game-winner Saturday against San Jose. A tie
would have meant yet another first-round playoff pairing for the
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Best resurgence: Hands down, Tony Meola. The former U.S.
national team 'keeper has had several lackluster and injury-riddled
seasons before this year, but he has been healthy all season and
has played a major role in the Wizards' astonishing turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   Best disappearing act: D.C. United, which fell from its
perennial perch atop the league to the cellar. United has woes off
the field as well: The deal to sell the team to a new
owner-investor fell through last week.
</P>
<P>
   Best excuse to miss a game: Colorado rookie Seth Trembly missed
a regular-season game because he was attending his high school
prom. With the increase of younger players entering the league, we
might see more of the same excuses in the future.
</P>
<P>
   MLS's fifth season has offered more ups and downs than any
other. We'll see what else shakes out during the playoffs.
\Nsubheds:Olympic soccer begins today Olympic soccer is scheduled
to kick off early this morning, Central time, with the U.S. facing
the Czech Republic in Canberra, Australia, at 4 a.m. CDT. In other
matches scheduled today, Nigeria faces Honduras, Cameroon plays
Kuwait, and Australia takes on Italy.
</P>
<P>
   The competition will be void of some global standouts because of
injuries, as well as the longstanding red-tape power struggles
between the International Olympic Committee and FIFA, soccer's
worldwide governing body. IOC rules limit players over the age of
23 to three per roster, but the clubs of those players often
hesitate to release their highly paid standouts. \Nsubheds:Ratings
high Even though the Burn was not playing in any of the three
games, the Dallas market recorded the highest overnight ratings of
any of the MLS markets for the last three games televised on ABC
this year. Also, for the Aug. 6 game between the MetroStars and
Chicago, the Dallas market topped all markets, both MLS and
non-MLS. Following are the overnight ratings for the three ABC
games: Date game National Dallas Aug. 16 NY/NJ vs. Chicago 1.2 2.7
Aug. 12 Tampa Bay vs. San Jose 1.0 1.8 Aug. 19 Los Angeles vs.
Chicago 0.9 2.4 \Nsubheds:Essay contest Nokia, Radio Shack and U.S.
Youth Soccer are sponsoring an online essay contest to determine
the ``Soccer Mom &AMP; Dad of the Year Award.'' The contest runs
through Sept. 30 and is accessible at www.youthsoccer.org.
</P>
<P>
   One soccer mom and one soccer dad will be chosen to represent
each of the four U.S. Youth Soccer regions. Of the eight
representatives, one mom and one dad will be chosen. Winners will
each receive a Nokia wireless phone, $1,000 in adidas clothing, and
a new Chevy Venture minivan. \Nsubheds:Briefly MLS executive vice
president Ivan Gazidis announced Tuesday that the league will
shorten the regular season from 32 to 28 games. Gazidis said the
date for the 2001 season to start is not definite, but some reports
have it starting in early April.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado Rapids midfielder/forward Paul Bravo, who scored an
overtime goal Friday to clinch the final playoff spot for Colorado
in a 1-0 victory against the Los Angeles Galaxy, has been selected
the final MLS Player of the Week for the 2000 season. Bravo, the
Rapids' all-time leading scorer, scored with 3:44 remaining.
nn
</P>
