<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-DEFENSEMEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS' FRIENDS ARE FOES IN BATTLE FOR POSITION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VAIL, Colo. _ The word ``and'' usually connects Richard
Jackman's name with Brad Lukowich's.
</P>
<P>
   Jackman and Lukowich are defensemen.
</P>
<P>
   Jackman and Lukowich are roommates.
</P>
<P>
   Jackman and Lukowich are good friends.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to the two open spots as the Stars' third
defensive pair, their names are connected by the word ``or,'' as in
either Jackman or Lukowich will be playing there with someone else.
The Stars don't want Jackman and Lukowich as the No. 5 and 6
defensemen because the team needs a more physical presence in that
pairing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the role of the sixth defenseman, and that role is
sitting there through exhibition for a \RJohn\S Erskine or a
\RSami\S Helenius,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``We
anticipate that sixth position being a physical position. Who it
will be, I don't know, but that's the position. The fifth guy will
be a guy who moves the puck.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said the fifth guy is likely to be Jackman or
Lukowich.
</P>
<P>
   There's the dreaded ``or'' word again. But for a Stars bunch
that lost big banger bodies when winger Scott Thornton and
defenseman Dave Manson departed via free agency, they can't afford
not to add a little toughness to the lineup. The No. 6 defenseman
spot seems like the perfect place.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it doesn't hurt that Erskine, Helenius and Dan
Jancevski are having much better training camps than anybody hoped.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning of the summer, I heard they didn't sign
Manson or whatever, and I heard they were keeping that spot open,''
Erskine said. ``And when camp began, Hitch said there is a few
spots open. He didn't say where they were, but everyone is fighting
for whatever spot is open.''
</P>
<P>
   Erskine, Helenius or Jancevski could easily fill the physical
role by size alone.
</P>
<P>
   Jancevski is the smallest, at 6 feet, 2 inches and 211 pounds,
which would make him the second-biggest defenseman in the Stars'
lineup behind 6-5, 230-pound Derian Hatcher. And if Hatcher misses
even one meal, Helenius could take that spot from him. He's 6-5,
225 pounds, with Erskine not far behind at 6-4, 213.
</P>
<P>
   ``Erskine takes after Hatch, a bigger guy,'' said Hatcher's
defensive partner, Richard Matvichuk. ``I think Luke and Jack are
more like myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad comparison considering Matvichuk was once a
freewheeling defenseman and has developed into the stay-at-home,
banging physical kind. The kind, Hitchcock said, he'd like for his
No. 5 to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an ideal world, we'd like the fifth guy to be physical,
too,'' Hitchcock said. ``But those guys are hard to find.''
</P>
<P>
   So the bodies fly during scrimmages as Erskine, Jancevski,
Helenius, Jackman and Lukowich all try to prove that they are that
guy to the note-taking coaches and scouts and, yes, general
manager, watching from the stands at Dobson Ice Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The players know what will happen if they don't.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm not, he'll go get someone else,'' Lukowich said, ``like
two guys from Chicago.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars acquired Manson from Chicago before the trading
deadline last season to bolster their lineup before the playoff
run. They're hoping they don't have to this season. It certainly
looks like they have enough in-house candidates to fill the three
open spots behind Hatcher, Matvichuk, Sergei Zubov and Darryl
Sydor. The third open spot is for a reserve, who wouldn't be active
for most games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we knew where the seven defensemen were coming from,
but two or three more have got in that mix,'' Hitchcock said.
``That's a big difference. There is competition and people now
realize who they are competing against for positions on the team.
It's getting very intense.''
</P>
<P>
   And Jackman or Lukowich could find themselves in the press box
looking down. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
