<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SELMA-MAYOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING HISTORY AT THE POLLS, SELMA ELECTS A BLACK MAYOR 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Joseph T. Smitherman, the former segregationist who
has been mayor of Selma, Ala., through 35 of the most restless
years in the Deep South, lost his tenth bid for re-election on
Tuesday night after a newly unified black electorate threw its
support to James Perkins Jr., a former computer consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins, 47, who had run against Smitherman twice before, will
become the first black mayor in the history of Selma, a city of
21,000 famous for its bloody response to the civil rights marches
of 1965 that led to the Voting Rights Act.
</P>
<P>
   Unofficial returns showed that Perkins won 57 percent of the
votes in the runoff election, while Smitherman won 43 percent. As
supporters of Perkins filled the streets and crossed back and forth
over the Edmund Pettus Bridge _ where hundreds of marchers were
beaten by sheriff's deputies in 1965 _ Smitherman ruefully
conceded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I put up a pretty damn good fight,'' he said in a
telephone interview from his home, ``but the blacks decided they
wanted a change, and now they've got one. They brought in all these
celebrities to energize the voters, and I didn't think it would
work, but I guess it did.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to a slogan used repeatedly by his opponents, he
added, ``They always said, `Joe gotta go,' and now Joe gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Smitherman won previous elections by getting most of the white
vote and enough black votes to achieve a majority, even though the
city has been mostly black for decades. Perkins was able to
assemble black voters into a majority, building on a financial
scandal in the mayor's last term and a sense in the city that
Smitherman, who is 70, had served long enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many have said and many have felt that this was about James
Perkins and Joe Smitherman, and that's not true,'' Perkins said at
a victory rally. ``Many have said it's about black and white. That
ain't so. This campaign has been about faith and fear. Faith won
this campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   The turnout was heavy, reflecting the surge in interest in the
race since Perkins forced Smitherman into a runoff for the first
time last month. Several civil rights leaders from around the
country came to Selma to support Perkins.
</P>
<P>
   Although Smitherman was mayor during the 1965 march, he always
said he was a moderate segregationist who played no role in the
beatings, an assertion confirmed by many of those who were there.
Over the years he acknowledged being ``on the wrong side of
history,'' appointing many black department heads and trying to
spread city services evenly around the city. He had gradually grown
more isolated as the City Council and the County Commission were
dominated by black elected officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-00 0116EDT &QL; 
