<HEADER>
A1606 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-BLUEJAYS-NY     09-13 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-BLUEJAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES CRUSH BLUE JAYS, 10-2 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He had his passion for playing baseball criticized by
the blustery principal owner of the Yankees, so he barked back. He
has been bothered by so many elbow, wrist and forearm injuries that
he could do a cameo on ``E.R.'' He had such a terrible defensive
game one night in June that the manager mercifully suggested he
leave Yankee Stadium before the contest was even over.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch has already endured a torturous and tumultuous
season, a season unlike any in his 10-year career. Knoblauch's
chronic throwing problems have not disappeared as much as they have
been tempered by his lack of playing time at second base. His next
throw could aggravate the tendinitis in his right elbow, the ball
could flutter like a Frisbee and cause George Steinbrenner to
screech again, or it could be accurate. It has been that perplexing
for Knoblauch.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees understand the importance of having a competent
Knoblauch leading off as they prepare for another postseason, and
that was underscored in their 10-2 victory over the Blue Jays on
Tuesday night at the Stadium. Knoblauch stroked a critical two-run
triple off Joey Hamilton in the second inning that gave Denny
Neagle an early cushion and helped him win his fourth straight
start.
</P>
<P>
   David Cone will return to the starting rotation after
dislocating his left shoulder eight days ago, but Neagle's
emergence has almost certainly made Cone's return Friday an
audition for the bullpen in October. Neagle (7-4) pitched
splendidly and received a standing ovation after allowing two runs
while whiffing seven in seven and two-thirds innings. Still, even
Neagle lauded Knoblauch.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's patented Knoblauch tonight,'' Neagle said. ``We all
know what he can do for us. I know his elbow is still sore, but
he's playing through the pain. He is going to get even better, and
that's going to make us stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   With Knoblauch providing the spark, Neagle providing the
pitching and Jose Canseco providing the power with three hits and
three runs batted in, the Yanks began a 10-day period in which they
will play the Blue Jays six times and the Indians four times. The
Yankees lead the American League East by eight games over the Red
Sox, but they will influence the wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   As the Yankees prepared for a run at their third straight World
Series title, Manager Joe Torre will continue tweaking them until
he believes they are ready. Torre needs relievers Mike Stanton and
Jeff Nelson to be sharper, and he needs the rotation to stay
effective. The piece that has been missing for over a month is
Knoblauch's tenacity atop the lineup. That is why Knoblauch's
simple contributions on Tuesday night loomed large.
</P>
<P>
   ``We traded for him and won two World Series with him,'' Torre
said. ``That tells you how important he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch, who had been sidelined since Aug. 3, returned to the
lineup on Sept. 6. It was less than a week after Steinbrenner
inferred that Knoblauch was hesitant to return because of his
throwing woes.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, Knoblauch is looking more as if he is really back. He
walked on four pitches in his first at-bat against the wobbly
Hamilton. With the Yankees up, 2-1, with two outs and runners on
second and third in the second, Knoblauch flicked a liner to right.
Chad Mottola should have let it drop for a single, but he dived
awkwardly, flailed at a ball that bounced five feet in front of him
and had it slither by him for a triple. It was just Knoblauch's
second hit in 19 at-bats since he was activated.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he gets going on offense,'' Tino Martinez said, ``he's a
pain to the other team.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch also ranged about 30 feet to his left to make a nice
stop and a strong off-balance throw in the fourth. But Torre still
replaced him with Jose Vizcaino to start the seventh, saying,
``That's what we do here.''
</P>
<P>
   Canseco belted a two-run shot into the left-field seats to make
the score 6-1 in the fourth, pausing briefly after he hit it to
stare at his bat and make sure it was not cracked. Like Knoblauch,
Canseco is another piece the Yankees need but have not had all
season. Like Knoblauch, Canseco's body is still healing after a
long stint on the disabled list. There is a different feeling when
Canseco bats at the Stadium, and the fans booed as he was
intentionally walked in the seventh. Ryan Thompson followed with a
three-run double.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a 6-1 lead in the fifth, Neagle encountered a ticklish
situation when Toronto loaded the bases with no outs. After Alex
Gonzalez singled in the second run, Mottola hit a pop down the
right-field line. Martinez scooted toward the stands, but the wind
pushed the ball into fair territory and Martinez had to deftly
lunge to his left to snare it.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Neagle could not exhale. Carlos Delgado, the favorite to
win the most valuable player award and a Triple Crown candidate,
was the next batter. Delgado smacked a hard grounder to Martinez,
who flipped the ball to Derek Jeter, who then tossed it back to
Neagle covering first for a nifty and timely double play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
