<HEADER>
A1629 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-PRIMARY-RDP-ART-1S     09-13 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PRIMARY-RDP-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORBES BATTLING IN LONG ISLAND; FIRST LADY WINS EASILY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating, rewriting throughout)  (ART ADV: Photos _ NYT 11,12,17,27 _ are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Attacked from all sides, U.S. Rep. Michael P. Forbes,
a Republican-turned Democrat from Long Island, was locked in a
dead-even struggle with his primary challenger on Tuesday night and
was one of the few incumbents who did not easily prevail in
contests that were marked by unusual rancor this season.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, of Quogue, acknowledged on Tuesday night that his race
against Regina Seltzer, 71, of Bellport, a longtime Democrat, was
too close to call. With Republicans clinging to a narrow majority
in the House, both national and state party officials had channeled
money and advertising into the district early on to sway even
Democrats to vote against the man who infuriated the Republicans by
switching parties in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from Washington late Tuesday night,
Forbes sounded resigned to whatever the outcome was, saying that
his adoptive party voters ``had a hard time accepting that Mike
Forbes embraced the same values they do,'' especially his fiscal
conservatism and his opposition to abortion.
</P>
<P>
   This primary election was also the first in which the name of a
first lady was on the ballot, with Hillary Rodham Clinton easily
winning the Democratic nomination for the U.S. Senate against Mark
S. McMahon, a little-known Manhattan orthopedic surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   With 98 percent of the vote counted, Clinton received 82 percent
of the vote, with McMahon receiving 18 percent. Aides to Clinton's
Republican opponent, Rep. Rick Lazio, had forecast that Clinton
would be viewed as a particularly weak contender for the November
general election if her opponent in the Democratic primary received
30 percent of the vote. Still, McMahon's showing suggested that
Clinton must contend with a group of Democratic voters who dislike
her.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of the congressional primary on Long Island,
Tuesday's races drew a light voter turnout and produced decisive
victories for several incumbent members of Congress and for most
incumbents in the State Legislature, according to unofficial
returns reported by The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   In Forbes's race, Seltzer, a lawyer who served from 1976 to 1980
on the Brookhaven Town Board, campaigned vigorously, although she
was outspent by Forbes. Seltzer stressed that, although Forbes
became a Democrat, he continued to cast his votes with the
Republican majority in the House on tax bills.
</P>
<P>
   She also stressed her support of a woman's right to choose
abortion while highlighting Forbes's opposition to the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes maintained that he has remained the same fiscal
conservative he always was and that he would continue to guard the
environment, balance the budget and reduce taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night's primaries also included third-party candidates
in the Senate race. The Independence Party, New York's arm of the
national Reform Party, fielded two candidates, and Jeff Graham, the
former mayor of Watertown, emerged victorious. The Green Party
offered up three candidates, and its winner won't be known for
several days because it was forced to use paper ballots in New York
City. Its candidates were Al Lewis, formerly known as ``Grandpa''
on ``The Munsters''; Ronnie Dugger, founding editor of the Texas
Observer; and Mark Dunau, an organic farmer.
</P>
<P>
   On the Right-to-Life line, Louis Wein, a Republican, was in a
dead heat with John Adefope, a telephone company engineer, for that
nomination. With nearly all precincts reporting, the race was too
close to call.
</P>
<P>
   Primary day began in Chappaqua with votes by Mrs. Clinton and
her husband at the Douglas G. Grafflin Elementary School in their
new hometown of Chappaqua, N.Y. The two arrived at 7:15 a.m. to a
waiting throng of photographers and reporters to cast their votes
in the sole voting booth in the school's lobby.
</P>
<P>
   After signing photographs and shaking hands with residents
outside the school lobby, Mrs. Clinton went into the aqua blue
booth first, followed by her husband. Asked afterward how it felt
to see Mrs. Clinton on the ballot for the first time, President
Clinton said: ``It was a thrill. After all these years of her
helping me, it was a thrill. I loved it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton was more demure, saying only that it felt ``great''
to vote for herself. But later, talking to reporters at a nearby
delicatessen, she elaborated somewhat on the occasion. ``I stood
there for a minute,'' she said, ``staring at my name.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
