<P>
   TAX-AVOIDANCE (Undated) _ Treasury officials say that abusive
corporate tax shelters are the government's biggest tax enforcement
problem, costing billions of dollars annually and often escaping
detection by the depleted enforcement staff of the Internal Revenue
Service. Now, a company called Tax People is teaching similarly
dubious tax avoidance techniques to middle-class Americans and says
it has already signed up 50,000 of them. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   CHASE-MORGAN-HISTORY (New York) _ A look at the history of J.P.
Morgan, on the eve of it's being acquired by Chase Manhattan. By
Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   CHASE-BANKS-HISTORY (New York) _ A generation ago, six major
commercial banks dominated the financial world in New York, which
itself was the financial capital of the world's largest economy.
Now J.P. Morgan _ the last of those six to stay independent _ is
about to be bought, in the latest example of a trend toward
financial concentration. If the planned takeover by Chase Manhattan
is completed, it will bring together four of the six biggest banks
in New York, circa 1980. And yet the combination reflects weakness
as much as strength, as both institutions seek growth in areas
where their previous efforts have not been especially successful.
By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   BURGERKING-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ For months, Burger King has
sought to stimulate flagging sales of its fast fare with a
seductive appeal carrying the theme ``Got the urge?'' Tuesday, it
was Burger King that had the urge _ the same old urge the company
has had so often, to place the creative duties for its general
market advertising account in review. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   DRESDNER-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ On reports that Dresdner Bank
AG, Germany's third-largest bank, is in talks to buy the U.S.
investment bank Wasserstein Perella Co. By Laura M. Holson.
