r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-DIAMONDBA     09-13 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-DIAMONDBACKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS WASTE HANSEN'S HISTORIC HOMER, LOSE TO D'BACKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The Dodgers got a big home run to get back into a
ballgame late. But, once again, defensive mistakes were their
downfall.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly something you'd see on ``Ripley's Believe It Or Not.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Hansen, the most dangerous pinch hitter in the game, set a
major-league record with his seventh pinch-hit homer of the season,
but two errors early and a fielding gaffe in the eighth inning led
to Arizona's 5-4 win against the Dodgers on Tuesday at Bank One
Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks scored the winning run when shortstop Alex Cora
took an extra step to throw the ball on David Dellucci's slow
bouncer behind pitcher Matt Herges. Cora threw an instant late and
Dellucci was safe, allowing pinch runner Matt Mieske to score from
third.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I caught it, I was trying to get it on a short hop,''
Cora said. ``When I reached for it, that's when I got off-balance.
When I took a step to get back on balance, that was the difference.
When you make it, `Wow, great play.' When you don't, you feel like
I feel right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The left side of the infield is talented, but it's also young.
And with such youth comes mistakes. Cora, whose throwing error in
the fourth led to two unearned runs, has made 12 errors and third
baseman Adrian Beltre has 22.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona also scored an unearned run in the fifth inning when a
grounder went through the legs of second baseman Jeff Branson with
the infield playing in and a runner on third. That was the Dodgers'
major-league-leading 128th error. Their .977 field percentage is
also the worst in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   That type of defense also makes it tough on pitchers, especially
ones making their first major-league start like right-hander Luke
Prokopec. He wasn't involved in the decision after allowing four
runs (one earned) on six hits in 4 1/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's part of what we're going through, some young, talented
defensive players that make inexperienced mistakes,'' Dodgers
manager Davey Johnson said. ``It's only going to get better, but
it's tough to go through. Emotions sometimes get the best of them
and they'll rush things.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, a late-inning homer by Hansen _ who went deep on the
first pitch he saw from Curt Schilling _ was wasted. The three-run
shot with two outs in the seventh was his seventh pinch-hit homer
of the season. Brooklyn's Johnny Frederick hit six in 1932.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all surprise home runs to me,'' said Hansen, batting
.271 with seven homers and 14 RBI as a pinch-hitter. ``I can't try
and hit home runs. I'd be the worst hitter in the world. In fact,
every time I do, I end up popping it up.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
