<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 02:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1663 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-DEVILRAYS-     09-13 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-DEVILRAYS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD AND NEW PAY OFF FOR ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ This has been a season full of the unexpected
for the Angels, so Tuesday's game against the Tampa Bay Devil Rays
should have come as no surprise.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have relied heavily on their core group of big
hitters, but they have collectively and suddenly gone into a slump.
</P>
<P>
   Enter an old man and two babies, relatively speaking.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-eight-year-old pitcher Tim Belcher went seven strong
innings and rookies Bengie Molina and Adam Kennedy provided most of
the offense as the Angels beat the Devil Rays 5-2 in front of
15,689 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's two-run triple in the seventh was the key hit of the
night. He also had an RBI single. Molina had three hits and the
Angels scored in each inning he had a hit.
</P>
<P>
   Shigetoshi Hasegawa pitched a 1-2-3 eighth to set up Troy
Percival, who pitched a scoreless ninth for his 29th save.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the victory, the Angels remained six games behind the
Mariners in the AL West with 17 to play. The Mariners' magic number
to eliminate the Angels was reduced to 12.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher gave up a two-run homer to Greg Vaughn in the second
inning, but that was it. He made only 74 pitches in his seven
innings, giving up five hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to think I can do that every time,'' Belcher (4-2)
said. ``That was as pitch-efficient as I've been in a long time.
That's what I need to be good, the way I pitch now.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher said he was able to get through the night without an
effective splitter because he was able to spot his fastball and
slider enough. And giving up the homer to Vaughn didn't upset him
in the least.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't pay to get too wrapped up in your mistakes,''
Belcher said. ``Since coming to the American League, I've learned
not to get too upset about giving up even as many as four runs
early in the game. Some games in this league are like beer-league
softball.''
</P>
<P>
   But that hasn't been the case with the Angels lately.
</P>
<P>
   It was the pitching that was supposed to determine the Angels'
fate down the stretch, but it was the hitting that went south in
the previous four games against the Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels scored a total of eight runs in the series. It would
be difficult to credit the Orioles pitching staff, considering its
ERA of 5.46 is second-worst in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   Including Tuesday's game, the Angels core hitters _ Garret
Anderson, Darin Erstad, Mo Vaughn, Tim Salmon and Troy Glaus _ are
hitting a combined .184 (16 for 87) with two RBI on the homestand
(five games).
</P>
<P>
   Enter Molina and Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not always going to get the middle of the lineup hitting
the ball out of the ballpark,'' Angels manager Mike Scioscia said.
``To score five runs with little ball, Adam and Bengie coming
through in RBI situations, that was a huge lift for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's was the biggest of all. With the Angels down 2-1 with
one out in the seventh, he lined a pitch from Bryan Rekar (6-10)
into the right-center-field gap for his team-leading 10th triple of
the season. It scored Anderson and Molina for the Angels' first
lead of the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've stalled a little bit,'' Kennedy said of the offense.
``But the bottom of the lineup the last couple of nights has been
able to produce a little bit and take the pressure off the rest of
the lineup.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
