<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 02:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1667 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-ANALYSIS-B     09-13 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLOT THICKENS, PULSE QUICKENS 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-ANALYSIS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The pulse is faint, but still there is a pulse.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after a raw New York rookie stymied them in Fenway
Park, three days after Scott Brosius took Pedro Martinez deep and _
in the minds of many Red Sox fans _ ended all realistic hopes for
any comeback this season, the Red Sox are showing life. Pesky is
not just the name of a former Red Sox shortstop; it is the nature
of this team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every win is important,'' said shortstop Nomar Garciaparra,
once again proving to be the nemesis of nemeses to the Indians.
``We all know that. It's been like that all year for us. All we can
do is go out there and play hard and see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened Tuesday &UR;  &LR; night was a convincing 8-6 Boston win
over Cleveland as the teams began a staggering stretch of eight
games against each other in 10 days. The Indians' lead over the Red
Sox is now two games in the wild-card chase and, as Boston center
fielder Carl Everett put it, ``We've got to be close to perfect
from now on.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Everett went further.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest with you, we can't lose,'' said Everett. ``Every
game is big from now on. We're in a situation now where we can't
look at other teams. If we don't win, we don't go anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox have squandered too many opportunities this season
for their fans to be drawn back so easily into a true September
playoff chase with merely consecutive wins over the Yankees and
Indians.
</P>
<P>
   So, while we wait for Boston to either spring back to life after
being pronounced comatose late Sunday afternoon in Fenway Park, or
head to late September anonymity, at least enjoy the entertainment.
And Tuesday &UR;  &LR; night, the entertainment was plentiful.
</P>
<P>
   Consider: A third-inning fly ball to the warning track by
Cleveland's Robby Alomar with the bases loaded and none out that
resulted in monstrous gaffes by three players, two on Cleveland and
one on the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   First, Everett didn't even get his glove on the ball in deep
left center when he seemed ready to make a routine catch. It seemed
that, at the last moment, Everett might have been distracted by
left fielder Bernard Gilkey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't so much I was distracted,'' said Everett. ``I've
played with Gilkey before, so I've got to give myself the blame. I
called for it. I should have just ran on through it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Everett didn't.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed that at least two Indians would score, with the ball
bounding free 400 feet from home plate, and perhaps all three.
</P>
<P>
   But first Nomar came to the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra had his back to the plate when he took Everett's
relay in short left center and had no clue what he would see when
he turned to the plate. Least of all, Garciaparra didn't expect
that the speedy Kenny Lofton, who was on second when the play
started, might still be far from home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just turned and I threw it,'' said Garciaparra, who let
loose a laser to catcher Jason Varitek. ``I wasn't able to look
behind me and see where (Lofton) was at.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lofton hadn't scored when Garciaparra threw the ball. In
fact, he not only slowed up as he approached the plate, but he also
didn't slide. All the while, Cleveland's next hitter, Manny
Ramirez, was the ultimate wooden Indian as he stood near the plate
and did not signal Lofton to slide. Lofton was easily tagged out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already talked to Manny,'' said Cleveland manager Charlie
Manuel. ``He's got to signal to Kenny to slide, but he didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   When all the gaffes had been weighed and measured, a possibly
huge Cleveland inning was reduced to a mere two-run rally, closing
Boston's lead to only 6-3. But after Red Sox starter Ramon Martinez
saw his gas tank show ``empty'' at the usual five-inning mark, Red
Sox relievers came on and shut down the Indians, who had crawled
back to 6-5.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, yes, the Red Sox relievers.
</P>
<P>
   High comedy erupted in the bottom of the seventh when Boston's
Rod Beck rushed in from the bullpen, only to stop 100 feet from the
infield when he saw Hector Carrasco take the mound for a second
inning of relief. Beck returned to the bullpen in embarrassment,
only to be summoned back moments later.
</P>
<P>
   ``They called down and they said I was in the game and I got hot
(warmed up),'' said Beck. ``So they open the gate and I was going
out there, and I see Hector's still throwing on the mound. So I
look in the dugout and (pitching coach Joe) Kerrigan waved me back.
So I went back to the bullpen, sat down, toweled off. I mean, I was
totally hot then. I was ready to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little embarrassing when you run out there. It makes
you look like you don't know what the hell you're doing. I've seen
it happen to other guys before. But it's the first time I've done
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Beck eventually was summoned back, pitched two strong innings of
scoreless relief, and could joke later about his comings and
goings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turned out that they had told Hector he was done,'' said
Beck, ``and he didn't understand. That's all right. It worked out
all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more hijinks erupted in the eighth when the Red Sox scored
two more runs, keyed by a Manny Alexander infield single after he
conked himself on the head with his own bat while trying to lay
down a sacrifice bunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I finally got the job done, move the runners over,'' said
Alexander. ``That's all that counts. Get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   And dead as they were Sunday evening in Boston, the new flicker
of life was aptly summed up by Red Sox designated hitter Dante
Bichette, who carefully reached into his locker and put on his Red
Sox cap before talking into the TV cameras about his two-run homer
in the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the hardest thing about coming to a new team,'' said
Bichette. ``Trying too hard to make an impression too fast.''
</P>
<P>
   But after the homer, Bichette felt he was part of the Red Sox.
The team that is, well, still alive and still pesky.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
