u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-INDIANS-BO     09-13 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX SHOW LIFE IN SHOWDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-INDIANS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Knockdown pitches. Home run dramas. Baseball
brinksmanship as two bitter rivals battled before a shrieking
sellout crowd for everything they staked their seasons on back in
the April chill.
</P>
<P>
   For all his steely restraint, even Red Sox manager Jimy Williams
could not help but distill his team's crucial showdown with the
Indians to its essence Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is more of a playoff situation for us,'' said Williams,
who normally would rather suck exhaust in stalled traffic on the
Central Artery than discuss the burden of New England's unrequited
lust for a championship.
</P>
<P>
   And the Sox, who last year roared back from a 2-0 deficit to
steal the Division Series from the startled Indians, looked again
like Comeback Kids, as they stunned Cleveland, 8-6, in the opener
of a three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   The victory narrowed Cleveland's lead in the wild-card struggle
to two games over the Sox, sending a scare through Indians country
with Pedro Martinez prepared to pitch the finale Thursday night.
Tomo Ohka starts Wednesday night for the Sox in a game the Indians
would lose at their peril.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every game we play against Cleveland brings back some very
good memories from last year,'' said Pedro's big brother, Ramon,
who earned the win because Boston scored enough runs to overcome
his shaky outing. ``It was nice to start on the right foot.''
</P>
<P>
   More than nice. With the Sox and Indians scheduled to play five
more games next week at Fenway, players on both sides viewed
Tuesday &UR;  &LR; night's game as the opener of an eight-game series that
will determine their fates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a huge win,'' said closer Derek Lowe, who picked up his
33d save despite a fright in the ninth. ``The first game of any
series is big, but especially when you're playing Cleveland.''
</P>
<P>
   Good for the Sox that their bats remained hot a second straight
night. The night before, they rode a pair of two-run homers past
the Yankees in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday &UR;  &LR; night, they pummeled Cleveland's talented lefty
starter, Chuck Finley, for six runs in a third-inning thrashing
that helped spare Martinez from defeat. After Manny Alexander drew
a one-out walk, the Sox banged out five straight hits: a perfectly
executed hit-and-run single by Darren Lewis, singles by Jose
Offerman and Nomar Garciaparra, a double by Carl Everett, and a
413-foot home run by Dante Bichette.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chuck got the ball up a few times,'' Bichette said with a
touch of understatement, ``and we capitalized.''
</P>
<P>
   But they were philanthropic, too. In Cleveland's half of the
third, for instance, Martinez and Everett helped the Indians narrow
their deficit. After Martinez gave up a single to Sandy Alomar,
walked Kenny Lofton, and hit Omar Vizquel in the backside to load
the bases, Roberto Alomar lifted a high fly to the warning track in
left-center.
</P>
<P>
   Left fielder Bernard Gilkey and center fielder Everett camped
comfortably under the ball but then Gilkey deferred to Everett, who
waved at the ball as it dropped.
</P>
<P>
   The error allowed Sandy Alomar to score, making it 6-2. Lofton
might have scored, too, but Garciaparra's relay from Everett to
catcher Jason Varitek nailed him, in part because Lofton did not
slide.
</P>
<P>
   Vizquel landed at third on the play and scored on a ground out
by Manny Ramirez, cutting the lead to 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a couple of mistakes and those are the kinds of things
that can't happen,'' Lewis said. ``Fortunately, we made up for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   But first Cleveland lurched back, making it 6-5 in the sixth, as
Martinez gave up a leadoff double to Roberto Alomar and a jarring
home run to Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   For Ramirez, who drove in four runs, the home run was his 28th.
And he increased his RBI total to 98 in 96 games.
</P>
<P>
   The blast also knocked Martinez out of the game. He gave way to
lefthander Rheal Cormier, who retired Jim Thome and David Segui on
grounders for the first two outs of the sixth. And righthander
Hector Carrasco, in his Sox debut, induced a ground out from Travis
Fryman to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Rod Beck pitched scoreless relief in the seventh
and eighth as Sox relievers mowed down 10 straight Indians before
Lowe ran into trouble in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Beck said the Sox are on a mission. ``We've got to win them all,
every day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox made up for their errors in the eighth, when they scored
two runs on a double by Brian Daubach, a single by Manny Alexander,
a walk to Midre Cummings, and a sacrifice fly by Everett. That made
it 8-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not a team that panics,'' Lewis said. ``We stay positive
whether we win two or three games in a row or lose two or three
games in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   Good thing, because there was cause for concern in the ninth.
With two outs, Lowe yielded a double to Travis Fryman and a
run-scoring single to Russell Branyan, making it 8-6. Branyan
reached third when right fielder Trot Nixon let Branyan's ball roll
past him to the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Up came Sandy Alomar, the potential tying run. But Lowe induced
him to ground out to preserve the win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was definitely scary,' Lowe said. ``But it shows why every
run is so precious against a good team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
