<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 10:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2144 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ELIAN-CARDENAS14-COX     09-13 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-CARDENAS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ELIAN'S HOME TOWN A HAVEN A PRIVACY
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARDENAS, Cuba _ There are no lawyers running to the
microphones, no angry protestors holding vigil, no banners or
posters or hordes of camera-wielding journalists.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Elian Gonzalez and his family like it that way.
</P>
<P>
   Just two months ago, the young shipwreck survivor was perhaps
the most famous 6-year-old in the world. Caught in the center of a
bitter custody fight between his Miami relatives and his Cuban
family, Elian became a symbol of the decades-old conflict between
communist Cuba and its capitalist neighbor to the north.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is just another student at Marcelo Salado(cq) primary
school, one of hundreds dressed in identical red, white and blue
school uniforms, running and shouting in the school's spacious
courtyard between classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very touching to see this family come full circle,'' said
Bob Edgar, head of the National Council of Churches, the American
group that worked to see Elian returned to Cuba during his
eight-month stay in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Edgar headed a small delegation that visited Cardenas recently
to present 1,500 packets containing pencils, paper and other
supplies to schoolchildren in the area. Elian's father, Juan Miguel
Gonzalez, and his two grandmothers attended the brief presentation
ceremony at Cardenas's museum, just across the street from Elian's
school.
</P>
<P>
   Elian did not attend, but it was still an emotional reunion for
Edgar, who helped arrange a visit by the boy's grandmothers to the
United States in January in a failed attempt to see Elian returned
to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're doing great,'' Edgar said, following a brief private
meeting with the family. ``Juan Miguel said when he takes Elian to
school now on his bicycle, people leave them alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Elian's return to Cuba in July, the Cuban government has
kept the Gonzalez family under tight security. For the first
several weeks, they reportedly lived in a boarding school in
Havana, and then took a vacation at a Cuban beach resort.
</P>
<P>
   Film footage of Elian frolicking at the beach was made
available, along with coverage of his first day at school.
Otherwise, there has been no media access to the boy or his family.
</P>
<P>
   The privacy is in sharp contrast to their experience in the
United States, where gangs of reporters dogged their every move,
camping out for months in front of the modest home in Miami's
Little Havana where Elian lived with his Florida relatives.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban government complained bitterly that the Miami
relatives were abusing Elian by parading him before the cameras. It
appears Cuban dictator Fidel Castro is determined not to let his
enemies in the Cuban exile community make the same charges now that
Elian is back home in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Castro has met with the boy and his family, but no film or
photographs of the meeting have been made public.
</P>
<P>
   It may be hard for Americans who witnessed the media onslaught
and political circus that surrounded Elian in the United States to
imagine the boy will ever have a normal life again. But if such a
recovery is possible, Cardenas may be the ideal setting.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is it Elian's home, it's also about as far removed from
the hustle and fervor of South Florida as you can get. A gritty
industrial town of 20,000, Cardenas's narrow, dusty streets are
lined with dilapidated buildings.
</P>
<P>
   There's a sleepy central square fronting the museum, but on most
hot summer afternoons, it stands vacant. The downtown streets are
lined by modest homes with adjoining walls. Wooden doors open into
small homes that usually feature a courtyard or patio in the back.
</P>
<P>
   There are more bicycles and horse-drawn carts than cars in
Cardenas. Old women talk to neighbors through open doors or
windows, some sharing a small cup of rich, black Cuban coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Most residents seem happy that the furor over Elian has passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is calm now and that's so much better,'' said
Conchita Rodriguez(cq), a grandmother who lives a few blocks from
Elian's school. ``I have grandsons, too, and it wasn't right for
the boy to be separated from his family.''
</P>
<P>
   Elian left Cardenas last November, taken by his mother, who
drowned along with 10 other people after their small boat capsized
off the Florida coast. Elian was found alone, floating in an inner
tube, on Thanksgiving Day.
</P>
<P>
   Since his recent return to school in early September, Elian
appears to be living the routine he knew before he left Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors say the family is still dealing with the loss of
Elian's mother and their bitter feelings toward the Miami
relatives. The Miami branch of the Gonzalez family accused Elian's
father of abusing the boy and his mother, and made a controversial
video of Elian telling his father he didn't want to go back to
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's father and mother were divorced, but his father has
remarried, and Elian has a half-brother who will soon celebrate his
first birthday. Edgar said the family was looking forward to the
celebration as another step in its return to normalcy.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas's residents appear ready to help the process along.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is so happy because all is tranquil now,'' said
Migdalia Davilas (cq), who lives half a block from Elian's school.
``He's the most famous person ever to come from Cardenas, but we
all want to let him be just a little boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Williams's e-mail address is mikew(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
