<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2248 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR &LR;      09-13 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORD LOVERS AS THICK AS GRAPE VINES 

</HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa , Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The literary connection sometimes goes this way: You get the
name of a book agent from your dog's vet who has another client
who's a writer and just sold his manuscript.
</P>
<P>
   Or the bartender, who is writing a book, has a brother-in-law in
L.A. who sometimes looks at scripts.
</P>
<P>
   To live in an area that is ripe with writers and artists is a
lucky thing. It is almost as good as living where there are fields
of lavender and olive oil festivals and where you can go
wine-tasting by bicycle.
</P>
<P>
   Writers and artists are natural resources but we don't see them
doing their work by the side of the road or on stage. They do their
creating in solitude. They sit at home in their office or studio
where, you imagine, they wear rumpled pajamas and drink coffee all
day and don't comb their hair until they hear the Fed Ex truck in
the driveway.
</P>
<P>
   A region with a strong creative community never lacks for a poet
or playwright to visit their classrooms. You can usually find at
least one book store in every town, and often a used-book store as
well. Book readings are sometimes standing room only.
</P>
<P>
   Copy stores are popular. So are libraries. In a writer-friendly
place you can walk into the post office with a fat brown envelope
addressed to New York and the clerk pats it and whispers ``good
luck.''
</P>
<P>
   If you live in a region that nourishes the arts, you can see
original art on restaurant walls that change monthly and you
sometimes know the name written in the corner. Maybe it's the woman
who cuts your hair or the guy you always see at the farmers'
market.
</P>
<P>
   There is a chance that one of your favorite authors also teaches
writing at the junior college, and that you will run into him at
the gym.
</P>
<P>
   While it is said that in L.A. every waiter is a would-be actor,
in Sonoma County he or she is often doing something with a pen or a
brush on the side. But so might be your plumber or your therapist
or the woman down the road who raises sheep.
</P>
<P>
   Here we have more artistic types than we have varieties of
heirloom tomatoes. If we could bottle our creative juices we might
rival the size of the wine industry.
</P>
<P>
   The first annual Sonoma County Book Fair happens on Saturday,
Sept. 16 and it's a pretty big deal for local writers and readers
and anyone who loves words. To have enough writers, poets, book
sellers and small publishers to fill a daylong event is a more
exciting sign of growth, in some people's minds, than a new uptown
store at the mall or another six-plex movie theater.
</P>
<P>
   There are 70 writers booked for the fair, and while I should
disclose that I get to be one of them, just think of that number.
Seventy people _ plus all the missing ones hiding in the woods or
spending their royalty check (ha!) in Antibes _ who call this
region home and are published writers.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be correct to say they make their living at it,
because the ones I know also teach and bartend and work in offices.
But they definitely make their passion from it.
</P>
<P>
   A celebration of the printed word comes at a good time because
writers and artists are feeling endangered these days, by whatever
threat or blessing comes from the huge world of the Internet and by
the limiting world of Wine Country real estate.
</P>
<P>
   The very things that inspire people to walk into the woods or
along the shore with a sketchpad or notebook move people with lots
of money to locate here and build big expensive houses. The wild
Pacific, magical redwoods and adorable cows are still free to look
at but the land costs a bundle, and this is bad news for inventive
types who once could live cheaply and do their art.
</P>
<P>
   It's ironic that as more money comes into the area which might
go toward such things as original art and patronizing book stores,
fewer original artists can afford to live here.
</P>
<P>
   If you're working 12 hours at a dot-com job you don't come home
and write novels.
</P>
<P>
   We don't have huge name writers living in Sonoma County. You
have to get closer to the Golden Gate to run into Isabel Allende
and go deep into Mendocino County to call Alice Walker your
neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   But we have Jean Hegland, who lives in the hills outside of
Healdsburg and who, one day in 1997, on her way to taking her kids
to piano lessons, found out her first novel, ``Into the Forest,''
was the subject of a New York bidding war.
</P>
<P>
   We used to have the late Suzanne Lipsett in Petaluma, who was
famous for introducing writers to writers at potlucks at her home.
She wrote a piece about sitting at her computer on her glassed-in
porch at 5 a.m., her family asleep, her only company the fog and
silent pasture.
</P>
<P>
   That's the kind of thing writers get from living here. And give
back.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. The Press Democrat is a member of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
