<DOCNO> NYT20000913.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 10:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2256 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-BIOTECH-MERGERS-BOS &LR;      09-13 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOTECH-MERGERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS STIR UP BIOTECHNOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NAOMI AOKI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Flush with cash and high stock valuations, biotechnology
companies are seeing a frenzy of mergers and acquisitions that
analysts say rivals any during the industry's 25-year history. And
analysts say the trend is likely to continue.
</P>
<P>
   This week alone, the industry has seen three takeovers, most
prominently Genzyme Corp.'s $1 billion acquisition of GelTex
Pharmaceuticals Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The other big deals this week include Human Genome Sciences
Inc.'s buyout of Principia Pharmaceutical Corp. for $120 million,
and Elan Corp.'s $1.8 billion deal to acquire Dura Pharmaceuticals
Inc. Human Genome is based in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   The deals are the most recent in a new wave of consolidation
among biotech companies. This year, there have been 60 biotech
mergers and acquisitions, according to Recombinant Capital Inc., a
San Francisco consulting firm for biotech companies. During the
same period last year, there were 35 such deals.
</P>
<P>
   Industry giants like Millennium Pharmaceuticals Inc. of
Cambridge, Mass. are scooping up their smaller brethren to fill
pipelines and position themselves as the pharmaceutical companies
of the future. Smaller biotech companies like Antigenics Inc. and
Aquila Inc. are merging complementary technologies to gain
competitive muscle.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts, who have yet to compile the number of deals this year,
say the increased activity is a sign of good times _ and a maturing
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The sector's strong performance on Wall Street in recent months
has helped biotech companies raise money and craft financially
attractive deals. Bigger companies that a decade ago focused
resources on in-house research and development are now looking to
expand their capabilities. Smaller companies are realizing they are
more likely to succeed by joining forces.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, biotech companies gave away much of a drug's
profits in partnerships with large pharmaceutical companies to gain
access to cash, sales and marketing resources. But as companies
mature today, they are realizing that they can have more productive
mergers with other biotech companies, said Mark Speers, managing
director of Health Advances Inc., a Wellesley management consulting
firm for life sciences companies.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the larger companies have substantial marketing and
sales infrastructures they didn't have a decade ago, Speers said.
Even some smaller companies have products on the market and other
promising drugs in their pipelines. And biotech executives believe
other biotech companies will have more respect for their companies'
products, Speers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A little bit of this is biotech strutting its new-found
independence,'' said Kevin Starr, chief financial officer for
Millennium. ``For years, the biotech industry has invested billions
in research and development and that is finally starting to bear
some fruit.''
</P>
<P>
   Mergers and acquisitions are a key element of Millennium's
strategy as the company transitions from a gene discovery to a
full-scale pharmaceutical company, Starr said.
</P>
<P>
   Acquisitions allow the company to quickly add capabilities that
would take years to build in-house. With its recent acquisition of
Cambridge Drug Discovery, an English company, Millennium added 150
chemists to work on its pipeline. Buying Leukosite Inc. of
Cambridge infused Millennium's pipeline with drugs in late-stage
development. Over the next decade, Starr predicts Millennium will
average as many as three acquisitions a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be increasingly important in building the
company and building the industry,'' Starr said.
</P>
<P>
   Elan's acquisition of Dura Pharmaceuticals allows the Irish
company to double its US sales force and gain Dura's antibiotics
and medicine-inhaling system. Genzyme's takeover of GelTex of
Waltham, mass.gives the company sole ownership of Renagel, a kidney
dialysis drug Genzyme, of Cambridge, expects to become its biggest
moneymaker.
</P>
<P>
   In smaller deals, like the one struck by Antigenics of New York
and Aquila of Framingham, Mass. last month, companies can combine
technologies in a way that strengthens them both, said Alison
Taunton-Rigby, Aquila's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Though Aquila had a rich pipeline, Taunton-Rigby said, the
company was too small to gain Wall Street's attention. By merging
with Antigenics, she said, the company gains the scale it needs to
advance. And, she said, Antigenics gains Aquila's products and its
partnerships with large pharmaceutical companies.
</P>
<P>
   Taunton-Rigby said she has also seen genomics companies buying
other biotech concerns to acquire technologies they need to turn
reams of information about the human genome into pharmaceutical
products. The companies need those technologies, they don't have
the time to build them, but they do have a lot of cash because of
the excitement about genomics, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``By hook or by crook, biotech companies somehow manage to keep
going and create value during the hard times,'' she said. ``But now
you've got companies with their stock prices in a good place. So
people feel more comfortable doing deals.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-00 1054EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
