<HEADLINE>
FIRMS READY TO MARKET UP TO NINE NEW DRUGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a couple of slow years, Massachusetts biotechnology
companies may get the green light to market as many as nine drugs,
including one produced in goats' milk and another from cows, in the
next year to 15 months.
</P>
<P>
   Several companies have spent more than $200 million and taken
seven to 10 years to develop and extensively test their proposed
medications before asking the US Food and Drug Administration for
marketing approval. Others have acquired promising drugs or bought
companies to get access to near-term drug candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, more than 370 biotech drugs are in various stages of
testing for the treatment of more than 200 diseases, a
Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers of America survey shows.
More than half have been developed to treat cancer.
</P>
<P>
   However, relatively few will reach the brass ring of FDA
approval. Only 92 biotech drugs gained FDA approval between 1982
and 1999, according to the Biotechnology Industry Organization, an
industry trade group.
</P>
<P>
   And while 20 percent of those approvals were for drugs from
Massachusetts biotech companies, there have been relatively few
drugs reaching the market in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Boston area has been one of the most productive in
delivering biotech drugs to the market, but in recent years there
has been a gap after the bigger companies like Genzyme, Biogen and
Genetics Institute delivered their first drugs,'' said John
Maraganore, vice president of strategic product development at
Millennium Pharmaceuticals of Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biotech industry is entering a more mature phase, where
products will come out,'' Maraganore said. ``But it is also a
question of timing as the pipeline of forthcoming drugs is getting
larger.''
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, only one drug, Welchol, a cholesterol-lowering
drug from GelTex Pharmaceuticals Inc. of Waltham, has gained FDA
approval.
</P>
<P>
   However, in the next 12 to 15 months, six Bay State companies
will seek FDA approval to market drugs. Two of the drugs are
designed to treat Fabry disease, a rare inherited disease. Others
are a blood thinner for patients undergoing cardiovascular
operations, a treatment for a common form of adult leukemia, a pair
of infertility treatments and another multiple sclerosis
medication.
</P>
<P>
   With a few exceptions, all of the biotech drugs coming out of
the state are targeted at small patient populations _ 2,000 to
100,000 people _ that have few choices of medication. Campath from
Millennium is aimed at about 10,000 to 20,000 people with adult
leukemia whose first and second lines of treatment have failed and
who have no further recourse.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Genzyme Transgenics is preparing to ask the FDA next
year for permission to market a drug made in the milk of goats that
prevents blood clots in patients undergoing cardiopulmonary bypass
operations who are resistant to heparin, a widely used blood
thinner. If approved, it will be the first drug developed from a
herd of goats.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest race to supply a life-saving drug to
patients with a rare disease is between Genzyme Corp. and
Transkaryotic Therapies Inc. Both are battling to provide an enzyme
replacement therapy to between 2,000 and 4,000 men with Fabry
disease, a rare inherited disorder with no treatment currently
available. FDA approvals are expected early next year.
</P>
<P>
   But in fulfilling the unmet medical needs of these patients,
some biotech companies also are prospering. Genzyme's revenues from
its treatment of Gaucher's disease, which affects about 3,000
people worldwide, are expected to surpass $500 million this year.
And last year, Biogen's Avonex, a treatment for multiple sclerosis
used by 90,000 patients, had revenues of $619 million.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Genzyme Corp. said it foresees turning Renagel, a
treatment for kidney disease that had revenues of nearly $20 milion
last year, into a billion-dollar blockbuster in the next 10 years.
Genzyme is spending more than $1 billion to acquire GelTex, which
developed Renagel.
</P>
<P>
   For Genzyme, Renagel also marks a transition from developing
drugs for small patient populations to developing drugs for much
larger groups, such as the 1 million patients worldwide with
late-stage kidney disease.
</P>
<P>
   Also hoping to expand with a mainstream drug next year is
Biopure Corp., which has spent 16 years and $330 million to develop
a human blood substitute. Called Hemopure, it is made from the
hemoglobin cells of cows. Instead of human blood, Biopure has
developed an oxygen-carrying blood substitute that can be stored at
room temperature, requires no tissue typing and can replace human
hemoglobin initially in patients undergoing orthopedic surgery,
such as hip replacements.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all these years, we are getting down to the wire and we
are excited about the prospects,'' said Carl W. Rausch, founder,
chairman and chief executive of the Cambridge-based company that
has tested Hemopure in 750 people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
