<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS DEALS INVOLVING GENOMICS ON THE RISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG and NAOMI AOKI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Biotech companies are mining the human genome, hunting for
potential drug targets, and making daily discoveries about the role
of genes and proteins in disease. Pharmaceutical companies need the
emerging science and technology to fill their pipelines. And they
can't get their hands on it fast enough.
</P>
<P>
   So pharmaceutical companies are striking deals with their
smaller, younger biotech brethren in record numbers. In the first
half of this year, business deals involving gene-related data and
technology rose 70 percent over the same period last year,
according to Cambridge Healthtech Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people have begun to recognize about genomics is that
it's an information business, and it just happens to be information
that is critical to being able to move forward,'' said Phillips
Kuhl, the institute's president.
</P>
<P>
   Cambridge Healthtech, a Newton group that researches the biotech
industry, tracks drug discovery and development deals. It recently
released a report about genomics deals that took place between
January 1999 and March 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In the first six months of 1999, there were 165 genomics deals.
The number grew to 216 for the second half of 1999, and to 278 in
the first half of 2000. Most of those deals took place among a
handful of companies. In 1999, the report stated, 10 companies were
involved in about 40 percent of the deals.
</P>
<P>
   The big pharmaceutical companies realize they can't build the
genomics expertise they need fast enough to stay competitive, Kuhl
said. And the biotech companies benefit from the resources and
experience pharmaceutical companies provide in shepherding a drug
through clinical testing and into distribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, it moves the research forward,'' he said. ``It's
beneficial for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Biogen teams with Eos
</P>
<P>
   to fight breast cancer
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to jump-start its development of drugs to treat breast
cancer, Biogen Inc. has turned to Eos Biotechnology Inc. of South
San Francisco, a small company that in July announced it had
identified a group of genes linked to breast cancer based on a
working draft of the human genome.
</P>
<P>
   Under a four year research and development collaboration,
Cambridge-based Biogen will pay Eos as much as $55 million, not
including royalties on sales of products identified through the
agreement. Separately, Biogen will make a $5 million equity
investment in the three-year-old privately held company.
</P>
<P>
   The hefty bet on Eos stems from its proprietary technology to
select out from human genome data the actual genes that produce the
body's proteins. Eos used this data to create two gene chips
containing probes for more than 80 percent of the active human
genome. The company then compared gene activity in breast cancer
tissues obtained from patients in Australia and Europe with their
consent to that of normal health tissue.
</P>
<P>
   The result was specific genes found to be more active in the
cancer tissue than in the healthy cells, from which drug targets
are created and supplied by Eos to Biogen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Biogen will use our considerable knowledge and skill in
biology and drug development to work with Eos on identifying
potential targets and commercializing products,'' said James C.
Mullen, the Biogen president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Proteome Inc. launches
</P>
<P>
   protein databases
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Proteome Inc., which assembles biological information from
public databases and scientific literature for the biotech and
pharmaceutical industries, launched the first human databases
coupling protein functional information to the human genome.
</P>
<P>
   One database contains 18,000 human, mouse and rat proteins,
including biochemical function and cellular location. The Beverly
company said the databases are designed for researchers to compare
biological pathways and molecular interactions conserved between
humans and model organisms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Understanding function of the proteins encoded by the genes is
the ultimate goal for advancing the drug discovery process,'' said
James I. Garrels, Proteome's president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bay State firm supplies
</P>
<P>
   radioactive seeds
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vanderbilt University Medical Center in Nashville has agreed to
become the first location to use permanent radioactive seeds from
Implant Sciences Corp. of Wakefield to treat patients with early
stage prostate and other cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, doctors inserted 90 radioactive seeds into a
patient's cancerous prostate gland using ultrasound guidance.
</P>
</TEXT>
