<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 10:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2263 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-BIOTECH-MEDICINE-ART-     09-13 1505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOTECH-MEDICINE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 MEDICINES CO. SALVAGES DRUGS OTHER FIRMS SHELVED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NAOMI AOKI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You might say Dr. Clive Meanwell is a bit of a scavenger.
</P>
<P>
   After all, he founded a business four years ago based on the
idea that there was money to be made off drugs other companies cast
aside. His start-up known as the Medicines Co. picks through and
rescues products languishing on shelves because of lackluster test
results, shifting corporate priorities, or development problems.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwell and his team of experienced pharmaceutical executives
in Cambridge, Mass. wanted drugs in late stages of development that
would take no more than four years and $60 million to get to
market. They needed three drugs in the pipeline to spread the risk,
each with the potential to generate at least $50 million in annual
sales.
</P>
<P>
   They spent six months considering more than 3,000 drugs. They
knew their first choice would be critical to the future of the
company. If it worked, there would be money and resources for the
other drugs behind it. If it failed, it was doubtful the company
could survive, even if the pipeline looked promising.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might be lucky. We might be better than average. But let's
assume we're not,'' Meanwell said. ``From a purely statistical
standpoint, we needed to start with five drugs. With a little
faith, three is OK. But if we were going with three, the first one
had to succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwell and his team chose a blood thinner called Hirulog as
their first project. Biogen Inc., a Cambridge company that is among
the oldest and largest in the biotech industry, had abandoned
Hirulog after spending six years and $150 million developing it as
a potential replacement for heparin, widely used to prevent blood
clots that lead to heart attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Hirulog had been expected to be a blockbuster drug. But when
results of a broad-based clinical trial showed it offered only
small improvements over heparin, Biogen scuttled the project. The
company would have to charge a relatively high price for Hirulog to
recoup its investment and cover its manufacturing costs. Given the
test results, Biogen feared it couldn't compete against the cheaper
heparin. Rather than invest more in Hirulog's development, the
company decided to cut its losses and shelve the drug.
</P>
<P>
   Where Biogen's executives saw disappointment, however,
Meanwell's group saw opportunity. The results of the clinical trial
showed Hirulog was as effective as heparin, and somewhat safer. It
has potential as a treatment for various cardiac conditions. And as
a smaller company with less infrastructure to support, the
Medicines Co. could afford to accept lower profit margins from the
drug than a company like Biogen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The level of skepticism from outside folks was high,''
Meanwell said. ``No one is going to look at Biogen and say they are
wrong. They're a highly successful company. The first question
everyone asked was, `Why did Biogen give up the drug?' ''
</P>
<P>
   At times, during the Medicines Co.'s three-year struggle for
regulatory approval, the choice seemed a poor one to investment and
industry professionals. Manufacturing issues promised to make the
drug expensive to produce. A Food and Drug Administration panel
initially rejected the company's request to approve the drug for
marketing in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But today, the drug's prospects _ and the company's _ are
greatly improved. The company received an ``approvable'' letter in
May from the FDA, indicating the agency's willingness to give
approval once some final conditions were met. The company met the
conditions and is now awaiting approval for the drug, renamed
Angiomax.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expect the drug to be launched early next year. They
estimate sales of $21 million in the first year, growing to $91
million by 2003 and leading the company into profitability.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've followed the drug's history, which has been long and
rocky,'' said Dr. Steven Gerber, managing director of CIBC World
Markets. ``But we firmly believe that it's going to be approved
now. We think it's going to be a product that leads to better
patient outcomes and saves the health care system money.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as the drug nears FDA approval, Dr. Burt Adelman, Biogen's
vice president of medical research, said the decision to sell the
rights to Hirulog to Meanwell's group was the right one for both
Biogen and the Medicines Co. The drug wasn't a good strategic fit
for Biogen, he said, but it was perfect for the Medicines Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fascinating and perhaps soon-to-be proven business
model,'' Adelman said, ``that you can find products reasonably far
along in development that no longer fit with the mother company and
do what is necessary to complete the process and take them
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwell's isn't the only company that specializes in drug
salvage. Gerber of CIBC World Markets said there are a handful of
similar companies. Gerber believes the strategy is a good one.
There is often less risk associated with late-stage products, and
as companies have merged and altered pipelines, the pool of
potential products has grown.
</P>
<P>
   But others point out that drug salvage is still a risky
business. Late-stage development is cash intensive, and there is no
guarantee that the product will get to market. Some drugs have been
shelved because problems arise that require more scientific
refinement or testing.
</P>
<P>
   The Medicines Co.'s second drug, a nasal spray for the treatment
of migraine headaches, ran into just such a problem. Although
Meanwell knew about the problems before buying the drug, he and his
colleagues underestimated the investment of time and money required
to resolve it. They decided to halt its development while looking
for a partner to help with the work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The drug might not work,'' Meanwell said. ``But it has a lot
of promise. The fact that we've put it on hold for now is a sign of
our discipline rather than a sign of failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, the company also acquired a third product _ a
naturally occurring lactobacillus in late-stage clinical testing
for the treatment of a common gynecological infection known as
bacterial vaginosis.
</P>
<P>
   The company also completed an initial public offering last
month, raising nearly $100 million. And the stock has held its
value at roughly $21 a share, up 30 percent from its offering price
of $16.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a fine line between being an abject failure and seeing
the beginnings of success,'' Meanwell said. ``The funny thing is
that our original business plan said we'd launch our first drug in
the year 2000 and that we'd need to raise $120 (million) to $200
million. The outline turned out to be about right. But we got all
the details wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   When the company bought Hirulog, or Angiomax, in March 1997 for
$30 million, including all future royalties, Meanwell expected to
accelerate the timeline laid out in the business plan.
</P>
<P>
   He and his group had run Biogen's data by the top doctors and
researchers in cardiology. They'd also reanalyzed the data and
found Angiomax decreased by almost half the number of patients who
suffered complications, such as excess bleeding, heart trouble, and
even death. The reduction in complications would save hospitals an
average of $750 per patient, the company estimated, giving Angiomax
a significant market advantage over heparin.
</P>
<P>
   But when the company presented its findings to an FDA panel in
fall 1998, the panel rejected the company's request for approval to
begin marketing the drug. The FDA wanted additional testing,
especially among high-risk patients.
</P>
<P>
   The news sent the company into what Meanwell now describes as
``a long, cold winter.'' Phone calls from people interested in the
company dwindled from an average of 40 a day to four. Money from
investors who just months earlier had dumped as much as $36 million
into the company dried up. The company's public image _ and its
confidence _ was shaken.
</P>
<P>
   ``I underestimated how devastating that kind of news can be for
a small company,'' Meanwell said. ``But it also becomes a sort of
defining experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem wasn't the drug, Meanwell said. The problem was that
he and the company's other executives weren't adequately prepared
for the rigors of the regulatory process.
</P>
<P>
   It has taken nearly two more years, additional clinical testing,
and a lot of conviction to finally meet those demands. Meanwell
believes the company has fulfilled all of the additional requests
outlined in the FDA's ``approvable'' letter. If it has, it should
receive FDA approval by year's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drug salvage is a tricky area to play in,'' Meanwell said.
``It has its own type of risk, a different type of risk. You have
to have a thick skin. If you fail, there are lots of people to come
along and say: `We told you so.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
