<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hey, Bush, didn't I make your A list?
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Presidential candidate George W. Bush called New York Times
reporter Adam Clymer a ``major-league'' body part that faces south
when you're headed north. Bush apparently didn't know the
microphone was on.
</P>
<P>
   This is good for a couple of reasons. If Bush is elected, it
will elevate the office of the -- residency from groping to popping
off. We're going from happy hands to happy lips, an obvious
improvement. ``Read my lips. You're an (at)$%&AMP;!.'' Also, this could
lead to a more exciting style of speechifying among our
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Bush when he knows the mike is on: ``My fellow Americans ...''
</P>
<P>
   Bush when he thinks the mike is off when it's really on: ``Why
don't you Democommies in the third row stick it where the sun don't
shine?''
</P>
<P>
   I doubt if the gaffe hurt Bush politically, because calling a
journalist a big jerk is like pointing out that elephants are
large. We in the journalism business are big jerks and darned proud
of it. We're paid to be big jerks. Hey, it's not a good day for me
unless I've made someone want to lunge for my throat. So if Bush
wanted to call somebody a bad name, he picked the right profession
to target.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if he'd said, ``Hey, there's Sister Mary Rosencranz, that
major-league (at)$&AMP;! from over at St. Patrick's Cathedral,'' it
might not have been received so well by the general public.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, Bush scored political points with me when he came
out and called the New York Times reporter a whatchamacallit. It
shows the man is human. It leads me to believe the guy may know how
to shoot pool. I like the idea of a president who goes around
telling Little Johnny You Know Who jokes from the third grade when
he thinks the sound has been cut off.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine this Rose Garden entrance if Bush is elected president:
</P>
<P>
   Announcer: ``Ladies and gentleman, the president of the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush: ``There once was a girl from Nantucket ...''
</P>
<P>
   Or how about a State of the Union -- ddress that starts, ``So
this giraffe walks into a bar ...''
</P>
<P>
   Has anybody considered the possibility that Bush decided to
lapse into vulgar language because he's trying to land Bobby
Knight's old job?
</P>
<P>
   There is one aspect of the incident that I find troubling: It
proves that Dick Cheney is a yes man with a brown nose. After Bush
called Clymer a _ and I'm lapsing into pig Latin here _ sass aye
ole hey, Bush's running mate responded on cue, ``Yeah, big time.''
</P>
<P>
   This tells me that George W. could say just about anything, and
Dick Cheney would bark on command. ``Hey, check out the legs on
that nurse.'' ``Yeah, big time.''
</P>
<P>
   The other thing I can't figure out _ and I guess I'm exposing my
big ego here _ is why Bush picked some chicken-bleep from New York
City to single out as the head major-league (at)$%&AMP; among writers.
New York City? How about giving some recognition to the hometown
coverage, George? What am I? Playing at the Double-A ball level or
something? I've been writing all this nasty stuff about George W.
Bush since he started running, and I don't even get a nod from the
guy? Hey, George, dance with the ones that brung you.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Email: jkelso(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
