<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY0914-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Threats to punish entertainment industry an assault on free
speech
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gloria Steinem is getting married and the Democrats want to
stifle smut.
</P>
<P>
   Wonders never cease.
</P>
<P>
   Steinem, 66, once said, ``A woman without a man is like a fish
without a bicycle.'' Now she has landed a 61-year-old,
twice-married entrepreneur named David Bale.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Steinem said that marriage ruins relationships. Now
she says her upcoming marriage proves ``that feminism is about the
ability to choose what's right at each time of our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, good luck to her. I hope she is more right now than she
was then. And I envy her ability to choose what is right at each
time of her life.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Sinatra, I have regrets too many to mention.
</P>
<P>
   A turnaround more surprising than Steinem's marriage is the
threat by Democratic standard bearers Al Gore and Joseph Lieberman
to use the power of the government to crack down on the
entertainment industry if it fails to keep smut and violence out of
the hands of children.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion for the threat was a Federal Trade Commission
report that said the entertainment industry markets smut and
violence to young people in spite of the industry's rating system.
</P>
<P>
   Surely the threat to punish the entertainment industry is a
result of letting voters know that God is going to be an active
participant on the Democratic ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Gore wants voters to know that he is going to be a moral
president, as opposed to you know who. That's why Gore chose
Lieberman to be the vice-presidential candidate. Lieberman
mentioned God 13 times in his first speech as born-again Gore's
running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Lieberman want American voters to know that their deep
religious beliefs will be dedicated to make the United States more
moral, more godly, if you will, when they are elected.
</P>
<P>
   It's not surprising to hear Republicans take the religious high
ground and attack the cultural depravity of Hollywood and the
entertainment industry. Republicans have been playing the religion
card for years, especially since Ronald Reagan exchanged votes for
mainstream validation of televangelists on the religious right.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning against the moral pollution of America's youth is
not a profile of political courage. It's easy. It's like
campaigning against the abolition of motherhood and homemade apple
pie.
</P>
<P>
   Is there empirical evidence that America's young people have
been morally corrupted by the entertainment industry?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe somewhere, but national statistics show that violent
juvenile crime fell 19 percent between 1994 and 1998. Juvenile
arrest rates for murder dropped 52 percent since 1993. Juvenile
violence has steadily decreased over the time that the FTC report
says the entertainment industry has been intentionally polluting
young minds.
</P>
<P>
   Even when Al and Tipper Gore launched a national campaign
against dirty lyrics in pop music, they did not call for punitive
legislation. Now Gore says he would support laws to punish the
entertainment industry for deceptive advertising.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how many kisses you blow at the First Amendment,
Gore's proposal would put the government in the position of being a
speech censor.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who declared ``Jesus Day'' in Texas and continues to court
the religious right, jumped on the me-too bandwagon and stood
four-square against smut and violence.
</P>
<P>
   Bush wants voters to know that he would restore morality,
integrity and, supposedly, God's will to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Voters need to know that there are dangers when politicians put
God on their political tickets. Mixing church and state threatens
both institutions. Iran, after all, is one nation under God.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
