<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2285 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-McCARTY0914-COX     09-13 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-McCARTY0914-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Keep the car a sanctuary to call our own
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You've got to give the Ford Motor Co. credit for trying to give
women what we want. For recognizing our power and might as
consumers and all that.
</P>
<P>
   But a new concept car designed to offer women literally
everything but the kitchen sink threatens to take away the one
thing we truly love about our cars: a place to call our thoughts
our own.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Windstar Solutions'' concept vehicle is a virtual house on
wheels, complete with Maytag washer and dryer, refrigerator,
microwave, trash compactor and wet/dry utility vacuum.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is for people who always find themselves saying, `I
practically live in my car,''' said Linda Lee, manager for the
women's marketing and product office for Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: Promotional materials promise that ``a shirt or a
party dress could be washed and dried in 15 minutes'' in the washer
and dryer built into the rear cargo area.
</P>
<P>
   My personal and highly scientific marketing research resulted in
a resounding, ``No way!'' Women shuddered at the notion of giving
up the one place they are not required to ``multi-task.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My car is my sanctuary, it's my own little place,'' said
Natasha Litvinova of Centerville. ``The car is my only place I
don't have to do anything except drive and enjoy my music.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you kidding?'' groaned another friend. ``I cannot imagine
doing a load of laundry and heating last night's leftovers while
trying to spot one of those road signs that pop up just as you've
almost missed your exit.''
</P>
<P>
   The concept car debuted in April at the National Kitchen and
Bath Industry Show in Chicago and has been making the auto-show
circuit ever since. ``It all sounds pretty handy, but it's one more
place for you to work,'' said University of Dayton history
professor John Heitmann, who teaches a car culture class.
</P>
<P>
   That's a paradox, he noted, that mirrors the evolution of the
automobile in the women's movement: ``It's no accident that the
women's suffrage movement took off when women got behind the wheel.
Yet before the automobile, services came to the home. Now we go
everywhere to make our stops. It's freedom, but not really freedom.
One of the inherent contradictions of four wheels is the burden of
more tasks for mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Spare us, in other words, yet another time-saving invention that
ends up piling on stress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we haven't gotten this far,'' sighed Montgomery County
Administrator Deborah Feldman.
</P>
<P>
   Ford seems to be bucking the trend that Feldman is witnessing
among friends and family: ``It seems people are trying very hard to
slow not only their own lives down but their kids' lives down. A
car like this says, 'We can do everything in our car.'''
</P>
<P>
   The most futuristic element is the ``Home Connection,'' which
would enable customers, using voice-activation technology, to
preheat the oven, inventory the refrigerator and monitor home
security systems. ``The controls to home might be nice, so you
could turn on the oven before you get home,'' Feldman admitted.
``But the things that are designed to avoid coming home, those I
wouldn't like.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford spokeswoman Lee said that the washer and dryer component
isn't likely to leap the divide from concept to reality: ``With a
concept car, you stretch the envelope. We'd need to have a lot more
people raise their hands before we decided to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Smart move. We appreciate your thinking of us and all, but when
we peel out of the driveway, we want to leave our Maytag far, far
behind.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Contact Mary McCarty by e-mail at marymccarty(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
