<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS14-FILE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS; THIS IS FILE 2 OF 2
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Isn't there another Bush brother in addition to George W. and
Jeb? Why do we never hear anything about him?
</P>
<P>
   A: In addition to Jeb, governor of Florida, George W. has two
other brothers: Neil, a management consultant in Texas; and Marvin,
a businessman in Virginia. He also has a sister, Dorothy Bush Koch.
All four siblings have let George W. have the spotlight lately,
although Marvin gave a TV interview and Neil appeared briefly on
CNN's ``Larry King Live'' at the time of the Republican National
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   If Neil Bush is the brother you're thinking of, he's generally
the least inclined to speak to reporters, probably because the
family feels like the media treated him harshly when he was caught
up in a savings and loan scandal. He was a director of the
Silverado Banking, Savings and Loan Association in Colorado, which
failed in 1988, costing the taxpayers an estimated $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   He was not charged with criminal wrongdoing, but agreed to pay
$50,000 in 1992 to settle a civil lawsuit lodged in 1990 by the
Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Q: On Aug. 30, the Dow Jones industrial average lost 112.9
points. On Aug. 31, it gained 112.9 points. The media reported the
numbers, but not on the fact that they were identical. Is this not
considered news?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Dow's balancing numbers two days in a row is a
coincidence with no economic implications whatsoever, said Myron
Greene, publisher of the Mutual Fund Timing Guide. The reason it
wasn't reported is that nobody cared, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My students and I were wondering what the initials VDB and FG
on pennies stand for. Do you know?
</P>
<P>
   A: The initials VDB, on Lincoln cents produced from 1909 to
1959, are for its designer, V.D. Brenner. FG is for Frank Gasparro,
who designed those produced since 1959.
</P>
<P>
   Information about specifications for all U.S. Mint legal tender
coins presently in circulation can be found online at this site:
www.usmint.gov/circulating/specifications.cfm.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are the ages for Girl Scouts, Cub Scouts and Boy Scouts?
A recent article reported on Latina scouting beginning at age 5.
That seems awfully young.
</P>
<P>
   A: Girl Scouting has five levels, for girls from kindergarten
through 12th grades (or ages 5-18).
</P>
<P>
   Cub Scouting has four levels, for boys in the first through
fifth grades (or ages 7-10).
</P>
<P>
   Boy Scouting is for boys who have earned the Arrow of Light
award or have completed the fifth grade or who are 11-17.
</P>
<P>
   Information online: Girl Scouts, www.gsusa.org/; Cubs,
www.scouting.org/nav/rec/cubs.html; Boy Scouts,
www.scouting.org/nav/rec/boys.html.
</P>
<P>
   Q: After all the publicity about the raising of the Confederate
submarine Hunley from Charleston Harbor, there's been no followup.
What, if anything, was found inside it?
</P>
<P>
   A: There's not much to report. The Hunley has been moved to the
Lasch Conservation Facility in Charleston, but it hasn't yet been
opened, said Faith Colaluca of the Friends of the Hunley. It's
hoped that the public will be allowed to view the sub by the end of
the month. When available, updates can be found online at
www.hunley.org.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The BatmanTV commercials for OnStar are awesome. Who plays
Batman and who plays the Joker?
</P>
<P>
   A: Actor Bruce Thomas (``Beverly Hills 90201,'' ``Veronica's
Closet,'' ``All My Children'' and others) is Batman; comedian
Curtis Armstrong (``Risky Business,'' ``Revenge of the Nerds,''
``Love Boat'' and others) is the Joker.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Young, OnStar's advertising manager in Troy, Mich., said
OnStar is the first enterprise granted permission to use
live-action Batman scenes with the approval of DC Comics and Warner
Bros., which own the rights to the character. Not only that, the
spots were filmed on sets used in the ``Batman'' movies, including
the Batcave, with its hydraulic gear to lift the Batcar into
motion. ``They felt like there was a tremendous link between Batman
and what we offer with OnStar,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   The OnStar vehicle navigation system combines Global Positioning
System satellite technology and wireless communication to link the
driver and vehicle with a 24-hour command center in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there any place online where can I find information about
traffic-related accidents and deaths in U.S. cities?
</P>
<P>
   A: Check http://www.nhtsa.dot.gov/, the site for the National
Highway Traffic Safety Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It's believed that the recent Concorde crash near Paris was
caused by debris from another aircraft on the runway at Charles de
Gaulle Airport. Is there an FAA regulation on runway inspections in
the United States? What is the policy at American airports?
</P>
<P>
   A: There's no specific Federal Aviation Agency requirement for
the number of inspections, or ``sweeps,'' a day at U.S. airports,
said agency spokeswoman Kathleen Bergen. The term ``sweep,'' by the
way, means making a visual check of the runways for any debris that
might be present, not literally sweeping the runways.
</P>
<P>
   Even though there's no required number, it's routine for these
checks to be made at airports in the United States. At Hartsfield
International Airport in Atlanta, for example, such checks are made
daily between 7:45 and 8 a.m. and after any significant weather
event, such as high wind or a thunderstorm. Also, every time an
aircraft with a problem comes in, the runway is checked after it
lands to see if the aircraft lost any debris.
</P>
<P>
   Other U.S. airports might do something different, Bergen said,
but procedures would be similar.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you explain the Air Quality Index and what the color
codes mean? I frequently read and hear reports about a city's air
quality using such terms as code yellow, code range and code red.
</P>
<P>
   A: The Environmental Protection Agency's AQI scale uses six
categories to assess local air quality, based on values from zero
to 500.
</P>
<P>
   Code green, 0-50, means air quality conditions are good; yellow,
51-100, moderate; orange, 101-150, unhealthy for sensitive groups;
red, 151-200, unhealthy; purple, 201-300, very unhealthy; maroon,
301-500, hazardous.
</P>
<P>
   The AQI evolved from the Pollutant Standards Index, established
in 1976, said Colin Marquis, senior meteorologist at The Weather
Channel. It incorporated levels of ground-level ozone, particulate
matter, carbon monoxide, sulfur dioxide and nitrogen dioxide. Its
categories included good, moderate and unhealthful.
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Protection Agency revised the index in the
past few years and renamed it the Air Quality Index, Marquis
explained. The new scale, with color coding and associated
health-related cautionary statements, can be found online at
www.epa.gov/airnow/aqibroch/aqi.htmlozone.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
