<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS14-FILE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS; THIS IS FILE 1 OF 1
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com. Please include your name and hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When was the Commission on Presidential Debates formed, and
how is it funded?
</P>
<P>
   A: Established in 1987, the commission is financed through
private contributions, according to information on its Web site
(www.debates.org/). It accepts no money from the government or
political parties.
</P>
<P>
   National Internet sponsors for the 2000 debates are AT&AMP;T, Sun
Microsystems, 3Com, Harris Interactive, Alteon WebSystems and
ZoneOfTrust. General debate sponsors are Anheuser-Busch, the
Century Foundation, the Marjorie Kovler Fund and 3Com.
</P>
<P>
   Each debate site agrees to pay $550,000 to stage the event. That
covers expenses for such things as production crews required for
the TV presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Green Party presidential candidate Ralph Nader, meanwhile, has
filed a suit to disallow corporate sponsorship of the debates.
Nader attorney Scott Lewis termed the debates essentially ``paid
advertisements subsidized by corporate contributions for those
candidates who participate in them.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: A lot of people at the Emmy awards presentation Sept. 10 were
wearing yellow ribbons. What did they signify?
</P>
<P>
   A: The ribbons (actually gold) were to show solidarity for union
members affiliated with the Screen Actors Guild and the American
Federation of Television and Radio Artists who work in commercials.
The two unions have been on strike against the advertising industry
since May 1.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recall that Firestone had a problem with its tires back in
the late '70s or early '80s. Can you refresh my memory?
</P>
<P>
   A: It was in 1978-79 that Firestone suffered through a major
product recall involving defective Firestone 500 radial tires. The
company ultimately recalled 13 million tires because of treads
peeling off.
</P>
<P>
   Firestone apparently knew about the problem as early as 1972,
but fought the government every step of the way in the subsequent
investigation. In December 1978, the National Highway Traffic
Safety Administration released an internal Firestone memorandum of
1972 in which one top Firestone official told another that problems
with steel-belted radials were so bad ``that we are in danger of
being cut off by Chevrolet because of separation failures.''
</P>
<P>
   It was reported at the time that the defective tires had caused
41 deaths and 65 personal injuries. Firestone lost almost $150
million in 1978, with the company losing market share because of
the incident. Weakened financially, it eventually was taken over by
Bridgestone.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We know the Boy Scouts' policy on homosexuality. Do the Girl
Scouts have an official policy?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. It's outlined in the organization's Blue Book of Basic
Documents (1994), said Lisa Hester of the Girl Scout Council of
Northwest Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The policy: ``The Girl Scout organization does not discriminate,
but we do not endorse any particular lifestyle and we do not
recruit lesbians as a group. We have firm standards relating to
appropriate conduct. We do not permit sexual displays of any sort
by our members. We do not permit the advocacy or promotion of a
personal lifestyle or sexual orientation. These are private matters
for girls and their families to address. Girl Scout volunteers and
staff must at all times serve as appropriate role models for
girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: In ``The Star-Spangled Banner,'' what are the ramparts in
``o'er the ramparts we watched''? No one has ever been able to
explain it to me.
</P>
<P>
   A: A rampart is an elevation or mound of earth raised as a
fortification to serve as a bulwark or defense.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the ramparts were at Fort McHenry, near
Baltimore's harbor. British naval forces bombarded the fort all day
Sept. 13, 1814, and almost all night. When Francis Scott Key saw
the American flag still flying over the walls of the fort as the
next day dawned, he was inspired to begin writing verses. His poem
was titled ``Defense of Fort M'Henry,'' and by November 1814 had
been published as ``The Star-Spangled Banner.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where does the oil from Alaska go?
</P>
<P>
   A: According to the General Accounting Office, 95 percent of
Alaskan oil is sold domestically; the remaining 5 percent is
exported to Japan, South Korea and Taiwan. That 5 percent is
roughly 60,000 barrels of oil a day.
</P>
<P>
   The exporting of Alaskan North Slope crude oil originally was
banned as a condition for building the 800-mile pipeline. Congress
repealed the export ban in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I know that CNN's Judy Woodruff got her start at WAGA-TV in
Atlanta, but can you give us some details about her career?
</P>
<P>
   A: After graduating from Duke University in 1968, Woodruff, 53,
worked from 1970 to 1975 as a correspondent for WAGA, the CBS
affiliate in Atlanta, reporting on the state Legislature and
anchoring the noon and evening news.
</P>
<P>
   She then was an Atlanta-based general assignment reporter for
NBC News in 1975-76, and served as NBC News' White House
correspondent from 1977 to 1983. She also was chief Washington
correspondent for NBC's ``Today.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1983 she left NBC for public TV, serving as ``Frontline''
anchor and as chief Washington correspondent for ``The
MacNeil/Lehrer NewsHour.''
</P>
<P>
   She joined CNN in 1993. At present she is CNN's prime anchor and
senior correspondent and co-anchors, with Bernard Shaw, ``Inside
Politics'' and ``WorldView.'' She also co-anchors the Wednesday
edition of ``CNN NewsStand.''
</P>
<P>
   More information about Woodruff online:
www.cnn.com/CNN/anchorsreporters/woodruff.judy.html.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have heard of the ``rebel yell'' for many years, but have
no idea what it sounds like. Is it ``Yee-Haw!,'' ``Yahoo!,''
``Yippy-i- ay!,'' or what?
</P>
<P>
   A: None of the above. Originally used in combat in the Civil
War, and intended to strike terror into the hearts of the enemy,
the yell is described in Facts on File Encyclopedia of Word and
Phrase Origins as loosely combining the turkey gobbler's cry with a
series of yelps.
</P>
<P>
   The Morris Dictionary of Word and Phrase Origins, meanwhile,
describes the rebel yell as a prolonged, high-pitched,
blood-curdling cross between a yell and a scream, proclaiming it
impossibe to express in words.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Now that we're into a new hurricane season, can you tell me
if hurricanes occur south of the Equator? If so, what are they
called?
</P>
<P>
   A: Such powerful, swirling storms that begin over a warm sea
indeed do occur south of the Equator. And while the word
``hurricane'' can be applied to all such storms, they do have
different labels, depending on where they occur.
</P>
<P>
   Generally speaking, they're called tropical cyclones near
Australia and in the Indian Ocean (south of the Equator). They're
known as hurricanes when they happen over the North Atlantic Ocean,
the Caribbean Sea, the Gulf of Mexico or the Northeast Pacific
Ocean (north of the Equator). And they're typhoons if they occur in
the Northwest Pacific Ocean (also north of the Equator), west of
the International Date Line.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
