<HEADLINE>
BASKETBALL TO FOOTBALL TO POLITICAL BALL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BILL THOMPSON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Random comments on people in the news:
</P>
<P>
   BOBBY KNIGHT: How in the world did this guy last as long as he
did? It's one thing to embarrass your employer by being an
arrogant, ill-tempered jerk _ but rubbing the boss's face in it?
</P>
<P>
   Not even Knight _ one of college basketball's all-time great
coaches _ was good enough at his job to get away with, in effect,
thumbing his nose at the president of Indiana University and the
``zero tolerance'' policy that the school had instituted regarding
Knight's outlandish behavior. The coach's latest offense _ grabbing
and intimidating a student who's not even a basketball player _
left IU no choice but to show Knight the door.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and another thing: Is Dallas Mavericks owner Mark Cuban
really stupid/goofy enough to hire this creep? What would Knight do
for the Mavericks _ instruct the other coaches in the art of
strangling basketball players?
</P>
<P>
   TROY AIKMAN: I was an Aikman fan even before he was the Dallas
Cowboys' quarterback. I attended his news conference when he came
to North Texas with UCLA to play in the 1989 Cotton Bowl game, and
it was obvious even then that he was exactly what the then-lowly
Cowboys needed to climb back to the top of the football world.
</P>
<P>
   He fulfilled the promise, leading the Cowboys to three Super
Bowl championships and providing football fans with front-row seats
to greatness.
</P>
<P>
   But he's done enough. Nine concussions _ eight with the Cowboys
and one in college _ are more than enough. He should follow the
example of concussion-prone quarterback Steve Young, who finally
faced up to reality and retired.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: The Democratic candidate for president is up in arms
over a government report that reveals the shocking information that
Hollywood markets violent entertainment to kids who aren't old
enough to watch the stuff.
</P>
<P>
   How disingenuous can Gore get? He's raking in campaign
contributions from those evil Hollywood moguls almost as fast as
the moguls are raking in bucks from slasher movies. There were so
many Tinseltown titans running around that Democratic convention in
Los Angeles last month that the joint looked more like a movie set
than a convention hall.
</P>
<P>
   If Gore is so horrified by Hollywood's marketing practices, why
doesn't he look over that list of contributors, identify the
culprits who aim violent trash at children, and order his campaign
money-changers to return every single one of those donations?
</P>
<P>
   Fat chance.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: OK, so the Republican candidate got knocked off
stride by the amazing post-convention bounce that revived Gore's
campaign and turned what had been starting to look like a Bush
cakewalk into a race that's too close to call. It stands to reason
that when one candidate is up, the other one is down; it's no big
deal.
</P>
<P>
   Watch for Bush to regain his footing, surprise the public and
the media with impressive performances in televised debates, and
surge back to the front as Election Day approaches. Bush is tougher
than he looks, folks; the man is a winner.
</P>
<P>
   BILL CLINTON: The president declared himself ``cheerleader in
chief'' the other day and said he loves his new role promoting the
campaigns of Gore and first lady Hillary Clinton, who is running
for a U.S. Senate seat in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family has a new candidate, and my party has a new
leader,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, that's the good news. The bad news is that the new
candidate is Hillary and the new leader is Gore.
</P>
<P>
   OPRAH WINFREY: Gore showed up on Oprah's TV talk show the other
day, and it was touch and go to see who would outgush whom. The
hour was filled with frantic fawning and fanatical flattering.
Winfrey even cranked up some videotape of the Al-Tipper kiss at the
convention _ and provided play-by-play commentary on the Gores'
amazing ``jaw action.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush is scheduled to appear on the Oprah program next week. Do
you suppose that Winfrey will show the same enthusiasm and
deference toward the Republican hopeful that she offered the
Democratic candidate?
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can reach him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
