<P>
   EDUCATION-COMPUTERS (San Francisco) _ Traditional educational
values have been eclipsed by an obsession with technology in recent
years, creating an unhealthy learning environment for children. So
says a coalition of doctors, educators and child development
experts who have spent nearly two years studying the role that
computers play in the education of children. By ALAN T. SARACEVIC.
</P>
<P>
   GILL-NETS (San Francisco) _ In an attempt to stop the drowning
deaths of more than a hundred marine mammals and thousands of
seabirds a year, the state is restricting gill-net fishing along
vast stretches of the Central Coast. By JANE KAY.
</P>
<P>
   MURDER-TRIAL (Del Rio, Texas) _ Jurors hear an eyewitness
account of the murder of 13-year-old Kaylene ``Katy'' Harris in the
capital murder trial of Tommy Lynn Sells, who is accused of killing
her and then trying to kill the eyewitness, 11-year-old Krystal
Surles. Sells, a carnival worker, has received nationwide notoriety
for his claims of having killed 20 or more people during two
decades on the road. By JOHN MacCORMACK.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-CHESS (Brownsville, Texas) _ An elementary school lauded
for its youth chess program here has been recognized as one of the
five best schools in the country by Hispanic Magazine. Nearly all
of Morningside Elementary School's students are from low-income
families and much of the all-Hispanic student body is in bilingual
education. Jay Harris, Morningside's principal credits the school's
teachers for the honor. By ALISON GREGOR.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   JOBS-APPLE (San Francisco) _ Steve Jobs has taken his act
overseas, unveiling a test version of Apple's newest operating
system at a trade show in Paris. Jobs, co-founder and CEO of Apple
Computers Inc., unveiled a test version of Mac OS X at Apple Expo
2000. By ALAN T. SARACEVIC.
</P>
