   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GOODBYE-SLIP (San Antonio) _ The slip had to die. A stake had to
be driven through its clingy tricot-and-lace heart. It had to be
sent slinking off to that great lingerie graveyard in the sky, home
to the girdle, corset, garter, underwire bra and all the other
devious inventions that have caused so much female misery. By
MELISSA FLETCHER STOELTJE.
</P>
<P>
   CHILDHOOD-REVEALED (Undated) _ Ryan Hammons, now 7, was one of
the littlest victims of the bombing that destroyed the Oklahoma
City federal building, killing 169 people. Ryan survived the
bombing, but suffered from post-traumatic stress syndrome. His
artwork, along with that of many other children, is in a new book
and part of a traveling art exhibit, ``Childhood Revealed: Art
Expressing Pain, Discovery and Hope.'' The exhibit, now in Houston,
will travel to San Francisco; Austin, Texas; Albuquerque and
Roswell, N.M.; and Arvada, Colo. By BARBARA KARKABI.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT(``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SPIDERMAN (Undated) _ Marvel Comics hopes to attract young
readers by scrapping decades of often-perplexing continuity and
starting at square one with its most popular comic book heroes. The
Ultimate Spider-Man launches this week, with Ultimate X-Men coming
in November. By BRUCE WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   LOUIS-ARMSTRONG (San Francisco) _ Hearing ``Swing That Music''
on my tabletop radio may have been my first exposure to the world
of swing, but more important, it was my introduction to the talents
of Louis Armstrong and to the world of black jazz. It never would
have occurred to fans in those years before World War II that there
would one day be internationally observed centennial birth-year
celebrations devoted to Armstrong. But there are many this year. By
PHILIP ELWOOD.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SAMARANCH (Sydney) _ For a man who was a confirmed fascist
earlier in his life, Juan Antonio Samaranch has become an old
softie as he nears octogenarian status. The man credited with
saving the Olympic movement following successive boycotts of the
Games in 1976, 1980 and 1984 is flourishing in his role as
ambassador to the world of sports. Samaranch has persuaded the two
Koreas, North and South, to march under one flag in Friday's
Opening Ceremonies at Olympic Stadium. By JOHN CRUMPACKER.
</P>
