<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WONG-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A HOT DOG MAN WHO SERVED HUMANITY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WILLIAM WONG  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ About 10 years ago, I introduced my son Sam to
a legendary Oakland treat, an Original Kasper's hot dog.
</P>
<P>
   After a soccer or hockey game, I'd drive Sam to a tiny
triangular red brick-and-wood building in the Temescal neighborhood
of north Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time, we stood in line, awaiting Harry Yaglijian's
attention. The wait was worth it, both for the scrumptious hot dogs
and for Harry's warm greetings. He flashed his impish grin at me,
but he really lit up when he saw Sam.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take Harry long to remember that Sam, who was only 7
years old at the time, liked his hot dog plain _ no mustard, no
relish, no onion or tomato slices, no salt, no black or hot pepper.
I, on the other hand, ordered one ``with everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Harry's friendliness was infectious. Legions of other Original
Kasper's customers apparently felt the same way about the hot dog
and Harry's personality. He had such a good ear for languages that
he often greeted customers in their native tongues.
</P>
<P>
   Four or five years ago, Harry was stricken by a stroke, but he
recovered enough to return to work. In early 1997, we were saddened
to learn Harry had had another stroke.
</P>
<P>
   This time, his affliction was more serious, and Harry no longer
was there behind the counter, lovingly slicing onions and tomatoes
to wedge into the hot dogs on buns he spread out in front of him on
a special slotted board, each slot holding a sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   His son, Harry Jr., a musician and community activist, filled in
admirably for his dad, exhibiting the same friendliness to the
wildly diverse patrons. I would ask Harry the son how his dad was
doing and he'd be as positive as he could, but I sensed that the
elder Harry wasn't doing well at all.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 28, the end came for Harry Yaglijian, who was 85, a man
whose life story epitomizes the American Dream. Many stories have
been written about Harry and his wonderful Original Kasper's hot
dogs, but I was fascinated by stories his son told me shortly after
his dad's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Yaglijian was born in Armenia, the youngest of seven
children and the only boy. He was orphaned in 1915 when his parents
were killed by Turkish soldiers. He and five of his sisters managed
to reunite and spent the next nine years living in Russia, Syria,
Lebanon and Iran, among other places.
</P>
<P>
   They wanted to emigrate to the United States, but couldn't, so
they went to Cuba instead, where Harry lived for about 15 years. He
came to the United States in 1939.
</P>
<P>
   In Cuba, he was a cobbler. As a new American immigrant, he
became a gem cutter, nurtured by the tight-knit Armenian refugee
community in California.
</P>
<P>
   After serving time in the U.S. Army Air Corps _ he loaded bombs
and weapons onto fighter planes in Europe during World War II _ he
got married to the daughter of Kasper Koojoolian, an Armenian
immigrant who moved to Oakland from Chicago. Koojoolian started the
hot dog business that Harry eventually took over in 1947.
</P>
<P>
   In his lifetime, Harry Yaglijian had four given names _
Harutiun, which means ``resurrection'' in Armenian; Muhammud, when
he was saved by an Arab Muslim woman named Fatima after his parents
were killed; Arturo, during his Cuban days; and finally Harry.
Actually, he took on a fifth name, Mr. Kasper's.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter what name he used.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad was a very ecumenical man. He paid more attention to
who you were, not what you were,'' Harry Jr. said. ``He was honest
and good and open and friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (William Wong is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is wongink(at)earthlink.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
