<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 12:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2480 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-JOBS-APPLE-HNS &LR;      09-13 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOBS-APPLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     APPLE UNVEILS NEW OPERATING SYSTEM IN PARIS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ALAN T. SARACEVIC  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Apple Computer Inc. chief executive Steve Jobs unveiled a test
version of his company's newest operating system Wednesday at a
trade show in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs, the co-founder of Apple, released the public beta Mac OS X
at the Apple Expo 2000, a gathering of European Mac enthusiasts
similar to the Macworld Expo held in San Francisco every January.
</P>
<P>
   A public beta is a test period preceding the launch of a new
line of software. Most software companies release a
close-to-finished version of their products, allowing their
tech-savvy customers to test it out and report any kinks or bugs
that remain.
</P>
<P>
   When finished, OS X, shorthand for operating system 10, will
feature a number of enhancements, according to Apple, including a
new interface called ``Aqua'' that features a watery look and feel.
The new operating system will also feature numerous graphics
additions and expanded crash-proofing features.
</P>
<P>
   The Macintosh faithful have been waiting anxiously for the
release of OS X, which was originally scheduled to be released in
late 1999. Apple delayed the launch, first saying it would come out
in early 2000, then putting it off even further. The official
version of OS X is now expected in early 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The delays have caused grumbling among the Mac community, but
Wall Street has learned to take software delays in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone says it's late, but operating systems are hard
work,'' said analyst Daniel Kunstler, who covers Apple for J.P.
Morgan &AMP; Company. ``It's important to get them right. Compared to
the delays we've seen with other companies, these delays are
relatively trivial, and they haven't hurt sales of the Macintosh
line.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the iMac and its business cousin, the G4, have both been
selling well in recent months, according to Kunstler, spurred by
the release of the latest, greatest G4: the Cube. The 8-inch by
8-inch computer is small in stature but packs a punch.
</P>
<P>
   Unveiled last month, it is being marketed as a home computer in
size with super-computer strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is going pretty well,'' Kunstler said. ``It appears
the Cube is doing very well, although I don't have hard data. My
general feeling from anecdotal evidence is that the Cube is
performing.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it wouldn't be an Apple conference without some
controversy. A group of European Apple enthusiasts had planned a
protest during Jobs' opening keynote address, complaining that
Apple was not meeting their needs.
</P>
<P>
   Among the complaints: Apple had canceled some localized versions
of the OS, and tight margins made it impossible for retailers to
turn a profit on the latest Mac products.
</P>
<P>
   According to a posting on the MacAddict.com Web site Tuesday,
the group had been appeased by representatives of Apple U.K. and
had canceled the protest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
