<HEADER>
A2498 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-FURNACES0914-COX     09-13 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FURNACES0914-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Watch and learn during annual fall furnace inspection
 &HT;    By James Cumming
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio - To those conscientious folks who are never late
with an oil change, who have a complete physical every year and who
keep track of everybody's birthday, this is a gentle reminder: It's
time to think about scheduling your annual furnace inspection and
cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   To those who can't remember their last oil change, physical or
their birthdays, maybe this should be the year you finally do
something about the black smoke billowing from your registers.
</P>
<P>
   You can find companies that do inspections and cleaning in the
Yellow Pages under ``Heating Contractors.'' An annual furnace
inspection will help ensure that your system is operating
efficiently, and that it won't fail during the dead of winter when
you need it most.
</P>
<P>
   Also observing a furnace inspection and cleaning will help you
understand how your heating system works and how you should
maintain it between professional service calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``By all means, when the service technician is working, you can
watch and ask lots of questions,'' said Bill Michael, service
manager for Stevenson Heating and Air Conditioning in New Carlisle.
``If you don't know where your furnace filter is or how to clean it
or change it, the technician can tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael and Tom Tanner, vice president of Tanner Heating and Air
Conditioning in Dayton, said their companies are fairly busy with
residential furnace service now, but the peak of the season is
around Oct. 1. If you call for a furnace inspection in early
October, expect to wait a few days to a week for an appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Fees vary between companies, but a typical cleaning and
inspection charge in this area is about $50 to $75 plus the cost of
parts if any are needed.
</P>
<P>
   If the fees worry you, consider the fact that if your heating
system goes out during the heating season, you'll end up paying
considerably more for emergency repairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When furnaces break down, it seems like it's always at night
or on the weekends,'' Tanner said. ``Not only do you have to pay
extra to get a service worker out, you may also run into problems
getting repair parts. Our suppliers don't stay open all weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Heating and air-conditioning companies always charge for
emergency response, and you probably will pay an extra 50 percent
to 100 percent for a night or weekend service call.
</P>
<P>
   During a normal fall inspection, a technician should inspect the
furnace inside and out, check safety circuits, inspect and
lubricate moving parts and make sure the ignition system works
properly.
</P>
<P>
   Tanner said, for example, that one step in the inspection
process is checking the ignition sequence. Almost all the furnaces
built in the past 10 years were built without continuously burning
pilot lights, so when the thermostat calls for heat, first a pilot
light comes on, then a sensor detects the pilot light, then the
burner is lit, then the fan turns on.
</P>
<P>
   The most critical part of the inspection is checking for cracks
or other leaks in the heat exchanger. The heat exchanger is the
part of the furnace that separates the chamber where combustion
occurs from the warmed air that circulates around the house.
</P>
<P>
   If the heat exchanger is damaged, dangerous carbon-monoxide
fumes can circulate through the house. Furnace-service technicians
usually can spot deterioration problems in a heat exchanger, but
ask the technician to use a carbon-monoxide detector at registers
to be sure the deadly gas is not circulating from an unseen leak.
</P>
<P>
   Your furnace technician also checks to see that the furnace is
operating at its rated efficiency. That begins with a visual
inspection of the flames; discolored flames or flames not at the
proper distance from the gas jets are indications of problems, and
the technician can make adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   The technician also can measure how much the air has been warmed
as it enters the ducts leading to registers, another measure of
efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   But you, the homeowner, have the most important role in
maintaining your furnace's efficiency. Change or clean the furnace
filter using the schedule in your furnace's owners manual. Also
check the instructions that came with the filter you are using;
some filters should be changed monthly while others last longer.
</P>
<P>
   You can also repeat some of the routine maintenance checks your
technician performs. Notice how he cleans and lubricates the fan
motor, for instance. Also if your furnace has a pilot light, ask
how to relight it if it goes out.
</P>
<P>
   If you had any of the following problems last winter, your
furnace definitely should be serviced before you use it again:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  You repeatedly heard strange noises while your unit was
operating. This might be a sign of poorly performing burners.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  You noticed unusual odors such as the smell of gas or sulfur.
(The smell you may detect the first time you turn on your furnace
each year comes from accumulated dust and dirt being heated on the
heat exchanger or furnace coils, and that's normal.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Components on the furnace or pipes look burnt, corroded or
unusually dirty.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The flames over the natural-gas burners in the furnace were
yellow.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  You experienced headache, nausea, fatigue or dizziness when
the furnace was operating. Flu-like symptoms that get worse when
you're at home and ease when you're outside can indicate the
presence of carbon monoxide in the house.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Email: jamescummings(at)coxohio.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
