A2500 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-RELIGIONSHOPPING0914-     09-13 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGIONSHOPPING0914-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Religious groups blanket college campuses, hoping to recruit a
few good souls
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. - At the heart of Florida Atlantic University's
campus, along 200 yards of the concrete breezeway at the school's
annual ``Clubfest,'' an evangelical Baptist group handing out Cokes
vies for attention with a Boca Raton Kabbalah organization offering
Tootsie Rolls.
</P>
<P>
   A few feet away, immersed in techno music from a nearby
fraternity trolling for members, a ministry for foreign exchange
students _ with pamphlets in Korean, Spanish and Russian _ is set
up across from a gay and lesbian support group. Interspersed
between two dozen more sororities, dance clubs and intramural
sports groups are representatives from the Fellowship for Christian
Athletes, the Catholic Newman House and the Jewish organization
Hillel, all making their pitches.
</P>
<P>
   At stake? Students like Lenny Marine, 20, a communications major
from Fort Lauderdale with an interest _ though not much of a formal
education _ in the religious and the spiritual. ``I was brought up
a little Jewish and a little Christian,'' Marine said. ``Basically
I believe in a god force, but I don't believe in a God that judges
people.''
</P>
<P>
   What exactly defines a ``god force'' is something Marine is
trying to figure out. So to better discern what spiritual path _ if
any _ he will follow, he jotted his name and number down on the
sign-up sheet next to the Tootsie Rolls. Next week, it may be
Buddhism or Hinduism. ``I like the whole mysticism idea,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of such decisions are being made on college campuses
across the country, as students return to school and are faced with
an army of ministries determined to show them the light, save their
souls or just get them to Mass. Some of the decisions made will
change lives and alter spiritual trajectories. Others will be
forgotten by the end of the day. For the people manning the tables,
the competition to convert, attract or at least educate is intense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is worried about how ... to protect their group from
other people who want to poach on their turf,'' said Andrew Walsh,
of the Center for the Study of Religion in Public Life at Trinity
College in Connecticut. ``There's still an expectation in our
Protestant-based society that at about this time in your life
you're expected to declare some sort of adult declaration of faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``(These groups) want to get their dibs in before their kids are
swallowed whole by hostile academic secularism.''
</P>
<P>
   College freshman away from home for the first time are at a
crossroads in their lives, and religious ministries know it. Out
from under their parents' wings, many will begin to question the
spiritual or religious foundations their parents may or may not
have laid for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had students come (who) say to me, `I'm literally
shopping for a religion,''' said Sharon Conley, a staffer with
InterVarsity, an evangelical Christian organization for college
kids and one of the women handing out Cokes at FAU. ``Those are my
favorites. I say, `Come check us out. See if Jesus stands up to his
claims.'''
</P>
<P>
   American religious leaders have been worried about college
freshman for 300 years. The YMCA and later the YWCA was born out of
an attempt to reach college students more than a century ago.
Entire institutions of higher learning have been built around the
premise that during young adulthood many people take a break from
their religious commitments. Campus ministries are designed to
prevent that.
</P>
<P>
   Campus Crusade for Christ, based in Orlando, Fla., is among the
largest such ministries in the nation. This year nearly 200,000
first-year students will receive ``Freshman Survival Kits''
consisting of a Bible, a video about alcohol or relationships and a
CD of Christian music.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something to provide them with answers to their spiritual
questions,'' said Nathan Dunn, director of communication for the
Campus Crusade for Christ. ``And they will have questions.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the student evangelists _ be they Muslim, Christian,
Jewish or Buddhists _ it is getting more difficult to seal the deal
with a generation sociologists say is more materialistic and
cynical and less philosophical than their baby boomer parents. In
1967, 83 percent of college freshman considered it essential or
very important to develop a meaningful philosophy of life. By 1996,
that had dropped to 42 percent, according to an annual values
survey conducted by the Higher Education Research Institute at
UCLA. Meanwhile, the percentage of freshman who considered it
essential or very important to be very well off financially rose
from 44 percent in 1966 to 74 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, this generation of freshman grew up being
taught the virtues of tolerance. As a result, few believe there is
only one path up the proverbial mountain. For them, their spiritual
search often leads to the mystical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's where the really important stuff is,'' Marine
said. ``It's what I'd like to learn more about.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Email: dougbelkin(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
