<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST WOMAN BISHOP OF AME CHURCH HONORED IN BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rev. Vashti M. McKenzie made history this summer.
</P>
<P>
   On July 11, she was elected the first woman bishop of the
African Methodist Episcopal Church, a move that also made her the
first woman bishop in any predominantly black denomination.
</P>
<P>
   McKenzie, 53, is a former journalist who was raised in the
Episcopal Church but converted to the AME church. For the last 10
years, she has served as pastor of the Payne Memorial Church in
Baltimore, an unusually active inner-city church that runs a
welfare-to-work program for the state of Maryland and helps
congregants start small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   McKenzie was honored in Boston, when where she went to speak at
the historic Charles Street AME Church. On the eve of her visit,
she spoke with the Globe about her rise to bishop, her experience
as a pastor in Baltimore, and her thoughts as she prepares to move
to Africa for her first assignment as a bishop.
</P>
<P>
   In Africa she will oversee an episcopal district that includes
200 churches in Botswana, Lesotho, Mozambique and Swaziland.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How did you become a minister?
</P>
<P>
   A. I came from a family of writers and journalists and really
had thought that was going to be my career. I started out in
journalism, expanded into broadcasting, ended up in broadcast
management, and received my call to ministry. I can't tell you that
lightning flashed, the earth moved and that, but it's a knowing,
it's a knowing down on the inside of your heart; it's listening to
that still, small voice; it's a push that nudges you in such a way
that you know that you'll respond.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why did you leave the Episcopal Church for the AME Church?
</P>
<P>
   A. Coming out of college, when you are making choices for
yourself, I found that what interested me, what was calling me was
what the AME church was doing. My concern had always been for the
community, that the church is to embrace the community, and where I
was, I didn't see that much going on. I was looking and searching
and found that here was a denomination that spoke to my interests
in building lives, building people.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Tell me about your experience at Payne Memorial.
</P>
<P>
   A. Payne is my third congregation. It was a congregation of
about 300, and we grew to over 1,700 persons. It was a Sunday-only
congregation and now Payne is a seven-day a week church. We have
worked very hard to erase the lines between sanctuary and
community, so that when you look at us you're looking at the
community. We anchor our community; we resource our community; we
are a stabilizing force in our community and we are a redevelopment
force in our community. I believe that that's what churches who are
in the urban core ought to be about. If you sit around and wait for
other city groups or government to do it, it just won't be done. If
it was going to be done, it would have been done, and since it's
not being done, somebody must move into that void, and I believe
it's us because we have a biblical mandate. We have the role model
of Jesus Christ, who did not spend all his time in the synagogue.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you worry that your emphasis on programming dilutes your
spiritual ministry?
</P>
<P>
   A. No, I don't. If there is no action after you have heard the
word of God, if there is no visible response, then we're just
throwing words out, we're just whistling Dixie. I believe that
ministry is the word and action. Faith without works is death.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Will it be challenging to be a woman leader in Africa?
</P>
<P>
   A. There is a history in Africa of strong women, and there is
patriarchy in Africa. There is patriarchy here in the United
States. There's sexism there and sexism here. Not too different.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How will your election affect women in other denominations?
</P>
<P>
   A. I'm hoping that it will be an encouragement to women to
continue to believe in the God that has called them to serve. The
election speaks to a change in the AME church, and hopefully a
change in other denominations as well. This is the 21st Century,
and we cannot afford not having the whole family at the table of
service and work. The issues are too great, the devastation is too
widespread for just one part of the family to be at the table
making decisions and providing leadership. We can transcend those
superficial divisions and join hands and partner for the welfare of
the community.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Will there always be a need for separate black denominations
in the US?
</P>
<P>
   A. History will play that out, to see how diversified we can be.
There are persons in the AME Church who are not African-American,
there are pastors who are not African-American. But the church was
born because it suffered the indignity of racism and segregation
within the larger congregation and it had to separate because of
the treatment of the people. Although we were born not for any
theological differences, but because of the prejudices that people
were experiencing, we still preach a gospel of inclusion, and
whether one is white, black, pink, green or purple, the same God
extends to them salvation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
