<SLUG> BC-SPIDERMAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW SPIDER-MAN DEBUTS FOR YOUNGER AUDIENCE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
Houston Chronicle 
As everyone knows, comics are for kids.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of course, that's when ``everyone'' refers to the vast majority
of people who never come near a comic book.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, comics have skewed toward adult buyers for years,
via the collectibles market, harder-edged material and slick,
costly comics and graphic novels.
</P>
<P>
   With the corresponding rise of video games, the Internet,
collectible card games such as Pokemon and other forms of
entertainment, today's kids are spending far less time reading
comics than kids of generations past.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it's their parents or older siblings who are buying
comics and sealing them in plastic bags for posterity.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, publishers face a challenge as daunting as Superman
escaping from a cell lined with Kryptonite: how to win young
readers back.
</P>
<P>
   Industry leader Marvel has what it hopes will be an answer: the
``Ultimate'' Marvel line.
</P>
<P>
   It debuts this month with Ultimate Spider-Man and will continue
by year's end with Ultimate X-Men.
</P>
<P>
   Both monthly books will retell the origins of Spider-Man and the
X-Men _ created in the early '60s _ but with a difference.
</P>
<P>
   Younger characters will be emphasized, and by starting fresh,
the yarns can be tweaked and updated.
</P>
<P>
   Marvel's new editor in chief, Joe Quesada, doesn't blame kids
for being turned off.
</P>
<P>
   ``The continuity of Marvel is 30-plus years, and unless you've
been with us for 30 years, it's daunting to catch up on all that
history,'' he said. ``So we created the Ultimate Marvel universe to
streamline and update it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimate Spider-Man No. 1, featuring a 48-page story with no
ads, costs $2.99. Later issues will have 22-page stories in 32-page
books (with ads) for $1.99.
</P>
<P>
   These are being sold not only by the ``hobby'' market of comics
shops but also by mass-market retailers such as drugstores.
</P>
<P>
   Quesada admits comics have ``lost some relevance to the youth
market,'' and a Houston dealer concurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average Marvel reader is 30 years old,'' said Richard
Evans, owner of Bedrock City Comic Co.. ``There's a shrinking
percentage of kid readers.''
</P>
<P>
   Quesada even feels there's a ``lost generation of kids who
didn't get into comics.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's never too late.
</P>
<P>
   Kids certainly discovered Marvel's ``X-Men'' movie, judging by
its success; it has made more than $150 million in the United
States alone.
</P>
<P>
   Quesada regrets failing to have Ultimate X-Men out in time for
the movie, ``but with a Spider-Man film looming, we're ready,'' he
said. ``A readable, fan-friendly Spider-Man will be on the stands
when it appears.''
</P>
<P>
   Due next year, that film will star Tobey Maguire. Quesada
expects the script to have fresh reinventions, much as ``X-Men''
did.
</P>
<P>
   Sporting a distinctive logo, Ultimate Spider-Man is aimed at
readers from ages 8 to adult. It doesn't talk down to kids, so
Quesada expects older fans to buy it, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to get kids reading comics again, but we hope
older readers will like this, even though they resist change. If
the product is great, it's great.''
</P>
<P>
   Marvel has tried kid-geared books before, such as Power Pack,
``but we've talked down to kids,'' Quesada said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Live and learn. We'll keep trying. Ultimate Spider-Man is a
big first step.''
</P>
<P>
   Its aim, he said, ``is not to reinvent the wheel, but to polish
the hubcap, retread it and put it on a new sports car. By doing
that, we hope to reach introductory readers.''
</P>
<P>
   When writer Stan Lee and artist Steve Ditko created Spider-Man
38 years ago, the origin tale zipped through many events in just a
few pages.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimate Spider-Man is taking its time, first reintroducing _
and slightly reinventing _ Peter Parker, the future Spider-Man.
</P>
<P>
   Peter is now a 15-year-old high school student in Queens, N.Y.,
wearing round glasses akin to Harry Potter's. (The original Peter
was a high school senior.)
</P>
<P>
   As before, the orphaned Peter lives with his Aunt May and Uncle
Ben. Ben was killed off in Spidey's first '60s appearance, but he
survives the first issue of Ultimate Spider-Man, in which his
character is fleshed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The original Uncle Ben would have fought in World War II, but
that's ancient history to a lot of kids,'' Quesada said. ``You've
got to slide it across time and make it relevant for today.''
</P>
<P>
   So this Ben wears his gray hair in a ponytail and speaks like a
hip, kindly child of Woodstock.
</P>
<P>
   In the first Ultimate Spider-Man, as in the first origin, Peter
is bitten by a radioactive spider and gains spider powers (super
strength and an adhesive touch that allows him to climb walls).
</P>
<P>
   But his shift to superherodom will be gradual.
</P>
<P>
   Decades ago, Peter created a costume and became Spider-Man in
his first appearance. At the end of Ultimate Spider-Man No. 1, he
hasn't even had such an idea yet.
</P>
<P>
   In other ways, the Ultimate universe will move even faster.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Jane Watson _ Peter's future girlfriend and wife in the
original series _ didn't appear in the original series until Issue
25. In Ultimate Spider-Man, she pops up in the first issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the luxury of fleshing out Stan's story and telling
what happened between the cracks,'' Quesada said. ``We'll tell the
origin in a six-issue story arc, establishing the relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   Some _ but not all _ tales and villains from Amazing
Spider-Man's early issues will be reworked.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll see Doctor Octopus and other classic villains, but
they'll be a little different,'' Quesada said. ``We don't want to
be married to the old books. We want a more modern context.''
</P>
<P>
   The new book is written by Brian Michael Bendis and penciled by
former Spidey artist Mark Bagley, who pays homage to Ditko's
distinctive splayed fingers and the highly expressive faces of Dave
Stevens, creator of the Rocketeer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The art is charming,'' Quesada said. ``You get a real feel for
the kids in school _ the way they dress, their mannerisms.''
</P>
<P>
   For Marvel, this shift is especially ironic. Its rise as a
comics power in the '60s was sparked by Lee's ardor to make comics
_ until then a kids' medium _ appealing for college students and
adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``Years ago, Stan made it cool for adults to read comics,''
Quesada said. ``Now we're trying to make it cool for kids to read
them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Marvel did their job too well,'' Evans said. ``Now comics
aren't perceived as being for kids _ and a lot of them aren't. But
comics stores are the same as any kind of book store. There's stuff
for kids, grown-ups, boys, girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Without kids, the comics market has declined in recent years,
after an early-'90s explosion fueled by adult collectors.
</P>
<P>
   Sales then were high because adults aggressively bought multiple
copies, hoping to resell them at a profit. They didn't. Many people
were turned off, and readership declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``Comics shouldn't be about collecting,'' Quesada said. ``They
should be about reading and having fun. When people got focused on
collecting, the market crashed.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Marvel slid into bankruptcy in '96, though it recovered
in '98 via a merger with toy manufacturer Toy Biz.
</P>
<P>
   While Ultimate Marvel is made for kids, it won't shove them into
a corner by themselves. The Ultimate storyline may even cross over
with Marvel's other titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not gonna be held down by the rules,'' Quesada said.
``Who's to say this (the Ultimate line) isn't the real marvel
universe?
</P>
<P>
   ``To a young reader, it doesn't matter. They don't mind a
change, and change is what this is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-00 1342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000913.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2526 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-SLOGANS-BOS &LR;      09-13 1399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-SLOGANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLOGANS A LOST ART ON THE CAMPAIGN TRAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even now, in a new century, in a period of impatience with
politics, these cries echo across history: He kept us out of war.
Rugged individualism. A new deal for the American people. Let's get
America moving again.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are these, from this election year, slogans
without power, punch, or passion: I'm for the people, not for the
powerful. A reformer with results.
</P>
<P>
   As a genre, the American political slogan, the art form that
allowed Woodrow Wilson, Herbert Hoover, Franklin Delano Roosevelt,
and John F. Kennedy to encapsulate an entire election with a
single, telling phrase, may be dying.
</P>
<P>
   And the death of the political slogan _ whether conjuring an
image, like William McKinley's ``full dinner pail'' during the
prosperity of 1900, or asking a question, like Ronald Reagan's
``Are you better off than you were four years ago?'' in 1980, or
drawing on the power and pith of a single word, like Warren G.
Harding's ``Normalcy'' in 1920 _ may have a significance far beyond
the rhetorical.
</P>
<P>
   At root, political slogans are nothing more than advertising
gambits and political campaigns are little more than marketing
offensives. The irony is that in this age of advertising and heyday
of mass marketing, Al Gore and George W. Bush are falling so flat.
</P>
<P>
   Consider, for example, the raw materials of this campaign. One
nominee, himself a two-term vice president, is the son of one of
the lions of the Senate _ enough to make ``Gore'' one of the most
resonant names in politics. The other, governor of a large state,
is the grandson of a senator and the son of a man who was both vice
president and president _ enough to render ``Bush'' one of the most
enduring brand names in American life.
</P>
<P>
   And yet in an era of ``branding'' _ when the most prosaic
products, even water _ have a strong marketplace identity, both
Gore and Bush have fumbled at developing a brand of their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what happens when you take one candidate, Vice
President Gore, who is not sure of who he is, and another, Governor
Bush, who was anointed by the power brokers,'' said L. Sandy
Maisel, a Colby College political scientist. ``There is no there
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the colorlessness of this campaign derives from the
particular appeal of both men, who from the start of their
political lives have prospered in the center, not the fringes. It
is hard to coin fighting words for a battle over the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Part of it comes from the times, with the public seeming to
almost welcome blandness in their would-be presidents, if only for
the contrast to the colorful but also deeply flawed figure the two
nominees are trying to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   And part of it comes from the nature of contemporary culture,
which is crowded with media images in a way that would startle
William Henry Harrison, who rode to office in 1840 on his
(completely false) image as the ``log-cabin-and-hard-cider''
candidate, and would astonish Dwight D. Eisenhower, whose entire
political persona seemed in 1952 (simplistically, it turned out) to
be summarized in the phrase ``I like Ike.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything in this country is marketing,'' said Richard Norton
Smith, a prominent presidential biographer. ``It is highly unlikely
that a slogan in this climate would move people or inspire people.
We're bombarded by so much sloganeering that it is hard to get
through the clutter.''
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't helped, of course, that both candidates seem to be
running through slogans at marathon speed.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Bush has conducted a ``change-the-tone-tour,''
vowed that under his administration there would be ``no child left
behind,'' and said his goal was ``renewing America's purpose.'' He
has spoken of ``prosperity with a purpose'' and of ``compassionate
conservatism'' and then, when Senator John McCain won the New
Hampshire primary on Feb. 1 with an insurrectionary campaign,
portrayed himself as a ``reformer with results.''
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, Bush unveiled yet another new slogan, ``Real
Plans for Real People.'' If the Bush slogan has a familiar sound to
it, it's because a dozen years ago John Hancock Insurance Co. ran
an ad campaign called ``Real Life, Real Answers,'' which was
followed by a Winston cigarette campaign called ``Real people, real
taste.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Bush may have crowded his one potentially enduring
slogan _ compassionate conservatism _ with rhetorical emphemera and
permitted the nation to sidestep a potentially important discussion
about the nature of both compassion and conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has swapped slogans as often as he has changed wardrobes.
In the primaries, the refrain was ``I want to fight for you.'' In
the general election he has turned to ``I'm for the people, not the
powerful.'' But in recent weeks that has faded, replaced by a new
slogan, ``Fighting for working families.''
</P>
<P>
   The candidates are switching slogans in part because they
haven't yet cemented their identities.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Bush's case, he hasn't been able to brand himself because
he can't yet find a rationale for his candidacy,'' said Michael
Sandel, a Harvard political scientist. ``This is a time of peace
and prosperity, and his only argument is that he would provide
leadership with a higher moral standard than Clinton. Gore's
campaign has a rationale _ keep things the way they are _ but he
lacks branding because he can't do what brands do: say that they
have something new and improved.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some of the most compelling slogans in American
political history have been two-word program descriptions, in
almost every case (important exceptions were Harry S. Truman's Fair
Deal and Lyndon B. Johnson's Great Society) beginning with the word
``New.'' Thus American history can be explained in outline form by
simply the phrases New Nationalism (Theodore Roosevelt), New
Freedom (Woodrow Wilson), New Deal (Franklin Roosevelt), New
Frontier (Kennedy), New Beginning (Reagan), and New Covenant (Bill
Clinton).
</P>
<P>
   The quick changes in persona and slogans undertaken by both
candidates have failed to convince in large measure because they
are so fleeting. One of the most compelling political slogans of
the postwar period was one of the most unlikely, the New Nixon
slogan that was so effective in 1968. Gore's efforts to project a
New Gore isn't nearly as convincing because his image isn't nearly
as fixed as Richard M. Nixon's was in the mid-1960s. The New Nixon
came after 25 years of exposure to the Old Nixon, first on Capitol
Hill, then in the vice presidency, then in a presidential campaign,
and finally in a doomed gubernatorial campaign in California.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of American elections have long cited the slogan (and
its soulmate, the bumper sticker) as the symbol of one of the evils
of the nation's politics, its tendency to favor the simplistic over
the serious.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, many American slogans have been neither honest
(Harrison was no poor, cider-swigging frontier lad) nor original
(Governor Alf Landon of Kansas spoke of a ``new frontier'' 24 years
before Kennedy's campaign). In most cases, political slogans have
had almost no ideological content. Slogans such as ``Give 'em hell,
Harry'' (Truman, 1948), ``All the way with LBJ'' Johnson, 1964),
and ``Nixon's the One'' (1968) are little more than grandstand
cheers.
</P>
<P>
   Slogans can have unexpected political side-effects, too. Hoover,
realizing that ``rugged individualism'' seemed harsh at the time of
great economic hardship, tried unsuccessfully to disclaim the
phrase as the Depression deepened. The Republicans ran their 1936
campaign around the sunflower, the symbol of Kansas, the home of
their nominee, Governor Landon. The Democrats countered with their
quip, ``Sunflowers die in November.'' They were right; FDR beat
Landon, taking all but Maine and Vermont. In 1964, Senator Barry
Goldwater of Arizona, the Republican nominee, chose a slogan
intended to show his ideological purity: ``In your heart you know
he's right.'' The Democrats countered with, ``In your heart you
know he's nuts.'' Goldwater lost 44 states.
</P>
<P>
   But all politicians, regardless of whether they have a
compelling slogan, have one thing in common, particularly as
Election Day approaches. They still believe in a place called Hope.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
