<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRUSTRATED THORNTON IS ON OUTISDE, LOOKING IN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ His Bruins teammates are in training camp, fighting for
jobs, rehabilitating injuries, and getting in shape for the season.
But north of the border in St. Thomas, Ontario, free agent center
Joe Thornton is having the gut feeling that he won't be joining
them for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton, whose shoulder has completely healed from offseason
surgery to repair stretched tendons, is skating with a junior
hockey team, the London Knights, near his home and hoping a
resolution to his status is just around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   The 21-year-old center has been commiserating with the other two
missing Bruins _ Sergei Samsonov and Anson Carter _ and that has
helped keep his spirits up.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, he is working with a personal trainer, skating
hard, and waiting. And waiting some more. The lines of
communication are open between Thornton's agent Mike Barnett and
Bruins management, but Thornton said talks have stalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely going to take some more time, I think,'' said
Thornton. ``At least we have been talking, and that's a good sign,
but I don't think too much has come out of it lately.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past two years Thornton has watched as other free agents
have sat out camp and in some cases part of the regular season. He
said he didn't want that to be him this fall, but if it happens,
he's prepared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd hope it would get done, but you never know,'' he said.
``With guys in the past, it's gone into the regular season so I
wouldn't be surprised if it does. We are all adults and hopefully
it will get resolved. We're feeling like we're being as fair as we
can without giving up a lot. Hopefully they'll start being fair,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Thornton, who became a free agent July 1, said he thinks a deal
could've been struck long before now, and he's frustrated it
wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had all summer to do it,'' he said. ``It is disappointing
to not be there at training camp when you knew something could've
been done two months ago. But it seems like they kept putting it on
the back burner. Hopefully it gets resolved as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not too far apart. We're not miles and miles apart.
We're still a good ways apart, though, that's for sure. We're just
going to have to wait it out and hopefully it will get resolved.
But the other aspect is the guys, hopefully, will be missing us
soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Last spring Thornton was stung by president/general manager
Harry Sinden's comments that the third-year player had not
developed as much as he should've. After thinking about it,
Thornton said he realized it was likely a preemptive negotiating
ploy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he kind of put it right there, that it was going to be
a tough, long summer,'' Thornton said. ``But me and coach (Pat)
Burns, I think we were doing fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Thornton said one of the most difficult aspects of this time is
how disappointing last season was for all the Bruins. A good start
is critical, and without the team's leading scorer and two strong
supporting players, that won't be easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The earlier they get us, the better the team chemistry is
going to be,'' he said. ``In years past, we never had guys there at
the start of the year. I think if we all get there together and
play some exhibition games together, I think we'll be that much
better at the start.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been tough but it's part of the learning process.
Hopefully, I won't have to do it ever again but I'm kind of
learning the ropes. Just looking at guys in the past, I don't think
anyone is surprised that we're holding out right now. We want it to
get done soon. We all know it's going to be tough, though. Every
year, I'm learning something. This is another thing I have to
learn.''
</P>
<P>
   His fellow free agents have told him to hang in there, his agent
is saying the same thing, and the Bruins who are in camp have told
him to do what he feels he has to do. Thornton said he just wishes
it didn't have to be this way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been through anything like this before, so it's a
little different,'' he said. ``But I've seen other guys do it in
years past so it's not different in that aspect. You have to do
what you have do and I think I'm going to help out my teammates by
doing this. You have to think of them, too. It's definitely weird
because I've always started training camp with the guys. In junior,
I was always there, too, so it's different. But it's something you
have to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
