<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-PUIG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUIG: A WRITER BETRAYED BY SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
MANUEL PUIG AND THE SPIDER WOMAN 
His Life and Fictions 
By Suzanne Jill Levine 
Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, 448 pp., illustrated, $27.50 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Manuel Puig spent as much of his waking life as he could in the
dream world of the movies, most particularly the great romantic
movies of the 1930s and 1940s. He wanted to write movies, and
ultimately he did. He met Rita Hayworth, saw Garbo on the street,
watched Marlene Dietrich at work in the dubbing room, and attended
a personal appearance by Joan Crawford. His most famous novel,
``Kiss of the Spider Woman,'' became an even more famous film and
after that a Broadway musical hit.
</P>
<P>
   Puig died of complications from gall-bladder surgery in 1990,
when he was 57. His agent told his biographer that Puig had been on
the verge of making more money than he had made in his entire
career, and that the musical would have given him carte blanche in
Hollywood and on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   The paradox is that Puig might not have wanted this particular
manifestation of success once it finally came to him. Out of the
raw material of popular culture, he had fashioned a personal and
literary art which even today has not been properly recognized and
acknowledged. The man who loved the movies hated ``Kiss of the
Spider Woman'' because it misrepresented his own achievement and
simplified everything he believed in and cared about. (In this he
found himself in a position parallel to Christopher Isherwood's _
Isherwood, too, found himself courted, coopted, and compromised by
Hollywood. ``Cabaret'' had very little to do with the perfect
little novels it was based on, but it made Ishwerwood financially
comfortable for the first time in his life.)
</P>
<P>
   Puig was born in General Villegas, an Argentine town of about
15,000 that was 12 hours by train from Buenos Aires. Puig's
lifeline was his weekly trip with his mother to Teatro Espagnol to
watch the American movies which had captivated his imagination; the
movies provided an alternative model to the all-too-real world Puig
found himself in.
</P>
<P>
   Puig later lived in Buenos Aires, in Rome (where he studied
film), in London, in New York, in Rio de Janeiro, and, finally, in
Mexico. His closest companion was his mother, elegant and
demanding, which whom he lived much of his life. He held all kinds
of odd jobs; while writing his first novel, ``Betrayed by Rita
Hayworth,'' he was working as a ticketing agent for Air France at
Kennedy Airport. He knew languages and taught them; once his books
began to attract notice, he worked a little on the academic
circuit. Ultimately he produced eight novels, along with several
plays and screenplays.
</P>
<P>
   Puig's literary achievement has not yet been properly evaluated.
His books became controversial for political reasons in South
America; there were points at which Puig had reason to fear for his
own safety and that of his family. The sensibility of the novels,
which mingles popular culture with an openly gay point of view,
made them controversial everywhere. Puig may always have spoken of
himself as a female and dubbed everyone else the same way (the
studiously straight William Hurt was ``la Hurt''), but he had
little interest in promoting himself as a ``gay novelist.'' That's
what happened to him anyway, with the result that his books have
been excessively praised and condemned for reasons having little to
do with their literary merits.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne Jill Levine was Puig's principal American translator;
she met him in 1968 and remained on friendly terms with him for the
rest of his life. Her biography is detailed, affectionate, and
appropriately breezy and colloquial in tone. She clearly enjoyed
Puig's company, alarming as it could sometimes be, and its easy to
see why _ Puig was a mildly outrageous character with a sharp
tongue and a warm heart. He had no use for the film stars of the
'80s who repudiated the glamor-puss images of their predecessors;
he dismissed Ellen Burstyn, Jill Clayburgh, Meryl Streep, and Glenn
Close as ``The Four Horsewomen of the Apocalypse.'' Once he threw a
close friend out into the street in the middle of a winter night
because the friend said Lana Turner was a lousy actress and a
whore.
</P>
<P>
   Puig loved to pose, vamp, and camp. One of his students at
Columbia University, the Colombian writer Jaime Manrique, wrote a
memorial tribute, ``The Writer as Diva,'' that provides a visual
image of Puig more striking than any photograph in the biography.
``Like Garbo's his eyes were a tool, a weapon, not just organs for
seeing, but for expressing what he saw. Like the great diva, he
raised his eyebrow (the left one) to indicate pain, disdain,
despair.'' But Manuel Puig did see an amazing amount with those
eyes, and what he learned to express on his Olivetti portable was
more durable than any pose in a doorway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
