<SLUG> BC-IDAHO-FIRES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMY LOSING TO FIRES IN IDAHO TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALMON, Idaho _ Base camp was a muddy mess.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters awoke to find their tents filled with water.
Vehicles skidded in the makeshift parking lot. Roads were declared
impassable.
</P>
<P>
   The men and women in familiar yellow shirts and flame-retardant
slacks were too exhausted to celebrate, but their relief was clear.
The mud, the rain, the cooler temperatures gave them a chance to
turn the corner in their fight to bring the worst US forest fires
in a half-century or more under control.
</P>
<P>
   ``This fire in Idaho was big, and it looked like it was going to
burn forever,'' said Douglas Johnston, a fire information officer
temporarily stationed in Salmon. ``It doesn't look like that now.''
</P>
<P>
   Forests continue to burn across the West, but firefighters from
around the country were leaving Montana by the planeload last week.
The Clear Creek Complex, as about 206,000 acres burning in Idaho's
Salmon-Challis National Forest are known, is now 77 percent
contained, up from 29 percent only days before. About 450
firefighters packed up their equipment and went home or moved on to
fires in other states.
</P>
<P>
   Hunters and hikers were allowed to venture out again, although
only in approved areas and not soon enough to salvage the economies
of Salmon and other small, tourist-dependent towns in fire
territory. Even towns not directly touched by fire found themselves
badly burned.
</P>
<P>
   Relatively few structures and no lives have been lost around
Salmon, where about 3,400 people live and thousands more visit each
year to run the River of No Return, hunt the bountiful forest, and
backpack through spectacular Lewis &AMP; Clark country. Summer is to
Salmon retailers and river guides what Christmas is to merchants
and ski resorts elsewhere. Salmon's relatively high-paying gold
mine was recently shuttered, its namesake fish is off-limits due to
endangerment, and logging is mostly a memory.
</P>
<P>
   But tourists have stayed away from Salmon this season,
frightened by the fires only about 10 miles from town and warned of
the inaccessibility of favored spots. At one point, the air was so
thick with smoke that people wore face masks and resident C.
Hokanson had to stay indoors day after day or risk an allergy
attack.
</P>
<P>
   The view of the mountains was so blurred that one second-grader
new to Salmon drew a picture of the town without them; he didn't
know they were there. The summer fair was a failure, the balloon
festival was canceled, and even some riders couldn't reach Salmon
for the annual rodeo, one of the biggest events of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You add the fire on top of what we've already gone through and
it's almost more than a community can take,'' said Salmon's mayor,
Stanley Davis, also the school district's maintenance supervisor.
``It's like kicking a guy when he's down. People were already
hurting, and now they're really hurting.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Stasiak, Lemhi County's newly appointed economic
development director, said he has been hearing complaints from the
merchants whose stores line Main Street that business is off from
10 percent to as much as 60 percent from the same time a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's touch and go,'' said Thyra Warren, who owns Rendezvous
Sports, where visitors can buy their gear and book their fishing
and rafting adventures. The store's business was down 37 percent in
July and 26 percent in August, Warren said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the worst summer in the seven years we've been in
business,'' Warren added. ``I make all my profits in the summer to
last me through the winter. I'm just hoping we get some business
back now.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with some forest reopened to tourists and hunting season
officially underway, no one expects a rebound overnight. Many
locals said they worry that the fires themselves will rebound once
the skies clear and the land dries. By late afternoon the other
day, base camp had already turned brown, leaving the ground parched
as usual. Deep in the forest, despite the fresh green grass, dust
was kicking up as temperatures began rising again.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, about 6.6 million acres have burned since January,
the agency said. For all the recent rain, for all the months of
effort, 33 large fires were still burning on 1.4 million acres in
10 states as of Friday, according to the National Interagency Fire
Center in Boise, Idaho. Six large fires constituting 633,231 acres
remained ablaze in Idaho alone.
</P>
<P>
   The fires in the Wildnerness Complex _ at 180,600 acres, one of
the state's largest _ are spreading. Even in the Clear Creek
Complex 1,502 firefighters, 16 helicopters, and 27 engine trucks
were battling blazes. Among the firefighters were 600 Marines newly
trained to fight fires.
</P>
<P>
   Still, by midweek, fire officials were using the word
``cautious'' to describe their optimism. Firefighters, many of them
staying at ``spike'' camps as close to the fires as possible, did,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got plenty of rain, but it could easily pop up again
somewhere,'' said Jon T. Lee, 40, a member of an elite, highly
trained Type 1 ``hotshot'' team. ``I chase fires for a living, and
I don't think I'm done chasing them yet this season.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee said he expects to put in 1,000 hours of overtime this fire
season, earning an estimated $35,000 for six months of 75-hour
back-wrenching weeks. For him, as for many others risking their
safety to contain the flames, the fires offer an economic boost, as
well as a surge of adrenaline and a sense of satisfaction. Each
spring, before the start of fire season, lines form around the
block to join the crews, especially in cities and towns with few
other job opportunities, according to one fire official.
</P>
<P>
   Some locals have profited from the fires, too. Although they
lost out on tourists, local hotels and motels have been filled with
firefighters, the parking lots packed with the equipment trucks and
four-wheel-drive vehicles the crews brought with them. Stasiak said
anyone with heavy or logging equipment to rent or fire-fighting
supplies to sell has done nicely.
</P>
<P>
   But in a county with an unemployment rate that hovers around 8
percent, the fires have hurt more people than they have helped.
Stasiak, the economic development director, called tourism the top
employer in Lemhi County, employing more people than the hospital,
the US Bureau of Land Management, or a company that makes laminated
wood beams.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists spent $21.5 million in Lemhi County in 1997, the most
recent figures available from the commerce department. The tourism
payroll topped $13.4 million, and that's in a county where Stasiak
said a wage of $15 an hour is rare and many employees work for
minimum wage or slightly higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to let people to know that we're in business, we're
still here,'' he said. ``Nothing has changed other than some areas
have burned.''
</P>
<P>
   Signs pointing otherwise are everywhere, however, from the
``Thank you firefighters'' placards around town, to the radio
stations that offer regular updates on closed areas, to the mostly
deserted downtown movie theater.
</P>
<P>
   And it has been a rough summer for hotels without business from
the fire crews. Said Linda Anderson, an employee at the normally
sold-out Salmon River Lodge, where a double goes for $72 a night,
``Business has slowed down 100 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, no residents said they were planning to leave Salmon or
shut down their businesses just yet. Isolated as they are _ a 2
1/2-hour winding drive from Missoula _ locals said they are
accustomed to adversity, and the fires may prove to be just another
obstacle to overcome in exchange for living in an area where deer,
bear, otter, and longhorn sheep, among other wildlife, can be
spotted regularly and the tap water is so tasty that the mayor has
considered bottling it for sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're known to be survivors,'' Mayor Davis said. ``We live 150
miles from nowhere, as some would say. We depend on each other for
survival. And we'll survive this, even if don't know how right
now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-00 1350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000913.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2546 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-13 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENDER GAP IS ZAPPING BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Those footsteps making all the difference in the presidential
election this past month don't all sound alike.
</P>
<P>
   There's the click of high heels, the scrunch of sandals, the
clip-clop of flats, the clunk of steel-toed welder's boots, the
near-silent tread of soccer-mom sneakers and nurses' slip-ons and
the crepe-soled whisper of women who are on their feet on the job
eight hours straight, before they get home to chores there before
they slide on the old slippers.
</P>
<P>
   It's the movement of female votes that brought Al Gore from way
behind to marginally ahead. If the election were limited to white
men, George W. Bush could quit today and still win. White males
have voted predictably Republican in presidential elections for
three decades, in the South some years by 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   But yawning wide under the unsteady gait of the Texas governor
is Gender Gap. His year-long trail-ride campaign, with his
saddlebags laden with $100 million in contributions, runs the risk
of plunging over that looming precipice. He had the women's vote,
tentatively and tenuously, till mid-August. Now it is bleeding
away, like a river through a broken levee, and Bush seems unsure as
to how to repair the damage.
</P>
<P>
   It was women who made Bill Clinton in two elections, and women
whose coolness to Prince Albert threatened to deny Mr. &AMP; Mrs. Gore
the chance to move in over the store. So what happened over the
last month? Women moved. To Gore.
</P>
<P>
   That much is clear. The ``why?'' is a little more obscure. Savvy
Republican veterans like Alan Simpson, the former Wyoming senator
who spent 18 years in D.C., kept murmuring all along that women
don't like the GOP's lining up against abortion. Bush is for
exceptions in rare cases (rape, incest, saving the mother's life)
but the platform won't even go that far.
</P>
<P>
   Bush went to great and largely successful lengths to make his a
softer-kinder-cuddlier convention. Lots of happy female and
minority faces. But he's trying to undo the damage done since
1994's savage Newt Gingrich revolution.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP fought family leave, raising the minimum wage (more
women than men make the bare minimum), and the Democrats have
generally out-bid the GOP congressional leadership on education,
health care, and prescription drugs, the issue that looms like the
iceberg-that-sank-the-Titanic of this election.
</P>
<P>
   Was it The Smooch? Gore's bear-hug-and-passionate-kiss of Tipper
en route to the podium for his big convention speech still
resonates. ``No kiss?'' demanded Oprah Winfrey when Al ambled onto
her set. ``I was hoping for something.'' So was Al, and he got it,
when the talk-show diva, with her 22 million viewers, let Al purr
and flirt. Dubbaya goes on Oprah next week, but he starts from way
behind with the women's vote.
</P>
<P>
   How far behind? Say about 20 points worth, in the Zogby poll, or
18 points, in the ABC/Washington Post count. Gore's lead among
women varies from state to state. In the South and West, Bush does
better. But in pivotal electoral vote hotspots like Illinois, where
Gore has an overall 15-point lead in the Zogby tally, Bush leads
among men, but trails by 25 points among women.
</P>
<P>
   And marital status matters. The Voter.com Battleground poll has
Gore and Bush deadlocked nationally at 41-40, but had Gore ahead
among women by nine, and Bush up with men by 8. That survey charts
a marriage gap _ Bush ahead by nine with marrieds, Gore up by 14
among singles. The conventional wisdom is that mothers are more
angry at Bill Clinton for his Monica dalliance than are single
women, and that parents are more upset with the current president
than nonparents.
</P>
<P>
   Both campaigns will tailor their ads and schedules to the
battleground states _ those eight or nine running from New Jersey
to Illinois and down to Missouri. The Lieberman factor is
apparently helping Gore with women, as well as in Florida, where
Bush spent two days this week hoping to hold onto to a state he
thought was a sure thing in July.
</P>
<P>
   It's clear that Bush cannot win New York (trailing by 25 points
in the Marist poll) and Illinois seems to be slipping from
contention (Gore up by 15, Zogby.) It remains to be seen whether
Hillary Clinton's seesaw Senate race in New York will get a lift
from Gore's surge among women. Hillary is doing nowhere near as
well with her gender she _ and I _ thought she would.
</P>
<P>
   That could still change. If it does, she's in.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
David Nyhan's e-mail address is nyhan(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
