<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2547 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-13 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD AND MADISON AVE. NEED TO BE REINED IN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; This is a good week to see how deep our children stand in
commercialism's grand canyon. Turn to the west and they are staring
at Hollywood's soaring walls of media violence. Turn to the east
and there is the sheer face of Madison Avenue's cold-blooded
manipulation of children's minds.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Federal Trade Commission released a report that
found that the movies, music, and video-game industries
aggressively market adult-rated wares to underage children. The FTC
found that 80 percent of R-rated movies, 70 percent of ``mature''
video games and all 55 music recordings with labels for
``explicit'' content were marketed to children under 17.
</P>
<P>
   FTC Chairman Robert Pitofsky said, ``They knew what they were
doing.'' The FTC received much of its information from industry
documents. Children are exposed to a barrage of shootings,
expletives, sexuality, and references to rape and mutilation
through TV commercials and movie theatre trailers that industry
executives know will be seen by elementary school viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Some PG-13 films are advertised during the Saturday morning
cartoons. Other PG-13 and some R-rated movies exploit the vast
youth audience for football, wrestling, and music videos shows.
Many PG-13 action movies reach young children with action toys.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC report was rare for being a big government project that
produced outrage across a wide political spectrum. Robert Knight,
senior director of cultural studies at the conservative Family
Research Council said, ``The tobacco industry was forced to
discontinue its use of `Joe Camel.' Well, Hollywood has a `Joe
Camel' problem of its own.'' First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, a
Democratic candidate for the US Senate, said, ``I am calling on the
industry to immediately stop marketing adult and violent
entertainment to children.''
</P>
<P>
   Outraged politicians should reserve some anger for other
manipulators as well. Wednesday and Thursday in New York,
advertising executives are brazenly patting themselves on the back
for getting children hooked onto junk food and video games,
celebrating the Golden Marble Awards for ads aimed at children.
</P>
<P>
   Many winners of the last two years add up to a chamber of
horrors in a nation facing an epidemic of child obesity: Hostess
pastries, Oreo cookies, Pepsi, McDonald's, Burger King, Post and
Kellogg's cereals, and Nintendo. The awards are not only ads
themselves but also for campaigns that tie products into TV
networks and movies that appeal to young children such as
Nickelodeon, Fox, Men in Black and Star Wars.
</P>
<P>
   As if they are playing a joke on the rest of the world, the
Golden Marble Awards reserve one puny category for public service.
After rewarding ad execs for turning nutritional gutters into gold
mines, the Golden Marbles have the audacity to applaud a handful
finalists whose ads fight obesity, drugs, and tell children to
question what they see on television.
</P>
<P>
   The absurd assault on children has convinced several dozen child
psychologists and critics of media manipulation from around the
nation to gather Thursday for a protest outside the Golden Marbles
at the New York Grand Hyatt. The protest is being organized by
Susan Linn, a Harvard Medical School psychologist and assistant
director of the media center at the Judge Baker Children's Center
at Children's Hospital, Diane Levin, Wheelock College education
professor who linked Power Rangers to violent playground behavior,
and Alvin Poussaint, a psychiatrist, associate dean at Harvard
Medical School, and consultant to ``The ``Cosby Show.''
</P>
<P>
   The organizers want the government to fund studies on the effect
of child marketing. ``It is appalling to us that creativity is
being rewarded in the service of maipulating children for profit,''
Linn said. ``We hope this is the beginning of a cohesive national
movement to challenge this.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a golden opportunity to protest these galling golden
marbles. When both right wingers and liberals compare violent
advertising to Joe Camel, that is a good day. The FTC report made
both Al Gore and George W. Bush denounce the marketing of violence
to children. That is a good day.
</P>
<P>
   We may be reaching a great day of critical mass of people who
are ready to rescue our children. Our kids face canyon walls too
high and too steep to avoid the deluge of commercial trash
collecting at whitewater speed at the bottom. Unless we pull our
kids away from the TV, or force Hollywood and Madison Avenue to
pull ads away from our children, they will be swept away.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Derrick Z. Jackson's e-mail address is jackson(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
