<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2553 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-GOODBYE-SLIP-HNS &LR;      09-13 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODBYE-SLIP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     KISS THE SLIP GOODBYE, AND NOT A MOMENT TOO SOON 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MELISSA FLETCHER STOELTJE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Any woman who has ever suffered through an outdoor
wedding reception during the summer will understand. The slip had
to die.
</P>
<P>
   A stake had to be driven through its clingy tricot-and-lace
heart. It had to be sent slinking off to that great lingerie
graveyard in the sky, home to the girdle, corset, garter, underwire
bra and all the other devious inventions that have caused so much
female misery.
</P>
<P>
   First pantyhose died a gasping death, as American women took a
clue from their more confident European sisters and sandal-wearing
celebrities and bared their legs, throwing caution and even skin
tones to the wind.
</P>
<P>
   Now the same fate has apparently befallen the humble slip, once
a de rigueur prop in the quest for feminine propriety and proper
dressing. Slips have slipped out of sight. They've disappeared.
Been shucked. In an age of sheer indulgence, they've gone pppffft.
</P>
<P>
   ``The slip is not only dead, we've already held the funeral,''
said Bernice Cantile, founder of the Menger Smart Shop, a bastion
of stylish dressing in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Cantile, who has worn her share of slips through the decades,
said these days even her ``larger sized'' customers _ women who
traditionally insisted on slips for modesty's sake _ have eschewed
the lacy, frilly, Aunt Bea-ish things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most clothes today are lined, so you don't need slips,'' she
said. ``They just add another layer and that's too bulky'' for
today's sleek designs.
</P>
<P>
   As for clothes you can see through _ well, that's sort of the
point, say fashion industry types.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dresses these days made of sheer material usually come with a
slip-dress underneath, or women buy a little slip-dress of nude or
black to go underneath,'' said Kelly Warren, spokeswoman for Saks
Fifth Avenue. ``It's supposed to show.''
</P>
<P>
   Slip dress, she said. Not slip. As slips have evolved from items
used to hide things _ panty lines, bra seams, that embarrassing gap
between your legs when you stand in front of a window _ they've
become chic, Warren said. Sexy. This is not your mother's
Oldsmobile _ those big, boxy, white, industrial-strength numbers
that were forever peeking out from under hemlines, the lingerie
equivalent of toilet paper stuck to your shoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we even have those hanging on the floor,''
Warren said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traditional slip is basically gone,'' said Liz Smith,
spokeswoman for Wacoal America, licensed for Donna Karan Intimates.
</P>
<P>
   Women are ``freer'' with their bodies these days, she said.
Well, um, sort of. Slip-liberation arrived, Smith said, with the
advent of ``shape wear'' _ lighter, smoother, less-sadistic
versions of yesterday's girdle (but still a girdle) that renders
the nylon go-between redundant.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't need that extra garment between the garments,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, most women of baby-boom vintage and older recall a time
when slip-wearing was simply something you had to do, especially
for church and other dressy affairs. It was usually a complicated
contraption involving lace at bottom and top and silky straps with
metal fasteners. Wearing one was like being encased in a frilly
sausage tube.
</P>
<P>
   But not to wear a slip was to hint at a certain female moral
laxity, an essential hussiness. ``You're not wearing a slip with
that?'' your mother would ask, her eyes wide.
</P>
<P>
   It was a classic female double bind: Not wearing a slip was
tacky, but letting your slip show was ultra-tacky.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, many women have rebelled, becoming defiant in
their non-slip-wearing-ways. It's not fashion that prompts them to
push their half-slips to the backs of their lingerie drawers,
little satin puddles of dejection. It's comfort.
</P>
<P>
   Stalwart slip-wearers remain, however, said Beverly Guyer,
director of marketing for Vanity Fair. In fact, studies show that
the top three sellers of ``daywear'' (slips, camisoles and the
like) at department stores nationwide continue to be half-slips and
slips. It's a regional thing: Slip sales are highest in the South,
said Kathy Reynolds, vice president and general manager of Vanity
Fair Brand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's related to (the region's) more conservative
nature,'' she said. ``Women in the South are more into dressing up
than dressing down, more apt to dress up for church on Sunday.
There's also a modesty issue related to the fact that (Southern
women) wear a lot of white and light colors.''
</P>
<P>
   Slip-buying may be a class thing as well: In fancy boutiques,
clothes come expensively lined; by the time you've hit Wal-Mart,
slips become more of a necessity.
</P>
<P>
   Those who rejoice in the demise of the slip shouldn't cheer too
loudly, Smith said. Slips in the form of lacy camisoles meant to
show through suits will be all the rage this fall. So will vintage
slips, Guyer said (that's right, your mother's Oldsmobile). Also
primed to rise from the grave (cue the theme song from ``Psycho'')
are pantyhose, particularly colored and patterned varieties.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Melissa Fletcher Stoeltje's e-mail address is
mstoeltje(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
