<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROADWAY BECKONS DR. LAURA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Diane White's column will now move on Mondays and
Wednesdays.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Gray's best-selling book ``Men Are from Mars, Women Are
from Venus'' is being turned into a musical. Why haven't more
self-help books been given the musical treatment?
</P>
<P>
   The musical theater could do worse than seek inspiration in the
vast literature of self-improvement. Actually, it does do worse.
Even now a musical extravaganza inspired by Barry Manilow's song
``Copacabana'' is warming up for a Boston debut. Need I say more?
</P>
<P>
   ``Men Are from Mars, Women Are from Venus'' seems almost made
for the stage, as do so many other self-help titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Co-Dependent No More.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Art of Living Single.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cinderella Complex.''
</P>
<P>
   `The Idiot's Guide to Amazing Sex.''
</P>
<P>
   That last title is perfect for the all-singing, all-dancing
treatment. I can almost hear the overture.
</P>
<P>
   But there's one self-help book that practically begs for musical
treatment: ``Ten Stupid Things Women Do to Mess Up Their Lives,''
by America's favorite moral taskmaster, Dr. Laura Schlessinger.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Laura has conquered radio, print, and television. Broadway
beckons. We've had enough ``feel-good'' musicals. It's time for a
``feel good or else'' musical.
</P>
<P>
   One problem: the title of the book is a little long. Maybe it
could be shortened to ``Ten Stupid Things.'' Or just ``Stupid
Things.'' (``These Stupid Things Remind Me of You''?)
</P>
<P>
   Since Dr. Laura is probably too busy to star in the production,
Kathie Lee Gifford might consider the role. She's been looking for
a juicy Broadway part.
</P>
<P>
   I see it as essentially a one-woman show (what else?), with a
back-up chorus. In the first act, chorus members could wear masks
and assume various identities _ single mothers, gays and lesbians,
tabloid reporters. As Dr. Laura/Kathie Lee belts out one of the
many show-stopping numbers _ ``Do as I Say (Not as I Do),'' ``You
Can't Have it All (Unless You're Me),'' ``I'm My Kid's Mom (And I'm
Your Mom Too, So Shut Up And Listen)'' _ the chorus would sing its
dissent, antiphonally. The possibilities for dramatic tension are
practically limitless, although in the end, Dr. Laura/Kathie Lee
would, as always, drown out the other voices.
</P>
<P>
   I haven't worked out all the details yet, but by the third act
Dr. Laura/Kathie Lee would have sung and danced her way through all
of ``The Ten Stupid Things Women Do to Mess Up Their Lives'' _
Stupid Devotion, Stupid Passion, Stupid Attachment, etc. The show
could end with her standing on stage in a single spotlight, taking
calls from the audience and giving advice, which would give people
the opportunity to actually talk on their cell phones in the
theater, instead just letting them ring during the show.
</P>
<P>
   Looking through my copy of ``The Ten Stupid Things Women Do to
Mess Up Their Lives,'' I see potential songs in the subtitles on
almost every page.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Sex Too Soon Can Do To You.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Living In Is Giving In.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dreams Can Be Dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I Have the Right to Leave?''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I Still Really Love Him.'' How does it go? ``I know he's a
bore/but I love him/ He's rotten to the core/but I love him. . .''
I can almost hear Kathie Lee putting her personal stamp on that
one.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Diane White is a Boston Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-00 1354EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
