<DOCNO> NYT20000913.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2556 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-FTC-COMMENT-BOS &LR;      09-13 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FTC-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE THRILL IS GONE: MARKETING VIOLENCE CALLS FOR ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   These are complicated times for rock 'n' roll moms.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Federal Trade Commission released a report that
finds that the music, film, and videogame industries aggressively
market violent, adult-oriented entertainment to underage youths.
This being an election year, the candidates have already come out
swinging. Vice President Al Gore threatened, if elected, to
initiate legislation if Hollywood can't clean up it's act _ a
gesture Governor George W. Bush's campaign has called hypocritical,
coming from the beneficiary of Hollywood's deep, largely Democratic
pockets. One can only imagine to what lengths Bush might go to
preserve family values.
</P>
<P>
   Even in a non-election year, the area spanning free speech and
an increasingly violence-drenched entertainment culture is gray. As
a music lover, an arts writer, and a supporter of freedom of
expression, I cringe at the idea of government intervention _ even
under the relatively innocent auspices of regulating advertising.
Once Washington establishes a controlling hand in the marketing of
art, it's a frighteningly short distance to content.
</P>
<P>
   As a mother, I cringe at the loss of innocence I observe in my
children on what seems to be a daily basis. They are enthralled
with image and sound, and happily seduced by every arm of the
entertainment industry. I have a 7-year-old who lisps menacing
dialogue from R-rated movie trailers he sees on TV. My 9-year-old
daughter chants lyrics to Eminem songs. The resident 12-year-old
argues with the desperate logic of an entertainment junkie that he
is mature enough to distinguish between fantasy and reality.
</P>
<P>
   Fates willing, that's true. There is, in fact, no hard evidence
that indicates exposure to violent media leads to acts of violence.
For every troubled teenager who guns down his schoolmates, there
are tens of thousands who listened to the same hard-core CDs,
played the same violence-strewn video games, and conned their
parents into taking them to see ``The Matrix'' _ and never hurt a
fly.
</P>
<P>
   The risks are subtler than that, and scarier, too. I'm not
worried that my children will grow into aggressive adults, or that
they'll imitate the behavior they see on a screen. Rather it's the
idea of experiencing violence as something interesting and
glamorous, exciting and entertaining, that's most distressing. It's
the prospect of a generation that's desensitized to suffering, and
proportionally titillated by the thrill of the kill.
</P>
<P>
   And that leads to the issue at hand: how to hold accountable an
entertainment industry that would prefer to collect revenues than
caretake the emotional and ethical development of children. The
FTC's study, conducted over 15 months, found that of the 44 R-rated
movies they looked at, 35 were systematically targeted at young
teens. Of 118 video games carrying an M rating (for 17 and over) 83
targeted children under 17, and all of the 55 music recordings with
explicit-content labels were intentionally marketed to young teens.
</P>
<P>
   All three major arms of the entertainment machine, the study
found, are intentionally circumventing their own voluntary labeling
systems with ad campaigns for adult product during teen-frequented
TV shows, in teen-targeted magazines, and on popular youth-oriented
Internet sites. It's arguably immoral and possibly actionable. It's
undeniably sleazy.
</P>
<P>
   But one could also argue that parents ultimately must shoulder
responsibility for monitoring their children's consumption That,
however, would involve two tasks that have become increasingly
uncommon as guilt-riddled, two-working-parent households become the
norm: tracking kids closely, and saying no.
</P>
<P>
   Censorship is not a solution The FTC isn't pressing for
legislation, but rather an expansion of voluntary codes prohibiting
promotion of adult product to underage kids that wouldn't trigger
First Amendment concerns. If the corporate engine that drives the
entertainment industry has even a vague grasp of the importance of
unfettered artistic expression _ never mind taking care of kids _
they'll respond quickly, not only with age-appropriate advertising
but with more informative ratings and content guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   And then it's up to me. To wake up at 7 after spending half the
night in a rock club, make bag lunches, go to work, and stumble
home bleary-eyed but with the will to do what's right, not what's
easy. I want my children to hear and see everything. They should
know that art doesn't have boundaries, and that self-expression
includes the dark, dank parts too. But they need the strength to
process it that comes with age and experience. And that should be
everyone's concern.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
