<SLUG> BC-FASHION-SNEAKERS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 SKULKING BACK INTO POPULARITY, SNEAKERS ARE VOGUE AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When British fashion designer Slinky Vagabond, whose lines are
inspired by such sports as fencing, sends male models dressed for
spring down the runway in New York Saturday, they'll be wearing
Reeboks. Funky ones. Made of coated denim or bronze, gold and
silver fabric, the sneakers sport an early-'80s running shoe
silhouette, including side stripes and rubber from the sole
stretched up to the tip of the toe.
</P>
<P>
   But don't go looking for the Slinky sneakers at City Sports. Try
Louis, Boston. Or Harrod's. These sneakers, after all, are more of
a ``look'' than an athletic shoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our fastest-growing segment of the business,'' said
Linda Beane, marketing director for the Canton, Mass. company's
Reebok Classic line, which creates ``lifestyle'' sneakers, as
opposed to the footwear favored by Olympic athletes. ``For 2001 and
2002, it's even bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   Shunned since the early '90s as unfashionable, sneakers have
become trendy again as Europeans crave brightly colored Pumas,
Adidas, and New Balance. Meanwhile, stateside, vintage sneakers _
especially Nikes _ have quietly developed a cult following.
</P>
<P>
   Reebok is zeroing in on the trend by launching about 50 new
sneakers this year, none designed with athletics in mind, though
the technology is built in just in case a sprint is in order. These
sneakers, the company declares proudly, are about fashion _ not
track and field.
</P>
<P>
   So, any old tennies won't do. Your sneakers should either look
like the ones you wore in sixth grade or seem suitable for a walk
in space.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the advent of the casual workplace . . . people want to
be comfortable and they want to look good being comfortable,''
Beane said. ``The old white sneakers cruising around town don't
work anymore for people who want to look urban.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Prada Sport's sneaker gets credit for truly pushing
such footwear into mainstream fashion, other design houses,
including DKNY, were early comers to the game, upping the sneaker
cache quotient instantly.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's OK to wear Skechers with a skirt. But prices _ like
styles _ vary widely.
</P>
<P>
   Prada Sport's silver and blue sneaker retails for $250, making
it among the most expensive. And Jil Sander and Hermes varieties
have never been cheap.
</P>
<P>
   DKNY's high-tech-looking sneakers _ some even have computer guts
or a ``motherboard'' motif _ are in the $95 range. Others in that
line, including no-lace suede slip-ons called ``Sphinx,'' cost
about $70.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are knockoffs. Steve Madden's lavender sneaker,
called ``Faster,'' is inspired by '70s models and not for the faint
of heart. Price: $49. Candie's makes a black and pink style for
$45. Freeport even makes a sneaker mule (is that an oxymoron?) for
$48.
</P>
<P>
   The most affordable hot shoe around may be Nike Air Rifts, which
retail for $85. Designed for Kenyan runners who are accustomed to
running barefoot, this split-toe sneaker looks like it was made for
an ostrich. It even comes with a split-toe sock.
</P>
<P>
   NikeTown on Newbury Street reports that it has trouble keeping
the shoe in stock. Meanwhile, sales clerks say shipment dates are
closely held secrets, as is the color of the next Air Rift. (Some
die-hards have begun collecting the shoe in all available colors.)
</P>
<P>
   Nike trotted out the Air Rift about five years ago, and recently
brought back the sneaker on a limited basis in New York, Los
Angeles, and a few other markets, including Boston. Certain colors
are sold only in certain cities, with such collectible exclusivity
contributing to the craze. (Robin's-egg blue is available here.)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Keds are making sneakers that look more like shoes.
</P>
<P>
   And Cole Haan has launched a line of sleek shoes that operate
more like sneakers, complete with Nike Air technology (that visible
little air bubble) built into the sole. Nike owns Cole Haan.
</P>
<P>
   Prada now makes a golf shoe that is intended for the fairway as
well as the runway. Gucci recently unveiled a biking-inspired shoe
(or was it a sneaker?). And this fall, bowling shoes are as popular
as bowling bags as a must-have accessory.
</P>
<P>
   All this amounts to the fact that the line between the two types
of footwear for men and women has become blurred.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are shoes _ again, shoes that almost look like
sneakers _ made by Icon that are ergonomically engineered with
flexible rubber soles, sporting Tide or Campbell's Tomato soup
logos or art, designed by individual painters, on the soft leather
uppers.
</P>
<P>
   Available locally at Saks Fifth Avenue, Tess, and Cuoio, Icons
are selling steadily at $260 _ or $500 for signed and numbered
versions.
</P>
<P>
   At those rates, tread lightly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
