<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-USSOCCER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US GOAL IS A SPOT IN SYDNEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ It's rather pleasant down in Canberra. There's the
afternoon tea and toast at the Parkroyal Hotel, a video arcade
featuring World Cup '98 in the lounge, and a gigantic shopping mall
across the street. And come Friday night, the US men's soccer team
can watch the Olympic opening ceremonies on TV, just like their
families back home.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the Americans make history here by surviving the
preliminary round, a week in Australia's capital is as close to the
heart of the Games as they're going to get.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not as much grandeur here as there is in Sydney,''
reports defender Jeff Agoos, whose mates take on the Czech Republic
in their opener Wednesday night in Canberra. ``We want to move on
and get the full Olympic experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless the Yanks make the final, which the country's betting
shops consider extremely unlikely, the closest they'll come to the
host city is the airport, which they passed through on their way
from San Diego to Canberra. Though the team could have marched in
the ceremonies, it would have meant standing for six hours in the
evening chill the day before its second match against Cameroon,
which is likely to decide whether the US stays or goes.
</P>
<P>
   In 11 appearances since 1924, the Americans have been long gone
before the medal round. They're 4-12-6 all-time and were 1-1-1 on
home soil four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   This time, though, with a roster filled with MLS and overseas
pros and a favorable draw with Kuwait for a finale, they've got
more than a passing chance to advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've got as good a chance as anyone in our group,''
says midfielder Peter Vagenas. `I mean, that's why we start off
with zero points. But if we bring our best and the others bring
their best, I think we'll get out of our group.''
</P>
<P>
   The US women, who won the gold medal in Atlanta and last year's
World Cup, will be in Sydney for sure. After their opener against
nemesis Norway in Melbourne Thursday afternoon, they'll fly up to
march in the ceremonies. But the only way they'll be back here is
if they survive a brutal group that also includes the Chinese, the
Olympic and World Cup finalists.
</P>
<P>
   If the Americans can handle the Norwegians, who've beaten them
three times this year, they'll need only defeat Nigeria to advance.
If they can't, they'll immediately be in a win-or-die fix.
</P>
<P>
   The US males are used to that. They lost to Italy in their 1992
opener and to Argentina last time. And their opener against the
burly Czechs figures to be their toughest match.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have our hands full,'' concedes coach Clive Charles,
who'll have veteran Brad Friedel in goal. ``The Czechs are big,
strong, and very direct. They go straight to goal. They not only
have talent, they have size, too.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Yanks can manage even a draw against the Czechs, they'll
have a good chance to make it to the quarterfinals against Brazil
up in sunny Brisbane on the Gold Coast. Odds are their quest would
end there, without their ever seeing Stadium Australia.
</P>
<P>
   That's no novelty for the Americans, though. Even as hosts last
time, they never got any closer to Atlanta than Birmingham, Ala.
``At a tournament of this size, you know you can't have everyone at
one venue,'' says Agoos. `We knew we'd be in satellite cities.''
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, Agoos and his playmates get to meet the
Kuwaitis in Melbourne, where the training complex in the industrial
suburbs is right next to an oil refinery with a smokestack that
burns with a huge flame. It's supposed to look a bit like the
Olympic cauldron.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
