<HEADER>
A2562 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-BULLS-RUN0914-COX     09-13 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BULLS-RUN0914-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Will Texas' Running of the Bulls rival Pamplona's?
 &HT;    By Pamela LeBlanc
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas - The way Derik Strelsky sees it, Pamplona's got
nothing on Jarrell, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   So when Oct. 14 rolls around, and 20 crossbred bulls come
barrelling down a 200-yard chute on the heels of however many
people are, well, crazy enough to climb in there with them,
Strelsky will be watching with glee as the dust rises around him.
</P>
<P>
   Music _ maybe Bruce Springsteen's ``Born to Run,'' or something
with Spanish flair _ will be blaring in the background, and
hundreds of people will be crowded along the fence, watching to see
what happens when you mix 2,000-pound Texas rodeo bulls with a
bunch of adrenalin junkies.
</P>
<P>
   Strelsky, a former rodeo clown and bullfighter, is modeling his
Running of the Bulls after the alcohol-soaked, centuries-old melee
in Pamplona, Spain, made famous in Ernest Hemingway's novel ``The
Sun Also Rises.'' But the Jarrell version, he says, will have Texas
style _ it will unfold on the baked dirt of a Williamson County
ranch under the blistering Texas sun instead of the cobblestone
streets of a quaint Spanish town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it'll be invigorating. I think the hair will be
standing up on the back of their necks. I think it'll be very
exciting for the participants,'' Strelsky said.
</P>
<P>
   If you think Texas is a strange place to stage a Running of the
Bulls, you're not alone. But Strelsky, who's spending about $20,000
to put it on, says just as soon as people tell him he's nuts for
planning it, they want to know how they can sign up. So far, more
than 75 people have registered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be disappointed, I'll cry if there's not 5,000 people
there,'' Strelsky said. ``I hope there's not enough places for
people to stand, I hope we don't have enough Port-a-Potties.''
</P>
<P>
   The running will take place at Gibbs Ranch near Jarrell, with
participants divided into groups of 50 or so. Twenty bulls will be
set free behind each batch of runners, who will dash down a
fenced-in alley toward an arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way I think they'll hurt anybody is if somebody falls
down and gets accidently stepped on,'' said stock contractor Wayne
Gibbs, who owns the ranch and the burly animals _ mixes of Watusi,
Longhorn and Brahman. ``They're not like the Mexican fighting bulls
that stay mad at the world all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, all sorts _ from lawyers and bankers to soldiers and
doctors _ have taken the bait. A bus load of tourists is scheduled
to drive down from Dallas, and companies are considering forming
teams to participate, Strelsky said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's just a bunch of thrill seekers _ people that want
to do something that nobody else does,'' Strelsky said. But not
him. ``Oh lord no. I'm too fat and old,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Caballero, a field marketing manager from Fort Worth who
works at Taco Bell's corporate offices in Dallas, has already
registered. ``Who knows, it might be fun,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And Caballero knows what he's getting into. He traveled to
Pamplona in July for the Fiestas de San Fermin, and survived the
running of the bulls there. He expects a calmer Texas version
because rodeo bulls are less aggressive than Spanish fighting
bulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not that macho. It's really scary,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Strelsky says he's staging the event as a way to draw attention
to the Pro Rodeo Cowboys Association sport of bullfighting, which
pits human against bovine in a 70-second one-on-one grudge match.
Unlike Spanish bullfighting, the idea is not to kill the bull, or
to swish a red cape at it, but to get as close to it as possible
without getting hooked or trampled. A bullfighting competition will
immediately follow the Running of the Bulls in Jarrell.
</P>
<P>
   Strelsky, who grew up in Rockdale and now lives in Temple, broke
ribs, fingers and his nose during his own rodeo career. ``It feels
like a baseball bat if they hit correctly,'' he said. ``But most of
the time they reach out to grab you and throw you up in the air and
you don't even feel that.''
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen people have died in the Pamplona running in the last
75 years. But Strelsky says his event will be safer _ bulls are
less likely to slip on dirt than cobblestones, and the Jarrell
event will cover just 200 yards instead of half a mile. Alcohol
will be sold on the premises, but participants will not be allowed
to drink until after they've run with the bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Ambulances will be on hand just in case. Participants also will
be required to sign a two-page waiver.
</P>
<P>
   The running won't be the first to take place outside of
Pamplona. Twice before, a similar event has taken place in
Mesquite, Nev. But the event has been postponed because of lagging
attendance.
</P>
<P>
   If the response is good in Jarrell, Strelsky says he'll plan
similar events in San Antonio, Dallas and Houston.
</P>
<P>
   A portion of proceeds will benefit the Peaceable Kingdom Retreat
for Children near Salado, Texas, a 125-acre retreat on the Lampasas
River for children with chronic illnesses. Strelsky says he wants
to donate at least $10,000, but that will depend on how much money
he raises.
</P>
<P>
   Strelsky says he has fielded some calls from animal rights
activists who don't want him to hold the event. But Strelsky says
the animals are treated better than most cattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``These bulls are probably some of the best kept, well-cared for
animals in the world,'' he said. ``If they didn't earn their keep,
they'd probably be on somebody's dinner table.''
</P>
<P>
   Williamson County Sheriff's Department animal control officers
and deputies will be on hand, spokeswoman Tracy Karol said.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Email: pleblanc(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
