u s BC-CAR-NHIS-BOS &LR;      09-13 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NHIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NHIS: REDUCED SPEED AHEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Faced with questions about the deaths of drivers Adam Petty and
Kenny Irwin, who were killed in similar accidents eight weeks apart
at New Hampshire International Speedway this year, NASCAR officials
announced Saturday they will attempt to curb speeds at the mile
oval in Loudon, N.H., by mandating the use of 1-inch carburetor
restrictor plates for the Winston Cup and Busch North Series events
this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Helton, NASCAR's senior vice president and chief operating
officer, said in a phone interview Tuesday from Daytona Beach,
Fla., that officials explored various measures aimed at improving
safety conditions at NHIS, including ``soft-wall'' technology last
week at the track.
</P>
<P>
   However, they were unable to come up with viable alternatives
that could be implemented in time for Sunday's Dura Lube 300
Sponsored by Kmart.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty clear to us that the track has not changed in the
time that we've been there, but what has changed is that the cars
are going faster,'' Helton said. ``Be that as it may, we've not
been able to answer enough questions about other options as to what
to do, but we can address the speed of the cars by using restrictor
plates, and we have experience with those, and we know how to react
to a restrictor plate in a short period of time, and that's why we
chose to do that for this weekend at New Hampshire.''
</P>
<P>
   Petty, the 19-year-old grandson of NASCAR legend Richard Petty
and son of Winston Cup driver Kyle Petty, was killed May 12 when
his car slammed into the wall in Turn 3.
</P>
<P>
   Eight weeks later, in the same spot, Irwin, 31, was killed when
his car hit the wall, rolled onto the driver's side, and skidded
along the banking for several hundred feet before rolling over onto
its roof.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is, in part, a search for an answer,'' Helton said.
``I think it's also, in part, a search for `what else can we do?'
when we can't explain why an accident like Kenny's and Adam's
occurs. What else can we do to try and (prevent) it, because
there's no universal fix that's going to make every one of these
laps, at every racetrack we go to, inescapable of incidents.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time of Irwin's death, several drivers insisted that
NASCAR should take a close look at the track, saying two fatalities
in such a short period at the same track couldn't be coincidental.
Some drivers even suggested implementing a foam-wall covering in
Turn 3, similar to those used as buffers in tire-wall barriers at
the road course in Watkins Glen, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Helton said NASCAR conducted a ``soft-wall'' impact test at NHIS
last week under simulated race conditions. This came a week after
the race at Darlington, S.C., where drivers hinted of a boycott at
NHIS if no safety improvements were made. But Helton said NASCAR
had scheduled the NHIS test well before the grumblings at
Darlington.
</P>
<P>
   So what did the tests show?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what we found was that there were too many concerns
and unanswered questions as to what reaction the material will
create,'' Helton said. ``So we've not been able to answer
sufficiently the questions of how do you attach the material and
what happens when a car hits the material and what effect the
reaction of that material has on the rest of the race cars, on the
racetrack, as well as the spectators and other elements.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we'll keep looking at that and we'll keep looking at other
possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   As Helton pointed out, the qualifying speeds of Winston Cup cars
at NHIS have risen steadily since 1993, when Mark Martin won the
pole with a lap of 126.871 miles per hour, to this past July, when
Rusty Wallace blistered the track with a record-setting lap of
132.089 m.p.h. Has the increasing sophistication and speed of the
cars made them too fast for the track at NHIS?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so,'' Helton said. ``The more significant area
where NASCAR polices the sport and makes decisions is on the
equipment, the race car itself. I think when it comes to a
racetrack being able to handle Winston Cup events, or even a Busch
Grand National event for that matter, it's up to the physical plant
to stay in tune with the racing surface and with the economic
ability to participate.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the promoter, economically, can keep his facility
in good shape and host the fans that attend and move them in and
out and afford the economics of the prize money and those different
components, those are the big issues. I think when NASCAR finds
something at a racetrack that's changed, and changed for the bad,
then NASCAR works with the promoter to fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   But, as Helton said in July, NASCAR has not found anything to
suggest a problem with the track at NHIS.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still maintain even today, here in September, that the track
has not changed,'' he said. ``There's nothing about that racetrack
that's different today than it was 10 years ago when we first
started racing there. I think relative to the conversation about
the two accidents, it's a positive for the track. I think it means
that nothing the track has done has led to those accidents
happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``So then it becomes a function of what led to those accidents
happening, and short of just taking a position that everybody
understands auto racing is inherently a dangerous sport, I think
the uniqueness of two incidents that have a great deal of
similarity has heightened the concern and the questioning of `Hey,
what's going on here?' ''
</P>
<P>
   And that's what is puzzling everyone about NHIS.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-00 1359EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
