<DOCNO> NYT20000913.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2565 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-     09-13 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS TRAINERS HELP WRAP UP COMEBACK WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three times Al Groh stopped to say thank you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without you, we wouldn't have won this game,'' he said. ``The
job you did for us was big.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the scene, in a near-empty locker room, more than an
hour after the New York Jets' dramatic come-from-behind victory
over the Patriots Monday night in Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But Groh wasn't talking to any of his players. Or his coaches.
They had left long before this. All that remained were used strips
of tape, soiled uniforms, equipment managers scurrying around
packing up _ and the training staff.
</P>
<P>
   In the mind of Groh, the first-year Jets head coach, the
trainers' contributions were just as important as those of on-field
heroes Vinny Testaverde, Wayne Chrebet, Bryan Cox, and Mo Lewis on
the memorable night.
</P>
<P>
   Chrebet, despite playing with a calf injury, came up large in
the fourth quarter with a series of exceptional catches, two for
touchdowns, that chilled a tremendous performance by the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we got to the stadium tonight, Chrebet wasn't playing,''
said Groh. ``When I saw him in the hotel (Sunday) night, I figured
no way. He could barely walk. His leg was all taped and wrapped in
ice. The kid was in pain. In my mind, I wasn't counting on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``But these trainers stayed with him all day for two days. He
had more treatment than anyone in an intensive care unit. It was
round-the-clock. They did everything they could do to get him back
on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw him in warmups, I thought what I was seeing was
exceptional on the part of our staff, and Wayne.''
</P>
<P>
   In a leisurely practice session Saturday, without pads or
contact, Chrebet, the Jets' best receiver and Testaverde's favorite
target, got hurt without getting hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a freak thing,'' said Groh. ``He jumped to catch a
pass, and when he came down, he stumbled and pulled something in
his calf. It was bad. He had a hard time walking on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Chrebet was in the lineup, but in the first 50 minutes of the
game, he was almost invisible. Whether it was the injury, or a
stifling Patriot defense, it just wasn't happening for the New York
offense.
</P>
<P>
   After an impressive, 12-play, 74-yard touchdown drive late in
the first quarter that gave New York a 7-3 lead, the Jets' offense
disappeared. Over the next 37 minutes, the Jets crossed midfield
once. For one play. For 10 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a combination of things,'' said Testaverde, who went
from awful to sensational in the final 10 minutes of the game.
``Their defense is very good. They have good players. They are very
quick and play their schemes well. But it was just as much our
fault as anything they were doing. We made a lot of mistakes, both
mental and physical. All of us did. And that isn't like us. We
usually don't play that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the fourth period, we changed what we were doing. We went
to the `empty nest' (no runners behind the quarterback) to spread
them out and force them to cover our wideouts more man to man. For
three periods, we wanted to look for the running back against their
linebacker matchups. It wasn't working. In the fourth period, we
went back to the wideouts, getting the ball to them.''
</P>
<P>
   This changed the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The frustratng part is that we made Vinny look so bad for
three quarters, and then they made all of the big plays in the
final 10 minutes to win the game,'' said Drew Bledsoe. ``Vinny's a
top quarterback, and when your defense can throw a guy like that
off his game, the way ours did, we should win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should have put the game out of reach before that, with all
of the chances we had. But give Vinny and those receivers credit.
They made some fantastic plays to beat us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until that fourth period, I felt sure we were going to win. We
had them. We had the crowd out of the game. The great feeling about
playing on the road in the NFL is to hear the silence in the
stadium when you have the lead and have the game under control. We
just let this game get away. It was a game we should have won.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Will McDonough is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail at
mcdonough(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
