<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2566 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-OLY-SYDNEY-ART-BOS &LR;      09-13 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SYDNEY-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 SYDNEY CAN FEEL THE TORCH'S HEAT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ It was the ``flyme'' that did it. The Olympics were
still a rumor until the runners bearing the fiery boomerang torch
hit town Monday. It was then that Sydneysiders who'd dreamed about,
dreaded, or shrugged off this five-ringed global circus finally
realized that showtime was at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``IT'S HERE,'' the Daily Telegraph proclaimed on its front page,
showing faces cheering as the flame went past. And on Friday
evening, one of Australia's own _ Dawn Fraser? Mel Gibson?
Crocodile Dundee? _ will use it to ignite the cauldron inside
Stadium Australia and the Games of the XXVIIth Olympiad will begin
in this cosmopolitan oceanside city.
</P>
<P>
   It's been 44 years since the Olympics have been held in what the
natives call Oz, and they have changed utterly. Only 3,000 athletes
from 72 countries competed in 150 events in Melbourne in 1956. This
time, the numbers are 10,000, 199, and 300. The athletes' village
is so huge that it will be a separate suburb (Newington) after the
Games.
</P>
<P>
   There was jubilation hereabouts seven years ago when Sydney
outpolled favored Beijing by two votes to stage the millennial
Games. And while the local attitude about this massive undertaking
was a breezy, ``No worries,'' the citizenry soon began having
second thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   Costs soared. Revenue estimates had to be scaled back. The
ticket plan was botched. Both of the country's International
Olympic Committee members _ Phil Coles and Kevan Gosper _ were
caught up in the Salt Lake City bidding scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Coles was censured by his peers and forced off the organizing
committee here. And though Gosper wriggled off the hook, he was
later ridiculed for arranging/allowing his 11-year-old daughter
Sophie to be the first Australian to carry the torch after it was
kindled at Olympia (``Sophie's Choice,'' the headlines smirked).
</P>
<P>
   As the Games drew closer, many Sydneysiders wondered whether
they shouldn't just box up the whole bloody thing and ship it back
to Switzerland on a tramp steamer.
</P>
<P>
   While they wanted to show the world that Australia is more than
kangaroos, sharks, and outback, they weren't sure they could handle
that much of the world at once.
</P>
<P>
   Could the city swallow nearly half a million Aussie tourists and
more than 100,000 foreigners for a fortnight? Were there enough
hotel rooms? Was there enough beer? Would the train and bus system
collapse? ``The world and his dog are on their way,'' warned
columnist Peter FitzSimons.
</P>
<P>
   They've been arriving all week, even as thousands of
Sydneysiders were skipping town for the States and Europe to avoid
the craziness. The visitors have been gawking at the Harbour Bridge
and the Opera House. They've been sunning themselves on Circle
Quay, watching the ferries chuff across the water. They've been
climbing up to The Rocks, heading out to Bondi Beach for an early
spring dip. And they'll be staying, most of them, until October.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fun side is starting to come in,'' said Eli Gallwey, who
has been seeing more than 3,000 visitors a day walk across the
threshold at the Sydney Visitor Centre. ``To see the quay
brightened up with all the flags and flowers . . .''
</P>
<P>
   All over the city, banners in the Olympic colors are flapping in
the breeze. Club France has set up shop at the old Rawson Institute
for Seamen. The peculiar sounds of espanol, italiano, russki, and
American are being overheard on George Street. And day by day, the
usual ``Sydney cynicism'' is giving way to exuberance and pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``WE'RE READY'' the Sun-Herald declared Sunday, after more than
90,000 people had turned up for the dress rehearsal of the opening
ceremonies. The trains are running all night now, with many
restaurants and shops staying open around the clock. And a nation
of understated skeptics has put on its green-and-gold glasses. Four
years ago in Atlanta, the Australian team won only 44 medals. Now,
the Daily Telegraph is projecting them for 99, only two fewer than
the US won while topping the table last time.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic schedule has been set up to showcase the home side.
The Matildas, the women's soccer team that had to pose naked for a
calendar to get anybody to notice them, will play Germany Wednesday
night in Canberra in the first event of the Games. And the first
medal event Saturday will be the women's triathlon, which the
Aussies are expected to sweep.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure on the cyclists, the sailors, the rowers, the field
hockey teams, and especially the swimmers, is immense.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking about the Olympic Games at the turn of the
century in your own country,'' said Don Talbot, who coaches the
Australian swim team. ``There's a lot of magic in that.''
</P>
<P>
   There was magic in Melbourne 44 years ago when the Aussies
finished third behind the Soviets and Yanks and Fraser and Murray
Rose and Betty Cuthbert became folk heroes. This time, the home
folks have crowned their heroes and heroines in advance.
</P>
<P>
   Months ago, they snapped up every ticket in the stadium for the
women's 400 meters to watch Cathy Freeman, their Aborigine world
champion. Ian ``The Thorpedo'' Thorpe, their teen-aged king of the
pool, is more visible than the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best and worst things are being recognized everywhere you
go, even walking down the street,'' Thorpe said. ``It can be quite
daunting.''
</P>
<P>
   If Thorpe can anchor the 400 freestyle relay team to a victory
over the never-beaten Yanks Saturday night, they'll put his face(or maybe his size-17 feet) on the $50 bill. If you wear the
green-and-gold, gold brings green when the Games are down under.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly half a century, the Olympics have been half a world
away beyond the equator. Now, they're back in a land where
September means spring. Until Kazakhs and Kenyans and Kuwaitis
began coming through customs this week, until the ``flyme'' finally
made it to New South Wales, the Games were merely a date on a
calendar. Now, for Sydney, it's time to say, ``G'day,'' to the
world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
