<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAILEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE STINK LINGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The geniuses who helped make Stone &AMP; Webster what it is today _
bankrupt, that is _ are convening again in Boston. And if I could
ask this sorry board of directors just one question at their
meeting at Ropes &AMP; Gray it would be this: Why has Kerner Smith been
allowed to walk away from the disaster he presided over with $3.5
million in goodbye money and Edward Sweeney, who got the shaft
after 35 years on the job, not seen a dime of the $3 million a jury
awarded him?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, of course, is all about who wins and who loses all
too often in Corporate America today.
</P>
<P>
   The meltdown of Stone &AMP; Webster, a once great Boston institution
that over 111 years built everything from the MIT campus to most of
the nation's nuclear plants, took years of mismanagement to
accomplish, starting with that fossil William F. Allen Jr. to his
handpicked successor, Bruce ``We Hardly Knew You'' Coles, to Kerner
Smith. Stone &AMP; Webster is gone, but the stink lives on in the
bankruptcy court, in shareholder suits, and a Securities and
Exchange Commission investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The big losers have been the shareholders and the employees, who
got the double whammy of losing their jobs and their savings. The
employees, after all, were the largest shareholders with about 4
million shares, or 30 percent of the company, in their pension fund
and employee savings plan. Those shares, which topped out at $55 a
few months after Smith arrived, are worth about $1.20 today.
</P>
<P>
   The people driving this train wreck, Smith and his crew, will
whine they lost out along with shareholders, that their options are
now worthless. But they will manage fine. The sale of Stone &AMP;
Webster's assets to a Louisiana company triggered golden parachutes
for Smith and three other executives equal to three times their
salary and bonus. A fifth executive got two times his salary and
bonus. All received medical and other goodies for three years.
(Smith, by the way, didn't return my call.)
</P>
<P>
   Smith's chute was worth about $3.5 million. Executive vice
president Peter M. Evans, who worked at Stone &AMP; Webster just 18
months, will get $2.2 million. (Another winner: Jacobs Engineering
Group., which lost out in the bidding to Shaw Group Inc. and will
get a $10 million breakup fee.)
</P>
<P>
   Unlike others who will have to wade through bankruptcy
proceeding to see what, if anything, they get, Smith and his top
executives have no such problem. Shaw assumed their contracts as
part of the buyout; they will get their money.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Sweeney isn't so lucky. Stone &AMP; Webster was the only place
Sweeney ever worked, joining the company straight out of college
and rising to vice president in 35 years. But Sweeney was fired in
1998, supposedly part of one of Smith's downsizings. He sued,
claiming he was a victim of age discrimination, and a Suffolk
County jury this year awarded him about $3 million. Unemployed and
living in San Diego, Sweeney is now one in a long line of unsecured
creditors hoping to get paid something.
</P>
<P>
   We will see no more brick-and-mortar monuments to the skill of
Stone &AMP; Webster's engineers, only mountains of paper from its
lawyers. The SEC, for instance, is investigating how the company
could issue an annual report and then restate its earnings weeks
later. Investigators will want to know who knew what, when in the
massive overruns at a power plant Stone &AMP; Webster was building in
Tiverton, R.I., the straw that broke the company's back. Where,
indeed, were the auditors?
</P>
<P>
   If I were, heaven forbid, a shareholder, I would have my lawyer
take depositions from every director. Among my questions: In the
three years that Smith was in charge, what kind of buyout offers
did the directors receive, and why did they pass?
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders and employees have bought and paid for nothing less
than the truth. They have a right to know what might have been.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
You can reach me at (617) 929-2902 or bailey(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
