<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2571 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COMMENT-     09-13 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS HAVE MET THE ENEMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Last week Bill Parcells declared the border
war was over between the New England Patriots and New York Jets. As
usual, Tuna was ahead of the curve.
</P>
<P>
   The border war is over all right, and Monday night the Jets
proved it. At the moment, they are the better team and the better
organization, so feuding with them is futile. What the Patriots
need to do is forget about the Jets and start worrying about
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Since this whole sordid affair between the Jets and Patriots
began four years ago, New York has beaten New England five times in
seven games, every time at the draft table, and twice at the
negotiating table. That is not a war. It's a rout.
</P>
<P>
   So it's time to put talk of Tuna Bowls and Tuna Helper Bowls
behind them and worry about a more pressing situation. Their own
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since their 1996 Super Bowl appearance, the Patriots have
slid downhill, with the pace picking up each season. They have gone
from 11-5 to 10-6 to 9-7 to 8-8 to 0-2. They have lost one of the
best running backs in the league and haven't come close to
replacing him (oh please don't compare Robert Edwards to Curtis
Martin, because when you do, you just show your ignorance). They
have seen their offensive line fall apart until the players have to
be introduced to each other every other play.
</P>
<P>
   They have a salary cap situation that is horrendous because they
paid the wrong players too much too often and they have a draft
history that is worse than the Selective Service's.
</P>
<P>
   They have a team with little depth that relies on a defense that
simply isn't as good as you want to believe it is.
</P>
<P>
   They have problems.
</P>
<P>
   What, you say, is the proof of the latter point about this
vaunted defense? The proof comes in games like Monday night's.
</P>
<P>
   For all the defense did to baffle Jets quarterback Vinny
Testaverde for much of the night, in the end it couldn't even slow
him down when it had to. That is not a great defense.
</P>
<P>
   One minute Testaverde was 7 of 25 for 116 yards. Next he was 9
of 12 for 165 yards and two touchdowns when the game was being
decided. If Monday night were an isolated incident, you could write
it off to bad luck, but it reminded you of a game a year ago when
this same vaunted defense held the Buffalo Bills and Doug Flutie in
check all afternoon in Foxborough _ until it counted most.
</P>
<P>
   That day, the defense let Flutie take the Bills down the field
to the touchdown that tied it, 10-10, late in the fourth quarter
and then right down the field again for the winning field goal in
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Great defenses don't do that. Great defenses win the 13-10 games
and they hold 19-7 leads with nine minutes to play.
</P>
<P>
   Great defenses play like the Tampa Bay Buccaneers or even the
Miami Dolphins. Given 19 points, they usually hold on. They do just
enough to win, as Tampa did against the Patriots two weekends ago.
They don't do just enough to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Give this defense 19 points and it might hold, and then again it
might not, because it has no game-breaking player. No Warren Sapp
to make the big sack or allow someone else to do it because of the
attention being paid to him.
</P>
<P>
   This is a defense of good to very good players but not great
ones, so it plays well, but is it as good a defense as Buffalo's or
Miami's?
</P>
<P>
   No.
</P>
<P>
   Is it as good as Tampa's? A thousand times no.
</P>
<P>
   So what are you left with?
</P>
<P>
   You're left with a loss in a game in which the offense
controlled the ball for nearly 31 of the final 45 minutes, meaning
the defense cannot complain that it was on the field too long.
</P>
<P>
   There are two ways to look at that. Unfortunately, both of them
are bad.
</P>
<P>
   In 31 minutes, the offense could score only one touchdown
despite being inside the Red Zone six times. This is not only
unacceptable, it is absurd.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, in 14 minutes of work, New England's much-praised
defense allowed two touchdowns to be scored on it. That is not only
unacceptable, it is deadly.
</P>
<P>
   So what can we say about the Patriots as they stare at a 0-2
record and a visit from the high-powered Minnesota Vikings Sunday?
</P>
<P>
   What we can say is what Bill Belichick has not said but is
clearly doing. What we can say is that this is not a competitive
year for the Patriots, it's a rebuilding year, and the process is
going to take a while.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because Martin averaged 4.3 yards a carry Monday night for
the Jets, and the Patriots' running game averaged 2.9.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because Testaverde was sacked only twice by what is
supposed to be an overpowering defense while Drew Bledsoe was
flattened six times by a team that hasn't had a pass rush in years.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because the Jets played with five offensive linemen from
start to finish while the Patriots looked like a cavalry charge
every other series as Belichick kept sending in reinforcements for
a line that is shakier than California real estate.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because the administration that preceded Belichick in New
England made too many mistakes in too many areas for too long
because it was too arrogant from top to bottom about what it
thought it knew and too unwilling to see that the way it was doing
business _ both in free agency and on draft day _ was a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there is a long way to go this season, and Belichick
may yet come up with ways to improve the Patriots' fortunes, but
don't believe for a minute there are unemployed football players
out there he can import to make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   Players who are still unemployed after Labor Day are in that
situation because they aren't good enough to impact a team. That is
simply a fact, unless someone can convince Barry Sanders to put
down the Coppertone and come out of retirement. Barring that
(forget about it), there will be no cavalry charge over the ridge
this fall unless it comes from the players already wearing Patriot
uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, there may be another border war with the Jets
someday, but for now that war is over. The fight is not with the
Jets anymore or with any other team in the National Football
League.
</P>
<P>
   The fight now is internal because the only thing that can save
the Patriots from a disastrous season is themselves. You don't have
to be a defensive genius to see that.
</P>
<P>
   You just have to have a pair of eyes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-00 1405EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
