u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     09-13 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZEFER FACES A NEW DOT.COM REALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Zefer Corp. was at the top of the heap in the glitter days of
Internet start-ups, walking away with the top prize in Harvard's
prestigious business plan competition and right into an
unprecedented one-shot, $100 million venture capital commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Those glitter days are just two years in the past but seem like
ancient history. Like everyone else working on the Web, managers at
Zefer have found today's business world a much more challenging
place.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston company's $45 million initial public stock offering
planned this month has been taken off the IPO schedule, at least
for now. Zefer had attempted an even larger $69 million offering in
the spring before pulling the deal.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, stock market conditions appeared to have more to
do with the decision than anything happening at the company. The
market for tech stocks collapsed before Zefer's IPO in the spring
and, more recently, investors have gone cold on an Internet
consulting sector seen as losing business momentum.
</P>
<P>
   None of that has slowed Zefer from its hyper-speed plan for
building up the business, more than tripling the work force to 762
people in just over a year by mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues have soared, up to $45 million for the first half of
this year. But Zefer has also spent money like water and produced
gaping deficits along the way.
</P>
<P>
   The hot little start-up has managed to burn through more than
$70 million and owes about $42 million in loans and credit lines.
Nearly half of the money to be raised in Zefer's latest IPO efforts
was earmarked to pay off the company's bank credit line rather than
be spent on new business plans.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Zefer's reported losses, more than $60 million, have
come in the last nine months. Company documents filed in connection
with its IPO plans report financial information through June 30.
</P>
<P>
   This is one expensive buildup for a consulting company. It isn't
sinking millions into hard assets like factories or airplanes or
even printing presses. The money has been spent to construct
marketing, training, research, and administrative functions that
can support a big organization.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of investment may turn out to be a shrewd idea. But it
can also evaporate before your eyes. Any kind of consulting
business depends, almost entirely, on its people, and they have a
habit of moving. What would Zefer own for all of its millions then?
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Zefer executives were not able to make their
pitch to us Tuesday. Citing the public comment restrictions imposed
by their still-active stock registration, company officials
declined to be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   But their strategy never came as a big surprise. When a single
venture capital firm like GTCR Golder Rauner LLC of Chicago drops
$100 million on a young company the message is clear: Use it to
spend your close competitors into the ground and catch up with
others who have a big headstart.
</P>
<P>
   GTCR also gave 20-something Zefer founder Anthony Tjan something
else. It installed technology consulting veteran William Seibel as
chief executive of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Seibel, once a senior executive at Cambridge Technology Partners
Inc., made no secret about his ideas for a very large new company
and how a limited corporate infrastructure contributed to the
buckling of Cambridge's operation as business soared there years
before.
</P>
<P>
   Now Zefer has spent a great deal of its venture investors' money
building the kind of business they had in mind. The question: Will
public investors want a piece of that strategy?
</P>
<P>
   Shares of all Internet consultants and ``integrators'' have been
under pressure in recent weeks because of mounting evidence that
dot-com clients are cutting expenses and more established companies
are slowing their Web plans since they can no longer feel the hot
breath of the wired world on their necks.
</P>
<P>
   Investors who own those stocks want what all Internet investors
want: profits. Now.
</P>
<P>
   Zefer's business was clearly soaring through the first half of
this year. The company's client roster included some big companies
such as Citicorp, Barclays, and Gillette Co. But Zefer also
expected 25 percent to 35 percent of its business this year to come
from a dot-com clientele.
</P>
<P>
   Zefer first emerged as a hot new Internet name in a different
time when buzz, not earnings, was the ultimate asset. Times change
and perhaps Zefer is changing with them.
</P>
<P>
   But to make it public now it will have to show investors
something other than more big losses in its immediate future.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
