<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USING JUMBO CDS TO INCREASE SAVINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I recently sold an underperforming fund in my rollover IRA
and am ready to add some conservative funds, and possibly even a
growth fund to cover inflation. I have been satisfied with the
funds in my taxable accounts, but I don't have any significant tax
deductions and in the past capital gains have pushed me into a
higher tax bracket. I need $2,000 a month from my portfolio. Can I
get this monthly income? Can this be achieved by investing in
fixed-income, and perhaps even tax-exempt funds? Will I be covered
for long-term inflation?
</P>
<P>
   C.H., Cambridge, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. There's not really anything wrong with your situation, but
you've got to get out of the money-market habit. The current level
of money-market holdings is nearly 70 percent, and while I realize
a good deal of this stems from a recent sale of a fund, I think the
correct percentage for somebody in your situation is zero.
</P>
<P>
   My suggestion would be to move the entire rollover IRA account
to five-year jumbo CDs, which are offered at rates as high as 7.71
percent entering this week. I wrote about these accounts at great
length last Sunday, so rather than repeat myself here, I suggest
you refer to that column. My specific suggestion would be to open
two $100,000 accounts, both at 7.71 percent, and a third for
$73,940, on which you can get 7.6 percent. I would then add $10,000
to your position in Vanguard GNMA, which has a current yield of
6.79 percent. The effect of these two moves would be to provide you
with fixed-income holdings sufficient to provide your required
income stream.
</P>
<P>
   That would leave you with $123,976 that could be put to work to
protect you against future inflation. And you will want it to work
a lot harder than money markets are likely to do. Let's suppose you
took that $10,000 that went into Vanguard GNMA from one of your
taxable money-market accounts. That would leave you with $52,094 in
money funds to put to work. My suggestion is one of two funds, both
of which should deliver the kind of solid long-term growth you will
need to deal with inflation, and both of which should help deal
with your tax woes.
</P>
<P>
   One is Vanguard Index 500, which is by definition quite
tax-efficient. The other is Vanguard Tax-Managed Growth and Income
fund, managed specifically to keep taxable distributions to a
minimum level.
</P>
<P>
   That would leave you with the balanced fund, the foreign fund,
and your Bell South common _ all of which I suggest you hang on to
_ and that small CD.
</P>
<P>
   I'm of two minds relative to the CD account. If it were my
money, I would wait until it matures and then move the money into
Vanguard Health Care fund _ after all, it is health care costs that
loom largest in the fears of people your age, and having the health
care industry help you meet your financial goals seems somewhat
fitting. But I am also aware that by suggesting you move either
into Vanguard 500 or Vanguard Tax-Managed Growth and Income fund, I
am quite significantly increasing the risk level of your overall
portfolio, and moving to Vanguard Health Care would increase it
still further.
</P>
<P>
   So if you are uncomfortable with that initial ratchet in the
risk level, you could use Vanguard Balanced Index instead of either
of the more aggressive funds I initially suggested. And if you are
uncomfortable with the second step into higher-risk funds
represented by the suggestion of Vanguard Health Care, you could
move the CD money into a fairly aggressive fixed-income position
such as Vanguard High-Yield Corporate Bond fund.
</P>
<P>
   But I would argue that my initial selections are indeed
appropriate, since the moves into the high-yielding CDs and the
increase in the GNMA position should provide your income, so all of
the remainder can be treated as long-term money. Moreover, you
would need to take the more aggressive stance to maintain a good
chance of keeping pace with inflation. Consider that, if you wanted
to maintain your annual buying power at the $24,000-a-year level,
you will have to draw some funds from the stock investments each
year, adding them to the fixed-income side.
</P>
<P>
   For example, next year you would require $24,850 to keep even
after a year if inflation runs at 3.5 percent for the next year; to
add that much to your income stream would require moving about
$11,000 from the stock side to the fixed-income side. If you did
come close to a 10 percent portfolio return in that year, you would
be able to do it, but it would be a lot more difficult in future
years. So I suggest you try to take some of the cost of inflation
out of your budget, making only modest _ if any _ additions to the
fixed-income side in the next half-decade and letting the growth
side of your portfolio build during that period.
</P>
<P>
   The bush I am beating around, I confess, is that you don't
really have enough cash for growth investments to protect yourself
comfortably against future inflation. But if you manage your money
_ and especially the costs _ carefully, you should be able to
finance a decent retirement. But at some point in your 70s you will
doubtless find things getting tighter, and it will be hard to keep
the principal value of your savings from declining. But remember,
declining principal isn't all that bad _ after all, it was to spend
it in your retirement that you have been saving all these years,
wasn't it?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I currently have $10,000 in a low-yielding savings account. I
would like to put it in a mutual fund for at least eight years but
no more than 10 years, with no additions to the account. I'm
considering Vanguard Growth and Income fund. Do you think this
would be a good move?
</P>
<P>
   B.W., Spring Valley, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, the conventional wisdom is that if you have an
intermediate investment time frame, which is between five and 10
years, a balanced fund is the ticket. If you stretch the time frame
out to 10 years, then an all-stock fund such as Vanguard Growth and
Income would be OK.
</P>
<P>
   But I think the current state of the market argues in favor of a
balanced investment, hedging your stock holdings with a sizeable
bond position. What I'm referring to is the past half decade of
regular and substantial stock market gains, a pattern that cannot
long continue, as many investors have seen this year. Whether the
markets will react to this with a severe drop, a so-called
correction, or simply a long period of meandering while corporate
earnings and dividends catch up to the current heady stock prices
is anybody's guess. But it is a very solid estimate that the
double-digit gains of past years are probably behind us.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, and because you may want to call upon your
money after eight years rather than 10, I suggest you go with
Vanguard Balanced Index rather than Growth and Income. At current
levels, Vanguard Balanced Index holds 58.8 percent of its assets in
a stock portfolio that represents a blend of growth and value
large-cap stocks. It has a 39.3 percent bond position, and the rest
of the portfolio in cash. Its five-year record shows 15.56 percent
average annual returns _ although your expectations if you go into
this fund should be somewhere in the 8 to 9 percent range. It has
returned 4.38 percent year to date, and yields 2.99 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard Growth and Income, on the other hand, holds 98.9
percent of its assets in a portfolio of value-oriented large-cap
stocks, with the balance in cash. Over five years it has averaged
23.75 percent returns, although long-term expectations should be
closer to the 10 percent area. It has returned 3.81 percent year to
date, and has a puny 0.90 percent yield.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I just received a letter from Janus fund announcing that Jim
Craig, manager of the fund for 17 years, is leaving. In addition, I
have read about a bitter dispute between Janus and its parent
company. My wife and I own both Janus and Janus 20 funds. Should we
be concerned enough to consider transferring to other funds? I also
noticed that Fidelity Select Biotechnology fund has had four
managers in four years. Should I be concerned about it?
</P>
<P>
   P.W., Keene, N.H. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. These are two pretty different situations. The game of
musical chairs at Fidelity _ and especially among the managers of
its sector funds such as the biotech offering you hold _ has been
going on for years with few discernible evil effects. It's an
approach to managing its business that Fidelity believes in, and it
has gone on long enough that you should not be at all concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Although Janus has said the departure of Craig has nothing to do
with the tension between the Janus team and Stilwell Financial,
which owns 82 percent of Janus, the news is certainly unsettling.
It is true, as Janus points out, that the team that will take
Craig's place includes managers with considerable success in
managing other funds, notably Janus Enterprise, Janus Mercury,
Janus Twenty, and Janus Worldwide. On the other hand, the friction
surrounding the management of Janus _ and especially the discussion
of whether Janus founder Thomas H. Bailey can be or might be fired
_ isn't something that should make Janus a particularly easy place
to work effectively.
</P>
<P>
   My instinct would be to watch your investment very carefully and
be prepared to jump ship (particularly with investments in IRAs and
other tax-deferred accounts in which there would be no short-term
tax consequences) in the event that Janus fund tends to be falling
behind its peers. Of course, if you're a long-term holder of Janus
in a taxable account, the tax consequences of selling should make
you willing to give the new managers a longer leash, but I would
still keep pretty close tabs on how they are doing.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to following the funds' results closely, if you have
a computer, I suggest you log onto www.morningstar.com regularly,
call up JANSX, and keep a fairly close tab on news stories relating
to the fund and its management.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box 2378,
Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
