<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RATING SLEAZE; COVERS THAT SKIMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VH1's as-addictive-as-crack ``Behind the Music'' series owes
much of its success to its big, juicy servings of musician
misbehavior. Yeah, it's nice to know the details behind John
Phillips writing the Mamas &AMP; the Papas' hit ``California Dreamin.'
'' But it's way more titillating to hear about wife Michelle's
steamy affair with his bandmate Denny Doherty.
</P>
<P>
   Sleaze is sweet, and since lists are the filler of choice for
idea-exhausted magazine editors, Spin has come up with perhaps its
best list yet _ the frightening and laugh-out-loud funny ``100
Sleaziest Moments in Rock.'' (Just the cover photo of Diamond David
Lee Roth in his raunchy prime is worth the price.) Boiling down
40-plus years of debauchery _ ``the good, the bad, and the hideous;
the amusingly repellent and the simply criminal,'' as Spin's
editors write _ must have been quite the task, and the list ranges
from the antics of Chuck Berry (No. 9) to Suge Knight (No. 7), from
the Bay City Rollers (No. 24) to Cynthia Plastercaster (No. 31),
the Chicago woman who made her name immortalizing the penises of
such rock stars as Jimi Hendrix in plaster.
</P>
<P>
   You get lots of the usual suspects, of course _ Tommy Lee, Keith
Richards, Sid Vicious, and Courtney Love, who comes in at No. 13
just for being the terror fabulous that is Courtney. Diana Ross
slips in at No. 96 for trying to foist those bargain-basement
Supremes on us earlier this year, and Metallica (No. 30) gets
scolded for busting 300,000 of their Napster-loving fans.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, there's a lot to quibble about _ what else are lists
really for anyway? Sure, Woodstock '99 was a violent, stupid mess,
but it just doesn't deserve a No. 4 slot over Jerry Lee Lewis's
cradle-robbing marriage to his 13-year-old cousin, which mustered
only a No. 38 slot. Much of the best stuff simply can't be
discussed in polite company, including the No. 1 choice _ no
argument here _ which involves Led Zeppelin, a groupie, and a mud
shark. 'Nuff said 'bout that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The barely covered girl
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maxim is a magazine for men; it says so right on the cover in
big bold white letters _ ``FOR MEN.'' So why does this men's
magazine have a postpubescent cover girl? That's barely-18-year-old
Kirsten Dunst wearing nothing but an unbuttoned denim jacket and a
pair of white hot pants _ any skimpier, and they'd be a
thong-thong-thong-thong-thong _ next to the headline ``Thirstin'
for Kirsten!'' on the September issue. Let's not even get into the
question of whether adult males should be thirsting for a girl who
isn't even old enough to buy a beer. Yes, Dunst is street legal,
but who needs to see her all tarted up in a series of revealing,
tourniquet-tight outfits, except for the Humbert Humberts of
Maxim's readership?
</P>
<P>
   In this strange new age of men's magazines, Maxim isn't the only
offender _ remember 17-year-old Jessica Biel's soft-porn spread in
Gear last year? Of course, you can blame the magazines only so
much. What dirty-minded editor is going to decline the opportunity
to feature a nubile starlet in his magazine? Getting near-naked in
men's magazines is the latest way for young female stars to shed
their goody-goody images, and they seem to be lining up for the
chance to wear little more than a come-hither stare.
</P>
<P>
   Dunst cracks nary a smile in her seven-page spread, and makes
clear in an interview (yes, there are actual words, too) with
Michael Atkinson that she wants to bust out of her sweetheart
roles, even though she turned down the Mena Suvari role in
``American Beauty.'' ``I didn't want to be kissing Kevin Spacey,''
she says. ``Come on! Lying there naked, covered with rose petals?''
Hey, Kirsten, what about sitting there almost-naked in a black
bikini in Maxim? Come on!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The snaked truth
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With a red bikini, lovingly accessorized with a big snake,
Elizabeth Hurley is pretty raw herself on the cover of Total Movie
_ but hey, she's a full-grown women. Total Movie enters an already
crowded field of film rags, but as editor in chief Gary Whitta
asserts, it's written by ``100% pure,
cut-me-do-I-not-bleed-celluloid film fanatics.'' And it also comes
with a great gimmick: Each issue will include a DVD chock-full of
movie trailers, short films, and extra features. This month's
edition includes previews for ``Pearl Harbor,'' ``Blair Witch 2:
Book of Shadows,'' and the re-release of ``The Exorcist.'' But
there are also lots of trailers for films that have already come
and gone, such as ``Titan A. E.'' Nobody wanted to see that film
when it was in theaters, so why would anyone want to see the
trailer now? There's also behind-the-scenes footage from ``Romeo
Must Die,'' and ``The Legend of Bagger Vance.'' But other than the
DVD, Total Movie is a standard stroke for Hollywood, as if they're
aren't enough shows and magazines already doing that. But hey,
here's a new gimmick for the next issue _ how's about a DVD player
so your readers can actually watch that free DVD?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-00 1410EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
