<HEADER>
A2578 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-BUYERS-EDGE-LEATHER14     09-13 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUYERS-EDGE-LEATHER14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Buying a smart-looking leather jacket at a good price is simple
if you know what to look for
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The leather report this fall calls for hot-looking jackets in
cool silhouettes.
</P>
<P>
   And while the leather jacket might change shape, it never loses
its edge _ or its sleek yet practical image. Wear it with wool
trousers for day or over a chiffon dress at night.
</P>
<P>
   Stores are filled with all types of jackets, from blazers to
trench styles to cropped, zip-front numbers. Although black is the
perennial No. 1 color choice, you can also sizzle in red, wine,
camel, ivory and brown.
</P>
<P>
   A good leather jacket is an investment, and a classically styled
piece can wear well and remain chic for decades. Often, what to
look for when buying leather can be confusing, but we tell you how
to shop smart for that second-skin look.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the following criteria:
</P>
<P>
   The skin game
</P>
<P>
   Leather jackets are made from the hides of cows, lambs and pigs.
They differ in texture, feel and price. In general, pig is the
least expensive, lamb the most expensive. However, certain grades
of cow leather can also be quite expensive.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in cow leather, you will find cowhide, which comes
from the skin of full-grown cows and is thicker, heavier and quite
durable. Sometimes the skin is split to obtain a desired thickness.
Many manufacturers use only top-grain cowhide for quality jackets.
Calf hide is leather made from the skins of young cattle. It is
lightweight and fine grain. Go by feel when buying a jacket. Soft,
smooth and supple are good guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   The finished look
</P>
<P>
   To create different textures, leather is tanned or treated. Some
of the more popular finishes, according to the leather buyers at
Federated Department Stores, are:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Aniline dyeing: An indigo or synthetic dye is used to dress
the skins in a large drum. These items are usually more expensive
because the most desirable and highest grades of leather are used.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Distressed: It's the process of making leather look old or
worn through buffing. Can also be achieved through spraying.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Coating: A substance such as oil, lacquer or synthetic covers
the fabric on one or both sides.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Embossing: Skins such as ostrich and crocodile are printed on
the grain side by a heated metal plate in a press.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nap or napping: Obtained by brushing the skin to achieve a
soft, smooth touch.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Suede: The flesh side of the skin is shaved and buffed,
creating a soft feel.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tanning: This is the process used by the tanner to convert
rawhide into a usable piece of leather.
</P>
<P>
   The inside scoop
</P>
<P>
   When buying a jacket, look at the lining. You will find silk or
lightweight synthetics, such as acetate and satins. These are soft
but won't keep you warm. Some jackets are lined with Thinsulate or
Thermolite, which is sporty, warm and durable. Also, examine the
jacket seams. Look for minimal lines and smooth stitching. Metal
zippers or buttonholes should be finished cleanly.
</P>
<P>
   The price factor
</P>
<P>
   Why does one jacket cost $200 while another costs $500? ``The
leather is two-thirds the price of a jacket,'' says Mark Schwartz,
director of leather buying for Wilson's Suede and Leather stores.
``And one manufacturer or designer may select a better-grade raw
material for its jacket than another designer does. This raises the
price. For example, the best leathers come from the sides of an
animal, where the grain is most consistent.'' Also, a
time-consuming finishing process can up the ante on a jacket. And,
if your jacket boasts a designer label, that, too, can increase the
cost, in terms of advertising and marketing.
</P>
<P>
   CARING FOR YOUR LEATHER JACKET
</P>
<P>
   It's your hide now, so care for it properly. The Leather Apparel
Association lists the following suggestions. Log on to
www.leatherassociation.com for more tips.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Leather jackets should be hung on wide or padded hangers to
maintain their shape. And they should be stored in a dark closet
that is neither too dry nor humid.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Do not use waxes, silicone products or other leather
preparations that impair a garment's ability to breathe.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Avoid spraying on perfume or hair spray while wearing your
jacket. They can discolor or damage leather. And wear a scarf at
the neck to keep body oils away from the collar.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  It is perfectly safe to iron leather. Set the controls to
rayon setting and use heavy brown wrapping paper as a pressing
cloth on the right side of the item and iron. Wrinkles should come
right out.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If you get caught wearing your leather jacket in the rain, let
it dry at room temperature away from heat.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Spill ketchup, wine or salad dressing on your jacket? Take it
to a professional cleaner as soon as possible and tell them exactly
what the stain is. Don't try to clean it yourself.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  To find a leather cleaner, Richard Mays of Ram Leather Care in
Conyers (770-483-3454) suggests you contact your local dry cleaner
and ask if it provides the service of cleaning leathers. If so, get
a quote on the charge and how long it will take to clean your
jacket. Many cleaners do not clean leathers on site.
</P>
<P>
   Marylin Johnson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
