<HEADER>
A2579 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-GARDENING14-COX     09-13 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hear the heavenly call of lovely angel's trumpet
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's something about angel's trumpet. More times than I can
remember I have grown at this plant. I did not say I have grown
this plant; I said I have grown at it.
</P>
<P>
   While I've been able to keep one of these shrubs alive from time
to time, my success at getting one to bloom is quite another story.
A short one: Several autumns ago a plant I'd grown for several
years finally put out white, fragrant blossoms. Just as I was
getting used to the loveliness, frost killed it back. The plant
returned once, then no more. Since then, none has bloomed for me,
despite full sun, good drainage, watering and feeding.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing I can figure is I just don't hold my mouth right.
But, sometimes, there's just no accounting for why a plant won't
work for you.
</P>
<P>
   My eyes clouded with visions of growing failures, I always look
with admiration at angel's trumpets that bloom with elegant abandon
in other gardens. My latest look was in Midtown Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Jones, better known as JJ, was inside when I arrived at his
home and got arrested by the lush landscaping. First, the
sunflowers, with their big bright faces, made me smile from across
the street. On the porch were many houseplants, including ficus,
lipstick plant, African violet, fern, palm, pencil cactus (I would
go home with a cutting from the huge parent plant), dumb cane,
peace lily. And coleus galore.
</P>
<P>
   More coleus grew in the narrow strip of land on the driveway
side of the house, where, surrounded by more sunflowers, the
angel's trumpet stood some 6 feet. With more than a dozen pale
yellow blossoms dangling in the morning sun, the shrub lit up the
space like a Christmas tree.
</P>
<P>
   JJ, whose twin passions are horticulture and doll-making, has
had more success with his angel's trumpet in a few months than I
have in 10 years. The plant, which typically blooms, rests, blooms,
way into autumn, enchants. Says JJ as he shows off the trumpet on
this muggy morning: ``These blooms are like angels dancing. To have
something this delicate, this ethereal ... I love it.''
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by his yellow-blooming trumpet, JJ is eager to get
growth from several cuttings given him by friend Jayme Proctor of
Pittsboro, N.C. Through these gifts and through purchases, JJ plans
to enjoy other plants, other colors _ white, pink, peach, orange.
Why not? He's got the touch.
</P>
<P>
   For my part, I went home and took a look at my latest angel's
trumpet. It came from a friend who takes 6-inch cuttings from
mature wood, puts them in water and stands back; they root quickly.
I put my cutting in the ground in the spring of 1999. I didn't
expect it to produce flowers last year, and I was not wrong. As
expected, the tender native of Peru got knocked to the ground in
the winter but returned last spring. Its height reached a foot and
has been stuck there all summer. And, yes, I have no flowers, see
no signs of any.
</P>
<P>
   My next act is to dig up the little angel's trumpet and put it
in a container. (That tack worked marvelously with my tea olive,
which blooms better and longer indoors than it ever did outside.)
One of the more attractive trumpets I'd seen lately was in a
container, growing happily in Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   That was before I visited JJ's place. If the container move
doesn't work for me, I can always go back for another look.
</P>
<P>
   Lee May writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
