<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-CHESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MAGAZINE RANKS TEXAS SCHOOL AMONG BEST IN NATION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ALISON GREGOR  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROWNSVILLE, Texas _ An elementary school lauded for its chess
program was recognized as one of the five best schools in the
country by Hispanic Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Morningside Elementary School, whose chess teams ranked among
the top 10 nationwide, received the honor for its outstanding and
unique programs, said a letter from Hispanic Magazine publisher Sam
Verdeja.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Harris, Morningside's principal, said the magazine
considered demographics, test scores and academic and
extracurricular programs. He gave a lot of the credit to the
school's teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really proud of the teachers,'' Harris said. ``They
believe that every child can learn and will learn, and they don't
let any obstacles get in their way.''
</P>
<P>
   One obstacle could have been poverty. Ninety-four percent of
Morningside's 930 students are from low-income families that
qualify for free or reduced-price school lunches. Much of the
almost all-Hispanic student body is in bilingual education.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't seem to have been a problem for the school,
which trounced public and private schools alike in state and
national chess competitions. State test scores have ranked the
school among the best, if not the best, in Texas in reading and
math, according to statistical analysis done by Just for the Kids,
an Austin group that studies Texas public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids do well,'' Harris said. ``They came in first in the
science fair.
</P>
<P>
   The principal said Morningside hopes to place first in academic
competition conducted by the University Interscholastic League, the
governing body for extracurricular activities for the state's
public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said Hispanic Magazine became interested in Morningside
when Secretary of Education Richard Riley mentioned the school's
chess achievements in a recent speech. The speech focused on the
importance of education for the nation's Hispanic community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who would have thought _ in a state where high school football
is sometimes king and English is for many a second language _ that
these students would go head to head with the best minds in the
country in one of the most challenging and intellectual games?''
Riley said. ``They did and so did their teachers, parents and
principals _ and that made all the difference.''
</P>
</TEXT>
