A2593 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CORRUPT-NATIONS-440&AMP;A     09-13 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORRUPT-NATIONS-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD CORRUPTION INDEX SHOWS THAT AN IMAGE IS NOT ALTERED IN A
DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ When a country gets a reputation for being
deeply corrupt, it takes a lot of time _ and more than just the
election of an anti-corruption government _ to make a dent in its
negative image, a corruption watchdog group said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The group, Transparency International, used the case of Nigeria
to make that point in its 2000 Corruption Perception Index.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria, whose president, Olusegun Obasanjo, is a former
advisory council chairman of Transparency International, is still
at the bottom of the index more than a year after the change of
government that restored democracy following a period of corrupt
military rule.
</P>
<P>
   The low ranking is in part related to a change in this year's
index, a measure of perceptions about corruption drawn from surveys
by international economic organizations and risk analysts. For the
first time, Transparency International, an independent organization
founded in 1995 by former World Bank officials to expose corruption
among public officials worldwide, used data from a three-year
period, not a single year. Change takes time to register, the
report says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Valiant efforts are being made by President Olusegun Obasanjo
to force full-scale changes in a country whose people have been
robbed by the grand corruption of their past leaders,'' said Peter
Eigen, chairman of Transparency International, which has chapters
in more than 70 countries. ``But the process of change initiated by
the new president is barely 12 months old, and so it is not
surprising that Nigeria's CPI score is virtually unchanged.''
</P>
<P>
   In the perceptions of business people, Transparency
International found this year that officials in Yugoslavia,
Ukraine, Azerbaijan, Indonesia and Angola are also at the bottom of
the list, which ranks countries on a score of 10, for the least
corrupt, to zero, for the most corrupt. They all have scores below
2.
</P>
<P>
   A number of countries seeking more trade and investment from the
United States and Europe _ among them China, Vietnam, India and
Mexico _ also rank low, all below 3.5.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 countries ranked least corrupt are Finland, Denmark, New
Zealand, Sweden, Canada, Iceland, Norway, Singapore, the
Netherlands and Britain. The United States is in 14th place, with
7.8 points on the 10-point scale. It ranks at about the same level
as Austria, Hong Kong, Germany and Chile.
</P>
<P>
   The Corruption Perceptions Index is available online at
http://www.transparency.org/documents/cpi/2000/cpi2000.html.
</P>
<P>
   Transparency International in based in Berlin, with offices in
London and Washington.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ninety countries were included in this year's report, down from
98 last year. Some countries were eliminated because not enough
information was available for the expanded three-year period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dropping out of the CPI for lack of data is bad news for
countries and may indicate reduced investor interest,'' the report
says.
</P>
<P>
   Transparency International, criticized in earlier years for
focusing on bribe-taking officials rather than bribe-paying
businesses, also began publishing a bribe payers' index last year.
Another survey of bribe payers will be published next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-00 1418EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000913.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2596 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-NIKITIN14-COX     09-13 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-NIKITIN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RUSSIA'S NUCLEAR WHISTLE-BLOWER ACQUITTED ON TREASON CHARGES
 &HT;    540&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By MARGARET COKER
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia's Supreme Court on Wednesday ended a nearly
five-year effort by government prosecutors to punish a retired
Russian naval captain for exposing the perils of Russia's decaying
nuclear fleet.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, which upheld a lower court decision acquitting
Alexander Nikitin on spy and treason charges, was praised by human
rights groups and military observers alike as a step toward
cracking the military's code of secrecy.
</P>
<P>
   Military secrecy, Nikitin's supporters say, led to the deaths of
118 sailors last month when the submarine Kursk sank.
</P>
<P>
   The charges against Nikitin stemmed from a report he published
in 1996 with the Norwegian environmental group Bellona that
documented alleged nuclear abuses by the Navy and the unsafe
conditions of the fleet's nuclear reactors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today I am very happy,'' said the 46-year-old with a military
flattop after Wednesday's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened is a triumph of law and justice. At the time
(the report was published), we said that if society is informed of
such facts, this forces the authorities to fix problems. The basis
of our case was that talking about so-called secrets is not a sign
of a traitor.''
</P>
<P>
   The verdict marks the first time a Russian has been found not
guilty on treason charges, according to Nikitin's lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Nikitin, himself a former submarine captain, has won several
international awards for his work in uncovering radiation dangers
here. He told reporters he would continue his environmental studies
in his own country and try to strengthen the support for such work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has to learn that the truth is the only way to
make sure there are no more accidents ... and that contaminating
our environment means contaminating people, too,'' Nikitin said.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 report described 52 abandoned nuclear submarines in a
remote shipyard near Russia's border with Norway. Its release
brought scorn from Russia's tight-lipped military brass and
intelligence agencies, and Nikitin was arrested in February of that
year by the Federal Security Service (FSB), domestic successor to
the Soviet KGB. He was jailed for two years and tried 13 separate
times.
</P>
<P>
   His acquittal by a St. Petersburg court in December 1999 was
upheld five months later by Russia's Supreme Court, which slammed
the FSB and the prosecutor's office for imprisoning Nikitin under
``secret'' regulations and trying him for violations of unpublished
and retroactively applied laws.
</P>
<P>
   Still, prosecutors didn't give up the case. They appealed the
decision to the Presidium of the Supreme Court, the nation's
highest court, which could have reopened the prosecution on
identical charges _ a process barred by the U.S. Constitution as
double jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   In their brief to the Presidium, prosecutors recommended
overturning Nikitin's acquittal on the grounds that the FSB had
violated the former submariner's human rights. In Russian legal
practice, a higher court can restart a prosecution if they are
convinced the original investigation was conducted incorrectly.
</P>
<P>
   ``That such a brief could be published shows that our legal
system is a farce. To say 'The police beat me and jailed me even
though I was innocent' as a reason to retry someone's guilt is
stranger than fiction,'' said Fredrick Hague, the director of
Bellona.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The Presidium's ruling closes the case for good, but
environmentalists in Russia still expect many fights ahead of them,
thanks to the slow pace of reform in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had a rational system in Russia, Nikitin would be made a
government consultant on how to prevent accidents like the Kursk.
But, unfortunately, our system still says that anyone without the
authority to speak must keep their mouths shut,'' said Alexei
Smirnov, the director of Moscow's Glasnost Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Several similar cases have tarnished Russia's already deplorable
record on environmental safety and military reform.
</P>
<P>
   Another former naval officer, Grigory Pasko, was imprisoned for
20 months on treason charges after providing videotaped evidence of
illegal nuclear dumping by Russia's Pacific Fleet to Japanese
journalists. He won an appeal on treason charges earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   The laboratory of Vladimir Sofyer, a Russian nuclear scientist,
was raided by the FSB in 1999 because the lab was carrying out an
unsanctioned study of the environmental effects of a 1985 Soviet
atomic-submarine accident in the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the Russian Ministry of Justice announced
that all nongovernmental organizations must register with the
government or face dissolution. Several human rights,
environmental, and antimilitarist groups were denied documentation,
essentially making them illegal groups.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.janes.com, www.government.gov.ru/english/
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Coker's E-mail address is: megc(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
