<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 14:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2622 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-LOUIS-ARMSTRONG-HNS &LR;      09-13 1287
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUIS-ARMSTRONG-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CELEBRATING THE LIFE OF A GREATER SWINGER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: Note optional trim)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PHILIP ELWOOD  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel such a thrill, my feet won't keep still, when they
swing that music for me.'' _ ``Swing That Music,'' Louis Armstrong,
1936; Decca Records
</P>
<P>
   Hearing ``Swing That Music'' on my tabletop radio may have been
my first exposure to the world of swing _ but more important, it
was my introduction to the talents of Louis Armstrong and to the
world of black jazz.
</P>
<P>
   It never would have occurred to fans in those years prior to
World War II that there would one day be internationally observed
centennial birth-year celebrations and commemorative stamps devoted
to Armstrong. (Armstrong died in 1971.)
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday night at the Monterey Jazz Festival, trumpeters
Nicholas Payton, Roy Hargrove, Tom Harrell and their bands will pay
tribute; the Jazz at Lincoln Center organization began its
year-long ``100 Years of Armstrong'' series with a concert by
Wynton Marsalis' JLC band in Liberty State Park on the Fourth of
July (despite evidence that Armstrong was not born on July 4, 1900,
as he claimed, but, rather, on Aug. 3, 1901); and Ken Burns'
lengthy ``Jazz'' documentary series, scheduled to air on PBS in
January, is devoting a full segment to Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   Like most jazz performers of the 1920s, Armstrong _ the all-time
greatest jazz soloist _ was resurfacing on the American music scene
in the mid-1930s after lengthy European touring, various personal
problems and Depression-era doldrums. A recording contract from
Jack Kapp's new Decca label sparked the Armstrong revival.
</P>
<P>
   In 1936, he appeared with Bing Crosby (his pal from earlier
years) in ``Pennies From Heaven,'' a popular Hollywood film, and
was a frequent guest on Crosby's radio show. This sort of thing was
controversial in the 1930s, but Crosby had clout and often had
black jazz and swing stars on his show.
</P>
<P>
   Crosby has been quoted in the JLC Armstrong guidebook as saying,
``Satch is the beginning and end of American music.''
</P>
<P>
   On the basis of recordings he had made 1923-31, Armstrong was,
in the 1930s, already considered by musicians the most inventive
and extraordinary of jazz soloists. Many observers and fans,
however, believed his best years were behind him _ that his
increasing role as a singing, clowning showman had diluted his jazz
career.
</P>
<P>
   But the critics were wrong. There was a new generation of jazz
(or swing) fans that were idolizing trumpeters like Bunny Berigan,
Harry James, Roy Eldridge, Dizzy Gillespie and a dozen more _ and
all of them said, ``listen to Armstrong _ he's the one.'' Trumpeter
Jack Purvis even issued a record titled ``Copyin' Louis,'' and
Gillespie's familiar quote (often mentioned), ``To speak his name
is to conjure up our whole world.''
</P>
<P>
   When Miles Davis was riding high in the 1960s, he commented to
Dan Morgenstern of the Rutgers Institute for Jazz Studies, ``You
can't play anything on the horn that Louis hasn't played.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1939-40, RCA Victor, Columbia and Decca Records were all
instituting reissue programs, generating interest in the jazz
background of swing music for younger buyers, as well as alerting
budding trumpet stars to the Armstrong genius.
</P>
<P>
   And he was a genius. No one had played as brilliantly nor
improvised as wondrously as Armstrong _ at least on recordings, or
in listeners' memories. From the beginning, Armstrong injected
blues harmonies, rhythmic swing and unbelievably complex melodic
improvisations into every solo.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia, under the guidance of George Avakian, started its Hot
Jazz Classics series with a four-disc (78 rpm) album set drawn from
Armstrong's earliest sessions _ the Hot Five and Hot Seven
recordings from 1925 to 1927. The public response was astonishing.
We had never heard trumpet playing like this; the swing trumpeters
were right _ Louis was ``the one.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's career began when he headed north from New Orleans
in 1923 to join King Oliver's band, with whom he stayed until
spring 1924. The Creole Jazz Band recorded a couple of dozen sides,
acoustically (into a horn) for four labels. He then went to New
York, taking the solo cornet chair with Fletcher Henderson's
Roseland Ballroom orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of his new wife, pianist Lil Hardin, he learned to
read music. His solos with Henderson are generally magnificent.
``We laughed at the way Louis looked when he arrived in New York,''
said drummer Kaiser Marshall. But after we heard one solo we all
shut up.''
</P>
<P>
   For three years starting in November 1925, Armstrong played in
bands large and small in Chicago and recorded extensively with his
Hot Five and Hot Seven groups, as well as with many blues singers,
from Bessie Smith and Ma Rainey to Sippie Wallace, Chippie Hill and
others.
</P>
<P>
   This was Armstrong's grandest era, during which he shifted from
cornet to trumpet and changed his recording group's complement
(added a sax or two, brought in younger, brighter guys like Earl
Hines). Following the Hines-Armstrong groups, Armstrong began
fronting big bands (one for each coast) and became a full-fledged
band leader.
</P>
<P>
   The body of work he recorded between 1925 and 1931 constitutes
the finest era in Armstrong's life; almost all of his recordings
from that era are now reissued in a four-CD set, titled ``Louis
Armstrong: The Complete Hot Five and Hot Seven Recordings'' on the
Columbia/Legacy label.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's trumpet is so inspired and played with such power,
that others in the Hot Five and Hot Seven (Kid Ory, Johnny Dodds)
have trouble keeping up. On ``Droppin' Shucks'' and ``Who'sit,''
Armstrong is off on a trumpet tear seldom heard on records;
incredible stuff. He played a slide-whistle solo on the latter.
</P>
<P>
   Included among the set's 89 tracks are ``Big Butter and Egg
Man,'' a great Armstrong vocal; ``Skid-Dat-De Dat,'' a marvelous
blues; ``Potato Head Blues,'' ``West End Blues'' (the pair
considered Armstrong's all-time greatest), ``New Orleans Stomp''
from a rare session, ``Beau Koo Jack'' _ unbelievable duet choruses
by Armstrong and Hines, trumpet and piano _ and ``Basin Street
Blues,'' ``Weather Bird'' (Hines and Armstrong duet) and ``Knockin'
A Jug,'' a famous session with Armstrong and trombonist Jack
Teagarden; the two joined again, after World War II, in the
Armstrong All-Star band.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong gigged around the East Coast (especially New York) in
1929-30, usually fronting a big band. There were microphones, now,
and he was singing more frequently in public performances. For
nearly a year he headlined with Les Hite's Los Angeles band at
Sebastian's Cotton Club in Los Angeles, and was recorded,
beautifully, playing and singing, ``I'm Confessin','' ``Shine,''
``If I Could Be With You One Hour Tonight,'' ``Sweethearts on
Parade'' and other classics.
</P>
<P>
   Vibist Lionel Hampton, 91 and still at it, ends each band set
with the now familiar ``What a Wonderful World,'' which Armstrong
recorded in 1970, a year before his death. In a workshop session at
the Lionel Hampton Jazz Festival in Moscow, Idaho, a young music
student commented, ``You sing `Wonderful World' just the way Louis
Armstrong did.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton chuckled and answered, ``Well, that's a compliment. Of
course I sound like Louis _ I heard him sing night after night when
I played drums (and learned how to play the vibes) with his band in
Los Angeles a number of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seventy years ago every trumpeter and every singer tried to
sound like Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the only one who mattered; still is, really.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
