<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 14:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2636 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-CONGRESS-CLEANCAR-NNS     09-13 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-CLEANCAR-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESCUE IN WORKS FOR CLEAN-CAR PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Wednesday, Sept. 13, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-212-499-3401; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(at)nytimes.com.)  
 By MIKE MAGNER  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After a near-fatal crash in Congress, a $2.5
billion federal program to develop fuel-efficient vehicles is
getting back on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Many members of the House of Representatives who voted to kill
the program in June have apparently been convinced that the
Partnership for a New Generation of Vehicles is not a form of aid
to automakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is in the national interest,'' said U.S. Rep. Fred Upton,
R-Mich., one of a host of Michigan lawmakers fighting to maintain
funding for the partnership in the waning weeks of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists who scorn the effort to build
80-miles-per-gallon cars concede that the auto industry and the
Clinton administration have won over enough House members to
reverse a 214-211 vote to end the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the fix is in,'' said Dan Becker, director of the
Sierra Club's global warming and energy project. The House is now
likely to go along with a Senate bill providing $140 million for
the partnership next year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Becker and other environmentalists argue that U.S. automakers
should be developing fuel-efficient vehicles without government
help.
</P>
<P>
   Two Japanese companies, Toyota and Honda, already have cars on
the U.S. market that get between 60 and 70 mpg, while American
makers promote pickups and sport-utility vehicles that average less
than 20 mpg, Becker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's time to pull the plug because it's really a
scam,'' he said of the partnership. ``The auto industry has spent a
billion and a half dollars of taxpayer money and come up with three
cars.''
</P>
<P>
   Becker was referring to three ``concept cars'' developed through
the partnership that were unveiled in March by General Motors
Corp., Ford Motor Co. and DaimlerChrysler AG.
</P>
<P>
   The GM Precept, the Ford Prodigy and the Dodge ESX3 each get
about 80 mpg from their highly efficient diesel-fueled engines, but
the cars are still too expensive for the mass market.
DaimlerChrysler estimates the Dodge ESX3 would cost about $7,500
more than the comparably sized Dodge Intrepid, and questions
whether people would pay that much just for better gas mileage.
</P>
<P>
   The main goal of the Partnership for a New Generation of
Vehicles, launched by President Clinton and the three U.S.
automakers in 1993, is to have a prototype for an affordable 80-mpg
family car by 2004.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still a lot more work to be done,'' said Lee Sechler,
spokesman for the U.S. Council for Automotive Research, which
manages the industry's side of the partnership for GM, Ford and
DaimlerChrysler.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept vehicles demonstrate there's technology out there
to come up with this car, but the next step is to put it into mass
production,'' Sechler said. ``That requires both government and
industry working together.''
</P>
<P>
   When the House voted to end funding for the program in June,
many members thought the automakers had simply received $1.25
billion in federal grants to produce the concept cars, said Cary
Gravatt, the government's partnership director.
</P>
<P>
   GM, Ford and DaimlerChrysler actually spent about $1.25 billion
of their own money developing the cars, while the federal funds
went for research by government labs, universities and hundreds of
automotive suppliers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the congressmen said they didn't realize that,''
Gravatt said. ``Many of them said, `We thought it all went to the
Big Three.'''
</P>
<P>
   Congressional leaders must now work out a compromise between the
House bill, which cuts money for the partnership, and the Senate
bill, which provides $140 million for the fiscal year starting Oct.
1.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is at the end of the day, the funding will be
restored,'' said Upton. ``There's strong support for it. With the
spike in gas prices we had this summer, we ought to do something to
help the industry develop fuel-efficient cars.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-00 1448EDT &QL; 
