</P>
<P>
   CHASE-REACT (Undated) _ How employees and others are reacting.
Looking at the fear of layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   POWER-DEREG (Undated) _ After a 1997 power shortage, Wisconsin
Electric began to support a go-slow approach to deregulation,
building in an extra margin of reliable power before encouraging
the state to remove its decades-old grip on the electricity
industry. Lately, the rest of the country has been drawing the same
conclusion. Just like Wisconsin, several other states have lost
their early faith in deregulation as surging consumer demand has
outstripped the supply of electricity, and regulators and utilities
scramble to cope with price volatility and power outages. Still,
few experts expect a return to the days of strict government
control. A world where various power generators compete openly to
provide electricity at market prices still offers the prospect of
both lower costs for business and consumers and higher profits for
utilities than is possible under the traditional, more inefficient
regulated system. But getting to that promised land is proving far
more difficult than expected. ``Deregulation was definitely
oversold to consumers by many people,'' one expert says. By Neela
Banerjee.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   JANUS-FUND (Undated) _ Janus Capital says it has closed its $50
billion Janus Fund to new investors and has filed a registration
statement with the Securities and Exchange Commission for a new
fund.
</P>
<P>
   INKTOMI-FASTFORWARD (Undated) _ Inktomi is buying FastForward
Networks, a developer of technology that distributes and manages
live online broadcasts, in a $1.3 billion deal. By Lawrence M.
Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA-BANKS (Singapore) _ Efforts by Malaysia to strengthen
its banking system by forcing its 54 financial institutions to
merge into just 10 appear to be backfiring, as concerns about
government interference rekindle doubts about the industry's health
and about the risks of investing in the country. By Wayne Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   LATIMES-LAYOFFS (Undated) _ The Los Angeles Times lays off 150
to 200 editorial employees. By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   ECONSCENE (Undated) _ The Economic Scene column.
</P>
<P>
