<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2702 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-GILL-NEWS-HNS &LR;      09-13 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GILL-NEWS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CALIFORNIA RESTRICTS USE OF GILL-NET FISHING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JANE KAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In an attempt to stop the drowning deaths of
more than a hundred marine mammals and thousands of seabirds a
year, California on Wednesday began restricting gill-net fishing
along a vast stretch of the Central Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Fishermen set the nets to catch halibut but also entrap
threatened otters and common murres at numbers high enough to
impede the recovery of their populations, the state Fish and Game
Department said in a preliminary order.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers of common murre being drowned were high enough to
threaten the viability of the Central Coast population,'' said
David Bunn, deputy director of the agency. ``The number of otters
are substantially below their historic numbers, and there is
concern that the gill-net fishery is hindering their recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   The California sea otter population had been dropping over four
years, only to rise slightly in the spring count to 2,377. Disease,
pollutants, killing by sharks and fishermen and entrapment in
fishing gear are suspected in the decline.
</P>
<P>
   Common murres, down to 100,000 from 1 million on the Farallon
Islands 200 years ago, have been killed in the last decades by oil
spills and gill nets.
</P>
<P>
   Seabirds such as the common murre, otters and other marine
mammals forage for food in the salmon zones where fishermen set
halibut nets: near shore rich with fish, shellfish and other sea
life.
</P>
<P>
   Over a year, National Marine Fisheries Service inspectors
monitored a quarter of the trips made by the 15 halibut boats that
use gill nets in Central California.
</P>
<P>
   According to estimates based on the data from the on-board
observer program, more than 5,200 common murres, 120 harbor
porpoises and at least one otter would be killed in a year by the
gill nets set for halibut in the Monterey Bay region alone.
</P>
<P>
   The observers also found elephant seals, harbor seals and
California sea lions drowned in the nets.
</P>
<P>
   The state's order restricts halibut fishermen from setting nets
shallower than 60 fathoms, or 360 feet, from Point Reyes to Carmel
and in Santa Barbara County from Point Sal to Point Arguello.
</P>
<P>
   The order will be in effect for 120 days while the department
takes public comment. The department is expected to make the order
permanent.
</P>
<P>
   Hung from buoys and anchored to the sea floor, the 10-foot-high
nylon gill nets with 8 1/2-inch mesh stretch tautly for about 1,800
feet. They earn their name by entangling big fish around the gills.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the regulations have restricted gill nets to a depth
no shallower than 30 fathoms, or 180 feet along most of California.
There had been no restrictions for the 20-mile section of Santa
Barbara County between Point Sal and Point Arguello, which is
frequented by a spreading population of otters.
</P>
<P>
   The new restriction most likely will put an end to halibut
fishing in California with gill nets, which represents about 6
percent of the state's halibut fishing, because to get the nets
that deep virtually would push the boats out of the fish's
territory. Most halibut are caught commercially by trawlers, which
drag nets in deeper waters, and by hook and line.
</P>
<P>
   For years coastal environmental groups such as Friends of the
Sea Otters, Center for Marine Conservation and Save Our Shores have
sought an end to the use of gill nets.
</P>
<P>
   In April, the Center for Biological Diversity in Oakland filed a
notice of intent to sue if the state didn't control the gill nets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very grateful to the director of Fish and Game for
giving the sea otter additional protection on the Central Coast and
closing a gap where the otter had no protection at all,'' said
Carol Fulton Yates, consultant to Friends of the Sea Otter in Santa
Cruz. ``We need to continue monitoring the areas where the gill
nets are still allowed to be set to be sure that they are not
drowning marine birds and animals.``
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
