<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2709 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-VOTING-HISTORY-NNS &LR;      09-13 1768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOTING-HISTORY-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTING RIGHTS IN U.S. HAVE MOVED IN FITS AND STARTS 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Wednesday, Sept. 13, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-212-499-3401; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(at)nytimes.com.)  
 Art Advisory: With three photos, of a 1965 Freedom Marcher in
Alabama (NNS1), a 19th century cartoon depicting an Indian
unwelcome at the polls (NNS2), and opponents of women's suffrage in
about 1915 (NNS3). 
 By DELIA M. RIOS  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The schoolbook version of voting rights history leaves the
impression that it was practically a pre-ordained march that
brought us from a time when only propertied white men could vote to
today, when almost all adult citizens can.
</P>
<P>
   So as another presidential election approaches, and with it the
hand-wringing over historic low voter turnouts, it is worth knowing
that it was not that simple.
</P>
<P>
   Just beneath the myth is a nuanced and often inspiring story of
how Americans have taken the Declaration of Independence at its
word _ that governments derive ``their just Powers from the Consent
of the Governed.'' It reveals the great difficulty with which the
United States evolved into the democracy that we know _ not so much
in that imagined march forward, but in fits and starts.
</P>
<P>
   Voting rights, in fact, have been bitterly contested for most of
our history. Not only that, they have been won and lost, and then
won again.
</P>
<P>
   As generations of Americans thrashed out the question of who
could vote, they went right to the core of what it means to be a
citizen and what rights and obligations that demands. Even today,
voting restrictions keep felons and residents who are not citizens
from the polling booths _ vestiges of what was once a long list of
obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   ``History rarely moves in simple, straight lines, and the
history of suffrage is no exception,'' Alexander Keyssar observed
in his just-published book, ``The Right to Vote: The Contested
History of Democracy in the United States'' (Basic Books).
</P>
<P>
   The historical record shows that New Jersey women could vote
until 1807, and then lost that right until a 1920 constitutional
amendment gave all women the vote. Blacks in some Northern states
could vote early in the 19th century until they, too, lost that
right as the nation moved toward civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Immigrants, for a time, were enfranchised as states competed to
attract them to sparsely populated areas. If they'd lived in the
United States for two years and declared their intent to become
citizens, they could vote. But they grew too numerous by 1900, and
suddenly were a political threat.
</P>
<P>
   And although the 15th Amendment in 1870 declared that race could
not infringe on voting rights, it took the Voting Rights Act of
1965 to guarantee that Southern blacks could freely exercise the
vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``A grant of suffrage was not forever,'' said Benjamin Ginsberg,
director of the Johns Hopkins Center for the Study of American
Government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shouldn't be sanguine about this,'' he believes, even now.
</P>
<P>
   Voting rights history is really a chronicle of a people
struggling to gain a foothold on democracy, whether it was Chinese
immigrants on the West Coast, African-Americans in the North and
South, the Irish in the Northeast, eastern and southern European
immigrants in the Midwest and Southwest, or the nation's women.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia University historian Eric Foner makes the case that
those who forced the broadening of American democracy are as much
``authors of the notion of freedom'' as the Founding Fathers. The
founders may have spoken loftily of having a voice in one's
government. But it was a voice that determined opponents, over two
centuries, tried to mute.
</P>
<P>
   This tension between America's promise and its reality was
articulated more than 100 years ago by a Massachusetts shoemaker
and future vice president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us give to all citizens equal rights, and then protect
everybody in the United States in the exercise of those rights,''
Henry Wilson, then a U.S. senator, argued during congressional
debates over the 15th Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we do that,'' Wilson warned, ``we are in a false
position, an illogical position _ a position that cannot be
defended.''
</P>
<P>
   As Keyssar recounted, the opportunity existed at that moment to
write a broader law, one upholding voting rights without regard not
only to race, but to ``nativity, property, education or creed.''
Women would still have been excluded.
</P>
<P>
   It is reasonable to assume, for most of us who are not
constitutional scholars, that an explicit right to vote can be
found somewhere in the U.S. Constitution. But for political reasons
_ primarily to ensure the survival of the Constitution itself _ the
determination of voting rights was left to the states. As British
colonies, they had devised their own voting rules, and they were
loathe to lose that authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Constitution adopted in 1787 left the federal government
without any clear power or mechanism, other than through
constitutional amendment, to institute a national conception of
voting rights, to express a national vision of democracy,'' wrote
Keyssar, a professor of history and public policy at Duke
University.
</P>
<P>
   And, he concluded, that was ``a fact that was to have
significant repercussions for almost two centuries.''
</P>
<P>
   The new country inherited a British notion that adult men who
owned property were the only worthy guardians of the vote. The
assumption was that their property gave them a stake in civic
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Franklin famously poked fun at that:
</P>
<P>
   ``Today a man owns a jackass worth fifty dollars and he is
entitled to vote; but before the next election the jackass dies.
... Now gentlemen, pray inform me, in whom is the right of
suffrage? In the man or in the jackass?''
</P>
<P>
   But a broader voting rights debate soon took shape.
</P>
<P>
   If the ``governed'' were to give their ``consent,'' just who was
going to participate in this new representative government? And was
voting a natural right or a privilege? The answers would determine
how broad or how limited the electorate would be.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   In compiling his history, Keyssar asked a fundamental question.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is by no means self-evident, as one looks at modern
history, that individuals who possess political power will (or can
be expected to) share that power with others, millions of others,''
he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did it happen, and why did the right to vote expand at
certain times and certain places, while contracting in others?''
</P>
<P>
   The arguments over nearly 200 years against this or that group
revealed significant and deeply ingrained attitudes. Were
immigrants intelligent enough to vote? Would the act of voting
degrade women and sully them with politics? Did the illiterate _
white or black _ pose a danger to the nation's political life? Did
Native Americans qualify as citizens if they ``adopted the habits
of civilized life?''
</P>
<P>
   Political interests always were at stake.
</P>
<P>
   That was true when states sought to attract immigrants with the
vote. And, Johns Hopkins' Ginsberg argues, it was true during the
Vietnam War. However much 18-year-olds may have wanted the vote
then, Ginsberg said that in giving it to them, Democrats hoped to
get the youth vote and Republicans hoped the kids would just stop
demonstrating.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Any number of social forces, including war and race, played
pivotal roles in whether the vote was expanded.
</P>
<P>
   Revolutionary fervor, for one, resulted in freed blacks getting
the vote in North Carolina, Massachusetts, New York, Pennsylvania,
Maryland and Vermont. And voting prohibitions against Roman
Catholics and Jews were dropped.
</P>
<P>
   The abolitionist movement against slavery that began gaining
force in the early 19th century encouraged hopes of an even broader
democracy. It led to an alliance of African-American abolitionists
and progressive women, many of whom would take leadership roles in
the women's suffrage movement that emerged at mid-century. But even
before they won the vote in 1920, as Kevin Mattson of the Walt
Whitman Center for the Culture and Politics of Democracy reminds
us, women organized and led social movements that thrust them into
civic and political life. Getting the vote was an ardous process of
some 70 years.
</P>
<P>
   And there were history's unintended consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Property and tax requirements were dropped in Northern and
Southern states before the large-scale immigration of the 19th
century and before it was conceivable that slavery would be
abolished. Suddenly there was a large working class, especially
visible in growing industrial centers, that changed the face of
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is this enormous kind of `oops' North and South,''
Keyssar said.
</P>
<P>
   Any number of voting restrictions from Oregon to Massachusetts
followed to limit the immigrant vote. And in the South, newly
imposed restrictions from literacy tests to ``good character''
tests would dilute the voting power of blacks deep into the 20th
century.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout, however, it is remarkable how Americans always have
taken the rhetoric of the Revolutionary War at face value. And that
was especially evident during wartime. From the Revolution through
Vietnam, Americans have realized that they could not ask their
soldiers to fight their wars and then deny them the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Voting restrictions, for example, kept many Native Americans
from voting as late as the 1940s, even though Congress had granted
all Indians citizenship in 1924. In part because of the protests of
Native American World War II veterans, those restrictions were
dropped.
</P>
<P>
   There is a particularly moving passage in Keyssar's book of
Virginians ``mustering in'' for service during the War of 1812. As
they did so, they lodged an eloquent protest by indicating whether
they could vote. Of 1,000 Shenandoah men, in one mustering, 700
could not. And Keyssar writes of how African-American veterans of
the Civil War paraded in jubiliation with their wives after they
had won the vote with the 15th Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who could not vote,'' Keyssar explained, ``were very
aware that they couldn't, and that they were excluded and that they
were not full citizens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
