<TEXT>
<P>
   Sports stories from The New York Times News Service for
 &UR; THURSDAY &LR; , Sept. 14.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-FREEMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The Times column on the
collapse of the old order in the N.F.L., with Dallas, Green Bay and
San Francisco all 0-2 and giving every sign that they will struggle
mightily this season. By Mike Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKS-JAYS (New York) _ Toronto at the Yankees, 7:05 p.m.
EDT start. By Jack Curry.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-METS-BREWERS (New York) _ Milwaukee at the Mets, 1 p.m. EDT
start. By Murray Chass.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OLYMPICS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SOC-MEN (Canberra, Australia) _ Brad Friedel remembers the
United States soccer team that went to the Summer Games in
Barcelona, Spain, eight years ago, ``two professionals on the
entire team,'' he recalled. This time it is different. The United
States started 10 professionals and one very impressive college
forward, Conor Casey, and outplayed the Czech Republic almost all
the way in a 2-2 tie tonight in the opening round of the Summer
Games tournament. By George Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-BOX-U.S. (Sydney, Australia) _ A look at the U.S. team and
its overall chances for medals, gold and otherwise, as well as who
these fighters are. By Bill Pennington.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-HOST-TEAM (Sydney, Australia) _ After failing to win even
one gold medal in the 1976 Montreal Games, an embarrassed Australia
set upon a plan to groom sports champions. The model? The former
East Germany, which had one of the world's best sports programs
with a population comparable to Australia. So the Aussies set up a
system of state-sponsored sports institutes, and the result is a
top-level Olympic team that may place as high as fourth or fifth in
the overall medal count, with marvelous athletes like Michellie
Jones and Ian Thorpe and strong teams like the Hockeyroos and the
women's softball squad. By Christopher Clarey.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other sports
stories from our partners: The Boston Globe, Cox News Service,
Hearst News Service, The Arizona Republic, Kansas City Star, Fort
Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles Daily News, San Francisco
Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
