<HEADER>
A2731 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-OLY-SAMARANCH-HNS &LR;      09-13 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SAMARANCH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LONGTIME OLYMPIC FIGURE HOPES FOR HIS OWN MEDAL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ For a man who was a confirmed fascist, at
least politically, much earlier in his life, Juan Antonio Samaranch
has become an old softie as he nears octogenarian status.
</P>
<P>
   The man credited with saving the Olympic movement following
successive boycotts of the Games in 1976, 1980 and 1984 is
flourishing in his role as ambassador to the world of sports.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch, who as a youth was a supporter of Francisco Franco in
Spain, has persuaded North and South Koreas to march under one flag
in Friday's Opening Ceremonies at Olympic Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Although there has been a softening of ideologies between the
two Koreas in recent months, filing into Olympic Stadium under the
same flag and wearing common uniforms is a significant gesture.
</P>
<P>
   It hardly matters that once competition begins Saturday the two
Koreas will go their separate ways in the uniforms of their
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch, 79, congratulated North Korea and South Korea for
uniting under the Olympic ideal of ``friendship, solidarity and
peace.''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Peace has been in short supply in turbulent East Timor, the
former Portuguese colony that Indonesia invaded in 1975. East Timor
recently declared its independence from Indonesia but has paid a
severe price for it in reprisals from Indonesian militias.
</P>
<P>
   East Timor's independence is so recent it is not yet a
full-fledged member of the International Olympic Committee.
Nevertheless, Samaranch, president of the IOC, invited four East
Timorese athletes to compete in Sydney as independent athletes.
</P>
<P>
   The four _ a boxer, a weightlifter and two marathon runners _
will wear plain white uniforms bearing the familiar five-ring
Olympic logo. They are the second group of independent athletes to
compete in an Olympic event.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   There's more peace on Earth and good will to men and women, at
least as regards Sydney 2000. A mixed group of Muslims, Serbs and
Croats will compete here under the flag of Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
   For Samaranch and the IOC, extending the olive branch to the
world's athletes means an ever-expanding roster of countries in the
Olympic Games. On Friday, 199 nations, some with delegations as
small as two or three and others as large as several hundred, are
expected to march into Sydney's 110,000-seat Olympic Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Not counting East Timor, of course. Its time will come as an IOC
member, possibly as soon as Athens in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   In a land as biologically diverse as Australia, from blistering
stretches of near complete desolation in the outback to rich
tropical rain forests in the north, Sydney is promoting the 2000
Olympics as the ``Green Games.''
</P>
<P>
   In the same sense, including more and more of the world's people
in the pursuit of competition and cooperation adds to the human
diversity of Sydney 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Before he steps down as head of the IOC, Samaranch may yet
receive his personal gold medal in the form of a Nobel Peace Prize.
He's longed for the prize for many years, yet his work furthering
the ideal of the Olympic Games does not come off as self-serving.
</P>
<P>
   From fascist youth to aging benefactor, the man has made quite a
transition in his life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
