<HEADER>
A2745 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX     09-13 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM PHILADELPHIA, BUTTER CAKES TO LOVE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BEVERLY BUNDY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dianne Fox e-mailed, looking for a recipe for her husband's
birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband is originally from Philadelphia. Whenever we visit
his family, the first food he wants is butter cake. It's not cake
as most people think of cake _ it's like a coffee cake with a
butter and sugar mixture on top.''
</P>
<P>
   And _ through the wonders of the Internet and
www.kitchenlink.com _ here are two versions of the ``cake.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA BUTTER CAKE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8-10
</P>
<P>
   2 medium white potatoes
</P>
<P>
   2 packages active dry yeast (or crumbled yeast cakes)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup warm water
</P>
<P>
   1 cup plus 1 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup water from cooked potatoes
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs, well-beaten
</P>
<P>
   Enough flour to make a soft dough (about 3 1/2 cups)
</P>
<P>
   Topping:
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup flour
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups extra-fine sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   Milk
</P>
<P>
   Scrub and peel potatoes; place in small saucepan. Cover
generously with water and boil rapidly until potatoes are very
tender. Drain, saving water. You will need 3/4 cup potato water. If
you do not have enough, add hot water to make that amount. Put
potatoes through a ricer. Dissolve yeast in 1/4 cup warm water to
which 1 teaspoon sugar has been added. Beat butter to cream it. A
little at a time, beat in remaining cup sugar and salt, then eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Stir the 3/4 cup potato water into mashed potatoes, then add to
egg mixture. Stir in yeast mixture. When well-mixed, add 1 cup
flour, beating constantly. Do not spare the beating. Add the second
and third cups of flour the same way, small amounts at a time. Be
sure to beat hard to make the gluten in the flour wake up, and try
not to have to add that last half cup of flour. The dough should
not be too stiff.
</P>
<P>
   Place a damp cloth (not wet, just damp) over bowl with dough and
let rise. If you refrigerate it during this rest period, it will
become firmer and still will rise to double in bulk, but it will
take a little longer. It is far better to allow a little more time
for the rising than to try to stiffen the dough with extra flour.
</P>
<P>
   Generously butter a 9-by-13-inch pan. When dough has doubled,
thump it down and turn it out onto lightly floured surface.
Sprinkle top lightly with flour and roll out with floured rolling
pin to a little more than 1/2 inch thickness and as close to the
rectangular shape of the pan as you can. Place it in pan, punching
it out toward sides and corners. Cover and let rise in warm place
out of drafts (the unheated oven is about the best place for this
in most kitchens) until doubled.
</P>
<P>
   To make topping: Beat butter to cream it. Sift together flour
and sugar, a little at a time; beat into butter mixture. Add eggs,
one at a time, beating each in thoroughly. By teaspoonfuls, add
enough milk to make mixture the right consistency to spread (this
could require 3 or 4 tablespoons of milk, but don't get it too
runny). Gently spread over risen dough. This makes a large coffee
cake-type of cake. The topping melts into it as it bakes, and the
top should be crisp but very moist and ``gooey'' underneath.
</P>
<P>
   Spread with topping and bake in a 350-degree oven for 35 to 40
minutes until done. Cool in pan before cutting.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 591 calories, 21 grams fat, 94
grams carbohydrates, 6 grams protein, 135 milligrams cholesterol,
453 milligrams sodium, 32 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   REAL PHILADELPHIA BUTTER CAKE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8-10
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup vegetable shortening
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg
</P>
<P>
   1 envelope active dry yeast
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup warm milk
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups flour
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   Topping:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound (2 sticks) unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup flour
</P>
<P>
   2 cups extra-fine sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 extra-large eggs
</P>
<P>
   4-5 tablespoons milk
</P>
<P>
   Prepare dough by mixing sugar with shortening and salt. Add egg
and beat with mixer 1 minute. Dissolve yeast in warm milk. Add
flour, then yeast-milk mixture and vanilla to sugar mix. Mix 3
minutes with dough hook or by hand. Turn onto floured board; knead
1 minute. Place in a lightly greased bowl, cover with a towel and
set in a warm place to rise for 1 hour, or until doubled.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, prepare topping. Cream butter, mix together flour and
sugar. Gradually beat sugar mixture into butter. Add eggs, one at a
time, beating well after each. By the teaspoonful, add milk to
bring mixture to an easy spreading consistency, being careful not
to make it too runny. Divide dough in two pieces. Roll or pat to
fit two well-greased 8-inch-square pans, or one 9-by-13-inch pan
(two is best). Crimp edges halfway up pan to hold topping. When
dough is spread, prick well with a fork to prevent bubbling. Divide
topping between pans, spread over the dough.
</P>
<P>
   Let cakes sit for 20 minutes. Bake at 375 degrees for 30 minutes
or until done. Do not overbake. Topping will be crusty but gooey.
Let cool before cutting.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 516 calories, 28 grams fat, 59
grams carbohydrates, 8 grams protein, 170 milligrams cholesterol,
107 milligrams sodium, 48 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Request:
</P>
<P>
   Lorraine Rose of Fort Worth would like a recipe for peanut
butter and banana pie.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or e-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-00 1533EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000913.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2758 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-HELEN-THOMAS-HNS &LR;      09-13 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HELEN-THOMAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NIXON'S BETRAYAL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By HELEN THOMAS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Can anything more shocking be added to former
President Richard Nixon's tragic legacy?
</P>
<P>
   Well, try this.
</P>
<P>
   In a new book, ``The Arrogance of Power, The Secret World of
Richard Nixon,'' author Anthony Summers charges that Nixon
deliberately sabotaged President Lyndon Johnson's attempt to win
South Vietnam's approval of a bombing halt in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Summers says that in October of that year, as the presidential
race neared an end, a desperate Nixon feared that his rival, Vice
President Hubert Humphrey, would win if Johnson's peace initiatives
gained acceptance in the unpopular war. A bombing halt would have
paved the way for talks with Hanoi.
</P>
<P>
   In Summers' account _ which has been corroborated by Harry
Middleton, the librarian at the LBJ presidential Library in Austin,
Texas _ Nixon enlisted the help of Anna Chennault, widow of Gen.
Claire Chennalt, who headed the famed Flying Tigers in World War
II.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon persuaded her to be his emissary to the government of
South Vietnamese President Nguyen Van Thieu. She frequently
contacted the South Vietnamese ambassador in Washington that fall
and even traveled to Saigon at Nixon's suggestion to personally
urge Thieu to reject Johnson's bid for his support to stop the
bombing of Hanoi.
</P>
<P>
   Her telephone calls to the South Vietnamese officials were
tapped by the FBI, and the CIA also kept track of her clandestine
activities.
</P>
<P>
   Thieu ultimately balked at Johnson's peace gesture, and Summers
speculated that he probably would have done so even without
Chennault's pleas. But Summers adds, ``The fact that Nixon
intervened, though, deliberately flouting the efforts of American
officials, was indefensible.''
</P>
<P>
   Anything to win!
</P>
<P>
   Nixon did win the election by a hair, 43.4 percent to Humphrey's
42.7 percent. But thousands more Americans and South Vietnamese
died and thousands more were wounded in the war under Nixon ``in
the name of the quest for an honorable peace,'' Summers writes.
</P>
<P>
   As the war dragged on, the bitter protests over the conflict
tore the country apart and shattered the people's faith in the
government. Sen. George Aiken, R-Vt., gave Nixon the same advice
that he had given Johnson: ``Declare a victory and leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, neither president would heed Aiken's sage advice.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1968 returns were in and his victory was sealed, Nixon
thanked Chennault effusively ``for her help in the election,''
Summers wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Chennault told Nixon curtly: ``I've paid dearly for it.'' Nixon
responded ``Yes, I appreciate that. You're a good soldier.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the FBI and the CIA, Johnson knew all about Nixon's
intrigues and apparently wrestled with the question of whether to
blow the whistle on his diabolical behavior. In the end, Johnson
remained silent. He apparently feared that if he exposed Nixon,
some national security operations would have to be revealed.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson knew that unless he laid out the evidence in detail
against Nixon, the accusation would be seen as a political ploy by
the Democrats to win the election. Johnson did inform Humphrey and
the late Defense Secretary Clark Clifford, both of whom decided
that a revelation of Nixon's treachery would damage national
security.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agreed with Johnson's decision. Bob Hardesty, a
Johnson speechwriter and later president of Southwest Texas State
University, LBJ's alma mater, dissented. He apparently thought the
country would have fared better if Nixon's betrayal had been
revealed during the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   I think he's right. The war, unwinnable short of dropping the
nuclear bomb, might have ended sooner. Thousands more Americans
might be alive today. And Nixon might have lost the election. The
nation then would have been spared the anguish of the Watergate
scandal when Nixon again broke laws in his effort to win reelection
in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   At one point during the 1968 campaign, Johnson summoned Nixon to
the Oval Office. I thought at the time it was extraordinary for the
president to do that since he was supporting Humphrey's candidacy.
The purpose of the meeting was not announced. We reporters at the
White House suspected it had something to do with national
security, but no official would say anything.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's refusal to unmask Nixon will be debated in the history
books. But that whole era could have been quite different if
Americans had been trusted with the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Thomas can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address helent(at)hearstdc.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
