<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2769 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-OLY-ATHLETES-SEX-TEX     09-13 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ATHLETES-SEX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S ANOTHER INSTANCE OF `GIVE THE AUDIENCE WHAT IT WANTS'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By DOUGLAS PERRY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Your typical female Olympian is far from a clothes horse. Check
out her closet and you'll find a lot of Banana Republic and Gap,
even Old Navy. Who's got time to worry about clothes when there's
training to do, right? She'll tell you that all she really needs
are her Nikes, a pair of sweats, and maybe a braided band to hold
back her hair.
</P>
<P>
   Except, of course, when she's dressing for a meet. That's where
the couture designers and makeup artists and image consultants come
in.
</P>
<P>
   In case you haven't noticed yet, high fashion has come to
Olympic sports _ although it's definitely not an attempt to lure
more female fans. The female swimmers now compete in sheer designer
suits that are fitted so tight that you unconsciously lean closer
to your TV set to see whether the seams are going to blow. Over on
the track, sprinters go all-out in colorful sports bras and teeny,
rump-hugging shorts.
</P>
<P>
   It's all about aerodynamics, they'll tell you _ and there's
something to that. (The men mostly wear the same garb, and Speedo's
new body suit is being credited with helping swimmers set world
records.)
</P>
<P>
   But with popular testosterone-fueled cable programs such as
``The Cindy Margolis Show'' and ``The Man Show'' raising viewer
expectations, it's more about meeting customer demand _ and making
sure that the Sydney Olympic Games are truly Must-See TV.
</P>
<P>
   All of which shows that, despite the progress that female
athletes have made in the 28 years since the landmark Title IX
ruling leveled the collegiate playing field between the sexes,
athletes and sports marketers still must face an indisputable fact:
To most men (who remain the chief consumers of sports), how women
look matters a lot more than how they play.
</P>
<P>
   The most visible example of this is Anna Kournikova. Lycos Inc.
reports that the Russian tennis star, who has yet to win a
professional tournament, is the most-searched-for athlete on the
Web, more than double the searches for Michael Jordan. During this
year's Wimbledon, where Kournikova lost in the second round, the
London Sun offered readers ``Kourna Corner,'' a daily page of
cleavage-exposing photographs of the unseeded player. When
Wimbledon isn't going on, the page is devoted to topless models.
</P>
<P>
   Tennis great Martina Navratilova recently lit into the
international tennis federation for encouraging such cheesecake
coverage, saying that it trivializes the players' abilities and
hard work _ and coarsens and degrades male attitudes toward female
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   But even among the sport's hard-core backers, such complaints
face opposition. Former Wimbledon champ Boris Becker, decrying
tennis' slipping TV ratings, has said that tennis ``needs more Anna
Kournikovas.''
</P>
<P>
   The International Olympic Committee, which has seen its ratings
fall, fully embraces this give-the-public-what-it-wants attitude.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the news media labeled Atlanta the ``Women's
Olympics,'' thanks to breakout stars such as Lisa Leslie. But
behind the scenes, it became known as the ``T&AMP;A Games'' because of
TV coverage that focused more on muscled thighs and heaving chests
than on the thrill of victory.
</P>
<P>
   The athletes are in step with the ``Zeitgeist.'' Well aware of
the importance of getting noticed in the increasingly crowded
Games, they are posing for calendars and magazines, all in the hope
of drawing viewers _ and maybe, just maybe, wowing them with more
than their pulchritude.
</P>
<P>
   As synchronized swimmer Nathalie Schneyder says, ``There's a lot
more to our sport than our butts.''
</P>
<P>
   That premise still brings giggles from many sports fans, but
athletes such as Schneyder can at least take comfort in knowing
that their doubters will be watching.
</P>
<P>
   (Douglas Perry is arts editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can reach him at (817) 390-7659 or at
dperry(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
