<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2774 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-APT-FUEL-COSTS-2TAKES     09-13 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APT-FUEL-COSTS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APARTMENT BUILDING MANAGERS CAN USE HIGH TECH TO REDUCE HEATING
BILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAY ROMANO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Homeowners who want to cut their heating costs
usually have several options: they can make sure all windows remain
closed when the heat is on; they can set the thermostat to whatever
temperature they want, day or night; they can avoid heating unused
rooms by selectively shutting off radiators or heat registers; and
they can make sweaters and thick socks mandatory attire for
occupants during the winter months.
</P>
<P>
   Owners and managers of multifamily buildings, on the other hand,
cannot avail themselves of such strategies because most states have
minimum temperature requirements that apply to every room in every
apartment in a building regardless of how individual tenants might
chose to dress.
</P>
<P>
   There are, however, a number of ways that multifamily building
owners can reduce heating bills _ sometimes significantly. A small
but noticeable savings may be obtained, for example, by ensuring
that the nozzle on the heating system's burner, a $5 part, is the
one recommended by the manufacturer. And savings of as much as 30
percent can be obtained by installing computer-controlled
temperature-sensing equipment on the furnace and at strategic
locations in the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the first signs of cold weather in most New York City
apartments is that it gets too hot in the apartment,'' said Richard
Cherry, president of Community Environmental Center, a
not-for-profit environmental services organization based in Long
Island City. ``That is because superintendents will usually pile on
the heat in their buildings to avoid complaints from tenants.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Cherry said, since the heating system in most
multifamily buildings is controlled by a heat-timer _ which turns
the system on and off for preset periods of time _ the most common
strategy superintendents use to determine whether there is
sufficient heat in the building is to keep the furnace running
until no one complains. That, however, often results in a huge
waste of fuel oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that the average daytime temperature in most
apartment buildings is between 78 and 80 degrees,'' he said. ``And
as excusable as this may have been when heating oil was 30 cents a
gallon, at $1 or more a gallon it's almost criminal.''
</P>
<P>
   One way to avoid overheating a multiunit building, Cherry said,
is to install Community Environmental Center's Total Energy
Management System. The system, he said, uses a control unit in the
boiler room to receive a constant stream of information from
sensors installed on the boiler or furnace itself and throughout
the building.
</P>
<P>
   The information provided by the sensors is analyzed by the
control unit, which then determines the heating needs and the
optimum time to run the furnace or boiler.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very similar to having a thermostatically controlled
building,'' he said, adding that information about the heating
system _ as well as reports of existing trouble or potential
malfunctions _ can be sent to superintendents and off-site managers
through a dial-up connection and computer.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of the Total Energy Management System, which includes a
comprehensive buildingwide heating-system analysis, would range
between $17,000 and $22,000 for most buildings, depending on the
size, Cherry said. ``We offer a money-back guarantee if a building
owner doesn't see a 10 percent reduction in fuel costs over the
previous year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A less expensive heating system add-on that comes with a similar
money-back guarantee is MicroTherm, a product manufactured in
Manchester, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Cocke, a Manhattan-based agent for the SNS Energy
Distribution Corp., a company in Amityville, N.Y., that sells the
product in the United States, explained that MicroTherm is a
``microprocessor in a box'' connected to the timing device that
controls the on-off cycle of the boiler or furnace. Using a sensor
that detects the temperature of water returning to the furnace
after it has made its way through radiators in the building, the
MicroTherm determines the optimum on-off cycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It acts as the gatekeeper for the burner control circuit,''
Cocke said, explaining that rather than allow the furnace or boiler
to cycle on and off solely in accordance with a preset time
schedule, the MicroTherm will either delay the start of a cycle or
extend a cycle in progress, based upon the temperature of the water
returning to the boiler.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's guaranteed to reduce your fuel consumption by 10
percent,'' Cocke said, adding that the installed cost of the
MicroTherm system in most buildings would be $3,250.
</P>
<P>
   Another high-tech way to monitor the efficiency of the heating
system in larger buildings is through the use of stand-alone
sensors that can be placed in apartments and common areas
throughout the building.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Baker, senior consultant for building automation of
Advanced Digital Internet, a Manhattan company, said his company is
now marketing a heating fuel efficiency system that uses wireless
digital thermometers installed at strategic locations in a building
to send signals to an on-site computer, which then transmits the
information over telephone lines to a Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``The information is then presented in a graphical format on our
Web site,'' Baker said, explaining that the information can be used
by a building's management to determine what areas of the building
are receiving too much or too little heat, and then remedy the
situation. He said Advanced Digital Internet _ which is also an
Internet service provider _ charges about $100 for each remote
thermometer and as little as $600 for the reporting device.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Henry Gifford, president of Gifford Fuel Savings Inc., a
Manhattan-based heating contractor, said he uses what he calls ``a
double-hung windowstat'' to determine whether a building is wasting
fuel by being unnecessarily overheated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stand in front of the building in the winter and see if
there are any open windows,'' Gifford said, explaining that in many
buildings, the amount of heat being supplied to the building is the
direct result of ``one cold tenant yelling for heat.''
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, Gifford said, cold apartments should be inspected
to determine whether there are any defective vents on steam
radiators, improperly installed radiators or radiators that have
been turned off or blocked by furniture or shelving. If there are
no obvious problems, he said, management might want to consider
installing larger radiators in the cold apartments.
</P>
<P>
   It is also possible _ with some heating systems _ to install
thermostats on individual radiators in each apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done this in a couple of 12-story buildings, and the
people are happy as clams,'' he said, adding that because of the
way heating systems work, thermostats can be efficiently used only
on hot-water heating systems and on ``two pipe'' steam systems that
have separate pipes for steam supply and return.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Gifford said, a building owner can ensure that his
heating plant is functioning as efficiently as possible for an
investment of as little as $5.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how much a nozzle costs for most burners,'' he said,
referring to the part of the burner that regulates combustion.
``And I have almost never seen the correct nozzle on an old
burner.''
</P>
<P>
   Gifford explained that while a burner will operate with a nozzle
that is a ``close fit,'' it will not operate at its peak
efficiency. Accordingly, he said, it is wise for building owners to
determine the correct nozzle for their heating system _ something
that can be done by calling the system manufacturer and providing
the model number of the system _ and then insisting that any
service contractor use the proper nozzle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
