<HEADLINE>
INTERIOR PAINT, THE OLD-FASHIONED WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before the introduction of modern latex and acrylic-based
paints, oil-based paint was the most common type of paint used for
commercial and residential applications. There was also another
type of paint that was made and used around the home, although
today few people have even heard of it. This was milk paint, and it
was made, as the name implies, with a milk base.
</P>
<P>
   It may seem strange to make paint out of milk, but milk has a
protein, called casein, that has strong adhesive properties (it was
often used as a glue) and which makes it an excellent binder for
paint pigments. It is manufactured by drying the curd of soured
skim milk. The powdered casein is then mixed with other ingredients
like pigment, clay, lime and water to create milk paint.
</P>
<P>
   Because it could be made easily by do-it-yourself homeowners,
milk paint was used extensively in homes built before the Civil
War. Decorators and painters interested in restoring or duplicating
period interiors use milk paint to recreate authentic colors and
textures. Another reason why milk paint is enjoying renewed
popularity is because it is made with natural ingredients. There
are no solvents. It is non-flammable, biodegradable and non-toxic
when dry.
</P>
<P>
   Milk paint is still being manufactured today and is available in
some stores or through mail-order sources (One source is the Old
Fashioned Milk Paint Co., P.O. Box 222, Groton, Mass. 01450). It
comes in powder form and is available in a wide variety of
traditional colors. It is also available in a colorless powder that
is contains only the casein binder and other dry ingredients but no
pigment. With this product, you can add your own powdered pigment
to create milk paint in a custom color of your choice.
</P>
<P>
   The milk paint must first be mixed with water to make liquid
paint. To mix the paint, start with equal amounts of powder and
warm water in separate containers. Stir the powder into the water
until you achieve the desired consistency. Let it stand for about
15 minutes so the water absorbs all the particles. The paint may
thicken somewhat as it stands, and it may be necessary to add more
water.
</P>
<P>
   One drawback to milk paint is that once it is mixed, it does not
store well. It is best therefore not to mix up more paint than you
can use in a day. If, for some reason, you are interrupted and must
store the liquid paint, pour it in an airtight container and place
it in the refrigerator. Refrigeration will only preserve the paint
for another day. The powder, however, will last indefinitely as
long as it kept in an airtight container.
</P>
<P>
   Another drawback to using milk paint is that even though the
final paint finish is tough and durable, it will waterspot and
readily absorb dirt (This makes milk paint impractical for outdoor
applications). For this reason, most manufacturers recommend
applying a protective sealer to the paint finish after it dries.
</P>
<P>
   You can use almost any sealer, like varnish or polyurethane, but
they may darken the color of the paint finish slightly. Most milk
paint manufacturers also offer a sealer for their products that is
water based and solvent free.
</P>
<P>
   Milk paint can be applied to almost surface that is clean, dry
and free of oil, grease, dust and dirt. Glossy surfaces should be
dulled with sandpaper or a degloss solution. Metal surfaces should
first be coated with a rust- inhibiting primer.
</P>
<P>
   When painting raw wood, first wipe the surface with a damp rag
to remove dust. Seal all knots with shellac to prevent bleeding.
When the shellac is thoroughly dry, you can paint the surface.
Since milk paint is a water-based paint, it should not be applied
with a natural-bristle brush. The brush fibers will absorb the
water and lose their shape and resiliency. Use a synthetic-fiber
brush or a foam brush to apply the paint.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you are not interested in painting with milk paint, you
may come across it if you like to refinish old furniture.
Do-it-yourselfers are often puzzled when they try to strip a paint
finish off an old piece and find that it is impervious to modern
paint removers. That is because the finish is probably milk paint
and it is unaffected by petroleum-based solvents. For many years,
the only solvent that would dissolve milk paint was ammonia. Today,
there is a remover made especially for milk paint. It is called
Behlen PDE-Milk and is formulated to soften a milk paint finish so
it can be scraped off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
