<HEADER>
A2787 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-ALLERGIES-ONLINE-     09-13 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ALLERGIES-ONLINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNEEZING? YOU CAN LOOK IT UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By MICHAEL POLLAK    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gen. George Patton's first rule of war _ get the other poor
blankety-blank before he gets you _ doesn't work with ragweed. It's
too prolific, and a single plant's lightweight, allergenic spores,
as many as 1 million a day, blow too far in the wind to let you
solve your watering, itching and sneezing problems in your own
backyard. Samples of ragweed pollen have been collected 400 miles
at sea and 2 miles high, according to the National Institutes of
Health.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean giving up. One of Patton's other rules
does apply: Know your enemy.
</P>
<P>
   To help with identification, the Plants Database of the federal
Department of Agriculture (http://plants.usda.gov/) gives profiles
of more than 20 ragweed varieties, along with many other plants.
Under common ragweed, the site has links to several picture
displays, notably those from the Weed Science Society of America,
whose pages show ragweed as a seedling, a young plant and a mature
plant.
</P>
<P>
   An excellent text and picture site comes from the Cooperative
Extension Service at Oklahoma State University
(http://plantsoil.okstate.edu/alfalfa/webnews/common(percent
sign)20ragweed.htm). You may not need its advice about herbicides
for your alfalfa field, but the close-ups of ragweed at different
stages provide clear identification for any homeowner. The photos
of baby ragweed can be especially useful next spring and early
summer, when you can weed on your property before the pollen begins
flying in early August and usually lasts until the killing frost.
</P>
<P>
   A page on ragweed from the University of Tulsa
(http://bio44.utulsa.edu/homepages/levetin/ragweed.htm) gives a
scientific description of the common ragweed plant (Ambrosia
artemisiifolia), which it calls the most important cause of
allergenic rhinitis and pollen asthma in North America. Two species
of ragweed, it notes, account for more hay fever than all other
plants together. Pollen release normally occurs in midmorning as
dew dries and humidity decreases, it says.
</P>
<P>
   A thorough account of ragweed, complete with literary
references, was compiled by Larry Mitich
(http://ext.agn.uiuc.edu/wssa/subpages/weed/10-1.htm). Why ragweed
acquired a beautiful generic name like Ambrosia, which means food
for the gods, is not known, he writes. He quotes an earlier
speculation that whoever first used the word ``may have had the
equine god in mind, for horses are very fond of this species, often
forsaking other food for its juicy leaves and branches.''
</P>
<P>
   Hay fever, or allergic rhinitis, affects more than 15 percent of
the population, according to the American College of Allergy,
Asthma and Immunology. Its advice page
(www.allergy.mcg.edu/patients/index.html) explains the various
forms of rhinitis, which can be seasonal or permanent and can be
caused by a wide variety of substances besides pollen, including
mold spores, dust mites, animal dander and certain foods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ragweed, which affects 75 percent of allergic rhinitis
sufferers, blankets most of the United States,'' even parts of
Alaska and Hawaii, the site says, adding: ``Allergist-immunologists
seldom recommend moving to another locale as a cure for
allergies.'' Rhinitis can be nonallergenic, the site notes; viruses
from colds or flu can be the culprit, as can air pollution or
aerosol sprays. Treatment options include avoidance, medication and
allergy shots.
</P>
<P>
   You may not be able to avoid ragweed entirely, but the National
Institute of Environmental Health Sciences has a short, readable
page of preventive strategies
(www.niehs.nih.gov/airborne/prevent/ragweed.html). The site has
individual pages on dust mites, cockroaches and other irritants, as
well as an asthma alert. Another important government site on
allergies, titled ``Something in the Air,'' from the National
Institutes of Health, is at
www.niaid.nih.gov/publications/allergens/full.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Asthma can be a killer and can be aggravated by many of the same
things that cause hay fever. The Asthma and Allergy Foundation of
America (www.aafa.org/) is a comprehensive online resource for
adults and children, including news updates, information on support
groups and an ``Ask the Allergist'' section. For those interested
in harder science, a collection of abstracts of original papers,
editorials and correspondence about asthma from The New England
Journal of Medicine is available at
www.nejm.org/content/collections/asthma.asp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
