<SLUG> BC-CIR-VIRTUA-TENNIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PONG REDUX WITH SWEAT AND SWAGGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By CHARLES HEROLD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Virtua Tennis, published by Sega for Dreamcast; $39.99; for all
ages.
</P>
<P>
   What right does that Tommy Haas have to be so smug? Look at him,
with his cocky walk and his stupid baseball hat on backward,
thinking he's so great because he slammed that ball past me and won
the match.
</P>
<P>
   I could have made that shot, but just as I was making a
desperate run for the ball, my wife walked in front of the TV and
blocked my view. Tommy Haas never had to deal with something like
that. You lucked out this time, Haas, but I'm hitting the Try Again
button, and this time I am out for blood.
</P>
<P>
   Haas, a real-life German tennis star, is one of an international
all-male cast of players you can compete against in Sega's Virtua
Tennis, an addictive game in which you can experience victory and
defeat without getting off the couch. The players are remarkably
lifelike, grunting when they serve, mopping up sweat between sets,
going for the ball with desperate leaps that have them tumbling
head over heels while the crowd gives a collective sigh.
</P>
<P>
   Virtual tennis looks so much like televised tennis, complete
with slow-motion instant replays, that you could very well start to
believe that you are seeing a real match.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to forget that this is not a spectator sport. You can
find yourself neglecting to control your player, staring at the
screen and thinking: ``What's wrong with that guy? Why is he just
standing there?''
</P>
<P>
   The game seems so athletic that after a while you may feel as
though you are that testosterone-pumped player on the court rather
than a couch potato with a game controller. You won't work up a
sweat, but you may feel as though you have. You may even be
convinced that you are getting physically stronger, faster and more
muscular _ until you play a live game of tennis and discover that
your muscles (except for those in your thumbs) have atrophied.
</P>
<P>
   Virtua Tennis is unlike most sports games in that you don't have
to like sports to enjoy playing. The game is not so much a sports
simulation as it is a retread of Pong, the game that began the
video game craze in the '70s. Underneath all the bells and
whistles, Virtua Tennis is a game about hitting a virtual
representation of a ball with a virtual representation of a racket,
an activity that has lost none of its charm in the last two and a
half decades.
</P>
<P>
   Like Pong, the game is simplicity itself. Direction keys run
your player across the court, and pushing a button makes him swing.
If the ball is nearby, he will move toward it and hit; if it's a
little too far away, he will jump for it. There is an incalculable
pleasure in seeing your opponent dive for a well-placed ball and
take a tumble, and a great frustration in doing so yourself.
</P>
<P>
   You choose a famous tennis player to play, and your choice
affects your tennis form: Mark Philippoussis has a hard serve;
Yevgeny Kafelnikov has a strong backhand. The effects are slight
but noticeable.
</P>
<P>
   Your computer opponents will also vary. Some will play the net;
some will volley; some will blast serves. Game play is also
affected by the court you choose, with concrete giving you more
bounce than clay or grass.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of playing against a computer opponent, you can choose
to play against someone sitting next to you on that couch of yours.
And since you can play singles or doubles matches, you can put four
people on that couch, each with a controller.
</P>
<P>
   Here is where the Pong essence of Virtua Tennis comes into play:
It isn't hard to persuade people to play with you, even those with
little interest in video games. Virtua Tennis is easy to play and
difficult to stop. It is both mindless and engaging. It appeals to
women as much as to men, to adults as well as to children.
</P>
<P>
   In a real game of tennis, you can attribute your losses to
arbitrary factors: the sun got in your eyes, there was a pebble
underfoot. Virtua Tennis also gives you problems beyond your
control. Like real tennis, one side of the court is easier to play
than the other, and you keep switching sides. The easy side is when
your player has his back to you. On this side, movement is pretty
natural, with the Up button moving you closer to the net, and the
Down button moving you away. It's more difficult to play from the
other side, where the controls are reversed. That gives you the
opportunity to say, ``I could have made that shot.''
</P>
<P>
   In singles mode, you can switch to an alternate view when on the
far side of the net, but in that view the ball is often off the
screen, one of the game's few shortcomings. You'll want to practice
on the far side anyway to train for those live competitions.
</P>
<P>
   Even when playing against the computer, you might feel as though
you have a live opponent _ not because of the intelligence of the
playing, although your computer opponents are frighteningly
proficient, but because of those moments when they shake their
heads after bad shots or pump their arms in excitement after good
ones. These reaction shots give a heightened sense of reality and
involvement; watching your opponent smirk after you miss an easy
shot will make you wish that Virtua Tennis had included a way to
throw your racket at the guy.
</P>
<P>
   When I won at an English tournament, I wasn't just beating a
computer, I was teaching Tommy Haas a lesson. So what if I couldn't
beat him in a real tennis match _ I'm sure I could destroy him in a
game of Pong. Then he might not be so smug.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
