<HEADLINE>
HELPING A PALM PILOT TO GET ITSELF IN SYNC 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I recently purchased a Palm V organizer and installed the
appropriate software in my computer, but I was unable to
synchronize the Palm functions with the PC. How do I remedy the
situation?
</P>
<P>
   A. There could be a number of things that are causing the
communications problem between the Palm organizer and the desktop
computer. Many problems with getting Palm's HotSync software to
work smoothly can be traced to the computer's COM ports, especially
if you have other programs using them.
</P>
<P>
   After you have made sure that the Palm's cradle is firmly
connected to the back of the computer, check to see whether the
HotSync Manager program is running. Look for a little red-and-blue
HotSync icon on your system tray, then open it and check the Setup
options in the menu to make sure that you have directed the HotSync
program to use an available COM port. That port cannot be the same
one that your internal modem uses and it cannot have the same IRQ
(Interrupt Request) value as your computer's mouse or any other
hardware device.
</P>
<P>
   There are probably too many unknown factors to diagnose the
precise reason for the HotSync problem here. Palm says that simply
quitting and restarting the HotSync Manager program will sometimes
fix the problem. Palm's Web site, however, has a very detailed
section on how to troubleshoot HotSync problems on both the Windows
and Macintosh platforms (www.palm.com/support/hotsync.html). The
page also contains links to documents about COM port management for
the Palm, problems with the USB version of the HotSync software and
Mac OS 9.0.4., and a host of other platform-related issues.
</P>
<P>
   Q. When I play CD-ROM programs on my computer, they seem to
stutter. Is that a mechanical problem with the CD drive?
</P>
<P>
   A. It could be a mechanical problem, but you might try cleaning
the lens on the CD-ROM drive first to see whether that helps with
the skipping. The CD player reads the disks with an optical lens,
and things like dust, dirt and pet hair can get sucked inside the
computer and wind up on the lens. If the lens is blocked by dirt,
it cannot read the disk accurately, and that causes skipping or
stuttering.
</P>
<P>
   One of the easiest ways to clean the drive is to purchase a
special lens-cleaner CD from a computer or electronics store. These
cleaning disks, which cost around $10 apiece and can be used
repeatedly, usually have tiny brushes embedded on the underside
that can sweep accumulated debris off the lens.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Some World Wide Web addresses have ``www'' in them, but I've
seen some that have ``www2'' instead, and I land there even if I
type ``www'' in the address. Why?
</P>
<P>
   A. The ``www'' is a common Internet standard indicating that the
computer you're trying to reach is a Web server. But it is not
mandatory, and it is not part of the site's domain name, which is
the main part of a Web address, like rockthevote.com.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on how the site was set up, ``www'' may be a required
part of the URL, or you may not even have to type it. Some sites
don't even have it in their addresses. Many just set set up
electronic pointers that will direct you to the right page, no
matter what variation of the domain name you type.
</P>
<P>
   When you see ``www2'' or something similar in a Web address,
odds are that the site had multiple servers with the same content,
and you were just redirected to another server in the site's fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Some Web browsers, like the current versions of Netscape
Navigator and Microsoft Internet Explorer, will helpfully insert
the ``http://www.'' and the ``.com'' for you. If you use one of
these browsers, you can type ``nytimes,'' for example, in the
address box and it will take you to www.nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
e-mail to Q&AMP;A(at)nytimes.com or mail to Questions, Circuits, The
New York Times, 229 West 43rd St., New York, N.Y. 10036-3959. This
column will answer questions of general interest, but letters
cannot be answered individually.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
