<SLUG> BC-OLY-WOMEN-UNDRESS-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKIN-BARING PHOTOS DO FEMALE ATHLETICS NO FAVORS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By J.R. LABBE 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   American swimmer Jenny Thompson bares practically all in a
photograph accompanying a Sports Illustrated story about her quest
to bring home another gold medal _ she has five _ at the Summer
Olympic games this month in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Russian tennis player Anna Kournikova leaves little to the
imagination, dressed in white micro-shorts and a clingy tube top,
on the cover of the August edition of GQ. (The same edition
features the top American male Olympic athletes in long-sleeved,
leather-jacketed, cover-the-body Armani suits and Ralph Lauren
slacks _ even the guy in the pool.)
</P>
<P>
   The August edition of Esquire brought the world ``Style &AMP;
Beauty: A portfolio of America's 10 sexiest athletes'' _ all women,
of course, and most of them clad in scanty panties and
breast-hugging tops.
</P>
<P>
   You've come a long way, baby. Not!
</P>
<P>
   This sort of Olympiad of ogling wasn't what the torch bearers
for Title IX had in mind back in the early 1970s, when they were
petitioning Congress and lobbying state legislatures and haranguing
local school boards for enhanced opportunities and participation
for female athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the Education Amendments of 1972, Title IX says: ``No
person in the United States, shall on the ground of race, color, or
national origin, be excluded from participation in, be denied the
benefits of, or be subjected to discrimination under any program or
activity receiving Federal financial assistance, or be so treated
on the basis of sex under most education programs or activities
receiving Federal assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   When Congress made Title IX the law of the land, female athletes
and their coaches across the country _ energized by optimism that
their day in the sport spotlight had finally arrived _ worked their
collective tails off to build competitive athletic programs for
girls and women.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just a question of securing funds for women's sports.
There was a credibility issue on the line, too. The prevailing
attitude at many colleges and universities _ and if many athletic
directors told the gospel truth, some would admit it still exists _
was that women weren't geared toward athletic competition, weren't
serious about competitive sports, didn't have what it takes to
build a loyal and, more important, paying audience.
</P>
<P>
   UNDRESSED FOR SUCCESS?: Today's trend of marketing female
athletes as if they were selling 1-900 numbers raises questions,
particularly for the female athletes who were on the front lines a
quarter-century ago seeking equity. The sweat and the hours spent
to build credible athletic programs was for ... what? So that, at
the dawn of a new millennium, female athletes could take their
clothes off for America?
</P>
<P>
   Chris Bobel, director of the Women's Center at the University of
Cincinnati, worries that the fixation on sexuality will aggravate
existing problems for female athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Focusing on the bodies of women athletes hypersensitizes young
women to the importance of their appearance,'' Bobel said. ``Given
the already disproportionate rate of eating disorders and related
body-image dysfunction among female athletes, this trend could
surely exacerbate an already serious problem.''
</P>
<P>
   But many female athlete don't see it that way, which is all too
apparent by their appearances sans sweats _ or any other athletic
apparel _ in calendars and magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Stacy Dragila, a 29-year-old world-champion pole vaulter from
Auburn, Calif., makes no apologies for posing nude with other
American women for a track-and-field calendar. Dragila told The New
York Times that she considers it a sign of progress that women are
confident enough about their bodies to expose them as figures of
strength and power instead of titillation.
</P>
<P>
   But some aren't buying that line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't insult my intelligence by telling me this is about
showing off your muscles,'' said Mary Jo Kane, director of the
Tucker Center for Girls and Women in Sport at the University of
Minnesota. ``It's not clear to me what muscle group their breasts
belong to. Jenny Thompson didn't win five gold medals because she
has nice breasts, so why are we talking about them?''
</P>
<P>
   Kane, whose center studies how sport and physical activity
affect girls and women, says that the news media's focus on the
sexuality of female athletes is not a new phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much of the data available and many of the studies I've done
show that historically, women athletes, when compared to male, are
more likely to be portrayed off the court, not in uniform, in
highly feminine poses,'' she said. ``What is unusual about today is
that female athletes, rather than being portrayed in classy evening
gowns or sorority shots, are shown in ways alarmingly similar to
soft porn poses.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   Kane is well aware that anyone who questions this latest trend
in marketing is labeled a prude and a moralist.
</P>
<P>
   ``To those who call us humorless feminists and say we don't get
it, all I'm asking with respect to the media's treatment or
marketing of women athletes is that there be some kind of parallel
or equitable portrayal of men. The day that Tiger Woods is
portrayed with a sexy smile standing on a golf course with nothing
but a Nike swoosh over his genitals, then I'll be quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   Who's humorless now, guys?
</P>
<P>
   SHOW THEM THE MONEY: Historically, the fastest way for a woman
to lose her credibility has been to disrobe. So why are so many
female athletes getting down to the bare essentials?
</P>
<P>
   Attention, which in the athletic world can translate into
lucrative endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants attention,'' said Marian Washington, head coach
of the women's basketball team at the University of Kansas and a
role model for this writer back in the mid-'70s, when I played
volleyball for KU and lobbied the state Legislature for sports
funding.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't think the athletes are always thinking the same
way as the marketing person. When they're draped in a flag, I don't
know that the marketing person is thinking that the message is they
work hard and their bodies are great. The marketing person is
thinking, `How do I to sell this magazine,' or, `How can I position
the athletes so they can get opportunities for endorsements?'
</P>
<P>
   ``The athletes feel they are going to have some leverage if they
are willing to come across with a more sexual undertone as part of
the promotion. It's too bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Olympic officials and sponsors are definitely paying more
attention to female athletes than ever before, sparked partly by
the success of last summer's Women's World Cup of soccer. You
remember the games, don't you? Or do you just remember American
Brandi Chastain peeling out of her jersey and down to her sports
bra after nailing the winning kick?
</P>
<P>
   ``I love that women are being shown more as athletes,'' said Dr.
Roberta Nutt, professor of psychology at Texas Women's University.
``But there is some distortion. People remember the women's soccer
team as Chastain with her shirt off. She and Mia Hamm get the big
publicity partly because of how they look, but the entire team
contributed to the victory.''
</P>
<P>
   And the women's teams do deserve attention this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year's Olympics is the first moment where America is
paying attention on a major scale to women's sports,'' the Tucker
Center's Kane said. ``The U.S. women compared to U.S. men, going
into the Sydney games, were clearly the story in terms of the
opportunity to garner medals _ gold medals in particular.
</P>
<P>
   ``The focus should be on that, and how far women have come, and
that all the physiological and biological and sociological
stereotypes of what women couldn't do in sports are being blown out
of the water. But the take is what it means for women athletes to
take their clothes off. Who's being served by this?''
</P>
<P>
   Nutt doesn't view the new wave of athletic portraiture as
entirely negative.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plus is that at least it's a more positive image than we
used to have,'' she said. ``We're seeing healthy, strong women with
muscles rather than waif-like models like Kate Moss who starve
themselves to death to get that look. But it's still
objectification of the female body. We're doing some of it with
men, too, but a male athlete who isn't gorgeous gets the same
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The negative part is that it reinforces that old message that
women are valued most for looks. Wonderful female athletes who are
not gorgeous don't get the same media coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   So the progress made for female athletes since the mid-'70s is
two steps forward and one shot of the naked back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk about how far we still have to go in my Psychology of
Women class,'' Nutt said. ``It's hard not to have students getting
discouraged. I try to create a balance as to where we have made
progress. And there is progress. At least now we're looking at
female athletes, and that's a good thing, and they are making more
money than they used to, and that's a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we live in a culture that still objectifies female bodies,
and that's a bad thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Kane, too, sees good news and bad news. Twenty-eight years after
its passage, Title IX has engendered a sense of entitlement in
young women who grew up with sport opportunities that those who
came before them had to fight for. The bad news, she said, is that
they don't understand that sacrifices were made to get here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't occur to them that a lot of blood has been spilled
so they can do what they do.''
</P>
<P>
   And doing what they do includes taking their clothes off for the
camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``As someone who has advocated for women's sport for last 20
years,'' Kane said, ``if this is what it means to have arrived, no
thanks. No thanks.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. She can be reached at
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com or (817) 390-7599. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
