   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-ROUNDUP (Undated) _ Al Gore and George W. Bush raid
each other's centerpiece issues. Gore moves to blunt Bush's inroads
on the traditionally Democratic issue of education by touting his
plan to make the first $10,000 of college expenses tax deductible.
Bush, in the mode of a Theodore Roosevelt-style environmentalist,
promises a $4.9 billion cleanup of the nation's bedraggled national
parks. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH (Undated) _ On a West Coast trek, Texas Gov. George W. Bush
pushes for improved maintenance of national parks and better
conservation of salmon. By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   GORE (Lewiston, Maine) _ Vice President Al Gore discusses
education at a high school in Maine, then swings through Boston and
Manchester, N.H., where he'll scoop up some campaign donations as a
consolation prize for the state's electoral votes that are likely
to go to Republican George W. Bush. By PATTY REINERT.
</P>
<P>
   POLL-ELECTION (Washington) _ A new poll shows Al Gore ahead of
George W. Bush among independent voters and parents with children
at home. Pollster John Zogby, who did the survey, also says Gore
has neutralized Bush's advantage among men. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MARRIAGE-TAX (Washington) _ In a vote sure to echo through the
fall political campaigns, the Republican-led House fails to
overturn President Clinton's veto of a bill cutting taxes by $292
billion over 10 years for millions of married couples. The 270-158
vote was 16 fewer than the two-thirds necessary to override the
veto of the ``marriage penalty'' bill. That likely killed one of
the GOP's signature pieces of legislation this year while giving
Republicans ammunition in their bid to help George W. Bush win the
White House and keep control of Congress. By KAREN MASTERSON.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-VIOLENCE (Washington) _ Decrying what he calls a ``culture
of carnage,'' Democratic vice presidential candidate Joe Lieberman
tells his Senate colleagues that unless the entertainment industry
polices itself, the government should step in to ban the sale of
violent movies, music and video games to children. Federal media
regulators have announced they will take a closer look at the
amount of sex and violence on the major networks. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   WORK-VISAS (Washington) _ A large coalition of businesses that
rely on unskilled or low-skilled workers is trying to convince
lawmakers to include this group in any legislation that increases
the number of work visas for technology workers. By JENNIFER HOYT.
</P>
