<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-TAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE REPUBLICANS FAIL TO OVERRIDE VETO OF MARRIAGE PENALTY BILL 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: we plan to update this story later with a longer version by
Richard W. Stevenson) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republicans fell short Wednesday in their
attempt to override President Clinton's veto of the ``marriage
penalty'' bill. But while the bill is dead, the issue it addresses
is very much alive politically.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was 270-158 in favor of overriding Clinton's veto,
short of the two-thirds required. Even if the bill had garnered the
necessary two-thirds in the House, vote-counters thought there was
virtually no chance of getting the same margin in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Dick Armey immediately signaled that
Republicans would try to use the marriage penalty as campaign
grist. ``Americans understand it is wrong to tax marriage,'' he
said. ``We will have to put it up on the floor next year and have a
president who will sign it.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats accused the Republicans of being more interested in
nurturing a political issue than in passing genuine and equitable
tax relief. ``It's the show that counts,'' said Rep. Steny H. Hoyer
of Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   When he vetoed the bill last month, Clinton said it would have
benefited wealthy people most while providing very little relief to
middle-income people.
</P>
<P>
   The bill that Clinton vetoed, and which died Wednesday in the
House, has been advertised by Republicans as a way to eliminate the
quirk in the tax code that leave many _ but not all _ two-income
couples paying a higher tax bill than they would if they had stayed
single.
</P>
<P>
   But it would have cut taxes for almost all married couples,
regardless of whether they now pay a penalty. Couples with one
working spouse, or households in which one spouse earns much more
than the other, typically pay a lower tax bill because they are
married than if they were single.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the bill would have raised the standard
deduction for married couples filing jointly, so that it would be
equal to that of two single people.
</P>
<P>
   The deduction is adjusted each year for inflation. For this
year, the standard deduction for couples filing jointly is $7,350.
That is only 1.67 times the deduction for single people, which is
$4,400, meaning that the married couples pay a ``penalty'' of
$1,450.
</P>
<P>
   Lost in the debate is the fact that this quirk _ like so many
others in the tax code _ arose because of attempts to correct
inequities that once penalized single people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
