<HEADER>
A2830 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-QUAKE-SITE-ART-NY     09-13 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-QUAKE-SITE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PLACE TO GO WHEN THERE'S A WHOLE LOTTA SHAKIN' GOIN' ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT10 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By KATIE HAFNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When an earthquake roused tens of thousands of Northern
California residents from their sleep early in the morning on Sept.
3, hundreds of those rattled souls went straight to their computers
and logged onto the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   First, many people checked the U.S. Geological Survey's Web site
(quake.wr.usgs.gov/recenteqs) for the magnitude (5.2) and epicenter
(near the town of Yountville, in Napa County), which were
calculated within minutes by seismic instruments and posted
automatically to the site.
</P>
<P>
   From there, a lot of people went to a page called Did You Feel
It? (pasadena.wr.usgs.gov/shake/ciim(underscore)nocal.html). They
entered their ZIP code and answered a list of questions about
things like how frightened they had been and whether their
appliances had moved.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the sun came up a few hours later, a color-coded map
showing where and how intensely the earthquake had been felt around
the San Francisco Bay Area had already taken shape.
</P>
<P>
   Such Community Internet Intensity Maps, like the one made for
the Napa quake, are the creation of Dr. David Wald, a 38-year-old
seismologist at the USGS in Pasadena, Calif., whose expertise in
computer modeling gave him the idea of moving intensity and damage
reporting to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Although the magnitude and epicenter of an earthquake are
valuable pieces of data, Wald said, they do not reveal much about
what the intensity of shaking was like in different places.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to gather that information someplace else,'' he said.
Seismic instruments generate automated shake-intensity maps after a
quake, but they do not tell the whole story.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't afford to put instruments everywhere,'' Wald said,
``but people are on the Net everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   And people, it turns out, are excellent seismometers. For years,
the Geological Survey gathered intensity data by mailing
questionnaires after a significant quake, then drawing its maps
based on responses.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1994 Northridge earthquake in Southern California,
which had a magnitude of 6.7, killed more than 60 people and caused
billions of dollars in damage, Dr. Lori Dengler, a geophysicist at
Humboldt State University, conducted post-quake telephone surveys.
She assigned numbers to the responses and used those numbers to map
intensity.
</P>
<P>
   As the Web gained popularity, Wald decided to apply Dengler's
methodology to the task of creating an interactive Web site that
would lead to intensity maps. The first questionnaire was put up in
1997, and since then, the intensity of hundreds of small and
moderate earthquakes has been mapped using the site. Most of the
maps apply to quakes in California, but Wald and his co-workers are
expanding the site to cover earthquakes around the country.
</P>
<P>
   There are also Did You Feel It? questionnaires for several large
historic quakes, including the Northridge quake and the 1989 Loma
Prieta quake near San Francisco, for people to fill out years after
the fact.
</P>
<P>
   The Did You Feel It? site asks a raft of questions, like ``Did
the earthquake wake you up?'' and ``Was it difficult to stand or
walk?'' and ``Did objects fall off shelves?''
</P>
<P>
   Each set of responses is assigned a numeric value and a
corresponding color, then plugged into the map. The map refreshes
itself every five minutes as the responses are received, filling in
with colors that range from white, for no shaking, to deep red, for
extreme shaking and very heavy damage.
</P>
<P>
   The more people who respond, the more accurately the map
reflects the actual intensity and the extent of damage.
</P>
<P>
   As the map forms, things begin to make geophysical sense, too.
People usually report more shaking in areas with softer sediment,
where the ground is less stable. Such was the case with the recent
Napa County quake.
</P>
<P>
   Although the quake was centered north of Napa, that city, which
sits on softer soil and is more densely populated, suffered the
most damage.
</P>
<P>
   Even mild earthquakes can be upsetting, and people who go to the
Did You Feel It? site appear to find comfort in seeing that others
felt what they felt.
</P>
<P>
   Wald said he was impressed by the number of people who took the
time to write lengthy accounts in the form's Additional Comments
section. ``People like to get it off their chest,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The most telling example of the effectiveness of the Did You
Feel It? site came at 3 a.m. on Oct. 16, 1999, when a 7.1-magnitude
quake was felt throughout Southern California. The epicenter of the
quake was in the middle of the desert, but 15 minutes after the
quake, more than 100 people had filled out the survey, and by later
that morning, 8,000 people had registered what they felt. Nearly
25,000 people have since filled out the form for that earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most amusing responses, Wald said, came from a police
officer who had been chasing a burglary suspect when the earthquake
hit. The officer was knocked off the concrete wall he had been
running on. ``Thief got away due to divine intervention,'' he
reported on Wald's site.
</P>
<P>
   Wald said that the site attracted pranksters here and there but
that they were not difficult to weed out. If answers are internally
inconsistent (nothing felt but severe damage reported, for
instance) the questionnaire is discounted.
</P>
<P>
   After one quake, an entry on the site included a 90210 ZIP code,
and Wald knew to discard the response.
</P>
<P>
   Wald said the site had been very useful for gathering data on
small and medium quakes, which leave people rattled but unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   In the event of a large earthquake, Wald said, it could take
several days to get responses in heavily damaged areas. Still, he
said, a delay of days is an improvement over the weeks of delay
that the Geological Survey faced in the past. Wald added: ``Having
a hole in a map that shows increasing intensity toward the hole
tells you what must have happened in areas that did not respond _
they couldn't. And that implies power outages and lost
communication.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-00 1620EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
