<HEADER>
A2834 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-COINS14-COX     09-13 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COINS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GRAMM SAYS AMERICA DESERVES MORE BEAUTIFUL COINS
 &HT;    By BRUCE HIGHT
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Phil Gramm, chairman of the Senate Banking
Committee, says the government should put new money into the
pockets of all Americans _ and can make a profit doing it.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, the Texas Republican and former coin collector said
Wednesday, is that U.S. coins, which should be ``both utilitarian
and beautiful,'' are unattractive, unworthy of a great nation and
in need of redesign.
</P>
<P>
   It costs much less to mint a coin than its face value, and
Americans have shown an enormous appetite for new coins. So a
redesigned coinage could become a major ``profit center'' for the
federal government, Gramm said.
</P>
<P>
   At what he called a ``symposium on coin design,'' Gramm
complained that current American coins, if dug up centuries from
now, would not ``conjure up an image of the greatest nation in the
history of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   As Robert Campbell, president of the American Numismatic
Association, put it, U.S. coins may not be ``crummy'' _ as Gramm
has said in the past _ but collectors regard them as a collection
of ``dead heads'' featuring tired designs.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm referred to the passion that another Republican, President
Theodore Roosevelt, brought to a redesign of American coins in the
first decade of 20th century, producing what many collectors regard
as some of the most beautiful coins ever.
</P>
<P>
   Those designs were later changed, but most current versions have
been around for more than a half-century. The Lincoln penny was
begun in 1909 and modified on one side in 1959. The Washington
quarter appeared in 1932, the Jefferson nickel in 1938, and the
Roosevelt dime in 1946. Even the Kennedy half-dollar, which doesn't
circulate much, has been around since 1964.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Doty, curator of numismatics at the Smithsonian National
Museum of American History, called America's coins ``distinctly
uninspired,'' cluttered and trite.
</P>
<P>
   But even if ugly, U.S. coins sure are in demand.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Johnson, director of the U.S. Mint, said coin-producing
facilities in Philadelphia and Denver are running three shifts a
day, ``nearly'' seven days a week to keep up with the demand for
coins _ 28 billion this year alone, 8 billion more than the
previous record.
</P>
<P>
   Americans apparently love the new state quarters, in which each
state was allowed to suggest the design for the reverse. The
quarters are being minted over the next several years in the order
in which the states entered the union.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said that before 1999, when the first state quarter came
out, the mint produced between 1 and 1.5 billion quarters a year;
now it's 6 billion a year and climbing. The new ``golden''
Sacagawea dollar also has been a success, he said.
</P>
<P>
   This year alone, the mint will generate $3.1 billion for the
treasury in ``profits,'' up from $550 million in 1998, mint
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson, while not directly challenging criticism of current
designs on U.S. coins, laid out some of the problems that make it
more difficult to produce coins as beautiful as the $20 gold piece
designed by sculptor Augustus Saint-Gaudens in 1907.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said the gold piece had to be modified almost
immediately, because the high relief in its design made them more
difficult to produce, and bankers found they didn't stack well.
</P>
<P>
   If the mint must substantially change the way it makes coins to
handle new ones with more detailed designs, different weights or
sizes, or metals, he said, it could ``seriously challenge our
ability to meet the nation's coin needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, Johnson said, coins must be capable of being used in
vending machines.
</P>
<P>
   But Gramm said that, given enormous advances in metallurgy over
the past century, surely more could be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is somewhat of a paradox to me that with the dramatic
improvement in the precision of American technology and, therefore,
in our capacity to mint finer coins than we've ever minted before,
the quality of American coins has dropped dramatically in the last
century,'' Gramm said.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm made no specific proposals for who or what should be on
redesigned coins _ he didn't even push a conservative hero, former
President Ronald Reagan, for a spot.
</P>
<P>
   A recent unscientific poll of 1,940 coin collectors by a Chicago
firm, Minkus &AMP; Dunne Communications for the coin dealers Littleton
and Co. found that the three top vote-getters for a place on
American coins were Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., Reagan and former
President Harry Truman.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan would be ``a contestant'' if it is decided to keep great
national leaders on coins, Gramm said after the symposium.
</P>
<P>
   But the senator said he wasn't even sure that the best design
would involve people: ``Maybe we should have coins that try to
embody the different concepts of American democracy _ liberty,
justice _ those kinds of things.''
</P>
<P>
   One possibility, he said, would be to resume production of the
famed ``Buffalo'' nickel that was minted between 1913 and 1938.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm has no pending legislation on coin redesign, but he said
he expects to take up the issue when the new Congress convenes in
January.
</P>
<P>
   As for his own coin collection, Gramm no longer has it. He said
he sold it for $300 in 1961 to help finance his college education.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Hight's e-mail address is bruceh(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
