<SLUG> BC-CD-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
 
 SIZING UP THE 10 MOST EAGERLY AWAITED FALL-RELEASE CDs 
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every year, record labels save up CDs from their biggest stars,
then unleash them during the cutthroat Christmas season.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the list of discs from high-profile artists is
typically staggering. Christina Aguilera, Limp Bizkit, The
Wallflowers, U2 and Radiohead, among others, will release discs
within the same few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a record company tradition to release a lot of new
records in the fall,'' says Dan Lightner, music manager for Borders
Books and Music in Fort Worth. ``It'll be Christmastime soon.
Everyone's shopping.''
</P>
<P>
   The fall deluge of top-talent efforts will be followed by even
more this winter, performed by the likes of the Dave Matthews Band
and the Backstreet Boys, increasing the Christmas competition.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, here's a look at the top 10 most-anticipated
CDs headed for the bins. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who: Christina Aguilera &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brief bio: The reigning queen of teen-pop. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The disc: ``Mi Reflejo'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Out: This week &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What to expect: An all-Spanish disc featuring en espanol
versions of established hits such as ``Genie in a Bottle,''
alongside a handful of new songs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At stake: Aguilera is pulling a reverse Ricky Martin: she's out
to conquer the Latin market the same way Martin cracked the U.S.
market. If she succeeds, she'll not only increase her fan base but
also gain credibility as a legit singer. If the disc flops, well,
thank heaven for American teen-age girls. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who: Erykah Badu &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brief bio: Sultry, Dallas-born R&AMP;B singer whose debut disc,
``Baduizm,'' not only sold extremely well _ thanks to the No. 1
single ``On and On'' _ but also served as a breath of fresh, rootsy
air in a genre dominated by plasticity. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The disc: ``Mama's Gun'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Out: Oct. 31 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What to expect: Recorded in Dallas and New York, Badu's second
disc is said to be in the same jazz-laced, R&AMP;B vein as
``Baduizm.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At stake: ``Baduizm'' came out three years ago, a lifetime in
the ever-changing, here-today-already-gone world of pop and R&AMP;B. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who: Johnny Cash &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brief bio: Country icon whose soot-dark voice and candid imagery
have haunted and enthralled country music for 40 years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The disc: ``American III: Solitary Man'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Out: Oct. 17 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What to expect: Another collection of ghostly acoustic songs
(including U2 and Neil Diamond covers) that could easily be an
accompaniment to his beautifully stark 1994 disc, ``American
Recordings.'' Tom Petty and Sheryl Crow guest. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At stake: Absolutely nothing. Country radio hasn't paid
attention to guys like Cash for years. Like Willie Nelson, Cash
makes music just because he wants to, not to hear cash registers
clink. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who: Green Day &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brief bio: Monstrously popular California punk trio whose major
label debut, ``Dookie,'' ushered in a wave of soundalikes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The disc: ``Warning'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Out: Oct. 3 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What to expect: Let's just say it's aptly titled. Not much on
``Warning'' resembles the band's past punk-pop efforts. Most of the
songs are strummy, acoustic-guitar-driven singalongs. Definitely a
change of pace. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At stake: Their longtime fans, who have stuck by them through
commercial ups and downs. Be interesting to see if they ditch them
for softening things up. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who: Limp Bizkit &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brief bio: Unstoppable kings of the rap-rock hill. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The disc: ``Chocolate Starfish and the Hot-Dog Flavored Water'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Out: Oct. 17 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What to expect: More of the same. For whatever reason, kids have
latched onto Limp Bizkit's vanilla-flavored metal-rock hybrid. The
Florida-bred band is certainly not gonna jeopardize its popularity
by changing its sure-thing formula. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At stake: Are you kidding? This thing's gonna sell even if it's
an hourlong recording of singer Fred Durst belching. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who: Madonna &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brief bio: Pop goddess who constantly reinvents herself. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The disc: ``Music'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Out: Tuesday &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What to expect: Another ``Ray of Light.'' Madonna's
platinum-plus success with that 1998 techno/dance effort led her
back to ``Light'' producer William Orbit, who tweaked ``Music''
along with dance-music gurus Groove Armada and Mirwais. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At stake: Madonna has always toyed with dance music, whether
it's for the charts or the clubs; she has nothing to lose, simply
because she's been making dance music for years, even though it's
often disguised as pop. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who: Marilyn Manson &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brief bio: Shock/shlock rocker bent on entertaining kids and
enraging their parents. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The disc: ``Holy Wood (In the Shadow of the Valley of Death)'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Out: Nov. 14 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What to expect: Manson's first ``concept album'' about a star
who self-destructs after becoming everything he once despised. No
word yet if it harks back to Manson's industrial days or his more
recent infatuation with glam. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At stake: Manson is still incredibly popular with a certain
slice of kids _ and he's still a target on the hit lists of certain
keep-America-beautiful organizations. The rest of the world ignores
him. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who: Radiohead &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brief bio: English rock outfit that blew away critics and fans
alike with its grandiose, art-rock 1997 effort, ``OK, Computer.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The disc: ``Kid A'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Out: Oct. 3 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What to expect: A more dreamy, atmospheric effort, with touches
of Brian Eno-esque ambience mixed in with crunchy guitar work. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At stake: Everything. This is easily one of the most anticipated
CDs of the year, and if it doesn't live up to ``Computer,'' the
band could lose the stardom it has worked for nearly a decade to
achieve. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who: U2 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brief bio: One of the most intelligent and inventive rock bands
to ever emerge from Ireland, or anywhere else. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The disc: ``All That You Can't Leave Behind'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Out: Oct. 31 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What to expect: A supposed return to the sparse, guitar-based
sound of their two best discs, ``The Unforgettable Fire'' and ``The
Joshua Tree.'' Brian Eno and Daniel Lanois _ producers of ``Fire''
and ``Tree'' _ are back behind the boards. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At stake: When it comes to U2, fans are very forgiving, perhaps
because they know that for every clunker like ``Rattle &AMP; Hum''
there will be a masterpiece, such as ``The Joshua Tree'' or
``Achtung Baby.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who: The Wallflowers &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brief bio: Led by Jakob Dylan, son of Bob Dylan, The Wallflowers
have steered clear of emulating Dylan Sr.'s folk leanings. Rather,
the band staked out its own roots-rock turf, adding dark layers
that went over surprisingly well with pop-music listeners. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The disc: ``Breach'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Out: Oct. 10 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What to expect: More introspection. Jakob Dylan has always shied
away from writing biographical songs. On ``Breach,'' he breaks that
tradition, while maintaining the band's trademark sound. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At stake: The Wallflowers are yet another band that lives from
disc to disc, and simply can't afford a commercial failure. If this
bombs, they'll be back to playing the Galaxy Club. Yes, they did
once play there. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Five other priority-one discs slated for this fall: country
singer Willie Nelson's all-blues foray, ``Milk Cow Blues'' (Sept.
19); boy-band 98 Degrees' latest syrup-coated CD, ``Revelation''
(Sept. 26); world-pop tunesmith Paul Simon's ``You're the One''
(Oct. 3); techno genius Fatboy Slim's ``Halfway Between the Gutter
and the Stars'' (Nov. 7); and the Spice Girls' comeback effort,
``Forever'' (Nov. 7).
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
