<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHORS-ATWOOD-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATWOOD'S NEWEST NOVEL CAN BE TOUGH GOING, BUT THEN, SO CAN THE
WRITER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MARSHALL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are books that are as comfy as an old pair of jeans, an
easy fit for many readers. Then there are books that raise demands
on readers, like schoolteachers, books that insist that serious
attention be paid, or else.
</P>
<P>
   The latest novel by Margaret Atwood is such a book. Canada's
leading literary figure has produced ``The Blind Assassin'' (Nan A.
Talese/Doubleday, 521 pages, $26). It is a literary afghan made of
a story within a story within a story, three unlikely threads of
narrative woven into a single piece of imposing craftwork. And the
60-year-old Atwood would not have it any other way, as a writer or
as a reader.
</P>
<P>
   ``A story within a story within a story is excessive, but I'm
not writing for people with short attention spans,'' Atwood in a
Seattle interview. ``I'm writing for readers like me who go into a
book and stay with it and like a challenge. Because I believe that
if a book is not risky, not a challenge _ if it's just something
you can do without any thinking or worry _ then it's not what I
want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   So ``The Blind Assassin'' includes the first-person life story
of one Iris Chase Griffen, a crusty octogenarian who spins forth a
Canadian family story of ``loss and regret and misery and
yearning.'' That alternates with chapters from a steamy 1940s' noir
novel (``The Blind Assassin'') supposedly written by her sister,
Laura, a noir novel that tracks two unnamed lovers through trysts
in seedy rented rooms in hopes of avoiding detection. And within
that noir novel, there is a violent sci-fi saga cooked up by the
male character to entertain his lover during post-passion repose.
</P>
<P>
   It's no wonder that what Atwood once envisioned as a 350-page
novel mushroomed way beyond that. Nor should it surprise that one
early critic, novelist Thomas Mallon in The New York Times Book
Review, has savaged the novel for ``its peculiar blend of low and
high, like a Nancy Drew story written by one of the Brontes.''
</P>
<P>
   Atwood declined to respond to that review's criticisms because,
she said, she has not read it (``it was hidden from me by my
assistant''). But mention of that review brought forth the writer's
prickly side, an arch intensity that is the stuff of legend.
Suddenly missing-in-action were Atwood's engaging smiles, witty
asides, easy laughter. In their place was a withering gaze, sharp
words.
</P>
<P>
   Such a review should not even be discussed unless ``the 99 good
reviews are also discussed,'' Atwood insisted, then named some
publications where they have appeared. Any question about that
negative review should be addressed not to her, Atwood added, but
to the review's editor who assigned it to Mallon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's the aura of the giant-killer game to this, and it is
not the first time this has happened,'' Atwood emphasized. ``I must
say it is boring to be asked about one review.''
</P>
<P>
   The subject was then dropped, like a microwaved potato, and
Atwood's demeanor brightened when she discussed how engaged she was
by all three stories in ``The Blind Assassin.'' Or how ``everything
is timing'' in a book with so many plot threads, or how alternating
the plots must be done carefully so the author can avoid ``getting
between the reader and the book itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether that is easier or more difficult for a writer of
Atwood's stature is open to debate. Atwood's work does come with
imposing luggage, from her often-mentioned feminist perspective to
her propensity for Gothic plot elements, from her legions of
fanatic readers (there is a Margaret Atwood Society in Canada with
$10 annual dues) to her prodigiousness as an artist.
</P>
<P>
   She has 15 works of fiction to her credit, along with 13 books
of poetry, plus five works of non-fiction and three books for
children. There is no denying that Atwood is a literary colossus of
formidable dexterity, like John Updike in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Her visit to Seattle was an early stop on an international book
campaign that will crisscross North America, then do the same in
Europe, with Australia, New Zealand and Japan to follow next
spring. This is a taxing (or ``horrifying,'' in Atwood's view)
schedule of readings and public appearances, especially for someone
who is known for being zealous about protecting her private life in
Toronto, other than making brief passing references to her husband
of two decades, writer Graeme Gibson, and their grown daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``My private life is so boring,'' Atwood said. ``People would
fall on their faces from the normality of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Atwood subjects herself to a book tour's inevitable questions
from interviewers and audiences out of a literary equivalent of
noblesse oblige. She believes it is part of her responsibility as a
hugely successful author to bring in all the money she can to
assist publishers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing is like hockey cards really,'' Atwood said.
``Publishers live off books that sell well and that allows them to
publish young writers and new writers, or writers who do not have
such a high profile.''
</P>
<P>
   That is also why Atwood's appearance before 800 people at First
United Methodist Church in Seattle was a much-appreciated benefit
for Copper Canyon Press, the fine poetry publisher in Port
Townsend. Atwood taught two summers long ago at the writer's
conference there and retains ``many fond memories'' of that place
and Copper Canyon's work.
</P>
<P>
   Atwood read a lengthy passage from ``The Blind Assassin'' before
the large crowd, which seemed to hang on her every word, chuckling
aloud when the author even slightly cocked a pencil-thin eyebrow.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Atwood answered a half-dozen questions, displaying both
her scissor wit and her cactus side. Those had also surfaced often
during the day when Atwood dealt with those she considers
functionaries of one sort or another: hotel staffers, bookstore
personnel, interviewers.
</P>
<P>
   A man in the audience who asked ``what writers inspire you''
soon found himself installed on the hot seat as Atwood peppered him
with questions, such as ``which century?'' and ``what period?'' and
``men or women?'' She then provided suggestions for further
reading.
</P>
<P>
   But the exchange with this stranger, which at first seemed
light-hearted and humorous, went on and on and soon sunk under the
leaden weight of condescension _ naive innocent vs. brilliant
writer.
</P>
<P>
   It was, of course, no great contest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
