<HEADER>
A2844 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-WITTY-NYT &LR;      09-13 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-WITTY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITTY CHASING A SPECIAL DOUBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ It took only a few minutes for Chris Witty
to discover she was a prodigy in speed skating. As a 10-year-old in
West Allis, Wis., she entered a 500-meter race wearing her
brother's figure skates. Still, she won so easily that she was
showing the gold medal to her mother by the time the second-place
skater reached the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   Having won silver and bronze medals at the 1998 Winter Olympics
in Nagano, Japan, Witty will again be a favorite in the middle
distances at the 2002 Winter Games in Salt Lake City. First,
however, she will enter the 500-meter cycling time trial on
Saturday at the Sydney Games, attempting to become only the fourth
person to win medals in both the Winter and Summer Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be awesome, probably more than I hoped for,'' Witty,
25, said in an interview last week.
</P>
<P>
   Only one athlete has ever won a gold medal in both Olympics.
Eddie Eagan of Denver took the light-heavyweight boxing title at
the 1920 Summer Games in Antwerp, Belgium; 12 years later, he
finished first as part of the four-man bobsled at the 1932 Winter
Games in Lake Placid, N.Y. Jacob Tullin Thams of Norway won the ski
jump at the 1924 Winter Games in Chamonix, France, and finished
second in the 8-meter sailing competition at the 1936 Summer Games
in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   The athletic ancestor to Witty was Christa Luding-Rothenburger
of the former East Germany, who won gold medals in speed skating at
the 1984 Sarajevo Games and the 1988 Calgary Olympics, then took a
silver in the cycling 1,000-meter match sprint at the 1988 Summer
Games in Seoul, South Korea. All of her medals have since been
devalued, given revelations about the state-sponsored system of
doping in the former East Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't compare people with East Germans and the system they
came up through,'' said Des Dickie, the American sprint track coach
for cycling.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, speed skaters have long used cycling for
cross-training. The Olympic 500-meter cycling time trial will
consist of two laps around the velodrome. It is not dissimilar to a
500-meter speed skating race. The times are similar, both involve
anaerobic sprints and the athletes are powered by the same primary
muscle groups, quads and glutes. The transfer is one way, however.
Because of the precise technique required, few cyclists take up
speed skating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Skating technique is not something you can learn in a couple
of years,'' Witty said. ``You have to learn when you're young.
Cycling is more brute strength. If you are fit, you can get on a
bike and smooth out your pedal stroke, and it's possible to get to
the top level.''
</P>
<P>
   Felicia Ballanger of France, the world-record holder at 34.0
seconds in the 500-meter time trial, will be favored in Sydney.
Witty's personal best is 35.5. A second and a half is like an hour
when it comes to races decided by hundredths of a second. If Witty
trained full time for cycling, she would be a consistent medal
contender in international events, Dickie said. She finished fourth
at the 1998 world championships. He ranks her among the top six in
Sydney and hopes for the magic of unexpected triumph that makes the
Olympics so riveting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at Olympic skating,'' Witty said. ``You have medal
favorites, and things don't go right, whether they're tense or
something, and someone normally seven through 10 ends up winning
the race or a medal. In the Olympics, you never know.''
</P>
<P>
   She speaks from disappointed experience. She had been favored to
win the 1,000 meters in speed skating at the Nagano Games, only to
grow nervous from expectation. Anxious, excited, Witty set an early
pace that was too fast, and even though she won the silver medal,
she felt as if she had squandered her chance.
</P>
<P>
   In cycling, the pressure of expectation is not so bulging as the
pressure in the tires. Perhaps Witty will feel as relaxed in Sydney
as she did at the 1994 Winter Games in Lillehammer, Norway, when,
as a carefree 18-year-old, she skated a personal best in finishing
23rd in the 1,000-meter race.
</P>
<P>
   ``In '98, I felt like the whole world was on my shoulders,''
Witty said. ``Here, it's kind of a mixture. I'm curious to see how
it will go. Will I start to feel tense? Or will I go back to '94,
beginner-type focus, relaxed?''
</P>
<P>
   As a girl, she skated on baseball diamonds in West Allis that
were flooded and frozen, paying a quarter or a half dollar for an
afternoon on the ice. Her promising career seemed as if it might
end when the factory that made agricultural machinery closed and
her father was left without a job. ``We'll find a way,'' her mother
told Chris and her three older brothers. She and her brother Mike
got paper routes. At skating competitions, they overstuffed hotel
rooms to save money.
</P>
<P>
   At 15 or 16, Witty began cross-training on her bike. She won a
bronze medal at the 1992 world junior championships and followed
with national championships in the 500-meter time trial in 1996 and
'98. The time trial was not an Olympic event in 1996, so Witty
bought her own tickets to the Atlanta Games, watching cycling,
diving, soccer and volleyball. This year, she will be sitting on
her bike in the Sydney velodrome instead of sitting in the
audience.
</P>
<P>
   Witty spent the summer training twice a day for her two sports,
riding her bike and her in-line skates. The biggest difference
between the two? Sunburn, she said. That shouldn't be much of a
problem in the chilly weather of the Southern Hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I chose this Olympics; it's winter,'' she said with
a laugh.
</P>
</TEXT>
