<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Thursday, Sept. 14. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-TRADE (Washington) _ The Senate rejected a plan, the
Thompson-Torricelli amendment, to impose sanctions on China for its
role in weapons proliferation, clearing the way for final passage
of President Clinton's landmark trade pact with Beijing after
months of delay. (Summary from wires) By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-FUEL (London) _ Oil trucks resumed limited deliveries
from petroleum refineries and storage depots on Wednesday, but
Prime Minister Tony Blair failed to break the siege that has left
almost all of Britain's filling stations dry. The flow of supplies
was estimated to be less than 10 percent of regular volume, and
almost all of it was designated for vital services like hospitals,
ambulances, fire and police departments rather than the nation's
gas pumps. The protests against high fuel prices that have
presented Blair with the most serious domestic crisis of his three
and a half years in office continued Wednesday, with pickets
monitoring the rigs exiting the oil company properties and creeping
convoys of truckers creating miles of traffic jams on major
intercity expressways and blocking the passage of cars in London
and other urban centers. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-MCDONALDS (Paris) _ A farmer who became something of a
national hero last year for leading an attack on a McDonald's
restaurant was convicted of criminal vandalism and sentenced to
three months in prison. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   LEE-RELEASE (Albuquerque, N.M.) _ Wen Ho Lee, the former Los
Alamos National Laboratory scientist, was set free Wednesday after
pleading guilty to one count of improperly downloading nuclear
secrets under a plea agreement reached with the government. Judge
James Parker released Lee Wednesday afternoon, with a sentence of
278 days, the time he has already served. He was also fined $100.
The judge apologized to Lee for the ``unfair manner'' of his
incarceration and said the Department of Justice and Energy ``have
embarrassed our entire nation and each of us who is a citizen of
it.'' By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CHASE-MORGAN (Undated) _ Ledeall: Chase Manhattan Corp., the
third-largest banking company in the United States, formally
announced Wednesday that it is acquiring J.P. Morgan Co., an
investment bank. A look at the strategy of Chase Manhattan now that
it has done its long-awaited Big Deal. Can it compete with
Citigroup? Can it meld Morgan's culture, proud of its history, into
its own? What does this deal say about other big banks like Bank of
American that do not have a major presence on Wall Street. By
Patrick McGeehan and Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   CIRCUITS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CIR-APPLE (Undated) _ On Wednesday, after years of waiting by
the Macintosh faithful, Apple Computer released to the public a
beta version of its Mac OS X (10) operating system software. The
system is new not only in its new interface, called Aqua, but also
at its core, which is based on the stable Unix operating system. By
J.D. Biersdorfer.
</P>
