<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2867 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-RANGERS-MESSIER-2     09-13 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-MESSIER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CAPTAIN IS BACK: MESSIER, NEARING 40, RETURNS TO DIRECT
RANGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURLINGTON, Vt. _ Between most hockey players, it would have
been just a routine encounter in the corridor on the first day of
training camp. But Mark Messier is not like most players. Even his
small gestures carry nuance and significance.
</P>
<P>
   So when Petr Nedved walked by the seated Messier, tapped him on
his padded leg and used the nickname ``Mess'' as his pleasant
greeting, you couldn't help notice that Messier responded by
looking up toward Nedved and saying, in his deep voice, ``Hey, how
are ya?'' in a friendly sort of way.
</P>
<P>
   When these two centers first played together on the Rangers, in
1994-95, Messier doubted Nedved's competitive fire, despite
Nedved's elite talent. Messier's animosity resulted in Nedved's
trade to Pittsburgh. In a game soon after that, Messier speared
Nedved. As time passed, Messier left New York in 1997 for three
seasons in Vancouver; Nedved returned to the Rangers in a trade in
1998; and Messier also came back, this time as an unrestricted free
agent in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   How Messier interacts with Nedved _ and just about everyone else
in the organization _ will affect this season's comprehensive
attempt to revive the Rangers, who have missed the playoffs in the
three seasons of Messier's exile. So far, the vibrations are good,
and Nedved is the personification of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's water under the bridge,'' Nedved said, referring to their
past difficulties. ``I was happy that the Rangers signed him. I'm
looking forward to working with him and playing with him. He's
going to make our team that much more dangerous. He's a great
leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Regarding Nedved, Messier said he had researched the subject by
talking with Adam Graves, Mike Richter and Brian Leetch, the only
three Rangers remaining from the 1994 team that Messier led to the
Stanley Cup. Those veterans praised Nedved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody here who has seen him play over the past couple
years can admire his courage, his heart,'' Messier said of Nedved.
``He was battered from pillar to post without receiving the proper
protection a player of his caliber should. He has played hard, game
in and game out.''
</P>
<P>
   Messier, Nedved, Graves, Leetch and Richter should make up
one-quarter of the 20-man roster being shaped by Glen Sather, the
new general manager, and Ron Low, the new coach. And the presence
of Sather and Low should suit Messier, whose disapproval of past
coaches has led to their dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   Sather was the young general manager and coach in Edmonton when
Messier broke into the National Hockey League as an 18-year-old
rookie in 1979. Low was a veteran goalie then, assigned by Sather
to be Messier's roommate on the road. Low watched him develop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark was a pretty rawboned kid at that time,'' Low recalled
after practice the other day at Gutterson Field House. ``He did a
lot of pretty crazy things as a player. He made some horrific
mistakes in his own end. But you could always count on him coming
back and doing something in the other end _ the good end. He was
never afraid to take a chance, to try something.''
</P>
<P>
   Messier is not so raw anymore and he is definitely not a kid. He
is 6 feet 1 inch and listed as 210 pounds, although he appears
heavier. Still bold, he is much balder and much older, among the
senior athletes in professional sports. Messier will celebrate his
40th birthday in January, midway through his 22nd NHL season. He is
the only player still active from the World Hockey Association,
which folded in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   In training camp, Messier appears to be gradually working
himself into shape. In a scrimmage on Monday, Nedved's line
dominated Messier's line with skating speed and puck movement.
Perhaps this was a meaningless workout, but it also encouraged
speculation about how much Messier has left. He left Tuesday's
practice early with a sore groin; the injury is not serious.
</P>
<P>
   In his final season with the Rangers, Messier scored 36 goals.
In three seasons with Vancouver, he accumulated only 52. Despite
changes of coaches, general managers and players, some of them
urged by Messier, the Canucks never made the playoffs while he was
their captain.
</P>
<P>
   They could have kept Messier this season, but they chose to buy
out his option and let him leave with no compensation. For the
Canadian Olympic team of 1998, Messier was not selected. Although
his age, diminishing production, dominant personality and $5.5
million salary would make Messier an awkward fit with some teams
now, the Rangers talk as if they are the right team at the right
time, just as they were in 1991 when he first came to New York from
Edmonton at age 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to have him back where I think he belongs,'' said
Leetch, who gave back the captain's ``C'' to Messier. ``The Ranger
jersey looks the best on him. I never really lost hope. It's going
to be a big boost to a lot of veterans around here. He's a
one-of-a-kind person, and he certainly wears his emotions on his
sleeve.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly this is true: He epitomizes hockey passion. Think of
Messier images over the years: stretching back his head and
laughing to celebrate six Stanley Cup championships, five of them
with Edmonton; or glaring, shouting and swinging at opponents
during angry confrontations on ice; or wiping tears from his eyes
in a Vancouver uniform during his first return to Madison Square
Garden in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never really wanted to leave New York,'' Leetch said.
</P>
<P>
   But he did depart after a contract tiff with Neil Smith, the
former general manager, and Dave Checketts, the president of the
Garden. They felt Messier had become overbearing. His departure
seemed to sap the spirit of Leetch, Richter and Graves. Recently,
in a Burlington restaurant, Messier, Richter and Leetch could be
seen dining and discussing the team's past, present and future.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems the same,'' Richter said of Messier. ``Mark brings an
awful lot to this locker room. And that comes down to character. We
need it.'' But even a disciple like Richter senses some unease.
``At this point in his career, with the type of player that he is,
it's not easy to jump teams,'' Richter said.
</P>
<P>
   In the hallways outside the locker rooms, Messier's presence
dominates the mood. He exudes relaxed authority. Rookies like Jamie
Lundmark, from junior teams, and minor-league hopefuls like Dale
Purinton follow Messier with their eyes as he makes his casual
rounds. And people instinctively step aside when Messier walks
past, just as players do when he skates on the ice. Sandy McCarthy,
a fistfighting expert acquired over the summer, discussed how
Messier intimidates opponents without having to throw punches the
way he once did.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows he's big and tough and you are going to get
something if you mess around with him, if not a stick, an elbow,''
McCarthy said. ``That's why he gets room on the ice.''
</P>
<P>
   Physical intimidation was one of the topics Messier addressed
while standing near the door to the coach's room for a news
conference. ``Toughness and sticking up for each other is something
that comes from within a team,'' Messier said. ``It does not come
from individuals. Part of the problem last year was the team was
fragmented, for whatever reason. The other team can sense it. They
know you are not together and you are not willing to fight for each
other. The whole situation last year got to be in such a downward
spiral that it really just spun out of control for everybody.
Nobody really knew where to turn to or what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said players must abide by a ``code of loyalty'' that
keeps internal discord private. This applied particularly to
Stephane Quintal, a defenseman suspended late last season for
saying he would like to leave the Rangers. Messier has granted
Quintal his forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the important thing for Stephane is to realize he made
a mistake,'' Messier said. ``He put the integrity of the
organization in jeopardy and it had to be dealt with and it was
dealt with.'' According to Quintal, Messier told him: ``Don't worry
about it. Go have fun.'' They should play golf or have lunch,
Messier told Quintal.
</P>
<P>
   Messier understands mistakes: even he makes them, Messier said,
``I've made plenty of mistakes in my career and so has everyone
else, and I'll continue to make mistakes.'' He said he puts them
behind and lives in the present. And he also told the reporters
that they, too, were part of his equation for winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to shed a good light for the public through the
media,'' Messier said. ``We need to be as open and as honest as we
possibly can. We want to be proud of ourselves on and off the ice.
And the way to do that is for us to handle the media properly so
that we convey a good message. Obviously, we did a good job of that
in the years I was here. And it's important to get back to that.''
</P>
<P>
   He also chatted casually about returning to Manhattan and
seeking an apartment on the Upper West Side. Prices are way up in
this prosperous era, he said.
</P>
<P>
   As the day drew to a close, a black Jeep pulled up near the
locker room door, his special transport to the nearby hotel through
the crowd of fans waiting for autographs. Some of them wore blue
and white Ranger jerseys with the name Messier and his number 11 on
the back. The charismatic man who once guaranteed a victory in a
crucial playoff game was not making any grand promises for the
first season of his second coming to New York. Not yet, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not coming back with the idea that things are going to be
the same,'' Messier said. ``In a way, it's good. It keeps it
exciting. Things will be different, but I think different in a good
way. We want to win. The sooner the better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
