<HEADER>
A2879 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-DINOSAURS-NYT &LR;      09-13 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-DINOSAURS-NYT </SLUG>
  
 DISCOVERING DINOSAURS ON 2 CD-ROMs  
 (Circuits)  
 (editors: product notes at end of reviews)  
 Alice Keim, a teacher, is the technology coordinator for the Horace
Mann Lower School in New York  
 By ALICE KEIM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long before Barney sank his purple talons into preschoolers,
dinosaurs fascinated children. Fortunately for parents, the study
of dinosaurs can develop important scientific inquiry skills in
young students, and the academic appeal lasts long after children
learn to distinguish Hollywood fiction from fact.
</P>
<P>
   I had high expectations for ``I See Sue'', a CD-ROM game
developed with The Field Museum of Chicago and based on Sue, the
largest and most complete Tyrannosaurus Rex ever discovered. Sue
was found in South Dakota 10 years ago and went on display in May.
</P>
<P>
   But the Field Museum's Web site (www.thefieldmuseum.com/)
provided more extensive and educational information on Sue and her
environment than the CD-ROM itself.
</P>
<P>
   The disk starts with a catchy jingle and flashes some dinosaur
images as a song explains the game. The program then shows a main
menu screen with four levels of difficulty, sound options and
whether to play against the computer or a friend. Square
color-coded game tiles appear in the bottom third of the screen,
each featuring the head, tail or body of a specific dinosaur. The
object of the game is to match the parts to complete a dinosaur.
</P>
<P>
   After you match three tiles, a completed dinosaur moves along a
trail. There are shortcuts for some species. If they have wings
they can fly over part of the trail, and if they are light and
graceful they can take a log bridge. The first player to complete
the trail is rewarded with a picture of Sue and a dinosaur drawing
to print out and color. Facts on each dinosaur are presented in
clever rhyming sentences that, if re-enforced throughout the
program, could have helped players retain information.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, the game is buried in its limitations. Names and facts
are in audio only, and young users will have trouble remembering
them. There is a help screen, but it only offers pictures of each
dinosaur and details like ``crosses log bridges.''
</P>
<P>
   For a game based on one of the most exciting modern dinosaur
discoveries, ``I See Sue'' is anti-climatic. After finishing the
trail, the player gets to see a bit of Sue accompanied by some
uninspiring animation. The real Sue deserves better.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, DK's ``Dinosaur Hunter Deluxe'' is buried
treasure. The program has two main sections: a virtual museum and
3D environments representing the environments in which the
dinosaurs lived. The environments are interesting, but the museum,
an interactive environment with exhibits and activities, brings
more than 50 species of dinosaurs to life, is a gem.
</P>
<P>
   The virtual visitor can wander the dark museum halls and follow
a time line through the Jurassic, Triassic and Cretaceous periods.
Along the way they can learn about specific dinosaurs and their
characteristics through videos, displays and puzzles. The central
exhibit hall, The Arena, provides extensive information about
Dinosaur anatomy and behavior. The second main exhibit area focuses
on the discovery, including information on where and how dinosaur
fossils were found and details about great discoverers.
</P>
<P>
   The program has brilliant explanations of the dinosaur's
characteristics and behavioral habits. For example, many of the
explanations combine animation with video of modern animals. A
section on how ancient herbivores chewed uses clips of camels to
demonstrate a circular grinding motion and reptiles using an up and
down movement, and then uses animation to show a dinosaur jaw in
motion, which looks like a combination of the above.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors can also go to the Dinosaur Excavation Site, a room
that features The Excavator, which is a virtual machine that allows
the user to uncover bones of dinosaur species. First, the user
chooses a species to complete and then reads about the dinosaur's
history. Next the visitor excavates several layers and uses tools
to find the bones.
</P>
<P>
   Bones can be identified by relative age, body part and shape.
The dig is not particularly difficult, but it requires patience to
search through the layers. Once all the bones are recovered, the
dinosaur comes to life and roams the museum corridors. The program
features wonderful graphics and explanatory animation. Young
dinosaur fans will delight in their prehistoric encounters here.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving the museum, visitors go to the Museum Store.
While the very name may have parents clutching their wallets, the
area offers free program accessories. Shoppers can download images
and sounds to their hard drives, or print out masks, stationary and
postcards. I enjoyed the jukebox where you could hear the sounds of
12 dinosaurs. The museum products are an excellent way to extend
the activities beyond the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dinosaur Hunter Deluxe'' is full of information and
educational activities, but navigating the program was frustrating.
For example, I found myself going in circles as I searched for the
excavation area. There is a help section that explains each area of
the museum, but this did not get me where I wanted to go. The halls
feel like the corridors of a true natural history museum but,
sadly, without the guards to guide you.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCT NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   ``I See Sue ... the T. Rex''
</P>
<P>
   (Simon and Schuster Interactive; $19.95; Windows 95/98 or
Macintosh Power PC.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Dinosaur Hunter Deluxe''
</P>
<P>
   (Dorling Kindersley; $19.95; Windows 95/98/2000.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
