<HEADER>
A2888 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-CHINESE-ANTIQUES-ART-     09-13 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINESE-ANTIQUES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE FOR YOUNG COLLECTORS: HIGH STYLE, LOW PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT4 and 5 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 (editors: sidebar at end of article)  
 By ELAINE LOUIE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Since the late 19th century, when Westerners began
trading extensively with China, there have been established wealthy
collectors seeking Chinese antiques. But in the last 10 years, a
group of younger, less affluent collectors has emerged. ``There are
two separate markets,'' said James Godfrey, the director for
Chinese works of art at Sotheby's auction house in Manhattan.
``There are buyers of classical furniture _ 16th-, 17th- and
18th-century material of huanghuali and zitan,'' two of the most
sought-after hardwoods. (In 1996, a 17th-century Chinese huanghuali
and marble screen sold for $1.1 million at Christie's.)
</P>
<P>
   The second market is for furniture made of camphor, elm,
ironwood or bamboo, said Theow H. Tow, the international director
for Chinese works of art at Christie's. Next week is Asia Week for
Sotheby's and Christie's, who will be offering Chinese camphor, elm
and bamboo furniture that has brought estimates from $4,000 to
$10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, said Lark E. Mason Jr., the director for online
auctions at Sothebys.com, he saw little Chinese furniture outside
of New York, Los Angeles and San Francisco. This year, he said, he
saw it being sold in Tulsa, Okla.
</P>
<P>
   Furniture made of camphor, bamboo and elm, along with simple
domestic objects like lacquered water jugs and ceramic planters,
are coveted by young collectors. For many, the minimalist, simple
lines of Chinese pieces work in a modern interior.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Didik, a producer of CD-ROMs, who is in his 30s, grew up
with parents who revered Asian things, and inherited this passion
rather like a gene. This year, Didik brought home to Brooklyn a
1905 Chinese chair that he bought for $1,200 from Xiaoping Cao, who
sells antiques and her interpretations of Chinese furniture in her
Soho shop. ``The simplistic design can blend with modern pieces,''
Didik said. ``You can't do that with Louis XVI.''
</P>
<P>
   Still others begin collecting Chinese furniture after going to
China. Mary Peng, who sells $50 Chinese wedding baskets and $3,500
Chinese antiques out of her Manhattan loft, said, ``The younger
collectors are seasoned travelers in their 20s, coming back to the
United States, who want to purchase the furniture they had seen
overseas, and who know that antiques don't have to be $10,000 to
start.''
</P>
<P>
   When Tish Durkin, a reporter for The New York Observer, went to
Beijing in 1995 to cover the World Conference on Women, she went to
an antiques market in search of a souvenir. Instead, she bought a
chicken coop/vegetable bin made of camphor wood; it stood 6 feet
tall, and was 39 inches wide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this thing,'' said Durkin, who is in her 30s and has
studied Chinese language and history. ``It was so solid. I love
Chinese language, and there are the characters for spring, summer,
winter and fall carved in the four little doors.'' The price was
$150. Cheaper than a halogen lamp, she noted.
</P>
<P>
   For Audrey Wu, a corporate events specialist in her 30s, who
works at Fulcrum Information Services in Manhattan, collecting
Chinese furniture began spontaneously. She was at an aunt's house
in Manhattan, saw a small wood Chinese kitchen cabinet, and said
something innocuous like ``Oh, what a cute piece of furniture.''
Her aunt gave it to her. The next year, Wu went to Shanghai and met
Annly Chyn, a furniture dealer, who took her to her warehouse
filled with chests, tables, chairs and screens.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were dusty, moldy and fading,'' said Wu, who saw chests
painted with hunters and dragons in a background of golden mist,
and promptly bought one for $300.
</P>
<P>
   Like Didik, Michael Stark, 29, an actor and graphic designer in
Manhattan, grew up in a family that loved all things Chinese. His
grandfather, Alexander Stark, who lived in Denver, collected
Chinese and Japanese art and furniture, and kept it in a private
room (no children allowed). Stark now collects small Chinese wood
chests fitted with bronze, while nurturing the desire to buy a
Chinese table someday.
</P>
<P>
   Mason of Sothebys.com has some advice for neophyte collectors.
``Think in terms of what you can use in your own home, because it's
tough to be a furniture collector of things you can't use,'' he
said. ``Second, think in terms of classic forms.'' As for the
lacquered box or bamboo basket, ``it can be fragile if you're
considering using a basket for magazines,'' he said. And finally,
he said, ``Look for dynamism.''
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   TREASURES OLD AND NEW &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Next week, Chinese furniture will be auctioned at Christie's and
Sotheby's. There are also shops where baskets and cabinets (many of
them restored) can be bought at reasonable prices. When you buy an
antique, ``you are not going to find a perfect piece of
furniture,'' said Theow H. Tow, the international director for
Chinese works of art at Christie's, ``because in every category _
French, English or Chinese _ these things were used and have a part
that's been replaced.''
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTIE'S, 20 Rockefeller Plaza. The Chinese auction will be
Thursday, Sept. 21, at 10 a.m. and at 2 p.m. Information: (212)
636-2000.
</P>
<P>
   SOTHEBY'S, 1334 York Ave. (72nd Street). The Chinese auction
will be Wednesday, Sept. 20, starting at 10:15 a.m. Information:
(212) 606-7332.
</P>
<P>
   XIAOPING DESIGN, 73 Hudson St. (Worth Street). Xiaoping Cao
sells antiques and her own interpretations of Chinese furniture. A
new garden bench starts at $400. Information: (212) 962-4080 or
www.xiaopingdesign.com.
</P>
<P>
   PENG VILLAGE ANTIQUES. Mary Peng sells bamboo baskets ($50)
along with cabinets ($3,500). By appointment: (212) 316-7006 or
www.pengvillage.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
