<HEADER>
A2901 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-KELLY-FILMS-COLUMN-TE     09-13 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELLY-FILMS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUR NEW MOVIE CRITIC PANS CYNICAL REVIEWERS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By CHRISTOPHER KELLY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it was announced that I was going to be the new film critic
for the Star-Telegram, I found myself answering a lot of the same
questions. ``What have you seen recently that you liked?'' (It was
a disappointing summer, but ``The Perfect Storm,'' with its
dazzling wave effects, qualifies as a major guilty pleasure);
``What are your favorite movies of all time?'' (I have lots of
favorites, but lately I've been citing ``A Hard Day's Night,'' Bob
Fosse's ``All That Jazz,'' and Alan Parker's ``Shoot the Moon'');
``Is there anything good coming out?'' (Watch for ``Billy Elliot,''
a British charmer about a young boy who wants to be a ballet
dancer.)
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, though, I'm asked more-general questions _ for
instance, ``What kind of movies do you like?'' or ``What sort of
things do you look for when you're evaluating a movie?'' And it's
here I run into a bit of trouble explaining myself.
</P>
<P>
   Like every other film critic, I have my quirks: I have a soft
spot for certain genres (domestic melodramas, children's films); a
handful of working directors (Jonathan Demme, Todd Haynes, David
Cronenberg) command my attention on even their worst days; and, as
a general rule, I tend to get irritated with movies that
prominently feature either junkies (''Trainspotting,'' ``Jesus'
Son'') or self-declared mutes (''The Piano,'' ``Little Voice'').
</P>
<P>
   Of course, such particulars don't really tell you much about how
I go about doing my job. In which case, I should probably tell you
how I don't go about doing my job _ and explain why I think too
many critics and filmgoers close themselves off to the pleasures
that movies, and movie criticism, can offer.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few years, an alarming number of American film
critics have adopted a doomsayer's pose. Of course, critics have
always bellyached that there aren't any good movies out there, but
more recently their ire has been directed at the audience. In two
widely-read essays, in The New York Times Magazine and The New
Yorker, respectively, Susan Sontag and David Denby both argued that
the real problem with our film culture is not the lack of great
movies, but the fact that an audience no longer exists for
challenging, original filmmaking.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's sentiments like these that leave many moviegoers
feeling alienated from critics. I know that's the way I often feel.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, for example, I saw ``The Sixth Sense'' a week after
it opened in theaters, and after having already been told by a
number of my colleagues that, as clever as the film was, the old
``Twilight Zone'' TV series covered the same material far more
effectively.
</P>
<P>
   Ignore the fact that I disagreed completely; it was, for my
money, one of the very best films of last year. What troubled me
most was how so many critics seemed uninterested in treating the
film as seriously as, say, the French film ``The Dreamlife of
Angels'' _ another film about mortality and emotional anxiety.
Troubling, too, was the fact that so few critics seemed interested
in going back to the film, and trying to understand why it struck
such a chord with viewers.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of critics will lazily suggest that audiences aren't
interested in such dialogue _ that their attention is focused not
on what they've just seen, but on which blockbuster they're going
to see next. I don't agree. Every day, I overhear or participate in
conversations (often with complete strangers) about movies _ recent
and old, obscure and popular _ at the video store, in line at the
bank, while shopping for groceries.
</P>
<P>
   So why are critics so jaded? And why has such a vast disconnect
developed between critics and their readership? The real problem
may be that our film culture looks stranger and more diverse than
it ever has before, especially since the explosion of independent
cinema in the early 1990s and, more recently, with the advent of
new technology. In any given week, you'll see movies that reinvent
filmmaking technique (''Three Kings,'' ``Timecode'') alongside
films that offer nothing but empty technique (''Mission: Impossible
2''), startlingly original films that seem piped in from outer
space (''Holy Smoke,'' ``South Park'') alongside startlingly banal
films that you wish could be shipped off to space (''The Green
Mile'').
</P>
<P>
   In which case, to a lot of people, the resulting film landscape
may look like nothing more than an ungainly _ and doomed _ mess.
The fact that an audience seems to exist for both the original
movies and the wretched ones might further suggest that the
audience just doesn't care what they see. But I like to think it
means that a critic simply has to work harder to sort things out.
</P>
<P>
   We do live in an increasingly speeded-up era, where movies zip
into and out of theaters, and onto and off the pop culture radar,
at a rate that can be exhausting. A critic's main job, then, is to
be the one who does keep up, and who helps readers figure out
what's worth keeping up on. But I also think it's the critic's job
to slow things down a bit _ to hold on to a movie that's
disappearing too fast, to question the value of a film that won't
seem to go away, and to try to figure out which direction the art
form is headed next.
</P>
<P>
   As film critic for the Star-Telegram, I can't promise I'll
always be right in my estimations. I can't even promise I'm always
going to be fair (especially if there is a mute involved). But I do
promise to convey, as accurately and honestly as I know how, why I
think movies still have life in them. And why I think the process
of thinking and talking and arguing about them can sometimes be the
most entertaining part of the show.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
