<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2912 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-DOG-CAMP14-COX     09-13 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOG-CAMP14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dances with dogs
 &HT;    By Ryan Rahe
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OXFORD, Ohio _ Usually reserved for two-legged athletes during
summer sports camps, Camp
</P>
<P>
   America, located just outside of Hueston Woods State Park in
southwest Ohio, recently was home to a unique camp designed for
four-legged friends.
</P>
<P>
   For the past four years Becky and Corkey Campbell have been
running their special breed of dog camp at the facility. The camp
is designed so that dogs and their owners can enjoy activities
together and learn, hands-on, new training techniques with
practical everyday uses.
</P>
<P>
   Each day of the three-day event provides many different
exercises and activities for dogs and their trainers. Activities
such as herding, water games, obstacle courses and agility tests
are held during the morning hours.
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon the dogs get a rest while their owners attend
various lectures on topics ranging from innovations in obedience
training to dog chiropractics and massage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shape behavior through positive methods. We don't use any
negative reinforcement,'' said Becky Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   The positive method approach seemed to be the underlying message
at the dog camp. By teaching your dog to obey you through positive
methods, such as rewards and positive verbal reinforcement, a
trainer develops a better rapport with the dog, and eventually a
friendship built on mutual respect and trust, Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Tucker and his wife, Leigh Ann, were in attendance at this
year's camp to give lessons on sheep herding. Paul, along with his
dog Craig, has won many awards for sheep herding including the Ohio
Valley Dog of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   This year Craig is in fourth place for Ohio Valley Dog of The
Year, despite the fact that he is almost 12 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Paul is very competitive with his dogs, the
competition at the camp is rather nonexistent. There are awards
given for various events, but the main point is to let the dogs
have fun. Even if a dog is not a purebred herding dog, or maybe
even 10 times smaller than the sheep, Paul will still let them have
an opportunity to try their ``paw'' at sheep herding.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only bring experienced sheep, so that they know what to do
even if the dogs don't,'' said Leigh Ann Tucker. ``The purpose is
not to make a sheep dog out of a poodle, it's to let a poodle see
what it's like to be a sheep dog.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the many lecturers in attendance this year was Leslie
Nelson, one the most prominent names in the country for animal
obedience. Nelson spoke about advanced dog training techniques.
Nelson continued the theme of positive reinforcement in her lecture
telling people that the more they force their dog to obey the less
the dog will enjoy activities with them.
</P>
<P>
   A new event this year at the camp is something Darla Paganini
likes to call ``Dancing With Dogs.'' This is like free-style
gymnastics with your dog. The owner and the dog work on a dance
routine set to music and often involving costumes. Darla and her
dog do a routine to the song ``The Lion Sleeps Tonight.'' Darla
wears a safari uniform, her dog a lion costume. They even complete
the event with a bow.
</P>
<P>
   The event that seemed to be enjoyed by the dogs the most was the
lure course.
</P>
<P>
   At this event, basically the dogs chase a white bag around a
field. The bag, or ``bunny'' as it is referred to, is placed on a
wire and run by a generator.
</P>
<P>
   The bag is kept in constant motion, just inches in front of the
dog. ``This is an event just about any dog can do with little or no
training,'' said Corkey Campbell. ``What dog doesn't like to chase
things.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really a camp where you can come and bring your dog to
sample just about everything that is going on either professionally
or for fun,'' said Corkey.
</P>
<P>
   And that is exactly what the camp is, a great place to bring you
dog to have
</P>
<P>
   fun. The camp is open to all dogs and owners.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
