<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN2-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FESTIVALS ARE IN THE AUTUMN AIR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Corrects date of Harvest Festival at the Berkshire Botanical
Garden.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fall is one of the best seasons in New England. There are still
lots of warm and sunny days, the crowds have left the popular
tourist areas, all attractions, restaurants, and resorts are open,
and, best of all, it's the most colorful season, not just from
foliage but also from festivals.
</P>
<P>
   If you have even a hint of Scottish blood, an event next weekend
is one not to miss. It's the 25th anniversary for the New Hampshire
Highland Games Friday through Sunday at Loon Mountain in New
Hampshire. The games have grown to become the largest Scottish
cultural festival in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   And there's more than just ``games'' at this festival. On
Saturday, 39 pipe bands will be performing at noon and 5:30 p.m.
And at 5 p.m. the first-ever Grade One Challenge of the top pipe
bands in the country _ the Los Angeles Scots and the City of
Washington band _ will be held. On Friday evening, Battlefield
Band, Scotland's favorite, will perform, and other musical events
will be held throughout the weekend. There also will be
whisky-tasting seminars, exhibits by more than 60 clans and
societies, dancing, dinners, 20 Scottish food outlets, tartan and
genealogical workshops, athletic events, a sheepdog competition, a
Highland dance championship, and lots of children's activities.
</P>
<P>
   For advance tickets, call 800-358-SCOT. For more information,
visit www.nhscot.org.
</P>
<P>
   Other New England events include:
</P>
<P>
   Harwich Cranberry Harvest Festival, now through Sunday, Harwich
on Cape Cod. Call 800-441-3199.
</P>
<P>
   King Richard's Faire, South Carver, weekends now through
Columbus Day. Call 508-866-5391.
</P>
<P>
   Newport International Boat Show, Newport Yachting Center,
Newport, R.I., Sept. 14-17. Includes an introduction to sailing.
Call 800-582-7846 or visit www.NewportBoatShow.com.
</P>
<P>
   Gloucester Seafood Festival, Sept. 15-17. Call 978-283-1601.
</P>
<P>
   The Eastern States Exposition (The Big E), the sixth largest
fair in North America, West Springfield, Sept. 15-Oct. 1. Call
413-737-2443 (Massachusetts Day is Sept. 21).
</P>
<P>
   Spear Throwing Championship, Chimney Point State Historic Site,
Vermont. 802-828-3051 or visit www.historicvermont.org.
</P>
<P>
   Vermont Archeology Week, Sept. 17-23;, events throughout the
state including hikes, tours, visits to archeology sites, and
talks. Call 802-656-4310.
</P>
<P>
   The 21st Annual Apple Squeeze Festival, Lenox, Sept. 23-24. Call
413-637-3646.
</P>
<P>
   The Berkshire Botanical Garden Harvest Festival in Stockbridge,
Oct. 7-8. Call 413-298-3926.
</P>
<P>
   Fall Foliage Festivals in Vermont's Northeast Kingdom, Sept.
30-Oct. 8. Call 802-563-2472.
</P>
<P>
   Fryeburg (Maine) Fair, Oct. 1-8, the state's largest
agricultural fair. Call 207-935-4725.
</P>
<P>
   The 45th Annual Fall Foliage Festival, North Adams, Oct. 1-10.
Call 413-663-3735.
</P>
<P>
   Cranberry Harvest Festival, Carver and Plymouth, Oct. 10-12.
Call 508-295-5799 or 508-747-2350.
</P>
<P>
   A welcome to the Dutch emissaries from New Amsterdam, Oct.
10-12, Plimoth Plantation, Plymouth. Re-creates historic 1627
meeting. Call 508-746-1622.
</P>
<P>
   Festival of Scarecrows, Oct. 14-28, Farnsworth Art Museum,
Rockland, Maine. Also on view is Andrew Wyeth's ``Christina's
World.'' Call 207-596-6457 or visit www.farnsworthmuseum.org.
</P>
<P>
   Berkshire Museum Festival of Trees, Pittsfield, Nov. 18-Dec. 31.
Call 413-443-7171.
</P>
<P>
   If that's not enough to keep you busy, call the Mount Washington
Valley Visitors Bureau (800-367-3364) for a free copy of ``More
than 50 Nifty and Free things to do'' in the valley.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Canada deals
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One way to catch the fall colors and save is to cross the border
and take in the Canadian sights. The Deerhurst Resort in
Huntsville, Ontario (800-461-4393), offers a Two for Tee package
that includes a round of golf at each of the resorts' courses
starting at $101 a night a person; the Westin Nova Scotian in
Halifax offers a package that includes accommodations and full
breakfast as well as parking at $107 a night (call 902-496-7435).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shenandoah in fall
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of America's most accessible national parks, Shenandoah,
just two hours from Washington, D.C., features some grand fall
colors and the scenic Skyline Drive, a spectacular 105-mile
journey. It's a road with a posted speed of 35 miles an hour, and
for good reason _ its a road for pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   You'll want to take your time and look for white-tailed deer,
black bear and bobcats, wild turkey, owls, and more than 200 other
bird species. The park's 196,000 acres include more than 100
varieties of trees, 200 species of birds, and 1,100 flowering
plants. Foliage in the park usually peaks between Oct. 5 and 25 In
addition to its natural wonders, the park includes a presidential
retreat that can be visited. Camp Rapidan was built by President
Herbert Hoover as a retreat, for himself and future presidents.
President Franklin D. Roosevelt instead built Camp David, which has
been used by all presidents since. Hoover donated the camp to the
National Park Service, which is now restoring it to its original
1931 appearance. For information on lodging, dining, and other
services in the park, call 800-778-2850 or visit
www.visitshenandoah.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mark Twain guide
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I never saw a place where morality and huckleberries
flourished as they do here,'' wrote Mark Twain about Hartford in
1868. Twain made his home in Hartford from 1871 to 1891, his most
productive years. Now there is a free brochure, ``Mark Twain's
Hartford,'' listing 17 sites associated with the author. While the
first place to visit is his home, now a National Historic Landmark,
the guide ``offers opportunities for outdoor recreation, shopping,
and dining, for a day or a weekend,'' said David Bush of the Mark
Twain House. For a copy, call 860-247-0998, ext. 40, e-mail
twain(at)hartnet.org, or write to Mark Twain House, 351 Farmington
Ave., Hartford, CT 06105. For more information on Twain, visit
www.MarkTwainHouse.org. For a free Connecticut Vacation Guide, call
800-282-6863 or visit www.ctbound.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New York in fall
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you are looking for ideas on visiting New York in the fall,
call for a free ``I Love NY Autumn Guide'' at 800-CALL NYS or visit
www.
</P>
<P>
   iloveny.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shrine visit
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 1, the pope will elevate Philadelphia-born Katharine
Drexel to sainthood. She founded the Sisters of the Blessed
Sacrament in 1891 and dedicated her life to Native America and
African American poor throughout the United States. With her
canonization, thousands are expected at her shrine in Bensalem, a
suburb of Philadelphia. Franklin Mills Mall and three area hotels
are offering travel packages that include a visit to her shrine and
accommodations. For information, call 212-632-1500 or visit
www.franklin-mills-mall.com.
</P>
