<DOCNO> NYT20000913.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2928 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-EMPTY-NEST-2TAKES-NYT     09-13 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMPTY-NEST-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SILVER LINING IN EMPTY NESTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla., N.C., Conn., Pa., Calif., Mass., Minn., Mo.)   By DEBORAH BALDWIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two weeks ago, we packed our daughter's sneakers,
CDs, laptop and rice cooker and drove her to college, doing our bit
to contribute to the biggest youth exodus since Woodstock. During
the weeks bracketing Labor Day, more than 13 million students
enrolled as college undergraduates, the first loud rumblings of a
baby boom echo that will have social ramifications for years to
come.
</P>
<P>
   Personal ramifications, too. Imagine our pangs the first time we
caught a glimpse of our daughter's new home, where vegan is the
preferred diet, ``clothing optional'' is a regular event and party
invitations hang in hallways next to envelopes of condoms.
</P>
<P>
   Turning back toward New York in a rental van suddenly grown
still, we wondered how our parents ever adjusted to life as
proprietors of empty nests.
</P>
<P>
   Then we had an epiphany: we hadn't lost a daughter _ we had
gained a room.
</P>
<P>
   When offspring leave, it creates a hole in the household, both
physical and psychological. ``It means a whole stage of your life
is over,'' said one mother of three, Audrey Goldsmith Kubie, who
has kept her oldest daughter's bedroom pretty much intact since her
daughter enrolled at Duke University, six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, in cities where space is often in short
supply, the departure of college-bound offspring opens up some
valuable real estate. ``At first I just used his desk,'' said Dr.
Jeannette Lofas, a family therapist, recalling the thrill of found
space in her Manhattan apartment when her son left for college.
</P>
<P>
   Careful to respect borders, she resisted opening drawers and
poking around. ``Then I moved in my PC,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he graduated, the takeover was a fait accompli, and
the boy's bedroom no longer contained a bed. When her son
boomeranged back temporarily after college, she cast about for a
new place to put him and finally found it ``in a back room.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale Burg, a New York writer, though careful not to let the
words ``what I could get for this if I put it on the open market''
pass her lips in front of her son, started mentally overhauling the
space he left over Labor Day weekend, when he entered Skidmore as a
freshman. During his last two years of high school, he had been
living in a studio apartment that is part of the family's co-op.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leaving it vacant, that's insane,'' said Burg, picturing its
potential as a guest room. She did suggest that he ``tidy up''
before taking off. Instead, he staked his turf (and temporarily
ruined it for anyone else) by leaving his shoes and other debris
all over the floor, ``as if Vesuvius exploded and then it was
frozen in time.''
</P>
<P>
   Real estate, a number of psychologists and family therapists
explained, often has an emotional subtext.
</P>
<P>
   ``Home is not only Mom and Dad, it's your room, too,'' said Dr.
Harold S. Koplewicz, a child psychiatrist and director of the Child
Study Center at New York University. He still remembers his little
sister trying to seize his bedroom when he left New York for the
University of Maryland 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Separation is one of the major tasks of adolescence,'' he
added. ``One thing we would counsel is, don't call the decorator
right away.''
</P>
<P>
   My parents didn't call a decorator, but they didn't have to. The
day after my college acceptance letter arrived, one of my brothers
appeared in the doorway of my 9-by-9 suburban bedroom, carrying his
collection of Rex Stout paperbacks and eyeing some display space
where my mother and I had hung a single roll of French wallpaper.
He was squeezed into shared quarters and thought my monastic single
would be an excellent place to spread his wings, the sooner the
better. During school holidays I moved in with my sister. I've
repressed the details.
</P>
<P>
   At least my parents stayed put (the wallpaper, pocked with my
brother's nail holes, hangs on). There are those parents who take
what one psychologist termed the passive-aggressive route: While a
child is away, they move.
</P>
<P>
   Every generation has to cope with the big handoff. What makes
this year's high school graduates different is their commitment to
higher education _ 65 percent will attend college, according to the
U.S. Department of Education _ and their large numbers. Reflecting
a growth spurt expected to peak around 2009, about 4 million
Americans turn 18 this year, up from about 3.3 million in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Many parents retain warm memories of coming home during their
raucous college years to comforting pink chenille bedspreads or,
more recently, ``Star Wars'' posters and Nirvana ticket stubs.
Bryan Burkhart, a co-author of ``Airstream: A History of the Land
Yacht'' (Chronicle Books), said he loved returning to San Diego
well into his 20s and finding ``no real changes except for the
sheets on the bed.'' His parents not only kept his younger siblings
at bay but maintained this historic site until he was 30, ``all
mine,'' he noted proudly, ``archaeologically speaking.''
</P>
<P>
   The shrine syndrome can indicate other problems. Dr. David
Lowenstein, a family therapist, said he sees many couples who
preserve rooms as an emblem of a time when they didn't have to talk
about (or even to) each other. Fragile marriages, he said, often
crack under the strain of silence. ``They have done a great job as
parents and forgotten how to be husband and wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually most fledglings need an assertive nudge out of the
nest, Koplewicz said, and once children are on their own, parents
can go about their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing says goodbye more clearly than emptying closets of
sports trophies and prom dresses _ or taking down walls. Garry
McGrath, an architect in St. Louis, said he does a brisk business
redesigning empty suburban nests to incorporate long-deferred
master bedroom suites and dream kitchens, with plenty of space for
an espresso machine _ and a breakfast nook for two.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Nests can't be rebuilt until children make a clean break, and
college separations are often messy. Part of the problem, several
family therapists said, is the way baby boomers rear their
children.
</P>
<P>
   Dwelling on every detail of the lives of their offsprings, from
first burp to last lines of college applications, baby boomers tend
be both solicitous and expectant, as if their children were
interesting extensions of themselves and their life work. When
families also inhabit small dwellings, the intimacy can overwhelm
children, forcing them to fight their way out.
</P>
<P>
   As college drew nearer, so did my daughter's secret identity.
Shedding her nice-guy act, she seemed suddenly irritated to find me
paging through one of her Cosmopolitan magazines, pausing to study
``Make Him Ache for You.'' Then came cruel attacks on my occasional
memory lapses and less-than-perfect pocketbook-organizing skills.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Barkin, author of ``When Your Kid Goes to College: A
Parent's Guide'' (Avon Books, 1999), said she was inspired to put
pen to paper after her own son began to act oddly just before
leaving. Friends related the same thing about their college-bound
offspring. ``This was supposed to be this summer of family
togetherness,'' she said one friend told her. ``My kid won't even
talk to me long enough to say whether he needs extra-long sheets''
for the extra-long mattresses colleges have these days.
</P>
<P>
   Jo Ellyn Rackleff of Tallahassee, Fla., whose children are 16,
19 and 21, described the drama that occurred in seeing the older
two off to college in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``They flop back and forth between incredibly childlike demands
and assertions of their `rights' as an adult,'' she said, adding:
``I think there is a natural impulse, maybe some kind of hormone
that gets released, that makes the parent and child do everything
to upset each other, so that the atmosphere in the nest is
sufficiently toxic to allow the bond to break enough for them to
fly.''
</P>
<P>
   Some parents use the term ``separation anxiety'' to describe the
mutual feelings. While clinically inexact, the term is apt, said
Dr. Nancy Giles, a psychologist in New York and the mother of three
adult children. While working with a group of pediatricians many
years ago, she tuned in to the way adults address 5-year-olds,
clapping them on the back and saying heartily, ``You're going off
to kindergarten! You're going to learn to read!''
</P>
<P>
   She said she often saw children hunched over as if bearing the
weight of the world. ``We trumpet these milestones,'' she said, and
often forget the follow-up: `` `You've gone off and done it before,
and you'll do a great job again.'''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jeffrey Cohen, a psychiatrist in Stamford, Conn., said he
had counseled a family whose only child was barely out of the house
when the parents announced they were splitting up, a development
that caught the son off guard. ``He got very angry with both of
them,'' Cohen said, because ``separation was already an issue,''
and the parents had made it much worse.
</P>
<P>
   Even in solid families, breaking up is hard to do. Kubie, who is
studying for a master's degree in social work at New York
University, remembers the day she and her husband dropped off their
firstborn at Duke. They had driven to Durham, N.C., from New York
with a friend and her daughter, also enrolling at Duke, and the
friend's housekeeper. ``We cried most of the way home,'' Kubie said
of the three women in the car, ``and it was a nine-hour trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the Kubies' third and last child is looking at
colleges, they have become philosophical. ``Every time one of the
girls left home, we bought another dog,'' Kubie said.
</P>
<P>
   Most parents weather the transition, said Dr. Robert L. Myers, a
psychologist in Chester, Pa., but for others the departure of
children can intensify the anxiety that 50-somethings face when
they look back on life and wonder what they have to show for it. To
ease this kind of post-parting depression, they head for the mall.
Mom's in charge of finding those extra-long twin sheets, and Dad
gets to exercise his wallet at the Wiz. This is the generation of
parents more likely than their own to treat children as equals,
taking them everywhere and conferring with them about every life
decision and consumer purchase. It may be one reason parents feel
guilty when they experience an overwhelming desire to turn a
child's private space into a retreat for watching television and
lifting weights.
</P>
<P>
   Taking over a child's abandoned room can be seen as marital
therapy, a sign that parents have a joint mission and a desire to
get on with life.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Salley, who designs houses on Cape Cod, sees a lot of
interesting family dynamics played out on the drawing board. One
couple communicated their late-in-life romance to children from
their previous marriages by tearing down bedroom walls for a
massive master bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Parents in other popular student-destination cities report that
it's not loneliness they suffer from but their taxing new roles as
innkeepers. Blair and Helaine Kaplan Prentice, who run a design
firm in Berkeley, Calif., gamely rose to the challenge when their
son Asa brought three fraternity brothers home from MIT this
summer. To augment sleeping arrangements in the hillside house they
designed when Asa and his brother were little, the Prentices
borrowed mattresses from neighbors and jury-rigged a platform bed
with plastic recycling bins. In August, as Asa was heading east for
his sophomore year, his father was busy devising a system of
couches able to morph into beds.
</P>
<P>
   Other parents prepare long in advance. When their three children
were still small, Georgiana Allan, a designer, and her husband,
Jerry Allan, an architect, created a house with maximum flexibility
for their family in Afton, Minn. Allan designed an oversize bedroom
for their artistically inclined daughter and a suite with two small
bedrooms for the boys, with common space between, separated from
the rest of the house by French doors. The notion was to create
privacy during their teen-age years (and ``when they come back with
their own families,'' Allan said hopefully) and a room that could
be converted for use by guests when their daughter left for
college.
</P>
<P>
   We've acquired a few extra mattresses of our own, just in case
our daughter pops in, bringing along her new family. And we have
been kept busy: putting all our stuff back into her dresser,
converting her bed back into our sofa and spreading out our
paperwork everywhere. I have caught up on Henry James and
refamiliarized myself with the ceiling tiles at the corner gym; and
my husband has begun renovating a closet.
</P>
<P>
   We looked at the calendar: only 70 days till Thanksgiving.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
