<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2937 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-PHILLY-MUSEUM-NYT     09-13 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-PHILLY-MUSEUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSEUM GOERS GET A VIRTUAL HANDS-ON EXPERIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By CATHERINE GREENMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most of the ceramics, lacquer ware and hand scrolls by the
17th-century Japanese artist Hon'ami Koetsu on display at the
Philadelphia Museum of Art are protected under heavy glass and dim
lighting. But two fragile items have been digitally recreated to
allow museum visitors to experience them as the artist intended: by
handling them.
</P>
<P>
   The two reproductions _ of a ceramic tea bowl and a 27-foot-long
painted scroll, are the result of a three-year project of the staff
and students at the International Academy of Media Arts and
Sciences, in Gifu, Japan. In both cases, a reproduction of the
object, which the user handles, is connected to a computer system
that shows corresponding images of the original.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was not to make just a replica but to give a sense of
what it is like to hold a tea bowl, or turn the scroll,'' said
Felice Fischer, curator of Japanese/East Asian Art at the museum,
where the Koetsu exhibition is running until Oct. 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an attempt to bring these static items to life and to
show their use to an audience that is totally unfamiliar with
Japanese art.''
</P>
<P>
   Using technology to incorporate a tactile experience into the
exhibition was important, Fischer said, because of the way such
objects were used in 16th- and 17th-century Japan. During tea
ceremonies and poetry readings, tea bowls and hand scrolls were
passed around or read among small groups of friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were luxury items, for special occasions, but meant to be
used,'' Fischer said.
</P>
<P>
   To recreate the original black Shichiri (``seven seas'') tea
bowl, a CAT scan was taken of it, which allowed the academy staff
and students in Japan to obtain precise information about the
clay's density and air pockets, and the subtle gradations in
Koetsu's pottery. (Like most artists during that time, Koetsu did
not use a potter's wheel, but molded his bowls by hand.) From the
CAT scan, the academy team produced an exact model of the bowl made
of hardened resin.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit uses a motion-tracking system developed by Polhemus,
based in Colchester, Vt. The resin bowl sits on a platform with a
flat-panel computer screen behind it. The bowl is tethered by a
cord containing a small receiver, with a transmitter underneath the
platform that creates an electromagnetic field.
</P>
<P>
   The system tracks the position and orientation of the receiver
as the resin bowl is picked up and handled, sending the data to a
PC, which uses graphics software to synchronize the replica's
movement with a three-dimensional rendering of the real bowl on the
screen.
</P>
<P>
   If the clear resin bowl is turned upside down, for example, the
computer screen will show an image of the original bowl turning
upside down as well.
</P>
<P>
   Although the resin bowl is clear and the original is black with
brown spots, the handlers get a sense of the exact shape and weight
of the bowl, and they can touch the characteristic smooth insides,
which were thought to be necessary for whisking the fine tea
powder.
</P>
<P>
   And although they can't feel the heat from a cup of tea, they
can feel how Koetsu made the bottom of the bowl thicker, so as to
warm the hands of the drinker without burning them.
</P>
<P>
   The handscroll exhibit is a reproduction of Koetsu's Crane
Scroll, which he collaborated on with another Japanese artist,
Tawaraya Sotatsu. (Sotatsu painted streaming motifs of cranes on
the scroll, while Koetsu wrote 36 Japanese poems on top of the
artwork, in calligraphy.)
</P>
<P>
   The scroll was constructed much like the original, with dowels
on both ends and paper that is similar in quality to the original.
The paper, however, is blank, sits underneath a sheet of glass and
acts as a display screen for images from the original scroll from a
projector underneath it, which is connected to a PowerMac G4.
</P>
<P>
   The scroll's dowels contain sensors that detect the user's
scrolling motions, which are sent to the computer, so that when the
scroll is turned, the corresponding verse and images are projected
onto the paper.
</P>
<P>
   Pressing a button on the glass causes the projector to show only
the calligraphy or only the cranes. The cranes alone can appear to
be either a group of cranes on the sheet, or the flight path of a
single crane, an effect that resembles modern-day animation
techniques, Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   The Crane Scroll exhibit also plays the chanted versions of the
poems. The oral chants are synchronized with the scroll sensors to
stop and start as the scroll is turned.
</P>
<P>
   The original tea bowl, on loan from a Tokyo museum, is on
display in an adjacent gallery at the museum, and the original
Crane Scroll, lent by the Kyoto National Museum, will be added to
the exhibit on Sept. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher said she had been pleasantly surprised at the level of
care museum visitors were taking with the exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology can be a useful tool, but sometimes it's tricky
because images on a screen can turn an exhibit into a toy or
game,'' Fisher said. ``But we think this works because you're
handling the objects rather than only pushing buttons or a mouse.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
