r l BC-DOGDRINK-SPORTS-TEX     09-13 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOGDRINK-SPORTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS DRINK IS FOR THE DOGS, BUT NOT ANDY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By JESSIE MILLIGAN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He looks at me with disappointment and resentment in his deep
brown eyes, as if to say, ``How could you do this to me?''
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is Rebound, `The World's First Sports Drink for
Dogs,''' I tell my West Highland white terrier, Andy.
</P>
<P>
   He will not drink it. He looks at me as if I'd poured him
poison.
</P>
<P>
   This, from a dog whom I have caught drinking out of the toilet.
</P>
<P>
   This, from a dog whose favorite food groups include anything
that has been dead at least one week.
</P>
<P>
   Andy will not drink Rebound, the canine equivalent of Gatorade.
</P>
<P>
   He turns up his nose and walks away, not caring that this 1.5
liters of dog stuff cost me $2.49, plus tax.
</P>
<P>
   Rebound is the brainchild of Gene B. Reilly and Robert Kodobocz,
both in their early 30s. The pair concocted the formula in an
Atlanta garage, formed a company called National Pet Supply to
market the dog drink, then found national distribution through
Kroger to more than 3,400 grocery stores around the nation. The
drink is sold at other retail stores and on several Internet sites.
</P>
<P>
   Rebound went on the market less than a year ago, and its sales
are likely to top $1 million this year, according to National Pet
Supply.
</P>
<P>
   Rebound is supposed to replace fluid and salts lost to the
process of panting during exertion. That's a reasonable concept.
Veterinarians in California and Alabama are quoted in the
Petsmart.com pet-care library as saying a dog will recover from
lack of water more quickly if it is given Pedialyte, a fluid
replacement for children, or Gatorade, a sports drink for people.
Just as these drinks are loaded with electrolytes, so is Rebound.
Electrolytes are minerals such as potassium and sodium that
transmit electrical impulses through the body.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes I think my Andy has too many electrical impulses
running through his body, and come to think of it, that may be
what's going on during his frenzied attempts to catch his own tail.
</P>
<P>
   Rebound also has vitamin E to combat stress. Andy has not had
any stress in his life since the other day, when the mailman came
to kill us _ or at least that's what Andy appeared to be suspecting
as he ferociously defended us from the uniformed agent of the
federal government who was armed with a package of socks and such
from One Hanes Place.
</P>
<P>
   Rebound's label says, ``It is modeled after human sports drinks
but has been formulated to meet the needs of today's canine
athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   Canine athlete? I should have known. Andy is not a canine
athlete, not unless 18-hour naps are a sport. Maybe, if
synchronized twitching becomes an Olympic event.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rebound contains less salt and sugar than sports drinks
intended for people,'' the label says.
</P>
<P>
   Which is probably why Andy won't drink it. He likes things
intended for people. Once I left the table to answer the telephone
during dinner. I said ``no thanks'' to the telemarketer, turned
around, and saw Andy sitting in my chair, nose in my dinner,
looking for more salt and sugar.
</P>
<P>
   So we stand there, my dog and I, looking at each other. I have a
1.5 liter bottle of sports drink for dogs in my hand. Our eyes
lock. I lift the bottle of Rebound and take a swig, thinking that
this will make it desirable to him.
</P>
<P>
   It tastes like watered-down Gatorade, which is not at all
desirable to me.
</P>
<P>
   I splash some on the kitchen floor, knowing how enthralled Andy
is with anything that falls there. When I cook, he is right by my
feet, staring at the floor where a morsel may fall at any moment.
He is my ever-vigilant spill hound. I trip over him frequently.
</P>
<P>
   But Andy does not lap up the puddle of sports drink for dogs. He
looks at it sideways. He looks at me sideways.
</P>
<P>
   I am sure there is a dog somewhere that likes sports drinks for
dogs. They all have different eating preferences. Andy likes
carrots and once tried to jump inside the refrigerator to get one.
But he won't eat any other vegetable, not unless it is covered with
salt or sugar, appears to be something I would like to eat and has
fallen on the kitchen floor in a place just out of his reach. Then
he wants it. Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   Rebound might best be reserved for the real athletes of the dog
world. Andy and I, we will stick to plain water.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
