<HEADER>
A2945 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-CUNY-ENROLL-475&AMP;AD     09-13 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CUNY-ENROLL-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRESHMAN CLASS GROWS AT CUNY, FIRST INCREASE IN 5 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The number of new freshmen in the senior colleges at
the City University of New York this fall has risen by 5 percent,
and at some campuses by more than 20 percent, according to
preliminary figures provided by the university.
</P>
<P>
   The increase, the first in five years, comes despite predictions
that CUNY's new policy of ending remedial instruction at CUNY's
senior colleges would cut sharply into enrollment. This is the
first year that the new policy is being applied on some campuses.
</P>
<P>
   CUNY officials attributed the gain to better-educated
applicants, more aggressive recruiting efforts and their efforts to
rebuild CUNY's image. They said that students who might once have
rejected CUNY as a remedial factory were now seeking admission and
that 87 percent of the applicants _ up from 80 percent a year ago _
were able to pass the entrance examinations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This increase shows that the reputation of the university has
improved and is attracting more and better students,'' said Dr.
Louise Mirrer, CUNY's vice chancellor for academic affairs.
</P>
<P>
   But there were more skeptical explanations as well.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the faculty union said they feared that CUNY was
bending its admissions guidelines to fill seats with unprepared
students, and that the numbers did not reveal whether minority
students were being squeezed out of the senior colleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``A large number of students came in at the last minute, and the
first question is who these students are and whether they are
prepared,'' said Steven London, the first vice president of the
faculty and staff union, the Professional Staff Congress.
</P>
<P>
   He said that many of the students who signed up at on-the-spot
recruiting drives were admitted without providing academic or
financial records. ``How many of these students will be here in a
month or two, I don't know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On at least one campus, Brooklyn College, where freshman
enrollment rose by 24 percent, there was a sharp increase in
students admitted through its SEEK program for economically and
educationally disadvantaged students who do not meet the regular
entrance criteria. (SEEK stands for Search for Education, Elevation
and Knowledge.)
</P>
<P>
   While the SEEK students will not be taking remedial classes,
their academic background is considered roughly equivalent to those
admitted as remedial students in previous years. SEEK is mandated
by the state Legislature. About two-thirds of the increase in
Brooklyn's freshmen enrollment (to 1,315 from 1,057 last year) can
be attributed to the increase in SEEK students.
</P>
<P>
   But Mirrer maintained that an improvement in CUNY's rigor and
reputation was responsible for the increased enrollment. She said
that at the senior colleges, which have been raising their own
entrance requirements in recent years, more students were arriving
with stronger high school records.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   She said that the number of students with four or more years of
high school English, for example, had risen by 10 percent to 11,381
this year, while those with three or more years of college
preparatory mathematics had climbed 6 percent, to 11,132. At the
same time, she said, the number of students with grade point
averages of 80 or higher (10,739) had risen by 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   She said that CUNY did not yet have data about the racial and
ethnic composition of the incoming class and could not say yet
whether it had changed since last year.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in freshmen helped stabilize CUNY's overall
enrollment, which has fallen since 1994, when it reached a recent
peak of 212,634 students. Total enrollment late last week was
195,620, up 0.3 percent from last year. CUNY officials expect to
revise the figures when they take their formal student census next
month, but do not expect the trends to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are beginning to think of CUNY as not the school of
last resort,'' said Larry Edwards, the liaison between CUNY and the
Board of Education and deputy to both chancellors. ``It's all
perception, and perceptions are beginning to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Sohmer, president of the university faculty senate, said
he expected the enrollment figures to be slightly lower in October
when the formal student census occurs, but he expected the freshmen
totals to still show gains. ``I don't think the increase will turn
out to be 5 percent, but I do think something positive has
happened,'' he said. ``There seems to be a turnaround.''
</P>
<P>
   Many public universities, including the State University of New
York, have shown enrollment gains in recent years as a college
degree has become more important to earn a decent salary.
</P>
<P>
   Tuition is $3,200 a year at CUNY's senior colleges, compared
with $3,400 at SUNY. A SUNY spokesman said he did not yet have data
on enrollments for this year, but that the number of freshmen at
SUNY's four-year colleges grew 4 percent (to 29,007) last year.
</P>
<P>
   CUNY began to lose enrollment in 1994, as it struggled with
cutbacks in its state aid and growing attacks from Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, Gov. George Pataki and its own board members, including
Herman Badillo _ now the chairman _ who asserted that the education
it offered was second-rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of rancor and negativity,'' said Matthew
Goldstein, CUNY's chancellor. He said CUNY lost students when it
put a one-year limit on remedial work at the senior colleges in
1995; he also said it lost more than 20,000 students on public
assistance when the city began to require welfare recipients to
work.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, CUNY's trustees voted to stop admitting any remedial
students to the senior colleges. Under its new policy, students who
cannot demonstrate their readiness for college-level English and
math may not enroll in bachelor's degree programs, but may enroll
in the two-year community college programs.
</P>
<P>
   The new policy took effect on seven of CUNY's 11 senior college
campuses this year, and will take effect at the others next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
