<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HURRICANE EVACUATION ROUTES COULD BE OVERWHELMED, STUDY SAYS
 &HT;    By ANGEL WILSON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Population growth in the Southeast over the past
decade has put a strain on hurricane evacuation routes, according
to a report released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The American Meteorological Society said shelters should be set
up along the evacuation routes so that people can seek shelter if
they are still on the road during a hurricane's landfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the increased population, relying strictly on
evacuation won't work,'' said Richard Greenfield, director of the
society's Atmospheric Policy Program, which developed the report in
response to a forum this summer sponsored by the Weather Channel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to find, in effect, backups,'' explained John
Clizbe(cq), vice president of Disaster Services for the American
Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   During the past decade, the number of people living in the
southern Atlantic states increased from 43.5 million to 49.5
million, according to the U.S. Census Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   The evacuation problem was highlighted by Hurricane Floyd last
year, when major roads were clogged by thousands of people being
evacuated in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The report noted that responses to evacuation warnings are often
uneven, with 30 percent of the population evacuating unnecessarily
and another 30 percent refusing to go.
</P>
<P>
   Although the number of fatalities from hurricanes has diminished
during the past century, before satellites gave forecasters early
warnings of approaching storms, ``the last 10 hurricane seasons
remind us that we are still vulnerable,'' Greenfield said. ``It's
just a matter of time before a major hurricane hits a vulnerable
area of the coast.''
</P>
<P>
   James Lee Witt, the director of Federal Emergency Management
Agency, said 20 percent of the U.S. population lives in
hurricane-prone areas along the southeast coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem,'' he said, is that ``the infrastructure
has not kept up with the population.
</P>
<P>
   Among the forum's recommendation were:
</P>
<P>
   _ A national hurricane preparedness assessment. This
Congress-mandated survey would evaluate the nation's vulnerability
to hurricanes, the existing systems and services, and propose
policies to improve them.
</P>
<P>
   _ Year-round communication. Strengthening the present hurricane
warning and response system to a year-round, closely coordinated
system involving national, regional, and local public and private
sector agencies.
</P>
<P>
   _ More research money. Congress should develop legislation to
provide long-term, continuous financial support for hurricane
research and improved services.
</P>
<P>
   John J. Kelly, director of the National Weather Service,
stressed that no matter how good the system improves, ``it will be
nothing'' unless people and communities respond to them.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   The Weather Channel: www.weather.com
</P>
<P>
   American Meteorological Society: www.ametsoc.org/AMS
</P>
<P>
   Federal Emergency Management Agency: www.fema.gov
</P>
<P>
   National Hurricane Center: www.nhc.noaa.gov
</P>
<P>
   Angel Wilson's e-mail address is angelw(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
