<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2961 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-ONLINE-SHOPPING-NYT &LR;      09-13 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-SHOPPING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE SHOPPER: UNDERCOVER BUYING, FAKE NAMES AND ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are a lot of things I do on Amazon.com that I don't
necessarily want everyone to know about.
</P>
<P>
   The day I compared prices on home pregnancy tests comes to mind.
So does the time that I placed a Bruce Springsteen CD in my
shopping cart, then removed it after being teased by my husband
(who refers to the aging Springsteen as ``the Wayne Newton of our
generation''). I am embarrassed about the hours I waste checking
the sales ranks of books I have written.
</P>
<P>
   So it hit me hard when Amazon.com recently announced a change in
its privacy policy. Under the old policy, the company said it
didn't sell, trade or rent its customers' personal information to
other companies. Under the new policy? I have no idea how many
people are someday going to get hold of my ``click stream data''
and find out that I had once priced ``Jane Fonda's Yoga Exercise
Workout'' video. (It was a gag gift, I swear.)
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly Amazon.com's cheery personal greeting _ ``Hello, M.
Slatalla. We have recommendations for you in Books, Music and
more'' _ seemed a little sinister. So the next time I shopped at
Amazon.com, I decided to slip on a disguise.
</P>
<P>
   I had a lot of choices. A number of escrow services and
online-payment companies have begun to act as go-betweens to limit
buyers' exposure to sellers. Last week, for example, American
Express announced that within a month, cardholders would be able to
use disposable credit-card numbers when shopping online. That is
happening because of growing concerns over how online shoppers can
preserve their privacy. (I think it's fair to say that all of us
who searched for Play-Doh at Disney's Toysmart.com felt a little
burned recently when the company threatened to sell its customer
list.)
</P>
<P>
   I wanted to hide everything about myself, so I went to
PrivateBuy.com, a new service from an e-commerce payments company
called Ecount, in Conshohocken, Pa. PrivateBuy promised to create
an untraceable online identity.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works. You give information to PrivateBuy _ your
e-mail address, your name and address, a credit card number and
expiration date _ and PrivateBuy issues you a secret identity to
use when shopping online. Your camouflage includes a name (the
worldly yet mysterious Private Buyer), a MasterCard account number
and expiration date to use when making purchases, and a billing
address (the stately 7156 Private Buy Lane, Privacy, PA 00000).
Before making a purchase, you must finance your PrivateBuy account
with a real credit card payment; PrivateBuy then will authorize
payments on your MasterCard up to that amount.
</P>
<P>
   That all sounded fine, but then something occurred to me: Why
should I trust PrivateBuy.com any more than Amazon.com? Just
because the service had the word ``private'' in its name? Call me
paranoid, but what if Ecount someday changed its privacy policy and
decided to share information?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, there's no guarantee,'' said Paul Raden, Ecount's
co-founder. ``But our whole product is based on getting people to
trust us. Our credibility would diminish.''
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat mollified, I then took a look at PrivateBuy.com's
prices. It costs $3.95 every time you put money into your
Privatebuy.com account. Either you put in a specific amount and
then spend it gradually _ most customers add $100 at a time, Raden
said _ or you wait until you are on the verge of making a purchase,
then add that exact amount. (PrivateBuy.com also charges online
merchants a standard MasterCard transaction fee.)
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, but $3.95 seemed awfully steep for a single purchase. On
the other hand, you might as well spend: PrivateBuy.com does not
have a mechanism to refund unused balances you have deposited.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a premium service for someone who might want to make
an anonymous gift or a discreet purchase,'' Raden said, ``and in
those instances, people are willing to pay for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Was I? I feared that I wouldn't be able to answer because when I
arrived at Amazon.com, the site greeted me by name as usual after
recognizing the cookie it had sent to my computer at an earlier
date. So I found the file on my computer where cookies are stored
and deleted those that seemed to relate to Amazon.com. When I
restarted my browser, Amazon no longer greeted me by name, but
after I anonymously put a few items into a shopping cart (don't ask
_ it's none of your business) and tried to check out, I was
informed that I would have to use an e-mail address to create a
customer account. PrivateBuy.com did not give me an anonymous
e-mail address, so I had to set up my own:
PrivateBuyer(at)hotmail.com. It was free, but setting it up took
about five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   When I returned yet again to Amazon.com, I realized that I had
overlooked another obvious point: if I entered a fake shipping
address, where would Amazon.com send my stuff? To Privacy, PA
00000?
</P>
<P>
   Raden suggested that I get a post office box to use as an
anonymous shipping address, so he clearly has no idea just how lazy
a shopper I am.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, why don't I just buy a factory in Taiwan and make my own
merchandise?
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com's new policy was suddenly seeming much less ominous.
I phoned Amazon.com to find out how likely it was that the company
was planning to share my secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Patty Smith, a spokeswoman for Amazon.com, tried to put things
in perspective: ``You are worried people will know you are looking
to see if your books are moving up in rank? Like, `I was ranked
112,000, and now I'm 98,000?'''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 24,497,'' I said coldly.
</P>
<P>
   She then explained that Amazon would share customer information
with a third party only under two conditions:
</P>
<P>
   1. If Amazon.com was sold or acquired.
</P>
<P>
   2. If a customer bought products from one of the independent
merchants who operate stores on the Amazon.com site.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news? Amazon.com has no control over what those
independent merchants, like Drugstore.com (which sells home
pregnancy tests), do with the information.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's safe to say that our partners treat customers as
carefully as Amazon does,'' Smith said. ``But if you're going to
transact business with one of the partners on our site, read their
policy as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe I'll just walk down to the real drugstore and plunk
down $9.99 in cash for the EPT pregnancy test. (It's a gag gift,
Mom.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-00 1716EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
