<HEADER>
A2968 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-TRENDS-NEXTGEN-NYTSF     09-13 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRENDS-NEXTGEN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEN WHY GOES BACK TO SCHOOL IN STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release September 13, 2000.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's TRENDS-NEXTGEN column. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of TRENDS-NEXTGEN _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By JANE RINZLER BUCKINGHAM  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's back-to-school time, and what your teen may be dreading
even more than the grind is the possibility of showing up looking
oh-so-last-year. I know you'd want to save him or her this
embarrassment. Here, based on a survey that my company, Youth
Intelligence, conducted for Fuji Film, is what 350 teens from
around the country said will be in _ and out _ this year on high
school campuses.
</P>
<P>
   PICTURES OF FRIENDS
</P>
<P>
   It's no surprise that 91 percent of the teens we surveyed stated
that pictures of friends are in this year. Teens trust their
friends more than anyone else. Their friends are their lifelines.
Pictures of friends are visible proof that you have a posse, that
your peeps are there for you, that you don't stand alone in the
crowd. Teens also know life can be tough, and they want to capture
the good times to help see themselves through the bad.
</P>
<P>
   Have to Have: Polaroid I-zone with sticker film or any digital
camera
</P>
<P>
   CELLULAR PHONE
</P>
<P>
   With 87 percent of teens saying cell phones are going to be in
this year, you may find your phone ringing off the hook until you
get one for yours. And don't think a simple little beeper will
suffice. Teens want to stay in touch with their friends anytime,
anywhere. In addition, cell phones afford them privacy, so their
friends can call them without annoying parents. Whether this is bad
news or good news depends on how you look at it. On the up side, a
teen with a cell phone is a teen with no excuse to miss a curfew.
The bad news _ your teen might be on the phone all the time. The
good news _ you can still talk on yours.
</P>
<P>
   Have to Have: Motorola V. series
</P>
<P>
   CARGO
</P>
<P>
   You can breathe a sigh of relief. You won't have to unload those
four pairs of cargo pants your teen couldn't live without last
spring. While fashion may be fleeting, this fad has managed to stay
hot. This is what 80 percent of teens say they'll be wearing in
school this year.
</P>
<P>
   Teens still love the practicality of these pants, with pockets
for cameras, cell phones and even an afternoon snack. However,
while the look may stay the same, the brands might be different.
Tommy is no longer as cool as Polo, and though Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch
still has a large piece of the market (72 percent of the teens we
surveyed say they want A&AMP;F cargoes), a slightly smaller number will
be wearing A&AMP;F than last year.
</P>
<P>
   Have to Have: Cargoes by 555 Soul, Polo, Ecko Unlimited
</P>
<P>
   BODY PIERCINGS
</P>
<P>
   I'm not recommending you run out and get your teen a nose ring,
but I am warning you that while this trend may be subsiding, it has
hardly pricked its last hole. Of the teens we surveyed, 76 percent
said piercing will still be in this year. The good news? Only 49
percent said tattoos will be in.
</P>
<P>
   Have to have: Their choice: Belly Ring. Your wish: Belly Chain
</P>
<P>
   DYED HAIR
</P>
<P>
   Think of it this way: at least dyed hair doesn't cost a lot. An
overwhelmingly large number of teens (72 percent) stated that it
would still be in this year. Interestingly, more males than females
said this, with 75 percent of boys giving it the thumbs up and only
69 percent of girls.
</P>
<P>
   The reason dyed hair seems so hot may be that teens are looking
for a way to express themselves. Hair is just as dramatic as
piercings and tattoos, but it's less permanent. Dyed hair can also
be changed based upon one's mood or needs. We didn't get a read on
which colors our teens favored, so maybe they just meant
highlights.
</P>
<P>
   Have to have: Clairol Extreme EFX
</P>
<P>
   GLITTERY MAKE-UP
</P>
<P>
   This trend seems most popular among the younger teens in grades
9 and 10, which probably signals that it won't make the list by
spring. But with 55 percent of teens overall (and 65 percent of
9th-graders saying it's still in), you'll be seeing glittery hair,
eyelids and cheeks well into the fall. The great thing about
glitter is that it's fun and frivolous. Younger teens today are
increasingly optimistic, and this is one of the clearest ways to
put their brightest face forward.
</P>
<P>
   Have to have: Anything Glitter from Hard Candy, Bourjois or Jane
Cosmetics Glitter
</P>
<P>
   BE ON THE LOOKOUT FOR:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Man Who Ate the 747'' (book)
</P>
<P>
   Nelly Furtado (music artist)
</P>
<P>
   Rimless sunglasses
</P>
<P>
   Jane Rinzler Buckingham is the president of Youth Intelligence,
a market-research firm specializing in the 7- to 35-year-old
market. Her company publishes the Cassandra Report, a comprehensive
survey focused on identifying emerging trends among Generations X
and Why?
</P>
<P>
   -----------
</P>
