<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERYDAY-ETHICS-COLUMN-ADV17-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV17 
 EVERYDAY ETHICS
</HEADLINE>
  FOR RELEASE Sunday, SEPT. 17, AND THEREAFTER. 
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's EVERYDAY ETHICS column. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the EVERYDAY ETHICS column _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.) 
 By RANDY COHEN 
 c.2000 Randy Cohen 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCHOOL DANCE
</P>
<P>
   Q: My full-time (but not live-in) baby sitter hinted that she
would like to use my address to enroll her daughter in my excellent
local public elementary school; her neighborhood school is awful.
The alternative is for her to send her daughter to private school,
a financial burden but not an impossibility. Should I offer my
address?
</P>
<P>
   _ L.A.B., Brooklyn, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A: You should not offer your address; it is not ethical to
facilitate your baby sitter's fraud. It is, of course, entirely
admirable to help her get her daughter into a good school, but
there are better ways to do so. Help her apply for a variance that
allows her daughter to attend an out-of-district school. Since
that's an admittedly iffy proposition, see if the two of you can
find any good schools or special programs in her district. That
said, many districts, even in New York, a city with some excellent
public schools, offer sadly limited choices. As a consequence,
while what your baby sitter proposes is improper, I don't have it
in me to chastise a mother's deception in trying to get her
daughter a decent education. The best way to eliminate these sorts
of address gymnastics is not through calls for individual
rectitude, but by providing good schools in all neighborhoods.
Sometimes a personal ethical goal _ a good education for your
sitter's daughter _ can be achieved only through political action.
So beyond the immediate steps you take on her behalf, I hope you
and she actively support efforts for better public schools. If your
sitter does opt for private school, you might help her apply for a
scholarship or even, if you can afford it, aid her financially
yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My neighbor, a twentysomething and quite good-looking, never
draws his blinds. The view from my apartment is extraordinary.
Every night at 8:15 he returns from jogging to shower and prepare
for bed, which I enjoy watching. Am I wrong to do so?
</P>
<P>
   _ Anonymous
</P>
<P>
   A: If the dreamboat across the way forgot one night to draw his
blinds, you should respect his privacy; it would not be right to
exploit a moment's carelessness. However, if he leaves them open
every night in a big city where he obviously has neighbors, you can
assume he knows what he's doing. Enjoy! It would be almost
insulting to avert your glance. Like Central Park or the Chrysler
Building, naked neighbors are part of the scenic splendor that is
New York. Alas, while there may be no ethical impediment to your
hobby, it is not without legal risk in some places for both the
observed and the observer. New York State law, for example,
proscribes various ``offenses against public sensibilities,'' and
although one is unlikely to be convicted of such a charge, the
arrest alone could be quite unpleasant.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I love to find the day's paper on the subway seat next to me
when I am caught without anything to read. Naturally, then, I feel
inclined to leave my paper behind on the subway when I am done with
it, despite the Metro Transit Authority's posted admonition against
littering. Is it unethical to contribute to this silent network of
newspaper readers?
</P>
<P>
   _ Luis Perez, Brooklyn, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A: Your volunteer subterranean bookmobile is the Transit
Authority's litter. It is reasonable of them to ask riders not to
strew newspapers around the subway; they must consider the possible
effects of millions of riders leaving their papers behind. And
while the commute would certainly be more pleasant if each train
included a library car (and while we're at it, a bar car), until
that utopian transit system arrives, you ought to follow the rules.
</P>
<P>
   Do you have ethical questions that you need answered? Send them
to ethicist(at)nytimes.com, or Everyday Ethics, New York Times
Syndicate, 122 E. 42nd St., 14th floor, New York, N.Y. 10168.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on EVERYDAY
ETHICS and other features. &QL;
</P>
