<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2987 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TRUMP-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     09-13 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUMP-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE TRUMPS': THE GRANDFATHER, THE FATHER, THE DONALD 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Publication notes at end of review.) 
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Gwenda Blair's copiously researched study of the Trump
family, readers can learn the academic credentials of the director
of Donald Trump's nursery school and the fact that building with
blocks was a main part of this future mogul's curriculum. Also
established are the colors of the boys' uniforms (gray shorts and
green shirts) at Camp Hilltop and the fact that counselors kept
records about the bowel movements and other digestive progress of
their charges.
</P>
<P>
   On the psychological front the author identifies Donald, who was
born in 1946, as part of a faux-firstborn generation emerging
immediately after World War II and apt to be assertive and
successful, regardless of exact birth order. Maybe so, but not all
these people have been able to plaster their names across the New
York skyline. And only one of them has been able to treat the city
as his personal Monopoly board or modestly attempt to turn his name
into a modifier. (``You're looking very Trump today,'' read a 1987
billboard in Atlantic City, the auxiliary Trump playground.) As to
what really makes Donald run, Blair's investigative account doesn't
offer much of a clue.
</P>
<P>
   It can be argued that enough has been said about Donald Trump
anyway, mostly by Trump himself, and that this exhaustive book is a
no-win proposition. In her attempt to eclipse the mogul's own
self-puffery and his invaluable presence as a gossip-column
fixture, Blair has dug back two generations to the first Trump
(actually Drumpf) presence on American soil.
</P>
<P>
   She has doggedly compiled the family history of a grandfather
(Friedrich, later Frederick), father (Fred) and glitz-seeking
Wunderkind, but the focus of her account is uncertain. There are
readers who want to know about the Uniform Land Use Review
Procedure, known as ULURP, ``the city's complex zoning approval
process,'' and others who wonder what Donald Trump's former
consorts and employees might have to say. Try as she may to steer
an even course between these polarities, Blair winds up with a
landslide of ULURP and little dish.
</P>
<P>
   The book has its most obvious trouble in cobbling together the
mostly undocumented story of Friedrich, who arrived in 1885 from
southwestern Germany. (The family would later occasionally
represent itself as Swedish.) Before settling down to adult life as
a barber, he lived adventurously in the Pacific Northwest in the
midst of gold miners, for whose benefit he ran a series of
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Blair assembles evidence that the ``dressmakers'' who could be
found at these establishments were actually prostitutes, which
would not have been entirely shocking in that setting, and which at
least is better proved than some of the more dubious details here.
Did Friedrich serve horse meat in his restaurants, for example?
Maybe not, ``but if he was like everyone else, he did what the
locals did _ went out and cut up a piece of old Nelly.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair is on more solid ground with the story of how Fred Trump
carved out a real estate empire in Brooklyn. Also richly endowed
with the family moxie, he initially learned the building trade
through YMCA and correspondence courses while also developing
expertise in finding legal loopholes within Federal Housing
Administration regulations. ``Without the FHA, Fred Trump would
have been running a supermarket,'' Blair asserts. ``With the FHA,
he was the biggest builder in Brooklyn, employing hundreds of
construction workers and turning out 400 homes a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Frederick Christ Trump (whose middle name was his mother's
family name, and who did not create further hubris problems by
passing it on to Donald) earned a reputation for dedication. He
dressed in a coat and tie to tour the houses he had built and to
greet residents. During one construction project near Coney Island
he installed bathing lockers so workers could swim on their breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Even at the height of his success, he remained ``a man who would
still spend an entire afternoon meticulously explaining to a
maintenance man how to mix liquid cockroach spray so as to avoid
calling an exterminator.'' In the words of one acquaintance, ``He
never tried to impress anybody with his wealth,'' and ``He didn't
seem to care if anybody had ever heard of him,'' proving how far an
apple can fall from a tree.
</P>
<P>
   The section devoted to Donald (other relatives are all but
invisible) combines pearls of hindsight (``You could tell he was
going to get somewhere'') with a litany of deal-making details for
which an appreciation of tax abatements and housing codes would be
welcome. What emerges is Blair's portrait of her subject as a
germ-phobic anti-Gatsby:
</P>
<P>
   ``He had no desire to pass for old money himself and considered
most of those who benefited from it to be phonies; likewise he was
not at all reticent about how he made his money but took every
opportunity to boast about just how clever he had been. Nor was
there a Daisy at whose feet he wished to lay himself and his
material possessions.''
</P>
<P>
   In place of Gatsby's poignant display of his shirts, we have
Trump telling reporters: ``See this railing? Same railing Onassis
had on his boat.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Almost Golden,'' her haunting book about the driven
television reporter Jessica Savitch, Blair also wrote about raging
ambition, and did it in a way that made readers complicit in
Savitch's relentlessness. But in that regard Donald Trump has
beaten any biographer to the punch. ``The Trumps'' does trace his
apotheosis as a star and brand name more valuable than any
65th-story penthouse (which, incidentally, would in the creatively
labeled Trump Tower actually be on the 59th floor). But it also
finds him in full control of his own image and reputation,
impregnable to the kinds of details that emerge here. From his
father and grandfather, as Blair does illustrate, he inherited the
ability to make lemons into lemonade.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what I think,'' he remarked while heavily in debt and
having to sell property on the auction block. ``I think there's
something very sophisticated and intelligent about auctions.''
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE TRUMPS'
</P>
<P>
   Three Generations That Built an Empire
</P>
<P>
   By Gwenda Blair
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 591 pages. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-00 1739EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
