<HEADER>
A2988 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-MINIS14-COX     09-13 0480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CD mini reviews
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton, Pierre Ruhe, and Mandi Albright
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTHER NEW RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  JAZZ
</P>
<P>
   ``How Can I Keep From Singing?''
</P>
<P>
   Rene Marie. MaxJazz. 12 Tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   No matter where your tastes lie on the broad spectrum of jazz
interpretation, there's something to like on Rene Marie's MaxJazz
debut. Applying an arsenal of styles to standards (''The Very
Thought of You,'' ``Tennessee Waltz,'' ``God Bless the Child'') and
originals like the title tune, Marie scats and yodels and purrs
with an exuberance that belies her 44 years. An added treat to this
release is the stellar piano/keyboard accompaniment from Mulgrew
Miller, Marvin Sewell's sultry strumming on guitar and Gerald
Cleaver's snappy drum work. Most alluring of all is the fourth
track, ``Four Women,'' in which the backup quintet lays down a
backbeat reminiscent of a Steely Dan ballad while Marie strings
tales of the struggles of red, yellow, tan and brown women
everywhere. Marie can't keep from singing because it'd be a
disservice to the listening public.
</P>
<P>
   _A. Scott Walton
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ON THE WEB : More on Rene Marie:
www.maxjazz.com/artists/rene/renesamples.html
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  CLASSICAL
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Meyer plays Bach Cello Suites on the Double Bass
</P>
<P>
   Sony Classical. 61 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   For J.S. Bach, a mix-and-match approach to composition and
performance was the norm. He'd write a piece for violin one day and
transcribe it for harpsichord the next. Thus it's no surprise to
find double bass virtuoso Edgar Meyer playing three suites (Nos. 1,
2 and 5) that Bach originally composed for solo .
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   The American folk canon consists of tunes that have been
informally passed down through the years, their original authorship
lost to the ether as various generations adopted (and adapted)
music and lyrics for entertainment purposes. ``Public Domain,''
Dave Alvin's latest release, follows purest folk tradition with its
reworking of the railroad, murder/revenge and religious songs that
remain integral swatches in the American cultural fabric. Alvin
infuses fuller, richer sound into time-worn staples like ``Maggie
Campbell,'' ``Delia'' and ``Railroad Bill,'' while managing to
retain the underlying simplicity that made these works classic in
the first place. But some of Alvin's old Blasters rockabilly vibes
assert themselves on ``Don't Let Your Deal Go Down'' and ``East
Virginia Blues,'' pumping up the volume when necessary. Popular by
definition and populist at heart, the songs of ``Public Domain''
are those of the people, by the people, for the people _
quintessentially American, but thematically universal.
</P>
<P>
   _Mandi Albright
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ON THE WEB: More on Dave Alvin: www.hightone.com;
www.davealvin.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
