<DOCNO> NYT20000913.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2989 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-ROCK14-COX     09-13 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-ROCK14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Famously fun odes to world of rock 'n' roll
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With ``Almost Famous,'' Cameron Crowe's ode to the rock life of
the early '70s, opening in metro theaters Friday, you may want to
think about rock movies available for rental. Trouble is, there are
so many of them out there _ good, bad and indifferent _ you could
probably rock around the clock for a solid month in front of your
VCR and never get past Early Elvis (the earlier, funkier flicks
from his ``Jailhouse Rock'' period). And some of us do have school,
I mean, work.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, assuming you know about the Beatles and the Who and
Sting and the Sex Pistols and a zillion others who've made the
crossover from song to cinema, here are some other titles to check
into.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Doors'' (1991): Like every other picture he's ever made,
this one is more about Oliver Stone than anything else. This time
he lights a fire under one of the '60s sexiest myths of
self-destruction _ the crash-and-burn career of Jim Morrison,
played with galvanizing power by a pre-Batman Val Kilmer. The movie
is the sort of frenzied demon-god memorial Morrison would've loved,
with the rest of the band pretty much relegated to background noise
(they're played by Kyle McLachlan, Frank Whaley and Kevin Dillon).
There's also Meg Ryan in granny glasses as Morrison's flower-power
girlfriend, a classic Movie Acid Trip and enough pretentiousness to
light a bonfire. This is not a film for devoted fans of the Doors
or for anyone soul-sick of the '60s, but it does capture the chaos
of charisma.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Rock 'n' Roll High School'' (1979): Sophomoric, crude, rowdy
and marvelously exuberant, this ``shameless display of adolescent
abandon'' stars P.J. (where are you now?) Soles as a Ramones freak
who has her fellow students at Vince Lombardi High dancing in the
halls. But the new principal (Mary Woronov) is putting static in
Soles' rock 'n' roll heaven. The Ramones appear as themselves.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``This Is Spinal Tap'' (1984): The movie that put the ``mock''
into mockumentary. This ``cinema verite'' head trip down the long
and winding road tour of a fictitious English band named Spinal Tap
is a peerless, pitch-perfect parody of every rockumentary made
since Dylan didn't look back. The film's caricatures are still
classic more than a decade and a half after it was made. Michael
McKean is the limp-locked vocalist; Christopher Guest, the moody
lead guitarist with his amp set on 11; co-scripter Harry Shearer,
the laconic bass player; and director Rob Reiner, the supposed
documentary's director. What happens to Spinal Tap on tour
shouldn't happen to Michael Bolton. Canceled concerts, getting lost
backstage, taking second billing to a puppet show. Too funny to be
true and sometimes too true to be funny, it's a splendid film.
</P>
<P>
   Note to DVD owners: A special edition has hit the stores
featuring an hour of never-before-seen footage and a Flower People
Press Conference (see the movie and you'll get the joke.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Still Crazy'' (1998): A poignant yet hilarious companion
piece to ``This Is Spinal Tap,'' this brilliant comedy takes us one
decade further, conjuring up a fictional British group from the
'70s called Strange Fruit. Twenty years after giving in to
factions, jealousies and even divine intervention, The Fruits, as
their fans call them, attempt a reunion tour. Loaded up on a bus
that was once used by the Psychedelic Furs, they hit the road. A
kind of tragicomedy for baby boomers, the movie is a celebration
and an elegy, reminding us that rock dreams take a long time to die
_ for those who made music as well as for those who listened. You
may recognize Stephen Rea (``The Crying Game'') as the keyboardist
or Billy Connolly (``Mrs. Brown'') as an ironic roadie. But the
standout is Bill Nighy as the group's lead singer, a tremulous
has-been heartthrob.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
