<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's Emmylou, in her own words
 &HT;    By Eileen Drennen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has to be a little daunting to make an album as achingly
perfect as ``Wrecking Ball.'' Harris' adventurous 1995 release _
with its haunting versions of songs by folks like Neil Young,
Daniel Lanois and Lucinda Williams, in all their fuzzy grandeur _
was a moody break from past personas (``Sweetheart of the Rodeo,''
``Blue Kentucky Girl,'' ``The Ballad of Sally Rose'') and a hint of
what might follow. It was drenched in the bayou night sounds that
producer Lanois had perfected on albums for the Neville Brothers,
U2 and Willie Nelson. But Harris' seasoned voice, with its raw and
scraping grace, made it a completely distinctive listen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Red Dirt Girl,'' produced by Lanois associate Malcolm Burn,
has much of the same dense atmospherics. But this time, Harris _ so
often an interpreter of other artists' music _ spotlights her own
poetic compositions. Love lost or never fully understood resonates
throughout, whether the song alludes to a parent (``Bang the Drum
Slowly''), a lover (``J'ai Fait Tout'' and ``I Don't Wanna Talk
About It Now'') or faith (``The Pearl'').
</P>
<P>
   Long respected for her generosity to her fellow singers'
projects, Harris gets ace backing vocals from Bruce Springsteen and
Patty Scialfa on the darkly beautiful ``Tragedy'' and Dave Matthews
on the C&AMP;W-flavored ``My Antonia.'' And in the process, she raises
the bar for herself yet again.
</P>
<P>
   _Eileen M. Drennen writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Emmylou Harris performs Oct. 24 at Variety Playhouse.
</P>
<P>
   'Red Dirt Girl'
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Emmylou Harris / Nonesuch Records / 12 tracks / Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   O N T H E W E B : More on Emmylou Harris: www.emmylou.net.
</P>
