<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NOTES14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Lie' about Dickey? Debate rages
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It seems that James Dickey is as controversial in death as he
was in life. Henry Hart, who exposed the poet's propensity for
prevarication in the biography ``James Dickey: The World as a Lie''
(Picador, $35), has been caught in a critical crossfire.
</P>
<P>
   The reviewer firing the most darts is Hemingway biographer
Jeffrey Meyers. In a negative review in The New Criterion, Meyers
accused Hart of sloppy scholarship, factual errors and an
overemphasis on Dickey's drunken escapades.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in the September issue of The New Criterion, the two
biographers have engaged in an epistolary form of ``Dueling
Banjos.'' Hart counters Meyers' criticism point by point and
accuses him of ``swinging his demolition ball at the current Dickey
books to make room for his own. ... Many of Meyers' other comments
are distortions motivated by spite, or just careless errors.''
</P>
<P>
   Meyers, in response, writes: ``Hart's whining letter, which
wisely ignores my major criticism of his work, is as bad as his
book. ... I'm not writing a life of Dickey but, if I did, (I)
certainly wouldn't use his shoddy research.''
</P>
<P>
   In the same issue, Dickey's son, Christopher, whose memoir
``Summer of Deliverance'' was not overly kind, joined Meyers in
criticizing Hart's work. ``The poetry's greatness _ and that is not
too big a word _ is lost in Hart's relentlessly banal and often
credulous repetition of Jim Dickey's personal failings.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickey fans can hear more from Hart in a lecture at 5:30 p.m.
Monday at Emory University. Woodruff Library's Jones Room, 540
Asbury Circle. 404-727-6887.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Movie how-to: Aspiring directors who want to shoot the next
``Blair Witch Project'' would do well to pick up a copy of ``Making
Independent Films: Advice From the Filmmakers'' (Allworth Press,
$16.95).
</P>
<P>
   The handy book by writers/producers Liz Stubbs of Roswell and
Richard Rodriguez of Miami offers an informative and entertaining
behind-the-curtain tour of the independent film scene. One of the
people interviewed is Michael Shoob, whose critically acclaimed
film ``Driven'' began its festival circuit in Atlanta. Before doing
``Driven,'' Shoob, son of U.S. District Court Judge Marvin Shoob of
Atlanta, wrote a 3-D horror movie in the early '80s called
``Parasite.'' It starred an unknown (at the time) soap opera
actress named Demi Moore.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
