<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-ADV16-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV16 
 TV TONIGHT
</HEADLINE>
   (For Release: Saturday, Sept. 16, 2000) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: TV TONIGHT, the daily TV column by Boston Herald
TV Editor Joel Brown, is for use by clients of The New York Times
Syndicate's TV TONIGHT feature. For more information about becoming
a client of TV TONIGHT, contact your Syndicate sales representative
at 1-888-269-8796. You may have received an unedited e-mail version
of TV TONIGHT that you should disregard. 
 (Editors: All times are Eastern Time unless otherwise specified.
Please check local listings for time and channel.) 
 By JOEL BROWN 
 c.2000 Joel Brown 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're an Olympics fan with a comfortable couch, boy have we
got a weekend for you. NBC promises 441.5 hours of coverage before
the Sydney games are over, either on the network itself or on its
CNBC and MSNBC cable channels. And a good chunk of those hours come
this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   If you're quick on the clicker, you'll never have to watch
anything else, actually. Coverage starts on MSNBC at 10 a.m.
Saturday (women's basketball and beach volleyball) and 9 a.m.
Sunday (baseball), and runs till after 2 a.m. Prime-time events on
NBC include swimming, men's gymnastics and other sports from
7-midnight on Saturday, and swimming and women's gymnastics on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is tape-delayed, of course. Since Sydney is many
times zones away from the United States, NBC will rely on host Bob
Costas and its crack team of editors to shape hours of raw tape
into compelling competition. If you just want results, you'll be
able to get those much earlier.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, if you're wondering where all the new shows are on
the other networks, we have some bad news for you. The start of the
fall TV season has been delayed until the first week of October, so
all those new shows don't have to compete with the Games.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIGHLIGHTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother,'' CBS Saturday at 8: R is for reality, which this
show is not. (Continued tomorrow!)
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor,'' CBS Saturday at 9: CBS continues its
counter-Olympic strategy with reruns of this summer sensation.
Tonight, episode 2: ``Generation Gap.'' B.B. gets voted off the
island, apparently because he's too useful.
</P>
<P>
   ``David Blaine: Street Magic,'' ABC Saturday at 10: Leonardo
DiCaprio and some of the Dallas Cowboys appear, but their appeal
pales next to the amazing sleight of hand by this young magician.
Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mad TV,'' Fox Saturday at 11: Busta Rhymes guests. It's a
rerun, but if you usually watch ``Saturday Night Live,'' pre-empted
by the Olympics tonight, you should give this younger, more daring
sketch comedy show a try.
</P>
<P>
   ''60 Minutes,'' CBS Sunday at 7: Gossip columnist Liz Smith,
presumably talking about her forthcoming autobiography.
</P>
<P>
   ``The '70s: The Decade That Changed Television,'' ABC Sunday at
7: Two-hour infotainment special about the years that gave us
``MASH'' and ``All in the Family'' _ also ``Three's Company'' and
``The Love Boat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Simpsons,'' Fox Sunday at 8: The strange episode that saw
the passing of Maude Flanders in a freak accident at a stock car
race. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Malcolm in the Middle,'' Fox Sunday at 8:30: Hal takes the
boys to a stock car race. Seems rather ill-advised in light of what
happened to Maude. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire,'' ABC Sunday at 9: Regis
Philbin hosts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Practice,'' ABC Sunday at 10: Ellenor makes a last-ditch
plea for Stuart Donovan's innocence, but if she fails, he gets a
lethal injection. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FAMILY FARE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Dick Van Dyke Show'' marathon, TVLand all weekend: This
48-hour marathon gives you a terrific chance to introduce your kids
to great comedy that doesn't involve any ``South Park'' language or
``Friends''-style couplings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CABLE CAST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Birds,'' AMC Saturday at 8:05: We never get tired of this
1963 Alfred Hitchcock masterpiece about a natural uprising that's
all the more powerful because it's never explained. The phone booth
scene is on par with anything else he's done. Rod Taylor, Tippi
Hedren, Suzanne Pleshette and Jessica Tandy star.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's Something About Mary,'' Cinemax Saturday at 8:
Hilarious and sick _ in a good way. A comedy with zippers, not-hair
gel and a dog in a body cast. Rated R. Ben Stiller and Cameron Diaz
star, with support from the demented Chris Elliott and musician
Jonathan Richman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inside the Actor's Studio,'' Bravo Sunday at 8: Now this ought
to be worth watching. Big-screen star Faye Dunaway can talk to the
students about ``Bonnie &AMP; Clyde,'' ``Chinatown,'' ``Network'' and
of course ``Mommie Dearest,'' which follows at 9 on Bravo. Maybe
she'll also talk about some of her legendary diva behavior on the
set.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shadow of a Doubt,'' AMC Sunday at 8: This comparatively
low-key Hitchcock classic was the director's favorite. Joseph
Cotton stars as the debonair uncle who comes to visit his relatives
in a bucolic small town; Teresa Wright is the niece who thinks he
might be the Merry Widow killer. Watch for Cotton's chilling
dinner-table soliloquy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hendrix,'' Showtime Sunday at 8: Wood Harris stars as 1960s
guitar god Jimi Hendrix in a brand-new biopic that's reportedly
heavy on the 1960s decadence but devoid of any actual Hendrix
music. How groovy can it be?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sex and the City,'' HBO Sunday at 9: The Los Angeles sojourn
continues, and now Charlotte joins her friends there. But with
these gals around, is it still the City of Angels?
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris Rock Show,'' HBO Sunday at 11:40: Guests are Spike Lee
and D'Angelo.
</P>
<P>
   ----------- &QC;
</P>
