<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3000 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-AALTO-DEMOLISH-2TAKES     09-13 1403
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AALTO-DEMOLISH-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AALTO ROOM MAY BE SHOWN THE DOOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Japan)   By JULIE V. IOVINE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An architectural gem is in danger of becoming an
architectural millstone. A suite of conference rooms designed in
1964 by Alvar Aalto could join the list of extinct legendary New
York interiors, now that their owner has announced that it would
like them removed from an office building near the United Nations.
The interior is not protected by landmark status.
</P>
<P>
   The Kaufmann Conference Center, as it is known, is one of only
four existing works designed by Aalto in the United States, and the
only one in New York. It represents ``one of the unique
architectural treasures of New York City,'' Kenneth Frampton, the
architectural historian, said.
</P>
<P>
   Aalto is the renowned Finnish architect with a humanistic bent,
who brought a love of natural materials and organic shapes to the
rigid contours of international style _ not to mention his immortal
1936 vase. The office space is named for Edgar J. Kaufmann, a
professor of architecture and a patron of architecture and
education who talked his parents into hiring Frank Lloyd Wright to
design Fallingwater. In this case, Kaufmann believed that Manhattan
deserved an Aalto.
</P>
<P>
   He commissioned the conference rooms in 1961 on behalf of the
Institute of International Education at 809 U.N. Plaza. The current
owner, a Japanese nonprofit organization, wants to convert the
Aalto space into offices.
</P>
<P>
   A hastily anointed band of Aalto enthusiasts and friends of New
York's modern legacies are on a quest to find guardian angels to
come to the rescue. Dismantling the large portable elements of the
room would be possible, but expensive and somewhat destructive.
Finding a new home has proved elusive. Some supporters believe a
way must be found to keep it in place; others just want it saved
any way possible.
</P>
<P>
   The 4,500-square-foot, three-room space with retractable walls
offers a choice menu of Aalto's signatures. Visiting the space
today, it looks so original that one experiences the shock of
modernism's early impact. A white plaster ceiling still undulates
as it rises up to a peak of 22 feet. Textured walls _ some made of
cylindrical royal blue porcelain ribs, others of long thin birch
battens layered at intervals over ash paneling _ move in waves,
too. The real eye-stopper, however, is a sculptural relief of
curvaceous wooden staves, shaped like hockey sticks and set deep
into one corner, Aalto's poetic abstract of a Finnish forest.
</P>
<P>
   Along one side, floor-to-ceiling, wall-to-wall windows provide a
ringside view of the doings at the United Nations and along the
East River, while an enormous screen of wooden louvers in a
checkerboard pattern protects the space from glare. The gold-plated
copper lighting fixtures, sculptured bronze door pulls, standing
lamps with leather posts and Aalto vase-like shades, black leather
and birch chairs and a portable bar and speaker's desk, were also
all made by Aalto. His second wife, Elissa, assisted on the project
and made the variegated brown rugs.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their inimitable significance, such rooms, said Roger
Lang of the New York Landmarks Conservancy, are ``very perishable,
and very hard to save.'' Tucked away on the top floor of a private
office building, the Kaufmann Conference Center doesn't meet the
legal criteria of public accessibility required for an interior
space to be granted landmark status. There is a another
disadvantage. ``It's modern,'' Lang said, ``and we're all trying to
come to grips with preserving things that are hard for people to
embrace because they belong to such recent history.''
</P>
<P>
   The space appears to have been barely touched for 36 years. An
old-fashioned pneumatic lever in a closet still raises an invisible
track to transform the space from three to four conference rooms.
Portability was an important theme of modernism, and Aalto designed
the rooms to be movable. In fact, much of the materials were made
in Finland. There are even spare parts _ mostly bundles of birch
battens and extra Arabia porcelain tiles _ in the basement, said
Gil Robinov, the exclusive agent for the building's Japanese
owners, the Foundation for the Support of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   When the foundation bought the building in 1998, it converted it
into a commercial condominium, and sold several floors to foreign
governments. Initially, they were unaware of the gem inside,
Robinov said. But a constant trickle of architecture enthusiasts
and students alerted the foundation to what it had. ``He's got a
fan club, no question about it,'' Robinov said about Aalto, adding
that security makes it difficult to allow people free access to the
space.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very sympathetic to the plight of the followers of this
architect,'' he said. ``These rooms should be in a place where they
are protected for posterity.'' He also noted that because the place
was private, ``whoever owns the building can do anything, including
taking it out and putting it in the Dumpster.''
</P>
<P>
   For the last five years, the Consulate General of Finland has
been watching the space, even hiring Finnish experts to appraise
its condition. Maija Lahteenmaki, the former consul general, took a
special interest in the rooms but her tour of duty in the United
States recently ended.
</P>
<P>
   Four months ago, she said, ``I was informed by the new owners
that they planned to convert it to office space because the market
was so hot.'' Lahteenmaki, with the help of Caroline Zaleski, a
recent graduate of the Columbia School of Architecture's
preservation program, solicited Frank Gehry, Robert Venturi, Tadao
Ando and other prominent architects to write letters emphasizing
the importance of preserving the interior. The owners responded by
offering to donate all the portable elements to anyone who would
pay the cost of removal.
</P>
<P>
   The preservation and architectural community is not unanimous
about what should be done. Some believe that, if it cannot remain
where it is, then it should be dismantled and stored with the hope
of reinstalling it at some future date. Others say that it should
be removed to an institution that would use it and make it
available to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The Museum of Modern Art was an obvious place to turn. The
museum's 1938 exhibition on Aalto's work was responsible for
bringing him to international attention. (A retrospective in 1998
worked up a new generation of midcentury modern fans.) This summer,
the museum did investigate the possibility of incorporating the
Kaufmann space into its new expansion plans, but concluded that it
wouldn't fit, said Terence Riley, chief curator of architecture and
design at the museum.
</P>
<P>
   More to the point, he added, ``Should museums be rescuing rooms
from the garbage can and become witting assistants to dismantling
rooms and removing them from their original place for the sake of
acquisition?''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the Kaufmann connection, Lynda Waggoner,
Fallingwater's director, said she was approached to either
reinstall the rooms in a barn on her site or to store all the
elements. She said neither was a possibility. ``It's very urban in
a way that wouldn't be appropriate to Fallingwater,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Other institutions, including the Guggenheim Museum and the
United Nations, have been approached but have not responded.
</P>
<P>
   It is estimated that it could cost $1 million to dismantle the
room, Lahteenmaki said. The porcelain tiles that line the walls _
setting the tone of textural sensuality at the entrance _ would be
especially expensive to take down and reinstall.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Museum of Modern Art has expressed an interest
in incorporating the Aalto rooms into space undergoing renovation.
``But whatever we could do would never be as good as where it is,''
said Aaron Betsky, the museum's curator of architecture, design and
digital products, who spent his vacation touring Aalto works in
Finland.
</P>
<P>
   As Robinov handed over a sales brochure for condo space in the
building featuring the Kaufmann room on the cover, he hastened to
say that the building's owners were not going to throw the
conference space out. ``We don't want a frenzy,'' he said. ``It's
safe here as far as we can see.'' He added that he hoped that a
solution would be found within six months. The raw space could sell
for $75 to $80 a square foot.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Jennifer J. Raab, the chairwoman of the New York City
Landmarks Preservation Commission, met with Robinov and acquired a
written agreement that the owners would do no work on the space for
90 days. During this time, the commission would not begin the
process of designating it a landmark, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a city as rich as this not to be able to save this
interior is scandalous,'' said Frampton, the architectural
historian, who continues to call to potential rescuers. Two weeks
ago, Donald Trump was contacted by Robinov. ``It would be a nice
amenity to his tenants,'' said Diana Gaines, an associate of
Robinov's, regarding Trump's condominium going up two blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   She noted that although Trump appeared not to have heard of
Aalto when they met to discuss the project, and has yet to visit
the space, he quickly took up the proposal. ``I'm seriously
considering it for Trump Royal Tower,'' Trump said last week,
adding that it could go into one of the ``super spa areas.'' ``It's
not going to be easy. You're talking about sizes that don't fit.''
Trump said he plans to make a decision by next month.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the Finnish Council maintains a watchful eye.
The ultimate option, Lahteenmaki said, would be to take the rooms
back to Finland. ``We're not going to stand by and see it
destroyed,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
