<HEADLINE>
SWEENEY FACES FULL SEASON WITHOUT BOURQUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For a dozen years, when defenseman Don Sweeney would
arrive at Bruins training camp, there was one constant: Ray
Bourque.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time since Sweeney's tenure began in 1988 that
Bourque, traded to the Colorado Avalanche in March, is notably and
permanently absent. But Sweeney said not having the former captain
around now isn't as weird as it was about a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, it felt strange when I was skating with him
beforehand (during informal practices in Salem, N.H.),'' said
Sweeney during a practice session in suburban Wilmington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first time I'd seen him in a Colorado Avalanche
practice jersey. Then, the strangest thing was when I knew he was
leaving on Wednesday and after we skated, you're sticking out your
hand and saying, `Have a good year and good luck.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque and Sweeney, both unrestricted free agents, decided to
stay put over the summer. Sweeney was assured by management that
the club was going to do everything it could to be competitive
again, which is what convinced Sweeney to remain in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to think there's a lot of renewed optimism in the
fact that we're going to be healthier, starting with (Jason
Allison),'' said Sweeney. ``Not many teams in this league are going
to win without their No. 1 centerman.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been little discussion about the missing free agents _
Joe Thornton, Anson Carter, and Sergei Samsonov _ but Sweeney, like
everyone in the Bruins' dressing room, believes they're an
important part of the equation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd love to see the other three guys because I think, without
saying anymore, they add a big part of our offense,'' Sweeney said.
``With Byron (Dafoe) and with Kyle (McLaren), those are big factors
in our lineup who weren't there for periods of time last year.
You're just not going to win without those horses. We've also gone
through a period of evaluation. We've seen where we have some
depth. With Cameron Mann, Andre Savage, Eric Nickulas just to name
a few. That's why you go through training camp and see if those
guys can re-emerge as players who can help us.''
</P>
<P>
   After Bourque's trade, Allison talked about how it was time for
the club's young players to take over the leadership role and how
it hadn't been easy for them to assert themselves for fear of
stepping on toes. Allison said it wasn't because of anything
Bourque did, quite the contrary, it was just a bit intimidating
considering Bourque's immense stature.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember it very well,'' said Sweeney, when asked if he
recalled the comments. ``Jason and I sat down and talked about it
because I thought the timing of it might not have been appropriate,
being the day after Raymond left, but the message was appropriate.
I think Ray was the first guy to say that. We'd be in a little bit
of a tailspin and he's say, `This is not my team. Look at Ally and
Kyle.' He was the first to say it. (The leadership) needs to be
spread around the room.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney said he believes the team has a terrific core of young
players, similar to the talent and leadership that were here during
coach Pat Burns's first season (1997-98).
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt we had that a couple of years ago but we lost that _
Tim Taylor, Dave Ellett, Ken Baumgartner, and Grant Ledyard,'' said
Sweeney. ``Things were in disarray a little bit. It was up to us to
correct that. I enjoyed reading (president/general manager Harry
Sinden's comments). It was a good analogy, that he brought a group
of individuals into training camp and it's up to them to make it a
team. It's part of Burnsie's responsibility, but that onus has to
be on us as players to go out and play together as a group. New
Jersey and Dallas have done it well. Colorado is looking to do
that, they have changed a few parts.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, Sweeney was the Bruins' most consistent blueliner
last season. Partly because of injuries and the revolving door of
players, it was difficult for the team to have any cohesiveness.
Sweeney said he expects that to be much different this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got six guys who have played an awful lot of hockey in
the NHL,'' he said. ``We've got a pretty good blend of size and
Paul Coffey obviously adds an element since Raymond's departure
that we probably missed power-play wise and on the offensive side
of things a little bit. Now you've got a chance to move in Darren
Van Impe and Kyle and maybe Jonathan Girard into those offensive
situations with a little less pressure maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney, as do Bruins' fans, knows that Feb. 21 in Colorado and
March 24 at the FleetCenter, he will be on the opposite side of his
close friend and former mentor. That likely will be even more
strange than when he wished him well earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray feels like (the Avalanche are) going to be together all
year and they'll be able to pick up where they fell a little short
last year,'' said Sweeney. ``He's really looking forward to it,
moving another step forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Here, Sweeney is too.
</P>
</TEXT>
