<SLUG> BC-OLY-SOC-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. MEN OPEN OLYMPIC SOCCER COMPETITION WITH 2-2 TIE AGAINST
CZECHS 
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANBERRA, Australia _ Brad Friedel remembers the U.S. soccer
team that went to the Summer Games in Barcelona eight years ago.
``Two professionals on the entire team,'' he recalled Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   This time it is different. The United States started 10
professionals and one very impressive college forward, Conor Casey,
and outplayed the Czech Republic almost all the way in a 2-2 tie
Tuesday night in the opening round of the Summer Games tournament.
Soccer opens the Games competition despite the fact that the
opening ceremonies are not until Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The tie was definitely a blow to the Czechs, who lumbered and
labored to stay with the Americans for much of the night. A penalty
kick in the 52nd minute allowed the Czechs to break even, but they
treated the outcome as a loss. ``They got through our defenses all
night, no matter what we did,'' said the Czech coach, Karel
Bruckner.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, which has never won a medal in men's Olympic
competition, will now play Cameroon here Saturday and Kuwait in
Melbourne next Tuesday, but this was a huge point.
</P>
<P>
   Friedel, who is the reserve goalkeeper for Liverpool in the
English Premier Division, was called to the American team two weeks
ago when the regular goalkeeper, Adin Brown, was hurt. Friedel, 29,
and looking a bit grizzled with his fuzzy bleached crewcut, is one
of the team's three over-23-year-old players allowed under Olympic
rules.
</P>
<P>
   He did not know some of the younger U.S. players, but has been
impressed with forwards like Casey, from the University of
Portland, Josh Wolff from the Chicago Fire and Chris Albright from
DC United, both of Major League Soccer. The three put pressure on
the Czechs all night, with Albright and Wolff both scoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The MLS makes a huge difference,'' Friedel said afterward.
``This Czech team has lost something like two games in 17, and at
times we played them right out of the park. Our team is so much
better than in 1992. This proves that MLS is developing good young
players. Yet the European leagues will pay these Czech guys a lot
of money. They should be taking some of the American players,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedel remembers the discrepancy in 1992. The United States
opened against the Italian under-23 team, and he recalled:
``They've got guys playing in Serie A and I'm going back to UCLA to
play San Diego State. It's different now. Our guys belong.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, the Americans, coached by Clive Charles, began
moving the ball predominately on the left side and popping it in
toward the large forward, Casey, the only college player on the
squad.
</P>
<P>
   The approach paid off in the 21st minute when Wolff made a run
down the left side and fired a cross in front of the goalmouth.
Casey slid and failed to touch the ball, but Albright slid in from
the right and poked the ball into the net.
</P>
<P>
   The United States held the lead for seven minutes until Marek
Jankulovski created a goal on his own, dribbling into traffic,
going right, faking Frankie Hejduk into an impromptu corkscrew, and
then dribbling left and firing a left-footed shot that Friedel
could not handle after his right foot slipped on the dewy grass.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans seemed recharged by the Czech goal and began
playing openly again. In the 44th minute, a long booming punt by
the keeper came back to haunt the Czechs when it was smartly
rebounded upfield. Casey controlled it on the left side, sent a
pass into the goalmouth that Wolff converted with his right foot
for a 2-1 lead at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Seven minutes into the second half, Chad McCarty, an American
defender, was called for taking down Marek Heinz in the penalty
area. Lukas Dosek converted the penalty kick for the fourth and
final goal of the match.
</P>
<P>
   However, Friedel and Wolff nearly stunned the Czechs in the 64th
minute when Friedel spotted Wolff on the fly and made a
discus-thrower heave that put the ball in front of Wolff, who could
not quite beat the goalkeeper.
</P>
<P>
   ``He put it on a dime,'' Wolff said later. ``I just didn't
control it with my foot.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedel, who has great hand skills from his basketball days in
Ohio _ he could have been a walk-on at UCLA _ was proud of his long
throw, as well as the tie. The last time the United States won its
opening Olympic match was in 1984 in Los Angeles. The American team
has never even advanced to the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   In the first game of the doubleheader before a packed house of
24,800 fans, Germany defeated Australia, 3-0, in a women's match.
The American women, defending Olympic champions and 1999 Women's
World Cup champions, make their debut in Melbourne on Thursday
against Norway, the only nation to have an advantage in past
competition over them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
