<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3019 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0914-COX     09-13 2685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0914-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: A Plan for the national parks
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fog-shrouded Skykomish River served as a backdrop as George
W. Bush announced his plans in Monroe, Wash., today to fix up
national parks and protect endangered salmon. Bush said he would
push Congress to appropriate $4.9 billion over five years to pay
for a backlog of projects to fix deteriorating highways, repair
leaky roofs at tourist attractions and purify polluted streams in
national parks. He blamed the Clinton administration for rundown
parks, saying too many federal dollars were spent acquiring land
and not enough went to maintaining existing properties, leaving the
National Park Service with more property but less money to take
care of it.
</P>
<P>
   HISTORY CLASS IN MAINE
</P>
<P>
   Returning his focus to education, Al Gore toured a high school
today in Lewiston, Maine, and declared that the importance of
lifelong learning is ``the single most important lesson the new
economy teaches us.'' To personalize his pitch, he spent a short
night at the home of local teachers, then met with Lewiston High
administrators, teachers and parents. ``I'm anxious to learn from
you,'' Gore told them before teaching a history class for nearly an
hour and talking up his higher education proposals at a rally. The
goal of Gore's swing was to hammer at his $170 billion proposal for
education, an issue that traditionally plays well for Democrats, in
an effort to counter George W. Bush's success promoting his own
education ideas.
</P>
<P>
   GOOD-GOVERNMENT GROUP SUES FEC
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of overhauling the campaign finance laws filed suit
in federal court today against the Federal Election Commission,
arguing that political party-financed ads in support of the
presidential candidates are illegal. The suit was brought by Scott
Harshbarger, head of Common Cause; ex- Watergate special prosecutor
Archibald Cox and ex-Common Cause head Fred Wertheimer. The FEC has
refused to rule that the ads are illegal. Al Gore and George W.
Bush each received $67.6 million in public funds for their fall
campaigns after agreeing not to raise outside funds nor spend any
additional money, except for lawyers and accountants. The lawsuit
argues that both campaigns are violating the law by helping to
develop the massive political party-financed advertising efforts.
</P>
<P>
   GORE OPENS UP CLEAR LEAD IN POLL
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore has opened a 7-point lead over George W. Bush in the
latest Reuters/Zogby poll released today _ the first time his lead
has been outside the statistical margin of error. The poll of 1,005
people who said they were likely to vote in the Nov. 7 presidential
election found Gore leading Bush by 46 to 39 percent. Green Party
candidate Ralph Nader had 4 percent, and the Reform Party's Pat
Buchanan had 1 percent. Gore's lead was just outside the
statistical margin of error of 3.2 percentage points. The poll was
conducted Sunday through Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   BOTH SIDES TO MEET ON DEBATE SET-UP
</P>
<P>
   Senior representatives from both major presidential campaigns
will meet Thursday to try to hammer out the number, dates,
locations and formats of the upcoming presidential debates. Al Gore
supports a proposal from the bipartisan Commission on Presidential
Debates to hold three 90-minute presidential forums and one vice
presidential debate in October. All would be carried by the three
major TV networks, several cable outlets as well as public
television. George W. Bush had proposed appearing with Gore on two
TV interview shows and holding only one commission-sponsored
debate. He abandoned that stance last week, but the Bush campaign
now declines to spell out its position.
</P>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA REPUBLICANS BEGIN TO WONDER
</P>
<P>
   From Washington state, George W. Bush returned again to
California today to campaign, but some Republicans question whether
he is fighting vigorously enough for the nation's most vote-rich
state. Bush is taking a swing through Southern California regions
that are in many cases already Republican territory, including San
Diego, Irvine and Newport Beach. He is leaving the state Friday for
home just as California Republicans gather for their party
convention. Bush has shown little interest in boosting the
candidacies of fellow Republicans in California, even though the
party has signaled it is counting on him to lift its fortunes. In
interviews with the Associated Press, some Republican officials and
strategists expressed concern that Bush's efforts have been
inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   WATTS TO BUSH: REV UP THE OFFENSE
</P>
<P>
   A top House Republican said today that George W. Bush needs to
get back on offense after allowing Al Gore to control the political
ball the past three weeks. ``If you're on defense, you're probably
losing,'' said Rep. J.C. Watts of Oklahoma, the House GOP
Conference chairman who was a University of Oklahoma Sooners
quarterback. Bush has struggled in recent weeks as Gore has pulled
ahead in some national polls and made races in some states
competitive.
</P>
<P>
   FARMERS AND THE ESTATE TAX
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney told farmers today that they shouldn't have to worry
about a federal estate tax when passing along the family farm.
Using a fourth-generation farm in western Michigan as a backdrop,
he told about 400 people about George W. Bush's plan to eliminate
the estate tax if elected president. ``We want to repeal the `death
tax,' `` Cheney said. ``We want to get rid of it.'' Wearing a
Michigan State University pullover, Cheney said it was part of
Bush's plan to return to the taxpayers about one-quarter of the
nation's expected tax surplus over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   YOU WANT A COMPLAINT? HERE'S A COMPLAINT
</P>
<P>
   Two Democratic senators complained to the Federal Communications
Commission about the Republican ad that subtly flashes the word
``RATS'' across the screen. The ad is already coming off the air,
but Sens. Ron Wyden of Oregon and John Breaux of Louisiana asked
for an investigation in a letter sent today to the FCC. In 1974,
the agency adopted a policy saying that subliminal advertising was
contrary to the public interest. FCC officials said Tuesday that
they had not received a complaint about the GOP ad, but would
investigate if one were filed.
</P>
<P>
   DECRYING VIOLENT ENTERTAINMENT
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lieberman decried a ``culture of carnage'' surrounding
America's young people and told a Senate committee today that the
government should stop the marketing of violent movies, music and
video games to children if the industry fails to police itself.
Lynne Cheney, wife of Dick Cheney and former head of the National
Endowment for the Humanities, espoused many of the same views as
Lieberman. But she took a swipe at the Democratic ticket, asking
that Lieberman and Al Gore deliver the message of accountability
when they attend a fund-raiser Thursday with Harvey Weinstein,
chairman of Miramax Films. She also decried the lyrics of rap star
Eminem: ``They could not be more despicable. They could not be more
hateful.''
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON AN EASY PRIMARY WINNER
</P>
<P>
   Primary challenge behind her, Hillary Clinton looked to the fall
today. As expected, she swept past her little-known challenger,
soundly defeating Dr. Mark McMahon, an orthopedic surgeon, with 82
percent of the vote. Now she goes on tonight to her first debate
with Republican opponent Rick Lazio, who was unopposed in his
primary. The televised, one-on-one forum in Buffalo moderated by
NBC's Tim Russert, will give many voters their longest and most
substantial look at the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ALL UNDER THE BRIDGE NOW?
</P>
<P>
   In Selma, Ala., African-American businessman James Perkins
defeated Joe Smitherman, a reformed segregationist whose tenure as
mayor reaches back to 1964 _ a few months before civil rights
marchers were met at Edmund Pettus Bridge by troopers with tear gas
and clubs in a clash that became known as ``Bloody Sunday.''
Perkins received 6,326 votes, or about 57 percent of the vote, in
the nonpartisan runoff. Smitherman had 4,854 votes, or about 43
percent. Perkins said race wasn't a factor. But many voters thought
otherwise. ``This was the final step of the march over the
bridge,'' said Selma resident Burl Brown.
</P>
<P>
   UPSET IN THE MAKING IN NEW YORK
</P>
<P>
   A 71-year-old ex-librarian is giving party-switching incumbent
Rep. Michael Forbes a run for his money in New York state. Regina
Seltzer, who raised $40,000 to Forbes' $1.4 million, was ahead by
39 votes of the 11,611 cast in unofficial returns Tuesday night.
Forbes said voting machines had been impounded for a recount that
would take several days. Forbes left the Republican Party last
year, saying the party had become too extremist. But Seltzer said
Forbes' opposition to abortion and votes to impeach President
Clinton proved he was no Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   MIXED MESSAGE ON GAY-COUPLES LAW
</P>
<P>
   Vermont voters had their first chance to weigh in on the civil
unions law _ and they sent a mixed message. Five Republican state
legislators who supported the law granting gay couples many of the
rights and benefits of marriage were defeated in their primaries.
One Democrat who opposed the law was also ousted. Four Republicans
and one Democrat who were targeted for defeat because they backed
the law survived their primaries. Another lawmaker who was
challenged for opposing the law was re-elected. It was the first
chance voters had to register their views since the Legislature
earlier this year enacted the closest thing in America to gay
unions.
</P>
<P>
   PACKERS TAKE IT IN FOR SCORE
</P>
<P>
   Voters approved a half-percent sales tax to help the Green Bay
Packers pay for a $295 million renovation of Lambeau Field, the
football team's home for the past 43 years. Brown County voters
favored it by 53-47 percent. The tax will provide a $160 million
public share for renovating and expanding 71,100-seat Lambeau
Field. The three-year project will add 10,000 seats, more bathrooms
and concession stands and a mall-like atrium.
</P>
<P>
   DELAWARE NOMINEE IN BY 46 VOTES
</P>
<P>
   Former Judge Bill Lee conceded the Republican gubernatorial
nomination in Delaware to former state Chamber of Commerce
President John Burris, whose narrow margin of victory held up after
a two-day review of the voting. Certified results of Saturday's GOP
primary showed Burris winning by 46 votes out of more than 27,000
cast, and the numbers stood after a recount. Lee plans to endorse
Burris, who will face Lt. Gov. Ruth Ann Minner in the Nov. 7
general election.
</P>
<P>
   CHENEY'S PROFIT: $18.3 MILLION
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney made an $18.3 million profit on the sale of 660,000
shares of Halliburton Co. stock late last month. It was a standard
divestiture of securities, and not connected to the election, said
his spokesman, Dirk Vande Beek. Cheney retired as chairman of
Halliburton, an oil services company based in Dallas, shortly after
being chosen as running mate by George W. Bush. ``These were
already vested options, and he cashed them in,'' Vande Beek said.
The 660,000 shares Cheney sold in August were valued at about $35
million, according to documents filed with the Securities and
Exchange Commission. In June, Cheney sold 100, 000 shares for an
estimated $5.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   NADER FINDS COMEDY A TOUGH GIG
</P>
<P>
   The Green party's Ralph Nader pulled a rubber chicken from
behind a couch and choked it on Jay Leno's TV show to make his
point that George W. Bush and Al Gore are ducking debates with him.
The gag drew tepid laughter. Nader ended up in an impromptu debate
with a fellow guest, comedian D.L. Hughley, who was cracking jokes
at Nader's expense. ``I was actually thinking about a two-piece and
a biscuit,'' Hughley said, looking at the limp chicken. When Nader
said he would continue to fly coach class, Hughley said he wasn't
keen on the president sitting next to him. ``Hey, hand me the
peanuts, prez,'' Hughley mockingly asked. When Nader said 10,500
people attended his rally in Portland, Ore., recently, Hughley
fired back: ``In Portland, Oregon, they don't have nothing else to
do.'' The audience roared. Nader had to laugh, too.
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY AND JOE _ TOGETHER IN NEW YORK
</P>
<P>
   From the day last month that Joe Lieberman was selected as the
Democratic vice presidential candidate, Hillary Clinton has said
she would like to campaign with him as she runs for a Senate seat
in New York. On Friday, she will get her chance. Lieberman will
campaign with Clinton in New York City. Clinton and her strategists
have said they hope that some of Lieberman's popularity will rub
off on her, particularly with Jewish voters. Polls have Clinton,
who is in a tight race with Rick Lazio, leading among Jewish voters
by a margin smaller than New York Democrats usually need to win
statewide races. But those same surveys show Al Gore, helped by
Lieberman, leading George W. Bush by 20 points or more in New York.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S BACK TO BEHIND CLOSED DOORS
</P>
<P>
   They sang, they danced, they laughed and they cried, but there
was no reprise of ``the kiss.'' Al and Tipper Gore headlined an
$800,000 Democratic Party fund-raiser in Camden, N.J., with stars
from the worlds of entertainment and politics. Bill Bradley,
defeated by Gore in the primaries, invited Gores to recreate the
lingering smooch Al delivered to Tipper on the night he accepted
the presidential nomination last month. Gore strode on stage and
played the moment, but settled for a demure kiss to Tipper's hand
instead.
</P>
<P>
   ALL WHO QUALIFY, LINE UP NOW
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush likes to say that anyone who pays income tax
would benefit from his proposed tax cut and has been trying to
dramatize the point by appearing with a supposedly typical family
at each campaign stop and crowing about the savings they would
receive under his plan. But becoming one of the ``tax families''
isn't that easy. An e-mail sent to New Mexico Republicans last week
said Bush was ``seeking two families in New Mexico to highlight his
plan for tax relief and prescription drugs.'' The qualification:
The family must make $35,000 to $70,000 a year, itemize its taxes,
have no children in day care, no children in college, no one
attending night school, no children younger than age 1, and ```no
substantial savings outside of 401(k).''
</P>
<P>
   CONTINUANCE FOR GORE'S SON
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore's son won't be tried on speeding and reckless driving
charges until after the Nov. 7 election. Trial for Albert Gore III,
17, was delayed until Nov. 22 at the request of his lawyer, William
Brumsey III. It had been scheduled to begin today in Currituck
County, N.C. Brumsey said the presidential campaign wasn't a factor
in the delay. A defense memo said young Gore attends school in the
Washington area and a court date at the start of his Thanksgiving
break would reduce the loss of school time. The memo also said he
doesn't deny that there is a factual basis for the charges. The
teenager was charged Aug. 12 with driving 97 mph in a 55 mph zone
and reckless driving near the Outer Banks, where he had been
vacationing with his family.
</P>
<P>
   OH, THOSE CRAZY YARMULKES
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lieberman, the nation's first Jewish vice presidential
candidate, has spawned another innovation: the country's first ever
campaign yarmulke. Zipple.com, a Web site devoted to Jewish
religion and culture, is selling the traditional Jewish skullcaps
emblazoned with the logo ``Lieberman 2000.'' Jory Rozner, the
company's president, said the idea came from the interest visitors
to the site expressed in Lieberman's candidacy. Rozner said she
wasn't concerned about the appropriateness of the Lieberman slogan,
adding that she has seen yarmulkes featuring Sesame Street
characters, the ``Rugrats'' and even one cheering on the University
of Michigan sports teams. ``People get crazy with them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
