<SLUG> BC-POLL-ELECTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GORE LEADS BUSH AMONG KEY VOTING BLOCS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore has widened his lead over
Texas Gov. George W. Bush among independents and among voters in
the $25,000 to $50,000 income bracket and has pulled even with Bush
among males, pollster John Zogby said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly Gore is in the ascendancy and Bush is faltering,''
said Zogby, who is based in Utica, N.Y. ``I think he's at rock
bottom now.''
</P>
<P>
   But Zogby said the race remains extremely close. ``If (Bush)can
get back on track _ and there's plenty of time to get back on track
_ we could be looking at a Kennedy-Nixon election.'' He was
referring to the 1960 battle when beat then Vice President Richard
Nixon by 118,574 votes.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Zogby's latest poll of 1,005 likely voters questioned
Sunday through Tuesday shows Gore over Bush, 46 percent to 39
percent. Green Party candidate Ralph Nader had 4 percent and
conservative commentator Pat Buchanan had 1 percent. Zogby
conducted the poll for the Reuters news service.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's 7-point advantage was a point higher than the last Zogby
poll, released Sept. 7. That survey showed Gore leading Bush 45.6
percent to 40.2 percent. Zogby's polls have a margin of error of
plus or minus 3.2 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Gore widened his lead slightly over Bush among independents. The
Wednesday poll showed him ahead of the Texan 43 percent to 32
percent in this category, compared with his 41.7 percent-to-33.8
percent lead last week.
</P>
<P>
   In the $25,000-$50,000 income group, Gore led Bush 51 percent to
34 percent this week. In last week's Zogby poll, Bush had a
razor-thin lead among these voters _ 45 percent to 44 percent. No
candidate since 1972 has won a presidential election without
carrying this income bracket.
</P>
<P>
   Zogby said Gore has consolidated his position with traditional
Democratic voters such as union members and minorities, and he said
the vice president's ability to ``make inroads among independents''
is an important gain.
</P>
<P>
   With male voters Gore made striking gains in Zogby's survey
Wednesday. He and Bush are now tied among men, at 43 percent each.
Men have tilted toward Republicans in recent elections, and in the
Sept. 7 Zogby poll they favored Bush over Gore 48 percent to 37
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Zogby also said Gore leads Bush 48 percent to 38 percent in a
wide swath of Midwestern/Great Lakes states stretching from Ohio
west to Minnesota and south to Missouri. Analysts say these states
are a key geographic battleground in the election.
</P>
<P>
   In last week's poll, Zogby said, Bush led Gore in this region by
a narrow 47 percent to 45 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Among parents with children under 17, Gore led Bush 45 percent
to 36 percent this week. In last week's Zogby poll, Bush led Gore
in this group by a narrower margin, 46 percent to 42 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Like other pollsters, Zogby said Gore is consolidating his
support among women, particularly those who are independent voters.
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address dan(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
