<HEADER>
A3026 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT &LR;      09-13 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LITMUS TEST FOR ROMANTICS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are many ways common and mysterious to use a book, from
reading to doorstop. But this summer a woman of my acquaintance
suggested one I had not thought of, although after some inquiries I
discovered it was not an uncommon convention or trick, albeit a
dangerous one. It is the book as litmus test, used mostly but not
always in measuring a lurking romance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a boyfriend who wasn't an ideal choice and a potential
boyfriend who also wasn't an ideal choice,'' the woman explained.
Her litmus test had a rather charming absurdity about it. She gave
each man John Kennedy Toole's Pulitzer Prize-winning risible
masterpiece, ``A Confederacy of Dunces'' (LSU, 1980), and that, in
fact, is what the two turned out to be. ``I wanted to see if they
cared enough about me to at least read a book I liked. I gave one
of them the novel a second time. Neither read it.'' She dumped them
both.
</P>
<P>
   This revelation led to an informal survey in which, for women at
least, two of the most popular test books were Tolstoy's tragedy of
a woman's faith in romantic love, ``Anna Karenina,'' and ``The Sun
Also Rises,'' Hemingway's so-called ``lost generation'' novel of
drinking, fighting, wandering and love-making among expatriates in
postwar Paris.
</P>
<P>
   For a woman who elected ``The Sun Also Rises,'' the novel was
not as absolute a measure as ``Confederacy'' but rather part of a
battery of tests. She described it this way: ``If they failed, I
didn't automatically dump them; I monitored them more carefully
about their sensibility. I liked the style and sensibility of the
novel's characters, particularly Lady Brett, and I wanted to see if
the guy could relate to a strong female like her. I even went to
Spain to give a guy a copy of the book. It was a bizarre little
dating test, and I ended up married to a guy who still hasn't read
the book.''
</P>
<P>
   Several women used ``Anna Karenina.'' Melissa Bank, the
best-selling author, said that a friend of hers was involved with a
man who identified with Anna Karenina's husband, Alexei Karenin,
``a man of remarkably weak character who was bound by convention
and not the least passionate.'' One doesn't need to write fiction
to know how that relationship fared. Bank added: ``Once on a date,
I was talking to this guy about Anna Karenina, and he missed the
point of Anna driving to the train station. This didn't bode well.
I know you are totally separated from someone when they don't get a
book, or they love a book you thought was terrible.'' Pretty
unforgiving testing grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Nan A. Talese, editorial director of her eponymous Doubleday
imprint, said: ``I've never directly used a book as such a test,
but I am very, very aware of what someone says about a book because
it says a great deal about themselves. You get a tremendous insight
into the character of people and their emotions from the books they
like.''
</P>
<P>
   So the book is pretty much established as an important psychic
tool, at least inferentially. One woman recalled that anyone she
had dated ``had to like Dickens because the importance of marrying
art to social justice was important to me, and if he didn't get
that he didn't get me. I gave `The Crisis of the Negro
Intellectual''' by Harold Cruse (William Morrow &AMP; Co., 1967) ``to a
guy who didn't get it, and I said, `I'm not sure about you,
buddy.''' She added, ``One guy never read novels, and I said to
myself, `Oh, my God, if I marry this guy our kids will lack the
genes for fiction.'''
</P>
<P>
   One woman, before marrying her second husband, gave him a
reading list of a novel each of Proust, Joyce and Henry James. ``If
he had not gotten through them, or said they were too boring, I
wouldn't have married him,'' she said. Actually, she read the Joyce
to him, ``and presumably he also read it himself.'' But she admits
she doesn't know that.
</P>
<P>
   There are variations on the book as litmus test. A female book
editor said that ``anyone who liked `The Bridges of Madison
County,''' Robert James Waller's 1992 wet-hanky read from Warner
Books, was off her list because of ``its terrible sentimental
dribble.'' But it must be admitted that there are others who for
the very same reason find it a must, and they made it a best
seller.
</P>
<P>
   Another woman said that she was given a test book, Kenneth
Grahame's ``Wind in the Willows,'' to see ``if I would respond to
its magical quality. He gained points with his choice of the test
but lost points when he impregnated someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, if it seems that using books as a relationship test is
mostly a woman thing, one male publishing executive recalled that
in his youth, ``Holden Caulfield spoke for me on some kind of level
and in making a new friend, male or female, I always managed to
find out early if they liked `Catcher.' If they didn't I felt a
little cooler toward them.'' He said that he read ``Catcher in the
Rye'' annually ``as an exercise'' until his mid-20s, when J.D.
Salinger's book stopped working for him at that intimate level. He
said that no book had replaced it.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the litmus test is not a particular book but an
author. Jerry Howard, editorial director of Broadway Books, a
Random House Inc. imprint, said: ``If a person I am talking to
turns out to be a Don DeLillo fan, there's a good chance we are
going to get along because it indicates a quality of mind and a
certain appreciation of cosmic ironies. I love this guy's writing
so much I look for fellow admirers.'' Howard edited DeLillo's
``Libra'' when it was published by Viking in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, for many the most basic test is simply whether the
other person ever picks up a book. Usually ``it's a woman asking if
she can be serious about a man who doesn't read at all,'' said John
Sterling, publisher of Henry Holt. ``It's not just what's your
favorite book. If he says `I haven't read one since ...' it isn't
going to help him.''
</P>
<P>
   Plato said that books ``seem to be alive, but do not answer a
word to the questions they are asked.'' Clearly he was wrong. They
apparently answer a lot of questions about relationships.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
