<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COCKFIGHTING14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ANIMAL ADVOCATES BACK BILL TO BAR SHIPMENT OF FIGHTING COCKS
 &HT;    By KAVITA KUMAR
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Animal welfare advocates urged Congress on
Wednesday to bar the interstate shipment of live birds for
cockfighting.
</P>
<P>
   They told the House Agriculture Committee they backed a
bipartisan bill that would close a loophole in federal law allowing
birds to be shipped to Louisiana, New Mexico, and Oklahoma, the
only states where cockfights are still legal.
</P>
<P>
   But members of the United Gamefowl Breeders Association from
Texas _ which borders all three states _ and elsewhere urged the
panel to reject the bill, saying it would bring economic pain to
hundreds of thousands of family farmers.
</P>
<P>
   The Humane Society of the United States, a major supporter of
the measure, says cockfighting continues to take place in all of
the 50 states. It estimates there are more than 30,000
cockfighters, who rake in large undisclosed amounts of money from
the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fighting birds so they injure themselves or kill one another
is the meaning of animal cruelty,'' Wayne Pacelle, senior vice
president of the Humane Society, told the committee. ``Cockfighting
is a gruesome, barbaric, and indefensible practice, and it should
receive no affirmation or approval from Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say the proposed legislation would help law
enforcement officials crack down on cockfighting in the 47 states
where it is banned.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, for example, one of 22 states where it is legal to
raise and possess fighting birds, people police believe to be
cockfighters often contend they are breeding the animals for legal
sale in other states or countries, said Lt. Sherry Schlueter of the
Broward County Sheriff's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Schlueter testified that even when police confiscate fighting
paraphernalia such as sparring muffs, blood clotting enhancers and
stimulants, prosecutors are often reluctant to press charges
because of the interstate transportation loophole.
</P>
<P>
   About 300 members of the United Gamefowl Breeders Association
who traveled from Texas, Georgia, North Carolina, Louisiana and
Mississippi told the committee the bill could wipe out the gamefowl
business outside of the three states where cockfighting is legal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill will put breeders out of business,'' said Rep. Bob
Riley, R-Ala., a committee member who opposes the measure. ``You
are talking about disenfranchising a whole group of people who have
been doing this their whole lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerns were also raised by animal breeders who travel
interstate with live birds to state fairs and other exhibitions.
Clell Agler of the American Poultry Association worried such legal
breeders would be ``unduly penalized and questioned.'' He also
pointed out there is no defining characteristic to differentiate a
fighting bird from one used for other purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Other opponents of the bill said marked the beginning of an
attempt to ban all cockfighting, and perhaps other blood sports
such as hunting.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a slippery slope between a back-door attempt to ban
cockfighting and other activities which members of this committee
support,'' said Rep. Chris John, D-La. ``It may be cockfighting
today, but it's bowhunting and fishing tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   The House bill, H.R. 1275, is a proposed amendment to the Animal
Welfare Act. It is sponsored by Rep. Collin Peterson, D-Minn., and
Rep. Joe Scarborough, R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Agriculture Committee approved a similar bill on
March 2.
</P>
<P>
   Kavita Kumar's e-mail address is kkumar(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
