A3042 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-MARRIAGE-TAX14-COX     09-13 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARRIAGE-TAX14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP LOSS IN VETO FIGHT KILLS CHANCES FOR BIG TAX CUTS
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republicans fell 16 votes short Wednesday in
their last-ditch attempt to override President Clinton's veto of a
bill that would have lowered taxes for all married couples.
</P>
<P>
   That ``absolutely'' killed any chances of big tax cuts this
year, Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., said after the 270-158 vote.
</P>
<P>
   Those voting to overturn Clinton's veto included 220
Republicans, 49 Democrats and one independent. Those upholding the
veto included 157 Democrats and one independent.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Republicans lost a similar showdown over
Clinton's veto of their proposal to phase out the estate tax, which
they call the ``death tax.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, who chairs the tax-writing Ways and
Means Committee, used lighthearted overstatement to sum up how
Republicans intend to exploit the issue in this fall's election
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past six years, President Clinton has blocked marriage
tax penalty relief more often than Tiger Woods has won major
championships,'' Archer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to pass laws, you want to pass bills that are
going to be vetoed,'' responded Rep. Charles Rangel of New York,
the ranking Democrat on Archer's committee. The death of the GOP
bill, which would have cost $289 billion over 10 years, should
clear the way for approval of a more limited $89 billion ``marriage
penalty relief'' bill favored by Clinton and the Democrats, Rangel
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Hastert and other GOP leaders said they would not consider
the Democratic proposal. While it would help all married couples
who use the standard deduction, the Democratic bill would help very
few of couples who itemize their deductions _ 25 percent of the
total _ the Republicans said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next choice on the table is paying down the debt,'' said
Hastert after the vote, as he posed on the lawn of the Capitol with
three recently married couples.
</P>
<P>
   The men in black tuxedos and the women in white bridal gowns
would have saved between $1,154 and $1,961 per couple under the
dead GOP plan. Republicans didn't calculate how much each couple
would have saved under the Democratic plan.
</P>
<P>
   Without debt reduction, each of those young couples would have
to pay about $190,000 in interest on the national debt during their
45 years in the workplace, Hastert said.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the previous day he had asked Clinton to agree to
use 90 percent of the $268 billion surplus predicted for the next
fiscal year for paying off the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton indicated that he would go along, but only if that can
be fit into his own plan for paying off the national debt within 13
years.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert's proposal would leave 10 percent, or about $27 billion,
available for tax cuts or spending increases to be agreed upon
between Congress and the White House for the fiscal year that
begins Oct. 1. It wouldn't cover years after that.
</P>
<P>
   In separate interviews, Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, and
Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, said they believe any compromise
on the $27 billion will include $14 billion in tax cuts for next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Both predicted that the $14 billion would include the first
year's portion of:
</P>
<P>
   _ Two bipartisan plans, including one re-wording some business
tax breaks so that they will conform with trade treaties, and
another prepared by Hastert and Clinton for ``community renewal''
tax breaks that encourage investments in poor regions and
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   _ Repeal of the federal telephone tax.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pension-related tax breaks, intended to make it easier for
people to save larger amounts in their tax-protected IRA or 401(k)
retirement savings accounts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Some small-business tax cuts favored by Republicans, which
would be attached to a one-dollar increase in the $5.15 minimum
wage, which is favored by the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I don't know,'' commented White House spokesman Joe
Lockhart. ``I think that (the Republicans) may be counting their
special-interest tax breaks before they hatch.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert told reporters he wasn't wedded to any particular split
of the $27 billion. ``As long as we set aside the 90 percent for
paying down the debt, you'd expect negotiations to settle the
details'' of how the rest is divided between spending increases and
tax cuts, he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Roll Call vote:
clerkweb.house.gov/cgi-bin/vote.exe?year &QC; 2000&AMP;rollnumber &QC; 466
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mollison's e-mail address is AndyM(at)Coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
