<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3051 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-GIRARD-DESIGN-ART-2TA     09-13 1473
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIRARD-DESIGN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESIGNER TO WORLD: LIGHTEN UP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., N.M., Ind., Italy)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By WILLIAM L. HAMILTON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There's something irresistible about the designs of
Alexander Girard, and it's not just the bright colors and the big
patterns or the friendly folk influences and toylike motifs.
</P>
<P>
   The brass, glass-jewel suns for La Fonda del Sol, the
Latin-American restaurant that Girard designed for the Time-Life
building in 1961; the poster-graphic ``Palio'' fabric (and over 300
others) that he created for the Herman Miller Furniture Co. from
1952 to 1973; and the tropical-travel painted fuselages for Braniff
Airlines in 1965: the stuff looks happy.
</P>
<P>
   That could be the key to its appeal right now _ it looks like
news and not nostalgia. It's hot, not cool, at a moment when
contemporary taste has settled with a lengthening snore into the
industrial safety of mid-20th-century icons like the Eameses or the
ironic suavities of fashion: shag-carpeted Los Angeles boutique
hotels and the faux-Zen design stores in SoHo and TriBeCa.
</P>
<P>
   Girard, who died in 1993, was in love with living, and it shows,
in designs being newly reissued and in a retrospective of his work,
which opened on Tuesday at the Cooper-Hewitt National Design
Museum. It's design that has a face on it, like the folk toys
Girard collected: inviting, eager to share. You want to meet it.
</P>
<P>
   For all its playfulness, it's very grown-up, very adult in its
issues: the sophistications of going to good restaurants or
entertaining at home, the education in seeing other cultures on
holiday and knowing that common objects like plates or pillows can
make the world personal for anyone.
</P>
<P>
   The Eameses, American ambassadors of the power of ``good
design,'' traversed the globe to promote it. Girard, born in New
York City in 1907 and raised in Florence, Italy, was a diplomat of
the delight in domestic detail. With his wife, Susan Needham
Girard, he owned and renovated three houses, including a historic
adobe in Sante Fe, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's really interesting about him is how he integrated
fabrics, furniture, graphics, into interior design,'' said Donald
Albrecht, curator of the Cooper-Hewitt exhibition. ``It's the
ensemble of these things that is really remarkable. And all the
rituals of life at home are very important to him: the hearth, the
dining table, even how you store _ with elaborate displays of
utensils in the kitchen.''
</P>
<P>
   It's utopia with a street address. ``Art is only art when it is
applied to living,'' said the designer, who trained as an
architect. He called himself a ``functionalist tempered by
frivolity.''
</P>
<P>
   Like his contemporary the graphic designer Paul Rand, who
created the company logo and corporate identity for IBM (the
alphabet-block-like ``Big Blue''), and who also illustrated books
for children, Girard introduced the pleasures of humor and whimsy
to the business of design, making them professionally respectable.
</P>
<P>
   Girard's savvy lack of cynicism _ his exuberant trademark, you
could say _ looks amazingly fresh.
</P>
<P>
   With his undoctrinal mixture of modern, decorative and naive
elements, Girard practiced an eclecticism now well-known to
interior designers, but it is a source of discovery for recent
collectors of modern design.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Ford, creative director of Gucci, grew up in Sante Fe, and
worked at the Compound, a restaurant that Girard designed. He was
later a friend, and remains a fan. Ford bought many of the
furnishings from the house when Susan Girard died, in 1996. It is
hard not to see the influence of Girard's ``opulent modernism'' in
Ford's fashion work: the clean, jetset cut and the brash materials.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that Modernism is a stark aesthetic is just not true
_ people miss a lot of the fun,'' said Richard Wright, a dealer and
auctioneer in Chicago, who is assembling a body of designs by
Girard to exhibit in November at the Modernism show at the Seventh
Regiment Armory on Park Avenue in New York. Vintage textiles and
furniture from a line designed for Herman Miller in 1967 (it lasted
a year) have appeared sporadically for sale in the last few years.
Herman Miller for the Home re-introduced nine Girard fabric
patterns in 1998. Maharam, a New York fabric showroom, will
reintroduce six more in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is starting to open to decoration and Girard was
really blazing the trail there,'' Wright said. ``He was a master
colorist _ wild combinations and patterns. And at his core, he's
extremely good with composition. His style of juxtaposing folk art
and ethnic objects with a Modernist aesthetic became extremely
fashionable, and largely influenced the Eameses' famous house. The
feel of that house is very much like Girard. He had already done
his residence in Detroit when they were at Cranbrook.''
</P>
<P>
   Girard, who was a friend of the Eameses, collaborated with
Charles Eames in 1957 on a short film, made in Mexico, on the Day
of the Dead. He picture-edited the couple's photographs, helping
choose the images for their ``House of Cards'' playing-card toy.
The couples spent Christmases together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christmas must have been maddening,'' Albrecht said. ``While
they're trying to eat dinner, Charles and Ray are running around
photographing the Girards' beautifully set dinner table. `Charles,
sit. Eat.'''
</P>
<P>
   In 1932, Girard returned to New York from Italy, as a young
architect. His second office, in Detroit, where he moved in search
of work in 1937, brought him to the attention of John Entenza, the
editor of the influential Arts and Architecture magazine. Girard
was introduced to Eliel and Eero Saarinen, the architects, at
Cranbrook Academy, where he also met the Eameses.
</P>
<P>
   In 1949, Girard was asked to chose the 3,200 objects for the
Detroit Institute of Art's exhibition ``For Modern Living,'' a
showcase promoting accessible, affordable design for postwar Middle
America, and the precursor of the Museum of Modern Art's series of
``Good Design'' shows in New York, which Girard also worked on in
the early 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   In 1951, recommended by Charles Eames and George Nelson, both
frustrated by the lack of modern textile designs available for
upholstering their furniture, Girard was asked by D.J. De Pree, the
chief executive of Herman Miller Furniture Co., to design fabrics.
A textiles division, which Girard headed, was created the next
year.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to understand how color could create so much
excitement, or controversy _ though the present historical moment
in design, dominated by unprepossessing shades of brown and gray,
could help explain the reaction to Girard's work.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a time when people got fainting fits if they saw
bright red,'' he said in an interview in 1983, speaking of the
1950s. Girard's vivid, '`untasteful'' blues, magentas, yellows and
reds broke with the prevailing, polite tradition of deadened ochres
and turquoises popular in interior design.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really anticipating the '60s and '70s, and Op and Pop
Art,'' Albrecht said of the designer's use of color and pattern,
even in black-and-white schemes, which he employed with an
eye-catching exaggeration.
</P>
<P>
   Girard's most important residential commission, interiors for
and J. Irwin Miller's house in Columbus, Ind., in 1955, displayed
his talents on a large scale. The designer collaborated with the
architects Eero Saarinen and Kevin Roche, and landscape designer
Dan Kiley, to create broad, interior vistas and living spaces with
four distinct, color-sensitive seasons of furnishings, including
rugs, draperies, upholsteries, and storage. There are greens in the
spring; fire reds in the winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the outstanding innovator of color of his particular
time,'' Miller said in a telephone conversation last week. ``Mrs.
Miller said to Eero, `I don't want to live in the same house all my
life.' He said, `We've built you a neutral house, that can be
changed.' It was very much influenced by Sandro.''
</P>
<P>
   The Miller residence also includes Girard's inadvertent
signature in the evolution of the living room: the conversation
pit. The low ceiling height in the house was predicated upon
acoustics and the Millers' love of music. The designer suggested
sinking the central seating group, rather than disrupting the
dramatic horizontal lines of the architecture's open plan with
sofas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We constructed a model of it at a shop in New York,'' Miller
recalled. ``We sat in it and asked ladies in the shop to walk by,
to see if their skirts exposed too much.'' At home, the Millers
realized that they had an excellent view of the underside of their
piano from the pit. The designer painted it scarlet red.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Girard's most memorable commercial commission _ and for many,
his most sadly missed _ was La Fonda del Sol, a themed restaurant
conceived by Joseph Baum of Restaurant Associates. Girard was
recommended by Philip Johnson, who had created the Four Seasons for
Baum.
</P>
<P>
   La Fonda del Sol was Girard's love of folk art _ the joy that it
captured and radiated _ put on public display. The staff costumes,
designed with Rudi Gernreich, including ponchos embroidered with
gold suns; the potterylike place settings; and the 80 different
matchbooks, with their grinning high-noon faces; and the
checkerboard tiles of the open kitchen, with its chefs behind a
flaming grill were like a market day in Mexico, brought in a basket
to Midtown Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   It was here that it is clearest why the simplicity of folk
tradition or craft would engage the empathy of modern design. It is
a humanizing lesson, still, for its latest audience.
</P>
<P>
   The Girards moved to Sante Fe in 1953, to more actively pursue
their interest in collecting. Their 100,000 folk art objects, which
Girard referred to as his toys, can now be visited at the
International Museum of Folk Art in the Girard Wing.
</P>
<P>
   The designer was asked in an interview why he collected folk
art. Was it inspiration?
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw it as a way to recapture all the wonderful enthusiasm
and the spirit of discovery that we experience as children, but
generally lose as we grow older,'' he answered.
</P>
<P>
   It was a way _ design might be another _ of being happy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
