<HEADER>
A3071 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH0914-COX     09-13 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH0914-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush introduces $5 billion plan for national parksBy Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONROE, Wash. _ GOP presidential nominee George W. Bush, eager
to get back on message, took his campaign to opponent Al Gore's
geographic and issue turf on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   At a campaign stop in Washington state, Bush tried to highlight
the difference between Republican and Democratic approaches to the
environment, an issue that polls show is a Bush weakness.
</P>
<P>
   Later Tuesday, Bush campaigned in California, an electoral vote
megastate that polls indicate is solidly in the Gore column.
</P>
<P>
   Bush stood along the Skykomish River here to pitch a $5 billion
national parks maintenance plan and assail the opposition's
philosophy and performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clinton-Gore administration has chosen to expand the
public ownership of land instead of tending to our parks,'' Bush
said. ``Their failure to make maintenance a priority has left our
parks at risk and at the breaking point.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton requested a 22 percent cut in maintenance funds in his
most recent budget request.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the use of our parks is increasing, the Clinton-Gore
administration has neglected their upkeep,'' said Bush. ``Under
this administration the parks are in worse shape than ever before.
Sewage runs untreated into the lakes and streams of Yellowstone
National Park. Civil War relics have been soaked by a leaky roof at
Gettysburg,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to his forceful, if sudden, interest in national
parks, Bush has not been an outspoken champion of state parks in
Texas during his two terms as governor. Reports by Texas A&AMP;M
University, the state auditor's office, the Texas Historical
Commission and the Legislature's Sunset Advisory Commission have
documented years of inadequate budgets, maintenance and land
acquisition. For example, San Jacinto Battleground and Monument, an
icon of the Texas revolution, needs millions of dollars for a
museum, visitors' center and landscape restoration.
</P>
<P>
   The governor acknowledged some of the problems in February when
he issued an executive order forming a conservation task force to
investigate and make recommendations. In his charge to the panel,
Bush noted that the state has ``an extensive system of state and
local parks that contribute directly to its quality of life, but
are currently overtaxed due to increased demand, aging
infrastructure and insufficient funding.'' The panel's report is
due Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign was ready Wednesday with a counter-assault on
Bush's environmental record in Texas, including the state's
relatively low funding for state parks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush's anti-environmental record in Texas was real good for
polluters and real bad for families and children,'' said Gore
spokesman Douglas Hattaway. ``Under Bush, Texas is the most
polluted state in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's attempt to score points on an environmental issue came as
polls continue to show Gore winning voters' confidence on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Bush was able to get widespread coverage and
discussion of his issue du jour. The National Parks Conservation
Association called it ``a bright spot in a presidential campaign
too often silent on environmental issues.''
</P>
<P>
   But Thomas Kiernan, the private nonprofit group's president,
also said the program would not go far enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Bush has the beginnings of a good agenda for park
protection, but critical elements are still missing, such as
preservation of cultural artifacts, improvements in park air
quality, and the need to expand existing parks and even create new
parks to he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also prodded Gore on a key issue in Washington, which is
viewed as a swing state. There has been prolonged debate about
whether to breach dams, which provide hydroelectricity, in order to
protect salmon runs which are also a key economic component in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not need to breach the dams to save the salmon,'' said
Bush. ``My opponent has refused to take a position on the issue of
salmon and the dams. . . . I think you deserve an answer. I think
you need to know where he stands on this important environmental
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has called for a ``salmon summit'' to discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
