<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHALING14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON THREATENS JAPAN SANCTIONS OVER WHALE HUNT
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Firing a shot across the bow of the Japanese
whaling industry, the White House suspended Japanese access to U.S.
fishing grounds on Wednesday and threatened to hit Tokyo with trade
sanctions within 60 days unless Japan ends its seasonal hunt for
whales.
</P>
<P>
   In his first sanctions threat against Japan in five years,
President Clinton directed aides to begin drafting a list of
sanctions options with an eye toward implementing them unless Japan
stops killing whales in the weeks ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're serious about this,'' White House chief of staff John
Podesta said at a news conference. ``We hope that the Japanese
government will reverse course on this, but the 60-day clock is now
ticking.''
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese government rebuked the White House, saying the
threats violate global trading rules and could undermine relations
between the giant Pacific allies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is inappropriate and would immediately send a negative
message to world markets,'' the Japanese government said a
statement by the Japanese Embassy in Washington. ``We are strongly
concerned that any such sanction would adversely affect the trade
relationship between our two countries.''
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese government further threatened to file a suit
against the United States with the World Trade Organization, the
Geneva-based global trade court, if Clinton carries out his
sanctions threat.
</P>
<P>
   Podesta would not say what sorts of sanctions are being
considered, insisting that the matter is under review by the U.S.
trade representative and various other U.S. agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever steps we take at the end of this process,'' said
Podesta, ``we believe we'll be able to defend within the WTO
process.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue is an annual hunt by Japanese whalers who kill several
hundred whales each year, citing the need for scientific research.
A global ban on commercial whaling permits limited whaling for such
purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Because the meat is later sold, mostly to upscale Tokyo
restaurants specializing in whale dishes, U.S. officials have long
doubted the scientific value of the annual killings and have urged
Japan to use non-lethal methods instead. Twice, in 1988 and 1995,
the White House has charged Japan with undermining the global
whaling conservation regime.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's research argument wore particularly thin to U.S.
officials this year, when Tokyo broadened its self-described
research to include the killing of sperm whales, which can grow to
60 feet long, and the smaller Bryde's whales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putting it plainly, Japan is killing whales in the name of
scientific research to satisfy a demand for whale meat in a few
high-end restaurants and gourmet boutiques,'' said Commerce
Secretary Norman Mineta. ``Our response must be clear and must be
decisive.''
</P>
<P>
   Mineta sent a letter to Clinton on Wednesday certifying that, in
the Commerce Department's view, Japan is engaged in activities that
undermine global whale conservation efforts as overseen by the
International Whaling Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The certification triggered a process wherein the president has
60 days to consider trade sanctions. In addition, the
administration placed Japanese vessels out of contention for rights
to fish for mackerel and herring in U.S. waters. Such rights are
expected to be granted, on a temporary basis, to the fleets of
other countries, before the fishing season ends this fall, as there
are surplus stocks of the fish in U.S. waters.
</P>
<P>
   The whale dispute is the sharpest to come between the United
States and Japan, this country's closest Pacific ally, since
Clinton threatened in May 1995 to slap $6 billion worth of
sanctions on Japanese luxury cars sold in this country. Those
sanctions never took effect, because the two countries reached an
agreement the following month on exports of U.S. autos and parts to
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and a host of
other diplomats and heads of state appealed directly to Japan to
scrap this year's hunt, but Japan's whaling fleet set sail in late
July.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said Japan intends to kill 440 minke whales this
year, along with 10 sperm whales and 50 Bryde's whales.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese government said in its statement that it has scaled
back those plans, and a Japanese diplomat said the hunt is expected
to end in about 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Deans's e-mail address is bobdeans(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
