<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3075 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-BOX-U.S.-ART-NYT &LR;      09-13 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BOX-U.S.-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. BOXERS, CONSIDERED THE STRONGEST GROUP SINCE 1976, ARE AIMING
HIGH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT22 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ The felon, the drug addict, the banker, the
dreamer, the staff sergeant, the next Golden Boy, a guy named Rocky
and another nicknamed Hawaiian Punch.
</P>
<P>
   They are the 2000 U.S. Olympic boxing team, and while they are
characters with rich personal stories, they are also considered the
strongest group of American Olympic boxers since the 1976 Games.
</P>
<P>
   When the boxing competition of the Sydney Games dawns Saturday,
the 2000 U.S. team will once again meet its arch-rivals, the
dominant Cubans, but they are also chasing the enduring memory of
the charismatic 1976 American squad.
</P>
<P>
   That team, led by Sugar Ray Leonard and the Spinks brothers,
Leon and Michael, won five gold medals in Montreal. This year's
team, with as many colorful personalities, is aiming even higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife has been in church praying for seven medals,'' said
U.S. coach Tom Mustin, though he did not specify gold medals.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a long road back to respectability for the
Americans, who won just one gold medal at the 1996 Olympics in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the 1997 world championships in Budapest, we won just one
bout,'' the American team leader, Gary Toney, said Wednesday, ``Not
one medal _ one bout. But by last year's world championships, we
had won four gold medals.''
</P>
<P>
   A change in philosophy has been credited with the improved
results as the U.S. team chose to compete more often
internationally. It has led to a seasoned, savvy and diverse team.
</P>
<P>
   Begin with welterweight Dante Craig of Cincinnati, who was not
even in boxing a little more than a year ago. After his mother died
of breast cancer in 1998, Craig had given up the sport and went to
work at a dry cleaner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the fastest pants presser they had,'' Craig said.
``Seventy pants an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Then one day his brother, Dion, came to him and said he had been
visited by their mother in a dream. She asked Dion to tell Dante to
resume boxing.
</P>
<P>
   Craig did just that and advanced to last year's world
championships, but a few days before he was to compete, he learned
that his three-month old son, Dante Jr., had died of a respiratory
infection. Craig, 22, pulled out of the tournament, then came back
again _ and in an upset qualified for a spot in the Olympic Trials.
He also had emergency root canal the day before the final bout.
</P>
<P>
   ``My story is so unbelievable, I don't know if I believe it,''
Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   American super heavyweight Calvin Brock has been boxing for 13
years, but with a college degree in finance he recently began a
management training program at a bank in his hometown of Charlotte,
N.C. During the spring, he asked his new bosses for time off in
September.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to the Olympics,'' he told them.
</P>
<P>
   They asked how he got tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm going to be in the Olympics,'' Brock said.
</P>
<P>
   Brock, who is 6-2 and 201, has had an enigmatic amateur boxing
career, including six losses in his first six fights. He has
certainly improved, even if he remains inconsistent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may not be showy, maybe people don't expect a lot of me when
they see me,'' Brock said, ``but I sneak up on people.''
</P>
<P>
   Heavyweight Michael Bennett is at the center of the Olympic
boxing tournament's most featured rivalry as he tries to unseat
two-time Olympic champion Felix Savon of Cuba. Bennett's path to
the Olympics, meanwhile, could not be more uncommon and his ascent
in the sport more meteoric.
</P>
<P>
   A little more than two years ago, Bennett, 29, was serving a
sentence for armed robbery. Bennett had taken up boxing in prison,
then quickly adapted to the techniques and styles of international
boxing.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he and Savon, the six-time world champion, were
scheduled to meet in the world championship gold medal final.
Savon, protesting an earlier judging decision against a Cuban
teammate, refused to enter the ring. Bennett won in a walkover, but
he wants another shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about knocking off the king of the hill,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett may be the best-known of the American fighters, but the
team is led by its smallest fighter, light flyweight Brian Viloria.
Viloria, also a reigning world champ, is the first Hawaiian native
on the boxing team in 44 years, and hence, his rather obvious
nickname.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hawaiian Punch isn't very original,'' the studious Viloria
said Wednesday in Sydney. ``But what are you going to do?''
</P>
<P>
   Viloria, who is 5-foot-4 and 106 pounds, is quick and powerful.
He began boxing 11 years ago when he was 8 years old _ mostly to
fend off his older brothers who kept stealing his toys. To
strengthen his hands, Viloria punched banana trees.
</P>
<P>
   Another reigning world champion is featherweight Ricardo Rocky
Juarez. He is named after Rocky Marciano, not Rocky Balboa.
</P>
<P>
   Olanda Anderson is the 27-year-old light heavyweight who was
added to the team when Michael Simms, the 1999 world champion in
the division, was thrown off the team for violating team policies.
</P>
<P>
   Lightweight David Jackson is the American entry at 132 pounds,
although a year ago he weighed 174 pounds. Jackson had been living
on the streets of Seattle, battling drug problems. Retired from
boxing, he went back in the gym hoping the sport could save him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without boxing, I'd probably be dead,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in Los Angeles, flyweight Jose Navarro was influenced
greatly by Oscar De La Hoya, a local hero and the 1992 Olympic
champion. With an easy smile, Navarro has been called the next
Golden Boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's saying a lot,'' Navarro, 19, said. ``I'm just getting
started.''
</P>
<P>
   Bantamweight Clarence Vinson, light welterweight Ricardo
Williams, Jr., light middleweight Jermain Taylor and middleweight
Jeff Lacy make up the rest of the U.S. boxing lineup, an engaging
team with high expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``People talk to us about the 1976 team all the time,'' Juarez
said today. ``Hopefully, we can win 12 gold medals.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
