<HEADER>
A3076 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-ROUNDUP-HNS &LR;      09-13 1246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-ROUNDUP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GORE, BUSH RAID RIVAL'S FAVORITE ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL   
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Democrat Al Gore and Republican George W. Bush staged raids on
their rival's centerpiece campaign issue Wednesday, with Gore
battling Bush for the role of education candidate and Bush taking
up the banner of conservationist.
</P>
<P>
   The jockeying over issues took place as the Gore campaign turned
over to the FBI unsolicited documents and videotaped material that
had apparently been leaked from Bush's secret preparations for the
looming presidential debates with Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The off-stage development took place as Gore, campaigning in
Lewiston, Maine, pressed his proposal to make the first $10,000 in
college tuition expenses tax deductible. Bush, appearing on the
banks of the Skykomish River in Monroe, Wash., announced a $4.9
billion cleanup of national parks.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates pitched their campaign appeals on opposite coasts
as national opinion surveys underscored the closest election since
1980, with Gore holding a slight edge over Bush in the nationwide
popular vote and Bush holding a slight lead over Gore in the
state-by-state electoral vote.
</P>
<P>
   The unsolicited material on Bush's debate preparations had been
delivered Wednesday morning to the office of former Rep. Tom
Downey, D-N.Y., a Gore confidant helping the vice president prepare
for the expected debates. Gore campaign chairman William Daley
telephoned Bush chairman Don Evans to alert him to the development.
The material was turned over to the FBI to enable the agency to
determine if the information had been illegally obtained.
</P>
<P>
   Downey, who briefly viewed the privileged material, withdrew
from Gore's debate preparations to avoid any question over misuse
of the material, Gore deputy campaign manager Mark Fabiani said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign's swift turnover of the politically sensitive
material contrasted to 1980 when the GOP presidential campaign of
Ronald Reagan received secret material revealing the debate
preparations of President Jimmy Carter. The Reagan campaign used
the material to prepare Reagan for a showdown with Carter that
helped tip the outcome of the election in Reagan's favor. The
incident provoked a congressional investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Gore tried to seize the education issue from Bush by telling
teachers, parents and administrators at a high school in Lewiston
that his plan to make a portion of college tuition expenses
deductible would help 75 percent of the nation's high school
graduates pursue higher education by 2010.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting a (high school) diploma is not the end of an education
but just the beginning,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's proposal, part of a $170 billion plan to improve
education, calls for a series of federal actions and tax breaks to
help families bear the cost of college education with either a 28
percent tax credit or full tax deductibility for the first $10,000
of annual college or higher education expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has devoted two days to touting his proposals for education
in hopes of blunting Bush's gains on an issue that has
traditionally favored Democrats. Voters rank education as their top
concern in the election, according to polls.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's plan was quickly dismissed by GOP vice presidential
candidate Dick Cheney as ``just financing failure.'' Cheney, the
former defense secretary who was campaigning in Michigan, said that
the Gore proposal provides ``more money for the bureaucrats'' than
schools and students.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign spokesman Dan Bartlett, in a statement from
Austin, Texas, said that the Clinton-Gore administration had
presided over ``an education recession'' that permitted 68 percent
of fourth-graders in the nation's poorest schools to read below
their grade level.
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett faulted Gore's proposed college tuition tax break,
saying it would only benefit families paying federal income tax _
potentially leaving out the college-age children of 29 million low-
and moderate-income families.
</P>
<P>
   As Gore tried to take back the education issue from Bush, Bush
laid claim to Gore's reputation as the conservationist. Recalling
the conservation launched by Republican President Theodore
Roosevelt _ who founded the national park system early in the 20th
century _ Bush vowed at the outset of a campaign swing to
Washington state and California that he would ``make conservation
an important commitment'' of his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that, if elected Nov. 7, he would press Congress to
spend $4.9 billion over five years to finance a backlog of repair
projects at national parks. Bush faulted the Clinton-Gore
administration for spending too much money on acquiring new
parkland at the expense of maintaining land already under federal
jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   The White House ``failure to make maintenance a priority has
left our parks at risk and at the breaking point,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also challenged Gore to take a position on the politically
sensitive question of whether to breach federally-constructed dams
in the Northwest as part of an effort to revive endangered salmon.
Clinton deferred a decision on the dams pending the outcome of
alternative salmon recovery efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, reflecting the position of farmers, shippers and power
users who benefit from the dams, favors federally-supported state
efforts to clean up salmon habitats without destroying the dams. He
visited a salmon pond known as Haskell Slough near Monroe to
spotlight the results of a $300,000 federal-state project that
enabled salmon to return to the area for the first time in 50 years
without throwing open the dams. Some environmentalists contend the
dams have imperiled salmon spawning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of command-and-control, we'll provide a helping hand''
because ``protecting our environment must be a shred
responsibility,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign struck back at Bush's bid to wear the mantle
of conservationist. Gore campaign spokesman Doug Hattaway dubbed
Texas ``the most polluted state in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Klain, a senior Gore adviser, cited the vice president's
efforts with Clinton to create 13 new national parks and to boost
the National Park Service budget. As governor of Texas, Bush had
allowed spending on state parks to rank 49th out of 50 states,
Klain said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to parks, Al Gore has a record of achievement
whereas George W. Bush has a record of neglect,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bush's effort on the west coast followed a furor on Tuesday over
a Republican Party campaign ad that flashed the word ``rats''
across the screen during criticism of Gore's proposal to expand
Medicare coverage to prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Independent pollster John Zogby said that the Bush campaign
needs to overcome campaign setbacks _ such as the distracting ad
and earlier questions over Gore's credibility for raising 1996
campaign funds at a Buddhist temple _ in order to focus instead
upon potentially appealing GOP proposals to strengthen public
education and expand Medicare coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to be positive on those kinds of issues,'' said
Zogby, based in Utica, N.Y. ``Those are the kinds of ads he should
be running. No rats, no Buddhist temple.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wire services contributed to this report.
</P>
