   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-FUEL (London) _ It's a study in chaos as Britons
hoarding gasoline and food show little faith in Tony Blair's
promise to get the crisis under control. About 90 percent of
Britain's 13,000 service stations remained closed. By Kevin Cullen.
1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-SHOOTING (Quebec) _ Investigative reporter known for
coverage of motorcycle gangs is shot and killed. The attack comes
hours after Quebec urges the federal government to suspend civil
liberties of bikers by outlawing membership in the Hells Angels,
Rock Machine and other outlaw groups. By Colin Nickerson. 1000
words.
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND-CLINTON (Washington) _ Protestant First Minister David
Trimble meets with President Clinton at the White House. Clinton
might announce he will make a final trip to Ireland before he
leaves office. By Susan Milligan. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-VIOLENCE (Washington) _ Each actor in an all-star
political cast _ Joseph Lieberman, Lynne Cheney, and John McCain _
give dramatic performances, blaming the entertainment industry for
polluting the popular culture and making it nearly impossible for
parents to police the films, recordings, and video games that amuse
their children. By Mary Leonard. 800 words. &UR;  &LR; (w and e coding)
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE-HATE (Washington) _ Giving a last-gasp hope to one of
President Clinton's biggest legislative priorities, the House is
expected to easily approve a measure supporting the expansion of
federal hate crimes legislation to protect victims of violence
based on gender, disability and sexual orientation. By Susan
Milligan. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS (p) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-GORE (Lewiston, Maine) _ Al Gore stops at a high school
to promote his educational package. By Michael Kranish and Yvonne
Abraham. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DNA-EXECUTE (Undated) _ The Boston Globe asks a Virginia court
to prevent that state's officials from destroying DNA evidence that
could prove whether an executed man, who claimed he was innocent,
was guilty. By John A. Farrell. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   MIT-DRINKING (Boston) _ MIT admits that its lax alcohol and
housing policies played a role in the 1997 death of freshman Scott
Krueger, agrees to pay a $6 million settlement to his family. By
Beth Healy. 900 words.
</P>
