<SLUG> BC-MOGALL-CLOSES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOGALL SHUTS DOWN AS WEB VENTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Software pioneer John Cullinane and former Boston TV
newsman Brian Leary have closed operations at Mogall Inc., the
business-to-business Internet venture they launched last summer,
and are working to repackage their product as corporate software.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Cullinane said he is ``discussing a merger
with another organization,'' which he would describe only as a
company ``engaged in e-mail support services.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten of 12 employees who worked in Mogall's leased office in
Watertown were laid off at the end of August, Cullinane and Leary
said. The office has been sublet to others and phone calls are
being rerouted to Cullinane's personal office in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Leary, the company's chief executive, and Matthew Morrissey, who
held the title of chief of staff, remain at work, overseeing work
to rewrite Mogall online service software so it can be sold as an
application for use with large corporate software systems.
</P>
<P>
   Mogall was founded last winter with a $2 million personal
investment by Cullinane, but couldn't raise more venture capital
after prices of many Internet and electronic-commerce stocks began
to plunge last March. Cullinane said he never intended to put more
money in himself.
</P>
<P>
   Mogall set out to be an online subscription database service
where companies could store data about clients, employees, vendors
and others and then retrieve it in ways that could provide new
intelligence for developing business leads.
</P>
<P>
   As Leary described Mogall last summer: ``We're talking about,
`who knows how to do what, who worked with the client before, who
has the relationship _ who can get us in the door.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Even as Mogall was hosting local political, business, and media
figures at a kickoff cocktail party in June the company's future
was uncertain, Cullinane said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a plan that was geared to make money, but when you get
caught in a downdraft, that's it,'' he said. ``To me it was a roll
of the dice, and I learned a lot,''
</P>
<P>
   Leary said a Boston Globe article in July in which Cullinane
told about Mogall's touch-and-go status may have hurt fund-raising.
``It became something of a self-fulfilling prophecy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Leary said Andersen Consulting, in Chicago, has shown strong
interest as a potential customer for a corporate ``enterprise''
edition of the Mogall software. He said Public Consulting Group
Inc. of Boston is also interested in marketing Mogall software.
</P>
<P>
   Leary and Morrissey are working at Dataware Inc., in Cambridge,
which wrote Mogall's core software. Cullinane said Dataware has a
stake in Mogall as a result of that work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
