<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-PEACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARAFAT'S LIMBO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY WAS TO have been the day Yasser Arafat unilaterally
declared an independent Palestinian state in the absence of a
negotiated final-status agreement with Israel. But there has been
no peace accord and no unilateral Palestinian declaration of
statehood.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, Arafat and his Palestinian Authority find
themselves in a situation of suspended animation, floating between
the compromises required for peace and the bravado of a gesture
that can only harm Palestinian interests. The reality is that
Palestinians and Israelis alike have no tolerable alternative but
to strike a bargain for peaceful coexistence.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, this is what Arafat heard from the major powers he
consulted after his fruitless summer sojourn at Camp David. In
European capitals, but also in Russia, China, and India, the
Palestinian leader was told that of course his old friends support
him and the Palestinian cause but he needs to work something out
with Israel if he wants to bring into being a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the international diplomatic reality. There are also
chronological constraints of the political calendars in Israel and
America.
</P>
<P>
   As Arafat must know, even if he refuses to acknowledge it in
public, the committed mediator who presided at Camp David,
President Clinton, will soon be replaced. The chances are his
successor will be either less willing to press compromises on
Israel or reluctant to entangle his new administration in the tar
baby of Mideast peacemaking for a year or two.
</P>
<P>
   The prospects for political change in Israel are, if anything,
even less promising for Arafat. If the aging Palestinian leader
does not come to an agreement with Prime Minister Ehud Barak in the
next six or seven weeks, Barak may be replaced by a more
intransigent successor, or he could return to office with a secular
coalition that includes the hardline Likud Party.
</P>
<P>
   In either case, Arafat can hardly expect to receive better terms
for a negotiated agreement than those that are now on offer. He may
obtain more concessions from Barak in the next few weeks than he
received at Camp David, but he cannot count on pocketing any
concessions at all if he does not strike a peace deal by November.
</P>
<P>
   If Arafat wants anytime soon to declare a state that is
recognized internationally and financed by wealthy Western and Arab
backers, he will have to seize a fleeting political moment and be
decisive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
