<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-GORE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RATED R, FOR RISKY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ONLY THE ENTERTAINMENT moguls can save us now. They're the ones
marketing R-rated movies, racy music, and shoot-and-splatter video
games to youngsters. And they're the best ones to change these
marketing tactics.
</P>
<P>
   If self-regulation doesn't happen, Vice President Al Gore has
threatened to take government action. That could be a low-budget,
horror-movie disaster _ with clumsy government wonks trying to
balance free speech and child-friendly speech.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the entertainment industry could save itself and the
First Amendment a lot of trouble by cleaning up its own act.
</P>
<P>
   The issue shook the country last year after the tragic Columbine
High School shooting. President Clinton asked the Federal Trade
Commission and the Department of Justice to determine whether
movies, music, and video games with violent content were being
marketed to youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   Released on Monday, an FTC report concluded that the answer is
``plainly `yes.' ''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't news to frustrated parents who have been to G or PG
movies only to find that the previews are for R-rated flicks.
</P>
<P>
   Marketing plans can be disturbingly explicit. One music company
identified its audience as ``Alternative/urban, rock, pop, hardcore
_ 12-34.'' Sometimes labels meant to warn parents end up as signals
to youngsters that this is a must-have item.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike music and movies, the games industry does consider
marketing inappropriate products to children to be a violation of
its self-regulatory code. But violations are common.
</P>
<P>
   What can the entertainment industry do? Disney is adapting its
policies. Entertainment executives attended Senate hearings
Wednesday. The industry should take other steps, including:
</P>
<P>
   --Stop marketing adult products through underage venues.
</P>
<P>
   --Set up a marketing code with real sanctions for offenders.
</P>
<P>
   --Do regular audits of ad placements.
</P>
<P>
   --Carefully develop public service announcements that feature
children and teenagers talking about how they think entertainment
violence affects real life. These messages probably won't advise
anyone to ``just say no.'' But they could bring missing insights to
the public debate.
</P>
<P>
   --Improve advisory labels and educate parents about them.
</P>
<P>
   --Enforce rules about refusing to sell certain products to
underage buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Entertainers should have their free speech and spare children
too _ because everyone will lose if this becomes government work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-00 1834EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000913.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3093 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-SYDNEY-ARCHDEACON0914     09-13 1438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYDNEY- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 ARCHDEACON0914-COX &HT;    Sites in Sydney are worth seeing, as are the people
 &HT;    By Tom Archdeacon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ My first morning on the other side of the world, I left
my small room in the sprawling Olympic Media Village _ which
previously was a mental hospital, an appropriate place for the
press, some say _ and immediately was greeted by raucous chatter
coming from the fronds of the nearby palm trees.
</P>
<P>
   King parrots, which fly around here in the wild, were
everywhere. So were a few sulphur crested cockatoos and a flock of
lorikeets.
</P>
<P>
   Coming back to my room in the moonlight, I heard a
thump...thump...thump on the other side of the fence flanking the
walkway. Studying the figures munching the underbrush in the eerie
glow, I realized several kangaroos _ including a mother with a joey
_ were having their late-night snacks.
</P>
<P>
   For all the exotica that bookended my first day in Sydney _
where the 2000 Olympic Games open Friday night _nothing quite
matched the spectacle that came in between. Long ago, Rudyard
Kipling called this place ``the city of pictures'' and now _ like
then _ the best portrait comes at the Sydney Harbour.
</P>
<P>
   Riding the monorail to the waterfront, you reach Circular Quay,
a series of piers from which cumbersome ferries, hydrofoils, water
taxis, racing yachts, luxury liners and myriad vessels continually
pull in and out so that the watery expanse becomes an ever-changing
tableau of sights and sounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people who come through here say this is the best
harbor in the world,'' said Neva Williams, who pilots ferries
across the harbor. ``I never seen the other ports of the world, but
I can't imagine something better than this. What could you not like
about this?''
</P>
<P>
   It would be hard to imagine, unless maybe you were one of the
Olympic triathletes who will paddle through these waters this
weekend. After all, in the past two months, there have been at
least nine incidents involving sharks in and around Sydney Harbor.
Off the harbor beach of Athol, a 61-year-old swimmer had his leg
chomped on and needed stitches. On the Parramatta River that
channels into the harbor, a boat load of high school rowers was
attacked by sharks. And at a nearby ocean beach, two boys were
knocked from their Boogie Board by a bulldozing shark.
</P>
<P>
   Granted none of this is quite as dramatic as the incident in
Queensland last month when a human head _ thought to belong to a
local fisherman who had fallen from a trawler _ was found in the
belly of a 97-pound flowery cod caught off the Great Barrier Reef.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Martin, head of the dive team that will accompany the
triathletes, scoffed at all that shark and cod talk. He said he and
his divers will be wearing something called Shark Pods strapped to
their dive tanks and ankles. He said the devices will emit
electrical fields that repel sharks within a seven-meter radius.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's a little nerve wracking if you think about it,''
American triathlete Hunter Kemper said. ``But how many times do you
hear of a guy getting eaten by a sharks. It doesn't happen, does
it?
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I'm not a big fan of the ocean and I really
don't like sharks. That's why I don't wear clear goggles. Out of
sight, out of mind. I don't want to see what's beneath me.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither will anyone else. They'll be too busy looking up at the
two masterpieces that put a pair of exclamation points on this
harbor. On one headland jutting out into the water is the Sydney
Opera House, whose glorious white-tiled arcs and vaulted shells
spread like sails against the blue skies and glimmering blue
waters. Across the water is the Sydney Harbor Bridge, the world's
largest steel-arched bridge, a towering monstrosity that is longer
than five football fields. For about $100 Australian _ after being
fitted with a special moon-walk type suit, being instructed for an
hour and harnessed to a safety line _ you can scale it for an
unparalleled view of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Connecting the bridge and the opera house is the Writers' Walk
that honors authors linked one way or another to Sydney. As Robert
Louis Stevenson put it: ``There is material for dozens of
buccaneering stories to be picked up in the hotels of Circular
Quay.''
</P>
<P>
   Hotels, in Aussie speak, are pubs and they are everywhere along
the waterfront, especially the area called The Rocks _ the oldest
area in the city.
</P>
<P>
   It was here - at a 150-year-old hole in the wall called the Hero
of Waterloo - that I stumbled upon a colorful character named Dick.
He wore a beat-up bush hat with sunglasses propped atop it, had a
long, flowing ZZ Top beard and a schooner of ale in one fist.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bar right here is where the (press) gangs used to whack
unsuspecting landlubbers like yourself on the head,'' he said.
``They'd push them down a trapdoor out back and next thing they
knew, they were out to sea. There's a lot of history right here on
these streets.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the area where the first 11 ships from England _
carrying 736 convicts including 188 women _ disgorged that night in
1788.
</P>
<P>
   They made their presence known on that first night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's beyond my ability to give a description of the scene of
debauchery and riot that ensued that first night,'' the ship
surgeon noted in his diary.
</P>
<P>
   That's how Australia began.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to know something, mate,'' Dick said. ``Almost none
of those prisoners ever went back to England once their sentences
were done and their chains were taken off. And none of the children
from those convicts went back to the land of their parents' either.
Once you spend some time here, you don't want to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the case with him. He showed up here from Melbourne
several years ago, got a job doing repair work beneath the bridge
and hasn't left since.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should I? I got it all here,'' he said. ``I live down the
street and I come in here every night with my mates.''
</P>
<P>
   He touched on a concept that differentiates this city from most
of its American counterparts. Sydney is a high-tech place, where
most everyone _ except Dick _ seems to be chatting on a cell phone.
A lot of the people seem especially Internet savvy, too, while in
America, technology seems to distance people from each other _
keeping them at home and conversing by computer. People here like
rubbing shoulders with their friends. They fill the beaches, the
sidewalks and especially the pubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about being a mate, `` Dick said. ``That's what this
country's built on. Convicts made it through by having a mate to
count on. It's the same for people in the bush. You survive if you
got a mate to count on. That's why, for generations, we've called
each other mate. These days it's gone from work to fun, too. ``
</P>
<P>
   With that openness comes more tolerance in some areas. Nudity is
less of an issue with 60-some topless beaches, a few totally nude
and several of Australia's Olympians posing sans clothes for
everything from calendars to a coffee table book.
</P>
<P>
   As Williams said when she saw one of the Matildas _ the
Australian women's soccer team that posed nude for a calendar last
year: ``Goodonya'' - an Aussie term that signals approval.
</P>
<P>
   Prostitution is legal, though the other night four hookers and
their madame showed up at the media village and caused a real stink
when they passed through the security checkpoints _because they
were credentialed _ and worked the bar several hours before they
were kicked out.
</P>
<P>
   Gambling is legal too and every pub has slot machines and there
are 20 times as many pokies (poker machines) here as in America.
</P>
<P>
   That explained Australian water polo player Debbie Watson's
openness: ``You should be allowed to bet. If I could get the right
odds, I'd put a fiver on our water polo team for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with gambling, sport is like religion here with Australian
rules football, rugby, cricket and, Olympic swimming, too, all
drawing backers as obsessed as those Dawg Pounders in the Cleveland
Browns years of a decade past.
</P>
<P>
   As I readied to leave the Waterloo _ by the front door, not the
trap _ Dick told me to take out my camera, so we could get a
picture together. With that, he turned away, swept his beard up
over his face, tucked it into his hat, then turned around and fixed
his hair-covered face with sunglasses and a cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   ``What'd YOU? think of that?'' he howled to the delight of
others nearby.
</P>
<P>
   As Kipling's claim came to life right before my eyes, I could
only think of one thing to say:
</P>
<P>
   ``Goodonya, mate.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
