u i BC-MIDEAST-PALESTINIANS-     09-13 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-PALESTINIANS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST ANOTHER DAY IN GAZA INSTEAD OF A MOMENT IN HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ On the day that Palestinians had hoped to declare
their state, some feuded among themselves instead, blocking
intersections, burning tires and hurling stones at cars in the Gaza
Strip.
</P>
<P>
   But the mini-uprising, reminiscent of those against Israel, had
nothing to do with disappointment that this date, meant to be so
significant, was to come and go without either peace or a state.
Gazans are used to disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the row grew out of a power struggle among members of
the Fatah organization of the Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
Many Fatah loyalists now fill the ranks of Arafat's security
forces, and they tend to be more loyal to their commander than to
Fatah itself. This has caused tensions, and the latest one began as
a petty dispute.
</P>
<P>
   The Gazan Accountants Association held elections last week, and
Fatah emerged victorious. Fatah members gathered in the streets of
Gaza City, shooting their weapons to celebrate. The police, who are
also Fatah, were called. They arrested several of the celebrating
accountants, and several others said that they had been roughed up.
</P>
<P>
   After that incident, both sides claimed the other had kidnapped
some of its men. The rancor grew into Wednesday's rioting, which
sent plumes of black smoke into the air and rocks flying at cars
with the red license plates of the Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
   In its account of the event, Fatah blamed everything on Moussa
Arafat, the head of police intelligence, who many think is a
divisive force. A leaflet warned him ``not to sink our society with
his cheap internal battles,'' saying he would be ``the address of
our next battle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We ask President Arafat,'' the leaflet said, ``to remove this
cancer from our national body so we will be able to build our
independent state with its capital in Jerusalem.''
</P>
<P>
   Moussa Arafat could not be reached for comment. Other police and
security officers noted that the forces acted with restraint
Wednesday, letting the scene play itself out and not using their
weapons to disperse the rioters.
</P>
<P>
   The episode distressed many Palestinians, who said they would
have understood demonstrations against Israel or over the decision
to delay statehood. ``But who the heck needs internal conflict on
this date in particular?'' one Gazan journalist asked.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian Central Council voted last weekend to defer
making a declaration of statehood Wednesday in order to give the
peace effort another couple of months. Sept. 13 was chosen as the
deadline because it was the date set by the most recent interim
peace agreement for accomplishing a final peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
   That deadline was also broken. But talks, which are deadlocked
over the seemingly intractable issue of Jerusalem's status, are to
begin again on Thursday in Washington, where senior Israeli and
Palestinian negotiators will meet with American mediators,
according to Israeli television. Discussion on the issues are
expected to pick up where they left off at Camp David in July,
although both sides fear that there has been backsliding from the
concessions that were on the table then.
</P>
<P>
   Anxious to give the peace effort more time, Prime Minister Ehud
Barak, whose government is in shambles, is working this week to
build a minority center-left coalition of 50 members of parliament.
He is counting on the 10 Israeli Arab members of parliament to
support his peace moves from outside the coalition.
</P>
<P>
   But tensions are running high after a police crackdown on the
Islamic Movement party and a move to shut down a quarry in Nazareth
that employs many Arabs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
