<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With ONLINE-MUSIC.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARCHING TO A NEW TUNE
</P>
<P>
   Recent MP3.com Inc. products and services that aren't on trial
</P>
<P>
   Retail Music
</P>
<P>
   Supplies digital music and advertising over the Internet to
retailers and others for use in stores and offices. MP3.com claims
that by the end of the month it will have 100 customers of the new
Muzak-style service.
</P>
<P>
   Subscription Music
</P>
<P>
   New children's channel lets computer users hear nonstop songs
like ``Frere Jacques'' and ``B-I-N-G-O'' for $4.99 a month or less.
Follows rollout of $9.99-a-month classical music channel earlier
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Radio Stations
</P>
<P>
   Supplies formatted digital music to a growing number of radio
stations across the country. Currently has nearly 200 customers,
including stations in major markets like Atlanta, Dallas, San
Antonio and Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Automobiles
</P>
<P>
   With mobile phone company Qualcomm Inc., company recently began
testing technology that could eventually allow delivery of
customized music into cars and cellular phones.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
