<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3098 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-ONLINE-MUSIC14-COX     09-13 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-MUSIC14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MP3.COM, BESET BY LAWSUITS, FINDING NEW WAYS TO DO BUSINESS
 &HT;    With ONLINE-DATA.
 &HT;    By BOB KEEFE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ While battling to stay alive at the center of the
controversy over copyrights, online music pioneer MP3.com Inc. has
been quietly redirecting its focus to less controversial _ and
potentially more profitable _ ways of doing business.
</P>
<P>
   So far, MP3.com isn't making much money off the new products,
which range from a Muzak-like service for retailers to a children's
channel where computer users can listen nonstop to songs like
``B-I-N-G-O'' for a monthly fee.
</P>
<P>
   But they're an indication of where the company _ and the online
music industry in general _ may be headed after devastating
lawsuits by big recording companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are the innovators,'' said Credit Suisse First
Boston Corp. analyst Heath Terry said of MP3.com. ``These guys come
out with a new idea, and three months later some Internet company
starts something exactly like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it was MP3.com's pioneering of a service that lets
music listeners store _ and in some cases, exchange _ copyrighted
music on the Internet that got the company in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a federal judge in New York ruled that San
Diego-based MP3.com willfully infringed on the copyrights of
Universal Music Group, setting the stage for what could amount to
$118 million or more in damages. The ruling came a month before a
federal appeals court is due to decide the fate of Napster Inc.,
which also was found guilty of infringing on recording companies'
copyrights.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, MP3.com founder and Chairman Michael Robertson
said he is still hoping to negotiate a settlement with Universal
before final damages are calculated in November. And, he said, the
company plans to reintroduce its bread-and-butter MyMP3.com service
within the next few weeks _ albeit this time with licensing
agreements from four other major recording companies in hand.
</P>
<P>
   But in the meantime, MP3.com also is turning its attention
toward new products that could help bring in badly needed revenues
should MP3.com be forced to pay a big damage settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've tried to do is define our legal team and put them
in a separate cage and said hey, we're going to move ahead,''
Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it's distracting. But even though in the last six months
we've been mired in all this legal action, we've been rolling out
new products, new technology _ and that's something I'm proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   What remains to be seen, of course, is whether MP3.com can
generate any profits from the new ventures. Robertson said he has
no set goals for the new businesses, and doesn't know when they
might be profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the company has more than $300 million in cash, like
many Internet companies it's still struggling to turn a profit.
</P>
<P>
   For the first six months of this year, the company took in $38
million in revenues, but lost $195 million _ in part because it put
aside $150 million to settle its copyright suits. Its stock price
is down about 80 percent from a year ago, closing Wednesday at
$5.38.
</P>
<P>
   Some industry watchers say the initiatives are just another sign
of the company struggling to find direction and survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the legal prospective, I think this is just (Robertson)
casting around for business model number three or four or whatever
number this is,'' said Jim Penhune, an analyst with the Yankee
Group research firm in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, MP3.com gets almost all its revenues from selling
advertising on its Web site. The new services would bring in
outside revenues from more predictable sources.
</P>
<P>
   One of the new products MP3.com is banking on is a service that
allows retailers and others to get customized music piped into
their stores and offices over the Internet. By the end of the
month, Robertson said the company will have 100 customers paying
anywhere from $30 to hundreds of dollars a month for the service.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this you can have not just different flavors of music but
different flavors of (customized) advertising, depending on where
you are and what you sell,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   California-based Rubio Restaurants Inc. recently inked a deal to
use the MP3.com service in its 126 Mexican-style restaurants in
five states. Vice President Richard Rubio said the service is 40
percent cheaper than its current music provider, Muzak, and lets
the restaurant chain custom-pick its music.
</P>
<P>
   Another retailer, the PETCO pet supply chain, is expected to
complete an agreement in a few weeks to put MP3.com music in its
500 stores nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com also is pushing hard to expand its growing radio
service, which sells pre-formatted music used typically to fill
space in odd hours by nearly 200 radio stations, including
major-market stations like Atlanta's WBTS-95.5 and 99.5 Kiss FM in
San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   It also is experimenting with new products, including a service
it recently began testing with Qualcomm Inc. that would let users
listen to customized digital music in their cars and on their cell
phones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology marches forward,'' Robertson said. ``And as we're a
technology company, we must seize the opportunities as they come
along.''
</P>
<P>
   At the center of all its initiatives is what MP3.com claims to
be the biggest collection of digital music on the Internet, with
more 562,000 songs from more than 87,000 artists that it legally
owns the rights to use.
</P>
<P>
   With the new services, MP3.com is simply finding new _ and less
controversial _ ways to use that music.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I've already built this big library, I can really maximize
that same investment through subscription channels, the retail
model, whatever I want,'' Robertson explained.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com's new children's channel, for instance, contains songs
that the company has already paid to use. The channel _ akin to
digital music channels offered by digital cable companies _ costs
subscribers $4.99 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent licensing agreements, much of MP3.com's music
still is by little-known artists.
</P>
<P>
   But that typically doesn't matter with preschool kids and
restaurant patrons, or listeners who tune in to radio stations in
the middle of the night to hear new artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our goals is to give an authentic flavor to our
customers,'' said Rubio, the restaurateur. ``But I could listen to
a number of mariachi songs and I couldn't tell you who the artist
was.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Keefe's e-mail address is bkeefe(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
