<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INKTOMI-FASTFORWARD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INKTOMI TO ACQUIRE FASTFORWARD NETWORKS IN $1.3 BILLION DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Inktomi Corp., which specializes in Internet
infrastructure, said Wednesday that it had agreed to acquire
FastForward Networks Inc. in a stock swap valued at about $1.3
billion. FastForward, based in San Francisco, has developed
software technology for the distribution and management of live
broadcasting over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Inktomi, which is based in Forest City, Calif., fell
$2.25, to $108.75 in Nasdaq trading.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the acquisition was a logical one, which fit
Inktomi's strategy of expanding the capabilities of its network
services business.
</P>
<P>
   Inktomi's network service products are aimed at improving Web
performance through the more efficient distribution of content, and
are typically bought by large Internet service providers like
Digital Island and Exodus Communications. Some major Web sites also
use Inktomi's network services to improve speed and reliability.
</P>
<P>
   The core product of Inktomi's network services business is
Traffic Server, a software application that runs on servers
deployed around the Internet, monitoring network traffic and
storing frequently requested objects closer to the user. Traffic
Server is a Web cache, performing a similar function to the onboard
memory added to microprocessors.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Brosseau, an analyst with SG Cowen, said the deal was
similar to Inktomi's acquisition last year of Webspective, a
company with a technology for managing the delivery of content over
networks. Adding this capability to Traffic Server, ``added the
intelligence to put the content into the caches in an intelligent
way and keep it up to date,'' he said. FastForward ``does the same
thing along a different direction, expanding the kinds of media
they're able to support.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet infrastructure companies like Inktomi have to broaden
their offerings to match the demand for rich media delivered over
the Web. As users come to expect graphics, animation, audio and
video, the need for higher performance increases exponentially.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that live broadcast and live streaming are going to
be a real factor on the Internet, and it's going to be very soon,''
David Peterschmidt, Inktomi's president and chief executive, said
in a telephone interview. ``These guys are just a real jump ahead
of anything on the market today.''
</P>
<P>
   Inktomi made a minority investment in FastForward last year,
along with America Online and Sun Microsystems. ``The more we
talked with them, the more I felt that this was a company that
reminded me of Inktomi two years ago,'' Peterschmidt said. ``It's
deep in scientists and engineers.''
</P>
<P>
   FastForward's technology has already been deployed by Digital
Island and Real Networks Inc., and Peterschmidt said the
acquisition would add $30 million to $40 million to Inktomi's
revenues in fiscal 2001, which begins Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   FastForward's staff will remain in San Francisco, where they
will be joined by other members of Inktomi's live media group, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   FastForward Networks will operate under the Inktomi name as the
media division withAbhay Parekh, FastForward's co-founder,
president and chief executive, as general manager. All employees of
FastForward Networks will join Inktomi.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
