<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-SHOOTING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORTER WHO COVERED MOTORCYLE GANG SHOT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds. Hells Angels is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ A Quebec journalist known for aggressive coverage of
the Hells Angels and their bloody campaign for control of the
Canadian drug trade was shot and wounded Wednesday outside the
offices of the newspaper Journal de Montreal, where he worked.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal police described the shooting as an ``assassination
attempt,'' but stressed that it remains unclear if 55-year-old
Michel Auger was the victim of one of the biker hit squads that in
recent years have turned Quebec into a free fire zone, with many
killed in shootings and car bombings.
</P>
<P>
   The ambush of Auger came only a day after Quebec's public
security minister made a highly unusual appeal to the Canadian
government to suspend certain constitutionally guaranteed civil
liberties to give police in the province greater leeway in fighting
the Hells Angels and their biker arch-rivals, the Montreal-based
Rock Machine.
</P>
<P>
   The attack also came a day after the Journal de Montreal
published Augur's two-page investigative piece probing the battle
between Quebec's biker gangs and the Mafia. Among other things, the
story identified prominent warlords living anonymously in some of
the city's most exclusive neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The journalist was shot in the back and shoulder by assailants
in the parking lot of Journal de Montreal, largest-circulation
newspaper in the largely French-speaking province. He was able to
call 911 on his cellphone to summon medical assistance after the
late morning attack. The journalist remained in stable condition
under heavy police guard Wednesday night at Montreal General
Hospital
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper has regularly assigned bodyguards to Auger in the
past, but he reportedly drove to work unaccompanied Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Although Auger had received numerous death threats during more
than two decades of covering organized crime, the targeting of
Canadian journalists by gangsters is extremely rare
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an outrage,'' said Journal editor-in-chief Paule
Beaugrand-Champagne. ``An attack against a journalist is an attack
against the free flow of information. And that's an attack against
the foundations of democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   A burning car was discovered a few blocks from the newspaper
offices after the shooting. Torching getaway vehicles in order to
destroy evidence is a trademark of Quebec biker gangs, but police
refused to speculate beyond saying the car was probably used by
Auger's assailants.
</P>
<P>
   Auger has been the top crime columnist at the tabloid newspaper
for the past 17 years, respected by both police and other
journalists for his in-depth reports on organized crime, especially
the biker gangs battling for control of drug trafficking,
smuggling, prostitution, auto theft, and other rackets worth tens
of millions of dollars in Quebec alone.
</P>
<P>
   The past decade has seen the Hells Angels emerge as a dominant
organized crime presence across Canada, with chapters in every
province except Ontario and tiny Prince Edward Island. In Quebec,
the gang known simply as ``les Hells'' has been locked since the
mid-1990s in a murderous war of attrition with the Rock Machine, an
outfit that serves as a sort of front line force for the Mafia and
other crime groups that have united against the Hells Angels.
</P>
<P>
   The Quebec war is the bloodiest in the 52-year history of the
world's most infamous biker bunch. More than 100 people _ mostly
gang members, but also civilians cut down in the crossfire _ have
been killed by bomb blasts, wild street shootouts, and midnight
executions across La Belle Province. Scores more have been maimed
or seriously wounded.
</P>
<P>
   So desperate has the situation become that Quebec Public
Security Minister Serge Menard on Tuesday asked the federal
government to suspend constitutional freedoms to allow the province
more leeway in fighting the Hells Angels. Specifically, Quebec
wants authority to outlaw membership in biker gangs, an
extraordinary move that Menard himself acknowledged goes against
liberties guaranteed by Canada's Charter of Rights and Freedoms,
equivalent to the US Bill of Rights.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government is thought to be reluctant to act on
Quebec's appeal, but if biker gangs prove to be behind the shooting
of Auger, heavy pressure could mount on Ottawa to invoke the
country's seldom-used ``notwithstanding'' clause and suspend
guarantees of freedom of association and other rights.
</P>
<P>
   Auger's hard-hitting reports are known to have aroused the wrath
of Maurice ``Mom'' Boucher, widely seen as the most powerful Hells
Angel honcho in Quebec. But the reporter also angered the Rock
Machine and Montreal's Mafia bosses with exposes of shifting
alliances in the crime world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michel's job involved making enemies of some very bad men,''
said a police investigator with a Canadian anti-biker unit,
speaking on condition of anonymity. ``He angered lots of dangerous
people, not just the Hells.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
