<P>
   WHALING _ WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration moved
Wednesday to punish Japan for overly aggressive whaling, beginning
a process that could lead to economic sanctions. (Deans, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Atlanta, International, Others
</P>
<P>
   FALUN-GONG _ ATLANTA _ An Atlanta engineer who traveled to China
to pay last respects to a dying relative has run afoul of the law
for carrying literature tied to the Falun Gong movement. Members of
Atlanta's Falun Gong community fear she will face severe penalties,
in light of the Chinese government's recent pledge to intensify its
crackdown on the movement's adherents. (Ahmed, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-NIKITIN _ MOSCOW _ Russia's Supreme Court laid to rest
the espionage case against anti-nuclear activist Alexander Nikitin,
rejecting Wednesday a bid by prosecutors to overturn his acquittal.
Nikitin, a retired submarine captain, has fought the treason
charges for almost five years, after he published a report
detailing unsafe conditions of Russia's nuclear fleet. Hailing the
verdict as ``just,'' Nikitin said the code of secrecy surrounding
the military still exists and still poses a danger to Russians and
the world. (Coker, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location Atlanta, category International, subcategory Other
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN-CARDENAS _ CARDENAS, Cuba _ There are no lawyers running
to the microphones, no angry protestors holding vigil, no banners
or posters or hordes of camera-wielding journalists. By all
accounts, Elian Gonzalez and his family like it that way. Just two
months ago, the young shipwreck survivor was perhaps the most
famous six-year-old in the world. Caught in the center of a bitter
custody fight between his Miami relatives and his Cuban family,
Elian became a symbol of the decades-old conflict between communist
Cuba and its capitalist neighbor to the north. Now he is just
another student at Marcelo Salado primary school, one of hundreds
dressed in identical red, white and blue school uniforms, running
and shouting in the school's spacious courtyard between classes.
(Williams, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location Atlanta, category International, subcategory Other
</P>
<P>
   POLAND-ELECTION _ Twenty years ago, Solidarity, the union that
would play a giant role in bringing down communism, was born. A
decade ago, Solidarity's leader, Lech Walesa, became his country's
first popularly elected president. Now, the Poles are again voting
for president but Walesa, who is again a candidate, is trailing
badly in a country that has gone through two decades of rapid
change. A look at Poland as the election approaches, through the
eyes of Hubert Tworzecki, an Emory University professor regarded as
an expert on his country. (Graham, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
