<P>
   OLYMPICS
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SCENE _ SYDNEY _ On the eve of the 2000 Games, we compare
Sydney's Olympic strategy with Atlanta '96. Unlike Atlanta's highly
centralized zone of activity downtown, Sydney's game plan involves
separating most of the athletic events. That essential difference,
designed to take advantage of the natural ebb and flow of this
harbor town, is paramount as Sydney takes center stage Friday,
hoping to avoid some of Atlanta's embarrassing mistakes. There are
similarities, as well, including transportation problems that need
to get fixed for these spread-out Games to work right.
(Unger/Brock, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30. WITH GRAPHIC AND
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-ARCH _ SYDNEY _ Arch from Down Under: My first morning on
the other side of the world, I left my small room in the sprawling
Olympic Media Village _ which
</P>
<P>
   previously was a mental hospital, an appropriate place for the
press, some
</P>
<P>
   say _ and immediately was greeted by raucous chatter coming from
the fronds
</P>
<P>
   of the nearby palm trees. King parrots, which fly around here in
the wild, were everywhere. So were a few sulphur crested cockatoos
and a flock of lorikeets. Coming back to my room in the moonlight,
I heard a thump...thump...thump on the other side of the fence
flanking the walkway. Studying the figures munching the underbrush
in the eerie glow, I realized several kangaroos _ including a
mother with a joey _ were having their late-night snacks. For all
the exotica that bookended my first day in Sydney _ where the 2000
Olympic Games open Friday night _nothing quite matched the
spectacle that came in between. (Archdeacon, Dayton Daily News) 30
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-BRANDI _ SYDNEY _ Beyond the sports bra. Brandi Chastain was
probably one of the least likely members of the World Cup soccer
team to gain fame and fortune. But her excellent play in the World
Cup _ and her attention-grabbing antics after the winning goal _
have propelled her into the spotlight, both on the field and off.
We look at what it all has meant to her heading into the Olympics.
(Parker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-ADIDAS-WEBBER _ SYDNEY _ Spot piece on Atlantan Antoine
Webber, who is competing in Adidas challenge on Wednesday. (Brock,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-WALKER _ When you talk about the Olympics, you have to talk
about the pressure. Unless you're Neil Walker. ``It's going to be
really fun,'' Walker said. If there's any athlete who's just happy
to be in Australia, it's Walker, a lanky Austin resident of Austin,
Texas and University of Texas swimmer. Four years ago he gained a
small measure of fame by missing the Olympics by the smallest of
margins, one-hundredth of a second as he was touched out for sixth
place in the 100 meter freestyle at the U.S. swim trials. In that
event, six swimmers can go to the Olympics for the 4X100 meter
freestyle relay team. This time around Walker could be anchoring
that race Saturday as well as later having a shot at medals in
another relay and two individual events. And that's after having a
couple of off swims and maybe one bad choice at the U.S. trials.
(Maher, Austin American-Statesman). 23.
</P>
