<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3110 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-BOOK-FRAILTY0914-COX     09-13 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-FRAILTY0914-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Male-female equality: true or a `myth'?
 &HT;    By Anne Morris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The speed of track star Marion Jones, the
strength of Olympic weight-lifter Cheryl Haworth and the power of
tennis champions Serena and Venus Williams all suggest that
Collette Dowling could be right _ women might one day become the
physical equals of men.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a long way to go, and fitness experts are not
readily swayed by her arguments.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Frailty Myth,'' Dowling asserts _ and few would contest
_ that women have long been held back by a culture that emphasizes
femininity and fertility over physical ability. She believes that
given the same athletic skill training and practice boys receive,
girls will approach equality. (In other words, they'll be able to
throw like a boy.)
</P>
<P>
   Dowling suggests the deficiencies go way beyond what was
rectified in Title IX, which established equity between genders in
athletic programs receiving federal aid. This feminist author, who
proclaimed in ``The Cinderella Complex'' (1989) that women have an
unconscious tendency to make themselves dependent on men, suggests
in her new book that it was men who for so long helped keep the
``weaker sex'' weaker. ``Men were certain that if women weren't
controlled, the very species was at risk,'' Dowling writes, and
``The dastardly effect of athletics on women's abilities to be
mothers . . . was continually proclaimed.''
</P>
<P>
   She says vestiges of the frailty myth persisted ``even after
women began outdoing men in endurance marathons in the 1990s and
plunging victoriously into the contact sports _ ice hockey,
football, rugby _ for so long considered ineffably `male.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Whether women are now on their way to equality is something to
ponder as you watch the elite women athletes compete in Sydney over
the next two weeks. They're running and swimming faster and, yes,
that's a 17-year-old girl hoisting more than 300 pounds over her
head in the first Olympic women's weight-lifting competition.
</P>
<P>
   Pre-Title IX and barely beyond frail ourselves, we turned to Jan
Todd, a University of Texas kinesiology and health education
professor once dubbed ``the strongest woman in the world,'' to
evaluate ``The Frailty Myth.'' A champion power lifter in the 1970s
and '80s, Todd at 48 is still about as far from frail as you can
get. She broke more than 60 records and appeared in the Guinness
Book of Records for 12 consecutive years before she retired to
teach and write books on fitness.
</P>
<P>
   The office in the basement of Anna Hiss Gym that she shares with
her husband, Terry, is filled with trophies and a library of
weight-lifting history. This former English major who reads the New
Yorker as avidly as she does fitness journals could hardly be more
sympathetic to Dowling's basic message. (It's the details she finds
faulty.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of what she's saying is dead-on,'' Todd said.
``For a long time most women were denied a full physical life.''
</P>
<P>
   She recalled when she started to train in the '70s how hard it
was to find a gym that had free weights she was allowed to use.
``Even 10 years ago, women weren't really welcome. And in the '70s,
gyms would have a ladies' side _ no weights, just machines.''
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean men were always the enemy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the support I had was from men,'' Todd said. ``It's
the women in my circle who were more concerned that what I was
doing was inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Todd balks at many of Dowling's assertions _ including the
biggest one. Asked outright if women will soon achieve physical
equality with men, Todd hesitated. ``Well (sigh, followed by long
pause), I have to admit that I think . . . oh, boy! _ as a feminist
I want to say yes. But as somebody in kinesiology and who's been
around lifting as long as I have, I don't think so.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the 21st century, we'll see records much closer,
but I don't think we'll see women surpassing men in terms of
absolutes,'' Todd said. ``Not in weight-lifting. Possibly in
distance events _ for example, long-distance swimmers. Possibly in
cycling. There are some phenomenal performances by women (in
lifting), but they're nowhere close.''
</P>
<P>
   (When John McEnroe gave commentary on the U.S. Open recently, he
remarked on the Williams' strength and muscularity but said even he
could come back from retirement and beat them. Last week there were
suggestions that Serena Williams might give him a chance to try.)
</P>
<P>
   Todd particularly faults ``The Frailty Myth'' for its cursory
treatment of strength records. ``She has a section in the book
called `Men's Fear of Women's Strength.' Well, why doesn't she talk
about strength? Instead she talks about body building, which is an
aesthetic. I was very surprised by what short shrift she gave to a
real physical strength argument.''
</P>
<P>
   What will hold women back in weight-lifting? Body structure and
perhaps hormonal differences, Todd said, though the muscle is the
same. ``No matter what we want to say, women's physiology is still
somewhat different _ and men have the structural advantage in upper
body strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, there's been lots of progress. Todd agrees Dowling is
onto something when she celebrates the new generation of women and
men's acceptance of their strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an episode of `The Sopranos' on TV this year where
all these mob guys were out supporting their daughters in soccer.
It was a great image, these icons of masculinity supporting their
daughters. I thought that was pretty wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
