<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-MIGRATION _ HAVANA _ The ever-smoldering war of words
between Cuba and the U.S. over immigration policies is flaring up
again after the shark-eaten bodies of two Cuban men were found off
the Florida Keys in August. Cuban officials charge that the U.S.
Cuban Adjustment Act encourages Cubans to risk the perilous voyage
across the Florida Straits by granting automatic asylum to any
Cuban who sets foot on U.S. soil. U.S. officials, meanwhile, say
the Cuban government has been blocking Cubans with proper visas
from emigrating. We profile the controversy, hopefully by finding
Cubans willing to talk about their problems in trying to obtain
visas. NOTE: This could prove difficult, and many interview
subjects are likely not going to agree to be named, for obvious
reasons. (Williams, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location, Atlanta; Category, International; Subcategory,
Other.
</P>
<P>
   Expected to move Thursday on the NYT Wire.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-JOURNAL _ MOSCOW _ How long does a superpower remain a
superpower? Ten years ago, the Soviet Union was dissolved, but many
Russians continue to believe their country is a great nation.
Adults proudly extend as proof Russia's high education levels,
industrial base, art and culture, and of course, their nuclear
arsenal. But as the remnants of this Soviet past rust and fade
away, what does the next generation of Russians, who grew up after
the end of the Cold War, believe? We spend a day in one of Moscow's
public schools to find out. Developing. (Coker, Cox News Service).
WITH PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   Expected to move Thursday on the NYT Wire in both International
and Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   NURSING-LAWSUITS _ WASHINGTON _ Where the government has been
lax, lawyers are becoming the de facto enforcers of nursing home
standards. Residents and their families are increasingingly filing
lawsuits and winning big awards for shoddy treatment in nursing
homes. (Malone, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Moving Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Atlanta, National, Social Issues
</P>
<P>
   TECH-ELECTION _ WASHINGTON _ Where Bush and Gore stand on tech
issues, and how the tech community is dividing in support. (Glass,
Cox News Service). With chart.
</P>
<P>
   Moving Thursday in (w) Washington, (p) politics and (f)
financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Atlanta, National, Politics
</P>
<P>
   TANGIER-ISLAND _ TANGIER ISLAND, Va. _ This tiny settlement of
fishermen in the Chesapeake Bay, settled in 1778 by English people
whose speech patterns still echo in their descendants, is fighting
a losing battle for existence against dwindling crab populations.
But the 650 permanent residents are fighting back by emphasizing
tourism, including golf-cart explorations of Tangier's quaint and
carless environs. (Dart, Cox News Service) WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   Moved Monday in (l) lifestyle and (t) travel categories.
</P>
<P>
   DEATHROW-GOBSON _ Death row inmate Exzavious Gibson is best
known for being the only capital defendant in the modern history of
the death penalty to go through a habeas corpus appeal without the
aid of an attorney. The Georgia Supremes ruled last year that was
OK, making Georgia the only state in the nation not to require
lawyers at this stage of their appeals. Had the Georgia Supremes
sent the case back for a hearing, with a lawyer, the judge would
have learned new revelations that, when he was convicted and
sentenced to die, Gibson was represented by a lawyer who was
working as an assistant state attorney general -- a clear conflict
of interest. And this lawyer billed just 33 hours of work for the
case -- including 6 hrs for travel. Now, a federal judge in Augusta
has taken extraordinary steps to bypass the Georgia Supremes,
demanding new hearings. Saying he'd never seen anything like it in
his 20 years on the bench, federal judge Dudley Bowen even called
the state court judge to ask him to consider hearing the case.
(Rankin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DOMESTIC-VIOLENCE _ Many immigrants, particularly women, are
more susceptible to domestic violence and less likely to report
abuse than native born Americans. Many don't speak English and are
dependent on a spouse who works; they don't know a shelter exists
and, even if they do, can't speak enough English to steer
themselves to one. There are cultural barriers, too. Many South
Asian women who get divorced are considered ``discarded objects''
with little chance of re-marrying b/c divorce is such a cultural
taboo. (Bixler, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 9
p.m.
</P>
