<P>
   COXNET BOOKS 0916: SALINGER'S DAUGHTER -- Margaret Salinger,
daugher of noted author J.D. Salinger, has taken it upon herself to
reveal not just how rotten her childhood was _ even with that
single regret _ but also what complete fruitcakes her father and
mother were. (Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes a
3-column color photo of Margaret Salinger and a 6-pica color photo
of a book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: HORSES AND WOMEN -- There comes a time in almost every
girl's life when she falls in love with horses. This phenomenon,
this quality of nature, is easily observable, but Melissa Holbrook
Pierson more than observes it; she muses on it to deep and lyrical
effect in ``Dark Horses and Black Beauties,'' her new collection of
slender and delicate essays on horses and women. (Bernstein, N.Y.
Times News Service) Art includes a 6-pica color photo of a book
jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: AUTHOR PROFILE -- Author Sherri Szeman writes in a style
like none other, taking chances and challenging readers with
flowing prose that leaps over decades and events: Her books read
like our minds work. (Dempsey, Dayton Daily News) Art includes a
6-pica color photo of author.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW FORTUNE TELLERS -- In ``The Fortune Tellers,''
journalist Howard Kurtz offers an insider story about the
superheated world of the stock market in the late 1990s and the
traders, television analysts and journalists who made highly
visible careers in it. (Bernstein, N.Y. Times News Service) Art
includes a 6-pica color photo of book jacket.
</P>
