<SLUG> BC-DEPOT-OLYAD0914-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Games all heart in Home Depot ad
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ You'll see no machismo or NASCAR-style rumble in Home
Depot's commercial tribute to the Summer Games in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based retailer likes to show its sensitive side
during the Olympics. That soft spot seems to hit overdrive in Home
Depot's sponsorship ad, which debuts Friday night during Opening
Ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   Reminiscent of ABC's old ``the thrill of victory and the agony
of defeat'' sports theme, the commercial captures athletes in their
moments of glory and disappointment. First up is a teary-eyed
runner, then shots of a triumphant weightlifter, giddy basketball
players and young fans glued to the TV.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the drama is a slow, pining rendition of the
children's song, ``If You're Happy and You Know It,'' performed by
members of the Chicago Symphony Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at the Olympics as an opportunity to tie into the
emotions of the Games ... so we decided to focus on the athletes
and their families,'' said Dick Hammill, senior vice president of
marketing and communications.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot first sponsored the Olympics in 1992, when it
supported the 1994 U.S. Olympic team in Lillehammer, Norway.
</P>
<P>
   The home improvement giant won't say how much it's spending on
Olympics advertising, but NBC recently said it has sold a record
$900 million in commercial time for its telecasts of the Games.
That's roughly 30 percent higher than NBC's $680 million in ad
sales for the 1996 Olympic Games in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Recent reports pegged the average price this year of a 30-second
commercial in prime time at $615,000, up from $420,000 in Atlanta
four years ago. Home Depot is running 30-second and 60-second ads
throughout the Games, which end Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot also sponsors NASCAR auto racing.
</P>
<P>
   Other major Atlanta-based sponsors of the Olympics include
Coca-Cola and United Parcel Service. Both will air commercials
during the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot's Olympic role also includes putting about 50
athletes on its payroll. The retailer employs athletes and Olympic
hopefuls through job programs by the United States, Canada, Puerto
Rico and Chile.
</P>
<P>
   The athletes work an average of 20 hours a week, and Home Depot
pays them full-time wages and benefits so that they can train for
the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot has hired more than 200 athletes since 1992, Hammill
said. About half made Olympic teams, and 53 won medals, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
