<SLUG> BC-HOUSTON-SYMPHONY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRIAN CONDUCTOR HANS GRAF IS NEW HEAD OF HOUSTON SYMPHONY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CHARLES WARD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
HOUSTON _ The Houston Symphony has named Austrian conductor Hans
Graf as its new music director. Graf's five-year contract will
begin with the 2001-2002 season.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Graf succeeds Christoph Eschenbach, who left the post of music
director in May 1999 after 11 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Graf was the overwhelming choice of the symphony's 19-member
search committee and the favorite of musicians, said Rodney H.
Margolis, president of the Houston Symphony Society.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel honestly honored and happy,'' Graf said from Bordeaux,
France, where he conducted Wednesday. ``I hope to keep going with
the wonderful (artistic) momentum created by Eschenbach.''
</P>
<P>
   Graf emerged as the leading candidate during a two-week visit to
Houston in March.
</P>
<P>
   Because of schedule conflicts, however, he will not conduct the
Houston Symphony again until May 12-14, when he leads
Rachmaninoff's Symphony No. 3 and Brahms' Piano Concerto No. 2,
with Garrick Ohlsson as soloist.
</P>
<P>
   Though not yet widely known in the classical music world, Graf
appears to be on the verge of a major international career.
</P>
<P>
   He is music director at the Calgary Philharmonic in Alberta,
Canada, and the Orchestre National Bordeaux-Aquitaine in France. He
will end his tenure in Calgary at the end of the 2002-2003 season.
His contract in Bordeaux also expires then.
</P>
<P>
   This season he will lead the Calgary orchestra on a European
tour, and will make guest appearances with the Stockholm
Philharmonic, the Boston Symphony, the St. Paul Chamber Orchestra
and the orchestras in Baltimore, Pittsburgh and Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Graf will conduct at least five subscription series programs in
the 2001-2002 season, plus other concerts, including the
season-opening gala.
</P>
<P>
   In subsequent years, he will lead 10 subscription series
programs and devote up to 16 weeks each season to the orchestra.
That is a typical commitment for the music director of an orchestra
like Houston, which presents 18 classical series programs, each
played three times.
</P>
<P>
   Born in the town of Marchtrenk, outside of Linz, Graf studied
violin with his father and earned a diploma in piano from the music
conservatory in Graz, Austria.
</P>
<P>
   He attended master classes with such major conducting teachers
as Franco Ferrara and Sergiu Celibidache. In 1972-73, he studied at
the Leningrad Conservatory with Arvid Jansons, father of Mariss
Jansons, music director of the Pittsburgh Symphony.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in 1977, Graf worked at the Vienna State Opera for
seven years, first as a pianist and coach, then as conductor.
</P>
<P>
   His key break came in 1979 when he won the Karl Bohm
Competition. The prize included two concerts with the Vienna
Symphony Orchestra, which provided valuable exposure.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1979, I was already an old guy _ I was 30 years old,'' he
said with a laugh. ``I was a late-starter.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, the famous Russian composer Kyril Kondrashin died
before the premiere of a Vienna State Opera Ballet production of
Stravinsky's Petrouchka. Graf stepped in.Similarly, his Boston
Symphony debut in 1995 resulted from the illness of Sir Roger
Norrington.
</P>
<P>
   From 1984 to 1994, he served as music director of the Mozarteum
Orchestra in Salzburg.
</P>
<P>
   Graf made his United States debut in 1989 at the Buffalo
Philharmonic. He became music director in Calgary in 1995 and
Bordeaux in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   He said that his main goal for the Houston Symphony is to build
on Eschenbach's artistic legacy. He expects to adjust the
repertoire, probably performing fewer Mahler works and adding
others by French and Russian composers.
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
