u i BC-ITALY-ENGLISH-NYT &LR;      09-13 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-ENGLISH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALIANS CLAMOR FOR `COLUMBO,' AMONG OTHER SHOWS, TO IMPROVE THEIR
ENGLISH 
</HEADLINE>
  (Foreign Journal) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Jason Priestley, the slouching star of ``Beverly Hills
90210,'' is not best known for his mastery of proper English
diction. But in Italy his high-school angst has been put to use to
help Italians learn English. Computer users can freeze a frame on a
CD-ROM version of the show and pause his mumbled delivery. If that
doesn't help, students can click to a more precise, mid-Atlantic
voice-over.
</P>
<P>
   Installments of ``MovieTalk,'' CD-ROMs that convert popular
American television shows into interactive English lessons, are
being given away free by the newsmagazine L'Espresso. The marketing
strategy is intended to sell magazines by tapping into Italians'
thirst to improve their English.
</P>
<P>
   English has become the lingua franca of the world, but among
European countries Italy has one of the lowest rates of
proficiency. Only 28 percent of Italians speak any English,
according to a 1999 study by the European Commission, compared with
78 percent of the Dutch, 77 percent of Swedes and 41 percent of
Germans. Even the prickly French have a higher percentage of
English-speakers: 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Italians' longstanding insistence on having foreign movies and
television shows dubbed into Italian is an important reason, Furio
Colombo, a columnist, wrote in the daily newspaper La Repubblica.
He believes that the dubbing has lulled Italians into a false sense
of security. ``Unconsciously, Italians have this idea that Italian
is so universal a language that even Woody Allen speaks it
fluently,'' Colombo said.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few years, however, Italians have scrambled to catch
up, prompted by the Internet and a desire to compete in the global
economy. Italy has more than 1,000 language schools, and many
newspapers and magazines provide written English lessons and,
increasingly, interactive lessons online.
</P>
<P>
   MovieTalk, a system designed by the American software company,
Softrade International, has already been marketed in Germany and
Japan using episodes of ``Beverly Hills 90210,'' ``Columbo,''
``Murder, She Wrote,'' and ``Star Trek.'' Its debut here, however,
is the latest Italian effort to gain proficiency without too much
effort _ the linguistic equivalent of the electronic
cellulite-jiggling devices that are demonstrated on quivering
models on Italian cable television 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``If everybody who bought English lesson tapes, CD-ROMs and
books followed through all the way, we would by now be a bilingual
nation,'' Marco Barina, marketing director of L'Espresso, said as
he was preparing for the distribution of 700,000 cassettes of
``Columbo,'' the detective series starring Peter Falk. ``This at
least allows people to be entertained while they learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Italians are beginning to express embarrassment over their
poor grasp of English, particularly as Internet use spreads and
English terms like ``killer,'' ``top model,'' ``downsizing'' and
``welfare'' seep into Italian newspapers and conversation. When the
Democrats of the Left, the largest party in the governing
center-left coalition, held their last convention, in January, they
adopted the English words ``I Care'' as their slogan.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, L'Espresso rated Italian politicians by their
fluency in English. Prime Minister Giuliano Amato was on the list
of those who spoke it well. His predecessor, the former Communist
Massimo D'Alema, was only ``so-so.'' Once he became prime minister
in October 1998, D'Alema began taking private English lessons on
his lunch break, worried that he might miss something at meetings
of the leaders of the major industrialized nations.
</P>
<P>
   Other Europeans improve their English by watching Hollywood
movies with the original soundtrack, accompanied by subtitles. Most
Italian move theaters, however, show American films dubbed into
Italian.
</P>
<P>
   Several companies in Italy now sell videocasettes of popular
Hollywood movies like ``You've Got Mail'' and ``There's Something
About Mary,'' with the original English-language soundtrack, and
also English-language subtitles, to help viewers follow the
dialogue. Speak Up, a monthly magazine intended for Italian
students of English, also sells videocasettes, along with
transcripts from the film.
</P>
<P>
   The personal ads in Speak Up suggest that at least some readers
cannot entirely accept Hollywood comedies as a serious language
study guide, however. ``Desperately seeking videocasette of `Sense
and Sensibility' or other rigorously British films,'' a reader
called Lina wrote this month.
</P>
<P>
   And some language instruction on the Internet includes a stern
moral lesson. Stephen Murrell, an Englishman who runs the English
Conversation Club, a language school in Genoa, supplies English
courses to Donna Moderna magazine, Italy's highest circulation
women's magazine, as well as the Donna Moderna Web site. Murrell,
who also teaches English to Italians on cruise ships, composes his
own texts to enhance vocabulary and reading comprehension _ asking
users to select the correct word from a list of five.
</P>
<P>
   One installment, ``Among the Slaves of the South in the
States,'' luridly recounts plantation life during the American
Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   One segment: ``A one-legged slave (grow, whip, surrender,
hobbled, bent) by. `Good morning, Master.'''
</P>
<P>
   ```We had to cut off his leg to stop him escaping when he was
younger,' smiled the plantation owner.''
</P>
<P>
   The text, which describes ``Negroes'' cheerfully picking cotton,
might startle American readers, but Murrell, who noted that the
editors had actually persuaded him to tone down his original
language, said Italians needed to learn the painful parts of
American _ and English _ history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no good expecting students to read boring texts,'' he
said. ``They have to read something they would read in their own
language. We also do a lot of stuff on the English royal family.
Italians love it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
