<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Thursday, Sept. 14 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   LEE-RELEASE (Albuquerque, N.M.) _ Dr. Wen Ho Lee, the former Los
Alamos scientist accused of mishandling nuclear secrets, walked
free from prison Wednesday under a plea agreement after the judge
in the case apologized to him and called the prosecution an
embarrassment. Lee pleaded guilty to one count of improperly
downloading nuclear secrets, a far cry from the 59-count indictment
and earlier suggestions by the government that he had spied for
China. The judge sentenced him to 278 days in prison, the time he
has already served.The judge apologized to Lee for the ``unfair
manner'' of his incarceration and said the Department of Justice
and Energy ``have embarrassed our entire nation and each of us who
is a citizen of it.'' By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: Early version has moved)
</P>
<P>
   NY-SENATE-DEBATE (Buffalo, N.Y.) _ In the New York race for the
U.S. Senate, Hillary Rodham Clinton faces off Wednesday in her
first debate with Republican rival Rick Lazio. The televised
debate, moderated by NBC's Tim Russert, is to be shown live from 7
p.m. to 8 p.m. EDT on NBC stations across the state. And, in a sign
of the wide interest the race has generated, it is to air
nationally on MSNBC from 10 p.m. to 11 p.m. (Summary from wires) By
Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-U.S.-TRADE (Washington) _ Developments on trade.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-FUNDRAISING (Undated) _ A look at Al Gore's fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE-KIDS (Washington) _ More hearings on media violence and
kids. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT20.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The Republicans' decision on
Capitol Hill to shift their message to debt reduction and away from
tax cuts in the waning weeks of the session is the latest example
that they are pursuing a campaign strategy independent of Gov.
George W. Bush. While refusing to criticize Bush's large tax plan,
Republican candidates and incumbents on the campaign trail instead
are sticking to a strategy they say has served House Republicans
well this year, emphasizing smaller bite-size tax cuts that target
married couples, small business owners and farmers. By Lizette
Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   CHASE-MORGAN (New York) _ Ledeall: Chase Manhattan Corp., the
third-largest banking company in the United States, formally
announced Wednesday that it is acquiring J.P. Morgan Co., an
investment bank. A look at the strategy of Chase Manhattan now that
it has done its long-awaited Big Deal. Can it compete with
Citigroup? Can it meld Morgan's culture, proud of its history, into
its own? What does this deal say about other big banks like Bank of
American that do not have a major presence on Wall Street. By
Patrick McGeehan and Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-FUEL (London) _ Oil trucks resumed limited deliveries
from petroleum refineries and storage depots on Wednesday, but
Prime Minister Tony Blair failed to break the siege that has left
almost all of Britain's filling stations dry. The flow of supplies
was estimated to be less than 10 percent of regular volume, and
almost all of it was designated for vital services like hospitals,
ambulances, fire and police departments rather than the nation's
gas pumps. The protests against high fuel prices that have
presented Blair with the most serious domestic crisis of his three
and a half years in office continued Wednesday, with pickets
monitoring the rigs exiting the oil company properties and creeping
convoys of truckers creating miles of traffic jams on major
intercity expressways and blocking the passage of cars in London
and other urban centers. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
