<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3137 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-PALTROW-HNS &LR;      09-13 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PALTROW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE REAL DUO BEHIND `DUETS'
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ERIC HARRISON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
TORONTO _ In ``Duets,'' Gwyneth Paltrow plays a kindhearted if not
very bright woman in her 20s who meets the father she's never known
and upends her life to be with him, even though he doesn't want her
around.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In real life, the reverse was almost true: Six weeks before
filming was to begin, Paltrow, in her 20s and by all accounts both
kindhearted
 &UR; and &LR;  bright, feared she was about to lose her father. Respected
television producer and director Bruce Paltrow, who was to direct
``Duets,'' was diagnosed with throat cancer.
</P>
<P>
   It was a trying time. Her paternal grandfather, who has since
died, had learned he had liver cancer less than two months earlier.
Doctors removed Bruce Paltrow's tonsils, lymph nodes and salivary
glands and began radiation treatments. The patient lost 40 pounds.
Nevertheless, he persevered, and ``Duets,'' an unlikely seriocomic
look at karaoke bar culture, opens Friday.
</P>
<P>
   While Paltrow's burgeoning stardom is the reason the movie got
made, she plays a relatively small role in an ensemble cast that
includes Andre Braugher, Huey Lewis, Paul Giamatti, Maria Bello and
Scott Speedman. The movie consists of the interwoven stories of
various searchers, desperate pilgrims looking for freedom,
security, love or family. They're all on the road _ Braugher's
character is also on the lam _ and their stories converge at a huge
karaoke contest in Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, Paltrow says the prospect of losing her father _
she calls him ``Daddy'' _ helped her to play the role of a woman
whose father had abandoned her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a sense of how to play her because I was so close to my
own father and he has been so important to who I am and so
important to my life,'' she said while sitting beside him at a news
conference at the Toronto International Film Festival. ``The
thought of not having him in my life informed the way I played her.
The edginess I'd feel without him was the way I'd suspect she
felt.''
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of it all, Paltrow won the Academy Award as best
actress for her role in ``Shakespeare in Love.'' Alluding to her
father's illness, she broke into tears during her acceptance
speech.
</P>
<P>
   Few people knew what she was going through. Her father had asked
her not to discuss it publicly. At the time she would say only that
his illness had been especially heart-rending because he'd tried to
make ``Duets'' for four years and the financing hadn't come
together until after he took ill. He'd worked on the movie for so
long, and it appeared he wouldn't be able to direct it.
</P>
<P>
   As for Bruce Paltrow, he said it was hard to go on, but focusing
on making the movie helped him to cope.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go to bed at night thinking about how the shoot went that
day or about what you have to shoot tomorrow as opposed to whether
I'll be here tomorrow to shoot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying so hard to be strong for him, but it was very
difficult,'' Gwyneth Paltrow said. ``He was very, very sick and not
himself. My biggest challenge was to just be professional and grown
up and not be a scared daughter and just try to make his life as
easy as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, actress Blythe Danner, and the rest of her family
stayed on location during the shoot to give support. This
heightened the feeling that it was a Paltrow family production, but
Bello said the Paltrows were extraordinarily inclusive. ``It wasn't
like there were the Paltrows and then the rest of us,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, Gwyneth Paltrow was to act in the movie beside Brad
Pitt, whom she was dating. But when they broke up, it seemed
awkward to continue with him in the movie. The script made the
rounds at a number of studios, each time going through rewrites and
then being put on hold. Without Pitt's star power, it was difficult
to get the movie made.
</P>
<P>
   Not until after Paltrow became a star in her own right with
roles in such hit movies as ``Emma,'' ``Sliding Doors'' and
``Shakespeare in Love'' did it become a ``go'' project again.
</P>
<P>
   The movie faced another crisis when Disney refused to release it
unless Bruce Paltrow toned down two violent incidents. He edited
one shooting to make it less graphic; in the other case, he deleted
footage of a killing, although the scenes leading up to it remain.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Paltrow has directed his daughter before. When she was 17,
he cast her in a television pilot. The job allowed her to get her
Screen Actors Guild membership card. Before that, he admitted, he
and Danner had reservations about Gwyneth acting.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife always had the feeling she would be like Margaret Mead
and maybe go into anthropology,'' he said. ``We did not want her to
act as a child. We wanted her to go on with her schooling. And she
did _ she went on through high school.''
</P>
<P>
   When she decided she wanted to drop out of college to act, her
parents supported her.
</P>
<P>
   A reporter asked Bruce Paltrow whether he feels protective of
his daughter because of the pitfalls that often come with
celebrity. Of course he does, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But parenting is an evolutionary process,'' he said. ``I
wasn't thrilled when she told me she crossed the street by herself
(for the first time). . . .We all have fears for our children, but
I think she does exceedingly well.''
</P>
<P>
   All of the major characters except Speedman's sing in the movie.
Though most of the voices are dubbed _ Paltrow is among those who
did their own singing _ the actors prepared in part by hanging out
at karaoke bars in and around Los Angeles and performing before
real audiences. What they learned, Bruce Paltrow said, was that
each bar had its own flavor and its own stars and ``weird
characters.''
</P>
<P>
   All of them said singing before an audience was exciting, and
scary, in a way that is different from acting. But Bello came to
love it.
</P>
<P>
   Before the movie, she said, she hadn't sung in public since the
fifth grade, when classmates made fun of her. ``I thought I would
never sing again as long as I live,'' she said. But the movie
changed that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admit that I have, since ''Duets,`` become obsessed with
karaoke _ completely obsessed,'' she said. ``If you see an uptight
executive get up and become the sexiest Tom Jones in the world _
well, that's what karaoke is all about. It helps you express your
inner essence.''
</P>
<P>
   XXXENDOFSTORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
