<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3138 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-SOAPS-HNS &LR;      09-13 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOAPS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOAPS SUDS BUBBLE AS PARODIES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
Among our guilty show-biz pleasures, few are more pleasurable than
daytime soaps, those sudsy tides of tantrums, tackiness, fashion
victims, absurdly contrived plots and _ when we're lucky _ steamy
romance.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even those who proclaim disdain of soaps find themselves hooked
when they are forced to stay home for a week and pass the time with
characters named Emerald or Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Filmmakers certainly seem hooked. Fictionalized soaps often turn
up within films or TV shows, both as objects of mirth and
touchstones to emotional icons.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, such phony soaps overplay the real soaps' melodrama and
acting flubs to get laughs. But they also show the soaps' power to
affect viewers in very real ways.
</P>
<P>
   Take ``A Reason to Love,'' a phony soap that's central to the
plot of the new movie ``Nurse Betty.''
</P>
<P>
   As the title character, Renee Zellweger is a waitress who falls
in love from afar with saintly physician Dr. David Ravell of ``A
Reason to Love'' _ the character, not the actor, who's played by
Greg Kinnear.
</P>
<P>
   To show the program on TV sets in the course of the film,
director Neil LaBute shot several scenes for almost 30 minutes of
footage. These were mailed to journalists in advance _ fittingly,
in serial form.
</P>
<P>
   The intro for ''A Reason to Love`` is styled much like that of
''The Young and the Restless,`` with cast members taking turns in
swirling vanity shots, and a smirking Kinnear holding a bouquet.
</P>
<P>
   The title screen then has cursive pink letters atop a hospital
illustration akin to that of ``General Hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, ``GH'' producer and director Shelly Curtis was a
technical adviser for shooting ``A Reason to Love.''
</P>
<P>
   She calls its scenes ``just slightly over the top,'' and in
truth, the phony soap is played fairly straight and on the level.
</P>
<P>
   Kinnear also spent two days on the ``GH'' set, where he learned
to respect the rigors of working so quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Not so smooth was the phony soap of 1991's ``Soapdish,'' in
which Sally Field played the hysterical diva of the long-running
``The Sun Also Sets.''
</P>
<P>
   Brain transplants drove its plot, while jealous backstabbing
drove the movie proper, with Cathy Moriarity as a rival actress
with a soap name: Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Another fake soap arose in this year's ``28 Days,'' in which
Sandra Bullock played an alcoholic being treated at an institution.
There, patients became hooked in another way: on ``Santa Cruz,'' a
phony soap whose name was a nod to the real ``Santa Barbara.''
</P>
<P>
   As in ``Nurse Betty,'' the fake soap of ``28 Days'' eventually
entered the real world, when a character from ``Santa Cruz'' _
``Falcon,'' played by Jack Armstrong _ arrived at the institution
for treatment of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Dustin Hoffman also had a dream of a drag role when he played a
struggling thespian disguising himself as an actress to land a soap
part in 1982's ``Tootsie.'' Jessica Lange won an Oscar as best
supporting actress for playing another actress on the ``Tootsie''
soap, which was called ``Southwest General.''
</P>
<P>
   On television, a fake soap appeared in a twisted series that was
convoluted and soapy on its own: 1990-91's ``Twin Peaks.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Twin Peaks'' characters raptly watched the daytime drama
``Invitation to Love,'' which had the nerdy Chett seduced by
temptress Emerald, twin sister of Jade, in a scheme involving yet
another Montana.
</P>
<P>
   On TV's ``Friends,'' aspiring actor Joey (Matt LeBlanc) once had
a fake soap role, but on a real soap, ``Days of Our Lives''
(conveniently on the same network).
</P>
<P>
   The clumsy Joey played an unconvincing surgeon, but he was
convincing enough for one fan, played by Brooke Shields _ a la
``Nurse Betty'' _ to fall in love with him.
</P>
<P>
   Even more phony and fun was ``As the Stomach Churns,'' a fake
soap that appeared as a recurring sketch on TV's ``Carol Burnett
Show'' in the '70s. Burnett, Harvey Korman, Lyle Wagner and others
played their mock soap parts with ``John!'' ``Marsha!'' fervor.
</P>
<P>
   Next up is ``Grosse Pointe,'' a comedy premiering at 7:30 p.m.
Sept. 22 on Channel 39. Its soap within the sitcom is a nighttime
teen drama along the lines of ``Beverly Hills, 90210'' _ ample
fodder for cutting and comic looks behind the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Will Emerald prevent Heather from seducing Victor before Dr.
Ravell's long-lost brother returns to claim the fortune that Falcon
wrested from Jade when he learned she was carrying Montana's child?
</P>
<P>
   Stay tuned, as the soaps keep on churning.
</P>
<P>
   XXXENDOFSTORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
