<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3139 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-MUSIC-APERFECTCIRCLE-     09-13 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-APERFECTCIRCLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIMING IS PERFECT FOR CIRCLE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MICHAEL D. CLARK 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
Attaining rock-star status is, in at least one respect, not much
different from achieving success in any career field. Timing is
everything, and it always helps to know the right people.
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a veteran studio engineer for such performers as David Bowie,
Tool and Smashing Pumpkins, songwriter Billy Howerdel knew lots of
people. Since matching his talents with those of Tool vocalist
Maynard James Keenan last year to form A Perfect Circle, his career
has been sweeping along like the hands of a finely tuned Rolex.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely going well. We sold 10,000 copies (of debut
album `Mer De Noms') the first day it was released. Almost every
show is sold out,'' Howerdel, 30, says from a San Francisco tour
stop. ``It's much more than we could have ever expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Last summer A Perfect Circle debuted its burdened and grieving,
deliberate metal rock at the Viper Room in Los Angeles. It was
Keenan's marquee power that drew Tool fans to hear unknown songs
from an unknown band written by an unknown Howerdel.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, and name-dropping Tool is becoming passe. A
Perfect Circle refined those songs and added a few more for the
release of ``Mer De Noms'' (French for ``Sea of Names'') in May.
The swooshing hands of synchronization started working for the band
when it decided to forgo a more widespread club tour in favor of an
opening slot on Nine Inch Nails' ``Fragility'' V2.0 tour.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to promote a debut album in the shadow of Trent Reznor's
Pretty Hate Machine could have been a huge gamble. In retrospect,
playing to giant arenas packed with thousands of fans agreeable to
aggressive music-assault therapy was a stroke of unintentional
marketing genius.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know if our songs would play to the Nail's crowd,
but it immediately felt locked in,'' Howerdel says. ``Now I think
the Nine Inch Nails record (last year's ''The Fragile``) helped
boost us a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   On the buzz strength of that tour and a first single,
``Judith,'' coupled with a dark video by director David Fincher
(``Fight Club,'' ``The Game,'' ``Seven'') ``Mer De Noms'' became a
summer hit.
</P>
<P>
   The album reached No. 4 on the Billboard charts, making it the
highest-charting debut album ever for a rock band. After 15 weeks
it still hovers around the Top 60 with help from second single, ``3
Libras.''
</P>
<P>
   Time hasn't always moved so swiftly for Howerdel. He began
crafting the tunes that would evolve into A Perfect Circle nearly
10 years ago, originally conceiving them in the acid-house, dream
pop vein that was popular at the dawn of the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   He learned a lot about creating and producing albums in his day
job as a guitar technician for the likes of Bowie, Tool, Smashing
Pumpkins and Fishbone. They became valued contacts when Howerdel
finally quit working on guitars in 1996 to work full-time on his
own music.
</P>
<P>
   The members of A Perfect Circle came together soon after.
</P>
<P>
   Paz Lenchantin is primarily credited as a bassist, but she also
contributes piano, violin and even vocals when needed.
</P>
<P>
   Drummer Josh Freese was a friend of Howerdel's back when both
worked with Guns N' Roses.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Van Leeuwen is a former guitarist for Failure who could
mimic the music Howerdel heard in his head.
</P>
<P>
   The most difficult person for Howerdel to see in A Perfect
Circle was the already established Keenan. Aside from being a
little intimidated by sharing his creative power with the Tool
mastermind, Howerdel felt Keenan's gravestone-voice was the wrong
gender for the Bjork-like harmonies that Howerdel had envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking for a female voice, and I hadn't even considered
a male,'' Howerdel says. ``I wanted a contradiction to this manly
music, but when I thought of Maynard I thought masculine.''
</P>
<P>
   That changed when the two started reworking songs like ``3
Libras.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I got plans for that song,'' was all Keenan said to Howerdel
as he started working out lyrics and composition. Because the Tool
veteran was arranging the song at the same time as the last
bristling Tool album, ``Aenima,'' the hurt of Howerdel's writing
most surely provided Keenan with a needed contrast.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the acoustic guitar brushes and string backing were
flushed with Keenan's soft balladry, Howerdel was overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got very emotional. I felt like I had graduated and gotten
my doctorate,'' he says. ``I knew I could trust Maynard from that
point.''
</P>
<P>
   Howerdel always thought ``3 Libras'' and ``Mer De Noms'''
opening track, ``The Hollow,'' had radio potential, but was
surprised that ``Judith'' took off as the debut hit.
</P>
<P>
   With its slashing Soundgarden guitars sending Keenan's wavering
whimper into bursts of intimidation, it's probably the song most
removed from Howerdel's original feminine touches.
</P>
<P>
   As a student of the studio, Howerdel was smart enough to let
Keenan take over the song to see where it led.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been around producers who get good reaction in songs and
I see what they do,'' says Howerdel, who is listed as the producer
of ``Mer De Noms.`` ``I just kept asking myself what he needed
emotionally to get to that performance and tried to give it to
him.''
</P>
<P>
   The versatility learned in the studio and on the road already
has Howerdel thinking about life beyond A Perfect Circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really banking on not being a musician,'' Howerdel says.
``I'm a visual guy, which could lead me to film. I want to be a
producer for albums and do a score for a movie''
</P>
<P>
   All that is on hold until A Perfect Circle runs its cycle.
</P>
<P>
   The members of the band are always in demand for session work,
and Keenan will eventually return to Tool.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere along the line all will find out if the worlds of both
Keenan's bands can be balanced.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, Howerdel the producer is smart enough to go with it
and see where it leads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm absolutely confident that Keenan is committed to this
band. If he's not here, I'm not and vice-versa,'' Howerdel says.
``Whatever happens now, happens.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
