<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-HATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE APPROVES HATE-CRIMES BILL, 232-192 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Giving a breath of hope to one of President
Clinton's fondest legislative priorities, the House Wednesday
approved a measure supporting the expansion of federal hate-crimes
legislation to protect victims of violence based on gender,
disability, and sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   By an unexpectedly wide 232-192 margin, the House voted for a
measure instructing House and Senate negotiators to include the
hate-crimes language in a Defense Department authorization bill the
two legislative chambers are finishing this month.
</P>
<P>
   The vote does not force the conference committee, which works
out the differences between the House and Senate defense bills, to
include the hate-crimes provision. But it does put heavy pressure
on the bipartisan panel to make the hate-crimes language law.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an important step forward,'' said Representative Barney
Frank, Democrat of Massachusetts, and a strong proponent of gay and
lesbian rights. ``Unfortunately, it's not binding,'' and Republican
House leaders _ who fought to thwart the measure _ could take the
unusual route of rejecting a direct request from the entire House,
Frank said.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the hate-crimes measure, which passed the Senate
57-42 in June, argue that it unfairly creates two classes of
victims and unconstitutionally punishes a perpetrator's thoughts,
however offensive those thoughts may be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prosecute people not for their motives but for their action,''
said Representative Lindsey Graham, Republican of South Carolina,
during the floor debate. The bill ``will ultimately divide
America,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was hailed by gay rights activists and by Clinton, who
has taken a strong interest in getting the hate-crimes legislation
passed. Invoking the cases of Matthew Shepard, a gay Wyoming man
who died after being tied to a post and beaten, and
African-American James Byrd Jr., dragged to his death in Texas, the
president has pleaded with Congress to expand the federal
hate-crimes law.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a sad and painful irony that at the beginning of a new
century ... with all the modern gadgets we enjoy, we are still
bedeviled by mankind's oldest failing: the fear of the other, which
so quickly can lead to distrust, then to dehumanization, then to
the kind of violence'' that killed Shepard and others, Clinton said
Wednesday at a White House event urging passage of the hate crimes
language.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may not ever fully conquer the disease that afflicts human
hearts everywhere, the compelling need to define ourselves up by
defining someone else down,'' the president said. ``But at least we
can do more to make sure that no one in our country is violated
simply becuase of who they are.''
</P>
<P>
   If the conference committee does not include the hate-crimes
language, Clinton could still insist on adoption of the language
during a possible post-election legislative session, threatening to
hold up spending bills unless the lame-duck Congress agrees to the
hate-crimes provision.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's tally had a surprising 41 yes votes from
Republicans, including Representative Bill McCollum, who was one of
the floor managers during the impeachment debate and is now facing
a tough fight for a Senate seat from Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The hate-crimes legislation would expand a 1968 law to allow
greater federal prosecution of victims of crimes motivated by bias.
Current law allows federal intervention only if the victim is
prevented from engaging in a federally protected activity, such as
voting.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, sponsored in the Senate by Edward M. Kennedy, would
also expand the groups protected by the current hate crimes law,
adding gender, sexual orientation, and disability to the existing
categories of race, religion, color, and national origin.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-two states have hate-crimes laws, but some localities are
reluctant to prosecute such crimes or lack the resources to do so,
backers of the federal proposal argue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just absolutely elated. It's a stunning victory,'' said
David Smith, spokesman for the Human Rights Campaign, the leading
gay and lesbian rights lobby.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
