<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, Sept. 14, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   High pressure moving off the New England seaboard will promote
sunny skies over most of the Northeastern states. Farther to the
west, isolated showers and thunderstorms will accompany a front
moving east from the Great Lakes. Showers and thunder will linger
in the south-central Gulf Coast states.
</P>
<P>
   Florence, a minimal hurricane, continues to disrupt shipping off
the East Coast as it remains nearly stationary. The hurricane is
producing dangerous seas, including riptides, along the
southeastern beaches, although it is 400 miles east of South
Carolina.The storm should move north and east during the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Remnant moisture from Tropical Storm Lane will produce patches
of clouds and isolated showers in the Pacific Northwest. Southern
California will be very warm.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: FICKLE RAIN
</P>
<P>
   Near Dallas, Monday was a testament to the fickle ways of summer
showers. More than an inch of rain drenched parts of the
metropolitan area while no rain fell at the official gauge,
extending the record streak of days without measurable rain to 73.
In summer, the jet stream that carries large scale storms typically
stays close to Canadian border. Much of the rain in the South
occurs when the strong sun helps produce rising currents in the
very warm, humid air. These currents can become showers and
thunderstorms a few miles wide which dampen some areas while
others, by chance, remain dry.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
