<HEADER>
A3156 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-U.S.-CHINA-TRADE-NYT     09-13 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-CHINA-TRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE CLEARS LAST HURDLE TO PASSING CHINA TRADE BILL 
</HEADLINE>
  By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With surprising and decisive ease, the Senate
cleared the last major hurdle Wednesday to passing a landmark trade
bill with China and handing President Clinton one of his top
remaining foreign policy goals.
</P>
<P>
   Senators rejected a contentious amendment to impose sanctions on
Chinese companies that export sophisticated weapons to hostile
nations, setting the stage to vote in a few days on legislation to
give China permanent normal trading privileges.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment was defeated on a bipartisan vote, 65-32, after a
furious last-minute lobbying campaign this week by pro-trade
business leaders and several of Clinton's cabinet officers, who
argued that the measure was redundant and could scuttle the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The vote virtually assures that the Senate will join the House
in ending the annual congressional review of China's trade status,
a ritual for 20 years that Beijing considers humiliating but that
opponents argue is a lever for improving human rights. More than 70
senators are generally expected to vote for the overall bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the big enchilada,'' said Sen. Max Baucus of Montana,
a pro-trade Democrat who led the fight against the amendment.
``We've got it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the situation in the House, where the trade bill survived
intense opposition from a coalition of labor and religious groups,
final passage in the Senate was never been in doubt, only the
course to get there. Supporters of the legislation have pressed for
a bill free of amendments because they say there is not enough time
before Election Day to reconcile an amended Senate bill with the
version that the House passed in May.
</P>
<P>
   One after another, amendments to improve human rights, religious
freedom and labor standards in China have fallen by lopsided votes
this week, not because senators opposed them on merit but because
of their potential harm to the underlying bill.
</P>
<P>
   But the amendment sponsored by Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., and
Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., to penalize Chinese companies that
traffic in nuclear, chemical and biological weapons, as well as
long-range missiles, struck a strong chord with lawmakers who are
increasingly alarmed by intelligence reports of Chinese arms
exports.
</P>
<P>
   Under the amendment, the president would have been required to
conduct an annual review of China's proliferation activities. If
Chinese companies trafficked in the prohibited weapons, Clinton
could have cut off sensitive technology exports and U.S. government
loans or credits. The president could have waived the sanctions if
it was in the national security interest of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator Thompson is asking us to put national security ahead
of greed,'' said Sen. Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., who supported the
amendment. ``What's wrong with that?''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio, added: ``This amendment is not just
about holding other nations accountable as proliferators. It is
also about holding our president accountable as the world's
principle proliferation enforcer.''
</P>
<P>
   But other senators, including Phil Gramm, R-Texas, voiced
support for the overall bill and its trade benefits and objected to
any amendments that could imperil them.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson mocked Gramm for naively believing that trade could
help reverse Beijing's penchant for selling missiles and missile
technology to countries like North Korea and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   ``His response is trade with them and one day we will magically
wake up and they will be dismantling their armaments,'' said
Thompson, who has clashed with Gramm in recent months over a bill
to govern export controls. ``When that happens, I will present the
tooth fairy on the floor of this body.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after Thompson had watered down his amendment to address
administration complaints that it focused too narrowly on China and
that its sanctions would hurt American farmers, the Clinton
administration strongly objected.
</P>
<P>
   This week, several cabinet members, including Defense Secretary
William Cohen and the national security adviser, Sandy Berger,
telephoned senators who were wavering on the amendment, warning
that it overlapped existing law and hindered the president's
ability to compel China to curb proliferation.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, 35 Democrats and 30 Republicans voted against
Thompson's measure, while 23 Republicans and nine Democrats voted
for it. Several Republicans who favored the amendment as a separate
bill, including Thad Cochran of Mississippi, Connie Mack of Florida
and Don Nickles of Oklahoma, voted against it as an amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is it, it's settled, it's all over but for the
shouting,'' said Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., who has
championed the trade bill.
</P>
<P>
   After the vote, Thompson's aides said he had not ruled out
bringing up the measure again before the Senate adjourns.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and China reached agreement last fall on a
deal to help pave China's eventual entry into the World Trade
Organization, the 135-member trade group that sets the rules for
global commerce. China will enter the WTO no matter how the Senate
votes. But without the blessing of Congress, Beijing could withhold
some of the trade benefits, including lower tariffs, from the
American farmers and companies that it will extend to other members
of the trade group.
</P>
<P>
   Business leaders hailed the surprisingly wide margin of the vote
and predicted speedy passage of the overall bill, perhaps as early
as Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
