<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV01-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., OCT. 1, 2000. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 c.2000 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: To publish Bernard Gladstone's ``Home Improvement
Questions and Answers'' it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndication Sales. For purchase
information call toll-free 1-888-269-8796.) 
 (The NYTSS sales representative also has information on how to
subscribe to Gladstone's ``Home Improvement Questions and Answers''
weekly column which moves on Wednesdays.) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: I have decided not to buy cheap ``throwaway'' roller covers
any more because they don't leave a really smooth paint finish. For
my next job I'm going to buy a top quality cover for use with latex
flat paint.
 &HT;    I would like some suggestions on how best to clean such roller
covers, especially when I will be switching from dark to light
colors?
 &HT;    A: Start by scraping as much excess paint out of the fibers as
you can, using a tool sold for this purpose or even the end of a
wooden stirrer.
 &HT;    Immerse the cover in a pail of warm water with a little
detergent added and squeeze the nap with your hand along its entire
length so as to distribute water through the fibers.
 &HT;    Rinse thoroughly in clean warm water and keep squeezing the
fibers until no more color comes out.
 &HT;    Then use a spinner (sold for use with brushes or roller covers)
to spin the cover rapidly while holding it inside a large garbage
pail or five gallon bucket.
 &HT;    After spinning it till it is almost dry and fluffy, stand it up
on edge to store.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: When it rains heavily, water runs down off a long sloping
hill in back of my house. The water tends to accumulate against the
foundation, creating puddles and occasionally leaking into my
basement around the windows.
 &HT;    What can I do to solve this problem without extensive
re-grading?
 &HT;    A: One solution would be to divert the ground water running off
the hill by digging a trench across the slope, at least 10 feet
uphill from the house and roughly parallel to the house.
 &HT;    This trench should be about 12 inches deep and 12 to 18 inches
wide and should be filled with gravel.
 &HT;    It should be long enough to extend past the house on each side,
and at each end the trench should gradually slant up to the surface
so that water can flow out easily.
 &HT;    The trench will then serve to catch water as it comes down off
the hill and divert it so that it runs off around each side of the
house.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: There is a damp spot on my upstairs bedroom ceiling where the
paint has peeled.
 &HT;    Before painting I had scraped off the old paint down to the bare
plaster and although the plaster does look like it is water
stained, there is no evident sign of a leak in the attic above this
room.
 &HT;    Any idea what could be the problem?
 &HT;    A: I would suspect condensation in the attic, probably on the
roof beams. This moisture then drips down onto the top of the
ceiling and soaks into the plaster, causing the paint to peel.
 &HT;    It could be that some of the eave vents are blocked or that the
attic simply needs more ventilation.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: There are a number of very fine hairline cracks in the walls
and ceiling of my living room and I am just getting ready to
repaint this room.
 &HT;    How do you recommend I should repair these before starting to
paint?
 &HT;    A: If the cracks are only in the paint, not in the plaster or
surface under the paint, then it is possible that simply applying a
fresh coat of paint will fill them in.
 &HT;    However, if the problem is due to a previous painting problem _
for example, poor application of previous coats, inadequate drying
time between coats, improper thinning, or failure to prepare the
surface before the last coat of paint was applied _ then the
cracking may reappear.
 &HT;    Either way, fine cracks are usually repaired by filling with
spackling compound, but loose or peeling paint should be scraped
off first.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    NOTE: Drawing captioned ``USING A SPINNER TO CLEAN ROLLER'' goes
with this column.
 &HT;    CAPTION: Spinning washed roller cover inside bucket will remove
water after thorough washing and will serve to dry fibers.
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.2000 Bernard Gladstone 
