<HEADLINE>
BUSH CLAIMS CLINTON-GORE ALLOWED NATIONAL PARKS TO DETERIORATE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONROE, Wash. _ Turning the environmental tables on Democratic
rival Al Gore, George W. Bush on Wednesday ripped into the
Clinton-Gore administration for allowing national parks to
deteriorate into ``worse shape than ever before.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing on the bank of the scenic, but foggy Skykomish River
north of Seattle, the Republican presidential nominee also
criticized Gore for not taking a stand on a key issue pitting
environmentalists against landowners in the Northwest _ a proposal
to breach four dams on the Snake River to protect salmon, one of
the region's best-known natural resources.
</P>
<P>
   Bush opposes breaching the dams and backs alternatives that, he
says, can protect the salmon's upriver spawning grounds. Gore has
proposed a regional summit to discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
   It was Bush's third visit to Snohomish County, one of a ring of
mixed suburban and rural counties surrounding Seattle that could be
key to winning Washington's 11 electoral votes. Polls indicate Gore
is leading in Washington but that the state is competitive.
</P>
<P>
   After being on the defensive for much of the time since last
month's Democratic National Convention recharged Gore's campaign,
the Texas governor tried to take the offensive Wednesday on the
environment, an issue that Gore likes to claim as his own.
</P>
<P>
   Bush proposed spending an additional $3.75 billion on national
park maintenance over the next five years and an extra $100 million
to improve natural science management at the parks.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when more people than ever before are visiting the
national parks, Bush said, the Clinton-Gore administration is
neglecting them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sewage flows untreated into the lakes and streams of
Yellowstone National Park,'' he said. ``Civil War relics have been
soaked by a leaky roof at Gettysburg.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican nominee, who has been criticized frequently by
Democrats over air and water pollution in Texas, said the
Clinton-Gore administration had requested a 22 percent decrease in
funding for major park maintenance for fiscal 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their failure to make maintenance a priority has left our
parks at risk and at the breaking point,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``The backlog of repairs runs into the billions of dollars. For
eight years, this administration has talked up environmentalism
while our national parks are crumbling.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that the National Park Service has a $4.9 billion
backlog for major maintenance and resource protection, which he
wants to eliminate within five years. The $3.75 billion he proposes
over five years would be in addition to $230 million a year that,
he says, is already in the agency's ``baseline'' for major
maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign responded that the administration has created
13 new national parks, and has required that 80 percent of park
entry fees go into park maintenance rather than into the general
fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to parks, Al Gore has a record of achievement
whereas George W. Bush has a record of neglect,'' said
Gore-Lieberman senior adviser Ron Klain, claiming that Bush has not
made state parks a priority in Texas during his tenure as governor.
</P>
<P>
   Bush made his remarks to a few hundred invited guests in a farm
pasture outside Monroe, where he viewed a restored slough, a
waterway off the Skykomish River that now serves as a nursery for
young salmon, allowing them to grow before they swim down river to
Puget Sound.
</P>
<P>
   The slough was reopened on private property with the help of
state and federal funds. It was hailed by Bush as an example of
public-private cooperation that would be a better way of protecting
salmon than breaching dams.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also supports ``fish-friendly'' turbines or the
installation of devices that divert fish around dams as ways of
letting adult salmon swim up river to their spawning grounds and
their offspring to make the return trip down river.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists have advocated breaching, or tearing down part
of, four dams on the Snake River in eastern Washington that were
built between the mid-1960s and 1970s. They help make much of the
Snake and the Columbia River into which it flows navigable, and
they provide irrigation for farmers and hydroelectric power.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said all of those uses are important to the economy of the
Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not need to breach the dams to save the salmon, and
should I become the president, we won't,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican nominee said that Gore had failed the leadership
test on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``My opponent has refused to take a stand on the importance of
salmon and dams,'' he said. ``He has refused to say whether he
would breach the dams or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said residents of Washington and the Northwest deserved to
know Gore's position before the election.
</P>
<P>
   Bush later left Washington state for southern California, where
he planned to campaign Thursday and Friday in Orange County and San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
   As Bush continued his efforts in California, polls there and
nationally continued to give Gore an edge, and the Bush campaign
announced it has hired Washington consultant Ed Gillespie to help
Bush hone his message.
</P>
<P>
   Gillespie, who oversaw the communications operation at the
Republican National Convention, will work for Bush communications
director Karen Hughes, who offered him the job last week.
</P>
<P>
   Considered an expert at melding policy and politics, Gillespie
will help Bush shape and deliver his agenda from the campaign's
headquarters in Austin. He has been an informal adviser to the
campaign for months. He is former policy and communications
director of the House Republican Caucus and held the same title
under Rep. Dick Armey, R-Irving, during the congressman's first
year as House majority leader. Gillespie will take a leave of
absence from his private sector consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   The latest Reuters/Zogby poll, released Wednesday, had Gore
leading Bush 46-39 nationwide, with Green Party nominee Ralph Nader
at 4 percent and Reform Party candidate Pat Buchanan at 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
