<P>
   TEMPER (Phoenix) - In America's polite cubicle culture, anger
has become the new taboo. That old school of militant factory
foremen and coaches with tempers like Bobby Knight is fading in
favor of zero tolerance policies and company-sponsored anger
management classes. Somewhere in Bobby Knight's 29 years of
coaching, between being inaugurated into the hall of fame and being
fired Sunday for that trademark temper, society changed. ``That old
routine of being a screamer and a cusser is completely out of
fashion all through the business world'' said John Crawford, a
communications professor at Arizona State University who studies
anger. ``There was a time when it wasn't at all uncommon to have
your foreman running up and down the line cussing people out . . .,
but now it's a very uncool thing to be doing.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, experts say, we're angrier than ever. By JAIMEE ROSE.
Story will move in the ``A'' category.
</P>
<P>
   MONTINI-COLUMN (Phoenix) {ndash} I have these two pictures in my
head. One shows Victor Rodriguez sitting near the body of his dead
son on the side of the road near Loredo, Tex. The other is a
photograph I imagine being taken in the near future. It shows a
group of dark-suited executives from Firestone and maybe Ford being
hauled off to jail. BY E.J. MONTINI. Story will move in the ``K''
category.
</P>
