<SLUG> BC-APPLE-OSX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPLE GIVES PUBLIC A PEEK AT NEW OS X OPERATING SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After years of tinkering with the bodywork of its
Macintosh computers, the engineers at Apple Computer Inc. are
popping open the hood.
</P>
<P>
   The innovative and radical styling of its iMac and iBook
computers has brought Apple back from the brink of ruin to a new
position of prestige and profitability. But all along, the
company's computers relied on an aging operating system that lagged
far behind the Windows software from rival Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   That's about to change. In Paris Wednesday Apple CEO Steve Jobs
unveiled a preview version or ``public beta'' of the new Mac OS X,
the company's long-delayed operating system upgrade. And a radical
upgrade it is _ the most dramatic redesign of the software since
the Mac made its debut during the 1984 Super Bowl. The new OS X
(pronounced ``ten,'' for Roman numeral 10) is built around a set of
advanced features that compare favorably not only to Windows, but
even to Linux, the fashionable free operating system that's
developed a worldwide following.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, OS X isn't free _ not even the unfinished beta
version. Apple is selling the software on CD-ROM for $29.95, and
the program will automatically cease to function in May 2001. No
price has been announced for the finished version, which is still
set for release early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, OS X has been profoundly affected by the free
software movement. The most basic part of the operating system, its
``kernel,'' is available at no charge to anybody who wants to
tinker with it. The kernel, named Darwin, is itself based on free
software products similar to Linux. Software developers around the
world are being welcomed to study Darwin, and even produce
modifications, that Apple may incorporate into future versions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing incredible response and feedback'' among free
software developers, said OS X product marketing manager Chris
Bourdon, who added that 40,000 programmers have signed up to work
with Darwin.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, Apple is placing much of the future development of
its core software in the hands of strangers. A few years ago, such
a strategy would have been unimaginable. The raw ``source code''
from which software is made was regarded as a company's crown
jewels, never to be revealed to outsiders. Microsoft is fighting
efforts to force the company to reveal the underlying ``source
code'' for Windows as part of a settlement in its antitrust case.
</P>
<P>
   The spectacular success of Linux, which boasts publicly
available source code, has changed a lot of minds. Apple now
welcomes the assistance of smart outsiders in devising improvements
to their core software.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, while the Darwin kernel is free, there's a great deal
more to Mac OS X, including a flashy new user interface and a
variety of built-in software utilities. These are the features
customers pay for, the ones that make a computer user-friendly and
attractive. Needless to say, Apple has no intention of giving away
this code.
</P>
<P>
   Mac OS X has something else in common with Linux _ both products
are descendants of the advanced Unix operating system developed in
the 1970s by AT&AMP;T Corp. for demanding data networking jobs. Linux
was designed as a cheap but powerful Unix alternative; with OS X,
Apple has done much the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   A copy of the beta software provided to the Globe reveals
dramatic improvements over the present Mac operating system, as
well as additional complexities that are likely to confuse some
experienced users. Still, these advanced features can largely be
ignored by current Mac owners, who'll be able to run most of their
present software exactly as they do now.
</P>
<P>
   For experienced users of advanced operating systems, OS X brings
an old-fashioned command-line terminal, where the user can control
the computer by typing complex commands instead of clicking icons.
The terminal accepts standard Unix commands and gives the user
direct access to the heart of the operating system.
</P>
<P>
   OS X has plainly borrowed some ideas from Windows. For instance,
OS X has adopted the Windows convention of displaying icons in a
bar at the bottom of the screen, to show which programs are
running. Of course, in traditional Apple style, the Mac taskbar is
a lot prettier _ the animated icons bounce up and down and seem to
pour themselves onto the screen.
</P>
<P>
   The new software seems to be a good deal more robust than
earlier versions. For example, a program crash that might have
forced a reboot in earlier Mac OS versions had no effect on the
rest of the system.
</P>
<P>
   This ``hardening'' of the operating system was a key goal of its
developers, and to achieve it they had to start from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   The present Mac OS descended from software written for Apple in
the early 1980s for computers that were far less powerful and
sophisticated. To make sure that older programs could run on newer
Macs, the company was forced to keep using old-fashioned features
in newer versions of the operating system. For example, the early
Macs weren't very good at letting a user switch between multiple
tasks _ copying a file, writing a letter and working on a
spreadsheet, for instance. And the current Mac OS 9 still has
problems with this.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem was the way that a failure of one program often
caused the entire computer to crash. This could be fixed by adding
``memory protection,'' a feature that ensures that each program
runs in its own private space and can't interfere with others.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft had confronted the same problems with its old MS-DOS
operating system. By 1995, it had found the answer in Windows 95.
While far from perfect, Windows 95 and its successors tended to be
more stable than Macs and were better at multitasking.
</P>
<P>
   Apple officials knew they needed something similar. So in the
mid-'90s the company decided to upgrade its operating system by
basing it on a piece of software called Mach _ a Unix-like kernel
developed at Carnegie Mellon University. Jobs, who'd cofounded
Apple, had been ousted in 1985. He'd started his own company, Next
Computer, which made NextStep, a Mach-based operating system. In
December 1996, Gil Amelio, Apple's CEO at the time, stunned the
computer industry by purchasing Next and bringing Jobs back to the
company.
</P>
<P>
   The deal also brought Avie Tevanian to Apple. He'd helped create
Mach as a grad student at Carnegie Mellon, and then worked on the
design of NextStep.
</P>
<P>
   Amelio planned to use NextStep as the basis for a new, robust
Mac OS to be called Rhapsody. Jobs liked that part of the plan, but
had no use for Amelio. In July of 1997, he forced Amelio's
resignation and took over.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs presided over a rapid renaissance at Apple, driven by the
company's restyled computers and high-speed PowerPC processor
chips. But only now has the new operating system project begun to
bear fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Tevanian and his colleagues combined his earlier Mach work with
code from another free Unix-like operating system called BSD, which
is especially well-suited for use in computer networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did it because the Mach-BSD combination is an incredibly
robust operating system,'' Tevanian said.
</P>
<P>
   But they faced another problem. If the new OS was too different,
old Mac programs wouldn't run any more, and thousands of people who
write Mac programs would have to be completely retrained. The Mac
OS team responded by building in a set of code called Carbon, which
makes it easier to modify old Mac programs to work under the new
system. They also built in a ``compatibility layer'' of code that
works just like the old Mac OS. When an OS X user wants to run an
older copy of, say, Microsoft Word, the computer boots up the older
Mac OS inside the new one. Then the user can easily hop between the
old and new programs.
</P>
<P>
   Software writers who've worked with OS X agree that it should
make their lives a good deal easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``The superior Mac interface is already a lot faster, but now
with the modern Mach kernel under the hood, both the human
interaction and raw computing will be so much faster,'' said Glenn
Carnagey, former Web master of the Chicago Sun-Times and now a
programmer in Round Rock, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But industry watchers doubt that a new operating system, however
impressive, will do much to expand Apple's popularity beyond its
present market niche. Dan Kusnetzky, an industry analyst with
International Data Corp., said that in 1999, Apple computers made
up only 5 percent of the desktop machines sold worldwide, compared
to 88 percent for Windows. He doubts that OS X will do much to
raise Apple's batting average.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are a large number of things in the marketplace
that consumers and users look at,'' said Kusnetzky, ``and for the
most part the operating system is secondary.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Apple's Tevanian hesitates to predict any big market share
breakthrough from OS X.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hope is that we make it so good that it attracts even more
customers to be Mac customers,'' he said. But he adds that the OS X
development team wasn't driven by a desire to have a rematch with
Windows in the desktop wars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think of it in those terms,'' said Tevanian. ``Our
goal is to build the best products.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
