u a BC-MIT-DRINKING-BOS &LR;      09-13 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIT-DRINKING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIT ADMITS POLICIES LED TO DRINKING DEATH OF STUDENT IN '97 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICK HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Massachusetts Institute of Technology admitted
Wednesday that its ``inadequate'' alcohol and housing policies
played a part in the 1997 death of freshman Scott Krueger, and
agreed to pay his family $6 million to avoid a civil lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement came only after MIT president Charles M. Vest
flew to Buffalo two weeks ago to apologize personally to Krueger's
parents, Robert and Darlene.
</P>
<P>
   Krueger, 18, was found unconscious in the basement room of MIT's
Phi Gamma Delta fraternity house in September,1997 after a night of
apparent hazing. His blood alcohol level was .401.
</P>
<P>
   During nine hours of mediated talks last month, Vest gave his
word that he would crack down on under-aged drinking on campus _
chiefly, by barring freshmen from choosing to live in Greek houses,
as Krueger did.
</P>
<P>
   And at the end of the day, he offered a hug to Mrs. Krueger, who
had long criticized MIT for not owning up to responsibility in her
son's death. The president's compassion, she said in an interview,
moved her enough to accept the settlement agreement, as well as a
long embrace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope this isn't too late, Mrs. Krueger,'' she recalled him
whispering.
</P>
<P>
   Vest followed up last week with a letter to the Kruegers, in
which MIT formally acknowledged for the first time that it was at
fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite your trust in MIT, things went terribly awry,'' Vest
wrote. ``At a very personal level, I feel that we at MIT failed you
and Scott.''
</P>
<P>
   The $6 million settlement ended a dramatic chapter in the
Krueger case, in which the family sought to make the university _
and by extension, higher education institutions nationwide _
accountable for alcohol-related deaths of students.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some MIT students said the campus faced a deeply entrenched
culture of drinking at the pressure-laden school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how MIT can really attack drinking,'' said
Danielle Schumaker, a sophomore and a member of Sigma Kappa. ``Even
in the dorms, students can get away with drinking.''
</P>
<P>
   MIT officials acknowledged that drinking was sometimes a problem
in dorms, but said they felt resident advisers could discourage
alcohol use there. More broadly, they said, memories of Krueger's
death have led so many students to see the danger of excessive
drinking that the campus has undergone ``a cultural change.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are five fraternities that are now alcohol free that
weren't three years ago,'' said MIT spokesman Ken Campbell. ``We've
had a lot more community events that are great times, with no
alcohol.''
</P>
<P>
   Krueger's death still casts a palpable pall over the MIT campus.
Several students clearly recalled details of Krueger's death in
interviews Wednesday, almost three years after he fell into a coma
and died from severe alcohol poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   The student newspaper reported this week that about 15 percent
fewer freshmen than last year were pledging membership to Greek
houses, and some fraternity members said bad publicity may be one
cause.
</P>
<P>
   The Suffolk County District Attorney's office charged the local
chapter of Phi Gamma Delta of involuntary manslaughter and hazing.
But the case effectively came to an end after MIT permanently shut
down the fraternity.
</P>
<P>
   The Kruegers plan to soon file a civil action against the local
and national chapters of Phi Gamma Delta, according to the family's
lawyer, Leo V. Boyle.
</P>
<P>
   The family and MIT, meanwhile, had discussed negotiations over
the last several months. Boyle would not say why the apology and
settlement took three years, but said Vest's apology and assurances
were enough for the family to drop plans to sue the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``MIT promised Mr. and Mrs. Krueger that campus life at MIT will
forever be changed,'' Boyle said at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in August 2002, all freshmen will be required to live
in university dorms. At the same time, fraternity enrollment events
will not be held during freshmen orientation. MIT has also moved to
place a resident adviser in all Greek houses and ensure its police
will patrol fraternity and sorority houses across the Charles River
in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Of the $6 million settlement, $4.75 million will go to the
Kruegers as compensatory damages, and the remaining $1.25 million
will be used to create a scholarship fund in Scott Krueger's name.
</P>
<P>
   An admission of responsibility and a monetary settlement is
unusual for an institution that has neither been sued nor promised
a confidentiality agreement in return, Boyle said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the lawyer, as well as MIT students, credited Vest with a
reputation for admitting when MIT was at fault, as he did last year
when he approved findings that some female professors had suffered
discrimination in pay and office space.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew what was important to the Kruegers, and I think in his
heart he knew what was important to him,'' Boyle said.
</P>
<P>
   Vest was not available for comment. In a statement, he said,
``We can now move on with the healing process.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Krueger agreed, saying she, for one, wanted to put MIT
behind her. ``There's no way I'll ever go back there,'' she said
after a press conference in Downtown Crossing, just a mile from the
campus. ``My son died there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
