<HEADLINE>
DELTA TO BEGIN FLIGHTS TO LONDON FROM BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Get ready for price wars to London from Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines, which began Boston-Los Angeles service this
summer and drove the fares down on that route, said Wednesday it
will begin service to London's Gatwick Airport from Logan
International Airport on June 1, pending federal government
approval.
</P>
<P>
   Four airlines _ American, United, British Airways, and Virgin _
fly nonstop from Boston to London, making it Logan's busiest
international route.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pleased to begin service on the largest international
market from Boston,'' said Mark Drusch, Delta's senior vice
president of network management, in a press release.
</P>
<P>
   While Delta, which flies more passengers to Europe than any
other US carrier, was expected to begin international service from
Boston when its new $400 million terminal is built and opened in
2004 or 2005, the proposed service for next year caught many by
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Even Massport officials were not aware of the decision until
Wednesday's press release was distributed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The addition of this flight underscores Delta's long-term
commitment to growth in Boston,'' said Drusch.
</P>
<P>
   Massport aviation director Thomas Kinton said if the service is
approved it will bring the number of daily flights to London to
eight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It speaks to the strength of the Boston international long
haul market. To support seven frequencies to London is remarkable.
This gears it up to almost a New York shuttle type frequency,''
Kinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's daily flights will seat 195 passenger, 48 in
BusinesssElite and 147 in economy.
</P>
<P>
   The eastbound flight will start in Los Angeles, stop in Boston
for two hours and continue on to London. The westbound flight will
end in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston-Gatwick route was originally held by Northwest
Airlines, and they dropped it. It was then picked up by American
(which also flies to Heathrow), and American dropped it last year,
Massport officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Delta is asking to use the route because it is dormant. If the
airline receives federal Department of Transportation approval, it
will begin selling tickets and an introductory fare is likely, a
Delta official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
