<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-NEWMACHINES0914-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke sees new bottle, can dispenser as a sales booster
 &HT;    By Scott Leith
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - The Coca-Cola Co. is rolling out a way to sell
everything from Coke to iced tea to orange juice, all from the same
vending machine.
</P>
<P>
   Dubbed the ``glass front vender,'' the new device is likely to
turn heads when it starts showing up around the nation. Made by
Maytag Corp., it offers a view of the products inside, much like a
candy machine or store cooler. It also holds different-sized
containers, enabling Coke to stock its full line of brands in one
machine.
</P>
<P>
   Coke is pitching it as a whole new vending experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``First and foremost is the variety that the machine provides,''
said David Karpan, director of vending for Coca-Cola North America.
During test runs last year in Greensboro, N.C., and Dallas, the
machine boosted sales significantly, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A new Coke machine might not sound like a breakthrough, but a
unique device can be important to a company's bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   Vending machines account for about 13 percent of soda sales,
said John Sicher, editor of Beverage Digest. ``The more interesting
the machine is, the more likely it is to attract customers,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Coke thinks its new device is entertaining, too, largely because
a little elevator moves up and down to get individual bottles and
cans before shooting them to the buyer. The practical benefit:
Bottled soda doesn't get fizzy due to dropping from the top.
</P>
<P>
   The machines are equipped for ``online'' vending, although not
all will have the feature from the start. With online vending, the
machine keeps track of its inventory and notifies the bottler when
it's getting low.
</P>
<P>
   The new machines will cost more than the current $2,500 models,
but Coke declined to discuss exact costs. The machines were
developed by Coke and a unit of Maytag, the Iowa-based appliance
maker. Production just started at Maytag's Dixie-Narco
manufacturing plant in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Maytag is promoting the machine under its own name rather than
Dixie-Narco, as in the past. ``This is unique to the industry,''
explained Doug Drenten, group vice president of research and
development for Maytag's Commercial Solutions group.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the only new machines around Atlanta are deep in
Coke's headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The machines will be sold to Coke bottlers. ``We'll have several
thousand in the marketplace over the next six months,'' Karpan
said. They're aimed mostly workplace settings, where customers can
be plied with orange juice in the morning and Coke in the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   DETAILS;
</P>
<P>
   What's new: The machine can hold containers ranging from
20-ounce plastic bottles to 12-ounce cans. An elevator travels up
and down to gather a buyer's choice.
</P>
<P>
   Where they've been tested: Greensboro, N.C., and Dallas
</P>
<P>
   Where they'll be used: Mostly workplace settings
</P>
<P>
   What they'll hold: Up to 45 different products in one machine
</P>
<P>
   For more information: See Maytag's special Web site at
www.gfv.maytag.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
