</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SPORTS NEWS ABOUT THE NET: 09.14.00
 &HT;    Ratings: More caught in Olympics web
 &HT;    Quokka COO discusses site's shift
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAVE TIME ONLINE: All stories and urls in this column are one
click away on ajc.com/enews
</P>
<P>
   RATINGS GAME: Nielsen//NetRatings has launched a monitor of
Internet traffic to Web sites covering the Sydney 2000 Olympic
Games. It will provide extensive reports of Internet traffic to key
sites from 14 countries in North America, Asia Pacific and Europe.
Not surprisingly, the data already reveals U.S.-based Web traffic
is surging to key sites. Traffic to NBCOlympics.com rose 41 percent
from July to August to 236,000 unique visitors. Nearly 63 percent
of those visiting the site were female; males made up 37 percent.
The official site, Olympics.com, jumped 51 percent in the U.S. to
184,000 unique home visitors. Females made up 54 percent of its
traffic; males 46 percent. In Australia, the number of unique
visitors to Olympics.com grew from 36,000 in May to almost 200,000
in August. Page views were up from 440,000 to more than 4.4
million.
</P>
<P>
   STATUS QUOKKA: WSJ.com's ``Nothing But Net'' has a Q&AMP;A with
Alvaro Saralegui, the former business manager for Sports
Illustrated who went on to become COO of Quokka Sports. Saralegui
defends his site's switch from specializing in less-popular sports
_ mountain climbing, sailing races _ to more mainstream fare.
Deciding not to change would have ``limited the magnitude of the
business,'' he said. Quokka has lined up a deal with NBC to cover
the Olympic on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   www.wsj.com
</P>
