<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3183 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-FLYING-ONLINE0914-COX     09-13 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLYING-ONLINE0914-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Discount airlines leading way in online ticket sales
 &HT;    By Nancy Fonti
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - AirTran Airways' Web site has never been busier.
</P>
<P>
   The Orlando-based airline, which operates an Atlanta hub, now
generates about one-third of its revenue through its Internet site,
compared with just 1 percent two years ago. During a fare sale last
week, tickets booked at airtran.com accounted for 42 percent of all
revenue taken in that day, the airline said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last two years we've seen phenomenal growth,'' said
Kevin Healy, vice president of planning.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines large and small began luring customers to their Web
sites in the late 1990s with frequent-flier perks and sales.
Discount airlines now lead the pack when it comes to selling
tickets through these sites.
</P>
<P>
   Most major carriers airlines sell 4 percent to 6 percent of
their tickets through their home sites, far lower than percentages
reported by AirTran and Southwest Airlines. Southwest, the
Dallas-based low fare airline, generates about 30 percent, or $1
billion, in revenue through its site annually.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason why discount airlines fare best is because
they have always encouraged travelers to book tickets directly
through them instead of through third parties; now they are
retraining customers to visit Web sites instead of calling 800
numbers. These companies also cater to tourists and entrepreneurs
willing to use the Internet to hunt for a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor: the sites are easy to use, requiring visitors to
click through as few as six pages before they buy a ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simplicity of their sites helps tremendously,'' said Terry
Trippler, a consultant and writer for travel site Onetravel.com.
``AirTran has had to think differently from the start, and low fare
airlines were quicker to embrace the idea of booking a ticket
online.''
</P>
<P>
   Airlines have a big motivation to push online bookings, which
dramatically cut processing costs. For example, a ticket booked
through AirTran's Web site costs the company 30 cents to 40 cents,
compared with $5 through its reservation desk, according to the
company. Commissions push the costs of a ticket sold through a
travel agent up to between $10 and $11.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest pays $1 to sell a ticket through its Web site, between
$3 and $7 through its reservation desk, and about $10 through a
travel agent.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Delta Air Lines, the nation's third-largest
carrier, now generates about 4 percent of its revenue through its
Web site and 10 percent through all sites at which it sells seats.
They include its own site, delta.com; name-your-own-price site
priceline.com; and online agents Travelocity.com and Expedia.com.
</P>
<P>
   Delta hopes to boost the percentage of tickets sold through all
online venues to 30 percent by 2003 but doesn't have specific
targets for its Web site, said spokesman John Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   An airline's Internet site is easily the cheapest place for it
to sell tickets because bookings aren't subject to commissions paid
to both online and traditional travel agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Big carriers also have invested in other online ventures. Delta
and four other top airlines are co-owners of Orbitz, the online
agent expected to start business in about a year. Delta was also
the first big airline to sell seats through priceline.com, which
gave it lucrative stock rights and the right to keep competitors
from selling through priceline.com flights on certain routes.
</P>
<P>
   Airline Web sites and travel agencies like Travelocity and
Expedia now split the share of tickets sold online evenly, but
airline sites eventually will win over more travelers as they
aggressively advertise their brands, said Heidi Kim, a travel
analyst at Jupiter Communications.
</P>
<P>
   By 2005, airline sites will sell online 55 percent of air travel
purchased, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suppliers were essentially asleep, but now we're at that
turning point,'' Kim said. ``(Airlines) have the advantage of using
their brand to pick up bookings. They can transition people from
the off line world to the online world.''
</P>
<P>
   Travel experts say consumers should not book a ticket through an
airline site without investigating other options. Before booking
through an airline site, always compare prices with an independent
online travel agency or a traditional travel agent, Trippler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know,'' he said. ``There could be a big deal on one
and not the other. Three words for the consumer to remember are
compare, compare, compare.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
