<HEADLINE>
NEWSPAPER SEEKS TO PRESERVE EXECUTED PRISONER'S DNA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ALOYSIUS FARRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRUNDY, Va. _ The Boston Globe asked a court Wednesday to
prevent Virginia officials from destroying DNA evidence that would
determine if Roger Coleman, who was executed by the state eight
years ago despite his claims of innocence, was indeed guilty of the
crime for which he died.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe also asked Judge Keary R. Williams of the Buchanan
County Circuit Court to reconsider his decision that the state, and
not his court, is the legal custodian of the evidence, and to
permit DNA testing.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman was executed by Virginia in May 1992 for the rape and
murder of his sister-in-law, Wanda McCoy. He was convicted on the
basis of circumstantial evidence, and his ability to appeal the
verdict was curtailed when one of his lawyers was a day late in
filing the necessary court papers.
</P>
<P>
   The Coleman case is often cited by the American Civil Liberties
Union and other foes of capital punishment as a wrongful execution.
He appeared on the cover of Time magazine before he died, and a
book, ``May God Have Mercy,'' has been written about the case,
raising doubts about his guilt.
</P>
<P>
   Besides its reknown, the Coleman case is unique because the DNA
evidence from the case has been frozen and preserved by a
California laboratory since his death. Unlike other cases where
executed inmates had proclaimed their innocence, there are no
questions about a chain of custody of the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its ongoing effort to test the claim of death penalty
foes that innocent men and women have been executed in America, the
Globe asked Judge Williams to authorize further testing in the
Coleman case last May.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe based its argument on the Virginia Freedom of
Information Act, the guarantees of the public's right to know and
the media's freedom of access contained in the US and Virginia
Constitutions. The Globe also cited, as a precedent, the order it
won in Houston County, Ga. this summer authorizing post-execution
testing of DNA material there in the case of Ellis Wayne Felker.
</P>
<P>
   In the Georgia case, Judge L.A. McConnell Jr. ruled that ``the
rights reserved to the public...would be hollow if the court only
allowed a visual inspection. . . . In order for the inspection to
be meaningful, the public should have a right to know what, if
anything, is contained in the subject evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   A rudimentary DNA test conducted in 1990 by Edward Blake, a
california-based expert in DNA testing, failed to exclude Coleman
as the murderer. At the Globe's request, Blake told the court in
July that today's DNA technology could yield a more definitive
answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such an analysis,'' Blake wrote Williams in a July 26 letter
urging the judge to approve new tests, ``could resolve any
lingering factual issues.'' Blake conducted the 1990 tests, and has
stored the DNA samples ever since.
</P>
<P>
   When the Attorney General's office learned of the Globe's
efforts, however, it moved to block the testing and regain control
of the DNA samples. Senior Assistant Attorney General Donald R.
Curry, who lobbied against the testing, declined to discuss his
reasons with the Globe.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Williams' predecessor, retired Judge Nicholas Persin, had
asserted his court's authority and ordered the 1990 DNA test. But
Judge Williams was persuaded by Curry's argument that the court did
not have that power, and that the legal custodian of the DNA
evidence is the state.
</P>
<P>
   Bowing to the Attorney General's argument, Judge Williams issued
an order on September 7, ordering Blake to return the DNA evidence
to the state police detective who had led the prosecution of the
Coleman case.
</P>
<P>
   Williams informed the Globe's lawyers of his order on Tuesday,
and the newspaper filed its response Wednesday: asking Williams to
reconsider, and urging the judge to stop Virginia officials from
destroying the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   In a similar case earlier this year, state authorities
incinerated the evidence that might have been tested from another
capital case, that of Joseph O'Dell, who had been executed in 1997
for a 1985 rape and murder. The Catholic Diocese of Richmond hoped
to test the evidence in the O'Dell case but lost its suit in the
Virginia Supreme Court, in part because there was not an intact
chain of custody.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Enzinna, the lawyer in the O'Dell case, filed a petition on
behalf of further testing in the Coleman case Wednesday on behalf
of Centurian Ministries, a non-profit group that helps inmates
prove their innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very concerned the Commonwealth of Virginia will do
everything in its power, as it did in the Joseph O'Dell case, to
destroy the evidence and, therefore, prevent the truth from coming
out,'' said James McCloskey, the minister who heads Centurian
Ministries and once worked with Coleman's defense team.
</P>
<P>
   David Botkins, press secretary for Virginia Attorney General
Mark Earley, appeared to leave room for a compromise Wednesday,
saying ``there have never been any conversations or discussions by
anyone in the Commonwealth about destroying any evidence.'' The
Attorney General's office acted only because it believed that
``whatever testing is going to be done, or should be done,'' should
be conducted in Virginia, Botkins said.
</P>
<P>
   McCloskey, in turn, said he would not object if the state used
its own forensic experts to test the samples. ``Let the chips fall
where they may, and let's discover the truth together,'' McCloskey
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
