<HEADLINE>
VERIZON TO MOVE MASSACHUSETTS JOBS TO DALLAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Verizon Communications said Wednesday it will move 500
to 550 of its 1,000 jobs at a Middleton directory publishing
business to Dallas over the next nine months.
</P>
<P>
   The company, created from the merger of Bell Atlantic and GTE,
said it has no idea yet how many if any people could be laid off.
It said anyone not offered a new position in Dallas will be offered
extensive job-placement assistance. Only management positions, not
union jobs, are involved, Verizon said.
</P>
<P>
   While Bell officials had warned employees in Middleton in
January that some jobs there might be moved as part of the merger,
people familiar with the office said many employees were devastated
by the news, especially those nearing retirement and
pension-collecting age, and unhappy about the prospect of moving to
Texas. However, several expected they could easily find another job
in the state's booming telecommunications industry.
</P>
<P>
   The Middleton site was headquarters of the Bell Atlantic unit
that oversees and publishes all paper and electronic directories,
including the Yellow Pages. About 400 to 450 jobs will be kept at
Middleton in sales, billing, customer care, and field staff, said
Verizon spokesman Jack Hoey.
</P>
<P>
   ``To date the only decision we have made so far is about
location,'' Hoey said. ``We haven't made any decision about
staffing. We're going to of course offer many employees an
opportunity to move to Dallas, and all other employees we will be
offering significant transition assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   Most job transfers will be completed by next March, Hoey said,
although it could take until fall 2002 before all transfers are
completed.
</P>
<P>
   Hoey characterized the move as part of an expected reshuffling
of Verizon sites in the wake of the Bell-GTE merger, which has
included merging the company's headquarters into Bell's New York
City site and moving and consolidating other offices.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon said that despite shedding 500 jobs in Massachusetts, it
will continue to rank as the state's largest employer of people in
full-time jobs, with more than 19,000, and has added over 1,700
management and union jobs here in the last three years on its
landline and wireless phone businesses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
