<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-VIOLENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP POLS DECRY MEDIA VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Each actor in the all-star political cast _ Joseph
I. Lieberman, Lynne Cheney, and John McCain _ gave dramatic
performances Wednesday, blaming the entertainment industry for
polluting the popular culture and making it nearly impossible for
parents to police the films, recordings, and video games that amuse
their children.
</P>
<P>
   The stage was the Senate Commerce Committee, chaired by McCain,
and the background was a scathing Federal Trade Commission report,
released Monday, that accuses Hollywood of deliberately marketing
violent entertainment to teenagers, a practice McCain called
``unconscionable.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman broke away from his Democratic vice presidential
campaign to testify on what he called ``the growing concern'' about
the decay of the nation's moral fabric and the ``culture of
carnage'' that influences youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than helping to shoulder some of the growing burden on
parents, the entertainment industry too often has chosen to go
behind parents' backs, targeting the sale of violent, adult-rated
products directly to children,'' the Connecticut senator said.
``This practice is deceptive, I believe it is outrageous, and it's
got to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, a longtime Senate critic of Hollywood's values, said
he and presidential candidate Al Gore are demanding the industry
immediately end its marketing of R-rated entertainment to children.
If self-regulation does not occur, he said, the FTC should take
action under rules that bar false and deceptive advertising. If the
FTC determines it lacks such power, Congress should pass
legislation expanding the agency's authority, Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, wife of GOP vice presidential candidate Dick Cheney and
herself a cultural warrior, said moral authority, not new
regulation, should pressure the entertainment industry to reform
itself. In her equal-time testimony, she hinted at hypocrisy on the
part of Gore and Lieberman because they will appear at a
fund-raiser in New York Thursday night hosted by Miramax studio
executive Harvey Weinstein expected to raise more than $5 million
for the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shouldn't people of stature go to Harvey Weinstein and ask him
to pledge that he will not fund works that debase the culture and
corrode our children's souls?'' asked Cheney, who was appointed to
head the National Endowment for the Humanities by President Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney said it was shameful for major companies to represent rap
artists like Eminem, whom she described as ``a violent
misogynist.'' His song, ``Kill You,'' describes the rape and murder
of his mother. Cheney said she wrote letters to two female
executives at the Seagram Co., which produces Eminem's best-selling
CDs, citing the offensive lyrics and warning that Congress could
move against the entertainment industry if it does not clean up its
act.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was furious that none of Hollywood's studio executives
agreed to appear at his hearing, and he reissued an invitation for
13 of them to testify before the committee on Sept. 27. Heads of
two record companies and two video-game manufactuers did appear,
defending their marketing and First Amendment protection against
censorship.
</P>
<P>
   ``By some uncanny coincidence, every single studio executive was
either out of the country or unavailable,'' McCain told the
standing-room-only crowd. ``I can only conclude the industry was
too ashamed of or unable to defend their marketing practices. Their
hubris is stunning.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Valenti, Hollywood's longtime Washington lobbyist,
testified for the film studios and insisted that the 32-year-old
voluntary industry rating system works for the majority of parents.
But he pledged to meet with his members, as well as theater owners,
to address issues about marketing and access of teens to violent
movies.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Valenti scoffed at Wednesday's session, saying
it was more about politicians vying to sound earnest and
family-friendly in an election year than about regulating or
legislating. His request to have the hearing delayed one week so
the Hollywood executives could participate was denied by McCain's
staff, said Valenti, president of the Motion Picture Association of
America.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, while the senators on the committee said they deplored
the coarsening of the culture and expressed angst about their own
helplessness as parents, the only calls for legislative remedies
came from Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   Even Robert Pitofsky, the FTC chairman who called the
entertainment industry's marketing of violent material ``brazen,''
said he was reluctant to move against Hollywood because it would be
unprecedented and sure to end up in court for years. ``We can't
wait forever,'' Pitofsky said, ``but I hope we can find ways to
cooperate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
