<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-STRANGLER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUIT HOPES TO REOPEN BOSTON STRANGLER CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RAPHAEL LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Relatives of Albert DeSalvo, who confessed to being the
Boston Strangler, and those of his last victim, will file a lawsuit
Thursday to reopen the case, armed with what they say is new,
exculpatory proof that DeSalvo was not the killer.
</P>
<P>
   An attorney representing the families told the Globe Wednesday
that DeSalvo made a crucial slip-up in his confession to the murder
of Mary Sullivan in 1964, a confession that was captured on a tape
they recently obtained.
</P>
<P>
   In the tape, DeSalvo admitted to ``penetrating and ejaculating
into'' Sullivan during her murder, but according to relatives'
attorney Elaine Whitfield Sharp, autopsy reports they obtained
Tuesday show no evidence of sexual assault.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is one of the major parts of the confession that he
made, and he got it wrong,'' Sharp said. ``He just plain got it
wrong, and the reason he got it wrong, we believe, was because he
was not there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you murdered somebody, wouldn't you remember what you
did?'' Sharp continued. ``So our position is, let's reopen the
case, but the government has put up road blocks for no apparent
reason.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, which the families will file in Suffolk County
Superior Court, demands that the attorney general's office, the
Boston Police Department, the county medical examiner's office, and
the state police return forensic and other evidence they have held
onto since Sullivan's 1964 killing. From there, they will attempt
to solve the case privately, and in the process, yank DeSalvo's
name from the shadow of the label ``Boston Strangler.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are sensitive to the families' concerns, but this is no
different from any other unsolved homicide,'' said Ann E. Donlan a
spokeswoman for Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly. ``Like we've
said before, no one has ever been charged, and as with any other
unsolved homicide, the investigation into the circumstances
surrounding the murders remains open. We will continue to work with
the Suffolk District Attorney's office and the Boston Police
Department.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Reilly said he was ``inclined'' to give the
families access to the evidence in the case _ which is still
technically open. Since then, however, Reilly's office sent a
letter to Sharp, who is representing the families for free, saying
no evidence was forthcoming, Sharp said.
</P>
<P>
   DeSalvo, who confessed to 13 murders that took place between
June 1962 and January 1964, was killed in Walpole Prison in 1973 by
a fellow inmate while serving time on unrelated charges. He was
never charged with the Stangler murders.
</P>
<P>
   This spring the Boston Police Department issued a statement
saying it would no longer investigate the Boston Strangler case,
due to deterioration of evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp hopes to disprove that assertion at a press conference
Thursday. She and the families will convene to play the confession
tape, in hopes of persuading Reilly and others that the case is
still worthy of investigation.
</P>
<P>
   That investigation would be led by James E. Starrs, a well-known
forensic scientist from George Washington University who has
volunteered to take on the case.
</P>
<P>
   The families also hope to exhume the bodies of DeSalvo and
Sullivan in hopes that modern DNA-reading technology would also end
questions once and for all about the connection between DeSalvo and
the Boston Strangler.
</P>
<P>
   Asked who was the killer, if not DeSalvo, Sharp declined to
speculate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get over this first step first,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
