<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3208 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-OLY-WAlKER0914-COX     09-13 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-WAlKER0914-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Austin swimmer Walker shrugs off talk about Olympic pressure
 &HT;    By John Maher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ When you talk about the Olympics, you have to talk
about the pressure. Unless you're Neil Walker.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be really fun,'' Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   If there's any athlete who's just happy to be in Australia, it's
Walker, a lanky Austin resident and former University of Texas
swimmer. Four years ago he gained a small measure of fame by
missing the Olympics by the smallest of margins, one-hundredth of a
second when he was touched out for sixth place in the 100-meter
freestyle at the U.S. swim trials. In that event, six swimmers can
go to the Olympics on the 400 freestyle relay team.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, Walker might be anchoring that race Saturday
and might later have a shot at medals in another relay and two
individual events in the 2000 Summer Olympics. And that's after
having a couple of off swims and maybe making one bad choice at the
U.S. trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy with how things went,'' Walker maintained. ``It was
a scary thing going into the trials. For the last six months I'd
looked past it. I saw myself on the Olympic team. It was a huge
relief to make the team in the 100 backstroke. I made the team and
won an event, the 100-meter freestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker might be the least intense looking athlete in the Olympic
pool. Your typical Type A swimming personality, he's not. He
doesn't move quickly on land or in the warm-down pool and likes
nothing better than to spend a lazy day fishing. Could you imagine
Alexander Popov as a cheese head? Walker, a former Wisconsin
resident and still a Green Bay Packers fan, owns one.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, looks can be very deceiving. In the Short Course World
Championships earlier this year, Walker won seven medals and set
five world records. In a way, he's almost too talented. At the U.S.
trials, Walker had so many races he decided to pass on the
100-meter butterfly _ a race in which he's the American record
holder.
</P>
<P>
   Here, Walker's first race will be the 400 freestyle relay. It's
a race the American men have never lost in the Olympics. They're
well aware of that and so are the Australians, who knocked them off
at that distance at the Pan Pacific Championships here in 1999.
Both teams know that one race can be huge for team momentum,
something the Americans can't let the Australians build in a swim
center that can hold 18,200 fans screaming ``Aussie, Aussie,
Aussie!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we've managed to muster up some really good confidence
that we can hang with the Aussies,'' Walker said. ``The team
concept is very important. It's contagious. It happened with the
Texas guys at the trials. One guy starts doing well, and then
everyone does.''
</P>
<P>
   In his first individual race, the 100 backstroke, Walker rates
as a medal threat behind the stroke's master, Lenny Krayzelburg.
Walker chuckles about their race in the U.S. trials, in which he
faded to second.
</P>
<P>
   Walker said, ``I took it out way too fast in the first 50
meters. I wound up going a lot slower than I usually do in the
final 50 meters. You don't want to go out too fast or too slow. In
that first 50 I used up all my energy and burst my energy bubble.
Lenny did the same thing. He took it out with me and faded more
than he usually does. I know I can go a lot faster in the
Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   At the U.S. trials, Walker took the 100 freestyle, in which he
was a clear favorite. Here it's a different matter. He might win.
He might not medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most heated race in the world,'' Walker marveled.
``The field is fast and deep. You've got the world record holder in
Alexander Popov and two or three other guys who should be right
there with him. Popov is swimming really well, and I think Gary
Hall will go a lot faster than he did in the trials. Anybody has a
shot at it. There are so many times when a huge underdog wins it.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker won't be competing in his favorite race. He has said he
likes the 50 freestyle because, ``It's the only race where you
actually go anywhere, even if it's just the other end of the pool.
The other races you get out where you start.''
</P>
<P>
   He shrugs off the third-place finish at the trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'd feel more disappointed if I got third by just a
little,'' he said. ``Three-tenths of a second doesn't sound like
much, but that's a lot in the 50 meters. Usually you can't even
tell who won. There were two guys that were above and beyond me.''
</P>
<P>
   The 50, however, was a race he picked over the 100 butterfly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went in there with the 50 free being my better race. I was
debating whether just to swim the butterfly for a time for the
coaches. But our butterfliers will be fine. Now, I get those days
off,'' he reasoned.
</P>
<P>
   Walker thought of posting one butterfly time in the prelims at
the trials to give himself and the coaches another option in the
400 medley relay. Now, it might come down to whether he's picked
for the freestyle leg or if that goes to the resurgent Hall, a
great freestyle talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little tricky. It's up to the coaches as to who wins
the gold medal and who doesn't,'' Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he was worried about that. But it didn't sound like it.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Email: jmaher(at)statesman.com or 445-3956.
</P>
