r e BC-E-LIVING14-COX     09-13 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-LIVING14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    News about the net: 09.14.00
 &HT;    By John Druckenmiller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Teen Web trends: Games for him, growth for her
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Surging women's Web use not being ignored
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lots of material in that fight for madonna.com
</P>
<P>
   EQUAL TIME: We all know that males are more click-happy with the
TV remote. It seems the same is true when it comes to the mouse.
While teen boys and girls use the Internet in equal numbers, the
boys are zipping to far more sites each month, says a Jupiter
Communications / Media Metrix study of 12- to 17-year-olds. The
breakdown:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  301.2 to 271.0: The number of pages viewed per month by a male
teen surfer compared with the girl surfer.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  47 to 32: The domains visited by the average boy each month
vs. the average girl.
</P>
<P>
   Their choices in sites pretty much go along the gender fault
line, too:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Similarities: Search, e-mail and instant messaging are the
most popular services for boys and girls. They average five hours a
month online. With adults ages 35-49, the average is 13 1/2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Guy thing: Technology, entertainment, time diversion,
downloads and games are the focus of teen boys. Although said to be
fickle, their top sites: cheatcc.com, cmgsccc.com, gamesages and
other game sites that list ways to cheat through computer games.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Girl thing: Girls appear more goal-oriented. They spend their
Internet time reading periodicals, sending e-greetings and doing
homework. They're more loyal to their known online communities. Top
sites: seventeen.com, alloy.com, delias.com and teenpeople.com.
</P>
<P>
   WONDER WOMEN: Another recent Web trends report showed how
strongly women are embracing the Web. Those stats haven't been
ignored. To help corner ``a huge combined audience of women,''
Lifetime cable network, women.com and mutual partner Hearst
Magazines are aligning to ``capture more than 10 percent of the
entire Web audience.'' Hearst, publisher of Cosmopolitan and Good
Housekeeping, already is a partner in Lifetime (available in 78
million households) and women.com (a top-50 Web site). This move
accelerates ``the convergence of the Internet, television and the
print world,'' says Marleen McDaniel, women.com chairman/chief
executive officer. Watch for co-branding, mutual site links and
other enhancements.
</P>
<P>
   www.lifetimetv.com
</P>
<P>
   www.women.com
</P>
<P>
   WWW.MADONNA: Madonna's fight for the domain name madonna.com is
a little more bizarre than first thought. The singer indeed
cherishes it and won't settle for second-best, baby. But then
there's the Catholic-run Madonna Rehabilitation Hospital in
Lincoln, Neb., which owns madonna.org and wants the dot-com, too.
Finally, there's Dan Parisi, a New Jersey entrepreneur who owns the
domain and previously used it for pornographic material. He claims
the Material Girl has no more right to it than anyone else with the
same name. And: He offered the name to the hospital last spring. A
decision on ultimate ownership is due from the United Nation's
World Intellectual Property Organization soon.
</P>
<P>
   SEARCH ENGINE:
</P>
<P>
   RECIPE SITES: What's cooking today? Some samples:
</P>
<P>
   68,000 recipes
</P>
<P>
   to send you SOARing
</P>
<P>
   The Searchable Online Archive of Recipes, with nearly 68,000
recipes, was, er, cooked up by students at the University of
California at Berkeley and has no ads or links to e-commerce sites.
It also doesn't have bells and whistles such as printer-friendly
versions of recipes. The recipes come from random sources but the
broad range, including 952 for chili alone and is celebrated for
its variety of ethnic cuisines.
</P>
<P>
   soar.berkeley.edu/recipes/
</P>
<P>
   Site offers an online recipe box to save your favorites
</P>
<P>
   This site features 11,000 tested recipes from Gourmet and Bon
Appetit magazines, accompanied by ratings from users, photos and
videos. A nice-looking layout makes the site fun to use, even
though you do have to deal with some flashing ads. There are also
``boxes'' where you can save your favorites.
</P>
<P>
   www.epicurious
</P>
<P>
   .com
</P>
<P>
   Video demos are site's just desserts
</P>
<P>
   The recipes _ more than 11,000 of them _ on this
easy-to-navigate site have been presented by chefs on the Food
Network. Also included: video demos for many of the recipes if the
technique sounds too advanced. A great part of this site is the
ability to search for a wine match for a specific recipe or style
of food, and by price range.
</P>
<P>
   www.foodtv.com
</P>
<P>
   EVENTS
</P>
<P>
   BIG DIG: Cyberspace is colliding with ``breaking'' ancient
history as the National Geographic Society's Web site is updating
dispatches and first-seen images from where Dr. Robert Ballard has
discovered remnants of human habitation some 300 feet below the
Black Sea. The expedition's findings suggest people thrived along
the Turkish coast before a catastrophic flood, one tentatively
linked to the biblical story of Noah by geologists William Ryan and
Walter Pitman in their 1997 book ``Noah's Flood.'' Included: Audio
and written reports, photo galleries, video, maps and more.
</P>
<P>
   nationalgeographic.com/ngnews/blacksea.html
