<HEADER>
A3224 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-HOUSEWORK-POLL14-COX     09-13 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSEWORK-POLL14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When it comes to chores, poll shows partners don't see eye to
eye
 &HT;    By Jill Young Miller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The sound of harmony in the Hughes household is a
whining vacuum cleaner _ when David, 29, is pushing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to vacuum,'' says Rachael, 31, David's wife.
</P>
<P>
   David also helps cook and clean, and he pitches in on the
laundry at their metro Atlanta home. Both Hugheses work full time:
He sells pagers, she sells computer hardware and software. They
agreed to halve the housework when they married four years ago, and
generally they've stuck to the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize that both of us are equally responsible,'' David
says.
</P>
<P>
   Says Rachael, ``If one person does everything, I think that
person just ends up going insane.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hugheses are a happy exception, according to the findings of
an Atlanta Journal-Constitution poll of 547 married adults in 12
Southern states.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the South, husbands are claiming to do more housework
than wives say their husbands are doing. Men took more credit for
cooking, laundry and housework in general than women allowed, the
poll found. In the housework category, for instance, 40 percent of
men said they either do it themselves or are an equal partner in
the housework. Meanwhile, just 23 percent of women said men do it
all or equally.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Jhung, author of ``How to Avoid Housework,'' isn't
surprised. ``I think housework is like sex in that people lie about
it a lot,'' she says. ``Everybody claims they're doing more'' than
they are.
</P>
<P>
   What percentage of the housework should working husbands and
wives do to keep harmony? Chloe Bird, formerly of Brown University
and now a behavioral scientist at the think tank Rand, led a team
of researchers last year that asked 1,256 men and women what share
of the housework they did _ then correlated it with their reported
psychological well-being and stress. The conclusion: Each spouse
should do 45.8 percent of the housework.
</P>
<P>
   Who does the rest, the remaining 8.4 percent? The children and
hired help, Bird says, or maybe it just doesn't get done.
</P>
<P>
   For the sake of domestic bliss, however, Bird cautions couples
against ``bean counting.'' ``If everybody's trying to make sure
they don't do more than half, this isn't going to work very well,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   AJC poll respondent Johnny Depew, 50, considers himself an equal
partner. He's a carpenter and musician who lives in Gainesville,
Ga., and has been married 33 years. His wife, a nurse, does most of
the laundry, he says, while he does most of the yard work.
</P>
<P>
   (By the way, ladies, just as you say men overstate their
housework contributions, you claim to do more yard work than men
say you do, according to the AJC poll.)
</P>
<P>
   Depew can't name a household chore he won't do. ``Everything has
to be done, and I don't not do any of it,'' he says. ``It's
probably why I've been married a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   There's some evidence that things may gradually become more
equal. Overall, women say they cook more than their mates do. But
women and men younger than 30 are more likely to say ``both
equally'' prepare meals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in a single-parent household,'' says poll respondent
John Bray, 32, a customer service agent for Delta Air Lines. ``I
learned early how to cook.''
</P>
<P>
   Says his wife, Cassandra, 31, who writes training material for
Delta: ``In my house, my mother did all the cooking. My father
viewed it as being a woman's job. I knew when I married somebody I
didn't want it to be that way, and I didn't start out our marriage
that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Jhung approves. ``I think if more men get involved, they'll find
their love life improving,'' she says. ``Maybe they need to put a
little Pledge behind their ears instead of slapping on the
aftershave.''
</P>
<P>
   She also advises that some women need to lighten up. ``Women in
general are just more caught up in details, and we certainly read
more decorating magazines (where) you never see the Sunday paper
strewn about the living room, or the laundry overflowing.''
</P>
<P>
   Poll respondent Jeanne Revis, 67, of Mountain Home, N.C., admits
she can't let go of making the beds just so, or of doing the
laundry. ``That's no-man's land, the laundry,'' she says. ``There
are probably those out there who could do an adequate job, but I've
yet to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jill Young Miller writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
