<HEADER>
A3232 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-VIOLENCE-KIDS-ART-NYT     09-13 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIOLENCE-KIDS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE HEARING FOCUSES ON KIDS, VIOLENCE, MOVIES AND PRESIDENTIAL
POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ADV: Photo _ NYT 20 _ is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Finally in this election year, the politicians
found something they can agree on: the entertainment industry
should be taken to task for marketing violent movies, music and
video games to children.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut, the Democratic candidate
for vice president, went before the Senate Commerce Committee on
Wednesday and said, ``This practice is outrageous, it is deceptive
and it has to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   An hour or so later, Lynne Cheney, whose husband, Dick, is the
Republican vice-presidential candidate, said the problem was even
worse than the marketing practices. ``There is a problem with the
product they market,'' she said, ``no matter how they market it.''
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the committee, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz.,
weighed in: ``While I do not begrudge anyone's honest profits, I do
not think they need to come at the expense of our children's
well-being.''
</P>
<P>
   But the presidential campaign was not far in the background.
Lieberman, for example, mentioned Vice President Al Gore several
times. If he and Gore are elected, he said, they intend to take
government action against the entertainment companies if they
persist in their marketing practices with children.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Cheney, the former chairwoman of the National Endowment for
the Humanities, noted pointedly that Gore and Lieberman planned to
attend a fund-raiser this week thrown by Harvey Weinstein,
co-chairman of Miramax, the movie studio.
</P>
<P>
   That led McCain to remark that the film industry had made $18
million in campaign contributions so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing on Wednesday was called to examine the report
released Monday by the Federal Trade Commission, which found that
the vast majority of adult-rated movies, recordings and electronic
games were marketed to underage customers.
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein and a dozen other movie executives refused to appear,
outraging McCain. ``Their hubris is stunning and serves to
underscore the lack of corporate responsibility so striking in this
report,'' the senator said.
</P>
<P>
   The chief lobbyist for the movie studios, Jack Valenti, did
testify. He said the movie executives had declined to come to
Washington ``not because they were ducking and running but because
they have other things on their schedules they could not erase.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain demanded that they come to a second hearing in two weeks,
and without making a specific commitment, Valenti suggested they
would comply.
</P>
<P>
   Valenti, who has been a prominent lobbyist for more than 30
years and who was a special assistant to President Lyndon B.
Johnson before that, is so comfortable at the witness table and so
familiar to the senators on the committee that their exchanges
seemed perfunctory, as if each side was making moves in a board
game.
</P>
<P>
   Valenti conceded that ``some marketing people'' seemed to have
``stepped over the line.'' He said there was no excuse, for
instance, in testing violent movies on focus groups of 10- and
12-year-olds, a practice the Federal Trade Commission cited, and
added: ``I can guarantee you that's not going to happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   On balance, Valenti said, the Congress ``should feel an immense
pride in this unique American creative asset and the daily
contributions of the movie and television industry to this nation's
art and commerce and the endurance of its responsibility to
American parents.''
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to the falling crime rate in recent years and said
that was good proof violent films did not cause crime.
</P>
<P>
   That was too much for Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C., who has been
in Washington since 1967, almost as long as Valenti. Rolling his
eyes, Hollings declared: ``To come here and have the unmitigated
gall to take credit for lowering the crime rate _ whoo-hee!''
</P>
<P>
   Valenti just smiled.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Cheney said the problem with popular culture was not merely
the marketing to children but the actual content of the movies and
music. The solution, she said, was not government regulation, which
would breach the First Amendment, but community pressure on the
entertainment companies.
</P>
<P>
   To make her case, she handed out to the committee members the
lyrics from ``Kill You,'' a song by Eminem, the rap and hip-hop
artist, filled with vulgarities, blood and rape. One line goes:
``Blood, guts, guns, cuts, knives, lives, wives, nuns, sluts.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Cheney said: ``It is despicable. It is horrible. This is
dreadful. This is shameful. This is awful.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she had written to female board members of Seagram Co.,
the parent company of Universal Music Group, which made the CD of
the song, and urged them to stop the distribution of such songs.
</P>
<P>
   Long after Mrs. Cheney had left the hearing, Danny Goldberg,
president of Artemis Records, became the first person of the day to
defend popular culture. ``Millions of people like it,'' Goldberg
said. ``In a free society, what do you do about it?''
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg suggested that one of the reasons young people were
disaffected with politics was that ``politicians and academics who
obviously have no real understanding of their culture make sweeping
generalizations about their entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not represented here today,'' Goldberg said. ``There
are no music fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Goldberg could not resist drawing the presidential campaign
into his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that there are many Americans who are offended by curse
words and don't want children exposed to them,'' he said.
``However, those people have no moral or legal right to impose such
a standard on my family or on the millions of other Americans who,
like George W. Bush, are comfortable with cursing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-00 1959EDT &QL; 
