<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3233 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-13 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: DANGER FROM WITHIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By BOB HERBERT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There were no safeguards. Although the facts were
clear, no one in the criminal justice system was willing to blow
the whistle on the unscrupulous prosecution of an honest cop named
Zaher Zahrey.
</P>
<P>
   High-ranking officials in the Police Department, the Brooklyn
district attorney's office and the office of the U.S. attorney for
the Eastern District ignored the overwhelming evidence that Zahrey
was innocent. Some exculpatory evidence was deliberately concealed.
And cops and prosecutors aggressively sought out and promoted the
outrageous lies of a violent predator named Sidney Quick, promising
him leniency and providing him with all sorts of favors, including
a conjugal visit in prison, in return for his perjured testimony
against Zahrey.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators were even willing to close their eyes to Quick's
apparent involvement in a murder, as long as he was willing to
testify against Zahrey.
</P>
<P>
   The question I'm asked most frequently about the Zahrey case is
why the Police Department was so anxious to nail this guy. I don't
know. Did some higher-up dislike him? Was there pressure to crack
down on some cop _ any cop _ in the aftermath of the Mollen
commission report? Rumors had circulated among cops about Zahrey's
possible involvement in criminal activity, but as far as I can tell
the source of those rumors was never determined. What is known is
that the cops out to get Zahrey, whose nickname was Zack, managed
to find a crank, a discredited former police informant, to parrot
the rumors.
</P>
<P>
   The crank's name was Carlos Torres. Torres was a drunk who was
known to be utterly unreliable. His own daughter told police he was
delusional, that he honestly believed he worked for the FBI and the
CIA. Torres had once been arrested when he showed up at a police
officer's funeral with a hand grenade.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone interested in the truth would have turned away from this
pathetic individual. But Robert Boyce, then a sergeant in internal
affairs, used Torres' nutty stories to help launch the official
investigation of Zahrey.
</P>
<P>
   Two things ultimately saved Zahrey _ the fine work of a fiercely
dedicated lawyer named Joel Rudin, and the intelligence and common
sense of a jury that could not be swayed by the government's
deceit.
</P>
<P>
   But what happens to those who are falsely targeted by police and
prosecutors and who don't have a Joel Rudin to fight for them?
</P>
<P>
   Rudin showed beyond any question that the case against Zahrey
had been crudely and deliberately manufactured. Every alarm bell in
the criminal justice system should have been clanging the very
first time anyone heard the tape of Boyce telling Quick, during an
interview in Sing Sing Prison: ``If you give me Zack, I'll drive
you home.''
</P>
<P>
   But what we found out, thanks to Rudin, is that prosecutors in
the office of the Brooklyn district attorney, Charles Hynes, were
concerned not with the outlandishness of the offer, but with the
fact that Boyce had been so careless as to tape it.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant District Attorney Theresa Corrigan was asked about the
propriety of the Sing Sing tape, in which Boyce told Quick he could
have a ``sweet deal'' if he could implicate Zahrey in a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Under oath, Corrigan said: ``There wasn't a discussion about
proper. I know at some point there was statements about there was
nothing wrong with this.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were discussions in Hynes' office about why Boyce and
a partner, Michael McWilliams, taped so much of their encounter
with Quick. Prosecutors made it clear they would have been happier
if only the comments damaging to Zahrey had been taped. And for a
while the tape was conveniently ``lost'' by the DA's office, and
would have remained buried except for the fact that Quick himself
blurted out to federal authorities that he had been taped at Sing
Sing.
</P>
<P>
   What is most frightening about this case is that it is not all
that unusual. The use of false testimony from criminal lowlifes to
manufacture cases against innocent defendants is far more
widespread than most Americans realize. The unusual aspects of this
case were the existence of the damning Sing Sing tape, and the fact
that the defendant was a cop.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
