<DOCNO> NYT20000913.0284 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3244 &Cx1f; kan-z
r b BC-STAFFORD-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      09-13 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAFFORD-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SURVIVOR' SKILLS PAY OFF IN WORKPLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hit show ``Survivor'' is old news by now _ except, perhaps,
to me. I never watched it. But I've read the postmortems with
morbid fascination.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, I've read about Richard, the $1 million winner
who survived the island head games better than 15 other
contestants.
</P>
<P>
   Articles describe Richard as (BEGIN ITALICS)evil, manipulative,
conniving, Machiavellian, smug, domineering, derisive, imperious
and Rasputinlike(END ITALICS), to reprint only the printable ones.
</P>
<P>
   But the appellation that puts Richard in a workplace column is
(BEGIN ITALICS)corporate trainer(END ITALICS). Before Richard
became famous for being naked and forming secret alliances, he
trained employees.
</P>
<P>
   Now there's a juicy coconut to milk.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate trainers, as most any corporate employee knows, are
hired to help improve morale, build teamwork, relieve stress and
teach leadership skills. Cynics are known to brand corporate
trainers as water-bearers for the management fad of the month club.
That may be true.
</P>
<P>
   But it would be unfair to leave it at that. I've sat through
many corporate training sessions, both in-house as an employee and
as research for my workplace and careers beat.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, I've heard much wise counsel about workplace
politics, co-worker relationships, career satisfaction and job
improvement. So I don't want every workplace trainer I've ever met
to take offense.
</P>
<P>
   I'm talking about Richard. And the training session I would most
like to hear him present is the one on ``building alliances.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard understood the power of alliances and used them to his
benefit better than anyone else on the island. And that, fellow
workers, is a template for the career path of many highly
successful business leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The altruistic, the capable, the personable were voted off the
island, victims of the Richard-made alliance that stood strong to
the end. The workplace parallel hardly needs explanation:
</P>
<P>
   Individual talent and nice people are prized in the workplace
but rarely get anywhere without successful, strategic alliances.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's a mentor-protege relationship, a strong team,
star-struck employees who will follow you anywhere, mutual respect
from co-workers who go way back, or a pure ``scratch my back, I'll
scratch yours'' pact, some kind of alliance is essential to advance
in the ranks.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, television viewers and fellow contestants hated
Richard. But he won the vote because of grudging admiration. The
others rewarded his ability to figure out the game and play it
better than anyone else, partly by fashioning the rules.
</P>
<P>
   Look back at the italicized words describing Richard. Do
employees want to work for someone described that way?
</P>
<P>
   Most workers would say of course not. But the fact is many do
work for Richardesque leaders. And if they don't, there's probably
a wannabe waiting in the wings, plotting entrance on stage.
</P>
<P>
   Cynical? Yes. Real world? You betcha.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean workers need to claw each other for the
spotlight. Not everyone wants it. But everyone should be very, very
aware of the alliances made to get there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-00 2003EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000913.0285 </DOCNO>
