<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3252 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      09-13 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH PRICES, LONG LINES, AND PEOPLE WILLING TO PAY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN SHAW AND BILL BRINK    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Jerry Patel, a retired coach from Orlando,
Fla., reached Sydney late Tuesday without Olympic tickets. Early
Wednesday he joined the long, last-minute lines for seats to the
Games.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets are selling at 50,000 a day as Australians, and visitors
like Patel, are rushing to join queues that stretch hundreds of
yards outside downtown agents.
</P>
<P>
   As he faced a three-hour wait on Wattle Street, Patel said he
was willing to pay $900 for good seats for Friday's opening
ceremony. A marshal told him there were only a ``handful'' left _
but there were several hundred potential buyers ahead of Patel.
</P>
<P>
   He was also a customer for seats for volleyball and table tennis
_ both of which he coached in India and the United States _ and
men's field hockey. The spring sunshine was warm _ and the forecast
is fair for the first Games days _ and Patel was unconcerned about
the long wait. ``I'll pay top dollar if I can get what I want,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Others in the line, mostly Australians, complained of delays,
box-office bungles and lack of suburban ticket outlets _ all
criticisms familiar to Sydney's Olympic ticket managers,
battle-scarred by 18 months of marketing problems, including
ill-fated attempts to hide reservations of seats for corporate
customers.
</P>
<P>
   With Games turnstiles about to start clicking, officials point
to the bottom line when customers, or reporters, point to the long
lines. Eighty percent of tickets have been sold, and Sydney is on
track to match or exceed Barcelona s 1992 record of 82 percent.
Through Wednesday, some 5.8 million of the 7,605,065 Olympic
tickets available had been sold, bringing overall ticket sales to
about $400 million (U.S.) so far.
</P>
<P>
   Juliet Crawford, a designer waiting to ask for gymnastics
tickets and willing to pay $240 for a family package, said, ``This
is a last-minute decision _ when I saw the torch on TV and the
Olympic flags in the streets, I got caught up in the emotion of it
all.`
</P>
<P>
   With lines getting longer, and time getting shorter, John
O'Neill, a ticketing spokesman, announced that some selling offices
would stay open 24 hours and express lanes would operate for
collection of pre-paid seats.
</P>
<P>
   Need a Ticket? How About Sailing?
</P>
<P>
   The sport with the highest percentage of tickets sold was
rhythymic gymnastics, according to figures released by the Sydney
organizing committee. Rhythmic gymnastics has sold 99 percent of
the 23,034 tickets available for five sessions at the 6,000-seat
pavilion at Olympic park. The triathlon, which has limited seating,
had sold out 98.48 of the 7,410 tickets available. Also popular in
this country mad about water sports was the swimming, with 98
percent of the nearly 200,000 tickets sold.
</P>
<P>
   The lowest number of tickets sold? Sailing, only 6,449 of the
21,000-plus available _ just 30 percent. Perhaps that was because
of the price tag _ the seats are on spectator boats in Sydney
Harbor _ with full-day packages ranging from $112 to $167. With the
lower package you get a seafood buffet; with the higher one, a
lunch hamper.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Men Gymnasts Seek to Upstage Women
</P>
<P>
   With his flamboyant gymnastics routine and attention-getting
tattoos, Blaine Wilson would be a difficult athlete to overshadow.
But Wilson and the other members of the U.S. men's team rank second
to their female counterparts in popularity, as well as Olympic
success, and Wilson wants that to change, beginning Saturday when
preliminary competition starts in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, we're proud of the girl's program,'' he said, ``but I
consider men's and women's gymnastics to be totally separate
sports. I don't do four events, I do six events. We're proud of
what they did in 1996, but we're out there doing our own thing this
year, and we're not going to be overshadowed by the women.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of people that want to talk about men's
gymnastics as compared to women's, but as I said before, would you
want to watch three hours on beam, or three hours crashing on high
bar. I'd rather watch high bar, personally. High bar's more
exciting. I think men's gymnastics is just a little bit more
exciting. But that's my opinion. And it will be up to the people at
home watching TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Bus Bungles
</P>
<P>
   First it was Sydney's trains that troubled Olympic organizers,
but now with the railroad mostly running on time it's the city's
buses that make officials anxious.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear the size of the task has been underestimated, we
need more drivers,'' conceded Olympics Minister Michael Knight, a
man not noted for apologies.
</P>
<P>
   The bus bungles, which involve rosters, routes and supply of
drivers and vehicles, are politically sensitive because they are
mostly affecting the passengers who can complain loudest _
international officials, foreign media and Olympic athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Bus managers are not yet coping well with special Olympic
demands and fleet expansion from 2,500 vehicles to 3,800. The 750
new drivers, new routes and changing schedules are causing delays
and no-shows on Olympic shuttles. These new services link the
athletes and media villages to training venues and press centers,
and ferry Games officials, national delegates and team coaches
between hotels, meetings and arenas.
</P>
<P>
   This week rookie drivers were blamed for leaving International
Olympic Committee President Juan Antonio Samaranch waiting on a
sidewalk, arriving three hours late to collect a group of
Aboriginal women artists, delaying the Australian shooting squad
two hours and causing the Australian water polo team to miss a
training session.
</P>
<P>
   Australian and IOC officials define the bus bungles as the usual
pre-Games ``teething problems.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-00 2007EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
