<DOCNO> NYT20000913.0288 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3253 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-REDSKINS-QBS-HNS &LR;      09-13 1672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REDSKINS-QBS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Redskins have potential for QB controversy
<TEXT>
<P>
   By RICHARD JUSTICE
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   ASHBURN, Va. _ Depending how the fickle winds of public opinion
are blowing, he is one of the most popular or most despised men in
the nation's capital. His every decision is analyzed, his private
life is not really private, and he faces an almost daily referendum
on his fitness for the job.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike the president, the quarterback of the Washington
Redskins doesn't have Secret Service protection or a guaranteed
four-year term.
</P>
<P>
   As the Redskins (1-1) began preparing for Monday night's game
with the Dallas Cowboys (0-2) at FedEx Field, Washington began a
balloting of another kind after Redskins quarterback Brad Johnson
threw four interceptions in a 15-10 loss at Detroit on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that at least two of the interceptions weren't his
fault. Never mind that Michael Westbrook, his best wideout,
suffered a season-ending knee injury in the third quarter. Never
mind that Johnson is coming off a terrific 1999 season, having led
the Redskins to their first playoff appearance in six years and
earning himself an invitation to the Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   And never mind that Johnson is a fellow of uncommon decency and
humility, one universally respected by both his teammates and
coaches.
</P>
<P>
   With the hated Cowboys coming to town, Johnson's job seemed up
for grabs. In the offseason, Redskins owner Daniel Snyder signed
free agent Jeff George to a four-year, $18.5 million contract. Now,
after a close defeat and four Johnson interceptions, the debate has
begun. The Washington Post posted a pick-the-quarterback ballot on
its Web site. The city's all-sports radio station became an open
forum on the Johnson-George debate. Some wondered when the ``Honk
if you love Jeff'' bumper stickers would be next.
</P>
<P>
   For all of its sophistication and feelings of self-importance,
Washington has for years taken the Redskins as seriously as Green
Bay or Dallas follows its NFL team. And no position on the team is
more scrutinized than quarterback. Many a family dinner has been
disrupted over the years as fathers and sons and husbands and wives
debated the merits of Redskins quarterbacks, probably beginning
with Sonny Jurgensen and Billy Kilmer's friendly competition in the
1970s. Later it would be Joe Theismann-Jurgensen, Doug Williams-Jay
Schroeder, Mark Rypien-Stan Humphries, Heath Shuler-Gus Frerotte
and Frerotte-Jeff Hostetler.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's Brad Johnson and Jeff George.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way it's going to be with a high-profile position
like quarterback,'' Redskins coach Norv Turner said in an interview
at Redskin Park. ``It's not an issue inside this building. Brad is
our quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner knows the Redskins brought this debate on themselves.
George's signing was the brainchild of Snyder, the 35-year-old
telemarketing executive who plunked down $800 million to buy the
franchise from the estate of the late Jack Kent Cooke 18 months
ago. Snyder had owned the franchise for about 10 minutes when he
announced he would like to win a Super Bowl very quickly _ like
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   He fired most of the front-office staff members after promising
to keep them. He became heavily involved in player personnel,
called a team meeting or two, and pretty much told Turner a playoff
appearance would be required for his continued employment.
</P>
<P>
   Turner caught a break. Just before Charley Casserly was
dismissed as general manager _ he is now GM of the Houston Texans _
he acquired Johnson from the Minnesota Vikings. For the first time
in six seasons in Washington, Turner had a bona fide quarterback,
and he rode Johnson's 24 touchdown passes to last year's NFC East
championship and a first-round playoff victory over Detroit. The
Redskins were eliminated by Tampa Bay in the second round, and
Snyder promptly announced this would be a Super Bowl-or-bust
season.
</P>
<P>
   This past summer, Snyder shelled out around $60 million in
signing bonuses to lure a who's who of free agents to Washington,
including Bruce Smith, Deion Sanders and Mark Carrier. Snyder also
signed George, almost guaranteeing there would be a quarterback
controversy. George was the NFL's third-rated passer last season.
Johnson was rated fifth.
</P>
<P>
   But remember, George hasn't exactly been regarded as a good
citizen during his 11 NFL seasons. The Redskins are his fifth team,
and although no one questions he has one of the league's best arms,
he has not always been viewed as a harmonious presence in the
locker room. ``Coach killer'' is the term one former teammate used
to describe George.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder might have relieved the problem a bit if he had extended
Johnson's contract. Instead, he allowed his Pro Bowl starter to
begin the year unsigned beyond this season _ a move tantamount to
daring him to have another good season. Some in the organization
speculated Snyder wanted George to play because Johnson was a
Casserly acquisition, and if the Redskins won the Super Bowl,
Casserly would have to get a chunk of the credit (he acquired most
of the rest of the team as well).
</P>
<P>
   Johnson sees it differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (Snyder) invested so much in this team doing well that
he wanted to have someone if something happened to me,'' he said.
``Jeff was out there, and they went out and got the best
quarterback they could.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Turner, who argued against the move, knows it could turn
out to be a smart decision if Johnson gets hurt. He points out that
history is against Johnson's starting every game for a second
consecutive season.
</P>
<P>
   Last year was the first time since 1996 Johnson made it through
an entire season without an injury. It is not just Johnson, either.
Two years ago, only five of the league's 31 starting quarterbacks
went the entire season without missing a game because of an injury.
Last season, only eight of the 31 starters went the distance.
</P>
<P>
   So if Johnson gets hurt, the Redskins have more than a backup.
They have the league's best backup.
</P>
<P>
   George stepped in for the injured Randall Cunningham last season
in Minnesota and went 9-3 as a starter, throwing for 23 touchdowns
and 2,816 yards. Despite his past problems, he still has managed to
compile an array of impressive numbers in his career _ 147
touchdown passes, 26,000 yards and 15 300-yard passing games.
</P>
<P>
   What he never has done is be part of a Super Bowl team, and even
though he has started 120 of his 126 career games, he said
Washington simply was too good an opportunity to pass up. He also
has gone out of his way not to make trouble, saying the best
situation is if he never plays a down this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to win championships. That's the only reason I
came,'' he said, calling the decision to sign with the Redskins ``a
no-brainer.''
</P>
<P>
   George once was viewed as the league's next great quarterback.
The Colts made him the No. 1 choice of the 1990 draft and hoped to
build a champion behind him. After four seasons of losing games and
enduring his tantrums, the Colts traded him to Atlanta in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   He was three games into his career with the Falcons when he got
into a sideline shouting match with coach June Jones. He was
suspended for four games and then released. He played two
relatively calm seasons in Oakland before joining the Vikings to be
Cunningham's backup.
</P>
<P>
   When Cunningham got hurt in the sixth game of last season,
George stepped in and led the Vikings to the playoffs. He threw
three touchdown passes in a playoff victory over the Cowboys and
four more in a loss to the St. Louis Rams. Still, after the season,
Vikings coach Dennis Green let George go and gave the starting job
to Daunte Culpepper.
</P>
<P>
   These days, George seems calmer, more thoughtful and certainly
less inclined to rock the boat.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a young age, I made some mistakes,'' he said. ``Obviously,
I went through things at an early age not a lot of people went
through. (But) I just turned 32. I'm a husband now, a dad. I'd like
to think that the best years are still ahead of me. Steve Young won
his first Super Bowl when he was 33. I feel young; my body feels
good; my arm feels great. Hopefully, I have another six, seven
years ahead of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson laughs off suggestions that he has been bothered by
George's presence or his unsettled contract situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at my history,'' Johnson said with a chuckle. ``I've been
with Rich Gannon, Warren Moon, Jim McMahon, Randall Cunningham,
Andre Ware, Charlie Ward you name it, I've had someone who'd either
won a Super Bowl or a Heisman or was going to the Hall of Fame.
There's always going to be someone else. I've been through all of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner, the man charged with orchestrating the show, emphasizes
that Johnson is the guy he is counting on to get the Redskins back
into the playoffs. But Johnson has stirred the controversy by not
playing particularly well in the first two games.
</P>
<P>
   Both Carolina and Detroit played soft pass defense to prevent
the Redskins from hitting the big plays that characterized last
season, when they scored 443 points, the third-highest total in
franchise history. As a result, Johnson has forced some throws into
coverage. His 67.8 quarterback rating is 25 percent below last
season's 90.0 rating, and he is ranked 24th among all NFL passers.
</P>
<P>
   But Turner said he remains convinced he can keep the swirling
waters of a quarterback debate away from Redskin Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``After visiting with Jeff before he signed with us, I found out
he's a very mature guy, very professional,'' Turner said. ``He's
been a great help to Brad and a plus in our locker room. But Brad
is our quarterback. All you have to do is go back and look at our
games a year ago and see what he did for this football team. He's
going to have more big games this year. I can say that a hundred
times, and some people are still going to ask when Jeff is going to
play. But I learned a long time ago you can't do anything about
what perceptions might be.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
