<HEADER>
A3255 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MALAYSIA-BANKS-ART-56     09-13 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALAYSIA-BANKS-ART-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERGERS OF MALAYSIAN BANKS APPEAR TO BE BACKFIRING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By WAYNE ARNOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SINGAPORE _ Efforts by Malaysia to strengthen its banking system
by forcing its 54 financial institutions to merge into just 10
appear to be backfiring, as concerns about government interference
revive doubt about the industry's health and the risks of investing
in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The banks had until Aug. 31 _ Malaysia's independence day _ to
complete their plans and gain tax incentives for doing so. They all
made it, but the deadline was followed by a drop in Malaysian
stocks, reflecting investor doubts about whether the hasty unions
represented workable matches.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of concern about the bank mergers was a deal
between two of them, reached the day of the deadline, that
undervalues the larger bank and overvalues the smaller one, which
also happens to be connected to one of the country's top
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   But the concern over the mergers also reflects further
exasperation among investors. Malaysia, some complain, seems to
prefer back-room economic deal making over a more open and
accountable system that enables banks and companies to find their
own solutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are big doubts in investors' minds as to whether
restructuring is driven by business sense or more by political
interest,'' said Cher Hung Jin, a fund manager at Daiwa Securities
in Singapore. Many investors wonder, he said, ``whether management
has a free hand to do what's good for shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   With stocks available for purchase from Wall Street to Shanghai,
``you have to offer things like transparency, earnings growth and
corporate governance,'' said Chong Yoon Chou, an investment
director at Aberdeen Asset Management in Singapore. ``In Malaysia's
case, they've lagged behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreign investors have felt frustrated with Malaysia _ and vice
versa _ since the Asian financial crisis of 1997-98. The country's
prime minister, Mahathir Mohamad, has blamed foreign speculators
for the crisis, pointing to their withdrawal of capital. In turn,
foreign investors blame him for turning the country into a global
pariah of finance.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for much of this year, Malaysia has been globalization's
gadfly. Despite refusing to let capital flow freely and vilifying
speculators, the country's economy grew, foreigners plowed money
in, and its stock market rose while a number of other markets in
Southeast Asia tumbled. Mahathir gained a following as an opponent
of Western free-market proselytizing, and the country has pushed
ahead with its own brand of financial reform, rejecting the
prescriptions of the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   But then in June, foreign investors began voting with their
feet. According to government statistics, they have withdrawn
roughly 4.4 billion ringgit, or $1.16 billion, from Malaysia in the
last three months.
</P>
<P>
   The economy appears to be doing fine. Exports and domestic
demand, combined with government spending and low interest rates,
are fueling economic growth that J.P. Morgan predicts will reach 10
percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the withdrawals is the fear that foreign investors
have of government policy changes that come without warning and
sometimes with disregard for investors' interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The perceived unfriendliness toward foreign investors is
stopping investments to Malaysia,'' said Chew Ping, an analyst at
Standard &AMP; Poor's in Singapore.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The story of Malaysia's bank merger plan is a case in point.
Cautious lending and stronger government oversight helped insulate
Malaysian banks from some of the weakness suffered by banks in
Indonesia and Thailand. Mahathir has in fact criticized Malaysian
banks as too prudent, depriving enterprises of funds.
</P>
<P>
   Yet most financial executives agree that there are too many
banks and that the government's plans to deregulate the industry
means that some of those banks must be merged with others. But in
July 1999, the central bank decreed that there be only six banks in
the country within eight weeks and told each bank who would be
taking over whom.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers were stunned. Smaller institutions in some cases were to
take over larger banks and weaker banks to take over stronger ones.
The shotgun engagements also threatened to reduce the financial
power of the country's economically dominant ethnic Chinese in
favor of its numerically dominant Malays.
</P>
<P>
   Three months later, there was an abrupt policy reversal. The
government capitulated to private lobbying by bankers and agreed to
let them find their own partners. This past February, the bankers
won approval to merge into 10 institutions by the end of this year.
A package of tax incentives was later thrown in for those who made
their merger plans final by the end of July. Progress toward
meeting the deadline was delayed by a group that fund managers say
is often ignored in Malaysia: Shareholders. But they were not just
any shareholders. Plans for the country's largest financial
institution, Malayan Banking, to take over a smaller one, Phileo
Allied Bank, stalled when a minority shareholder controlled by
Mahathir's son balked at the sale price. Such disputes led the
central bank to extend its deadline by a month, to the end of
August.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
