<HEADER>
A3256 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-VKILMER-FEATURE-LADN &LR;      09-13 0289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VKILMER-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   cc,78p3 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Val Kilmer has played many legendary heroes: Batman, The Saint,
Doc Holliday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But he seems particularly pleased by his latest good guy, whom
he humbly refers to as The Space Janitor.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Red Planet,'' an ecologically-themed, colonization-of-Mars
adventure set a few decades in the future, Kilmer is part of a
terraforming expedition to our celestial neighbor that runs into
all kinds of trouble, man-made and otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very selfless character who's in charge of the
maintenance of the ship,'' the actor explains. ``He's not on the
science team or the military side of it. He's a reluctant hero;
Harrison Ford would've enjoyed it a while ago. It's a great part,
though, and the whole style of the film is a fantastic balance
between subtle, small moments and large, epic-size adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   Which required epic-size locations. When a planned shoot in
Iceland didn't pan out, the production moved to blazing deserts in
Jordan and Australia. Outside temperatures reached well into three
digits and some cast members' space suit ventilation systems
malfunctioned.
</P>
<P>
   But for Kilmer, who spent childhood summers in Chatsworth and
currently resides in New Mexico, the heat was no problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I revelled in it,'' he admits. ``Whenever a Warner
Bros. executive who I knew from the `Batman' days would call the
set, he'd say `I bet you're the only one who's loving it out
there!' And it made an incredible difference that we were in such
rough terrain; it really gave us and the film the feeling that we
were on Mars.'' (Nov. 3) &QL; 
_ Bob Strauss &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-00 2010EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
