<HEADER>
A3261 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-WORK-VISAS-HNS &LR;      09-13 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORK-VISAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COALITION CALLS ON CONGRESS TO EASE IMMIGRATION RESTRICTIONS BEFORE
ADJOURNING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JENNIFER HOYT 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With Congress nearing the end of its session,
immigrant groups and a coalition of businesses are calling for
lawmakers to ease immigration restrictions before adjourning for
the year.
</P>
<P>
   The business coalition says the vibrant U.S. economy has created
a demand for unskilled and semi-skilled workers and the United
States must look to foreign labor to help fill job vacancies. The
national unemployment rate was 4.1 percent in August.
</P>
<P>
   The request to ease restrictions differs from legislation to
help overcome a shortage in the coming years of high-tech workers
for the nation's growing technology industry.
</P>
<P>
   To help fill future vacancies, lawmakers are pushing to increase
the number of temporary work visas for highly skilled workers from
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   But with Congress trying to wrap up and go home by Oct. 6 to
campaign for re-election, chances are considered slim for passage
of any major changes in U.S. immigration law.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats blame Republicans for blocking legislation supported
by the immigrants from passing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans don't want to deal with this stuff, it's
pretty clear,'' one congressional aide said. ``Everytime they've
had an opportunity to do something on these issues, they've chosen
not to. And unfortunately they control what comes to the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   At a rally at the Capitol on Wednesday, several hundred
immigrants pushed for passage of the Latino and Immigrant Fairness
Act, which would allow non-citizens who have lived in the United
States for at least 14 years to become permanent residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are modest measures designed to provide relief for folks
who have given so much to our country,'' California Rep. Xavier
Becerra said. ``They've paid their taxes, worked hard and raised
their families here in America. We must do the right thing by
moving these measures forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the legislation would:
</P>
<P>
   1) Allow immigrants who have been in the United States since
1986 to become permanent residents. Legislation approved that year
gave amnesty to immigrants who have lived here since 1972.
</P>
<P>
   2) Revise immigration law to allow non-citizens already in the
United States to remain here while waiting for the government to
declare them permanent residents. Since 1997, many immigrants have
been forced to leave the United States before they can receive
visas to become permanent residents.
</P>
<P>
   3) Ease restrictions on immigrants from Guatemala, El Salvador,
Honduras and Haiti to become permanent residents. The rules were
relaxed in 1997 for Nicaraguans and Cubans.
</P>
<P>
   Becerra was less than optimistic the legislation would pass this
year, but he did not rule it out. ``We're closer than we've ever
been if you compare it to, say, five years ago,'' he said, adding
that ``the clock always works against you.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure pushed by Becerra and the immigrants is supported by
Democrats and has the backing of President Clinton. One of the bill
sponsors is Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee, D-Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Also touting the bill is Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic
nominee for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing we lack is the clear signal from leadership
from the Republican side,'' Becerra said.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to lawmakers, the Essential Worker Immigration
Coalition wrote, ``There simply are not enough workers in the U.S.
to meet the demand of our strong economy, and we must recognize
that foreign workers are part of the answer.''
</P>
<P>
   John Gay, co-chairman of the coalition and senior director of
governmental affairs for the American Hotel and Motel Association,
said industries have tried to recruit American workers and programs
such as welfare-to-work have been successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's been great, but it clearly has not been
enough,'' he said. ``We're looking at a serious labor shortage in
several areas of the country right now that's not getting any
better.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
