A3262 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-LEDER-FEATURE-LADN &LR;      09-13 0292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEDER-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   cc,78p3 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After winning Emmys for directing ``ER,'' Mimi Leder logically
figured that &QL;
</P>
<P>
   her film career would be marked by equally compelling human
dramas.
</P>
<P>
   A ``Peacemaker'' and ``Deep Impact'' later, that may finally
come to pass with ``Pay It Forward.'' The Good Samaritan story
certainly has the acting talent to pull it off -- Oscar-winners
Kevin Spacey and Helen Hunt, and cinema's most admired child star,
Haley Joel Osment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This felt like I was going home,'' says Leder, a
second-generation, Valley-raised industry veteran. ``It wasn't an
unusual thing for me to do at all. It's where I began, and I always
look at material and storytelling from a dramatic point of view.
It's how I always thought my first movie would be; not my third.''
</P>
<P>
   Leder says she wasn't intimidated by her high-powered cast --
even when the formidable Spacey won his second Academy Award in the
middle of the production schedule. After all, the filmmaker could
claim her own significant milestone: ``Deep Impact'' is the
highest-grossing feature film ever directed by a woman.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that also adds another layer of expectation to a
movie that definitely has a lot to live up to.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just tried to tell the best story we could,'' Leder shrugs.
``I tried to keep it as real as we could. We all dove into the
material ferociously, tried to make every moment honest, and these
people became their characters to me. I didn't look at them as
people with statues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I just want to put it out there. As proud as I am of
having made this movie, I'm trying not to have any expectations.''
(Oct. 20) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
