<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE DOESN'T SAY MUCH AS HE GETS HIS PICTURE TAKEN AT SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT3 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Showing no desire to steal attention from Gov. George
W. Bush's troubles, Vice President Al Gore went about the hard work
of not making news Wednesday as he manufactured gauzy pictures in a
Maine high school and avoided the missteps that have tormented his
rival in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   To the extent possible, Gore and his aides are essentially
trying to run out the clock during this stage of the campaign,
letting Bush struggle on his own while Gore emphasizes and
re-emphasizes policy positions that seem to be touching a chord.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Gore campaign plans to turn its full attention to
debates with Bush, which will be the subject of a critical meeting
between the campaigns on Thursday, and to battling the
better-financed Republicans on the airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   And so Wednesday, Gore came to Lewiston High School in southern
Maine, where he devoted most of the day to a series of
photo-friendly encounters that conveyed his concern about
education. As he did so, his aides drew attention to a letter
written by two Democratic senators asking the Federal
Communications Commission to investigate a Republican television
commercial that, they alleged, may have violated a 1974 federal
rule against subliminal advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said nothing on that topic Wednesday, leaving the task to
Sens. Ron Wyden of Oregon and John Breaux of Louisiana. The
senators wrote the FCC to express concern about a Republican
National Committee ad that shows the word ``rats'' in a single
frame.
</P>
<P>
   David Fiske, a spokesman for the FCC, said that the request
would be studied, but that the commission would only have the
authority to sanction stations that knowingly broadcast an illegal
ad, not the political strategists who produced it.
</P>
<P>
   Gore flew from Maine to Boston on Wednesday afternoon for a
rally with his running mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman, and a
fund-raiser expected to collect close to $2 million for the
Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But the day's primary images came from the Gore campaign's
eight-hour occupation of Lewiston High. Throughout the day, Secret
Service agents patrolled the corridors along with hall monitors,
and bomb-sniffing dogs examined the backpacks of slouching
students. Gore's speeches were interrupted repeatedly by intercom
announcements from the principal's office, and the vice president
sampled Lewiston's cafeteria cuisine, downing two cheeseburgers and
some fries.
</P>
<P>
   It was the seventh ``school day'' of Gore's campaign. As always,
he spent the night before at the home of teachers, in this case
Donald and Susan Jalbert, both of whom teach at the school. Gore
arrived at 1 a.m., stayed up talking with the Jalberts and their
two children until 2, and then rose at 6:15 a.m. to eat the
blueberry scones that Mrs. Jalbert had been baking since 4:30.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the day was spent in a succession of meetings _ with
parents, school counselors, teachers and students. He provided
research help to the juniors in Joan M. Macri's American history
class as they scanned textbooks and Internet sites for the answers
to questions about the Constitution and political history. He
instructed Seth Morin, a 16-year-old junior, how to find an Elvis
Presley letter to Richard Nixon on the National Archives Web site.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, cameras recorded the scenes. If there was a slip
in the stagecraft, it was only that Gore, in his meeting with
teachers, allowed himself to be photographed while seated beneath a
picture labeled ``prehistoric man.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Gore devoted a midday session with students and teachers in the
library to promote his plans for making college more affordable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming out of high school, kids in middle-class families are
under a lot of pressure, and their parents are under a lot of
pressure,'' Gore said. ``Many of them have no idea where they're
going to get the money to pay tuition.'' Gore's proposals include
increasing an existing federal tax deduction so that families could
deduct 28 percent of annual tuition payments _ up to $10,000 in
tuition for each child _ instead of the current 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That proposal has been criticized by the Bush campaign because
it would only assist those who pay taxes, and would thus exclude
many low-income families. Gore's aides said that those families are
already eligible for a variety of federal college grants.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also would create savings accounts that would allow parents
to make pre-tax contributions that would be matched by the federal
government and could be withdrawn without penalty to pay for
college tuition. And he would create new tax-free accounts, similar
to 401(k) accounts, that would permit individuals and their
employers to put money away for adult learning and training.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
