<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACC-NCSTATE0914-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Under new coach Amato, N.C. State has shaped up and is 2-0
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Something weird, wild and, well, amazing is going on at North
Carolina State.
</P>
<P>
   The Wolfpack football team, with an entirely new coaching staff,
with only four returning starters on offense, without All-ACC
quarterback Jamie Barnette for the first time in four seasons, is
shaking up college football.
</P>
<P>
   Give some credit to Chuck Amato, the new coach. The former FSU
assistant head coach directed the defensive line and then
linebackers for Bobby Bowden's program for 18 years and earned his
reputation as a defensive specialist.
</P>
<P>
   But with Amato's defensive experience, how to explain N.C.
State's sudden offensive surge? The Wolfpack is averaging 39.5
points a game with a freshman at quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Amato first made headlines when he hired his coaching staff. His
assistants' combined salaries totaled more than $1 million; their
combined years of experience is more than 200. One of those
assistants is Norm Chow, who orchestrated Brigham Young's offense
for the past 24 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Then he signed Philip Rivers out of Athens, Ala., a 6-foot-5,
221-pound quarterback who was coached by his father and named
Alabama player of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Amato, who looks like a weight-lifter but never has lifted
weights, then issued an ultimatum. His team was fat and out of
shape, and he wanted it lean and mean. To facilitate, he installed
a ``Belly Board'' in the weight room. The Belly Board consisted of
more than 20 frontal shots of the players without their shirts and
their bellies exposed. When they met his weight requirements, they
got to remove the embarrassing snap shots from the board. The
result was a net team loss of 700 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Everything he has done seems to have worked. The Wolfpack opened
the season with two wins, a double-overtime victory over Arkansas
State and a 41-38 come-from-behind win at Indiana last week after
trailing 21-3. They host SMU on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Amato isn't fooled by his team's 2-0 start. ``If you looked at
the films, you wouldn't say that we are doing this well,'' he said.
``It shows you how important winning a close game is. We're that
close to being 0-2.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference-maker has been Rivers. The savvy quarterback has
completed 60 of 109 passes for 798 yards and 8 touchdowns. He leads
the nation in total offense and is third in completions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a little bit different,'' Rivers said. ``Last year,
you're looking at it in high school in your own local newspaper.
Now, you're leading the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
