<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SOCCER0914-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. men find positives in 2-2 tie with Czech Republic
</P>
<P>
   By Wendy Parker
</P>
<P>
   CANBERRA, Australia - The best way to counter an occasionally
shaky defense is to keep pushing _ and don't let up.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. men's soccer coach Clive Charles used a football term to
describe how his offensive-minded club set the pace early in a 2-2
draw with the Czech Republic in its Group C opener Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our best defense was the fact that we attacked and played in
their end a good part of the game,'' Charles said.
</P>
<P>
   When the Americans were tested on the back line, however, they
showed where they are most vulnerable. The U.S. twice lost leads,
with the Czechs equalizing fast both times.
</P>
<P>
   The toughest blow was a penalty kick called against American
captain Chad McCarty, who brought down Marek Heinz from behind two
steps inside the box in the 52nd minute. Lukas Dosek converted the
penalty kick, and the U.S. settled for one, instead of three points
in what figured to be its toughest group match.
</P>
<P>
   For the U.S. men, who never have advanced out of group play in
the Olympics, squandering such a chance is a significant letdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``A part of me is disappointed,'' Charles said. ``But the
players were very disappointed, and that's what made me feel
good.''
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the fast-paced American striking trio was
ex-Parkview High standout Josh Wolff, who scored a goal and
assisted on the other. Wolff barely missed a marvelous chance to
get the winner in the 63rd minute when he nearly finished off a
superb throw almost the length of the field from goalkeeper Brad
Friedel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pulled away, and the ball was in the air and came right at
me,'' Wolff said. ``I should have put that one away. It could have
won us the game.''
</P>
<P>
   A replay showed that he might have been bumped off the ball just
as he neared the Czech goal. But Brazilian referee Carlos Eugenio
Simon said to play on, just as he did when Wolff took a dive with
two minutes to play.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans will need to equal their debut performance against
medal hopeful Cameroon here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we surprised them with the way we came out early, with
a lot of confidence,'' Wolff said. He is a third-year pro enjoying
his best season for the Chicago Fire of Major League Soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Wolff assisted on the first goal on a cross that Chris Albright
tapped home for a 1-0 lead early in the first half. Then Wolff
scored on a feed from Conor Casey just before the end of the first
half. Both goals were triggered by alert long balls from defender
Jeff Agoos.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were getting all our defensive formations no matter what
we tried,'' Czech coach Karel Bruckner said. ``Nothing was working.
Their fast, constant penetration of our defense was very
impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. outshot the Czechs 13-8 and put eight on goal to three
for the opponents. After Wolff's dramatic near-miss, Agoos drilled
a volley that Czech keeper Jaroslav Drobny parried away before
turning aside a point-blank attempt from Casey.
</P>
<P>
   ``We earned some respect out there,'' Wolff said. ``Now, we have
to go out and duplicate it in the next game and show it's not a
fluke.''
</P>
<P>
   Other games
</P>
<P>
   Cameroon 3, Kuwait 2: At Brisbane, Lauren Etame Mayer scored
with five minutes left. Nicolas Alnoudji gave Cameroon the lead in
the 36th minute. Patrick Mboma connected in the 75th and Mayer
scored the winner off a setup by Patrice Abanda. Italy 1, Australia
0: Andrea Pirlo, frustrated by the crossbar and a goal-line
clearance, finally scored off the inside of the goalpost with nine
minutes to go. A packed stadium of 93,252 at Melbourne Cricket
Ground went home disappointed, although the hosts had plenty of
scoring opportunities. Nigeria 3, Honduras 3: At Adelaide, Nigeria,
the defending Olympic champion, scored twice in the final 13
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Agali scored in the 77th and Yakubu Ayegbeni in the 89th,
nullifying a two-goal performance by Honduras' David Suazo. Bright
Igbinadolor had tied the match for Nigeria in the 50th.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
