<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RITALIN-LAWSUITS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUITS CHARGE CONSPIRACY TO EXPAND RITALIN USE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.J., Texas, Miss.)   By BARRY MEIER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lawyers involved in class-action lawsuits against the tobacco
industry, gun makers and health maintenance organizations filed two
lawsuits Wednesday against another target, the widely used drug
Ritalin.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits, filed in federal courts in California and New
Jersey, charge that Novartis Pharmaceuticals Corp., the drug's
manufacturer, and the American Psychiatric Association, a
professional group, conspired to create a market for Ritalin and
expand its use.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a decade, Ritalin has been increasingly prescribed
for children who have been given a diagnosis of attention deficit
disorder or attention deficit hyperactivity disorder. That trend
has prompted debate among scientists, psychiatrists and government
officials over whether children are receiving too much medication
or are being given incorrect diagnoses of behavioral disorders.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of both Novartis Pharmaceuticals, a unit of Novartis
AG, and the American Psychiatric Association said that they had not
seen the lawsuits and so could not comment on them.
</P>
<P>
   But representatives of the groups said the accusations sounded
similar to those in a class-action lawsuit brought earlier this
year against them in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, Novartis said that Ritalin, also known by its
chemical name methylphenidate, had been used safely and effectively
in thousands of children for more than 40 years and that it was the
most studied drug used for attention deficit hyperactive disorder.
</P>
<P>
   The psychiatric association called the accusations in the Texas
suit ``groundless'' and an ``opportunistic attack on the scientific
process that underlies this effort.''
</P>
<P>
   The new lawsuits seek to halt what they call unlawful practices
and ask that profits from the drug sales be returned to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   One of those bringing the latest lawsuits is Richard Scruggs, a
lawyer from Pascagoula, Miss., who represented dozens of states in
actions brought in recent years against cigarette makers. This
year, Scruggs also filed suits against several HMO's charging that
they had defrauded consumers by failing to provide them with
treatments.
</P>
<P>
   John Coale, a Washington lawyer who is also involved in the
lawsuits, said the litigation was brought because Novartis and the
psychiatric group promoted the idea that large numbers of children
had attention deficit disorder and attention deficit hyperactivity
disorder as a way of expanding the market for Ritalin.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were giving this stuff away like candy,'' Coale said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House this year announced a major effort to reverse a
sharp increase in the number of preschool children using Ritalin,
Prozac and other powerful psychiatric drugs. The trend had been
reported in The Journal of the American Medical Association.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-00 2012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000913.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3269 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-2     09-13 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE JUKEBOX COMES HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By MICHEL MARRIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mention the word jukebox and most of us imagine some garish,
pot-bellied machine that spins a few records (or compact discs) for
a handful of coins.
</P>
<P>
   No more. The new jukeboxes, born of a fledgling marriage of
traditional audio and newfangled computer technology, are intended
for home use and play music in MP3 and other digital formats. They
come in different sizes, shapes and prices (none cheap), but all
are designed to store or sort large collections of music for easier
playback. They are being aimed at music lovers with crates full of
CDs or hard drives overloaded with music files.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody really needs any of these players (except perhaps some
traveling, tech-forward DJ). That, apparently, hasn't stopped their
makers from introducing more and more of these hybrid players in
recent months. Of all the models I have seen and tried, at least
one of them could be hard to resist, if you have the cash.
</P>
<P>
   The AudioReQuest ARQ1 Digital Music System by ReQuest
Multimedia, at $800, provides a place to store and play back an
entire music collection. The device, which is crammed with PC
technology including a 17.3-gigabyte hard drive, is about the size
of a large multidisc CD player. It is designed primarily to copy
songs from CDs (it can also copy from cassette tapes and vinyl
records), translate their tunes into MP3 files, store them and play
them back. It can also play individual CDs.
</P>
<P>
   The AudioReQuest, which was introduced this year, can hold up to
320 hours of music if the songs are recorded at the near-CD-quality
bitrate of 128 kilobits per second. The device is capable of much
higher-quality recordings, but at the expense of holding fewer
songs. No matter what rate is chosen, translating CDs into MP3
files is a bit of a chore. Recording a 55-minute CD at 128 kbps,
which is recommended, took 19 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Using a standard computer keyboard, which is not included, and
plugging the system into a conventional television set for a
monitor, I was able to create playlists of my favorite songs. The
AudioReQuest also permits users to quickly locate music on its hard
drive by song, album and artist via the device's wireless remote
control. The remote is more than a handful, mostly because it has
too many buttons, including a keyboard that is close to useless _
the tiny keys are laid out in alphabetical order, forcing you to
hunt and peck.
</P>
<P>
   The device comes with cables to make connecting the unit to a
PC, a PC monitor or TV very simple. But to take full advantage of
the AudioReQuest's best features, you need to link it to a home
stereo system, an Internet-linked PC and a television set. But the
length of its cables are too short to connect everything together
at once.
</P>
<P>
   Once the music is placed on the AudioRequest hard drive _
existing MP3 files in a personal computer can also be imported into
the device _ playback of the music files is remarkably good. This
machine is expensive and may be a harbinger of the future of home
audio, but it is easy enough to resist buying right now.
</P>
<P>
   The only device I tested that is truly tempting was made by
Creative, a Singapore-based technology company that was an early
innovator in PC sound. Its Nomad Jukebox, introduced this month, is
a portable music player about the size of a portable CD player, but
heavier, and holds the equivalent of 150 CDs of music.
</P>
<P>
   The Nomad Jukebox has a modest-size LCD screen and a smattering
of buttons on its contoured face and a headphone jack on its right
side. But the device's resemblance to a CD player stops there. The
Nomad Jukebox doesn't play CDs. What it does, once linked to a PC
or Mac by way of a USB cable, is store more than 100 hours of MP3
music files on its six-gigabyte, shock-resistant hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   The Nomad Jukebox will also store up to 2,600 hours of
spoken-word files as well as store and read multiple sound file
formats, including WMA and WAV.
</P>
<P>
   The Creative PlayCenter 2 software for the Nomad was easy to
install on a standard PC, but not always the easiest to use. I ran
into a few glitches in setting up the encoding, often called
ripping, of scores of CDs I eventually loaded into the Nomad
Jukebox. Once I got underway, each CD took about 10 minutes to be
turned into MP3 files and moved into the jukebox.
</P>
<P>
   Once the music was in the Nomad Jukebox, its sound, heard on a
set of included headphones, was very good. There are spatialization
effects that can make, for example, the Red Hot Chili Peppers sound
as if they were performing in an empty recital hall. And the
jukebox reverb, bass and treble controls were good. Best of all was
the easy access to all the music, which can be called up by
playlists, artist, album or style.
</P>
<P>
   The player also lets you search for a song by typing in a few
letters of the title. But typing is more like pecking, using a
couple of tiny buttons. Another downside is that for a device that
is touted to be so mobile, its battery life is extremely limited. I
never got more than four hours of continuous play from four
rechargeable nickel-hydride batteries.
</P>
<P>
   At $500, the Nomad Jukebox may seem expensive, but compared with
equally costly MP3 players, all of which have only a fraction of
the storage capacity, it seems like a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   That could not be said for the Escient TuneBase 100. It is a
$3,000, 15-pound set-top box, 3 and a half inches tall and 17
inches wide. The TuneBase plugs into an Internet connection, a CD
changer holding 100 or more CDs and a television, or an optional
$2,000 LCD touch-screen controller.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, to use this device, you can already have a CD
changer with at least 100 slots (more expensive models come with
much larger CD changers). Then, presumably you have a lot more on
your mind other than remembering where ``James Brown Live at the
Apollo'' is in slot 191, or that Joni Mitchell's ``Misses'' is the
20th CD out of 300 ready to play.
</P>
<P>
   So, since you obviously are the sort of person who spends a lot
on music, you might buy the TuneBase, too. Here's what it will do
for you:
</P>
<P>
   It will list every CD loaded into a changer. Drawing upon PC
technology, the TuneBase locates a unique identification code and
automatically goes online to the Compact Disc Database, which
contains all the information a CD would ordinarily display on its
cover, like the name of the artist, each song title, album cover
art and liner notes. That information is then downloaded into the
TuneBase's hard drive and shown on any display screen connected to
the system.
</P>
<P>
   All of that is done at PC speed and usually works without a
hitch. Sometimes the database doesn't have any information on an
obscure CD. But usually the result is a real-time listing, by name
of artist, genre or song, of every CD loaded into the system. Then
you can create a playlist and hear the songs you like in the order
you like.
</P>
<P>
   And with additional CD changers, either large and expensive ones
or daisy-chaining multiple changers, the TuneBase can handle more
than 4,500 CDs. A similar $7,500 system by Escient called PowerPlay
works with DVD movies as well as CDs. The number of people who have
enough DVDs to warrant a $7,500 sorter is probably even smaller
than the number of people who want a $3,000 CD sorter, but
technology marches on.
</P>
<P>
   The most time-consuming part of the process is the physical
loading of your CD collection into the changer and the wait for the
TuneBase to read, retrieve and remember all of the music data it
requires to operate. But if you give it a weekend, the TuneBase can
slice and dice your music collection into favorite playlists or
call it up at the touch of a remote-control button to display and
play any piece of music you have in the system.
</P>
<P>
   Note that the TuneBase does not actually play the CDs. It has
neither speakers nor amplifiers. Your music system has to be all
set up and ready to go. What it does, for $3,000, is store,
identify and organize the tunes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
