<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3279 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-DIKE14-COX     09-13 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIKE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Eliot Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The 40-foot dike around Lake Okeechobee leaks
and needs a $180 million overhaul, U.S. Army Corps of Engineers
officials told local emergency managers Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The corps plans to submit an $80-million proposal in the 2002
federal budget for the first part of the repair job, a shoring up
of the 22 miles of levee from Port Mayaca to Belle Glade, said Ed
Middleton, Chief of Engineering and dam safety officer for the
corps' Jacksonville district. If the money is approved, work would
start that year and probably would take about four years. Middleton
explained the project Wednesday at the monthly meeting of Palm
Beach County's Local Emergency Management Network, gathered at the
county's Emergency Operations Center.
</P>
<P>
   There is virtually no chance of the dike breaching and sending a
deadly wall of water onto the 40,000 people living around the lake,
Middleton said. But the possibility can't be ruled out, he said,
and the danger grows greater the more leaks show up in the dike,
which rings the lake for about 120 miles.
</P>
<P>
   The problems so far have shown up only on the lake's east side,
from around Okeechobee to Moore Haven, Middleton said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the uncertainty, Michael Loehr, an administrator with
the Florida Department of Emergency Management, said at Wednesday's
meeting that he'd probably suggest an evacuation of cities along
the lake if it were high to brimming and a major hurricane was
aiming at it.
</P>
<P>
   The corps has had anecdotal evidence of leaks for decades and
has documented seepage and stability problems since 1984, but
undertook a $4 million survey after heavy rains in 1995 and 1998
sent the lake level past 18 1/2 feet and sparked major leaks,
Middleton said. The corps considers the dike at dangerous levels
for failure at about 21 feet; its highest recorded level was 18.9
feet in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   There's no danger of flooding right now. Following a recent run
of low rainfall, the lake stood Wednesday about 11.8 feet above sea
level.
</P>
<P>
   Water is not squirting, but rather seeping out at various spots.
But what is causing the most damage is the dirt and rock the water
carries with it, undermining the walls of the dike, which was built
over four decades to protect the Glades from a repeat of the
catastrophic 1928 hurricane. That storm killed as many as 3,000
people when the 6-foot dike then surrounding the lake gave way.
</P>
<P>
   The corps does not believe the lake would spill over the top,
but the higher the water, the more it pushes against the base of
the dike. In some cases, water actually seeps into the ground under
the pyramid-shaped dike, undermining its foundation and causing
water and sand to boil out of the ground sometimes hundreds of feet
from the dike.
</P>
<P>
   The repair work would involve adding a 5-foot-thick blanket of
rock and other fill that, like a coffee filter, would let any
leaking water pass through while holding in the materials that form
the dike, Middleton said.
</P>
<P>
   EliotKleinberg(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
