<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3280 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-DRAGONCON-ARRESTED14-     09-13 0167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRAGONCON-ARRESTED14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DragonCon founder charged with child abuse
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The founder of DragonCon, a popular sci-fi and pop
culture convention, is in the Gwinnett County jail without bond on
child sex abuse charges.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Eliot Kramer, 39, of Duluth, Ga., is scheduled to appear
in court this afternoon for a bond hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Kramer is charged with aggravated child molestation of a
13-year-old boy who was sodomized in July, according to the
criminal arrest warrant.
</P>
<P>
   His attorney, James Altman, of Atlanta, said only that:
``Everybody's presumed innocent until proven guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year's convention in downtown Atlanta drew an estimated
40,000 who share a love of Star Wars, Star Trek, comic books and
horror flicks.
</P>
<P>
   The case remains under investigating and additional charges
involving more victims are possible, prosecutor Nancy DuPree said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-00 2015EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000913.0306 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3283 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-POLAND-ELECTION14-COX     09-13 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLAND-ELECTION14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Polish native amazed by homeland's transformation
 &HT;    By Keith Graham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In many ways, the Poland of today is ``a different country''
from the one Hubert Tworzecki left in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   After 44 years of Communist rule ending with the free elections
of 1989, the country has moved rapidly toward an economy led by
private enterprise, now accounting for about 70 percent of Polish
jobs. After wrenching market reforms in the early '90s, growth has
averaged around 6 percent a year since mid-decade.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign investors have pumped $40 billion into Polish industry.
Wages now average around $400 a month, compared with $50 a month in
neighboring Ukraine. Stores are filled with consumer goods _ to the
point today's young people ``can't remember the endless queues for
the most basic necessities of life,'' Tworzecki says.
</P>
<P>
   And in small ways _ for instance, the fresh paint on houses _
the sense of newfound prosperity is tangible. ``The place looks
much more tidy and well taken care of than was the case just a
little while ago,'' Tworzecki says.
</P>
<P>
   This different world fascinates Tworzecki, an Emory University
political scientist who continues to keep a keen eye on his
homeland's development. On a recent day, he sat in his office on
the Atlanta campus analyzing the latest polling figures for the
upcoming Polish presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Televised campaigning is just beginning but the race for the
Oct. 8 election looks all but finished. Incumbent Aleksander
Kwasniewski, an ex-Communist turned social democrat, continues to
enjoy high approval ratings and is far ahead of his main rivals _
centrist technocrat Andrzej Olechowski and Marian Krzaklewski,
leader of the Solidarity bloc, which controls the reigning
coalition in Poland's parliamentary government. Barring a major
turn of events, the rivals' only hope _ an unlikely one _ is to
force Kwasniewski into a runoff.
</P>
<P>
   Solidarity, rooted in the pre-1989 anti-Communist coalition, has
controlled parliament since 1997, but its members are divided and
the party is the target of criticism from Poles concerned about
unemployment and a shrinking social net. Besides the presidential
race, Solidarity also faces the prospect of crashing badly in the
more important parliamentary elections next year.
</P>
<P>
   The party's leaders had hoped that recently approved legislation
to turn over state-owned housing and other property to ordinary
Poles would help. But polls showed voters sharply divided on the
plan, and Kwasniewski _ saying it would throw property rights into
disarray _ vetoed it this week.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Polish leader best known to Americans, Lech
Walesa, wallows far behind in the 13-candidate presidential race.
Walesa, who won the Nobel Peace Prize for his efforts to create a
free Poland, was elected president in 1990 but lost to Kwasniewski
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Walesa is still respected as a historical figure, Tworzecki
says. ``But people wish he would stay as a historical figure and
not get involved with politics. ... Walesa was a great fighter but
he was not a very good manager.''
</P>
<P>
   For all its progress since it swept the Communists from power in
1989, Poland today still faces serious problems. At the
governmental level, a need to strengthen its court system and
efforts to stamp out corruption rank high on the list, Tworzecki
said.
</P>
<P>
   Other issues are perhaps predictable outgrowths of the
transition from communism. Some people have fared better than
others. And a sizable pool of people are still stuck in the
mentality that assumes the state will provide for them.
</P>
<P>
   To various degrees, attitudes toward the Communist era remain a
major fault line. But the current interpretations of history are
not simple ones.
</P>
<P>
   Even Walesa, who led the fight for liberty and democracy, now
cautions against both ``a monopoly of Solidarity'' and unfettered
capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   The one-time shipyard electrician turned freedom fighter
recently ripped the current version of Solidarity as ``a debased
bureaucracy'' run by ``third-rate militants'' who ``would do
anything to keep their place.''
</P>
<P>
   Capitalism, too, he said, ``must change its face. ... At the
dawn of the 21st century, capitalism needs some regulation. God has
not given everyone the same things, and the markets must be
controlled and regulated to be complementary so everyone can profit
from this.''
</P>
<P>
   Walesa might not be making a dent in the polls, but he is not
alone in his reassessment.
</P>
<P>
   Among people who express ``various degrees of fondness'' for the
Communist era, Tworzecki says, are those who recognize the
oppression and lack of freedom of the period but who also feel some
pride in post-World War II Polish reconstruction efforts and in the
social and economic advancement that took place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Communism in Poland after 1956 was quite distinct from its
variants in Russia or Czechoslovakia or East Germany or Romania,''
Tworzecki says. The Communist leadership was not as repressive as
that in some countries nor as paternalistic as others, and it
allowed a certain amount of access to the West and to Western
goods.
</P>
<P>
   While interpretations of that era's history likely will continue
to influence Polish politics for some time, no one expects Poland
to turn the clock back.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy percent of Poland's trade now is with the European
Union, compared with only 10 percent with countries of the former
Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   The Poland that was an anchor of the Warsaw Pact is now a member
of NATO _ a step that was even more important than the still
pending effort to join the European Union, Tworzecki says. ``Among
the (new) countries that joined NATO, Polish opinion was the most
supportive'' of the air campaign to end Serb ethnic cleansing in
Kosovo last year, he says. ``The balance of opinion was we are in
it now and we have to do our share.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's Poland is ``a trusted ally'' of the United States, he
adds, and a nation whose ``relations with the U.S. are quite
exemplary'' on all fronts.
</P>
<P>
   And even the intricacies of the election illustrate a larger and
far more dramatic change: In the past decade, once-Communist Poland
has rapidly transformed itself into a country where, as Tworzecki
puts it, ``the fundamentals of democracy are firmly in place.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
