<SLUG> BC-U.N.-SOVERNEIGNTY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADA TRIES TO DEFINE LINE BETWEEN HUMAN AND NATIONAL RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind.)  (Eds: Legwaila Joseph Legwaila in 9th graf is cq) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Secretary-General Kofi Annan shocked many
nations last year by arguing that leaders who abuse citizens can no
longer escape reckoning by hiding behind national sovereignty. Now
Canada is about to announce that it has asked a panel to write the
first concrete guidelines for making the tough calls between human
rights and national rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably the most important debate that we face at this
juncture,'' Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy said Wednesday. In an
interview, he said the divide between those who say prominence
should be given to international standards of human rights and
those who hold to ``more classic nation-state interests'' has
widened and sharpened.
</P>
<P>
   Some, but not all, the nations most strongly opposed to
international intervention aimed at saving people _ or sometimes
saving democratic institutions _ are in the developing world. There
is also a strong lobby in the United States, reflected in the
Republican leadership in Congress, against any erosion of the
principle of national sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   The debate, however has been impossible to avoid, diplomats say.
From the creation of the United Nations in 1945 and throughout the
Cold War, the protection of national interests was almost
inevitably prominent, Axworthy said, adding: ``Our take has been
that since the end of the Cold War we have to focus on individuals,
on the people. That is as much in the charter as sovereignty.''
</P>
<P>
   Axworthy said that a year ago, just after Annan's groundbreaking
speech to the General Assembly, Canada offered to pay for a program
within the United Nations to study the legality and the
implications of what diplomats call ``humanitarian intervention.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't considered to be prudent, because there was so
much opposition to it by certain countries, as well as within the
bureaucracy,'' Axworthy said. ``It became too controversial.''
</P>
<P>
   So Canada decided on its own to commission a study, with the
help of four U.S. foundations, the Carnegie Corp., the Hewlett
Foundation, the John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation and
the Rockefeller Foundation. Canada is to announce its plans on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Two former foreign ministers, Gareth Evans of Australia and
Mohamed A. Sahnoun of Algeria, will be chairmen of the panel, to be
called the International Commission on Intervention and State
Sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   Panel members, not all of who have been chosen, will include Lee
H. Hamilton, a former Democratic Congressman from Indiana and
member of the House International Relations Committee; Michael
Ignatieff, the writer; Legwaila Joseph Legwaila, Botswana's
ambassador to the United Nations; Vladimir Lukin, chairman of the
Foreign Affairs Committee of the Russian Duma; Cornelius Sommaruga,
former president of the International Committee of the Red Cross,
and Ramesh Thakur, an Indian who is vice rector of the U.N.
University in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Axworthy said the study would look at all types of material like
case studies, public opinion surveys and published research to draw
up guidelines. ``We hope, to use the buzzword of the day, that this
can be a little bit of a tipping agent toward actually getting the
adoption of some criteria, some understanding _ maybe simply
conventional practice, as opposed to something that's codified in
law,'' he said. ``But at least we'll get the debate out there.
We'll flush people out and get some serious research.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
