<HEADLINE>
A SPORTS-CRAZED HOST NATION HOPES FOR OLYMPIC SUCCESSES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT30 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ The weather and lifestyle have always been
hospitable to sports in Australia. The sun shines frequently and
temperatures in the major cities enable Australians to play all
manner of games year-round.
</P>
<P>
   But by 1976, something had changed. Australians failed to bring
home any gold medals that year from the Summer Olympics in
Montreal. That outcome _ a sharp reversal from the eight golds won
by Australians at the 1972 Games in Munich _ was unacceptable for a
country that had grown accustomed to defining itself through
international sports success.
</P>
<P>
   Sports officials devised a plan to become more competitive after
1976, and one of the models was East Germany, a country whose
population of 16.7 million was comparable to Australia's but whose
athletes had won 40 gold medals in Montreal to finish second in the
overall count behind the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   The East Germans had developed a centralized,
government-sponsored sports system. Australians decided to do the
same, and in January 1981, the Australian Institute of Sport opened
its doors in Canberra, the capital. The goal, based on the East
German example, was to bring together athletes, coaches,
scientists, trainers, physiotherapists and nutritionists on a
large, leafy campus to maximize elite athletes' performances.
Institutionalized doping was certainly not part of the plan,
although it later became clear that it was an essential reason for
East Germany's success.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two decades later, with the Sydney Games set to open on
Friday, Australia has nearly completed its comeback. It is again an
Olympic power, and with the help of home crowds and
hyper-motivated, well-prepared athletes, it could set a new
national standard by winning as many as 60 medals in everything
from field hockey to trap shooting to tennis. Australia might
finish as high as fourth in the medal count.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a remarkable achievement for a nation of only 19
million people. (The United States, with 260 million people, won
101 medals in the 1996 Games in Atlanta.) And what makes the
prospect even more noteworthy is that most Australians prefer to
play and watch sports that are not even on the Olympic program.
</P>
<P>
   Though there are celebrated Australian swimmers in abundance
(Ian Thorpe, Grant Hackett, Susan O'Neill, Kieren Perkins, Michael
Klim) and one celebrity runner (Cathy Freeman, the two-time world
400-meter champion), the majority of Australia's most prominent
athletes will not be splashing or sprinting for gold. Steve Waugh
and Shane Warne play cricket. Greg Norman and Karrie Webb play
golf. John Eales and George Gregan play rugby union, the
15-man-a-side version of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Australians won world titles in rugby union, cricket
and netball, a popular women's game here that resembles basketball.
They also won the Davis Cup in tennis and individual world titles
in sports as diverse as alpine skiing and track and field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sport in this country is the No. 1 thing,'' said an Australian
assistant swim coach, Gennadi Touretsky, a Russian who was once a
national swim coach in the former Soviet Union. ``I don't know
another country with a sports culture like this. Not one. I think
we had a similar thing in Russia from the 1950s up until the 1970s.
But this sport culture here is supported financially, because sport
is one of the most successful businesses in Australia. It was never
that kind of business in Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   The team representing Australia at the Sydney Games will include
628 athletes, the biggest contingent at the Olympics. More than
half of the athletes, 320 in all, have received scholarships at one
time or another from the Australian Institute of Sport and others
have received aid from state sports institutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian Institute does not help every Australian athlete:
Wealthy tennis players like Pat Rafter and Mark Philippoussis no
longer require its financial assistance, nor do well-sponsored
stars like Freeman and Thorpe.
</P>
<P>
   For those in residence in Canberra, life is hardly luxurious.
Long jumper Jai Taurima calls the dormitory rooms ``cells'' and a
quick glance at the spartan, charmless confines of a room that
recently became vacant makes it easy to see his point. Stipends are
not large. Taurima, for example, who lives off-campus, receives the
equivalent of less than $400 in American dollars to cover his
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   But as at the U.S. Olympic Training Center in Colorado Springs,
Col., the hundreds of athletes at the Australian Institute have
subsidized access to healthy food, excellent coaching, good if not
necessarily state-of-the-art facilities, medical treatment and one
of the world's most respected sports science departments.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got everything at your beck and call,'' said Taurima,
who left Brisbane and his beloved surfboard behind for Canberra
three years ago. ``At home, I don't get any of that support stuff.
The only thing is that no one is very keen to come down here.''
</P>
<P>
   That is because Canberra is geographically isolated and
provincial in feel. But the national sports institute does get
results: In Atlanta, 76 percent of the Australian medalists were
former and current scholarship holders.
</P>
<P>
   The national and the state institutes are not the only reasons
for Australia's Olympic renaissance. As is customary when a nation
hosts an Olympics, public and private spending on sports has
increased significantly. Regional and municipal facilities also
have improved dramatically in the last 10 years throughout
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse of Eastern Europe's communist regimes has also
contributed to the resurgence of Australian athletes. Countries
like the former East Germany no longer accumulate Olympic medals.
Of course, East Germany's remarkable Olympic success has now been
discredited because of systematic, government-sponsored doping.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an element of irony there certainly,'' said John
Boultbee, the director of the Australian Institute of Sport.
</P>
<P>
   The East German model was not the ideal model after all. ``A lot
of the stuff from the east was replicated here, but to say it's the
same in every respect would certainly not be true,'' Boultbee said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there has been a doping scandal at the Australian
Institute. In 1987, a javelin thrower, Sue Howland, tested positive
for steroids and then implicated coaches and other athletes
connected to the institute whom she believed were using drugs. A
government inquiry in 1989 was critical of the sports institute's
drug-prevention efforts, particularly in track and field and
weightlifting, and the institute was stripped of some of its
autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last decade, however, Australia has been one of the
most vocal advocates for improved drug testing, and scientists at
the national institute helped develop the new blood test for the
banned substance EPO. The test is being used in conjunction with a
French urine test for EPO in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bit pious to say it, but I do think we are relatively
clean even in the at-risk sports compared to a lot of our
competitor countries,'' Boultbee said.
</P>
<P>
   Host nations traditionally perform much better than usual at the
Olympics. The last time the Games were held in Australia, in 1956
in Melbourne, Australians won 13 golds, a national record. This
time, the president of the Australian Olympic Committee, John
Coates is predicting as many as 20.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
