<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AT LAST, THE VALOR IN WORLD WAR II MAY BE COMMEMORATED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, Sept. 17)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Earlier this month our country commemorated the
55th anniversary of the end of World War II, and this week the
government may make the final decision on how and where to honor
the victorious warriors of that devastating conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The war, a bloody ordeal of more than three and a half years for
the United States, cost more than 400,000 American lives, totally
changed the international balance of power, ushered in the nuclear
age and gave birth to the United Nations and the Marshall Plan.
</P>
<P>
   It was the seminal event of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 2 we marked the anniversary of the signing of the peace
agreement in Tokyo Bay in 1945. On Wednesday, the National Capital
Planning Commission is to meet in special session, presumably to
determine at long last the design and placement of the proposed
memorial.
</P>
<P>
   The logical location is the National Mall, which now is the site
of memorials to George Washington and Abraham Lincoln. The lives
and deeds of Thomas Jefferson and Franklin D. Roosevelt and the
wars in Vietnam and Korea are recalled in memorials near or along
the side of the mall.
</P>
<P>
   But a plan to place the World War II memorial in the middle of
the mall has ignited a firestorm of controversy. Some critics
object to the design _ a plaza featuring a pool and pillars adorned
with bronze wreaths, created by architect Friedrich St. Florian.
Others oppose breaking the open sweep between the Lincoln Memorial
and the Capitol with a new structure.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan was so impressed with the view that he moved the
presidential inaugural in 1981 from the east side of the Capitol to
the west side so he could see the Washington Monument and Lincoln
Memorial as he took the oath of office.
</P>
<P>
   Some people propose that a tunnel be constructed to carry
traffic under the mall and that the World War II memorial be
constructed on the land above the tunnel. In doing that the
government would have to keep the new structure low enough so that
it would not break up the mall's majestic vista.
</P>
<P>
   But the continued haggling should stop. Time is of the essence
if any of the men and women who served in the war are to witness
completion of the memorial commemorating their valor. Almost all of
them are now in their seventies or older.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, their number dwindles. By the time the memorial is
built and dedicated, few will around to savor it.
</P>
<P>
   The World War II experience was unique in our history. As soon
as Americans learned on Dec. 7, 1941, that Japanese bombs had
decimated the Pacific fleet, killing and wounding many service men,
old animosities suddenly were replaced by new kinships.
</P>
<P>
   Then four days after the Pearl Harbor attack, Adolf Hitler, who
had conquered most of Western Europe, and his ally, Italy's Benito
Mussolini, declared war on the United States.
</P>
<P>
   After that, something remarkable occurred in America.
Isolationists and interventionists, laborers and industrial giants
as well as friends and foes of Franklin D. Roosevelt's New Deal
locked arms in the march to victory over the hated Axis.
</P>
<P>
   For one magic moment in the consciousness of America, business
and industry leaders, who had spent much of a decade fighting
Roosevelt and his revolutionary governmental reforms, converted
their factories to the production of arms and military equipment,
and many accepted high governmental positions for $1 a year.
</P>
<P>
   By war's end, Americans had fought the enemy in Europe, Asia and
Africa. In addition to those killed, nearly 700,000 were wounded,
bringing total U.S. casualties to some 1.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   All of the famous World War II military heroes are gone. But
during the war, everyone could identify Gens. George Marshall,
Dwight Eisenhower, Douglas MacArthur, George Patton, Omar Bradley
and Mark Clark and Adms. Chester Nimitz and William Halsey.
</P>
<P>
   The sites of decisive battles now are but part of a dynamic
legend. They include Bastogne, Bizerte, El Alamein, Guadalcandal,
Iwo Jima, Midway, Monte Cassino, Normandy, Okinawa, Salerno, St.
Lo, Tobruk and Wake Island.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers, sailors and Marines indulged in the usual amount of
griping, but in battle they stood together, united by a joint
resolve.
</P>
<P>
   A horrendous year-long battle that began on May 6, 1944, with
the invasion of Normandy ended in Germany's unconditional surrender
at Reims, France, on May 7, 1945. By that time, Hitler had
committed suicide in his Berlin bunker, and Mussolini had been
executed by Italian partisans.
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt had died of a stroke on April 12, 1945, and had been
succeeded by Harry Truman, who gave the order to drop atomic bombs
on Hiroshima and Nagasaki and later advanced the Marshall Plan that
rebuilt devastated Western Europe and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The events of World War II _ the heroics and the heartbreaks _
should be commemorated so that future Americans and their foreign
friends can reflect on the sacrifices made by plain, peace-loving
men and women when their country and their way of life were
threatened by tyrants from abroad.
</P>
<P>
   As the Civil War was America's defining event of the 19th
century, World War II was defining event of the 20th century. It
should be commemorated as such _ not just for those who lived
through it but also for those who continue to share the fruits of
victory over tyranny.
</P>
<P>
   Robert E. Thompson may be reached at 202-298-6920.
</P>
</TEXT>
