<SLUG> BC-SPACE-STATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASTRONAUTS USE HAMMER, CHISEL TO REPLACE AGING BATTERY ABOARD SPACE
STATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Encountering an unanticipated obstacle, the visiting
Atlantis astronauts grabbed hammer and chisel on Wednesday to
replace an aging power storage battery aboard the international
space station.
</P>
<P>
   The brute force approach worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crew did a little bit of garage work today,'' chuckled
NASA's Mark Ferrying, the space station flight director who
authorized the unusual repair tactic with Russian ground teams.
</P>
<P>
   After a long midday rest, the shuttle's five American astronauts
and two Russian cosmonauts planned to re-board the orbital outpost
late Wednesday for more work on the expanding electrical power
system.
</P>
<P>
   Giant solar arrays that jut from the station generate electrical
power while the outpost circles the Earth in sunlight. When the
station slips into darkness, power soaked up by the batteries is
discharged to keep critical life support, communications and
computer systems operating.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlantis crew docked with the station Sunday to kick off a
week of high tech housework intended to prepare the outpost for the
arrival of its first resident crew in early November.
</P>
<P>
   After a spacewalk that linked external power cables to the
station's latest major addition, the Zvezda crew module, the
astronauts streamed aboard to bolster the internal distribution of
electricity.
</P>
<P>
   With its living and working accommodations for three, Zvezda's
late July addition rendered the station habitable for the first
time since orbital assembly began nearly two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   However, Zvezda was launched with just five of its eight
batteries installed, a weight-saving tactic.
</P>
<P>
   Cosmonaut Yuri Malenchenko and astronaut Ed Lu had little
difficulty Wednesday installing three more.
</P>
<P>
   It was a different story in the station's neighboring Zarya
compartment, the Russian-built propulsion module that became the
new station's cornerstone with its launching in November 1998.
</P>
<P>
   There, astronaut Dan Burbank and cosmonaut Boris Morukov were
trying to remove two aging storage batteries slated for
replacement. Four of the propulsion module's six batteries had been
replaced with little difficulty by another shuttle crew in May.
</P>
<P>
   Much to their dismay the two men found that fasteners securing a
bracket they needed to remove had been riveted rather than bolted
into place.
</P>
<P>
   So with hammer and chisel retrieved from the station's tool kit,
Burbank, a former Coast Guard search and rescue pilot, and Morukov,
a medical doctor, popped eight unwanted rivets.
</P>
<P>
   Though successful, the battery replacement task took longer than
planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a surprise. We weren't aware they would have
problems,'' Ferring explained later. ``What was really good,
though, was that we had the tools on board and the know how on the
ground to find a way to work around that.''
</P>
<P>
   The final Zarya battery replacement was planned for early
Thursday as was the installation of a charging device to ensure
that Russian Soyuz crew transport and Progress cargo capsules that
dock with the station have plenty of electricity.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
