<HEADER>
A3293 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-GOLF-PIG-LAWSUIT14-CO     09-13 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-PIG-LAWSUIT14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Golf club drops '98 noise lawsuit against pig farmer
 &HT;    By Pat Moore
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   STUART, Fla. _ Golfers at the Florida Club will soon be hitting
balls off pig-decorated tees, eating pork sandwiches in the
clubhouse and dodging a new ``yield for pig crossing'' sign at the
15th hole.
</P>
<P>
   But Florida Club officials will no longer be battling pig
farmer/neighbor Paul Thompson in court.
</P>
<P>
   Club owners Wednesday dropped their 1998 lawsuit in which they
accused Thompson of playing loud music for his 135 hogs and pigs to
harass golfers and thwart home sales.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of fighting in court, club officials decided to
capitalize on the infamous squabble that has drawn worldwide
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm outraged,'' Thompson said after learning the suit was
dropped. ``It's been going on for 2 1/2 years, and it's cost me a
lot of time, money and aggravation. I've lived there since 1957 and
haven't violated anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida Club President Bob Kramer said club officials decided to
drop the suit because the music levels from Thompson's farm has
dropped significantly in recent weeks and because a landscaped berm
recently added near the farm has reduced the intrusion of the music
on club residents.
</P>
<P>
   Kramer said the noise level dropped on Thompson's farm after a
judge ordered his neighbors, Thomas and Faith Rossano, to lower the
volume of the music they play for their pigs.
</P>
<P>
   The judge told them to lower the level below that allowed by the
county's noise ordinance and to point their loudspeakers away from
the Florida Club property.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ruling in the Rossano case several weeks ago and the
implementation of the new county noise ordinance clearly
establishes that playing loud music that impacts a neighbor, be it
The Florida Club or anyone else, is not acceptable,'' Kramer said
in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   But Thompson said he has never reduced the music that he plays
to keep his pigs fat and happy _ and has always played it within
the levels required by the county noise ordinance that was adopted
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can say anything they want, but the (sound) meter reading
hasn't changed,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson's attorney, Lance Richard, also refuted the club's
reasons for dropping the suit that was scheduled for trial Oct. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's total nonsense,'' he said. ``I think they never
intended to try this case. They just tried to squeeze Mr. Thompson
and his wife out.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard and co-counsel Deborah Gowen said the Florida Club's
sound expert, Bernard Kinney, previously testified that the berm
built across from Thompson's farm a year ago did not block the
music.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson's attorneys filed court documents two weeks ago asking
Circuit Judge Ben Bryan to throw out the case without a trial. The
judge was set to hear that argument next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Thompsons had a 100 percent defense to a nuisance suit,''
Richard said. ``Legally (the Florida Club) had no basis to bring
this suit, because they never could win it.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida Club attorney Tom Wackeen said the request for the judge
to throw out the case before trial played no part in the club's
decision to drop the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Kramer said the high visibility of the lawsuits against both pig
farmers has brought additional golfers to the club about 7 miles
southwest of Stuart.
</P>
<P>
   A charitable tournament is scheduled at the club this year to
benefit the Martin County Humane Society.
</P>
<P>
   Richard said he will ask the Florida Club to pay for some of
Thompson's costs in defending what he described as a frivolous
suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they should sponsor a golf tournament to benefit the
Paul Thompson recovery plan,'' Gowen said.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said he would settle for a cut of the club's
pig-promotion profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want royalties to pay my attorneys' bill,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   patmoore(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
