<SLUG> BC-IXL0914-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IXL reaches major deal; stock drops
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - IXL's troubles continued Wednesday despite the
announcement of a two-year, multimillion-dollar deal with
telecommunications giant BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   IXL stock tumbled to a 52-week low at midafternoon but bounced
back slightly after the Midtown-based Internet consulting firm said
it had the contract to create a new look for BellSouth's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Bert Ellis, chairman and chief executive officer, said iXL will
begin the first phase of what it said was a ``multimillion-dollar
initiative that will utilize a full range of disciplines ... to
create an individual, personalized experience for BellSouth
customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis is hoping the BellSouth announcement will help revive
iXL's stock price, which hit a 52-week low of $4.63 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   By midafternoon, after the BellSouth announcement, the stock
rose slightly but still finished down 63 cents for the day at
$4.75.
</P>
<P>
   The stock's initial public offering was $14 and hit an all-time
high of $58.75 Jan. 20. The previous low of $5.25 was set on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Christine Overby, an analyst with Forrester Research, says that
it is part of iXL's culture and marketing strategy to announce big
client wins to the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw when they announced relationships with GE, we saw them
announcing they had signed the largest Internet services contract
of all time. This type of overcommunicating with the market that
iXL has always done,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Overby said that announcing big wins isn't a bad thing ``in and
of itself.''
</P>
<P>
   But given iXL's current financial troubles and corporate
reorganization, she said iXL needs not only to land big accounts
but to prove it can deliver the goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you make a lot of noise, people are going see if you can
deliver on quality. I wouldn't say iXL isn't the only company to
fall victim to this. The excitement is legitimate. But you have to
have the products and services to back it up.''
</P>
<P>
   IXL has been working with BellSouth since May on a number of
projects, and Wednesday's announcement marks a more formalized,
long-term expansion of the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth spokesman Jeff Battcher said iXL has been
straightforward about its financial problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been very honest with us about everything that's
going on and reassured us that everything we want to get done gets
done,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think they are the right people. The recent issues have no
bearing on the work we think they do for us. Bert is totally
committed to BellSouth and making sure this whole process works and
this whole contract is something we'll be happy with.''
</P>
<P>
   Overby said she is ``more interested in hearing iXL talk
candidly about how they are going to deliver quality services to
the clients they already have and build out their business
development efforts and get their internal operations in order.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
