<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTOROLA14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Motorola names manufacturing chief
 &HT;    By Kirk Ladendorf
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In a move aimed at bolstering its ties to key
customers, Motorola Inc.'s Austin-based semiconductor business
named a top sales executive as its head of worldwide manufacturing
and related services.
</P>
<P>
   Hans Wildenberg, 44, formerly the top sales executive in
Motorola's chip business, was named to the post Wednesday,
succeeding Bill Walker, who last week became general manager and
No. 2 executive in the company's $7.4 billion chip business.
</P>
<P>
   Janelle Harris, a senior executive in the company's service and
logistics operations, was promoted to Wildenberg's former job of
vice president and director of global sales.
</P>
<P>
   In his new job, Wildenberg, a native of the Netherlands and a
longtime executive of Motorola in Europe, heads a
manufacturing-related operation that employs 23,000 of Motorola's
33,000 chip workers worldwide, including more than 4,000 of the
company's 10,000 employees in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Wildenberg said one of his top priorities is to push Motorola to
conduct more of its business and exchange more of its information
with customers over Internet-based software systems.
</P>
<P>
   The object, he said, is to give Motorola's chip customers more
timely information on the company's manufacturing operations and
order-delivery process to help them plan their own operations
better.
</P>
<P>
   More electronics companies, Wildenberg said, want to use the
Internet to operate more efficiently, much as Cisco Systems and
other companies have learned to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an e-business environment and we are going to be very
active in that,'' Wildenberg said. ``It's a big, big thing right
now in the electronics industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris, 43, a former manufacturing manager with National
Semiconductor Corp., has worked at senior manufacturing and
operations management jobs at Motorola since 1991. She was named
director of manufacturing operations in 1997 and became vice
president of customer service in 1998. Later that year, her job was
expanded to vice president of service and logistics.You may contact
Kirk Ladendorf at kladendorf(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
