<HEADLINE>
TV YOU NEED NOT SEE 
</HEADLINE>
  (New York Times OpEd for Thursday, September 14, and thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 &HT;    By ANDY BOROWITZ  
 c.2000 New York Times   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the fall TV season gets under way, network honchos find
themselves trapped in their own version of ``Survivor,'' with a
nemesis more treacherous than a rat, a snake or a fat naked guy: a
new electronic device called TiVo, which eliminates TV commercials.
</P>
<P>
   But TiVo may just be the beginning. If it proves successful, it
is only a matter of time before manufacturers produce other
TV-altering devices to complicate network executives' lives even
further:
</P>
<P>
   TeenGo: Filters out vapid dialogue from teen-age drama shows;
voice-recognition feature activated by the words ``popular,''
``unfair'' and ``duh.''
</P>
<P>
   VeTo: Instantly zaps a despised program that is regrettably the
favorite of one's spouse; popular settings include ``WWF
Smackdown'' and ``Antiques Roadshow.''
</P>
<P>
   SleaZo: Eliminates blatant, shoddy network rip-offs of HBO's hit
``Sex and the City.''
</P>
<P>
   KathieLeeVo: In a nod to the ratings surge enjoyed by ``Live
with Regis'' since the departure of Regis Philbin's co-host,
removes Kathie Lee Gifford from all other shows in which she might
appear.
</P>
<P>
   SqueaKo: Excises all subliminal references to rodents from
negative campaign ads.
</P>
<P>
   GeeZo: Prevents the broadcast of heavyweight boxing matches
between former champions over the age of 60.
</P>
<P>
   DeleTo: Instantly edits out all FTC officials' Hollywood-blaming
speeches that feature the phrase, ``This isn't about censorship.''
</P>
<P>
   HeaveHo: Seeks out and eliminates all programs destined for an
early cancellation; device is set to be especially sensitive to
programs featuring single dads coping with unruly broods of
smart-mouthed children, and any talk shows involving Roseanne.
</P>
<P>
   (Andy Borowitz is the author of ``The Trillionaire Next Door.'')
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
