<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-TREASON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN COURT REAFFIRMS ACQUITTAL OF CAPTAIN ACCUSED OF TREASON 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ As onlookers applauded from the gallery, the Supreme
Court Wednesday rebuffed a final government plea to reopen a
treason case against Alexander Nikitin, the former naval captain
who gave details of radioactive pollution by Russian submarines to
opponents of nuclear energy.
</P>
<P>
   The decision ended _ for good, apparently _ the government's
five-year prosecution of Nikitin, a pursuit that had become an
international human rights and environmental issue.
</P>
<P>
   It also gives support to President Vladimir Putin's claim that
he is establishing supremacy of the law in a society that has
operated mostly outside the rules since the collapse of the Soviet
Union nine years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Putin has suggested that Russia's environmental movement is a
threat to national security and a tool of foreign interests. And it
was during his tenure as head of the Federal Security Service, the
successor to the KGB's domestic arm, that the government's campaign
against Nikitin reached a head.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kremlin stood aside this year when the Supreme Court
first ruled that the government had no case against Nikitin, and it
seemed to stand aside again now when the court rejected prosecutors
requests' to reopen the charges.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday a jubilant Nikitin called the decision ``a very, very
small step toward creating a state ruled by law.'' One expert and
former American diplomat in Russia, Thomas Graham of the Carnegie
Endowment for International Peace, seconded that appraisal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Supreme Court made an encouraging decision,'' he said in a
telephone interview from Washington, ``but there are a lot of other
worrying signs that this might be the exception as opposed to the
pattern in Russia. It runs contrary to a lot of what we've been
getting out of Russia in the last couple of months.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia's progress toward democratic rule has fallen into doubt
lately among some critics, who see a shift toward authoritarianism
in the Kremlin's attempts to silence critical news media and in its
disregard of human rights questions about its conduct in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Nikitin is not the only environmental activist under legal
attack. Grigory Pasko, a journalist for a naval newspaper in
Russia's Pacific fleet, was also acquitted last year of treason
charges brought after he discussed the fleet's environmental and
financial policies with Japanese journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors are seeking to reopen that case as well, although
Pasko's lawyers argue that military censors had cleared all his
information before it was ever discussed with the Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Pasko and Nikitin argue that the prosecutions show
not only the continuing power of the Federal Security Service and
the intelligence apparatus within Russian society, but also the
service's refusal to recognize that the nation now has a more open
political system.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Security Service arrested Nikitin in 1996 after he
wrote reports for Bellona, a Norwegian environmental group,
detailing radioactive pollution in the Arctic seas. He also
reported on the Soviet Union's practice of dumping nuclear waste at
sea from the 1960s through the 1980s, and about past disasters
involving Soviet submarines.
</P>
<P>
   And he reported on reactor safety systems aboard nuclear subs of
the same class as the Kursk, which sank almost a month ago in the
Barents Sea, killing 118 crew members.
</P>
<P>
   Government prosecutors imprisoned Nikitin for 10 months and
charged him with espionage and high treason for discussing
submarine accidents and reactor safety systems with foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   Nikitin and Bellona insisted that the information was
unclassified and, in any case, did not threaten Russia's national
security, arguments that eventually won over the judge in a trial
in St. Petersburg City Court last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court affirmed that decision this year, and refused
Monday to let the prosecutors try again.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Frederic Hauge, the Bellona president, said the verdict
showed Russians that ``if you fight, you can win _ and they need to
see that in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Nikitin said he would remain in Russia and would continue to
work on environmental issues for Bellona.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
