<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHASE-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIEWS DIFFER ON NUMBER AND NATURE OF JOB CUTS THAT MORGAN DEAL WILL
BRING 
</HEADLINE>
   by JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Moments after e-mail messages went out to tens of
thousands of employees of Chase Manhattan and J.P. Morgan on
Wednesday morning announcing a proposed union of the two companies,
Fritz Georges was one of the few willing to discuss publicly what
many preferred to remain private.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is a little concerned,'' Georges said as he leaned
against his black sedan outside J.P. Morgan's headquarters at 60
Wall St., where he works as a driver for executives. ``They don't
know who is going to be next, who is on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   As company officials announced their plan for Chase Manhattan to
acquire J.P. Morgan for more than $30 billion, some industry
analysts speculated that the merged company could shed as many as
10,000 employees. Company executives, who declined to discuss
specific numbers, acknowledged that they had several duplicate
areas of business, as well as buildings and support services, that
could be eliminated. But they said their target was to save about
$500 million in employment costs, suggesting that cuts are likely
to involve no more than a few thousand people.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company, to be called J.P. Morgan Chase, would have
about 100,000 employees worldwide, with roughly 18,000 based in New
York, where both companies have their headquarters. Several
thousand Chase employees in Manhattan are scheduled to move into a
45-story tower planned for Jersey City, N.J., in the next few
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you have two giants, you are going to have a lot of
people with the same job titles,'' said Gary Goldstein, president
of Whitney Group, a recruiting company.
</P>
<P>
   To increase efficiency, Chase and J.P. Morgan will probably move
quickly to to cut jobs, the analysts said. Generally, the acquired
company is the one that loses the most jobs, but analysts said it
was unclear how that would play out, given J.P. Morgan's strengths.
</P>
<P>
   As far as Georges was concerned, however, Chase, as the
acquiring bank, can be expected to impose most of the cuts on J.P.
Morgan employees. ``There is an old saying that goes, `Every new
current carries its own fish,''' he said. ``People are worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Jon Diat, a Chase Manhattan spokesman, declined to comment in
detail about potential layoffs. Company officials said the merger
could be completed by the first quarter of next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This transaction is about growth,'' Diat said. ``There is
obviously some overlap between the two organizations. However,
there should be a smaller percentage of job loss in New York City
than in other mergers.''
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail message to employees, William B. Harrison, Chase's
chief executive, was a bit more candid. ``Our merger is all about
growth, but it will also provide opportunities to increase
efficiency and reduce expenses,'' he wrote. ``We expect savings
from combining facilities and systems.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrison added that each employee would be given consideration
based on merits. ``Where there are overlapping jobs, some positions
may need to be eliminated,'' he said. ``Any decisions will be made
fairly and objectively on a case-by-case basis.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, the merger of Chemical Bank and Manufacturers Hanover
Corp. eliminated more than 6,000 jobs. In 1995, the acquisition of
Chase by the enlarged new Chemical Bank, which assumed the Chase
name, led to the elimination of even more jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike those mergers, this deal involves two banks that
complement each other more than they overlap. Chase has been a
full-service bank, weakest in investment banking, while J.P. Morgan
focused on raising capital for top-tier corporations and managing
the wealth of the monied elite.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some natural benefit because they have different
strengths,'' said Mitchell Moss, a professor at New York
University.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, when Chase and Chemical combined, it was the union
of two companies with large commercial bank operations.
</P>
<P>
   But those caveats did not allay employees' concerns. Members of
the banks' support staffs are vulnerable, while investment banking
units with overlapping corporate managers, stock analysts and
Chase's European operations probably face layoffs, analysts said.
Chase's retail banking division, which has no counterpart at
Morgan, is unlikely to be affected.
</P>
<P>
   From investment bankers to data processors and executive
secretaries, the mood outside the Manhattan offices of both
companies was skittish, even as most reassured themselves that, in
view of the strong economy and healthy demand for talent, they
could manage a soft landing even if the worst happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uncertainty, that's the key word,'' said one recently hired
J.P. Morgan investment banker. ``Especially in areas like foreign
exchange and derivatives, where there is a lot of overlap.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on conversations he had in the weeks before the planned
deal was announced, Georges said ``the secretaries of the big shots
seem the most concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They know,'' he explained, ``if their bosses go, they are the
next to go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-00 2038EDT &QL; 
