<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHASE-MORGAN-NEXT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER CHASE-MORGAN ANNOUNCEMENT, WALL STREET WONERS WHO'S NEXT 
</HEADLINE>
   By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Who will be next?
</P>
<P>
   That was the question being asked on Wall Street on Wednesday
after Chase Manhattan announced that it would buy J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co.
for $30.9 billion. As with squads of teen-agers huddled in the gym
bleachers at a high school dance, the gossip was endless. Mid-size
firms, like Lehman Brothers and Bear Stearns, will be the next to
pair up with larger rivals, traders said. Merrill Lynch, a
perennial takeover candidate, surely could not survive on its own.
Even powerhouses like Goldman Sachs Group and Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter were considered vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Such talk is a familiar ritual the day a big merger is announced
and, usually, the gossip is indeed just that. ``The market is
evolving,'' said Tom Burnett, president of Merger Insight, an
advisory firm in New York. ``No one really knows what is going to
happen.'' Still, he added, the industry is changing and investors
and corporate clients alike could benefit from that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of having the top three players,'' Burnett said,
referring to the large investment banks of Goldman Sachs, Morgan
Stanley and Merrill Lynch, ``we are going to have a top six or
seven.'' With that comes more competition. ``Why pay $30 million in
fees for a banker when you can pay less?'' he added. ``There is
room for improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason Wall Street firms are merging is to dominate in the
lucrative global merger advisory business, as well as lead in stock
and bond offerings. That is one of the reasons Credit Suisse First
Boston agreed to acquire Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette for $11.5
billion two weeks ago. In July, UBS AG said it would buy
PaineWebber for $10 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But not every firm offers the same benefit. Henry McVey, a
securities and banking analyst at Morgan Stanley, said a competitor
might buy Lehman Brothers, for instance, to increase its presence
in Europe. Nearly half of Lehman's revenue is from outside the
United States, he said. Bear Stearns, for its part, earns much of
its revenue processing trades and providing capital for smaller
Wall Street firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is becoming a scale game,'' McVey said. ``The bigger the
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Investment banks are feeling pressure to grow, in part because
they market their expertise using so-called league tables that rank
how active they are in merger advice, initial public offerings and
other investment banking services. But being involved in a
high-profile transaction does not always guarantee big profits.
J.P. Morgan, for instance, advised Exxon Corp. in its merger with
Mobil Corp. but was paid a paltry $8 million. For a deal that size,
investment bankers can make five times that. But in the Exxon-Mobil
merger, most of the details were worked out between the chief
executives, not investment bankers.
</P>
<P>
   As such, league tables are more about bragging rights than a
sign of how profitable a firm can be. ``The beauty contests are
driven by who is No. 1,'' Burnett said, referring to the
presentations investment banks make to win a client's business.
</P>
<P>
   But one risk that few people consider until after a Wall Street
merger is announced is how well the culture of any two firms will
mesh. When Credit Suisse announced two weeks ago that it was buying
DLJ, tongues wagged about whether the collegial and almost clubby
DLJ bankers would thrive at Credit Suisse, where bankers are said
to have sharper elbows. In fact, some Credit Suisse bankers at the
time privately complained that they would be hard pressed to report
to their new colleagues at Donaldson.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing we've learned from the Salomon Smith Barney merger
is that integration is difficult,'' McVey said, referring to the
merger of Salomon Brothers and Smith Barney. ``There is the vision
and the integration, and the two can be at odds.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
