 PERSONALS: President's Pal Shares His Whispers 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Susan Estrich &LR; , a law professor who ran  &UR; Michael Dukakis &LR; ' campaign
and is a good friend of  &UR; Bill Clinton &LR; 's, writes in George magazine
about the heart-to-heart talk they had last year when she slept
over at the White House. Revealing a friend's thoughts about his
marriage is apparently just one facet of friendship among
politicos.
</P>
<P>
   Her marriage was troubled at the time (she's since divorced),
and Clinton told her he was determined to save his own. ``If
Hillary had walked out,'' he said, ``it would have made Monica an
impeachable offense. . . . They think I got away with it. They have
no idea what we went through to save this marriage, how hard we've
worked to save it. Or perhaps how important it was that we did . .
. not just for the country, but for the two of us.''
</P>
<P>
   (Some readers may be startled by the wording of the president's
assertion, which implies that ``the two of us'' is a greater entity
than ``just the country,'' but that would be nitpicking.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; MORE SMELL NEWS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A New Yorker profile of clothing designer  &UR; Helmut Lang &LR; 
describes his new scent, Helmut Lang.
</P>
<P>
   According to artist  &UR; Jenny Holzer &LR; , its odor is ``the smell of
the morning after a passionate but difficult night.'' According to
its marketing director,  &UR; Jonny Lichtenstein &LR; , it's ``the way a man
smells right after he has had sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Lang himself called it ``worn but fresh.'' And the profile
writer,  &UR; John Seabrook &LR; , describes it as ``flowery and buttery at
the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps a rose is a rose is a rose. When the scent was
tested by Procter &AMP; Gamble, which is marketing it, ``people reacted
badly.'' Lang refused to change it.
</P>
