u i BC-EUROPE-FUEL-1STLD-WRI     09-13 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-FUEL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-980(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAIR CALLS ON PROTESTERS TO LIFT BLOCKADE OF OIL REFINERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs for new lede, updating and expansion, rewriting throughout)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Facing the most serious challenge to his leadership,
Prime Minister Tony Blair on Wednesday night called on protesters
to lift their virtual siege of oil refineries and storage depots,
saying their actions were paralyzing the country and endangering
lives.
</P>
<P>
   After a second day of emergency meetings at 10 Downing Street
aimed at easing blockades that have left 90 percent of the
country's filling stations dry, Blair grimly told a news conference
that despite the pledge he had made on Tuesday of showing progress
within 24 hours, the situation had only worsened.
</P>
<P>
   Blair, by refusing to accede to the protesters' demands to cut
fuel taxes, has increasingly become the target of the protesters,
and on Wednesday night he upped the stakes by angrily denouncing
the demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result of these blockades and this intimidation, real
damage is now being done to real people,'' he said. Doctors,
nurses, police officers and firefighters are having problems
getting to their jobs and ``lives are at risk if those people can't
get to work,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   He also reiterated his determination to resist pleas for a
sudden cut in fuel taxes, which are the highest in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the protesters' feelings,'' he said, ``and I repeat
that I understand the real difficulties people have over the high
price of petrol, it cannot be right to force a change in policy by
these means.'' Any government that did, he added, would lose all
credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Although both businesses and labor unions have called for an end
to the protests, the opposition Tories on Wednesday joined in the
attacks on Blair.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Ancram, chairman of the Conservative Party, scorned
Blair's characterization of the picketers as ``an insult to the
many decent, law-abiding people conducting lawful protests.''
</P>
<P>
   Asserting that the real problem was ``a prime minister in
panic,'' Ancram said: ``Last night Tony Blair confidently strode
into a press conference and said, `Give me 24 hours and I'll solve
the fuel crisis.' Twenty-four hours later, he skulked back into the
same room and admitted the crisis had got far worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Oil trucks resumed limited deliveries on Wednesday, but the flow
was estimated to be less than 15 percent of normal volume. Almost
all of it was designated for the police, fire departments,
hospitals and ambulances, rather than the nation's gas pumps.
</P>
<P>
   The Petrol Retailers Association warned that it could be three
weeks before Britain was back to normal.
</P>
<P>
   The protests intensified Wednesday across the country, with
pickets monitoring the rigs leaving oil company properties and
creeping convoys of truckers creating miles of traffic jams. At
some refineries, drivers refused to take on oil either out of
sympathy with the protesters or in fear at possible retaliation
from them.
</P>
<P>
   The protests, which caught the Blair government off guard, have
been mounted by truck owners, farmers and self-employed workers
claiming that rising fuel prices _ gasoline costs about $4.37 a
gallon _ are putting them out of business. Supermarkets reported
empty shelves from panic buying, the Royal Mail said it could not
guarantee deliveries, banks said they were running short of cash
and many schools closed because they had no bus service.
</P>
<P>
   The National Health Service was put on ``red alert'' _ in which
it is supposed to prepare for treating only emergency cases _ and
the Ministry of Defense on Wednesday night deployed 80 oil trucks
at strategic points around the country to deliver fuel for
emergency services.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the severe inconveniences, the protests continued to
attract substantial sympathy from the public and to focus anger on
the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard Blair say he wouldn't cave in to the protesters, but
he should know that 90 percent of the public are with them, not
him,'' said Dave Cummings, a taxi driver in Edinburgh who said he
backed the movement even though he had only a half tank of gas left
on Wednesday morning and no likelihood of a refill. ``Here we have
all this oil in the North Sea, and we're paying the highest petrol
prices in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the main reasons why gasoline is so expensive here is the
76.2 percent tax on gasoline, about triple the rate in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   After Blair made his high-risk pledge to get the fuel situation
``on the way back to normal'' within 24 hours, protesters reacted
with defiance of their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony Blair said last night this will all be over in 24 hours,
and we want to ram those words down his throat,'' said Julie
Charles, a truck owner from Yeovil, Somerset, in the southwest.
</P>
<P>
   Blair is determined to appear decisive, aware of the power of
popular protest in Britain to bring down governments. A so-called
winter of discontent in 1979 began the fall of the Labor
administration of Prime Minister James Callaghan, who was perceived
as failing to get a grip on the wave of strikes that brought
Britain to its knees. ``We are all bound by history,'' Education
Secretary David Blunkett said pointedly on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Blair summoned oil company executives on Wednesday morning to a
second blunt-spoken session in Downing Street, and the executives
emerged saying they would do everything they could to resume normal
deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   They had argued that they were unwilling to order drivers to
make shipments because of fear for their safety. ``We will be
stepping this up as soon as possible to get back to normal, `` said
Shell Oil's chief executive, Malcolm Brinder, reading from a joint
statement after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The protests were largely incident-free until Wednesday, when
the police were ordered to clear routes for oil trucks and arrested
some demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   Sir John Evans, of the Association of Chief Police Officers,
said he had received reports of intimidation and was offering to
put constables in the cabs of trucks if necessary.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
