<HEADLINE>
`SURVIVOR' TACTICS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By ROB LOWMAN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   cc,78p3 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The thrill of victory, the agony of getting voted off the island
amid tiki &QL;
</P>
<P>
   torches.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, you can experience it all again as ``Survivor'' (otherwise
known as ``Rich's Lessons in How to Eliminate Your Competitors and
Gain Riches 101'') returns for 13 straight nights in reruns
starting Friday at 9 p.m. on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Not enough of a fix? Buy the book ``Survivor: The Ultimate
Game'' by Mark Burnett with Martin Dugard (TV Books, 240 pages,
paperback; $17.95). Burnett is the executive producer of the show
and is reportedly selecting contestants here in L.A. for ``Survivor
II,'' which takes place in the Australian outback and premieres
after the Super Bowl in late January. The book promises to ``take
readers behind the scenes, share stories not seen on any broadcast
and explore what it takes to survive on Pulau Tiga.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the reruns, we suggest you study the moves of ultimate
million- dollar survivor Richard Hatch. You may not win any cash,
but you might be able to get rid of a pesky office rival. Wonder
how the sales of tiki torches are doing?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-00 2043EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000913.0333 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3349 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-EUROPE-FUEL-1STLD-WRI     09-13 0448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-FUEL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LONDON: if necessary.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Both business and labor groups condemned the protests and called
for their immediate end.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the Trades Union Congress said the
demonstrations were an unlawful attempt to bully the government.
``They must not succeed,'' the statement said. ``The blockades are
not a legitimate form of industrial action but a challenge to
democracy and crude attempt to hold the country to ransom.''
</P>
<P>
   The British Chambers of Commerce and the Confederation of
British Industry warned that many businesses were being hurt and
said that while they sympathized with the pleas for lower taxes,
the government must not give in to the protesters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prime minister's promise to get fuel flowing from depots
must be delivered rapidly, using whatever means are available,''
said Chris Humphries, the director general of the chambers.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Brown, the chancellor of the exchequer, who brought the
taxes to their current level, said, ``We will not fall for the
quick fix and the irresponsible short-termism of making tax policy
this afternoon because of blockades this morning.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the increased revenues were being used for much needed
investment in hospitals and schools and in transportation and
public services. He also argued that while Britain had higher fuel
taxes than its European neighbors, it enjoyed lower rates of income
tax and business taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The Conservative Party leader, William Hague, said, ``The whole
country has now paid the price for having an arrogant out-of-touch
government.''
</P>
<P>
   He refused however, to endorse an immediate reduction in the
gasoline tax, saying only that if the Tories returned to power, it
would be a ``strong candidate'' for a cut.
</P>
<P>
   The Tories' unease may stem from the fact that when they were in
government, they introduced a ``fuel-duty escalator'' that
committed the Treasury to raise the tax on gasoline and diesel
annually above the inflation rate. Though it was put forward as a
means of encouraging conservation, it became notorious with
motorists, and Brown ended the escalator in March.
</P>
<P>
   Overall taxes on fuel have continued to rise, however, and Brown
failed to anticipate the anger they would draw from consumers as
crude oil prices also rose. What is a current windfall for the
Treasury could become a liability for Labor as it prepares for a
national election expected in May.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Riddell, the chief political writer of The Times of
London, predicted, however, that a tough response from Blair would
limit any electoral damage. ``This is a test of the Government's
will,'' he said, ``not of its political future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
