<HEADER>
A3352 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-WILSON-MUSIC-REVIEW-N     09-13 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILSON-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RECLUSIVE BEACH BOY REVISITS A BREAKTHROUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   By JON PARELES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most Brian Wilson fans never expected to see him onstage
performing the Beach Boys' groundbreaking 1966 album, ``Pet
Sounds,'' from beginning to end. He made the album in isolation
after he stopped touring with the Beach Boys, working in the studio
oblivious to commercial prospects or to whether the elaborately
orchestrated songs could ever be played in concert. Yet there he
was on Sunday night at the Jones Beach Theater with a band and
orchestra behind him, introducing ``Pet Sounds'' as ``about 40
minutes of really nice music.''
</P>
<P>
   It was that and more. ``Pet Sounds'' is more touching now than
it was in the experimental heyday of 1960s rock. It was the work of
a 23-year-old songwriter who was painfully diffident and bursting
with ambition at the same time. Wilson sang about how hard it was
to find love, friendship and a kindred soul: ``Every time I get the
inspiration to go change things around/No one wants to help me look
for places where new things might be found,'' he sang in ``I Just
Wasn't Made for These Times.''
</P>
<P>
   The tunes don't move steadily like most pop songs; they pause
and ruminate in orchestral interludes as if unsure how to continue.
But the complex tempo changes, eccentric orchestrations and soaring
vocal harmonies are the work of a songwriter who purposely defied
the conventions he had already mastered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pet Sounds'' was part of the second set in a two-part concert
that concentrated on Wilson's 1960s songs. Until the finale, with
ebullient early Beach Boys songs like ``I Get Around'' and ``Fun,
Fun, Fun,'' many of the songs brought out Wilson's plaintive side.
In ``Until I Die'' and ``In My Room,'' the lyrics confessed to an
abiding loneliness while the music created a refuge of overarching
harmony. Once Wilson shared vocal harmonies with his brothers in
the Beach Boys; now he shares them with fans onstage and in the
audience.
</P>
<P>
   His voice is not the pure instrument it was. It strains and
sometimes misses notes; it has been a long time since the 1960s.
Wilson, famous for stage fright in the past, was not entirely at
ease, but he cheerfully introduced most songs and sometimes pointed
to his heart or pointed a finger to highlight a favorite passage.
Songs like ``Caroline, No,'' ``Don't Talk'' and ``I Know There's an
Answer'' took on extra poignancy from the passage of time.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson is touring with musicians who are scholars of his music.
As on his 1999 tour, the core band is the Wondermints, who are
dedicated to recreating lapidary 1960s pop; they took along many of
the instruments Wilson used on ``Pet Sounds,'' including banjo,
bass harmonica, bicycle horn, alto flute and tannerin, the
instrument actually used on ``Good Vibrations'' and ``I Just Wasn't
Made for These Times'' because it is easier to control than the
theremin.
</P>
<P>
   The orchestra cushioned the music with strings and filled in the
interludes and unlikely transitions that Wilson had devised for
brass and woodwinds. It also opened the concert with a symphonic
medley, arranged by Wilson's occasional collaborator, Van Dyke
Parks, that strung together well-known and obscure Beach Boys songs
as a kind of lost Hollywood epic. Sometimes it teased out inner
voices, and sometimes it unfurled the melodies like grand
silhouettes against a Southern California sunset.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
