<HEADER>
A3363 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TECH-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      09-13 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUGHES WINS SATELLITE WORK
</P>
<P>
   New ICO, the satellite communications company soon to merge into
Craig O. McCaw's ambitious Teledesic satellite venture, announced
Wednesday that it had reached an agreement with Hughes Space &AMP;
Communications Co. on plans for Hughes to produce 14 satellites.
The agreement includes three new satellites and modifications to 11
spacecraft that Hughes had in production when ICO Global
Communications, New ICO's predecessor, filed for bankruptcy just
over a year ago. McCaw led a group that brought the company out of
bankruptcy for $1.2 billion and forged plans for a satellite system
capable of offering a range of data and Internet services in
addition to the voice traffic ICO Global had originally envisioned.
The network is now slated to begin operations in 2003. Hughes said
the satellite design is one of the most complex ever undertaken.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT ACQUIRES MUSIC WEB SITE
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft said Wednesday that it had acquired MongoMusic Inc., a
Redwood City, Calif., producer of Web-based digital music
technology. The MongoMusic.com Web site allows consumers to sample
music and create their own ``stations'' of favorite tunes. Founded
in June 1999, the company was originally financed by Nokia and
Sony. Microsoft officials said they found MongoMusic attractive
because of its history of strong relationships with the recording
industry. With the acquisition of MongoMusic, Microsoft is
expanding its MSN network of Web sites, which already includes the
WindowsMedia.com music site. The value of the acquisition was not
disclosed, but industry sources estimated it at $65 million. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NAPSTER FILES ARGUMENTS
</P>
<P>
   Napster Inc., the music software company whose software lets
consumers download and share music files, made its final written
presentation Wednesday to the 9th Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals in
San Francisco. The presentation was in reply to the brief filed
last week by the Recording Industry Association of America, the
plaintiff in the case. Napster, based in Redwood City, Calif., is
seeking to overturn a lower court decision in July that threatens
to shut down the company by blocking major-label songs from being
traded on the Napster service. Napster's presentation contends that
its service does not diminish the value of the plaintiff's
copyrights, insisting rather that the RIAA is trying to maintain
control over music distribution. Oral arguments in the case are
scheduled for Oct. 2.
</P>
<P>
   NBA ADDS TO WEB PRESENCE
</P>
<P>
   Intel and the National Basketball Association announced an
agreement Wednesday that would create a combined venture that will
include a broadband programming and interactive game broadcasts.
Officials said the deal will give fans access to daily NBA and WNBA
highlights as well as archived NBA highlights. In May, Intel, the
world's largest computer chip maker, and Excalibur Technologies, an
Internet company, announced that they would form a new company,
Convera Corp., to enable owners of valuable content produce and
securely sell audio, video and other information. According to the
agreement Wednesday, the NBA will receive a 10 percent equity take
in Convera and the NBA's commissioner, David Stern, will join the
company's board of directors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   STARMEDIA TO CUT 125 JOBS
</P>
<P>
   In pursuit of profitability, StarMedia Network company, said
Wednesday that it planned to cut 125 jobs, or 15 percent of its
staff, and take a one-time charge of $2 million to $4 million in
the third quarter of this year. StarMedia, a New York-based company
that aims at Spanish- and Portuguese-speaking audiences around the
world, said the job cuts were expected to generate savings of $15
million to $20 million in 2001 and would enable it to record a
profit in the fourth quarter of 2001, a year earlier than expected.
StarMedia's stock fell 50 cents, or 4 percent, to $11.50. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CARNIVORE CHOICE DUE SEPT. 25
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department plans to make a final decision on the
university that will conduct a technical review of the Carnivore
surveillance system on Sept. 25, a department spokeswoman said
Wednesday. The department posted the standards and specific
expectations for the academic review on its Web site
(www.usdoj.gov) in late August. The Carnivore program, used by the
FBI, can intercept and search private e-mail for words and phrases,
allowing agents to quickly sift through many messages.
</P>
<P>
   RAMBUS JUMPS ON LICENSING DEAL
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Rambus advanced Wednesday after the memory chip
designer said it had reached a licensing agreement with NEC of
Japan, the world's second-largest chip maker. NEC is the largest
chip maker to sign a licensing agreement with Rambus, which is
embroiled in lawsuits over licensing royalties. It is the fourth
such deal for Rambus, which designs but does not manufacture memory
chips. Rambus finished up $6.50, or 8 percent, at $83.31. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
