<HEADER>
A3364 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TOYPIANO-ARTIST-TEX     09-13 0410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOYPIANO-ARTIST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIANIST TOYS WITH THE AUDIENCE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 WAYNE LEE GAY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Van Cliburn has about 14 grand pianos _ nobody's made
an exact count _ in his Fort Worth mansion.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Leng Tan has about 14 toy pianos _ once again, nobody's
counted exactly _ in her New York apartment.
</P>
<P>
   You might say she's the Cliburn of the toy piano.
</P>
<P>
   A student of renowned piano teacher Adele Marcus at Juilliard,
Tan became interested in the toy piano in the early 1980s when she
came under the spell of the late great American avant-gardist John
Cage, who had written a Suite for Toy Piano in 1948. Since then,
she's become a leading and enthusiastic advocate of the miniature
instrument.
</P>
<P>
   She'll bring that enthusiasm to Dallas on Sept. 21 when she
presents her ``Ode to Schroeder'' program at McKinney Avenue
Contemporary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty aggressive little instrument,'' she said in a
recent telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Tan points out two tremendous advantages.
</P>
<P>
   ``From practicing the toy piano, because of the difficulty of
the action, my fingertip control became extremely refined,'' she
says. ``I can do four different shades of pianississimo on the real
piano.''
</P>
<P>
   And the instrument is not, as one might suspect, limited in
repertoire; she can play significant excerpts from 18th-century
works and works of Beethoven, she points out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's actually closer in sound to Beethoven's piano than the
modern concert grand,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   For her Dallas appearance, she'll perform on two toy pianos _ an
upright and a made-to-specification ``grand,'' _ presenting works
of Glass, Cage, the Beatles and Beethoven, including a synchronized
play-along with a performance of the opening section of Beethoven's
Piano Sonata Opus 2, No. 3 played with Charles Schulz's cartoon
character Schroeder from the animated Peanuts classic ``Play it
Again, Charlie Brown.''
</P>
<P>
   She'll perform, at various points in the concert, on separate
toy pianos, on both pianos together, on toy percussion and a toy
accordion. And she'll deliver plenty of what she calls ``sit-down
comedy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as way-out as it sounds,'' she says of the toy piano
as a concert instrument. ``Your only limit is your imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   (Wayne Lee Gay covers classical music for the Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDBU/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
