<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jones to run final relay rounds only
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ To aid Marion Jones' quest for five gold medals, U.S.
coaches plan to rest her in the early rounds of the relays and run
her in the finals only.
</P>
<P>
   Jones is entered in the 100 meters, the 200 and the long jump,
along with the 400-meter and 1,600-meter relays. The first rounds
and semifinals of the relays are Sept. 29, the same day as the
final in the long jump. The finals for the relays are Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, we're concerned about (her wearing down),'' women's
coach Karen Dennis said. ``You hope her legs are fine, and we'll
watch as she goes along. That's why she'll only run the final
rounds. Marion is a big, strong girl, and she has the talent and
energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones is staying in a private residence here to avoid the
distractions of the Olympic village. To further reduce the hoopla,
she is refusing to grant interviews before her competition begins
next Friday with the 100 meters.
</P>
<P>
   With Michael Johnson and Maurice Greene entered in just one
individual event each, the men's coaches don't have to protect a
superstar athlete in the relay rounds. Johnson is definitely
running the 1,600-meter relay and Greene the 400 relay, but coach
John Chaplin won't decide on the other members until after the
individual 100 and 400-meter races.
</P>
<P>
   Greene has been outspoken about desiring to run with HSI
teammates Jon Drummond, Curtis Johnson and Bernard Williams.
``Everyone's got some say, but I have final say,'' Chaplin said.
</P>
<P>
   HAMSTRING TWINGE FOR JOHNSON
</P>
<P>
   Allen Johnson, defending Olympic champ in the 110-meter hurdles,
pulled up with a twinge in his hamstring during a final tuneup over
the weekend. Johnson claims he was playing it safe, but he ran in
an informal meet here Thursday, and coaches want to see how he
recovers.
</P>
<P>
   SALUTE TO CAPTAINS
</P>
<P>
   Defending high jump gold medalist Charles Austin and four-time
Olympian Joetta Clark were picked as captains for the U.S. track
team. Austin set an Olympic record of 7 feet, 10 inches in 1996 in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
