<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3366 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NATIONAL-MONUMENTS-AR     09-13 1287
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATIONAL-MONUMENTS-ART-1200(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANS TO PROTECT HISTORIC RIVER CLASH WITH AIMS OF MONTANA
RANCHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ore., Colo., Idaho, Calif., Utah, Virgin Islands)  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINIFRED, Mont. _ The federal government calls this stretch of
the Upper Missouri River ``a priceless remnant of primitive
America.''
</P>
<P>
   So why has the idea of permanent protection for this remote
quarter of the prairies, little changed from the days of Lewis and
Clark, inspired the kind of not-in-my-backyard animosity usually
attached to prisons and garbage dumps?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, expressed loud and clear by ranchers here, says a
lot about Montana _ and even more about the resistance to a plan
for conservation of public lands, in which President Clinton, in
his final months in office, is trying to rival President Theodore
Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has already set aside more land as national monuments in
the lower 48 states than any previous president. But as the
administration eyes fresh targets, including the rugged lands that
surround the Upper Missouri, it is running into stiff opposition
from people who regard monuments not as a legacy, but as an
imposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much land is enough?'' asked John Witt, a state
legislator, adding his voice to the anger expressed at a hastily
organized meeting at the Winifred school. ``America has 500 million
acres of public land already. It's a little like, `Are we a state,
or are we the District of Washington?'''
</P>
<P>
   The list of new or expanded monuments by Clinton stands at 11,
and Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt has signaled that the
designation process is not over.
</P>
<P>
   At issue here is a 149-mile stretch of the Missouri and rugged
lands that plunge steeply to the water, known as the Missouri
Breaks. The area is among eight proposed monuments that
administration officials say could be designated before Clinton
leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect has won applause from environmental groups. But in
Western states like Montana, where many residents regard monument
status as a potential barrier to the land on which they depend,
feelings against the plans are running so high that administration
officials say that Clinton is likely to postpone most if not all
announcements until after Election Day, to avoid hurting the
chances of Democratic candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth of the matter is that Secretary Babbitt and
President Clinton want to lock up as many environmentally sensitive
areas as they can before they shut the lights off,'' an aide to a
Western Democratic lawmaker said. ``And what they're running up
against is that in the rural West, these folks are clinging to a
way of life that they would lose through these monument
designations.''
</P>
<P>
   In Montana, where polls show the public to be split on the
issue, one glimpse of the debate can be seen in what might be
called a battle of slogans.
</P>
<P>
   With his 1996 book ``Undaunted Courage,'' the historian and
author Stephen Ambrose helped to draw attention to the Upper
Missouri, virtually the only stretch of the 2,700-mile-long river
that has remained undeveloped in the nearly 200 years since
Meriwether Lewis and William Clark and their Corps of Discovery
used the Missouri as their main water route.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the least inhabited, most precious part of the Lower
48,'' Ambrose has said in advocating national monument status.
``It's ours to preserve for our progeny. It would be sacrilegious
not to.''
</P>
<P>
   A very different view has been expressed by the Montana
Stockgrowers' Association, a group of cattlemen who say that
ranchers are perfectly capable of preserving the area themselves,
as they have since homesteaders first settled the land. The
organization calls its group Undaunted Stewards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of the river as a sidewalk that runs in front of your
house,'' said one member, Matt Knox, whose 28,000-acre ranch
northeast of Winifred would be in the monument.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Montana land proposed for monument status, 400,000
acres in the current draft, is already in public hands, controlled
by the Bureau of Land Management. A small part is privately held,
and while those owners would be permitted to remain, many fear that
the government's aim is to buy them out. And though Babbitt has
assured local residents that grazing and hunting would be allowed
to continue, many worry that they will find themselves enmeshed in
federal regulations.
</P>
<P>
   At the national level, among the many Republicans who have
denounced what they call a land grab is the Republican
vice-presidential candidate, Dick Cheney, a native of Wyoming who
has accused the administration of misusing its authority and acting
``willy-nilly all over the West'' in imposing new restrictions on
the use of public land.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt says that he has tried hard to seek consensus in
communities that would be affected by any plan. In many cases, he
said, the administration has agreed to compromises, often by
allowing hunting and grazing to continue even after a monument has
been established.
</P>
<P>
   But he stopped short of saying the administration would defer to
local wishes, particularly in Montana, where the proposed monument
has met such strong opposition. And Babbitt insisted that the
reason for the administration's haste reflected less a quest for a
political legacy than a quest to save land that might one day be
overrun by development.
</P>
<P>
   ``The empty spaces are filling up all over the West,'' Babbitt
said, arguing that in Clinton's presidency, the need to protect
land had become ``much more urgent than it was, say, 50 years ago
when almost no one was on it.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue in Montana and other states that would be affected by
any presidential declaration are rival visions not only about the
federal government but also about who knows what is best for the
land.
</P>
<P>
   In southeast Oregon, plans for a possible Steens Mountain
monument have been tangled by a county law that requires no net
loss of private land. And in northwest Colorado, powerful
sentiments have been kindled by a proposed 280,000-acre Vermillion
National Monument, on grasslands long used for grazing.
</P>
<P>
   Similar controversies have arisen over other proposals,
including the possible expansion of Craters of the Moon National
Monument in Idaho, which, like the Vermillion proposal, is now
awaiting Clinton's approval.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Steens Mountain and the Missouri Breaks, the other
areas under review by the Interior Department as national monuments
include the Carrizo Plains, in west-central California; the Santa
Rosa Mountains, near Palm Springs, Calif.; an expansion of the
Colorado National Monument, and, in a development that has not yet
been publicized, a possible offshore monument designed to protect
the coral reefs of St. John's in the Virgin Islands.
</P>
<P>
   The authority to establish national monuments is spelled out in
the Antiquities Act of 1906, which authorizes the president to
designate such areas in order to protect ``objects of historic and
scientific interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has used that mandate broadly, setting aside the 1.7
million acre Grand Staircase-Escalante National Monument in
southwest Utah, for example, as part of a strategy intended to
sidestep opposition from a Republican-controlled Congress to any
steps that would add new restrictions to development on public
land. An act of Congress is required for the designation of a
national park or national forest, steps that could carry somewhat
more protection than monument status.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As the founder of the national park system, Roosevelt, set aside
more public land as protected areas than anyone else. Since
January, Clinton has set aside 10 monuments in order to protect,
for example, areas that include a forest of giant redwoods in
California and the last undammed stretch of the Columbia River in
eastern Washington. A Republican-led attempt to stop the effort by
stripping the president of his monument-designation status failed
in the Senate on a 50 to 49 vote in July.
</P>
<P>
   A monument designation could not be undone by a new president,
though it could be overturned by an act of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the battles, the one raging over the Missouri Breaks may
be the most divisive. Even Sen. Max Baucus of Montana, a Democrat,
has so far remained neutral, in apparent deference to local
sensitivities, while Sen. Conrad Burns and the state's sole
congressman, Rick Hill, both Republicans, have expressed adamant
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the people who live on the land, and who have their
culture on the land, usually make the best decisions for the
land,'' Burns said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Conservationists argue that the river and surrounding land needs
national monument status, in part to preserve habitat for species
like the big-horned sheep, antelope and elk. And with the Lewis and
Clark bicentennial approaching, beginning in 2003, they say it is
also important that new campgrounds and visitor centers be put in
place to help accommodate the expected visitors, with many floating
down the slow, shallow river in canoes, beneath stunning rock
formations and the dazzling White Cliffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that this is a once in a lifetime opportunity,
particularly not knowing what the next presidential administration
will be like,'' said Dave Dittloff, conservation director of the
Montana Wildlife Federation. As the stretch of the Missouri becomes
better known, ``recreational issues are going to get bad,''
Dittloff said, ``and development issues are going to get worse and
worse.''
</P>
</TEXT>
