<HEADER>
A3370 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-BUSH-SPI &LR;      09-13 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH TALKS UP SALMON RESTORATION, NATIONAL PARKS IMPROVEMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY and CHRIS McGANN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONROE _ Visiting a region he described as a ``battleground of
environmental war and environmental policy,'' GOP presidential
nominee George W. Bush Wednesday used a cattle farm as backdrop to
extol the joys of nature, praise salmon restoration projects and
pledge a $4.9 billion program to improve upkeep of national parks.
</P>
<P>
   Alluding to his ranch near Waco that is his pride and place of
privacy, Bush talked of nature as a source of ``serenity and
peace'' and quoted Theodore Roosevelt on ``the value of silent
places unworn by man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you own your own land, every day is Earth Day,'' Bush said
against the back drop of trees, the Skykomish River and the Cadman
Sky River gravel pit.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor went on to say: ``I love to fish. ... I want
our land to be as pristine as it can possibly be.'' He praised
community-based salmon restoration efforts and pledged to back the
Salmon Recovery Funding Board's $20 million request for local
programs in the Puget Sound area.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also repeated that he won't breach Snake River dams to
restore salmon runs, and that he is a defender of private property
owners.
</P>
<P>
   Bush continues to treat Washington as a poltical battleground,
even though it rejected his father in the 1988 and 1992 elections
and gave only 37 percent of its vote to GOP presidential nominee
Bob Dole in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   As he arrived beside the Skykomish River, just as a morning sun
began to burn away the fog, Bush was making his seventh Washington
visit in the past 14 months, and his third foray into Snohomish
County.
</P>
<P>
   His running mate, Dick Cheney is tentatively slated to campaign
in the state next Monday, and Bush will return in the next few
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has recently taken a beating in the national media for
verbal gaffes and the missteps of his campaign. Wednesday, he spoke
to about 100 invited guests and was not made available to answer
reporters' questions.
</P>
<P>
   But he made a positive impression on leaders of salmon recovery
projects who sat with him beside Haskell Slough and explained how
the restored channel provides a home to young salmon.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had done his homework. What I heard today is what I believe
in, reaching out to private landowners in the cause of
conservation,'' said Darlene Madenwald, former chairwoman of the
Washington Environmental Council.
</P>
<P>
   John Sayre, executive director of Northwest Chinook Recovery,
added: ``We talked the same language. He was genuinely interested.
We talked about the recovery of Texas redfish, one of the great
fish recovery stories in this nation.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Puget Sound basin, where chinook salmon have been listed
as threatened under the Endangered Species Act, 53 percent of land
is privately owned. Streams flowing through private land constitute
the prime habitat for coho salmon, a major user of the Haskell
Slough habitat.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., termed it ``a major step forward''
that Bush took the time to visit the slough and witness the success
of a project backed by landowners and paid for by state and federal
agencies and Indian tribes.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us care for things that we see _ I'm convinced that
over the next four years we will have very strong support from the
top, the White House,'' Gorton said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's proposal on national parks _ a five-year program to
eliminate a backlog on maintenance and repairs _ received a more
mixed reception.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Washington state, Bush talks about fixing national parks
while ignoring them in Texas,'' said Ken Kramer, director of the
Lone Star Chapter of the Sierra Club.
</P>
<P>
   Kramer argued that there is a $186 million backlog of state park
maintenance needs in Texas parks, and that the state ranks 49th of
50 in per capita spending on its parks.
</P>
<P>
   Praise, with qualification, came from the National Parks and
Conservation Association, an 81-year-old national group dedicated
to protecting and enhancing the park system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Providing money needed to get rid of the maintenance backlog
is key to getting parks in peak condition,'' said Thomas Kiernan,
president of the association.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's only half the story,'' he said. ``The backlog results
from a $500 million to $1 billion shortfall in the Park Service's
annual operating budget. Governor Bush's proposal fixes the
backlog, but does not solve the underlying problem of an inadequate
annual budget for the Park Service to protect the plants, animals
and historic artifacts in its care.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also outlined a stewardship philosophy in which local
communities, free of excessive regulation, work to protect the
environment. He said the federal government should support such
efforts with incentives, not mandates.
</P>
<P>
   The approach resonated with area landowners, many of them
farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Reiner, who owns the riverfront farm and much of the
3.5-mile Haskell Slough habitat restoration project, said Bush's
ideas are on target.
</P>
<P>
   Reiner worked with neighbors, volunteers, environmental groups,
state and federal agencies to transform a sediment-choked back
channel of the Skykomish River into a robust rearing area for
steelhead, chinook and coho salmon.
</P>
<P>
   Reiner said current environmental policy is built on the idea of
letting nature restore itself _ regardless of how that would effect
people.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, Reiner said, is that the Endangered Species Act
gives too much power to mid-level bureaucrats who want to prohibit
almost any land use in environmentally sensitive areas.
</P>
<P>
   A better approach, he said, is to come up with cooperative
solutions, such as the Haskell Slough project, in which management
can improve the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We built more diversity into this project in the last three
years than nature may do in 80 (years),'' Reiner said. ``There's
room for people and fish.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
