<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3374 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-OLY-AUSSIE-SWIMMING-H     09-13 1492
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-AUSSIE-SWIMMING-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Australia's consciousness immersed in swimming
</P>
<P>
   By DANNY ROBBINS
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ To pass through the main entrance of the
Olympic swimming venue, the Sydney International Aquatic Center, is
to pass through a large portion of Australia's sports history.
</P>
<P>
   The exploits of 10 of Australia's greatest swimmers and divers
are described on plates of bronze in the sidewalk, sort of an
Aquatic Walk of Fame. Those of another 94 are portrayed in similar
fashion on the outer walls.
</P>
<P>
   From Australia's best-known Olympian of the past, Dawn Fraser,
to its current Wunderkind, Ian Thorpe, the names speak to the
success Australians have experienced in swimming competition. They
also speak to the host nation's expectations for the Sydney
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   As swimming unfolds over the first eight days of the Games,
Australians will immerse themselves in every race and live and die
with those involving the 44 men and women representing their
country.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in swimming has always been high in Australia, but it
is perhaps at a new level now, with the Games in Sydney and the
Australian team loaded with potential gold-medal winners, some of
whom already have become national celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   After the opening ceremonies, perhaps the most anticipated
elements of the Olympics for Australians are the first and last
days of the swimming competition.
</P>
<P>
   Day 1 will mark the Olympic debut of Thorpe, the 17-year-old who
has emerged in the last two years as the world's best
middle-distance swimmer. Day 8 will include the finals of the
1,500-meter freestyle, in which two Australians, two-time Olympic
champion Kieren Perkins and Grant Hackett, are likely to battle for
the gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of watching eight men swim a mile may not quicken the
pulse of the average American camped out in his easy chair, but it
means high drama to an Australian.
</P>
<P>
   ``We grow up with water in our backgrounds because of our
beaches and estuaries,'' said John Devitt, who won four Olympic
medals swimming for Australia in 1956 and 1960 and now serves as
vice president of the Australian Olympic Committee. ``Most of our
population is one hour from a coastline. Because of that, just
about everybody learns to swim, usually by the age of 4 or 5. It's
part of the early (school) curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   ``American teams that come over here are very jealous of our
crowds because they're so knowledgeable, and the reason they're so
knowledgeable is everybody here swims at one time or another.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Devitt, there are approximately 100 Olympic-size
pools (50 meters) in Sydney and its suburbs. Included in that group
is the venerable North Sydney Olympic Pool, where nearly 90 world
records have been set in 64 years.
</P>
<P>
   As much as swimming is embedded in Australia's culture, it has
become an even greater part of the country's sports scene in recent
years, the surge due in large measure to Perkins, the king of the
1,500 meters; Susie O'Neill, the world-record holder and defending
Olympic champion in the 200 butterfly; and Thorpe, the teen
sensation.
</P>
<P>
   When the Pan Pacific swimming championships were held in Sydney
last year, the finals and semifinals were televised live by Channel
9, one of Australia's three national networks, and five of the
shows wound up among the 12 highest-rated prime-time programs for
the year. The finals and semifinals of the Australian Olympic
trials in May also were televised live by the network.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins is a national icon, easily on a level with tennis player
Pat Rafter and golfer Greg Norman. Eight years ago in Barcelona,
Perkins became the fifth Australian to win the Olympic 1,500, and
he did it again four years later in Atlanta after barely reaching
the finals because of a rib-cage injury.
</P>
<P>
   Now 27 and competing in his last Olympics, he faces the biggest
challenge of his career _ overcoming the 21-year-old Hackett, who
won the 1,500 at the Australian trials and hasn't lost in the event
since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   For many Australians, the expected Perkins-Hackett showdown in
the finals of the 1,500 is the most anticipated event of the Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The race that stops the nation,'' wrote Ian Hanson, the
Australian swim team's press officer, in his Olympic preview for a
magazine he edits, The Swimmer. ``No matter where you are, stop,
look and listen to what many people believe will be the
most-watched 15 minutes of the Games.''
</P>
<P>
   Devitt said the Australian public treats Perkins' races in much
the same way it treats the Melbourne Cup, a horse race that takes
place every year on the first Tuesday in November and is regarded
as an occasion of national significance.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter where you are, you stop and listen to the Melbourne
Cup,'' Devitt said. ``That's what happens when Perkins is
swimming.''
</P>
<P>
   Thorpe, 10 years younger than Perkins, represents Australia's
newest obsession. Known as the ``Thorpedo,'' he is the Australian
equivalent of the Tiger Woods phenomenon, having won the world
championship in the 400 freestyle two years ago at 15 before going
on to claim world records in both the 400 and 200.
</P>
<P>
   On the first day of the Olympics, he will swim the 400, his best
event, and be a part of Australia's 400 freestyle relay.
</P>
<P>
   According to Hanson, multiple gold medals from Thorpe would make
his impact on the Sydney Games ``what (U.S. track star) Michael
Johnson was to Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   The Australian public is fixated on just about everything
relating to Thorpe, from his size-17 feet to his taste in movies
(Adam Sandler). A product of Sydney's suburbs, he has shown a
maturity beyond his years in dealing with the hype, a trait evident
at a packed pre-Olympic news conference orchestrated by the
Australian Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he had found to be the best and worst things stemming
from his success, Thorpe answered without hesitating.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best and worst are the same thing,'' he said. ``Walking
down the street, being recognized in that situation, that's
fantastic. But it also can be quite daunting. Maybe you're not
having your best day, and you want to get away from it all. That's
often very difficult to do.''
</P>
<P>
   That Australia would field one of its strongest Olympic swim
teams with Sydney serving as host of the Games is not entirely an
accident. At the same time the International Olympic Committee
awarded the Games to Australia's largest city, the country's
telecommunications giant, Telstra, began pouring money into
Australian swimming, sponsoring the national program as well as
individual competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Now that everything is in place, the pressure is on the
Australians to have a showing similar to the one the 1956 team
achieved in Melbourne, where Australia won eight of the 12 gold
medals awarded in swimming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the most humorous thing for those of us who were
there in '56 is it's taken 44 years for another Olympic team to be
compared to us,'' said Devitt, who that year earned a gold medal in
the 800 relay and a silver in the 100 freestyle. ``I can see the
connection _ the Games returning to Australia and another strong
(Australian) team. Unfortunately, it adds a lot of pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   The heat also is on the Australian swimmers to win more medals
than the United States. The U.S. medal count in Atlanta was 26, 14
more than the Australian total. In terms of gold medals, the United
States had 13 to Australia's two. The United States has won the
most Olympic swimming medals of any country _ 400 _ with Australia
second at 123.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the rivalry last week was an exchange through the
media between Perkins and U.S. sprinter Gary Hall Jr. As part of a
column he writes on the Internet, Hall said the United States would
smash the Australians ``like guitars.'' Perkins responded by
saying, ``I don't take a lot of notice of drug cheats,'' a
reference to Hall's three-month suspension in 1998 for using
marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about the rivalry have led Don Talbot, head coach of
the Australian team, to complain that the competition has been
incorrectly framed as Australia vs. the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole world tries to beat the States,'' he said.
``Obviously, you try to knock the Americans off their pedestal, but
to do that, we all need help. The German team is a great team. The
Dutch team is a great team. There are a lot of great teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trying to focus on a duel meet between the Americans and
Australians, I think you're out of your mind. The press that has
been created on those lines is by you people (the media), not us.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we're doing is trying like hell for Australia. We're going
to give the Australian crowd, the Australian people, as much as we
can, just like the Americans did in Atlanta, and try to get the
best out of ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   For the millions of Australians hanging on every stroke, that
will hopefully be good enough.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
