<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 &HT;     
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jornada Handheld Gets a Makeover
</P>
<P>
   They're smaller than a laptop _ and a breadbox _ but bigger than
a Palm Pilot. Unlike their digital siblings, however, handheld PC's
never fulfilled predictions that they were destined to become
mass-market gadgets.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is enough interest in the in-between-size PC's that
Hewlett-Packard has revamped its Jornada handheld. Cherie Britt, a
spokeswoman for the company, said that handhelds were mainly used
by people who traveled _ but not very far _ while on the job.
``They might only be around the campus or at work,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Typical customers include doctors who carry the devices while
making their rounds in large hospitals, Britt said.
</P>
<P>
   Handheld PC's also offer a feature missing from most personal
digital assistants: A keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``That allows people who are on the road to create small
documents and not just access them,'' Britt said.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a catch. To squeeze everything into a package that
is roughly twice the size of a large PDA, the Jornada's keyboard is
only three-quarters the size of a laptop keyboard. The most
obvious, and perhaps least important, difference between the
Jornada 720 and early models is color. The new model is dark blue
instead of purple.
</P>
<P>
   The new unit's processor speed has been increased to 206 MHz
from 133 MHz. But unlike laptops with more powerful CPU's, the
revised Jornada has improved battery life. Hewlett-Packard says
that the 720's lithium-ion cell will run for nine hours on a single
charge.
</P>
<P>
   The new Jornada also has a standard feature not commonly found
on PC's of any size: A built-in smart card reader. Among other
things, Britt said, the device will read the cards that many
employees need to open doors in their workplace and to prevent
unauthorized access to their computers.
</P>
<P>
   But the Jornada is not all work and no play. Unlike earlier
models, the 720 includes a jack and a volume switch for stereo
headphones. Britt said she anticipated that the feature would
mostly be used for listening to downloaded music.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Offers a System Upgrade, But It's Not Free This Time
</P>
<P>
   When Palm Computing introduced a batch of new Palm handhelds in
February with a new operating system, Palm OS 3.5, it said the new
system would be posted on its Web site in about 30 days or so. As
in the past, owners of earlier Palm models would be able to
download it for free.
</P>
<P>
   March and several more months have come and gone, and no upgrade
has been made available.
</P>
<P>
   The upgrade will be released sometime this fall, Palm now says,
but it will not be free.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically what you have seen in a Palm upgrade has been very
incremental,'' said John Cook, senior director for consumer product
marketing at the company. ``We think we have added a lot more
value.''
</P>
<P>
   OS 3.5 incorporates many features that have been available for
years as third-party add-ons: Making menus appear by tapping the
top of the screen and a new view in the calendar that shows both
appointments and ``to do'' items.
</P>
<P>
   Cook said that Palm planned to charge less than $20 for the
upgrade. It will be available on the Web or on a CD that will also
have a new version of the Palm Desktop software for personal
computers. The release is timed to coincide with the availability
of Palm's Mobile Internet Kit, which will include OS 3.5 as well as
wireless Internet software for under $50.
</P>
<P>
   Cook said that he had already heard grumbling from some Palm
users about the upgrading fee and that some future releases might
still be free.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it will make sense to charge for an upgrade,'' he
said. ``Sometimes we will just give it to you to keep you whole as
a customer.''
</P>
<P>
   A Camera That Reads Text Without Moving Its Lips
</P>
<P>
   Document scanners that can convert a page of text into an
electronic file made their debut several years ago, and they have
been saving businesses time, money and treatment bills for
repetitive-stress injuries since then. But while text scanners tend
to be big and bulky, Philips Electronics recently introduced a
small portable camera for the PC that can scan images and text on
the go, even with a laptop PC.
</P>
<P>
   The Vesta Pro Scan package, which includes the Vesta Pro camera
and PageCam software developed by Xerox, can also handle
video-conferencing chores and can record digital motion pictures at
up to 30 frames per second with a maximum resolution of 640 by 480
pixels.
</P>
<P>
   The Vesta Pro camera has a built-in microphone and easy-focus
lens and will also take still photographs at a resolution of 800 by
600 pixels.
</P>
<P>
   The small camera, which resembles an egg with a lens on the
front, connects to the computer via the USB port. It comes with a
small metal tripod to steady it for scanning text and photos. Once
an item is scanned by the camera, it can be copied and pasted from
the PageCam software into another program.
</P>
<P>
   The Vesta Pro Scan package will work with computers running
Windows 98 that have 32 megabytes of RAM and a 200-MHz
Pentium-level processor. The package has a suggested price of
$129.99, and road warriors will be heartened to know that there's
one less thing to pack _ the camera draws its power from the USB
port so there's no need to carry an extra power cord.
</P>
<P>
   Cell Phone Radiation Levels Now Published on the Web
</P>
<P>
   Do-Mode, a search engine company in Los Angeles, has published a
list of specific absorption radiation, or SAR, levels for many cell
phone models. In 1996, the Federal Communications Commission
mandated a requirement limiting SAR levels on phones sold in the
United States to less than 1.6 watts per kilogram of human tissue.
According to the list (www.sardata.com/sardata.htm), which was
compiled from information on the commission's Web site, the cell
phone with the highest SAR level in digital mode is Ericsson's T28
World model (1.49 watts per kilogram); Motorola's StarTAC 7860 has
the lowest level (0.24 watts per kilogram).
</P>
<P>
   Jo-Anne Basile of the Cellular Communications Technology
Association pointed out that these numbers represent peak radiation
levels, while SAR levels fluctuate, depending on the user's
location and the phone's battery status. She also pointed out that
the 1.6 number ``has a substantial margin of safety built into
it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
