<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3385 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-BRANDI914-COX     09-13 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BRANDI914-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In support of Brandi
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELBOURNE, AUSTRALIA _ Brandi Chastain has few moments to
reflect on her improbable fame, or just to let her mind wander.
When she does, it usually is driving down the northern California
coast, cell phone in hand, as she was doing one day in late August.
And wearing a sports bra that serves as both support and fashion
statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just how I am,'' she says while traveling to watch her
old Santa Clara University team play in San Luis Obispo. ``I wear
this everywhere. To me, it's very comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   For Chastain, being comfortable in her own skin is a literal
phrase. The indelible moment she provided after booting home the
winning penalty kick to beat China in last summer's Women's World
Cup finals drew international attention. Ripping off her white
jersey to reveal a black sports bra _ and the well-cut physique she
developed to rejuvenate her career _ became a liberating
experience.
</P>
<P>
   The 32-year-old Chastain, a leftside defender, hasn't had what
could be considered a distinctive playing career. She lost her spot
on the team for two years in the mid-1990s, and her gaffe in the
World Cup quarterfinals against Germany resulted in an own goal
that could have sunk the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   But more than a year after her stunning World Cup ride _ which
began with a nude photo spread in Gear magazine before the
tournament _ Life Beyond the Sports Bra has intensified for
Chastain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more than I could ever have hoped for,'' she said. ``More
things are coming from this that don't have anything to do with
soccer. Now, people are calling me.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, she and Mia Hamm are the only members of the U.S.
women's team to have official replica jerseys on sale.
</P>
<P>
   Today, as the U.S. women meet rival Norway on the Melbourne
Cricket Ground in their Olympic opener, the team that was
noticeably absent from NBC's airwaves in 1996 has evolved into one
of the biggest American stories of the Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
   And Chastain has become a lightning rod for a current firestorm
of debate about women athletes, their bodies and the touchy topic
of sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Women's sports activists and female sportswriters criticized
U.S. swimmer Jenny Thompson's pose for a recent Sports Illustrated
article. Thompson, in which she wore an American-flag bikini bottom
and red suede boots and cupped her hands over her breasts.
</P>
<P>
   But Chastain happily defends the photos, which she thinks just
displays a powerful body.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand what's wrong with attractive, beautiful
things,'' she said. ``I don't think about sex when I see a
beautifully toned athlete. I think of all the hard work they put
into getting that way. I can appreciate what that's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   She ought to find the relaxed cultural climate in Australia more
inviting. The Australian women's soccer team, which didn't win a
match in the World Cup, posed nude for a team calendar and caused a
ruckus earlier this year. But the Australian Olympic federation was
upset about the calendar distributors using the word ``Olympic''
without permission and not about the nakedness of the athletes.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the World Cup, just as the Gear photo spread was
published, with a glistening, muscular Chastain posing with only a
strategically placed soccer ball, she paid a visit to the David
Letterman late-night talk show.
</P>
<P>
   The photographs were shown at length. ``Babe City'' was born,
and the pop-culture bandwagon rolled through the next month,
leading to her unforgettable brandishment at the World Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   Chastain also delights in having a different perspective on her
sport in other ways. She is probably the biggest soccer nut on the
team and a real student of the game. Her belated honeymoon with
Jerry Smith, the women's soccer coach at Santa Clara, was spent at
the 1998 World Cup. If a Major League Soccer game is anywhere close
to the team's training or touring schedule, she will hop in the car
and go watch.
</P>
<P>
   Her inspiration was George Best, once the dashing genius of
Manchester United's 1968 European champions who wound down his
playing career with her hometown San Jose Earthquakes of the North
American Soccer League.
</P>
<P>
   Chastain almost ended her career after she was omitted from the
1995 World Cup team, but she has reclaimed it.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly lazy about training, Chastain was told by former
coach Tony DiCicco to get in better shape.
</P>
<P>
   After accepting that challenge, and making the transition from
striker to defender, she glorified in the triumph of Olympic gold
in 1996. She also gloried in the self-confidence she got from being
supremely fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ran my (rear) off for this body,'' she responded famously to
the critics of her Gear photos, many of them the same people who
lambasted Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have issues,'' Chastain said more recently. ``If I can
feel more comfortable with myself, then I'll stand up a little
taller and be better on the field. I don't have to be ashamed of
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
