<DOCNO> NYT20000913.0350 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3386 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-CHIPS-NYT &LR;      09-13 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-CHIPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAXIMIZING POWER BY `CAPPING' A PROCESSOR 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT HERCZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The trouble with microprocessors today, according to David
Albonesi, a professor of electrical and computer engineering at the
University of Rochester, is that they are too powerful. Most of the
programs they run tap only a fraction of a processor's capacity,
yet the unused portion exacts a price, as every notebook computer
owner who has raced against a fading battery knows. Powerful means
power-hungry.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might have one microprocessor design find its way into
everything from portable devices to high-end servers,'' Albonesi
said. ``But if you look at the characteristics of the application
software, ideally you'd like to design different microprocessor
hardware for each one, because they have different requirements.''
</P>
<P>
   Albonesi is working toward changing today's
one-processor-fits-all paradigm without changing the processor. He
is developing a model he calls complexity-adaptive processing, or
CAP, that will allow a general purpose microprocessor to conserve
power by slowing or shutting down unneeded components within a few
nanoseconds of starting an application. The process is continuous:
the configuration is re-evaluated and adjusted millions of times a
second.
</P>
<P>
   One Saturday in 1996, Albonesi stepped into his office, closed
the door, and vowed not to emerge until he had one really great new
idea. Where others might have starved in such an effort, Albonesi
appeared in time for dinner, CAP in hand.
</P>
<P>
   In only four years, Albonesi has demonstrated that one of his
techniques can reduce the power consumption of a microprocessor
(also called the central processing unit, or CPU) by up to 50
percent while increasing its performance. That has drawn interest
from IBM, whose research division is collaborating with Albonesi's
team in Rochester in a three-year study. The goal is to use CAP to
produce a prototype microprocessor that will make today's low-power
chips look insatiable by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   The breakthroughs that have made modern microprocessors so
powerful _ the number of transistors packed into a few square
millimeters of silicon and the antastic speeds at which they are
run _ are responsible for the present assault on batteries. If you
double the number of transistors, you also double the power the
processor draws.
</P>
<P>
   Since Intel released its first commercial microprocessor in
1974, the number of transistors that can be placed on a chip has
increased from 6,000 initially to nearly 10 million today. Another
factor is the CPUs clock speed, or frequency. Doubling the clock
speed also doubles the power consumption. Over the same period,
clock rates have gone from 2 MHz to 1,000 MHz. Now the CPU is the
biggest drain on a laptop's battery, outdrawing large, bright
screens and components like the hard disk and CD-ROM drives. In
some configurations, the CPU can use more watts than everything
else in the computer put together.
</P>
<P>
   That may explain why Transmeta Corp., a new company in Santa
Clara, Calif., that announced a new line of power-saving
microprocessors in January, is attracting so much interest.
Transmeta says that its Crusoe chip consumes 1 or 2 watts in normal
operation, compared with the 6 to 16 watts of other mobile CPUs.
Notebook computers with Crusoe chips are expected this fall from
Sony, Hitachi and IBM. Although the Crusoe chip is not yet on the
market, Intel and Advanced Micro Devices have responded with plans
for their own new low-power chips. Power management has become a
hot pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   Albonesi does not plan to drastically redesign the C.P.U. By
increasing the circuitry on a standard CPU by a few percent, CAP
will be able to use software to control the processor. In a limited
way, that is what Transmeta, Intel and AMD are already doing. Each
has a program that monitors how busy the microprocessor is. If the
microprocessor can be slowed down without affecting system
performance, it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of common applications run very well at 300, 400, 500
MHz, and the user isn't going to notice a huge difference in
performance, although he is going to notice a huge difference in
battery life,'' said Martin Booth, a marketing manager at AMD.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, chipmakers treat the microprocessor as an indivisible
whole, but Albonesi sees each of its many components as a candidate
to be slowed down or turned off.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the processor's own on-board memory, or cache,
stores for rapid retrieval the instructions that are used most
frequently when a program is running. But not all programs make use
of the whole cache, and the unused memory is a double burden,
wasting power and slowing the CPU.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some programs would work better with a small, fast cache
because they fit into a small amount of memory,'' Albonesi said.
``For other programs, it would be better to have that cache be
bigger, even if it was slower, because it reduces the amount of
requests that have to be made to the main memory for data. What we
have is the ability to dynamically change the cache according to
the requirements of the program.''
</P>
<P>
   Figuring out how much cache memory can be shut down is a matter
of trial and error: You keep increasing the cache size while
measuring a program's performance. When increasing the cache
results in no further improvement, you have passed the optimum.
</P>
<P>
   Deciding how to spend the gains is another question. A smaller
cache will run faster, which could improve the performance of some
programs, but would be useless in others. In those cases, CAP would
elect to slow down the cache's clock, which would further reduce
the amount of power drawn. The Rochester team has not tested its
cache design on a real microprocessor, but using a computer
simulation they have found that by reducing power demands and
improving performance the efficiency of a microprocessor can be
doubled. That's just one part of a processor.
</P>
<P>
   What applies to the cache may also apply to other CPU components
like the floating-point processor (used for complex numerical
calculations), or the units that fetch instructions from memory and
issue them to the module that will execute them. Albonesi has many
ideas about where power can be saved, but the problem now is to
find those that will deliver the biggest returns for the least
overhead. By overhead, Albonesi means the power requirements of the
hardware and software that are used to monitor the microprocessor.
</P>
<P>
   There are tradeoffs, Albonesi said. ``Nothing comes completely
for free in computer design. The tricks are to find all of the
places where you can tolerate the overhead that you are adding.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Eric Kronstadt, director of VLSI systems at the IBMs Watson
Research Center in Westchester County, N.Y., is clear about CAPs
potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you get higher performance _ not just in microprocessors
but other chips too _ they require more power,'' Dr. Eric Kronstadt
said. ``Power management is going to affect the entire spectrum,
the architecture, the implementation, the software, the circuits
that you design-everything. We will be using whatever techniques we
find that work.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
