<SLUG> BC-JANUS-FUND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JANUS CAPITAL CLOSES ITS FLAGSHIP FUND TO NEW INVESTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DANNY HAKIM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The money keeps coming, but the number of Janus funds
keeps shrinking. Wednesday, Janus Capital closed its flagship Janus
Fund to new investors, its fifth fund closing this year.
</P>
<P>
   The assets of Janus have nearly tripled since the beginning of
last year, and to effectively manage its rapidly expanding assets,
the company has now closed half of its 16 equity funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we topped the $50 billion level, I started worrying we'd
have a flood of new investors coming in that would dilute the
effect of our great ideas for current shareholders,'' said Blaine
Rollins, who took over management of the $48.6 billion Janus Fund
in January. Since the beginning of last year, the fund has nearly
doubled in size and has become the nation's fourth-largest mutual
fund.
</P>
<P>
   Such girth is generally thought to make the task of running a
fund more difficult. Investments in small and midsize companies
have less impact on the fund's performance, a manager's moves are
closely scrutinized and investments in each stock grow so large
they can be difficult to shift quietly without moving the market
price.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, several of the nation's biggest mutual funds,
including the $109.8 billion Fidelity Magellan, are closed, except
to existing investors and regular retirement plan contributions.
But Janus, the fifth-largest fund company, has growing pains
firmwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Managing their growth is a huge issue,'' said Russ Kinnel, an
analyst at the fund-tracking firm, Morningstar. ``They've grown so
fast that it's starting to strain their resources. One of the
issues is that because they have so many funds closed, it channels
the new money into the remaining funds.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the last year has been a tumultuous one for Janus.
First, there was the long-running feud between executives of Janus
and executives of its parent, Kansas City Southern Industries.
Earlier this year, Janus was packaged in a spinoff, called Stilwell
Financial, with several of Kansas City Southern's financial
holdings. Janus officials, including Thomas Bailey, the company's
founder, had publicly objected to the deal, preferring to be spun
off on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, James Craig, Janus' highly regarded chief
investment officer and the longtime manager of the Janus Fund,
retired to manage a charitable foundation.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was the market. Most of the Janus equity funds
have similar investing styles and make aggressive bets on
technology stocks _ the firm's top holding is Nokia. Last year,
those bets led Janus to chart-topping returns, and the Janus Fund
gained 47 percent, more than double the gain of the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index.
</P>
<P>
   This year, however, has not been nearly as kind to technology
investors. The Janus Fund has held up well, gaining 5.8 percent,
better than the 1 percent return of the S&AMP;P 500. But the firm's
popular Janus Twenty fund has struggled. It has lost 5.9 percent
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Janus continues to be the best-selling mutual fund
firm in the industry. The $38.8 billion in new money that came in
the first eight months of this year is already $2 billion more than
flowed in during all of last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I became concerned what the tidal wave of inflows would be
next year,'' Rollins said. ``If the fund is going to $100 billion,
I want to do that on the performance side.''
</P>
<P>
   To help absorb some of the company's new assets, Janus said it
would introduce Janus Fund 2, which will be managed by one of
Rollins' assistants. Janus Fund will remain open to existing
investors and retirement plan contributors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
