<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-QUANN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO QUANN, GOLD IS A GIVEN  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of all the Seattle-area athletes competing at the Sydney
Olympics this month, Megan Quann has the best chance of bringing
home a gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   Chance? To Quann, it's a given. Start planning that victory
parade and building that new pool in Puyallup, Wash., then unfurl
those banners for the next meet at the Megan Quann Aquatic Center.
</P>
<P>
   The brash 16-year-old leaves your head swimming with
possibilities. In Quann's world, they're probabilities.
</P>
<P>
   The junior at Puyallup High School was amazing enough in the
pool last month in Indianapolis, breaking her own American record
in the preliminaries before winning the 100-meter breastroke finals
and earning a berth on the U.S. Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   Quann made bigger ripples once she dried off and began to talk.
She may well supplant Greg Norman as the next Great White Shark, a
fierce competitor with a commanding presence and predatory nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to win the gold,'' is what Quann said before she
went to Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   After arriving, Quann swam a 1:07.12 in the preliminaries,
fastest ever by an American, and proclaimed: ``I'm very happy with
my swim, but I'm not satisfied. Because the world record is such a
low time (1:06.52), people think it's untouchable. I don't feel
that way. I have a goal to break that record, and I believe I can
get it.''
</P>
<P>
   After winning the 100 breaststroke final, Quann outdid herself
by offering up another swaggering monologue.
</P>
<P>
   Reminded that she did not break the world record as predicted,
Quann said: ``I came up a little bit short on that, but leading up
to the Olympics, I'll do that 1:05.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that South Africa's Penny Heyns owns the world-record
mark of 1:06.52, Quann said: ``She's going down. She's 26 or 27,
I'm 16. She's got a lot ahead of her. I'm going to be there, race
my heart out and win that gold.''
</P>
<P>
   In swimming, conquerors usually emerge from the pool, speak
graciously about their opponents and tell warm-and-fuzzy stories
about how their dreams of becoming an Olympian are reality.
</P>
<P>
   Along comes Quann, dissing a South African, talking smack,
making predictions and providing bulletin-board material for a
sport that usually just posts times there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what my goals are,'' Quann said from Brisbane,
Australia, where the U.S. swim team is training. ``I can accomplish
what I set my mind to. Some people say that's cocky; I'm just
saying I know what I can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are afraid to say it, because they're going to get
bad publicity or they're afraid to fail. I just figure if I don't
do it this time, I'll do it next time.''
</P>
<P>
   Her parents used to try to rein her in until Quann proved her
point, reaching what her father, Tom, thought was an unrealistic
goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to her, `Don't you think you should shoot for something
more reasonable?' I looked at her face, and she was annoyed at me.
Then she went out and did it. Ever since then, I've kept my mouth
shut.''
</P>
<P>
   Quann is already enjoying her Australian experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm loving it here,'' she said. ``Everybody is super-nice, the
weather is beautiful, we're right on the beach and I'm swimming
fast in practice.''
</P>
<P>
   When Quann dives into the pool at the Sydney International
Aquatic Center, it will be in front of 18,000 fans, all seated on
one side of the facility. ``You look up and can't even see the top
row,'' Quann said.
</P>
<P>
   Swimmers are as well-known in Australia as NBA stars are in the
United States. When Quann walks down the streets of Brisbane,
people know who she is.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of these Games, she might be known around the globe.
NBC spent three days with her a couple of months ago at her home,
preparing a Quann feature.
</P>
<P>
   What you'll see is a bedroom filled with good-luck banners,
medals and posters of various swimmers, including a former American
sweetheart, Janet Evans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's really very little wall space (left),'' said Tom
Quann.
</P>
<P>
   She might have to find room for another medal, maybe more. Asked
if she planned to win gold, Quann said: ``Definitely ... two of
'em.'' Quann also hopes to swim in the 400-medley relay in the
breaststroke leg of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence shows that Quann just may back up her beliefs. In what
might be a gamble for others, Quann tapered with the Olympics in
mind, not the U.S. Olympic swimming trials. That's risky: if you
don't finish in the top two at the trials, you don't get a sniff of
Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   If you taper for the trials and qualify for the Games, then you
have to load up on the laps again, and probably won't be in prime
shape for the gold-medal race.
</P>
<P>
   Also, even though Heyns holds the world record, Quann has the
fastest time this year and beat Heyns in the 100 breaststroke last
December in the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``She hasn't gone under 1:08 since the Pan Pacific
(Championships) last year,'' Quann said.
</P>
<P>
   So get out the confetti and ticker tape: Quann will be coming
home Oct. 2, perhaps as a conquering hero.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
