u s BC-OLY-TEENS-SPI &LR;      09-13 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TEENS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FUTURE IS NOW: YOUTH WILL BE SERVED IN SYDNEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM CAPLE   
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carl Lewis won't be there. Jackie Joyner-Kersee won't be there.
Matt Ghaffari won't be there, either.
</P>
<P>
   But if many of the familiar faces from Olympics past are absent
in Sydney, there are plenty of younger athletes ready to replace
them.
</P>
<P>
   Make that very young.
</P>
<P>
   Puyallup (Wash.) high school swimmer Megan Quann is 16 and
doesn't have a driver's license. American backstroker Aaron Peirsol
is 17. Australian swimmer Ian Thorpe is 17. American weightlifter
Cheryl Haworth is 17. Chinese diver Sang Xue is 16.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, do you feel old yet?
</P>
<P>
   Gymnast brothers Paul and Morgan Hamm are 17. Gymnast Elise Ray
is 18. Australian women's basketball forward/center Lauren Jackson
is 19.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of Juan Antonio Samaranch, Harry Potter should preside
over the Games. 'N Sync should sing the national anthems.
</P>
<P>
   They are young enough to be the children of some of the
Olympians, young enough to make Marion Jones seem like a cast
member of the ``Golden Girls.'' But they didn't qualify for the
Olympics by lacking confidence or approaching their sports timidly.
</P>
<P>
   Quann won the 100-meter breaststroke at the U.S. Olympic trials
and is a favorite to win a medal in Sydney, while her classmates
ponder the Pythagorean Theorem on the other side of the world. In
fact, she was disappointed when she won the event, because she
didn't also break the world record.
</P>
<P>
   ``You usually see the 15- and 16-year-olds all bubbly and happy
to be there,'' American gold medalist Rowdy Gaines said. ``Well,
she's not happy just to be there. She wants to win and she wants
the world record.''
</P>
<P>
   After qualifying at the U.S. Trials, Quann predicted that she
will smash the world record and beat reigning world champ Penny
Heyns of South Africa, saying with the confidence and perspective
of youth, ``She's 26 or 27. I'm 16.''
</P>
<P>
   Quann probably won't be the teen with the most medals draped
around her neck at the pool, though.
</P>
<P>
   Nicknamed ``Thorpedo,'' Thorpe is a sports icon in Australia,
where swimming is virtually the country's national pastime. His
size 17 feet prompted at least one scientist to speculate that they
aid him by working as flippers, but that diminishes his amazing
accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   Thorpe won his first world championship at age 14, set six world
records in an 18-month span and would be a major disappointment if
he didn't win at least two gold medals in Sydney, where he will be
swimming in front of a very partisan home crowd of 15,000 howling
Australians.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a heavy burden for him to bear, especially for a
17-year-old,'' Gaines said. ``It could be a crash-and-burn
situation for him, like Mark Spitz in 1968.''
</P>
<P>
   Peirsol, meanwhile, is closing ground (or water) quickly on
world champion Lenny Krayzelburg, an old man at age 24 in the 200
back.
</P>
<P>
   There are usually young swimmers and gymnasts competing at the
Olympics _ remember Janet Evans in 1988? Nadia Comaneci in 1976? _
but Haworth is a much more interesting case.
</P>
<P>
   In a sport where the best weight lifters generally reach their
peak around age 30, she is a serious gold-medal candidate before
being old enough to vote.
</P>
<P>
   The Savannah, Ga., native can lift nearly 300 pounds above her
head (the equivalent of more than two Megan Quanns), leg-press
almost 500 pounds and has a 26-inch vertical leap. She can outlift
any boy in her age group. She lifts 15-30 tons during her two-hour
workouts, more than an offensive lineman might lift in a normal
workout, the equivalent of five African elephants.
</P>
<P>
   She is 5-feet-10 and weighs 306 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   And she's a senior in high school.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, opponents will be dealing with her for a very
long time. As they will with the other teens, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that no matter what happens to me,'' Haworth told
reporters, ``I think I'm going to keep going until I absolutely
can't do it anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
