<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR THURSDAY, SEPT. 14 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds.: These corrections appeared in The New York Times on
Thursday, Sept. 14. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-DEATH-PENALTY-STUDY (moved Monday, September 11)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, September
11 about a Justice Department review of the federal death penalty
misstated the record of the United States attorney's office in
Alaska since 1995 on referrals of capital cases to the department
for review. It has indeed submitted a case, but only one.
</P>
<P>
   BC-NY-OLYMPICS-NYT (moved Monday, September 11)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, September
11 about plans to lure the Olympic Games to New York City in 2012
referred incorrectly to the schedule for the Games that year. They
will be held from July 27 to Aug. 12, not in September.
</P>
<P>
   BC-DRESDNER-WASSERSTEIN-MARKETPLACE-NYT (moved Tuesday,
September 12)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, September
12 about talks over the possible acquisition of Wasserstein Perella
&AMP; Co. by Dresdner Bank of Germany, misstated the given name of
Wasserstein's chief executive. He is Michael Biondi. (Frank Biondi
Jr., his brother, is a senior managing director at WaterView
Advisors in Santa Monica, Calif.)
</P>
<P>
   BC-VIDEO-CHIP-NYT (moved Sunday, September 10)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, September
10 about a new digital camera chip made by Foveon misstated the
type of film cameras that it might be able to challenge. Images
made from the chip could one day be comparable to those made by
so-called medium-format cameras, made by Hasselblad and others,
which use film that is 6 by 6 centimeters. The chip images are not
comparable to those made from film that is 4 by 5 inches, which
produces a higher resolution. Hasselblad does not make a 4-by-5
camera.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
