<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3411 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-ADIDAS-WEBSTER14-     09-13 0403
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ADIDAS-WEBSTER14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia's Webster always out front
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sydney _ Not long ago, Antoine Webster was running out front
during his baseball workouts. Next thing he knew, he was on a ``747
double-decker '' headed to the Olympics. Not bad for a boy of 13.
</P>
<P>
   This kid from Lithonia, Ga., is fierce.
</P>
<P>
   One of 50 youngsters from nine countries who came here this week
for a track and field competition put on by Adidas, Webster has
been living the life. When he gets back to his ninth-grade class at
Stephenson High School on Monday, he won't be wearing any gold
medals. But give him a few years.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he's been:
</P>
<P>
   Surfing the Pacific. ``I got up on the board about four times,
but it was extremely cold, big-time. We wore wet suits, but it
didn't help.''
</P>
<P>
   Checking out Australian wildlife at the Sydney Aquarium. ``We
saw the sharks, the penguins, the crocodiles, the seals. I'd never
seen seals or penguins in person before. Or sharks.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering the flavor of kangaroo: ``If I find a place, I might
try it. It's all about new experiences.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not Webster makes the 2004 Olympic team, he's already
a hero. He won the 200-meter in the friendly Adidas
competitionWednesday, and placed second in his group in the
800-meter.
</P>
<P>
   His coaches noticed that he was swift when he was 7 or 8. During
baseball warm-ups, ``I used to be in the front a lot. So I went out
for track, and I've been good ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's evident in all the games we have done that Antoine is an
excellent athlete,'' said Jennifer Thomas, a promotions specialist
with Adidas America. ``He's a fabulous kid.
</P>
<P>
   A straight-A student who won an essay contest that got him into
the preliminary sports competition in Sacramento, Calif., earlier
this year, Webster is undoubtedly the apple of the eye of his mom,
Felecia Williams, a U.S. Postal Service supervisor in Atlanta. ``I
have three choices for a profession, either be an architect, an
engineer or a doctor,'' he says. ``I don't know. I haven't narrowed
down the choice.''
</P>
<P>
   So many choices. The other night, they fed him a fancy dish of
pasta and salmon. It was so-so. ``Now if they had put a plate of
catfish in front of me, I would have eaten that.''
</P>
<P>
   Spoken like a life-long Georgia boy.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
