u p BC-GORE-HNS &LR;      09-13 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Gore dashes off to school for history lesson, in grueling
campaign day
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By PATTY REINERT
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEWISTON, Maine _ Democratic presidential nominee Al Gore
grabbed four hours' sleep and downed a blueberry scone Wednesday
before picking up his already brutal campaign pace, teaching a high
school history class in Maine, taking a ferry boat ride in
Massachusetts and rallying supporters in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president emerged from the home of Lewiston High School
teachers Donald and Susan Jalbert shortly after 7 a.m. and posed
for a photo with the family after spending the night on their
fold-out couch.
</P>
<P>
   On his way down the driveway, he turned back to whisper
something to 12-year-old Marissa Jalbert, who was still in her bare
feet, getting ready for school. She ran inside the house and
returned to hand Gore a diet soda as he boarded a van with the
Jalberts and their 16-year-old son, Nathan.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Jalbert said that Gore, who arrived late Tuesday after
attending a fund-raiser in New Jersey, had stayed up talking with
the family until after 2 a.m. Wednesday
</P>
<P>
   At Lewiston High, the vice president gave history students a
lesson on the Electoral College and presidential term limits, ate
lunch in the school cafeteria, and promised to help parents pay for
their children's college education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every one of you who wants to go to college, ought to be able
to go to college, regardless of your family's income,'' Gore told
the students. ``And I say that not just because it's good for you,
but because it's good for our country.``
</P>
<P>
   Gore has spent the week touting his 10-year, $170 billion
education plan, calling for universal preschool, increased teacher
salaries and standards, smaller class sizes and funding to fix
decaying schools and to connect more schools to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, he turned his attention to college education,
pledging to increase enrollment by making tuition tax-deductible,
increasing federal education grants and creating tax-free savings
plans to pay for lifelong education and job-training to keep up
with technology.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's plan includes a tax deduction for up to $10,000 a year
spent on tuition and fees for college, graduate school or
job-training. It also would create a 401(j) account, modeled after
the 401(k), to allow workers to get employer matching funds to save
tax-free for their children's college or their own continuing
education.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also proposes creating a National College Tuition Savings
plan, which would link existing state programs that allow parents
to pre-pay their children's college tuition at today's rates. He
would expand the federal Pell grant program to help more low-income
students and would reduce interest rates for student loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many kids are graduating from college with the equivalent
of a home mortgage, and they don't have a home,'' Gore told a group
of parents, teachers and students gathered in the school library.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then they (ITAL) come (UNITAL) home,'' he joked.
</P>
<P>
   Saddled with that debt, many young people are forced to launch
immediately into high-paying careers without having time to explore
other options, such as considering lower-paying teaching jobs or
taking time out to volunteer before beginning their working life.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Gore flew to Boston for a rally, where he was confronted
with protesters denouncing, among other things, the Gore family's
ties with Occidental Petroleum and the company's plans to drill
near lands claimed by the U'Wa, (CQ) an indigenous people in
Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators interrupted Gore's speech with chants, and a
group of the vice president's supporters briefly scuffled with the
protesters until police separated the groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's hear it for the First Amendment,'' Gore said before
continuing his address. ``Let's hear it for free speech.''
</P>
<P>
   With Gore in Boston were his running mate, Sen. Joseph
Lieberman, D-Conn., and Sen. Ted Kennedy, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday evening, Gore was to attend a Democratic National
Committee fund-raiser featuring singer James Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he has scheduled a visit to a junior high school in
Manchester, N.H., before joining daughters Karenna Gore-Schiff and
Sarah Gore in New York for a youth event.
</P>
<P>
   Later, he is to appear on the ``David Letterman Show'' and
attend another DNC fund-raising concert, this one at Radio City
Music Hall and featuring Jimmy Buffett, Bette Midler and Paul
Simon, among many other performers who are helping him bring in
more than $7 million total for the Democratic Party this week.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
