u p BC-CAMPAIGN-GORE-BOS &LR;      09-13 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-GORE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE GETS THE HARBOR TOUR ON ARRIVAL IN BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By YVONNE ABRAHAM AND MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ After a morning spent preaching his education policies
in Maine, Al Gore paid a visit Wednesday to the choir: heavily
Democratic Boston, for a rally at Long Wharf and a million-dollar
fund-raiser at the Park Plaza Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Flanked by his running mate, Connecticut Senator Joseph I.
Lieberman, Boston Mayor Thomas M. Menino, and two Kennedys _
Senator Edward Kennedy and his nephew, former Representative Joseph
Kennedy _ Gore arrived in novel fashion, with a blustery ferry ride
across a gleaming Boston Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   In a scene reminiscent of Camelot, Senator Kennedy pointed out
landmarks to Gore and Lieberman, dressed casually, the wind
whipping their hair.
</P>
<P>
   As the sun set over the harbor, lighting up the many sailboats
behind him, Gore told an appreciative crowd of about two thousand
of his great fondness for Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this city,'' Gore said. ``I proposed to my wife Tipper
in this city.''
</P>
<P>
   All of Gore's and Lieberman's rallying cries found cheers, all
the punchlines laughter. At one point, Menino, as if conceding the
redundancy of the rally, urged those in the crowd to spread the
word on to people in other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got this crowd well prepared, Teddy,'' Lieberman joked
at one point.
</P>
<P>
   Not quite well prepared enough, however. When Gore rose to
speak, discordant notes arose in this unlikeliest of places, as a
small but loud group of protesters raised signs and chanted, ``Al
Gore's a corporate puppet!'' and ``Fair trade, not free trade!''
and ``No blood for oil!''
</P>
<P>
   One Gore supporter moved close to the group and began shaking a
Gore sign, to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need more signs,'' he said, forlornly.
</P>
<P>
   More came, as a group of black T-shirted Carpenters' Union
members rushed over to block the protesters. A scuffle ensued, and
police, who descended on the area, removed the unionists, leaving
the protesters to their chants.
</P>
<P>
   They were so loud that Gore eventually had to recognize them.
``Let's hear it for the First Amendment,'' he yelled, to deafening
cheers. ``Let's hear it for freedom of speech!''
</P>
<P>
   From then on, he pulled out all the stops to whip the crowd into
cheers loud enough to take back the rally.
</P>
<P>
   He repeated the I-may-be-boring-but-I-can-do-a-great-job mantra
begun with his speech at the Democratic National Convention, in a
form especially tailored to his audience: ``I will not always be
the most exciting politician, like Tom Menino,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   More deafening cheers.
</P>
<P>
   From the rally, at which he hit many populist notes, Gore went
on to the Western-themed fund-raiser at the Park Plaza, where
singer James Taylor was to entertain the crowd. A thousand guests
each paid $1,000 to attend the event, which raised $2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday was typical of Gore's campaign style, mixing detailed
discussion of the issues with boisterous rallies and glittering
fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, after yet another day devoted to his education message,
Gore plans to appear on the ``David Letterman Show'' in New York
and attend yet another money marathon, picking up $5 million at a
Radio City Music Hall gala hosted by Michael Douglas, and attended
by actors Julia Roberts and Ben Affleck, among many others.
</P>
<P>
   But between the celebrity-filled events, Gore relentlessly
focuses on the issue he is convinced will help him win the
election: education.
</P>
<P>
   He spent Tuesday night at the home of a Maine teacher, as he
often does on what he calls ``school days.'' Wednesday, he headed
to Lewiston High School. Addressing the US history class of teacher
Joan M. Macri, Gore got a lesson himself. The blackboard featured
pictures of past presidents including George Bush, the father of
his Republican opponent, as well as a fact sheet about the
difficulty of vice presidents ascending to the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Gore ended his visit to Lewiston High at one of his favorite
venues, a packed-to-the-rafters gymnasium, filled with cheering
students, cheerleaders, and marching bands. ``You're our Maine
man,'' a poster said. While Maine has only four electoral votes,
the state is considered a tossup that could make a difference on
Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day at a news conference on the State House
steps, Governor Paul Cellucci gave Gore failing grades on his
education record and proposals.
</P>
<P>
   The governor stood in front of a placard labeled ``Al Gore's
Education Report Card.'' He gave the vice-president a ``D-'' on
``cutting red tape'' and three ``F's'' for ``closing the
achievement gap,'' ``insisting on accountabilty and standards'' and
``expanding parental choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci said US students have dropped further behind their
international competitors during the Clinton-Gore adnministration.
He hailed Bush for supporting Texas reforms, such as a high-stakes
standardized test and a school rating system, that may have boosted
that state's scores on national tests. Bush didn't initiate those
reforms, but he has been credited with keeping them in place.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Scott S. Greenberger of the Globe staff contributed to this story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-00 2121EDT &QL; 
