<HEADLINE>
H&AMP;R BLOCK ANNUAL MEETING PAYS TRIBUTE TO RETIRING CO-FOUNDER HENRY
BLOCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GENE MEYER  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Shareholders and employees of H&AMP;R Block Inc.
gave retiring company co-founder and Chairman Henry Bloch a
standing ovation Wednesday at the company's annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Bloch's departure, which was announced earlier this year, marks
the first time since just after World War II that the Kansas
City-based enterprise or a predecessor company, United Business
Co., has been without a member of the Bloch family at its head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Building a company is a lot like raising a child,'' Bloch told
shareholders, employees and other guests at the meeting at the
Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to instill values, purpose and character. You work
hard. You take some risks. You worry a lot. Along the way, you try
to provide direction, guidance and set an example.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the child grows up and comes into its own and, if you are
lucky, surprises you by accomplishing great things _ things you
never imagined possible. That has been so true of my life with this
company.''
</P>
<P>
   After a 15-minute video tribute _ narrated by veteran newsman
Walter Cronkite _ that outlined Block's growth from a second-story
walk-up office near 31st and Main streets to an international
enterprise serving more than 19 million clients worldwide, Bloch
reflected on his career. He spoke of the enterprise's significant
milestones _ franchising the operation in the late 1950s; becoming
publicly traded and expanding across the United States and into
Canada and Europe in the 1960s and 1970s; and its forays into
electronic filing in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have shared smooth highways, navigated a few bumpy roads,
even taken a few wrong turns,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He thanked family members and key executives whose help and
guidance made those milestones possible and the entire group of
thousands of longtime tax preparers and other associates who, by
earning the trust and loyalty of millions of customers over the
decades, have become what he called the heart and soul of H&AMP;R
Block.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping those bonds will be vital to the company's future as it
continues to expand into new and more complex financial services
enterprises, Bloch said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we adhere to high standards, I believe our
customers will continue to appreciate us and our company will
continue to thrive,'' Bloch said.
</P>
<P>
   Frank L. Salizzoni, who succeeds Bloch as company chairman, and
Mark Ernst, the company's president and chief operating officer,
pledged to maintain those high standards as an important part of a
strategy to recover from setbacks in the last 12 months on Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   Investors dismayed by Block's acquisition last year of Olde
Financial Corp., the nation's fourth-largest discount brokerage
operation, and by lower than expected earnings in the year ended
April 30 have sold shares so heavily that the total value of
Block's shares on the market has dropped more than 40 percent in
less than 12 months, Salizzoni said.
</P>
<P>
   To recover, ``we're developing plans that build on the strengths
of our business and also address the difficulties of this past
year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders peppered company executives with questions about
recent litigation, higher pricing for company services and changes
in the management structure at some tax service offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We share the concern about pricing,'' Ernst said. He said the
company was reviewing its prices and practices to make sure
customers were getting full value for services offered.
</P>
<P>
   Ernst told shareholders that the esteem and trust that Block had
developed with tax clients over the years would be an important
element of future plans.
</P>
</TEXT>
