<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Americans welcomed to Village
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sydney _ The U.S. Olympic team received its official welcome and
the American flag was raised today in the Olympic Village. The flag
waved against the backdrop of a massive Cuban flag draped over
three stories of a four-story residential building.
</P>
<P>
   About 150 athletes, coaches and USOC officials attended the
welcoming ceremony, which was one of 32 staged today. Another 45
will be staged Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my gosh, it brought tears to my eyes,'' taekwondo player
Barbara Kunkel said. ``The kids singing the `G'day Song' _ we're
trying to find out if we can get it on CD _ and just hearing the
national anthem again.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabine Sugarman of Atlanta, a protocol manager in the village,
was chosen by her staff to carry the placard for the U.S. team in
the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very inspiring to be with the athletes,'' said Sugarman,
who was protocol manager of the Olympic family hotel in Atlanta.
``You get a very good feeling about humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   Children wearing body paint and the traditional costume
performed a program of Aboriginal dance. Some 50 students from an
elementary school sang ``The Star-Spangled Banner'' with an Aussie
twang, along with the specially composed ``G'day Song.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a wonderful village here,'' said Sandra Baldwin, the
U.S. chef de mission, or team leader, who received a ceremonial
``message stick.'' ``We've got a very focused team and they're just
a great bunch of kids.''
</P>
<P>
   She certainly hopes so. If there's trouble, as in Nagano where
U.S. hockey players trashed some of the rooms, Baldwin will have to
handle it.
</P>
<P>
   GYMNASTICS
</P>
<P>
   Close call for McCain
</P>
<P>
   U.S. gymnast Stephen McCain did not mind that the name card at
his seat read ``Stephanie'' at a news conference Wednesday. He was
just glad to be in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   McCain suffered a serious ankle sprain 11 days ago at a training
camp and did not know until Wednesday if he would be healthy enough
to compete in the Olympics. Coach Peter Kormann tested McCain at
podium training Wednesday. ``He responded with brilliance,''
Kormann said. ``He gets the badge of courage for today.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain hurt himself during a training camp in San Diego on a
floor-exercise dismount. ``Needless to say, I did it very bad and
landed on my face and crunched both my ankles,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The right ankle was worse than the left, and the next morning
McCain was on crutches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I woke up and started crying because I couldn't even stand on
my feet,'' McCain said. ``To make the team, and then all of a
sudden, it was like it was gone _ it was hard to cope with at
first.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain probably will be the third all-arounder, with Blaine
Wilson and Paul Hamm, because three-time Olympian John
Roethlisberger has sore legs and a strained calf muscle and cannot
do floor exercise or vault.
</P>
<P>
   WEIGHTLIFTING
</P>
<P>
   Here comes the bride
</P>
<P>
   U.S. weightlifting team reserve Suzanne Leathers won't march in
the Opening Ceremonies. Instead, she'll walk down the aisle.
</P>
<P>
   Leathers, a Rhode Island native who has been training in
Savannah, and Don McCauley will wed today at the Bankstown Sports
Club in suburban Sydney. U.S. coach Michael Cohen of Savannah will
give Leathers away, with teammates Cheryl Haworth, Cara Heads-Lane
and Robin Goad in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   The bride and groom even invited the international media and
vowed to be available for interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ETC.
</P>
<P>
   Some bus drivers walk out
</P>
<P>
   Transport problems at the Games intensified when dozens of
drivers quit the Olympic bus service, saying they were angry about
working conditions and poor organization of timetables. Fifty
drivers reportedly failed to come to work Wednesday.... The
International Olympic Committee ended its three-day session by
choosing 14 new members, including U.S. Olympic committee president
Bill Hybl and former Kenyan distance running great Kip Keino.
Thomas Bach, a former German Olympic fencing champion, was elected
as one of the IOC's four vice presidents, defeating Japan's Chiharu
Igaya. Former U.S. Secretary of State Henry Kissinger was one of
five ``honor members'' chosen.... U.S. baseball team pitcher Jon
Rauch, who had a combined 16-4 record and a 2.66 ERA at two
minor-league levels, was selected minor league player of year by
Baseball America.... Bulgarian triple and long jumper Iva
Prandzheva and Kazakstan swimmer Yevgeniya Yermakova were barred
from the Games after positive drug tests.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
