<HEADER>
A3424 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-APPLE-BETA-NYT &LR;      09-13 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-APPLE-BETA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UP AND RUNNING IN 25 MINUTES 
</HEADLINE>
  (With CIR-APPLE) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER WITH DON DONOFRIO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Mac OS X beta software comes neatly packaged from Apple
inside a clean white folder with a big blue X on the front. Even
though Apple says X should be pronounced ``ten,'' the enigmatic
appeal of the letter X seems vaguely more appropriate. X, after
all, is the unknown _ and the unknown is both the joy and the curse
of betaware.
</P>
<P>
   Following documentation included with the Mac OS X CD-ROM, we
installed a copy of the Mac OS X beta onto a separate 9-gigabyte
disk partition (akin to giving the OS a hard drive all its own) of
a 400-megahertz iMac running Mac OS 9.0.4 with 128 megabytes of
RAM. We were up and running in about 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't have a lot of time to jump into OS X and pound on it,
so what follows is mostly what we observed, not the results of a
true test. The system generally behaved quite well, although it
would get sluggish on occasion
</P>
<P>
   The Aqua interface is visually stunning, but it took a few
minutes to adjust to some of the new features. The old standby
Apple Menu is gone, as is the Chooser. Applications can be launched
from the Dock, the animated palette at the bottom of the screen,
from the applications' icon or desktop aliases. The desktop and the
Finder have been separated, and the Finder now reveals your
computer's contents in a window that resembles a Web browser's,
with shortcut and Back buttons and three different views.
</P>
<P>
   Open windows seem to hover in the foreground of the screen,
casting shadows on the desktop and other windows underneath them.
Animated Save dialog boxes glide down from document title bars, and
buttons slowly pulsate until clicked. Each title bar contains a
Minimize button that sends the windows swirling into the Dock when
clicked. The System Preferences icon in the Dock allows users to
change system settings, much like the Control Panels in the Apple
menu used to do. There are even options for running the system in
English, French or German right out of the box.
</P>
<P>
   We were able to switch back and forth between Mac OS 9 and the
OS X beta systems, and even work in old software programs and print
documents in what Apple calls the Classic environment, which
basically flips you back into OS 9 for using older software
programs.
</P>
<P>
   While the user interface is elegant and intuitive, it is merely
eye candy if all it does is look pretty. The core of the system is
called Darwin, which is based on the Berkeley Software Distribution
variant of Unix. It contains all the hallmarks of a modern
operating system, like pre-emptive multitasking and protected
memory. Pre-emptive multitasking basically means that the system
will work faster and more efficiently. Protected memory (which can
be seen in action with the included Process Manager application)
which protects against the whole system crashing when a single
program does. Unfortunately, the Classic environment is not
protected this way. The booklet included with the beta CD was
clearly written and provided comparisions between Mac OS 9 and Mac
OS X that helped make sense of the changes in OS X more quickly.
The beta is not a complete system, as support for many
network-related functions and external hardware devices aren't
included yet.
</P>
<P>
   Beta hopefuls will need to have a machine running Mac OS 9 with
least a G3 processor, 128 megabytes of RAM, 1.5 gigbytes if hard
disk space and an internal video card. The original G3 PowerBook
and computers upgraded with G3 cards are not supported. Full system
requirements and support information are available on Apple's Web
site at www.apple.com/support/macosx.
</P>
<P>
   As with all beta software, however, the user should be aware
that it is still a work-in-progress and putting it on any Mac that
is critical to daily work or functions is not advised. If you have
the resources to try the Mac OS X beta, there is a lot of
intriguing new territory _ and probably some bugs _ to explore. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So is the Mac OS X beta for you?
</P>
<P>
   It depends on how you plan to use it. The beta comes complete
with a useable email client and a blazingly fast version of
Microsoft Internet Explorer written for OS X. There is a growing
list of other applications written for it, which will become
available as the beta becomes more widely used. Using Mac OS X is a
real treat.
</P>
<P>
   The stunning interface is intuitive and is new while still
feeling mac-like. However, if you will need to rely heavily on
applications that require the Classic environment, it would be best
to wait for a more mature version of Mac OS X.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
