<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TUVALU-UN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELCOME TO THE UNITED NATIONS, TUVALU!
</HEADLINE>
 
 (EDS: Corrects Eritrea information)  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By JESSIE MILLIGAN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It seemed so surprisingly modern for the tiny South Pacific
nation of Tuvalu to join the United Nations last week, hoisting
above New York City streets its light-blue flag that fluttered in
the breeze as an emblem of entry into the modern world.
</P>
<P>
   Tuvalu, however, a group of nine coral atolls halfway between
Australia and Hawaii, unwittingly joined the world community some
time ago. Its entry may spell great fortune as islanders become
Internet entrepreneurs. And it may mean great tragedy: Scientists
predict that the low-lying islands will disappear under the waves
if global warming continues to raise sea levels. Tuvalu could
become the next Atlantis. Just as easily, it could find a way to
thrive in a technologically sophisticated world.
</P>
<P>
   Will the people of Tuvalu be survivors? Intrigued? We were, too.
Here's our guide to Tuvalu, a tiny nation feeling the stresses of
the modern world:
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Geography 101 stats:
</P>
<P>
   Population: 10,000, about the same number of people as Saginaw,
Texas, or the Dallas enclave of Highland Park
</P>
<P>
   Size of islands: 10 square miles
</P>
<P>
   Life expectancy: 68 years, at least 10 years less than life
expectancy in the United States
</P>
<P>
   Chief export: Dried coconut meat, used in making coconut oil
</P>
<P>
   Imports: Food, fuel and manufactured goods
</P>
<P>
   Nationhood: Tuvalu gained independence from Britain in 1978
</P>
<P>
   Amenities: One unpaved road, few computers, no newspapers, few
televisions, and airline service is so poor that only about 1,000
tourists venture to its shores each year
</P>
<P>
   What it's known for: American World War II veterans may remember
Tuvalu by its former name of Ellice Islands, and recall it as home
to three now-abandoned war-era American airfields.
</P>
<P>
   Income: Licenses sold to American, Korean and Taiwanese tuna
fishing boats, and revenue from a trust fund set up by the
governments of Australia, New Zealand and the United Kingdom. Other
revenue comes from the sale of colorful postage stamps to
collectors.
</P>
<P>
   GNP: $10 million in U.S. dollars
</P>
<P>
   Average annual income: Higher managerial, $9,983 in U.S.
dollars; clerical, $4,308
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The islands stand to make a fortune from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The nation of Tuvalu in April sold its Internet domain, .tv, for
$50 million to DotTV, a business started by Idealab of Pasadena,
Calif., to sell the .tv domain spaces to folks who will probably
pay large sums for the descriptive Web site address.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the United Kingdom received .uk as a domain name, and
Austraila received .au, Tuvalu was assigned the .tv location long
before anyone knew how lucrative that address suffix would prove to
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very, very, very poor, but now we are getting some
money from the marketing of assets like .tv,'' Tuvalu Parliament
member Koloa Talake told the Los Angeles Times in April.
</P>
<P>
   Talake, who says he has never even seen a Web site, now holds a
seat on DotTV's board.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet millions are to be paid to Tuvalu in increments of
$1 million a quarter.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The island once made lots of money from phone sex operations.
</P>
<P>
   The DotTV deal isn't the first time islanders have tried to cash
in on technology. In 1996, new telephone service to the islands
created excess international service capacity, which islanders
sold. Unfortunately, the buyers of Tuvalu's international access
code, 688, were telephone sex operators in Japan, the United States
and the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1998, the arrangement earned Tuvalu ($68,550 in U.S.
dollars), and 10 percent of the country's budget is now covered by
income from telephone sex,'' writes David Stanley, author of ``The
South Pacific Handbook'' (Avalon Travel Publishing, 1999.)
</P>
<P>
   The contracts with the operators were later canceled by
officials in the Christian nation.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   You can see Tuvalu on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Tuvalu isn't entirely removed from the Western world.
</P>
<P>
   A ``Tuvalu-Canadian'' family on the islands runs a Web site
called Tuvalu online. Its address is
http://members.xoom.com//tuvaluonline.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Tuvalu's window to the world
</P>
<P>
   A few of the islands have solar-powered satellite
telecommunications receivers, allowing the handful of TV owners to
pick up MTV, CNN, the Disney Channel and other cable stations,
according to Stanley. ``South Pacific Handbook'' (Avalon Travel
Publishing, 1999).
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The island is disappearing (perhaps making this the perfect
setting for a future ``Survivor'' series?).
</P>
<P>
   Residents of the islands are noticing that the Pacific Ocean
keeps creeping deeper onto their properties.
</P>
<P>
   Enele Sopoaga, Tuvalu's ambassador to Fiji, told reporters last
year that sea levels are forecast to rise between more than a foot
to more than 3 feet within 100 years, due to climatic shifts toward
warmer temperatures, which is melting the polar ice caps. The
climate change is attributed partly to emissions from fossil fuels.
</P>
<P>
   Tuvalu sits, on average, 3 feet above sea level, and seawater
already laps at some doors during particularly high tides.
</P>
<P>
   The plight has attracted the attention of U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan, who said in a special session of the General Assembly
last year that there is ``trouble in paradise'' because of global
warming.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Tuvalu government pleaded for foreign assurance
of assistance. In June, New Zealand Foreign Minister Phil Goff
promised that New Zealand, Australia and other Pacific nations will
welcome anyone from Tuvalu displaced by rising water.
</P>
<P>
   Sopoaga, in an account carried by the San Jose Mercury News last
year, said: ``Our people are a religious people. This is the main
topic of our church services and prayers. We believe God will
somehow show his hand of protection to the small island states and
Tuvalu.'' He is said to have fallen silent as tears sprang to his
eyes. ``I really don't know where we will be in 50 years' time,
whether there will still be a place called Tuvalu.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Fine footsteps: The 10 nations to join the United Nations most
recently, by date:
</P>
<P>
   Tuvalu _ (Sept. 5, 2000) Islands in the South Pacific
</P>
<P>
   Tonga _ (Sept. 14, 1999) Islands in the South Pacific
</P>
<P>
   Nauru _ (Sept. 14, 1999) A single island in the South Pacific
</P>
<P>
   Kiribati _ (Sept. 14, 1999) Islands in the Western Pacific,
formerly the Gilbert and Line Islands
</P>
<P>
   Palau _ (Dec. 15, 1994) Islands in the western Pacific
</P>
<P>
   Andorra _ (July 28, 1993) Tiny principality in the Pyrenees
between France and Spain
</P>
<P>
   Eritrea _ (May 28, 1993) A breakaway from Ethiopia, in the Horn
of Africa
</P>
<P>
   Monaco _ (May 28, 1993) Mediterranean enclave in southeast
France
</P>
<P>
   The former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia _ (April 8, 1993) Like
Croatia and Bosnia-Herzegovina, a breakaway from Yugoslavia
</P>
<P>
   Slovakia _ (Jan. 19, 1993) A Central European nation surrounded
by Poland, Ukraine, Hungary, Austria and the Czech Republic;
formerly part of Czechoslovakia.
</P>
<P>
   Source: United Nations
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
