<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3434 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-MEDIA-VIOLENCE-HNS &LR;      09-13 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-VIOLENCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Lieberman, Lynne Cheney accuse entertainment companies of
contributing to youth violence
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By STEVE LASH
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice presidential candidate Joseph Lieberman found
common ground with Lynne Cheney, the wife of his Republican
opponent, as they accused entertainment companies Wednesday of
contributing to youth violence by marketing their violent and
sexually oriented material to children.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing separately before a Senate committee, Lieberman and
Cheney urged makers of movies, musical recordings and video games
to act responsibly and not advertise adult-themed entertainment to
youngsters. While both said the entertainment industry should
restrain itself, Lieberman _ Vice President Al Gore's running mate
_ added that federal regulators should step in if self-restraint
fails.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, whose husband, Richard, is running with Texas Gov.
George W. Bush, made an overt reference to the presidential
campaign, saying she hopes Lieberman makes that strong case to
entertainment executives at a Democratic Party fund-raiser in New
York City tonight. (THURSDAY)
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Lieberman, a U.S. senator from Connecticut, said
the candidate has no qualms about telling Hollywood moguls what he
thinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not shy about sharing his concerns about the negative
impact the entertainment industry has on children,'' said spokesman
Dan Gerstein. ``He is not afraid to tell his friends when they're
doing something wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Spurring the Senate Commerce Committee's examination of the
entertainment industry was the release of a Federal Trade
Commission study Monday that found widespread and aggressive
marketing of adult fare to children. For example, the commission
found advertising of adult-oriented entertainment during television
shows popular with children, including ``Xena: Warrior Princess''
and ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer.''
</P>
<P>
   The pervasive advertising to youngsters belies the industry's
efforts to help parents monitor what their children see and hear by
rating the age-appropriateness of its products, the report stated.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying before the Senate panel, industry representatives
said they do not market violent and sexual material to children.
They also cautioned the Commerce Committee against regulating their
advertising, saying such governmental intervention would encroach
on their right to free speech.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Goldberg, president and chief executive officer of Artemis
Records, expressed strong concern that federal oversight of
advertising would lead to governmental censorship of the arts.
Gibing the Texas governor, Goldberg said he was concerned for
groups like the heavy metal band Kittie, whose song lyrics contain
profanity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that there are many Americans who are offended by curse
words and don't want children exposed to them,'' Goldberg said.
``However, those people have no moral or legal right to impose such
a standard on my family or the millions of other Americans who,
like George Bush, are comfortable with cursing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, during a campaign rally in Illinois this month, referred
to New York Times reporter Adam Clymer as a ``major league
a------,'' a remark that was picked up by an open microphone.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Moore, president of video-game maker Sega of America Inc.,
expressed anger at politicians who blame entertainment companies
for youth violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any responsible parent knows that there are a multitude of
factors involved in childhood development,'' said Moore, the father
of three. ``The more time our government spends scapegoating one of
the thousands of impressions made everyday on children, the less
time is spent on real, sustainable solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Valenti, president and chief executive officer of the
Motion Picture Association of America, said the movie industry has
for nearly 32 years alerted parents to any adult content. These
familiar ratings include ``R,'' for adult-oriented movies that
require children under age 17 to be accompanied by a parent, and
``NC-17,'' movies that are closed to children under 17 because of
explicit sex scenes or excessive violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reviews of just about every movie released appear in
publications and on television,'' Valenti said. ``There is no
scarcity of ratings advice for parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., the committee's chairman, expressed
anger that movie company executives sent their chief lobbyist,
Valenti, rather than appear at the hearing themselves. Saying
``their hubris is stunning,'' McCain pledged to invite the
executives again to a similar hearing on advertising that will
occur later this month.
</P>
<P>
   The Wednesday hearing, ostensibly an examination of advertising
practices, became a forum for a the tight presidential race because
of the appearances of Lieberman and Lynne Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   Their testimony followed campaign statements from Gore and Bush
in which both candidates blamed sex and violence in movies, records
and video games for destroying the nation's moral fabric,
especially for America's youth.
</P>
<P>
   Picking up on the campaign theme, Lieberman, a long-time critic
of the industry, urged entertainment companies to ensure that that
their adult-oriented entertainment is not marketed to children.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are asking for today is not censorship, but simply
better citizenship,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These companies contribute so much to our economy, to our
culture, to the American experience,'' he added. ``But they are
also contributing to a serious national problem and we need their
cooperation.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the self-restraint approach fails, Lieberman said the
Federal Trade Commission should cite the industry for falsely and
deceptively advertising adult entertainment to children. The
government, however, should not sanction the companies for their
movies, records and video games because these productions enjoy
constitutional protection, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman also said parents must ``do more to monitor their
children's media diets.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, by contrast, echoed the Bush campaign by calling direct
federal intervention in advertising unnecessary. Instead, national
and community leaders can spur companies to alter their marketing
efforts and improve the quality of their products by holding up for
ridicule corporate executives who fail to act responsibly, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is something to be said for the old-fashioned concept of
shame,'' added Cheney, a former chairwoman of the National
Endowment for the Humanities.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
