<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3437 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-FARGAS-LADN-(SLAN     09-13 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FARGAS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FARGAS USES INJURY INJURY AS MOTIVATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ For Justin Fargas, complete closure occurred just
a few seconds into Michigan's first game against Bowling Green
three weeks ago. In one play, 22 months of frustration ended.
</P>
<P>
   Pain free, slightly apprehensive and energetic to his limit,
Fargas, the former Notre Dame of Sherman Oaks star and the greatest
running back ever produced by the San Fernando Valley, fielded the
opening kickoff, darted 11 yards and then got smashed to the turf.
</P>
<P>
   After missing nearly half his freshman year and all of 1999 with
a devastating broken leg _ enduring three surgeries, facing the
frightening possibility of losing his right foot and an arduous
rehabilitation process _ it never felt better to get hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping that they would kick it to me,'' Fargas said.
``The return didn't set up just right. But I was glad to get the
ball in my hands and get that first contact out of the way. I knew
then I was back.''
</P>
<P>
   This week Fargas comes full circle _ he returns home to Southern
California to play UCLA, a school he seriously considered signing
with out of high school _ to play in front of family and friends
for the first time since leaving for Michigan two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there's nothing he wants more than to show everyone the
flashy running style and breathtaking speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a game I've been looking forward to ever since I
committed to play here,'' Fargas said. ``A chance to go home and
play in front of family and friends is a great experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Michigan coach Lloyd Carr agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any question that this game was a
motivating factor for him in coming back,'' Carr said. ``And he's
done a great job of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Fargas' first trip home with Michigan wasn't supposed to happen
this way. Instead of facing the uncertainty coming off a serious
injury, he was expected to be firmly established as one of the top
juniors in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows, maybe this would be the week Fargas launched a
Heisman Trophy campaign _ here at home, at the Rose Bowl against
the Bruins in front of loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   The reality is, he's a redshirt sophomore playing behind senior
Anthony Thomas, trying to carve out a niche while proving to
himself and others that he's the same player as before the injury.
</P>
<P>
   Fargas finished with 70 yards on eight carries in the opener
against Bowling Green _ although he fumbled on his first carry _
then was limited to just seven yards on six carries last week
against Rice. Playing time has been spotty thus far.
</P>
<P>
   Fargas, who rushed for 6,334 yards and 82 touchdowns in three
years at Notre Dame, hoped to be more established for his only
regular-season trip home. While he had only 277 yards his freshman
season at Michigan, 120 of them came against Northwestern _ the
week before he got hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for different reasons, this return might be sweeter than the
one he envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a dream come true,'' Fargas said. ``I've come a long way
to get to this point. It felt good to be out there playing football
again. I missed something that I loved for a long time and I'm glad
to have it back.''
</P>
<P>
   And so are his biggest supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so much that he's coming back home to show what he
can do,'' Notre Dame coach Kevin Rooney said. ``It's the fact that
he's back playing football again and that he overcame some serious
hardships to get back. That's reason enough for all of us to be
happy. It's been a long haul for Justin.''
</P>
<P>
   There was some question whether he'd get here. Fargas literally
shattered his leg two years ago, suffering multiple fractures
against Wisconsin. It was such a gruesome injury, Michigan trainer
Paul Schmidt said it looked like something you might see in a car
crash.
</P>
<P>
   Fargas had two titanium rods and 12 screws implanted in his leg
during surgery, only to learn four months later the leg was not
healing properly. He required another surgery in which his leg was
rebroken and two metal plates were inserted, forcing him to
redshirt in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The rehabilitation was difficult and strenuous, but Fargas
focused on making it all the way back so he could play and be
effective by the time Michigan traveled to the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt if there was anyone who could come back from something
like this, it was Justin,'' Rooney said. ``Because of his great
willpower, determination and toughness. Doctors said this was as
bad a break as they'd seen, or maybe ever seen. So to come back as
he has really says a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, it looks like Fargas is close to where he was, showing
the same explosive burst and cutting ability as before.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's making a lot of great cuts,'' Carr said. ``I can't tell a
difference in his speed and he's a much better pass receiver. He's
a very important part of our offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Fargas, who had a third surgery to fix tendons in his right big
toe, recalls the devastating possibility of losing his right foot
in the aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forget that _ the excruciating pain,'' Fargas said.
``A lot of things run through your mind when you know your leg's
broken. Taking away a leg is like taking away Superman's cape. I
can't run without my leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``To know I've come from almost losing my leg to being able to
play now, that just makes me want to play even harder. I didn't
know what it was like to break a leg _ I'd never broken anything. I
thought it was a routine thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found out it was more like falling off a building or being
in a major car accident. To hear that I could have even lost my
foot, I think about it, and I think about how lucky I am just to be
running, much less to be playing football for Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Fargas' performance against Bowling Green showed he's back. Now
the focus is on getting better. He has three years to become the
running back everyone predicted coming out of high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``He still looks fast and he's stronger and more determined,''
said Antonio Fargas, Justin's dad. ``I'm really encouraged. I think
we can relax now.''
</P>
<P>
   Carr, who convinced Fargas to leave the West Coast for Ann
Arbor, now watches from the sidelines with pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw him run out on that first kickoff return, those
were great feelings to see that kid get an opportunity to play
again,'' Carr said. ``I thought he did an excellent job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
