<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3438 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-CHASE-MORGAN-ART-475(     09-13 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHASE-MORGAN-ART-475(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHASE HOPES DEAL FOR MORGAN WILL BRING IT PRESTIGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CHASE-MARKETPLACE, CHASE-MORGAN-NEXT, CHASE-MORGAN-NEXT,
CHASE-REACT) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT16 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN and SAUL HANSELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On Wall Street, Chase Manhattan Corp. has long been
considered an investment banking also-ran. No matter how much stock
trading or underwriting Chase did, its competitors continued to
disparage it as a declasse commercial bank.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with its proposed purchase of J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co., Chase
hopes that it will finally break into the club of financial firms
with enduring global clout. But whether Chase, the product of a
series of mergers of consumer banks, will join that elite club
remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing Wednesday that it plans to acquire J.P. Morgan for
$30.9 billion in stock, Chase executives argued that the
combination of Chase's broad base of customers with Morgan's
exclusive clientele and financial expertise would prevent the two
banks from being left behind in the race to determine which firms
will dominate corporate finance.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be less than a handful of endgame winners,'' said
William B. Harrison Jr., chairman and chief executive of Chase.
``We will be an endgame winner.''
</P>
<P>
   For now at least, the combined J.P. Morgan Chase &AMP; Co. clearly
would have the size to claim a spot among the world's financial
titans. It would have about $660 billion in assets, more than
90,000 employees around the world and a stock market value of about
$95 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But it still will be smaller than two other American financial
conglomerates, Citigroup and Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co., and
it still will have to prove that it can compete with them and
several other firms for the most lucrative roles of underwriting
stocks and advising on mergers and acquisitions. If anything, the
proposed deal will intensify the pressure on some of the biggest
investment banks, like Goldman Sachs Group and Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.,
to get even bigger soon.
</P>
<P>
   Each of those firms has spent many millions of dollars building
itself from a specialized domestic firm into an international
company with a diverse set of financial products and services to
offer corporations and, in some cases, individual investors. By
pushing its way into that set, Chase would be moving even farther
away from consumer banking. While it retains a network of more than
500 bank branches in the New York area and in Texas, Chase would
derive only about 27 percent of its revenue and 19 percent of its
pretax earnings from consumer services, including credit cards and
home and auto loans.
</P>
<P>
   Though Harrison said Chase had no plans to divest any major
lines of business, he displayed no sentimental attachment to the
consumer bank operations. ``Today, we're happy with all of our
consumer businesses,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he added that Chase would consider exiting any business that
failed to meet management's expectations. Some analysts believe
that one of Chase's first moves will be to stop making car loans.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Shares of Chase fell $1.31, to $51.19, on Wednesday, after the
companies confirmed reports of the deal. Analysts said that
investors were concerned about how much the acquisition would
dilute Chase's earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Mandle, an analyst at Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP; Co., said
Chase is expected to report earnings about 5 percent lower than
what had been expected before the deal was announced. On top of
that, he said, investors have some doubts about whether and when
Chase can achieve the revenue gains it is promising from the
combination.
</P>
<P>
   Chase is offering to issue 3.7 new shares of stock for each
share of Morgan stock. Based on the $52.50 closing price for Chase
shares on Tuesday Morgan's 159 million shares would be worth $30.9
billion. But Chase said it would be acquiring 186 million shares of
Morgan stock, counting all of the options and restricted shares
Morgan employees own. That discrepancy and the changing price of
Chase's stock led to disparities in estimates of the value of the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   To reduce the impact of the deal on Chase's earnings, Marc J.
Shapiro, a Chase vice chairman, said the banks expect to reduce
their combined expenses by about $1.5 billion annually. About
one-third of those cost reductions are likely to come from
eliminating jobs, Harrison said, though he declined to say how many
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts estimated that the number of jobs would be reduced by
several hundred to a few thousand, a small percentage of total
employment at the banks. The real challenge facing the new
management team will not be in eliminating jobs but in retaining
enough of Morgan's investment bankers to justify the high price
that Chase is paying.
</P>
<P>
   Chase executives may see themselves as equals to their
counterparts at Wall Street's biggest firms, but investment bankers
still see a gulf between themselves and most Chase employees. With
most investment banks competing fiercely for young financiers,
especially those with an understanding of technology, Morgan
employees may choose to defect to another bona-fide member of what
is known on Wall Street as the top tier. Debates rage about who
belongs in that small group of leading investment banks, but it
undisputably includes Morgan Stanley, Goldman Sachs, Merrill Lynch
and the Salomon Smith Barney unit of Citigroup.
</P>
<P>
   ``The risk is that they have to smoothly blend the cultures and
keep the key people,'' said Mandle of Sanford C. Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   One Chase executive, who spoke on the condition of anonymity,
said he hoped that acquiring Morgan would help Chase stem the
number of talented employees leaving for Goldman, Sachs and other
investment banks. He also said that Chase might fill holes by
hiring people from Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, an investment bank
that is being acquired by Credit Suisse Group.
</P>
<P>
   Chase executives said they had set aside a pool of stock to be
used to retain the Morgan employees they most want to keep, but
they repeatedly declined to say how big the pool was or how many
people might share in it. They did not disclose the financial
packages offered to any of Morgan's senior executives. Instead,
they emphasized that they had attempted to head off typical
pre-merger friction by quickly deciding who would fill the 40 or 50
jobs they considered most important.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The list of top managers chosen includes several executives from
J.P. Morgan. Douglas Warner, Morgan's chairman and chief executive,
would be chairman of the merged company, and two investment bankers
from Morgan, Clayton Rose and Walter Gubert, will have senior
management positions in the investment banking operation, to be
known as J.P. Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts and observers have depicted Warner as the
unfortunate chairman who was left with no choice but to sell
Morgan, one of the best known names in finance, ending its 150-year
run as an independent bank. But in an interview, Warner waved off
that view with a stern ``no way.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Morgan could have continued to go its own way quite
profitably and he did not feel pressured to merge. ``There was no
event'' that pushed Morgan into negotiations, until Harrison called
three weeks ago and ``offered us a powerfully better option,''
Warner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the end'' of J.P. Morgan, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But it would be the end of Morgan's tenure as a company focused
almost solely on managing the finances of blue-chip corporations
and some of the wealthiest individuals in America and Europe.
Likewise for Chase, the deal would spell the end of any impression
that it has its competitive sights set on anybody other than the
biggest investment banks.
</P>
<P>
   The deal may well create even tougher competition for the
top-tier investment banks, but it will have little or no effect on
other commercial banks, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   That's because of the demise of what was once known as the money
center bank _ the biggest banks in the biggest cities that took
deposits from individuals and lent them to big companies. Most of
those banks have combined into sprawling regional banking
companies, like BankOne, First Union and Wells Fargo, that find
more fertile opportunities serving consumers and small businesses
than trying to finance a multinational company.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fortune 1000 doesn't borrow from banks any more, and
that's why money center banking isn't around,'' said Lori B.
Appelbaum, an analyst with Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the bigger regional banks have bought brokerage firms,
but generally these have been smaller firms that serve their
existing clients rather than those that aim to butt heads with
Goldman, Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is happening here is you have to make a choice,'' said
Susan Roth, an analyst with Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette. ``Are you
going to be a niche player or are you going to be full service and
global because there is nothing in between. No one can be half
global.''
</P>
<P>
   There are only three banks in the United States left that
combine local and global businesses _ Chase, Citigroup and perhaps
Bank of America.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say that at Chase, the consumer and small business
lines will continue to be a smaller and smaller portion of the
company. While there is no compelling reason why the two aspects of
Chase need to be together, there is no pressure to split them
apart, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chase's mass market business is growing slower than the rest
of the company but it has nice returns on equity,'' Roth said.
``There is no reason for them to get rid of it.''
</P>
<P>
   At Citigroup, perhaps one of the few things that its main
components _ Travelers Group and Citicorp _ had in common was that
they were committed to building both consumer and corporate
business, and that continues in the combined institution. That
said, much of Citigroup's biggest wholesale opportunities are with
midsize companies in the 100 countries in which it does business
rather than with the world leaders that the new J.P. Morgan Chase
is going after.
</P>
<P>
   Bank of America is one bank that has a choice yet to make about
whether it will compete in the big leagues of investment banking.
It has longstanding lending relationships with big companies and a
growing regional brokerage business. But it has been consumed by
the slow and difficult work of stitching together the myriad banks
it has acquired from Miami to Seattle. And its stock price has
lagged as investors grew impatient, making any acquisitions now
very difficult.
</P>
<P>
   This puts the company in a difficult situation, analysts said,
that may lead the bank to forgo investment banking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it,'' Appelbaum said. ``The lesson of J.P. Morgan
is it doesn't pay to build it yourself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
