<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3441 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CHASE-MARKETPLACE-NYT     09-13 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHASE-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: A DEAL THAT DILUTES EARNINGS BUT MAY GENERATE NEW
ENERGY 
</HEADLINE>
  (With CHASE-MORGAN) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The immediate verdict by investors on the decision by
Chase Manhattan to take over J.P. Morgan was a resounding hiss;
Chase's share price fell 11 percent the last two days, after rumors
of the deal began to spread.
</P>
<P>
   There are good reasons for such a reaction: Chase is paying a
hefty premium over market value, and financial services mergers
often run into problems of integration that result in some of the
most valuable people leaving. Plans to cut costs sometimes
backfire, as it turns out that the people being let go really were
valuable to the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Chase's stock has been a good performer in recent years, but it
is now trading around 12 times its trailing earnings. Morgan, whose
stock had done less well until recently, is trading at 16 times
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Since this is a stock swap, with each Morgan share exchanged for
3.7 Chase shares, it is simple arithmetic that the merger will
substantially dilute Chase's earnings _ unless there is synergy
that raises revenue while allowing costs to be reduced. That is
precisely what William B. Harrison Jr., the chief executive of
Chase, who is to keep that role in the merged company, expects to
happen. ``This is a global financial powerhouse,'' he told stock
analysts Wednesday. ``This is a situation, I am convinced, where
one plus one will substantially exceed two.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrison was expressing the current wisdom of many in the
financial services industry when he said that there would be ``less
than a handful of winners in the wholesale investment banking
race.'' If that is true, then both Chase and Morgan had to do
something, for separately their efforts to burst into the top tier
of investment banking had met with limited success at best.
</P>
<P>
   Some outsiders think Chase can do it. ``The group of five
becomes a group of six,'' said Tom Burnett, president of Merger
Insight, an institutional research firm. By his count, the top five
in worldwide finance are now Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, Goldman,
Sachs, Merrill Lynch, Citigroup and Credit Suisse. He sees Deutsche
Bank and UBS on the edge.
</P>
<P>
   The theory is that size and scope matter, that companies want
financial advisers with operations in all regions of the world, and
capabilities in everything from corporate lending to mergers and
stock underwriting. Chase and Morgan have individually had
middling-to-poor success in breaking into some of these markets.
(One joke that made the rounds Wednesday was that the deal would
certainly raise each bank's standing in mergers-and-acquisition
tables, at least for one quarter. That is because Chase listed
Chase as its financial adviser, and Morgan listed Morgan.)
</P>
<P>
   Harrison set forth a plan by which Morgan's investment banking
operations would benefit from access to Chase's individual and
corporate customers. ``No firm will have a broader, deeper client
relationship than this firm will have and that is very
leverageable,'' he said. Morgan's chief, Douglas A. Warner III, was
similarly enthusiastic, saying the combined operation would ``take
our platform and drive it through Chase's much larger client
base.''
</P>
<P>
   On the retail side, there is precedence. Such synergies appear
to be working at Citigroup, the parent of Citibank, Travelers
Insurance and Salomon Smith Barney. That combination was received
with initial enthusiasm on Wall Street, followed by a lot of doubt
_ not to mention by a bit of panic after the Russian default in
1998, and Citigroup's stock price suffered. But the stock has
sharply rebounded amid indications that the merger is working.
</P>
<P>
   On the institutional side, the plan to sell more services to
corporate customers depends heavily on two things: convincing them
that the new Morgan Chase is a top-notch competitor and taking the
business away from some highly regarded rivals who will be doing
their best to keep it. Citigroup seems to have done that; it
remains to be seen whether or not the new Chase can.
</P>
<P>
   Chase pledged to maintain its current annual dividend of $1.28 a
share, a yield of 2.5 percent at current stock prices. Morgan
shareholders will see their annual payout rise by nearly one-fifth.
</P>
<P>
   In the financial world these days, a low dividend is perversely
a sign of investor confidence, indicating that share buyers expect
growth to produce bountiful rewards without hefty dividend
payments. Goldman, Morgan Stanley, Citigroup and Merrill Lynch all
have dividend yields of 1 percent or less. That the new Chase
Morgan will pay more in dividends than the companies did
independently may indicate that management is not confident
investors will believe the merged company is leaping into the top
rank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-00 2139EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
