<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3444 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-EUROPE-U.S.-TRADE-980     09-13 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-U.S.-TRADE-980(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON DELAYS NEW IMPORT DUTIES FOR EUROPEAN GOODS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also U.S.-CHINA-TRADE) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton has delayed new punitive duties
on European luxury goods, including Scottish cashmere, British
shortbread and Italian pecorino cheese, because Prime Minister Tony
Blair of Britain has shifted his position on two festering trade
issues to help the United States, administration officials said on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton decided to put off publication of a new sanctions list
late last week after Blair made an impassioned appeal to Clinton,
arguing that the 100 percent duties _ especially those planned on
$50 million of cashmere that comes from the United Kingdom _ would
do more harm than good to an already strained United States-Europe
trade relationship, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The reprieve also gives U.S. trade negotiators some leverage to
avoid a head-on collision with Europe in a separate and potentially
far more costly trade dispute over tax breaks Washington gives
major American exporters.
</P>
<P>
   Talks between the United States and Europe over how to avoid
massive retaliation against American products in the export tax
case will resume in Washington this week, with one administration
official saying he was ``cautiously hopeful'' that a pending Oct. 1
deadline could be extended while a compromise is worked out.
</P>
<P>
   The confluence of these issues shows how delicate United
States-Europe trade relations have become. Each side has won
headline-grabbing victories against the other at the Geneva-based
World Trade Organization. But both sides must grapple with
influential domestic constituencies and broad diplomatic concerns
as they ponder whether and how to impose retaliatory sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   The administration is obligated by law to shuffle the list of
$300 million worth of European luxury goods sanctioned after the
United States won a trade organization case against Europe's
restrictions on beef and banana imports.
</P>
<P>
   Congress mandated the rotation to make the sanctions more
painful and less predictable, ideally forcing Europe to open its
market to foreign beef and bananas instead of refusing to adhere to
the trade body's decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The luxury-goods sanctions have been placed in ``strategic
limbo,'' one senior administration official said. The official said
the decision was made after Blair's personal appeal to Clinton on
the sidelines of a United Nations summit last week; the two men are
considered close allies and friends.
</P>
<P>
   But the official added that it also became clear that Britain
had pushed a moderate line within the European Union on resolving
the banana and tax break disputes, including in a European Union
ministers meeting last Friday. The U.S. official described that
support as ``unprecedented.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, one administration official said that he believes the
threat of including key British exports on the sanctions list has
proven more powerful than actually pulling the trigger; as word of
the new list leaked out in recent weeks, Britain became
demonstrably more cooperative, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is not likely to put off new sanctions indefinitely.
Barring an unanticipated breakthrough in pressing trade disputes, a
new list will be published shortly, officials said. But they added
that they are not mandated to include cashmere, which has proven
especially worrisome to Blair.
</P>
<P>
   Britain is considered essential to resolving the longstanding
banana dispute because the European Union, which set trade policy
for its member states, effectively inherited the British system of
preference for goods produced in its former colonies around the
world. Once considered the most vociferous proponent of maintaining
that preference system, Britain is now seen by some administration
officials as their strongest advocate for opening Europe's market
to freer trade in bananas.
</P>
<P>
   Blair has also argued that he has been pushing a more flexible
European line on the tax break issue, the official said. And the
tax breaks are, by a factor of 20, more important to American
companies than beef and bananas.
</P>
<P>
   American companies, including Boeing and General Motors, avoid
an estimated $4 billion each year in taxes by sheltering some
foreign sales in offshore shell companies. Earlier this year, the
World Trade Organization ruled that provision in the American tax
code violates international trade agreements, and Europe has the
right to impose potentially sweeping sanctions on American goods as
soon as October.
</P>
<P>
   The administration is trying to buy time from Europe to pass
legislation that would overhaul the tax code, potentially bringing
it into compliance with the trade organization's rules.
</P>
<P>
   The House of Representatives on Wednesday overwhelmingly
approved the administration's plan by a vote of 315-109. The Senate
is expected to take up the measure shortly. The bill would replace
the so-called Foreign Sales Corporation program with a new tax plan
that would exempt certain kinds of foreign-earned profits from U.S.
taxes. The new rules do not require that those sales be channeled
through offshore tax havens.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters argue that the revamped tax break meets the trade
organization's requirements because it becomes a part of the
general tax code rather than an targeted export subsidy, which is
forbidden under trade rules. But the new law would actually
increase tax breaks on foreign sales by American corporations to an
estimated $6 billion annually.
</P>
<P>
   European Union officials have flatly rejected the new scheme as
nothing more than a broader application of the same subsidy,
insisting that they will press ahead with their challenge and
implement what could amount of many billions of dollars in
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Some American officials hope a compromise is still possible.
They are pressing European counterparts this week to agree to
suspend any sanctions for weeks or months after the Oct. 1 deadline
_ at least until the trade organization has a chance to review the
new U.S. tax rules.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said they had no intention of swapping
sanctions on beef and bananas for European good will on the tax
issue. But at the same time, they said, the overlap in the two
disputes makes it impossible to ignore that the quick application
of sanctions on luxury goods could prompt a damaging escalation of
the dispute over taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The domestic politics of the sanctions nexus are also tricky.
Carl H. Lindner, chief executive of Chiquita Brands International,
a major banana producer, has pushed incessantly to punish British
goods, administration officials said. Lindner is a major donor to
both political parties. Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott has also
argued strongly that the sanctions list should be published
immediately, and that it should have teeth.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are three months late with the list,'' said John S.
Czwartacki, Lott's spokesman. ``We need to hit this now.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, administration officials said that the chief
executives of numerous multinationals had made clear that they
consider the tax break question a top priority.
</P>
<P>
   Sooner or later, the administration is likely to slap heavy
duties on a new list of luxury goods. A tentative list includes a
variety of popular European imports.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those under consideration are: mineral water, canned
fruits, paprika and sweet biscuits, as well as cashmere, the
headline item. They would replace some goods on which duties have
been levied since April, 1999, including: bath salts, lithographs,
batteries and chicory.
</P>
<P>
   Sanctions on several items, including plastic handbags, such as
those made by Louis Vuitton, are expected to carry over to the new
list from the old one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
