<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-LOTTO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    PAYOUT REDEMPTION
 &HT;    Lottery winner looks beyond criminal past
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By JOHN W. GONZALEZ
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Collecting his share of a $64.8 million lottery
prize Wednesday, John Osorio of Richardson scoffed at suggestions
he was getting cosmic ``payback'' for being one of the few people
who landed in prison for the 1972 Sharpstown scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was ``ironic'' the word he was looking for to capture his
sentiments, now that his share of the lump sum cash payout of $34.1
million was deposited in his bank account.
</P>
<P>
   Was it was ``fate'' or ``karma''? reporters asked Osorio and his
close friend, co-winner Lois Loden, who purchased the winning
ticket for the Sept. 9 drawing using his money and her favorite
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel redeemed. How's that? I feel great,'' Osorio, 78, said.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years ago, Osorio was a key figure in the biggest
political scandal Texas has ever seen. Convicted and imprisoned on
embezzlement and conspiracy charges, he also weathered allegations
of selling unregistered stock and offering false testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed by reporters to ponder how someone who was so reviled as
a swindler could be collecting on the largest single
jackpot-winning ticket ever sold in Texas, Osorio claimed he was
simply the beneficiary of dumb luck _ not even his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luck. Her luck. Oh, she's lucky,'' Osorio said of Loden. After
all, just two years ago, she collected $1,895 for hitting five of
the six numbers required to grab the game's top prize.
</P>
<P>
   Had it not been for her sudden impulse to pick some numbers
rather than let a computer select all of them for her, the couple
might not have been at Texas Lottery Commission headquarters to
reap their shared bonanza.
</P>
<P>
   ``We bought two sets of five `Quick Picks' and then I just made
the remark to John that if we're ever really going to win, we're
going to have to pick the winning number. So I took the time to
fill out the sheet with five selections and the one right in the
center is the one that won,'' Loden said. She described her chosen
numbers as ``just random'' dates for loved ones' birthdays and
anniversaries.
</P>
<P>
   Added Osorio: ``This is a $1 ticket that won this money. It
doesn't relate to my background or anything else. Anybody can do
that (buy a ticket). I just accept it for what it is, and I'm here
to celebrate the win.''
</P>
<P>
   Osorio was terse and uneasy fielding questions about his past,
and he offered few details about his future. A practicing lawyer in
good standing, according to the State Bar of Texas, Osorio said he
must fulfill pending work commitments before turning his attention
to a life of leisure and travel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a few projects I've got to continue. Then I'm going
to step out. I might step off this world,'' he said, adding that
he's already led a full life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just about done everything I could do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for his involvement in the Sharpstown scandal that rocked
state government and ruined several political careers, Osorio said,
``I don't want to rehash history. If it's done, it's done.''
</P>
<P>
   Osorio, a gubernatorial appointee who headed the state insurance
regulatory agency from 1955 to 1957, was convicted in 1973 of three
counts of conspiracy and embezzlement resulting from the Sharpstown
investigation that also led to the bribery conviction of then-House
Speaker Gus Mutscher.
</P>
<P>
   Osorio was convicted of using $641,250 from a pension fund he
was managing as loan collateral. He was sentenced to three years in
prison and fined $6,000. After serving 14 months in federal prison,
Osorio was released Aug. 19, 1975.
</P>
<P>
   While imprisoned, Osorio was acquitted on additional fraud and
conspiracy counts, and in 1977 he was acquitted after being
indicted in New York in a $6 million counterfeit U.S. Treasury note
scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Osorio's resurfacing in the news sent his phone ringing off the
wall, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've received 300 phone calls. Some are from back then
(Sharpstown). No, Ben (Barnes) has not called,'' Osorio said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, Osorio claimed Barnes, then lieutenant governor, wanted
cash for a role in passage of legislation favorable to some
bankers. Though no charges resulted and Barnes vehemently denied
the account, his rising political star faltered after Osorio made
his claims.
</P>
<P>
   Osorio said he did his time, paid his fine and has therefore
repaid his debt to society and the individuals he may have harmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been 30 years ago,'' Osorio said, adding, ``Nothing's
hanging over my head right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Osorio said he and Loden, a typist, met through mutual friends
about five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a partnership-type arrangement. Now it's a financial
partnership,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if theirs was a romantic relationship, he said, ``Not yet,
but it's getting there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never known a better person in my life,'' she cooed.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
