<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3467 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CHASE-EXECUTIVE-NYT &LR;      09-13 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHASE-EXECUTIVE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 CHASE CEO IS UNASSUMING PLAYER WHO EXERTS QUIET CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
  (With CHASE-MORGAN) 
 By DAVID LEONHARDT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For one of the nation's top bank executives, William
B. Harrison Jr. is surprisingly accustomed to the background.
</P>
<P>
   At the University of North Carolina in the 1960's, he warmed the
bench on a basketball team that included a future member of the
Hall of Fame. At Chemical Bank, which he joined soon after
graduation, he rose through the ranks in the shadow of Walter
Shipley, his mentor. Even last year, when Harrison became the chief
executive of Chase Manhattan, with which Chemical had earlier
merged, many employees still had little sense of who he was.
</P>
<P>
   Today, however, as the chief executive of the corporate behemoth
that will result from the combination of Chase Manhattan and J.P.
Morgan, Harrison finds himself squarely in the spotlight. The lanky
North Carolina native may lack the forceful personality of other
bank executives, like Sanford I. Weill at Citigroup or David H.
Komansky at Merrill Lynch, but his task will be one of the most
watched on Wall Street: to successfully meld two different
companies into the world's third-largest financial institution.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan, founded in 1861 by its namesake, is among the
leading managers of money for blue-chip companies and wealthy
individuals. Chase has a larger, middle-market business, with a
commercial unit that includes more than 500 branches and a
corporate division focused on smaller or higher-risk concerns.
Harrison and his fellow executives hope the new company can combine
J.P. Morgan's expertise at developing new products with Chase's
large customer base to become one of the nation's top investment
banks, which neither has been on its own.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison may not be the most charismatic leader, friends and
associates said, but few other executives have his experience in
overseeing complicated mergers. Over the last decade, he has played
a key role in the two important deals.
</P>
<P>
   First, Chemical merged with Manufacturers Hanover, another New
York bank, in 1991, the same year Harrison became vice chairman.
Five years later, it bought Chase Manhattan and took the name of
the older company in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Shipley and Harrison were careful not to pull a
power play by ousting all the top executives at the banks they were
acquiring. Instead, the two tried to identify the most talented
managers and then sought to keep them, analysts said, and Harrison
has also been comfortable dipping into competitors' executive ranks
to fill key posts.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they've done mergers, they've done them in a very
collegial way,'' said Ronald Mandle, an analyst at Sanford C.
Bernstein, who had predicted the Chase-Morgan merger.
</P>
<P>
   James McCormick, the president of First Manhattan Consulting
Group, who has worked on and off with Harrison the last 15 years,
said his experience handling bank mergers is ``unparalleled,''
particularly as it relates to not upsetting the large corporate
clients of either bank.
</P>
<P>
   Associates say Harrison is a good listener who is also
comfortable crunching numbers on his own or making an unpopular
decision. ``I don't think he's a consensus manager by any stretch
of the imagination,'' said John F. McGillicuddy, the former head of
Manufacturers Hanover who sits on Chase's international advisory
board. ``He listens to people and then makes his own decision.''
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview with American Banker, Harrison said, ``I'm
not the type of person who goes home and agonizes over a decision
I've made.''
</P>
<P>
   His banking roots run deep. He was born in 1943 in Rocky Mount,
N.C., where his grandfather ran a bank at the middle of the
century. As a teen-ager, Harrison worked at the bank in the summer.
His father was a full-time employee and also served as the mayor of
Rocky Mount.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, the younger Harrison moved 100 miles west to Chapel
Hill to attend the University of North Carolina and play basketball
there, as his father had in the 1930s. The son was far from a star,
however. In his only year on the varsity, the 6-foot-4 forward
played in just two games and took two shots, making one. (The star
of the team was Billy Cunningham, now in the Hall of Fame.)
</P>
<P>
   Even though Harrison quit after that season, he has said he
learned a good deal about management from his coach, Dean Smith,
who was then in the third year of a tenure that would last 35 more
years.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison joined Chemical soon after graduating with a degree in
economics, and has never left. He oversaw its European business in
the early 1980s and then returned to New York to lead Chemical's
corporate banking division.
</P>
<P>
   Since becoming chief executive last year, Harrison has spent
much of his time trying to change Chase's status as a technology
laggard, with a struggling online banking business and little
ability to underwrite initial public offerings. He took the bank's
senior executives on a trip to the West Coast to meet with Bill
Gates, the chairman of Microsoft, and Scott McNealy, the head of
Sun Microsystems. Harrison also led Chase's purchase of Hambrecht &AMP;
Quist, a San Francisco boutique known for helping small technology
companies go public.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, however, he has developed little of a public
persona and, if Wednesday's announcement of the deal was any
indication, Harrison may be happy to let that continue. As is his
custom, he deferred to other Chase executives on a variety of
questions. He even allowed Douglas A. Warner III _ the head of J.P.
Morgan, the company Harrison is taking over _ to speak first and,
in an interview later, to interrupt him on more than once
occasion. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
