<HEADER>
A3470 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-SCENE14-COX     09-13 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SCENE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How Sydney 2000 compares with Atlanta 1996
 &HT;    By Henry Unger and Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sydney _ Divide and conquer appears to be one of the central
tenets of Olympic organizers here.
</P>
<P>
   Officials are taking advantage of this beautiful, sprawling
city, which draws its energy from its seemingly inexhaustible
supply of zigzagging beaches and the inherent kindness and charm of
its laid-back residents.
</P>
<P>
   The game plan of separating most of the athletic events from the
entertainment area is the exact opposite of the one used four years
ago by Atlanta organizers, who squeezed visitors and events onto
the already crowded downtown landscape.
</P>
<P>
   That essential difference, designed to take advantage of the
natural ebb and flow of this harbor town, will be paramount when
Sydney takes center stage Friday, hoping to avoid Atlanta's
well-publicized excesses and glitches.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney and Atlanta also have similarities, including
transportation problems that need to get fixed for these spread-out
Games to function properly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Transportation is the single biggest challenge we face, and
it's important we straighten it out,'' said Brett Gale, a spokesman
for the Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
   But first, the differences in the two undertakings:
</P>
<P>
   After Atlanta's unchecked commercialism, with billboards,
sidewalk stands and kiosks giving the city the air of a sprawling
Southern carnival, the International Olympic Committee mandated
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IOC was very strong on us not having the commercialism
Atlanta had,'' Gale said.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a clean and expansive Olympic Park relatively free
of flashy logos and intrusive commercial displays. At 1,900 acres,
it is about three times the size of Centennial Park, the Georgia
Dome, Philips Arena and CNN Center combined. The park has room to
breathe, and sponsor pavillions have been placed on the far
southern corner.
</P>
<P>
   The site, about 45 minutes from the central business district,
used to be the home of an enormous meat-packing plant and
slaughterhouse and a dumping ground for industrial waste. The
environmental group Greenpeace worked with Olympic builders to
clean up the site and make it eco-friendly and solar-powered. The
result is intensive recycling, no plastic soda cups and disposable
cutlery made from wood and solid cornstarch.
</P>
<P>
   The village housing the athletes is across a creek from the
venues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The land was a site basically going to the dogs,'' Gale said.
``It made a perfect location'' for the massive project.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsorship banners are evident, to be sure, but no billboards
clog the entrance to the city from the airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say it's more controlled (commercially),'' said Elsie
Hasting, an Olympic media manager who held a similar position
during the Atlanta Games. ``It's been quite interesting to see the
marketing gurus be as creative as possible within the guidelines
set by the IOC.''
</P>
<P>
   An example: ``Look at the Goodyear blimp,'' she said. ``It says
`G'day' in blue and gold, and yet everybody recognizes the shape
and what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   However, seven McDonald's outlets are in the park and two are in
the athlete's village.
</P>
<P>
   By concentrating the sports on one end of the city, organizers
were able to put most of the entertainment in the harbor area,
where officials expect to draw more than 1 million visitors. In
contrast, about 500,000 people are expected to attend the events in
Olympic Park.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Olympic Arts Festival has preceded the big noise of
the Games. The festival opened Aug. 18, and virtually every event
after Friday will be in the opera house.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision to separate (athletics and entertainment)
reflects the geography of the city and removes a huge crush of
people,'' Gale said.
</P>
<P>
   Even the entertainment events will be split among six different
areas around the central business district and harbor. The spots
will offer different types of music, from family-oriented themes
and symphony to rock `n' roll and hip-hop.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, much of the entertainment was in Centennial Park,
where some of the Games' sponsors built huge pavilions. And
Coca-Cola built its Olympic City amusement area adjacent to the
park.
</P>
<P>
   While the soft-drink giant is a visible sponsor in Sydney's
harbor area, company spokesman Scott Jacobson said, ``We don't have
something on the scale of Coca-Cola Olympic City.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based United Parcel Service is represented in all six
entertainment areas here, but UPS spokeswoman Susan Rosenberg said,
``They're not huge pavilions that some sponsors had in Centennial
Olympic Park.''
</P>
<P>
   Another key difference is created by Mother Nature. For the most
part, Atlanta's heat and humidity during the '96 Games turned out
to be milder than predicted.
</P>
<P>
   But Sydney this time of year can be cool and windy. Some
organizers are concerned that the weather might increase the threat
of pulled muscles in track and field, especially for sprinters.
</P>
<P>
   Others worry about a major negative from all of the water
surrounding the city. Sharks are in the harbor area where the
swimming leg of the new triathlon event takes place. Georgia's Lake
Lanier had no such worries.
</P>
<P>
   In both Games, local residents complained that the high and
mighty got much better access to good tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Both cities are using the Games to pole vault themselves onto
the world stage. Atlanta wanted to take what it believed was its
rightful place among international cities. Sydney wants to promote
itself to the billions who will be watching and hope that viewers
will conclude that a trip Down Under is worth it, despite the long
travel time and jet lag.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest glitch so far has been transportation. As in
Atlanta, volunteer drivers are getting lost, and hundreds of
additional drivers are needed. That number could increase if some
of the drivers quit in frustration because of the disorganization.
</P>
<P>
   The main headline in Wednesday's Sydney Morning Herald blared:
``Organisers own up to bungling on buses.''
</P>
<P>
   The bungling label is one pinned on Atlanta organizers
repeatedly because of transportation and computer glitches. And
it's one Sydney wants desperately to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
