<HEADER>
A3476 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;      09-13 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. Delays Punitive Duties on European Luxury Goods
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has delayed punitive duties on European luxury
goods, including Scottish cashmere, British shortbread and Italian
pecorino cheese, because Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain has
shown ``unprecedented'' support for the American position on two
trade disputes, administration officials said. The reprieve gives
United States trade negotiators some leverage to avoid a head-on
collision with Europe in a potentially far more costly trade
dispute over tax breaks Washington gives American exporters.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate cleared the last major hurdle to passing a trade bill
with China, and handing President Clinton one of his top remaining
foreign policy goals.
</P>
<P>
   Inktomi to Buy Software Developer
</P>
<P>
   Inktomi, which specializes in Internet infrastructure, said that
it had agreed to acquire FastForward Networks in a stock swap
valued at about $1.3 billion. FastForward, based in San Francisco,
has developed software technology for the distribution and
management of live broadcasting over the Internet. Shares of
Inktomi, which is based in Forest City, Calif., fell $2.25, to
$108.75.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks Mixed on Earnings
</P>
<P>
   Anxiety Continued nervousness about earnings left stocks mixed.
The Dow Jones industrial average fell 51.05 points, or 0.5 percent,
to 11,182.18. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index edged up 2.92
points, or 0.2 percent, to 1,484.91, and the Nasdaq composite index
rose 44.38 points, or 1.2 percent, to 3,893.89.
</P>
<P>
   Suits Filed Against the Drug Ritalin
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers involved in class-action lawsuits against the tobacco
industry, gun makers and health maintenance organizations filed two
suits against the widely used drug Ritalin. The suits contend that
Novartis Pharmaceuticals, the drug's maker, and the American
Psychiatric Association conspired to create a market for Ritalin
and expand its use.
</P>
<P>
   Janus Fund Closed to New Investors
</P>
<P>
   Janus Capital closed its flagship Janus Fund to new investors.
The company has now closed half of its 16 equity funds.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking Through the Ad Gridlock
</P>
<P>
   For the 2001 model year, which formally begins Oct. 1,
automakers will eagerly try to gain attention in an American market
more cluttered than ever. Agencies are scrambling to find
compelling ways to sell vehicles, like the new Lexus LS 430.
</P>
<P>
   Bank Reform Struggles in Malaysia
</P>
<P>
   Efforts by Malaysia to strengthen its banking system by forcing
its 54 financial institutions to merge into just 10 appear to be
backfiring, as concerns about government interference revive doubt
about the industry's health and the risks of investing in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Current Account Deficit Hits Record
</P>
<P>
   The United States current account deficit, the broadest measure
of foreign trade, widened 4.6 percent, to $106.14 billion, in the
second quarter, surpassing the earlier record of $101.51 billion
set in the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
   A Decline in Work-Related Injuries
</P>
<P>
   Since 1992, the number of work-related injuries and illnesses
has fallen 25 percent, translating into at least a $125 billion
annual lift for the economy. The decline in injuries reverses a
historical pattern: injuries usually rise when unemployment falls
because work intensity increases and many inexperienced workers are
hired.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
