<SLUG> BC-FBC-FARGASBOX-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOLEDO WANTED FOSTER AND FARGAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The California high school football recruiting
class of 1998 was one of the best in the decade. It included such
names as Carson Palmer, Jason Thomas, Robert Thomas, Ken Kocher and
Jashon Sykes. But right at the top of the list were two running
backs _ DeShaun Foster and Justin Fargas.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame of Sherman Oaks' Fargas, by winning the state
100-meter championship as a junior, began his senior season as the
state's premier prospect. But Foster's phenomenal senior season at
Tustin _ he rushed for 3,398 yards and a state-record 59 touchdowns
_ brought him the same attention.
</P>
<P>
   As signing day approached, UCLA was a finalist for both players.
</P>
<P>
   But the day before, Fargas announced he would attend Michigan
instead of UCLA or USC. Foster, in a press conference the next day,
chose UCLA over Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted both of them,'' UCLA coach Bob Toledo said. ``They
were both outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo said during the recruiting process, neither Fargas nor
Foster asked him about the other one _ a sign, he said, of
confidence in both players that they would be the marquee
attraction.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he would have done had he gotten both, Toledo smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It worked out,'' he said, hinting at his allegiance to Foster.
``Fargas would have really helped us at cornerback.''
</P>
</TEXT>
