<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-O-LINE0914-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons' offensive fortunes on the line
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ While walking off the field Sunday in Mile High
Stadium, Bob Hallen muttered, among other things, ``It's
embarassing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons' left guard could have been talking about the play
of the entire team after a 42-14 loss. Or he could have been
talking about the offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The head coach wants, and rightfully so, to get the five best
guys on the field, and we'll keep working toward that,'' offensive
line coach Art Shell said.
</P>
<P>
   Training camp is over, but tryouts continue. At least seven
offensive linemen will play Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons gave up six sacks to the Broncos, and quarterback
Chris Chandler spent a lot of time on the ground. While all weren't
the fault of the line, that's where the problems start.
</P>
<P>
   Hallen will start, and Chris Banks, claimed off waivers two
weeks ago, will get at least 15 plays at left guard.
</P>
<P>
   Travis Claridge and Ephraim Salaam will split time again at
right tackle, and Claridge probably will get a few snaps at right
guard in place of starter Anthony Redmon.
</P>
<P>
   In Denver, Atlanta didn't get a first down on its first seven
possessions. ``When you get that many three-and-outs, you didn't do
a good job,'' coach Dan Reeves said. ``Our performance offensively
was so poor. It always starts up front.''
</P>
<P>
   Claridge said, ``We've got to communicate better. We need to
talk more so everybody knows what the (defensive) front is, how we
need to block it.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Falcons went 14-2 in 1998, the starters were the same
for all 16 games _ Bob Whitfield, Calvin Collins, Robbie Tobeck,
Gene Williams and Salaam, from left to right.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, only Whitfield, the left tackle, and Salaam started
all 16 games.
</P>
<P>
   Continuity, chemistry, cohesion _ whatever you want to call it _
began crumbling in the first game. The 1998 lineup had started
every preseason game, but before the regular season started,
coaches moved Hallen, the team's second-round draft choice a year
earlier, in front of Collins, a sixth-round choice in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Hallen lost his job to Greg Bishop and got it back because of an
injury, but then other injuries ransacked the interior line.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Tobeck is on injured reserve in Seattle, Williams is
playing the bass guitar somewhere under the nickname ``Big Daddy
Chocolate,'' Collins is at center, where he played in 1997, and
Salaam is rebounding from knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have a better overall group,'' Shell said. ``We're
not as experienced, but we have more talent, more athletic ability.
But we have to get a little more adept at picking up the game,
especially stunts.''
</P>
<P>
   Hallen said, ``In the running game, we need to stay on our
blocks longer. As far as pass-blocking, you just have to get it
done. If Chris (Chandler) needs 10 seconds to throw the ball, we
need to block for 10 seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the line is learning as it plays. ``Anthony is new to
the system, . . . and things are being taught to him differently
than before,'' Shell said. ``Everything is being thrown at Travis
at once.
</P>
<P>
   ``Calvin is back to center,'' he said, ``but the only constant
is Whitfield, and it's reflected in his play. He's a hell of a
player, . . . but the rest of them got to get it going.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
