s e BC-COMPANY-OF-MEN-DANCE-     09-13 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPANY-OF-MEN-DANCE-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREEING MEN FROM THE FEAR OF TOUCHING 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 17) 
 By GIA KOURLAS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As Charles Wright sees it, one of the greatest
disparities between men and women has to do with touch. ``Women
have the freedom to touch in public, and men don't,'' Wright, the
artistic director of the downtown school Dance Space Center, says.
``Words like brotherhood are a little corny, but men do need a
forum to be able express whatever they want.''
</P>
<P>
   His solution, In the Company of Men, is a series devoted to the
theme of men. Now in its fifth season, the program, organized by
Wright and presented at the Pace Downtown Theater Sept. 21 through
Sept. 24, is a celebration of the dynamic of men dancing together,
in both joyous and virtuosic terms.
</P>
<P>
   The AIDS epidemic provided the impetus for Wright, who started
In the Company of Men in 1994 as a way to honor male dancers, both
living and dead. ``But if you took AIDS out of the picture, young
boys are still not entering the dance force,'' Wright says. ``I
always thought that the feminist movement would have a trickle-down
effect; that it would suddenly be acceptable for men to be nurses,
women to be doctors and boys to be dancers. But it hasn't happened.
So part of the genesis of In the Company of Men is to do my part
and say, `This is a great profession.'''
</P>
<P>
   With Jerome Foundation support, the series has transformed
itself from a pickup group presenting existing pieces into a
diverse, powerful forum for new work. This season, premieres are
offered by eight choreographers. While Nathan Trice delves into
mythology in ``Prophet and Betrayer,'' Andrew Asnes and John Selya
_ former members of the Paul Taylor Dance Company and Ballet
Theater, respectively _ present a hilarious number set to music by
Duke Ellington and Coleman Hawkins.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Synch or Swim,'' Asnes and Selya tap effortlessly in an
elegant soft-shoe routine and soar through the air in astonishing
leaps and turns _ not wearing soft ballet slippers or jazz shoes
but flippers. ``Dancing is hard enough,'' says Selya, who also
performs with Twyla Tharp's new group. ``You know those people who
run with ankle weights? When they take them off, they're winged
gods. Well, if I can do an entrechat-huit in flippers, after I shed
them?'' _ he raises an eyebrow dramatically _ ``Nijinsky!''
</P>
<P>
   There is an ecological message running throughout this riotous
yet challenging piece. At the start, Selya sits on the side of a
boat. He drinks a can of soda, crushes it and throws it into an
imaginary ocean. Then the two dancers, in unison, explode in jumps
and faux-swimming antics on the floor _ in one, they glide across
the stage on their stomachs like acrobatic worms _ as sickly fish
and garbage float by, pulled by strings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're funny by nature, but this is a serious eco-statement,''
Selya, an avid surfer, explains. ``So we put that message out
against our little dance, and it's a nice juxtaposition.''
</P>
<P>
   For Asnes, who retired from Taylor's company in August and
danced briefly with Tharp, it is also an opportunity to have some
fun. ``I didn't want to worry about making anything
extraordinary,'' he says. ``The pressure when you leave a company
like Paul's and choreograph is that everybody's looking to see what
you can do. We just wanted to make something that we'd enjoy.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Jensen, an emerging choreographer based in Minneapolis,
takes a more sober approach in ``Herakles and Ganymede,'' a duet
inspired by Greek sculptures that depict men engaged in battle or
desire. ``I wanted to see if I could diffuse the conflict and the
sex of the images,'' he says. ``To see if there is another way for
men to touch that doesn't have to do with fighting or sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Jensen's ``Herakles'' directly addresses the stereotypes that
Wright believes hamper male dancing _ that it deals only with
issues of homoeroticism or aggression. But there is more at stake
for Jensen: ``I like the idea that, for once, I won't have the
dressing room all to myself.'' He laughs. ``I always felt left out.
I missed out on all the gossip! This will be the one time when I
get to be part of the crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
