<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3495 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-STODA-COLUMN0914-COX     09-13 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STODA-COLUMN0914-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Knight did this to himself
 &HT;    By Greg Stoda
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Better late than never.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Knight _ or Coach Knight or Mister Knight or General Knight
or god or whatever it is he wants to be called by anyone he deems
unworthy of his presence _ had this coming.
</P>
<P>
   And he has had this coming for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he looks pathetic, which is what happens to a bully the
instant he discovers his number really is up. Knight bleating about
how he's misunderstood and mistreated comes as no surprise. He has
his apostles and apologists who agree with him when he says his
words and actions are too often misinterpreted.
</P>
<P>
   How convenient. It's always somebody else's fault.
</P>
<P>
   There's no need to list again the litany of misbehavior Knight
exhibited during his 29-year dictatorship as head basketball coach
at Indiana University. In the end, the only review necessary is
this one: Knight couldn't control himself even when he knew the
slightest step outside a zero-tolerance guideline set down by
school administrators just four months ago would result in his
dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   Knight couldn't even do that. Not even when he was warned,
finally, in public and private by university officials that the
institution wouldn't stand for another of his embarrassing
episodes.
</P>
<P>
   Know why he couldn't control himself?
</P>
<P>
   Because he didn't want to.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody tells Knight what to do.
</P>
<P>
   It's absurd to believe Knight didn't understand the rules set
forth under the zero-tolerance policy. What's not absurd is to
believe he contested the policy's constraints whenever it suited
his purpose. He had to know a physical confrontation with a student
_ over nothing more than the student addressing him as ``Knight''
and Knight finding that discourteous _ would mean trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he grabbed the kid hard by the arm or maybe he just
grabbed him. Maybe he cursed the kid and maybe he didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   The incident in and of itself, as Indiana University President
Myles Brand said, wasn't enough to warrant Knight's firing. It was
the incident heaped upon several others cited since the May edict
was put into effect. This wasn't the first time Knight violated the
zero terms of zero tolerance; it just happened to be the last.
</P>
<P>
   JUST ENOUGH ROPE
</P>
<P>
   Brand said Knight has acted in a ``defiant and hostile'' manner
and been argumentative and uncooperative in several instances since
May.
</P>
<P>
   What happened was the university gave Knight enough rope to hang
himself, and he obliged. Knight's explanation for the campus
encounter with freshman Kent Harvey _ and good luck to that kid at
dear ol' IU _ was that he felt disrespected and was trying to teach
him some manners.
</P>
<P>
   Knight on civility.
</P>
<P>
   Quick, somebody hire him to teach a class on human relations.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody will hire him, of course.
</P>
<P>
   He's a brilliant basketball coach. He never cheated to win, and
he won a lot. His players graduated at a rate far above the
national average.
</P>
<P>
   But the worst part of Knight long ago consumed the best part.
Knight's belligerent arrogance was so staggering he couldn't save
himself from himself.
</P>
<P>
   It's important to remember that. Nobody did this to Knight. He
did it to himself.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
