</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-BOMB-1STLD-WRITETHRU-540&AMP;ADD-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOMB BLASTS THROUGH INDONESIAN STOCK EXCHANGE BUILDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (UPDATES death total in lede; SUBS 15th graf to conform)  
(This story does not carry a byline) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ A car bomb exploded in the parking garage
of the Indonesian Stock Exchange building Wednesday, killing at
least 13 people and wounding dozens in the latest round of violence
to hit this troubled country.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion was the latest unexplained bombing in recent weeks
in Jakarta and other cities, and came just hours before a
high-profile corruption trial against Indonesia's former president,
Suharto, was to resume on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A Jakarta police detective said that anecdotal evidence linked
Wednesday's blast to the case against Suharto. The night before the
trial opened on Aug. 31, another car bomb exploded 300 yards from a
building in south Jakarta where the case was being tried.
</P>
<P>
   The police detective, Harry Montolalu, told reporters at the
scene, ``This is being done to create instability.''
</P>
<P>
   But the national police chief, Gen. Rusdihardjo, who uses only
one name, refused to speculate about the involvement of anyone
linked to Suharto or his trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we haven't caught the suspects yet and the motive
is still not clear, we shouldn't conclude that way,'' the general
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   President Abdurrahman Wahid has accused military and political
extremists linked to Suharto of planting bombs and inciting unrest
across the country to discredit him and destabilize his
democratically elected government.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Wahid also accused elements within the army of responsibility
for an attack last week on a U.N. refugee agency office in West
Timor that killed three foreign aid workers.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The country's attorney general, Marzuki Darusman, who spent
eight months investigating the Suharto family, has contended that
Suharto's supporters were instigating violence in order to derail
the corruption trial as well as investigations into past human
rights abuses by the military, including in East Timor last year.
</P>
<P>
   Darusman said those incidents included a bomb explosion at his
office complex in July, just one hour after Suharto's youngest son
was questioned in connection with the corruption case against his
father. No one was injured in that blast.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's short-staffed and poorly equipped police force has
failed to name a single suspect in any of the incidents, and
Wednesday's explosion was expected to increase international
pressure on Wahid to restore order in his country of 210 million
people.
</P>
<P>
   Rusdihardjo said, ``I apologize for not being able to solve the
previous explosion cases, but trust me, the Indonesian police are
doing our best, and we will guarantee an improvement of security.''
</P>
<P>
   The explosion occurred about 3:25 p.m. on the second basement
level of the 36-story building's underground parking garage in
Jakarta's central business district.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 people fled as the blast reverberated throughout
the building and black smoke billowed into the sky from the parking
garage entrance.
</P>
<P>
   At least 27 people were rushed to the nearby Pertamina state
hospital, which soon overflowed with casualties.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Firefighters rushed to the scene to battle an underground blaze
in the garage that was apparently started by a power generator
damaged in the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   At least five people were believed to have died from smoke
inhalation, some while hiding in their cars in hopes of escaping
the fire. Rescue workers pulled at least three burned bodies from
the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is confirmed that the explosion came from a bomb in a
car,''the police spokesman, Nur Usman, told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's bombing appeared to further erode the public's faith
in the country's security forces and re-enforced the perception
that Indonesia, the world's fourth-largest nation, is spiraling out
of control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what has happened is that the capacity of the security
forces to control this has really broken down,'' said Andi
Mallarangeng, a leading political analyst, who said he had been in
the stock exchange building only two hours before the blast.
</P>
</TEXT>
