<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CODY-GIFFORD14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tabloid seeks more info on Cody Gifford
 &HT;    By Scott McCabe
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Kathie Lee Gifford's 10-year-old son may
not be a star yet, but he's getting star treatment by the Boca
Raton-based tabloid, ``The National Examiner.''
</P>
<P>
   The weekly trashed Cody Gifford in February with a story
headlined, ``Kathie Lee Wrecking Cody's Life! Pushy Mom's creating
a monster.'' Describing him as a ``rebel without a clue,'' it said
he threw tantrums, spit calamari in a restaurant and took a Magic
Marker to a pair of pants at a children's clothing store.
</P>
<P>
   The Giffords sued April 6, saying the article was false and
defamatory. Now ``The National Examiner'' is getting personal.
</P>
<P>
   The tabloid is asking the family to turn over anything that
might show that Cody Gifford had behavioral problems before the
article was written.
</P>
<P>
   Report cards. Home movies. Classmates' addresses. The names of
nannies. Prescriptions and medical records. Summer camp records.
Disciplinary records.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's offensive to me that after they lied about the kid, they
are now asking him to answer these kinds of questions,'' said the
Giffords' attorney, Deborah Drooz, of Los Angeles. ``They don't
care who they hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   The requests for personal information won't intimidate the
Giffords, Drooz said. They will ask the judge, Palm Beach County
Circuit Judge Timothy McCarthy, to deny requests for irrelevant
information.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday in West Palm Beach, McCarthy will hear both sides'
arguments on the tabloid's motion to have the suit thrown out. If
the judge lets it move forward, the Giffords will have 30 days to
ask him to throw out the publication's request for the information.
</P>
<P>
   The tabloid's attorney, Jay Shapiro, of Miami, was unable to
return phone calls, according to his office.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit is not the first to be spawned by tabloid interest
in the Gifford family. ``The Globe'' sued the ``National Enquirer''
in 1998 over a story about Frank Gifford's 1997 affair with Delray
Beach flight attendant Suzen Johnson, saying they had exclusive
rights to the story. American Media Inc., which owned ``The
National Enquirer `` then, now owns ``The Globe'' and ``The
National Examiner.''
</P>
<P>
   While Kathie Lee Gifford has fought to keep her children's lives
out of the the tabloids, she has let Cody appear on television
shows. In the March 12 ABC-TV movie ``Janine &AMP; Alex: Cover Girls,''
Cody played the younger brother of a sexy supermodel. He also has
appeared on Kathie Lee's talk show and holiday specials.
</P>
<P>
   Kathie and Frank Gifford understand that they are fodder for the
tabloids, said Drooz. That doesn't mean their children should be,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gifford's primary concern is about the kids,'' Drooz said.
``They want to send the message to the hounding tabloids: Stay away
from our kids.''
</P>
<P>
   scottmccabe(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
