<HEADER>
A3498 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-KNIGHT-RALLY0914-COX     09-13 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KNIGHT-RALLY0914-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The General's last stand
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLOOMINGTON, IND. _ On a festive evening that evoked Indian
summer, Bob Knight bid farewell Wednesday to the crowd that always
loved him best, the University of Indiana student body.
</P>
<P>
   In a rambling 20-minute speech, Knight made a pitch for his wife
Karen's walk-run for cancer fund raiser next month, took several
minor shots at the administration that fired him Sunday, even
complaining that none of the top executives at IU thanked him for
doing a good job.
</P>
<P>
   But his big pitch was to the students, asking that they support
this year's team as they had supported his teams since 1971, though
it appeared none of the 2000-01 team members was present.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wanted our players to be members of the student body
and the students to be a part of our team,'' he said. ``If you want
to do something to remember me by, contribute the same energy, the
same enthusiasm as the students who came before you.''
</P>
<P>
   In a telling omission, he did not mention interim coach Mike
Davis. And when he recounted the names of favorite Hoosier players,
he mentioned Indiana Pacers coach Isiah Thomas, who offered Knight
a spot on his staff.
</P>
<P>
   The farewell to Knight, sponsored by the student newspaper, the
Indiana Daily Student, was held on a dirt-pocked field known as
Dunn Meadow, a long block down from the main entrance to the
campus. There were no less than less than 10 satellite TV trucks
with 21 cameras set up in areas that were ribboned off.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street, a few students watched from the porch of a
narrow frame house called ``The Roach Motel.'' Someone had put a
hand-lettered sign that read, ``The Roach Motel Supports the
General.''
</P>
<P>
   Entrepreneurs produced pro-Knight T-shirts that sold for $15.
One read ``Hoosier Daddy Now'' on the front and on the back said,
``Good Knight General, the day IU died, Sept. 10, 2000.'' Joe Dorn
sold his shirts, 200 of them, out of the back of a Chevy Blazer.
``Good Knight, Farewell Coach, Farewell Basketball Tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   And the student body responded, starting to gather two hours
before Knight's scheduled appearance at 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Some students admitted they were skipping class to honor Knight.
In an area police suggested could accommodate 6,000, there were
students up on banks leading to the sidewalks, flowing into the
street and perched in trees, a few holding placards that supported
Knight.
</P>
<P>
   In all, there might have been about 8,000, approximating the
number allowed in Assembly Hall for each Indiana basketball game.
</P>
<P>
   In leaving them, Knight said he hoped he would find students as
responsive in his next coaching post and asked them for one more
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take a minute and in any fashion that you want, say a prayer
for my family and for me just as I will say one for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty minutes after he arrived, Knight was gone. The students
cheered and then wandered into the adjacent village.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
