<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3506 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-DROUGHT0914-COX     09-13 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DROUGHT0914-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Harshest drought in decades looms
 &HT;    By Robert P. King
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ After nine rain-filled years, South Florida
may be on the brink of its harshest water shortage in modern
history.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with an unusually dry summer and predictions of an even
drier winter, water managers issued a warning Wednesday asking
residents, utilities and farms to conserve voluntarily in almost
all of South Florida from southern Martin County to the Keys.
</P>
<P>
   And they warned that the region faces a 90 percent chance of
mandatory cuts between now and June, which could include limiting
lawn sprinkling to three days a week.
</P>
<P>
   To keep water flowing to farms and cities throughout the winter,
water managers also are ready to drain Lake Okeechobee below its
lowest levels ever recorded.
</P>
<P>
   But at least for now, they've abandoned a proposal that drew
immediate opposition from lake activists and state environmental
regulators: replenishing the lake with polluted runoff from sugar
farms.
</P>
<P>
   The district's roster of possible strategies even includes
cloud-seeding _ dropping chemicals in clouds to induce rain _ a
perennial favorite in desperate times.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to prepare for the worst,'' said Frank Finch,
executive director of the South Florida Water Management District.
And according to his staff, the worst might be on the way _ a
situation that had farmers fretting about lost crops and burning
muck.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have a dry winter, it will be the most serious
(shortage) we've ever had,'' said Tom MacVicar, an agricultural
water consultant and former district deputy director. Even if fall
and winter rainfall is average, the growers are preparing for a 20
to 30 percent shortfall in the water available for irrigation.
</P>
<P>
   While South Florida's last drought ended in 1991, the rest of
Florida and the Southeastern United States have been in the grip of
a three-year drought that has killed crops, shriveled rivers and
caused wells to go dry.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's water shortage declaration, accompanied by $3.3
million in emergency spending, was a sharp turnabout from last
spring, when the district dumped 130 billion gallons out of the
lake to rescue its vast interior marsh after years of drowning.
</P>
<P>
   The lake has dropped about 3 feet since then _ 1 foot because of
those drastic releases and 2 feet because of evaporation and normal
lake releases to cities and farms, hydrologists said.
</P>
<P>
   The lower lake levels have resulted in clearer water and modest
regrowth of bottom plants along much of the south and west shores.
But the district's actions brought renewed criticism Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say, 'I told you so,' `` said Fred Rapach of
Palm Beach County's utilities department.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just did,'' said district Chairman Mike Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Even one supporter of the lake lowering was in disbelief about
the turn of events.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely incredible to me that in two months' time
we've gone from 'The lake's too high' to 'Maybe the lake is too
low,' `` said Okeechobee County fisherman Wayne Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the recriminations, some board members criticized the
majority for having cut millions of dollars from next year's budget
for conservation programs and development of water supplies.
Audubon Society activist Rosa Durando said the district had
worsened the region's readiness for drought by approving scores of
development projects that will increase the demand for water.
</P>
<P>
   Through Wednesday, West Palm Beach had received 23.31 inches of
rain this year, 44 percent below normal. The lake, the heart of
South Florida's water system, stood at 11.8 feet above sea level
Wednesday, 3 feet below average for this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   By the next rainy season in June, district planners said, the
lake could break its all-time record low, 9.8 feet, reached in 1981
during a severe drought. It could even fall below 9 feet, so low
that water couldn't drain on its own into canals that serve the
region's farms, the Everglades and coastal cities.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare for that possibility, the district is spending $2.2
million on a dozen electric pumps that could pull water out of the
lake.
</P>
<P>
   Mandatory cutbacks will take place if the lake falls below 11
feet after Oct. 1. On the plus side, the district hopes the low
water will allow it to burn 10,000 acres of foreign weeds that have
taken over much of the lake's marsh.
</P>
<P>
   The most furor erupted Wednesday after water managers revived
the idea of pumping sugar farm drainage _ possibly laden with
phosphorus, nitrogen and pesticides _ into the south end of the
lake.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists warned that the pumping could turn the lake
murky, killing the plants that have resprouted this summer. Heavy
pumping has also coincided with increases in suspected carcinogens
in the drinking water of some lakeside cities.
</P>
<P>
   A proposed pumping test showed up on the final agenda for
Wednesday's meeting, prepared at 6 a.m. Finch and other employees
said they didn't know who had suggested the tests. Collins rebuffed
requests from Audubon activist Paul Gray for a public explanation
of how the tests would work, suggesting he speak privately with a
district scientist.
</P>
<P>
   Gray wasn't the only one baffled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like you guys, I don't know what in the world they are
proposing,'' said Melissa Meeker, regional director for the state
Department of Environmental Protection. She said the DEP would have
to approve any pumping, and so far, the answer was no. Collins
withdrew the idea, but said pumping could return as a last resort.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the water managers are hoping their appeal for
voluntary conservation will reap better results than government
commands.
</P>
<P>
   ``A large part of how we do during the coming year will depend
on the homeowners _ how they water their lawns, how they take their
showers,'' said district spokesman Bruce Adams.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
