<SLUG> BC-FISHMAN-ART-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ABSTRACTIONIST MAINTAINS THE FAITH IN A SKEPTICAL ERA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, September 17)  
 By EDWARD M. GOMEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his diaries from the heyday of abstract painting in the
1950s, Ad Reinhardt (1913-1967) observed that each time he started
a new canvas, he felt a frisson of awe _ and an inevitable weight
of familiarity. He suggested that each new work was, perhaps
inescapably, one and the same with those that came before it.
</P>
<P>
   Decades later, in the 1970s, process art, with links to
abstraction and minimalism, called attention to how artists
manipulated their media: sometimes finished objects looked like
specimens from testing labs for industrial materials _ a
transformation that was exactly the artists' point.
</P>
<P>
   The lessons of those eras and the artistic self-awareness they
awakened are still discernible in the paintings of Louise Fishman.
Fishman, who was born and grew up in Philadelphia, is now 61 years
old. Over the years this self-described ``third-generation Abstract
Expressionist'' has not dominated art-world headlines, but since
settling in New York in 1965, she has created a substantial body of
work that has been shown regularly in gallery and museum shows and
that has won the admiration of dealers, collectors and other
artists for her dogged commitment to the language, ethos and
expressive power of abstraction.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with a group of new Fishman canvases on view at Cheim and
Read, a gallery in Chelsea, through Oct. 21, people can see for
themselves how a thoughtful, self-critical artist is holding up the
mantle of abstract painting in an era of familiar, sometimes tired
postmodern polemics. The subject of the new paintings is the making
of abstract paintings itself _ the methods an artist can use to
create them and, ultimately, what they may mean and how they convey
their meanings.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, making a painting is a very complicated process; often
there's a lot of struggle,'' the artist said during a recent
interview at her gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in work pants and a sweatshirt, Fishman cut a reedy
figure standing before some of her largest new canvases; at times,
expansive swaths of strong color slapped against their surfaces
seemed to engulf her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may work on four or five pieces at a time, including little
ones,'' she said. ``But I don't intentionally work in series. Many
of these got started last year after I pulled out some paintings I
had been working on but had put away, then took out and started
scraping and reworking.''
</P>
<P>
   Fishman's laborious approach is well-known to her peers. In
1988, she made a trip to Eastern Europe, accompanied by a friend
who was an artist, a collector and a survivor of Nazi death camps.
The travelers visited the region's major capitals, as well as
Auschwitz and Terezin. After returning to New York, Fishman
produced a group of somber tableaus.
</P>
<P>
   Honoring Jewish themes of survival and remembrance in mood and
title, they use unfussy, rectilinear arrangements of broad
brushstrokes to whisper hauntingly for attention through nearly
transparent washes of dark color. Subsequently, Fishman said, she
found that her art ``loosened up'' _ but she worked at freeing up
her touch, too.
</P>
<P>
   Fishman recalled: ``Gesture came up in the early '90s for me,
but one reason I had difficulty using it was that I had a
rigid &UR;  &LR; understanding of what I wanted. I rely on my intuition, but
what fuels my work is my intellectual side.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of ``letting the ease'' of more free-flowing, gestural
painting ``become the brain of a work,'' she has tended to ``put a
lot of things together and throw a lot of things out the window.''
</P>
<P>
   Fishman added: ``I think of myself as a perpetual student.''
</P>
<P>
   Her education began at home, for both her mother and an aunt
were accomplished painters. Young Louise devoured the issues of
Artnews her mother received by mail, poring over photo essays by
Rudy Burckhardt that showed Abstract Expressionists like Joan
Mitchell in the step-by-step process _ and considerable drama _ of
making a painting. As a teen-ager, Fishman played basketball; then,
in 1956, at the Philadelphia College of Art, she took up a brush.
``I fell in love with oil painting,'' she said. ``I just loved it.
There's something about this that never ceases to interest me.''
</P>
<P>
   During the 1970s, Fishman became deeply involved in the feminist
movement, and her work took a mixed-media turn toward the
sculptural. It reflected the themes of handicrafts and ``women's
work'' that feminist artists were reconsidering from a new
aesthetic and political perspective. In time, though, she returned
to oil painting.
</P>
<P>
   While some artists are known for bringing color theory
prominently to their work, Fishman has been more fascinated by the
physical qualities of oil paint's luminous, elastic goo. ``It's
ground-up earth and rocks; it's earthy, plastic and metallic,'' she
said, referring to its pigments. Only recently, she said, has she
been able to regard standard cadmium red as something more than an
industrially concocted, aspiring-color interloper on her own
palette.
</P>
<P>
   Varieties of such bright hues, along with new elaborations of
the darting, calligraphic strokes and ``now you see them, now you
don't,'' underlying structural grids that have characterized her
paintings in recent years turn up in the new works at Cheim and
Read. In ``Razzmatazz,'' shots of pastel yellow poke through a
cascade of black-gray strokes that almost obscure a middle layer of
turquoise. A twister of broad, knotted gray strokes gathers gale
force in the big, pink expanse of ``A Stranger,'' and in ``Sunrise
Ruby,'' one of Fishman's largest new pictures, patches of mossy
green hug its surface, at once in the field of color and seemingly
afloat on a separate plane above it.
</P>
<P>
   Although she focuses intensely on her work, Fishman, who lives
in and keeps a studio in Manhattan, routinely makes time to see
museum and gallery shows. She is interested in contemporary video
art and has a small collection of Chinese scholars' rocks. Lately
she has steeped herself in Emily Dickinson's poetry and Emerson's
essays. Then there's Pollock. Of the Abstract Expressionist giant's
career-spanning exhibition at the Museum of Modern Art last year,
Fishman said: ``I was willing to go everywhere with him to see what
he kept uncovering about abstraction's emotional and psychological
power.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after four decades of creating abstract works herself, she
holds no formulas for making an image say or mean anything in
particular. A work's emotive force, she said, still emerges
mysteriously.
</P>
<P>
   With a group of ambitious new paintings freshly behind her,
Fishman appeared both enormously satisfied and a bit on edge.
``After a show, when I go back to work, I feel I'll never paint
again,'' she said. anxiety in her voice. Then, resuming the role of
her own strictest critic, she added: ``I'm not concerned about
whether the next work will be good or not. I'm just concerned about
making it _ that it'll be something really vital and fighting that
makes me feel alive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
