<SLUG> BC-WASH-HOUSE-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BATTLE FOR HOUSE CONTROL, BOTH PARTIES EYE A DISTRICT OUTSIDE
SEATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Eds.: The following article, incorporating various editing
changes, subs for story sent on 9-12 and held. Story is now
released.) (ART ADV: Graphic and map are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EVERETT, Wash. _ Democrats held the congressional seat here in
this northwest Washington district for 30 years until the
Republican tide of 1994 brought in Jack Metcalf, a former high
school history teacher and state legislator who finally made it to
the House of Representatives 26 years after his first attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with Metcalf sticking to a pledge to leave Congress after
three terms, and with Democrats seeing the open seat as a prime
opportunity to gain in the battle for control of the House, the
race here in the 2nd Congressional District shows signs of becoming
one of the most tightly fought in the nation this fall.
</P>
<P>
   And though each of the major party candidates plays down the
notion that presidential coattails will be a major factor, some of
the emerging themes in their race are strikingly similar to those
in the campaign for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican candidate, John Koster, a 49-year-old state
representative and third-generation dairy farmer, puts it simply in
promising to push for a big federal tax cut: ``Taxes are the first
thing people are talking about to me.''
</P>
<P>
   His Democratic foe, Rick Larsen, 35, a Snohomish County
councilman, says he will push for first reducing the national debt
and shoring up Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I hear from people in this district is, they're more
concerned about using the surplus to pay down the debt,'' Larsen
said. ``They want government to get its fiscal house in order. They
want schools to be safe, they want to be sure seniors can get
prescription drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   While drawing considerable attention because it involves the
only open congressional seat in the state, the race here is one of
at least three congressional contests that are considered
competitive this fall in Washington, a state that proved to be an
interesting electoral bellwether in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The state's voters broadly backed Bill Clinton and congressional
Democrats in 1992, then turned with a fury to Republicans in 1994,
giving them a 7-2 margin in the House delegation and even throwing
out the speaker of the House, Thomas Foley, a Spokane Democrat. But
they returned to Clinton in 1996, and by 1998, the Democrats had
regained the edge, 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   Now Democrats are hoping to add to that advantage by winning the
district, which stretches from the Seattle suburbs northward to the
Canadian border, and possibly even oust George Nethercutt, the
Republican who unseated Foley six years ago and is now reneging on
a term-limits pledge he made then.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are hoping to hold on to both of those seats and
even regain an edge by knocking off the incumbent Democrat in the
neighboring 1st District, Jay Inslee, whose seat changed hands
three times in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of the closely contested races here in Washington
could go a long way to determining control of the House, where the
Republicans now have a tenuous majority: 222 seats, as against 210
for the Democrats and two for independents, one routinely in the
Democratic camp, the other in the Republican. (One seat is vacant.)
Those numbers mean that Democrats can regain control by picking up
as few as seven seats in November.
</P>
<P>
   The district here was once reliably, even staunchly, Democratic.
It was represented in the 1940s by Henry M. Jackson of Everett, who
went on to become a senator and a national political figure. In the
years afterward, as the Boeing Co. became the ever more dominant
employer in the region, thousands of union workers here voted the
Democratic line.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Koster noted in an interview, a number of Snohomish
County's fastest-growing suburbs have leaned Republican in recent
years, and the more agricultural areas to the north also have
tended to vote Republican. Koster and Larsen agree that roughly
speaking, the district's electorate now is probably a third
Democratic, a third Republican and a third independent.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign here has yet to catch fire but will undoubtedly do
so as Election Day draws nearer. The two candidates have debated
face to face only once so far, in a relatively polite exchange in
July at a Rotary Club. But they have clashed more recently over
each other's records in office, and are expected to debate in
coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Neither expects to run expensive television advertising until
next month. For one thing, while the primaries Tuesday are
crucially important in some races, they are not central to this
one: Each man is running unopposed for nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, neither currently reports having a huge amount of cash
on hand _ Koster had only $176,00 as of Aug. 31, Larsen $212,000 _
although national leaders in both parties have said they expect to
pour significant amounts into the race.
</P>
<P>
   If moderate swing voters are the key to the election, some
advantages may befall Larsen, who often casts himself as a
moderate.
</P>
<P>
   Koster is an unabashed conservative. He said at the July debate
that he was proud to have voted against every state budget since
1994, and he is staunchly anti-abortion: In fund-raising letter
earlier this year, he said he would ``support all efforts to defund
the abortion industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with voters in the district suggested that many are
only beginning to focus on the race, although quite a few cited
cultural issues that had them leaning Republican and could energize
the turnout for Koster.
</P>
<P>
   But others said the tax reductions advocated by Koster did not
hold a lot of appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tax cut, that's not as important as knowing your Medicare
coverage will be there, knowing Social Security is sound,'' said
Sherry Andrews, 51, a human resources administrator at Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor at play is Vice President Al Gore's rising
standing in some statewide polls. If that trend holds, Koster might
get less of a ride on the coattails of Gov. George W. Bush than
some analysts were predicting earlier this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I've heard a lot of theories on this,'' said Koster.
``Of course, when Bush's numbers were much higher, everyone
expected there'd be coattails. But we're running this campaign like
it all depends on us. If there are coattails, that's fine and
dandy, but I'm not counting on it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
