<HEADLINE>
HOUSE ADDS ASSAULTS ON GAYS TO HATE CRIMES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: S.C., Mass., Ore., Mich., Wyo., Texas, Ill.)   By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House of Representatives on Wednesday endorsed
for the first time a measure to make attacks on gays a federal hate
crime, a move that was one of President Clinton's legislative
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   But the 232-192 vote was entirely symbolic because it did not
force lawmakers to adopt the measure, which passed the Senate as an
amendment to a defense bill in June, with broad bipartisan support.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the measure, which drew the support of 41 Republicans,
was an effort by Democrats to force Republicans, as the elections
approach, to take a recorded stand on expanding the hate crimes
definition to include attacks on gays and to pressure Republicans
into accepting the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders said Wednesday that the Senate amendment
would be stripped from the defense bill, a decision that is likely
to lead to an end-of-the-year confrontation with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the House cast its vote, the president attended a
rally for supporters of the measure, including Sherialyn Byrdsong,
the widow of Ricky Byrdsong, a black man who was killed in 1999 by
a 21-year-old white supremacist.
</P>
<P>
   Likening hate crimes to the Holocaust and efforts by Serbs to
force ethnic Albanians out of Kosovo, Clinton urged Congress to
endorse the measure, and he said he was ordering the Justice
Department to improve its reporting of hate crimes. Some 7,755 hate
crimes were reported last year, ``only the tip of the iceberg,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So this is very important,'' he added. ``It is just not true
that hate crimes are like other crimes. It is not even true that
every crime is a hate crime. And that fundamentally is at the heart
of this debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and congressional Democrats say they hope today's strong
vote sends a signal to Republican leaders that they should rethink
their decision to kill the measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that it will be very hard to explain to the
American people why, with bipartisan votes in both Houses, this
isn't included in legislation that becomes law this year,'' said
Jake Siewert, Clinton's press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   The vote Wednesday was a procedural one, a request that the
lawmakers who are negotiating the defense authorization bill
include the Senate hate crimes legislation in the final product.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, sponsored by Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., and Sen.
Gordon Smith, R-Ore., would expand federal jurisdiction for crimes
based on race, religion and national origin to include sexual
orientation, sex and disabilities. It passed the Senate 57-42.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore said, ``Passage of a strong hate crimes
law will send a clear message that we value everyone in our
society, and we will work together to oppose those who use hate to
divide us.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans who voted not to endorse the motion argued that the
legislation was unnecessary because hate crimes were already
adequately prosecuted by states and localities. They also sought to
frame the debate as one of state rights, maintaining that the bill
would grant the U.S. attorney general too much power.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lindsey Graham, R-S.C., offered an alternative proposal
that failed. Graham argued that all crimes were heinous, none more
so than the next.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. David Bonior, D-Mich., said: ``When hateful thoughts
turn into hateful deeds, the Congress must act and act decisively.
We can't outlaw hatred, but we have a moral responsibility to stand
up to those who could be its victims.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
