<SLUG> BC-LATIMES-LAYOFFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES TIMES CLOSING 14 PAPERS FOCUSING ON SUBURBAN COVERAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (This story, eliminated earlier, is now restored)  
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Executives of The Los Angeles Times said Wednesday that they
were closing 14 money-losing ``Our Times'' local newspapers, laying
off 125 employees and abandoning the strategy of winning new
readers and advertisers with hyperlocal coverage of traffic,
schools and community groups.
</P>
<P>
   The move by the paper's publisher, John Puerner, and its editor,
John S. Carroll, represents the sharpest break from the past since
Tribune Co. announced in March that it was buying Times Mirror Co.,
the newspaper's parent. Still, it continued a pattern set almost
immediately, when Tribune executives revised The Times' March
circulation figures downward, indicating that the original numbers
were overstated.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll said that the decision largely to scrap the ``Our
Times'' strategy was ``difficult in terms of the human
consequences, and also difficult in terms of community relations,
but journalistically and financially it was an easy decision.''
Puerner said that ``all of them were losing money, and the
financial performance was deterioriating.''
</P>
<P>
   While most of the publications, which were run under a separate
division called Times Community Newspapers, will close, the section
that served the inland area around Ontario, in western San
Bernardino County, will continue, as will three other local weekly
supplements. The local newspaper in Ontario is owned by the
MediaNews Group, whose chief executive, Dean Singleton, owns
several newspapers that compete with The Times.
</P>
<P>
   Also surviving are some Times-owned local newspapers that served
areas like Newport Beach, Glendale and Huntington Beach and Burbank
before being absorbed into Times Community Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The decision undoes one of the last strategic initiatives begun
by Mark H. Willes, the former chief executive of Times Mirror, and
Kathryn Downing, who succeeded Willes as publisher of The Times.
Robert G. Magnuson, the executive who had been in charge of the
``Our Times'' effort, left the newspaper not long after it was
bought by Tribune Co.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll said in an interview that part of the savings would be
reinvested in news coverage. He added that the closing of the local
newspapers _ some of which had been published as stand-alone papers
and some of which were distributed as sections within The Times _
was a step in rethinking local coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say anything that suggests we're not as
committed as we've ever been to national and foreign news,'' he
said, ``but I do think there's more work that needs to be done in
figuring out how you cover this region. In some ways it's a much
more complicated question.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll and Puerner said they would continue publication of the
newspaper's three regional editions in Orange County, Ventura
County and in the San Fernando Valley.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-00 2235EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
