u w BC-CONGRESS-TAX-1STLD-WR     09-13 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-TAX-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE UPHOLDS VETO OF MARRIAGE-PENALTY BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs for refinements and additional information; story grows by
about 200 words)  
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republicans fell short Wednesday in their
attempt to override President Clinton's veto of the
marriage-penalty bill. But while the bill is dead, the issue it
addresses is very much alive politically.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was 270-158 in favor of overriding Clinton's veto,
short of the two-thirds needed. Even if the bill had garnered
enough votes in the House, it was given virtually no chance of
getting two-thirds in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now is our chance to right this wrong and finally put an end
to the marriage tax penalty for 25 million married couples,'' said
House Majority Leader Dick Armey before the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats accused the Republicans of being more interested in
nurturing a political issue than in passing fair tax relief. ``It's
the show that counts,'' said Rep. Steny H. Hoyer, D-Md.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have made relief from the marriage penalty a focal
point for the fall campaign. ``Americans understand it is wrong to
tax marriage,'' Armey said. ``We will have to put it up on the
floor next year and have a president who will sign it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Wednesday's vote showed that the Republican
majority in Congress wanted to steer the country off the ``path of
fiscal discipline'' that he said his administration had followed,
and he appealed to lawmakers to work with him on fair tax relief
for the middle class.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would have cut taxes for married couples by $292
billion over the next decade. Forty-nine Democrats joined 220
Republicans in trying to override the president's veto. Voting to
sustain the veto were 157 Democrats and no Republicans. (The two
independents in the House were divided.)
</P>
<P>
   The vote Wednesday was similar to the 271-156 tally by which the
House voted for a somewhat smaller marriage-penalty-relief bill in
February. The Senate passed its version on July 18, by 61-38.
</P>
<P>
   The marriage penalty is more complicated than it is sometimes
made out to be. It affects many two-income couples in the middle-
and upper-income brackets, typically those in which husband and
wife earn roughly the same amount, by pushing them into a higher
tax bracket than they would be in if they could file as single
people.
</P>
<P>
   A Treasury Department study found that about 25 million couples
paid an average marriage penalty of $1,141 on their 1999 returns.
</P>
<P>
   But the study found that 21 million couples received a ``bonus''
averaging $1,274 because they were married. These were couples in
which only one spouse worked, or in which one partner earned much
more than the other.
</P>
<P>
   When he vetoed the Republican-backed bill last month, Clinton
said it would have benefited the wealthy while providing little
relief to middle-income people.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the year, Clinton proposed his own idea for alleviating
the marriage penalty. His plan would not have helped couples who
itemize their deductions, as most people with higher incomes do.
The White House estimated the cost of his proposal at $45 billion
over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The bill that fell short in the House on Wednesday would have
cut taxes for almost all married couples, regardless of whether
they now pay a penalty. It would have raised the standard deduction
for married couples filing jointly but not itemizing, so that their
deduction would be equal to that of two single people.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would have also gradually expanded the bottom 15
percent tax bracket for married couples to twice the corresponding
bracket for single taxpayers. And it would have increased the
earned-income tax credit limit for low-income families by $2,000 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   The marriage-penalty quirk arose from an effort to correct an
inequity that went the other way. Until about 50 years ago,
households with one wage earner were taxed more heavily than those
with a similar total income in which there were two wage earners.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
