<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VT-PRIMARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERMONT LAW ON GAY RIGHTS PROVES A FACTOR IN PRIMARIES
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In a sign that voters in Vermont remain divided over
the state's new civil union law, five Republican state legislators
who supported the gay-rights law were defeated in Tuesday's
primary, while four other Republicans and one Democrat who
supported the law won their contested primaries.
</P>
<P>
   The primary was largely seen as a referendum on civil unions,
with many challengers campaigning largely on the issue. Earlier
this year, the Legislature enacted the nation's first law granting
same-sex couples many of the benefits and protections of marriage.
At the time, some voters threatened to retaliate at the polls
against legislators who voted for the law.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Marion Milne, a Republican who was the top
vote-getter in her central Vermont district two years ago, lost
overwhelmingly to Sylvia Kennedy, who was strongly opposed to the
civil-union law.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of angry people out there,'' Milne said of
her campaign this summer. ``I saw it and I tried to talk to people
about some of the other issues, although I did tell everybody that
I was proud of my vote.''
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Thomas Little, a Republican who led the House
Judiciary Committee in writing the civil-union law, defeated his
challenger, Rod Fisher. But Little said he was shaken up by the
fact that about 40 percent of his district's voters cast ballots
against him.
</P>
<P>
   In another Vermont race, Ed Flanagan, the state auditor,
narrowly defeated state Sen. Jan Backus in the Democratic primary
for U.S. Senate. Flanagan will challenge Sen. James Jeffords, a
Republican, who is running for a third term. Flanagan is the first
openly gay candidate to win a major party nomination for the U.S.
Senate, according to the Gay and Lesbian Victory Fund, a national
organization seeking to increase the number of openly gay and
lesbian public officials.
</P>
<P>
   The civil-unions law was not an issue in the Senate race because
Flanagan and Backus supported it. Jeffords also has said he
believed the law was appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the electoral fates of about a dozen House incumbents,
most of them Republicans, were thought to have hinged on their
civil-union votes. One Democrat from Burlington, Vt., who opposed
the law was ousted in favor of a candidate who said he would have
supported it.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Abbarno, executive director of the Vermont Republican
Party, said that voters were clearly ``sending a message,'' in
keeping with the ``Take Back Vermont'' signs that have sprung up
across the state in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether or not it's a backlash at civil unions or not, you
can't ignore that there is an umbrella issue over Vermont,''
Abbarno said, ``that those in Montpelier aren't listening to what
the people really want.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
