u f BC-KINGFISHER-WOOLWORTH-     09-13 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KINGFISHER-WOOLWORTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BRITISH WOOLWORTH'S HANGS ON IN THE MODERN MARKETPLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUZANNE KAPNER  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ One of the last vestiges of the Woolworth's empire
lives on in a British company, Kingfisher PLC, and though it has
managed to outlast its American parent, the chain of five-and-dime
stores is still searching for its place in modern retailing.
</P>
<P>
   That place looked a bit less certain Wednesday, when Kingfisher
said it would split itself in two as it reported half-year
financial results that were dragged down by sagging profit in its
general merchandise business.
</P>
<P>
   Pretax profit for the group fell 10 percent to 232.5 million
pounds, or nearly $328 million, on sales of 5.4 billion pounds.
</P>
<P>
   The home improvement and electronics stores will form a new
Kingfisher, the company said, while the general merchandise
business, consisting of Woolworth's and a drugstore chain, will be
shunted off into an as-yet-unnamed separate company. Kingfisher's
chief executive, Sir Geoffrey Mulcahy, said the breakup would help
stimulate international expansion in the new Kingfisher's
businesses. The old one will try to stem its profit decline at
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a shareholder, you'd want your shares in new
Kingfisher, that's the bit that's doing very well,'' said Michael
Godliman, a director with Verdict Research, a consulting group
here.
</P>
<P>
   Investors apparently agreed. Kingfisher shares, which fell more
than 6 percent on the news of the breakup, rebounded to close in
London with a 5.3 percent gain, at 4.775 pounds, or $6.73.
</P>
<P>
   For the Woolworth store brand, however, the breakup is an
indignity, merely the latest in a series of retreats that resulted
in the near-disappearance of the famous name in the United States _
the long shadow of the Woolworth Building in Manhattan aside. The
spread of discount stores, and later the huge, specialized
``category killers,'' made the Woolworth five-and-dime format
obsolete, a relic of retailing. Remnants of it were repackaged into
Venator Group, but even those stores would be closed.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in Britain, the Woolworth chain, which was founded by the
same Frank W. Woolworth, has managed to live on. The first British
Woolworth opened on Nov. 5, 1909, on Church Street in Liverpool.
The stores, selling everything from ladies' gloves to confectionery
for less than a dime, numbered 768 by the outset of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1970s, Woolworth, in disarray, was bought by a
London-based consortium, which closed 200 stores and revitalized
the rest. By the mid-1980s, the company was expanding, purchasing
Comet, a British electronics retailer, in 1984, and Superdrug, a
cut-price chain, three years later. The transformation was complete
in 1989, when the company changed its name to Kingfisher. Woolworth
continued to thrive for the next eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Woolworth's has managed to survive because Britain hasn't had
a tradition of discount stores,'' Godliman said, ``and so it didn't
have a lot of competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, discounting is coming to this country with a vengeance.
Stores like Matalan, modeled on Wal-Mart, are booming. Wal-Mart
itself has opened a supercenter and has bought the British
supermarket chain Asda. All the while, the Internet is taking an
increased share of Woolworth's music, video and book businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Woolworth is feeling the bite. For the
six-month period ending on July 29, its profit declined 40 percent,
to 10 million pounds, or about $14.1 million, on sales of 735
million pounds. The business that begot Kingfisher accounts today
for just 4 percent of the company's overall profit and 14 percent
of its sales.
</P>
<P>
   Still, British Woolworth, unwilling to go the way of its
moribund American relative, keeps trying to modernize. It is
opening general stores that sell food. And a Big W format, 10 times
the size of a typical store, is seeking to compete with
supercenters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will have to reconfigure what Woolworth's means in the
21st century,'' Godliman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
