<HEADLINE>
EVERYTHING NOT PEACHY WITH BULLDOGS FANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Following an embarrassing 21-10 loss to South Carolina last
Saturday, Georgia coach Jim Donnan is no doubt regretting his
summer comments about the Bulldogs.
</P>
<P>
   During a meeting last month with the Bulldog Club booster group,
Donnan gushed, ``I've been waiting 55 years to be the head coach of
a football team that has this much potential. And I guarantee you
that we're going to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   That guarantee proved costly as the normally genteel residents
of the Peach State reacted in a nasty manner this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Humiliating upset has the line buzzing and many people want
Donnan's head,'' roared a headline in the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The Augusta Chronicle began its report of the loss this way: ``A
moment of silence, please, for the death of the Georgia Bulldogs'
2000 football season.''
</P>
<P>
   It could be enough to make Donnan regret his offseason decision
to refuse a job offer from his alma mater, North Carolina State.
</P>
<P>
   For months, Donnan denied reports he was up for the Wolfpack
job. Then, during the summer, he admitted the university had
offered him ``an unbelievable'' deal.
</P>
<P>
   Donnan's denial and contradictory admission hardly endeared him
to Georgia fans, who already consider him untrustworthy because of
his penchant for interviewing at other schools.
</P>
<P>
   More troubling to Georgia fans: Donnan is just 20-13 in
Southeastern Conference games and 2-8 against top-10 teams since
being hired in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   __ Playing on fire: During the San Diego State mascot's dance
prior to the Illinois game on Saturday night, the fireball from his
torch accidentally fell onto the Qualcomm Stadium turf.
</P>
<P>
   After five minutes and several attempts to extinguish the flame,
the fire still burned on the 5-yard line before it eventually went
out.
</P>
<P>
   __ Boller wiser: Cal quarterback Kyle Boller, a graduate of Hart
High of Newhall, admitted last season was confusing at times as he
tried to run the offense as a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like playing cards and not knowing how to play the
game,'' Boller said. ``Some of the plays last year were like a
blur. I would drop back and all I would see were jerseys.''
</P>
<P>
   There was some thought that the experience might leave him a bit
shell shocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw him smack in the middle of some turmoil,'' Cal coach
Tom Holmoe said. ``People wondered whether I was going to scar him.
Well, maybe he got some physical scars but not emotional ones.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Class warfare: Stanford was humiliated for the third
consecutive season by San Jose State, the lightly regarded public
school 10 miles down the road from ritzy Palo Alto. And that angle
is precisely what drives Spartan players against the Cardinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the little rich kids up the street,'' San Jose State
defensive tackle John Hammer said. ``They won the Pac-10, but how
good is the Pac-10? I think the WAC is better than the Pac-10.''
</P>
<P>
   Said running Deonce Whitaker: ``Everyone knows what they have up
there and what we don't. It's like Beverly Hills getting beat by
Watts.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Spartans' 40-27 victory, San Jose State fans began
chanting ``Three-peat, three-peat, three-peat.''
</P>
<P>
   San Jose State players walked past the Stanford locker room on
the way to the visiting locker room and shouted, ``Pac-10,
schmack-10,'' and ``Pac-Who?''
</P>
<P>
   __ No responsibility: The Pac-10's perceived weakness has
nothing to do with Oregon State.
</P>
<P>
   The Beavers' victory over New Mexico marked Oregon State's 12th
consecutive regular-season victory over a nonconference opponent.
Their last loss was at Baylor on Sept. 21, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   __ Miraculous recovery: Wisconsin originally said wide receiver
Chris Chambers would be unavailable for its first four games when
he suffered a stress fracture in his foot during the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   The Badgers stuck with that diagnosis when Chambers was one of
26 players suspended for their role in receiving improper discounts
from an athletic shoe store.
</P>
<P>
   Then the NCAA, which originally said Chambers could serve his
three-game suspension while injured, changed its mind and decided
Chambers' suspensions couldn't start until he was deemed healthy
enough to play.
</P>
<P>
   Now, magically, it seems, Wisconsin coach Barry Alvarez said a
second diagnosis by team trainers has determined that Chambers
could have played against Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   That means the Oregon game and games this week against
Cincinnati and next week against Northwestern will complete
Chambers' suspension and make him eligible to return Sept. 30
against Michigan, which is when he was originally scheduled to
return.
</P>
<P>
   __ No fan of media: Iowa coach Kirk Ferentz ripped reporters
following the Hawkeyes' 27-21 loss to Western Michigan, Iowa's 10th
straight defeat and 16th in the past 17 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a headline in a paper that said if we didn't win today,
we may never win this year,'' Ferentz said. ``I'm glad that guy
wasn't in charge of our country. I don't think most competitive
people think like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have 10 games left. I like the guys we have on our
football team. We're far from ready to pack it in.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
