<SLUG> BC-CHEF-HARASS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER WHITE HOUSE CHEF FILES HARASSMENT SUIT
</HEADLINE>
  By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first woman hired as a full-time chef at the White House has
filed a sexual harassment lawsuit against her boss, the executive
pastry chef, and against President Clinton, accusing the president
of failing to provide a procedure for filing such a complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Franette McCulloch, who went to work for the executive pastry
chef, Roland Mesnier, in 1983 as assistant pastry chef, claims in
her suit that Mesnier had subjected her to ``severe sexual
harassment.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is named in the complaint because the head of a federal
agency, in this case the White House, is typically named in civil
rights suits brought against the agency. The complaint says that he
failed to establish a method for White House employees to report
civil rights violations, as required by a 1997 law.
</P>
<P>
   McCulloch is asking for $1 million from Mesnier and $1 million
from the president in the suit, which was filed Wednesday in U.S.
District Court in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Mesnier refused to comment on the suit. The White House press
secretary, Joe Lockhart, refused to discuss details of the case,
but said that all employees were informed of their rights for
filing grievances with the equal employment opportunity office at
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for McCulloch said there was no equal employment
opportunity office at the White House until recently.
</P>
<P>
   Mesnier hired McCulloch after she completed an apprenticeship
with him. Her suit claims Mesnier began harassing her in 1991 when
he told her he was planning to divorce his wife. When she refused
his overtures, the suit claims, the harassment escalated, with
demands for sex, phone calls to her at home, hostility and
abusiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Over several years, McCulloch complained to Gary Walters, the
chief usher at the White House, who, the suit claims, said he would
talk to Mesnier. This angered Mesnier, the suit says, and he became
more abusive, excluding her from the creative process of dessert
planning, and instead assigning her menial tasks like peeling kiwis
and cleaning out the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, McCulloch received her first less-than-perfect
evaluation, the suit says, claiming that Mesnier linked the
evaluation to ``the little problem we had.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation became increasingly tense until 1997 when, the
suit says, McCulloch began to see a therapist on a regular basis
for stress and depression. In June 1999, McCulloch, on the advice
of a doctor, went on disability leave without pay, the suit says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
