<HEADER>
A3555 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-OLY-RUNYAN-LADN-(SLAN     09-13 1509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-RUNYAN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUNYAN ALREADY BIG WINNER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATTHEW KREDELL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As a runner at Camarillo (Calif.) High, Marla
Runyan would sometimes break down and cry before races because she
was so scared. Insecurity over her running is something Runyan
battled throughout high school and college.
</P>
<P>
   ``She always had butterflies before a race,'' said Chuck
Stevenson, who coaches track at Camarillo. ``I tried to calm her
down. I told her, 'Marla, you'll be OK.' And then of course, she
would go out and win.''
</P>
<P>
   When Runyan took her position before the start of the 1,500 at
the Olympic Trials in Sacramento in July, she had every reason to
go through all of those same insecurities.
</P>
<P>
   Here was her chance to do something special, not just for
herself but for all blind people and those with other disabilities
who look to her, and Runyan couldn't even run a practice lap.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't her eyesight _ Runyan has been legally blind since
childhood because of a retina-deteriorating condition called
Stargardt's Disease _ that made her status unknown up until race
time.
</P>
<P>
   Runyan hurt her knee while training on a public trail near her
home in Eugene, Ore., six weeks before the trials. She jumped out
of the way of a child on a bicycle who she couldn't see until she
was too close.
</P>
<P>
   She went to a Colorado doctor who had worked miracles before for
rehabilitation. With only a few weeks until the Olympic Trials, it
was as if she was being plopped in front of Billy Crystal's miracle
man in ``The Princess Bride,'' needing to be brought back from the
dead.
</P>
<P>
   On July 4, 12 days before her Olympic hopes in the 1,500 would
be on the line, Runyan thought she would need to pull out of the
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``How in the world could I do it?'' Runyan said. ``But the next
day I could rotate my knee in the pool and started doing pool
workouts. I could only take two strides running and then the knee
would lock up, but it gave me hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Runyan went to Sacramento and prepared for the biggest race of
her life in the only way she could.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two days before the race, I couldn't run,'' Runyan said. ``I
tried to jog and could only make it six minutes. The day of the
race, I was able to jog one lap. Then I tried to do one more and I
couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I still had confidence in myself. I felt that, other than
my knee being injured, my body was really fit. I felt my mind was
really fit. I visualized the race so many times, like I was
training in my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   The night before the race, Runyan sat up visualizing herself
running. She didn't visualize herself winning, she told her
boyfriend and trainer, Matt Lonergan. She saw herself finishing
third (the top three finishers qualify for the Olympics).
</P>
<P>
   It sounded great, and Lonergan hoped that once the race started,
Runyan's mind would be able to overcome her body.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was easier for her than for us watching,'' Lonergan said.
``From our perspective it was, `How the hell is she going to do
it?' '' I was a wreck. I was sitting in the stands off the last
turn with a college friend of mine. When she was at the line, I
told him I was going to be sick, I was so nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, Runyan stayed calm. She found that if she crossed her
legs and pulled her left toe up, she could get a really good
stretch that made her forget about the pain for a bit.
</P>
<P>
   She ignored first and second _ Regina Jacobs and Suzy Favor
Hamilton would have been heavily favored even if Runyan had two
good wheels _ and focused on third.
</P>
<P>
   Runyan started out cautiously but got in a good position because
of what she called a perfect pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really thankful that Suzy and Regina didn't go out like
crazy,'' Runyan said. ``When I saw how Suzy (who started next to
Runyan) went off the line, I knew I would have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Runyan hoped that if the pace began slowly, she could reach
another gear down the backstrech. In fifth place, Runyan pushed for
that gear and found it, blowing by Shayne Culpepper to take third
by nearly two seconds.
</P>
<P>
   As the former four-time gold medalist in the World Paralympics
Games crossed the finish line, becoming the first legally blind
athlete to make a U.S. Olympic team, she thrust her arms in the air
triumphantly.
</P>
<P>
   That was just for finishing. She still wasn't sure she had
qualified for the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually went up to the official and asked if I was third,''
Runyan said. ``I couldn't see Suzy or Regina ahead of me and I
wasn't sure there was not another runner with them. I was 98
percent sure.''
</P>
<P>
   The official confirmed and Runyan got to do another thing she
had been visualizing, taking an American flag and doing a victory
lap with Jacobs and Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   Runyan's feelings after qualifying for the Olympics were not
what she had envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I would feel like a different person, but I felt
like the same person,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction from others, however, was much more than she had
expected. Runyan was been bombarded by media requests from around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got back from Sacramento, I had 250 e-mails,'' said
Runyan, who had to change her e-mail address as the messages piled
up. ``Most of the response was from the media.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the media attention has focused on her eyesight,
something Runyan has always tried to downplay. She was in the
fourth grade when diagnosed with Stargardt's Disease and her
eyesight now is about the same as it was in high school.
</P>
<P>
   Still, her vision is 20/300 in her left eye and 20/400 in her
right _ and that's with contact lenses. She can barely see things
directly in front of her.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media has always thought I was the type of kid that
couldn't do it, but there was always one person who said, 'Yes, you
can,' '' Runyan said. ``It's the other way around, with me always
saying I can do this and everyone else saying you can't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson, who beamed with pride while talking about his first
Camarillo High disciple to make the Olympics, found out quickly to
never doubt what Runyan could do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was never a big deal,'' Stevenson said of Runyan's
eyesight. ``We knew she had the handicap and I'm sure the people
she ran against, some realized it and some didn't even know. She
didn't ask for any special favors or anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson points out that Runyan didn't only find a way to excel
on the track but also in the classroom. Using a camera that
projected pages of books onto a screen so they could be enlarged,
Runyan finished high school with a 3.98 GPA. She went on to get a
bachelor's degree in education of the deaf and a master's degree in
education of deaf-blind children from San Diego State.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't understand that this is the way the world has
looked to me since I was 10,'' Runyan said. ``I have only seen the
track as I see it now. I have nothing else to compare it to. I
don't think I have a disability. I think I'm normal and everyone
else just has really good vision.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why it was so surprising to Runyan when she returned from
the Trials to get so much attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just amazing,'' she said. ``I have received more e-mails
and letters than I know what to do with. In many ways, the positive
results (from making the Olympics) are more important than my race
at the Olympics itself. I didn't think it would be like this. It's
kind of cool. A lot of people make the Olympic team and it goes
unnoticed.''
</P>
<P>
   After the trials, Runyan fit visits to blind children into her
busy training and rehabilitation schedule. She escaped the confines
of her Colorado-based training site to meet with kids at a Denver
center for blind children in early August and has exchanged e-mails
with legally blind children through the U.S. Association of Blind
Athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat lost in all of the commotion is that she still has a
little business to take care of in Sydney. Runyan is progressing
well in recovering fully from her knee injury. In mid-August, she
could run 46 minutes without pain, a far cry from the six minutes
she was jogging leading up to the trials.
</P>
<P>
   Runyan's ultimate goal has been to qualify for the Olympics. She
is not expected to medal in Sydney. Her new goal is to make the
finals and run a personal-best time.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike those races back in high school, Runyan will step to
the line with confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it just shows how much I've matured,'' she said.
``I've heard myself say how important attitude is because I have
many interviews with people who always want to talk about my
vision. I've said it millions of times in interviews. If I get into
a funk, I can hear myself, and I tell myself that I need to take my
own advice or I'm a hypocrite.''
</P>
<P>
   Representing people with disabilities, the United States,
Camarillo and herself, Runyan won't have a shortage of people
pulling for another miracle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she will represent us very well there,'' Stevenson
said. ``She won't give up, that's for sure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
