<HEADER>
A3561 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-MARRIAGE-TAX-HNS &LR;      09-13 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARRIAGE-TAX-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Clinton's veto is upheld on marriage tax
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By KAREN MASTERSON
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Not enough Democrats said, ``I do,'' Wednesday in a
bid to override the president's veto of the so-called marriage
penalty tax repeal, killing the proposal for the remainder of this
legislative session.
</P>
<P>
   In a House vote of 270-158, the veto override effort fell 16
votes short of the two-thirds majority needed.
</P>
<P>
   The vote may be the GOP's last major battle with the White House
over tax-cut proposals. And the party didn't give it up without a
show.
</P>
<P>
   On the Capitol grounds, Republicans constructed a scene that
looked a lot like the top of a crowded wedding cake. A marriage
trellis with braided white taffeta hung over three recently married
couples dressed in white gowns and tuxedoes.
</P>
<P>
   The scene served as the backdrop for an afternoon news
conference. As Felix Mendelssohn's wedding march sounded from a
small boom box, the Republican leadership slammed Democrats for
failing to support ``love and marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats want to spend the surplus on new, big government
programs,'' said House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Sugar Land.
Republicans, he said, want to return that money to taxpayers,
especially married couples now paying the ``unfair'' and
``immoral`` penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton vetoed the bill in August because he said it was part of
a package of Republican tax cuts that would eat too much of the
nation's projected $2.2 trillion, 10-year budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm terribly disappointed,'' said Rep. Kevin Brady, R-The
Woodlands. ``Ending the marriage penalty should be a bipartisan
effort. I'm frustrated because many Democrats claim they stand for
working families.''
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats maintained that they support repealing the
``marriage penalty'' tax, although not as proposed by Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to repeal the penalty,'' said Rep. Gene Green,
D-Houston. ``But we should have one tax cut, one bill at a time.
Republicans included so much into the same bill, it was not really
just the marriage penalty. The rest was other little things they
wanted in there, like a tax benefit to stay-at-home parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Green said he backed the Democrats' alternative, which would
have cost less and been limited in scope.
</P>
<P>
   Only 49 Democrats joined 220 Republicans and one Independent in
support of the override; 157 Democrats and one Independent backed
the president and voted against it.
</P>
<P>
   Of the Democrats who voted for the override, two were from
Texas: Rep. Ralph M. Hall of Rockwall and Rep. Max Sandlin of
Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers from the Houston area voted along party lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton's latest veto leaves a Clinton/Gore legacy
of denying 25 million married couples relief from the marriage tax
penalty,'' said Rep. Bill Archer, R-Houston. Archer is chairman of
the House Ways and Means Committee, which writes the nation's tax
laws.
</P>
<P>
   The Marriage Penalty Tax Relief Act, drafted by Archer, would
have cut married couples' taxes by $292 billion over 10 years. The
Democrats' plan would have cut taxes by $95 billion over the same
period.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans would have changed the standard deduction for
married couples filing jointly to make it equal to twice the
standard deduction for single tax payers, which is similar to the
Democrats' bill. Currently, those deductions are $4,400 for single
people and $7,350 for married couples.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the Democrats' bill, Archer's legislation would have
expanded tax credit programs for families living on one income, for
low-incomes families and for families with children and expenses
associated with education and adoptions.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to failing to override the veto, Republicans also
could not muster the votes last week to override the president's
veto of the estate tax repeal.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have since switched gears and are now calling on
Democrats to roll 90 percent of next year's projected surplus _
about $240 billion _ into a one-time pay-down of the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``They stopped the tax cuts because they know Al Gore has a big
spending program,'' said Speaker of the House J. Dennis Hastert,
R-Ill. ``Let's pay down the debt, so taxpayers don't have to
continue to pay for the interest.''
</P>
<P>
   As for couples in the warm Washington weather, they made their
own plea to end the ``marriage penalty.``
</P>
<P>
   ``Our wedding was a happy day for us,'' said Helena Charters,
standing before reporters in a pearl-studded white dress and veil.
``But it was also a happy day for the IRS.''
</P>
<P>
   Charters is an elementary school teacher, and her husband,
Timothy, is an aide to a Republican congressman.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
