<HEADER>
A3567 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-WOODY-HAYES0915-C     09-13 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-WOODY-HAYES0915-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hayes presence will be felt in Saturday's game between Miami
University and Ohio State
 &HT;    By Pete Conrad
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OXFORD, Ohio _ Woody Hayes. Mention the name, and you've
conjured up vivid images of a man with a passion for college
football. Images of Heisman Trophy running backs and clouds of
dust, of Rose Bowls and national championship celebrations, of a
gentle man with an explosive temper.
</P>
<P>
   Mention the name, and you're likely to start an argument.
</P>
<P>
   There can be no argument about the fact, however, that when
Miami University and Ohio State finally collide Saturday afternoon
after going their separate ways for 89 years, the atmosphere of
Ohio Stadium will be saturated by the
</P>
<P>
   spirit of Woody Hayes, probably more than any other college game
played since his death in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   On one sideline will be the red and white of Miami, the
university where Hayes flared briefly like a shooting star and then
was gone, leaving one of the great seasons in school history in his
wake.
</P>
<P>
   On the other sideline will be the scarlet and gray of Ohio
State, the university where Hayes spent 28 of the most
unpredictable years in college football history, and where he
coached two of the greatest teams in college football history _ the
1954 and 1968 Buckeyes _ to undefeated national championships.
</P>
<P>
   Former players who were coached by Hayes at each school remember
him not only as the same type of man, but use the same words to do
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a stern taskmaster,'' said Joe Codiano, who played for
Hayes at Miami in 1949 and '50, ``but he really liked the people
around him and he'd do anything for you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a taskmaster and he expected the best,'' said Bill
Wilks, the former Hamilton High football and basketball standout
who became Hayes' first recruit at Ohio State in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   Codiano, a resident of Brookville, Ind., who graduated from
Miami in 1952 and went on to a distinguished coaching career in
Indiana, was recruited as a quarterback by Hayes' predecessor in
Oxford, George Blackburn. Blackburn spent only one year at Miami,
guiding the 1948 Redskins to the Mid-American Conference
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost transferred to the University of Cincinnati after
Coach Blackburn left,'' Codiano recalled. ``But Coach Hayes talked
me out of it, and I'm happy he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Codiano changed positions and started as a defensive back and
inside linebacker for the Miami team that won the 1950 Salad Bowl
(now it's the Fiesta Bowl) by whipping Arizona State 34-21.
</P>
<P>
   The following year Hayes found himself in the big time. He also
found himself without a suitable starting quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wesley Fesler was coach of Ohio State and left to go to
another school,'' Wilks said, ``so Woody got the job. Coach Fesler
had a single-wing offense, and (after he left) they didn't have a
`T' quarterback at Ohio State.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilks, who had played quarterback for the Big Blue under coach
Chuck Thackara, had been recruited out of Hamilton as a basketball
player and became a three-year starter for the Buckeyes. Hayes knew
about Wilks' other talents, so he went to OSU basketball coach
Floyd Stahl and asked if he would allow Wilks, who was then a
junior, to play quarterback during football season. Stahl said
sure.
</P>
<P>
   Wilks started a handful of games in Hayes' first season at Ohio
State, but saw little playing time during his senior season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Woody was looking to build, and he wasn't looking at me as his
future quarterback,'' Wilks said. ``Eventually he developed Will
Leggett as his quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   Leggett, under Hayes' guidance, helped lead the 1954 Buckeyes to
the national championship, along with legendary running back Howard
``Hopalong'' Cassady. Wilks said he is bothered by comparisons in
recent days between Hayes and Indiana basketball coach Bobby
Knight. Both lost their jobs because of well-publicized outbursts,
but Wilks said Hayes and Knight really have little in common.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no comparison,'' Wilks said. ``Woody never used
profanity, and he never was disrespectful to his players. Ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd throw his hat on the ground and jump on it and pound his
fist. Whether he had lost his temper and was trying to take it out
on the ground or was just trying to make a point, I don't know. But
Woody said he'd never blame a player, and he never did.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Codiano, Hayes ``was a stickler on getting things
done and getting them done his way, but he was also a friend to
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
