<P>
   (NYT38) BUFFALO, N.Y. -- Sept. 13, 2000 -- NY-SENATE-DEBATE-3 --
Facing off in what turned out to be an often testy first debate of
their Senate campaign in New York, Hillary Rodham Clinton
repeatedly attacked Republican Rep. Rick Lazio on Wednesday as a
disciple of conservative former House Speaker Newt Gingrich. Lazio,
in turn, sought again and again to link the first lady to the
policies and even peccadilloes of her husband. Lazio and Clinton
during their first of three debates. (James Estrin/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) WACO, Texas -- Sept. 13, 2000 -- GORE-FUNDRAISING -- For
Vice President Al Gore, a November 1995 fund-raising dinner at the
Houston home of attorney John Eddie Williams Jr., was the chance to
promote a budding relationship between the Democratic Party and a
handful of powerful Texas trial lawyers. The relationship blossomed
but it produced heavy-handed fund-raising techniques that have
recently drawn the scrutiny of federal campaign finance
investigators. Williams and his wife Sheridan during an event at
Baylor Law School, Oct. 26, 1998. (Duane A. Laverty/The Houston
Chronicle) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) BOSTON -- Sept. 13, 2000 -- GORE-3 -- Ted Kennedy chats
with Democratic presidential candidate Al Gore as they head towards
the center of Boston while cruising across Boston Harbor aboard the
``Flying Cloud'' ferry, Wednesday. Gore and running mate Joseph
Lieberman were on their way to a predinner rally in Christopher
Columbus park in Boston, where Gore told a crowd of 5,000 that
Republicans ``have some gall'' claiming the nation was better off
before the Clinton administration took over from his rival's
father, former President Bush. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times )
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 13, 2000 -- VIOLENCE-KIDS-2 -- Sen.
Joseph I. Lieberman, right, Rep. Henry J. Hyde, center, and Sen.
Orrin G. Hatch at a Senate hearing before the Senate Commerce
Committee, Wednesday on the level of sex and violence in movies,
videos and TV shows. The Senators warned entertainment industry
executives to clean up material aimed at children or face federal
regulation. (Susana Raab/The New York Times) MAGS OUT.....NO SALES
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) BUFFALO, N.Y. -- Sept. 13, 2000 -- NY-SENATE-DEBATE-2 --
Hillary Rodham Clinton and Republican Rep. Rick Lazio launched into
their first debate Wednesday, with the first lady defending her
failed effort at health care reform and her opponent accusing her
of acting against the interest of New Yorkers. Facing off in what
turned out to be an often testy debate, Lazio at one point walked
to Clinton's side and tried unsuccessfully to get her to sign a
pledge to bar soft money from their campaigns. After having his
pledge waved in her face, she told him ``that was a wonderful
performance.'' ``I'm not asking you to admire it, I'm asking you to
sign it,'' Lazio shot back. (James Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Sept. 13, 2000 --
BIOTECH-MEDICINE-BOS -- Dr. Clive Meanwell founded a business four
years ago based on the idea that there was money to be made off
drugs other companies cast aside. His start-up known as the
Medicines Co. picks through and rescues products languishing on
shelves because of lackluster test results, shifting corporate
priorities, or development problems. Meanwell holding Angiomax, a
blood thinner used to prevent blood clots. (David L. Ryan/The
Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) BOSTON -- Sept. 13, 2000 -- GORE-2 -- The fingers of Ted
Kennedy, his nephew Joseph Kennedy and Joseph Lieberman point past
Democratic presidential candidate Al Gore as they gesture towards
the center of Boston while cruising across Boston Harbor aboard the
``Flying Cloud'' ferry, Wednesday. Gore and Lieberman were on their
way to a predinner rally in Christopher Columbus park in Boston,
where Gore told a crowd of 5,000 that Republicans ``have some
gall'' claiming the nation was better off before the Clinton
administration took over from his rival's father, former President
Bush. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times )
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) BUFFALO, N.Y. -- Sept. 13, 2000 -- NY-SENATE-DEBATE-1 --
Hillary Rodham Clinton and Republican Rep. Rick Lazio launched into
their first debate Wednesday, with the first lady defending her
failed effort at health care reform and her opponent accusing her
of acting against the interest of New Yorkers. Facing off in what
turned out to be an often testy debate, Lazio at one point walked
to Clinton's side and tried unsuccessfully to get her to sign a
pledge to bar soft money from their campaigns. After having his
pledge waved in her face, she told him ``that was a wonderful
performance.'' ``I'm not asking you to admire it, I'm asking you to
sign it,'' Lazio shot back. (James Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) SYDNEY, Australia -- Sept. 13, 2000 -- OLY-HOST-TEAM --
Australia is once again an Olympic power, and with the help of home
crowds and hyper-motivated, well-prepared athletes, it could set a
new national standard by winning as many as 60 medals in everything
from field hockey to trap shooting to tennis. Australia might
finish as high as fourth in the medal count. Andrew Gaze, a member
of the Australian basketball team during a press conference to
announce that he will be the flag bearer for Australia. (Francisco
Bernasconi/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) SYDNEY, Australia -- Sept. 13, 2000 -- OLY-SYDNEY-BOS --
The Olympics were still a rumor until the runners bearing the fiery
boomerang torch hit town this week. On Friday evening, one of
Australia's own will use the Olympic torch to ignite the cauldron
inside Stadium Australia and the Games of the XXVII Olympiad will
begin. It's been 44 years since the Olympics were held in
Australia. The Olympic Boulevared in the Olympic Park gets a final
cleaning before the start of the Games on Friday. (Mark Wilson/The
Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) PALALY, Sri Lanka -- Sept. 13, 2000 --
SRILANKA-CHILD-SOLDIERS-2 -- Two years ago the Liberation Tigers of
Tamil Eelam met in the northern jungles of Sri Lanka with Olara A.
Ottunu, the U.N. official charged with trying to halt the use of an
estimated 300,000 child soldiers worldwide. They promised him they
would stop using children to fight thier war. But recent evidence
strongly suggests they have continued using children. Renuka
Ramaswamy, 13, emerging from the detention center in Palaly where
she's being held. Ramaswamy says she was a solder for the Tiger
rebels. (Celia Dugger/The New York Times) STORY AND ONE OTHER PHOTO
MOVED ON SEPT. 10, 2000
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) MONTAGUE, Mich. -- Sept. 13, 2000 -- CHENEY-BUSH --
Republican vice presidential nominee Dick Cheney told farmers
Wednesday that they shouldn't have to worry about a federal estate
tax when passing along the family farm. Using a fourth-generation
farm in western Michigan as a backdrop, Cheney told about 400
people about his running mate George W. Bush's plan to eliminate
the estate tax if elected president. (Andrea Mohin/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Sept. 13, 2000 --
ASTRONOMY-NAMES-BOS -- At the offices of the Minor Planets Center,
which certifies new asteroid discoveries, name suggestions pour in
every day. The director of the center, Dr. Brian Marsden,63, finds
the naming to be a simple part of the process. The center's mandate
is to sift out, from observatories on five continents, evidence of
new objects so that their orbits can be calculated, with a careful
eye to ``near-earth objects.'' Marsden with the ``Great Refractor''
telescope. For 20 years it was the largest telesope in the United
States. (Jonathan Wiggs/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) DAYTON, Ohio -- Sept. 13, 2000 -- END-DYING-COX --
Futile care, almost everyone agrees, is any attempt to save lives
after that point. Nor is there much dispute that futile care is
something to be avoided, inflicting physical and emotional pain
along with expense. But the consensus evaporates over exactly where
the noble fight against death turns into unwarranted interference.
``I think it's always going to be a squiggly line,'' says Sister
Carol Bauer, an ethicist who is vice president of mission
effectiveness at Good Samaritan Hospital in Dayton, Ohio. ``It
depends, for example, on individual circumstances and the patient's
wishes.'' (Bill Reinke/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) BOSTON -- Sept. 13, 2000 -- FASHION-SNEAKERS-BOS --
Shunned since the early '90s as unfashionable, sneakers have become
trendy again as Europeans crave brightly colored Pumas, Adidas, and
New Balance. Prada Sport's sneaker gets credit for truly pushing
such footwear into mainstream fashion, upping the sneaker cache
quotient instantly. Prada Sport's silver and blue sneaker retails
for $250, making it among the most expensive. (Suzanne Kreiter/The
Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) BOSTON -- Sept. 13, 2000 -- NEJM-REVAMP-BOS -- The New
England Journal of Medicine, the world's most esteemed medical
magazine is taking on a decidedly different look that ensures it
will continue to be the center of controversy. Dr. Jeffrey Drazen,
the new editor-in-chief of the New England Journal of Medicine in
his office in Boston. (Jim Davis/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) SYDNEY, Australia -- Sept. 13, 2000 -- OLY-BOX-US -- The
felon, the drug addict, the banker, the dreamer, the staff
sergeant, the next Golden Boy, a guy named Rocky and another
nicknamed Hawaiian Punch. They are the 2000 United States Olympic
Boxing team, and while they are characters with rich personal
stories, they are also considered the strongest group of American
Olympic boxers in nearly 25 years. From left: Jermain Taylor, Jeff
Lacy, Olanda Anderson, Michael Bennett, and Calvin Brock during a
press conference on Wednesday. (Francisco Bernasconi/The New York
Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) AUSTIN, Texas -- Sept. 13, 2000 -- BULLS-RUN-COX --
Derik Strelsky, a former rodeo clown and bullfighter, is modeling a
Texas version of Spain's Running of the Bulls after the
centuries-old melee in Pamplona, Spain. Strelsky says he's staging
the event in Jarrell, Texas as a way to draw attention to the Pro
Rodeo Cowboys Association sport of bullfighting, which pits human
against bovine in a one-on-one grudge match. Unlike running down
cobblestone streets in Pamplona, twenty bulls will be set free
behind groups of runners, who will dash down a fenced-in alley
toward an arena. (Laura Skelding/The Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 13, 2000 -- VIOLENCE-KIDS --
Senators decried the level of sex and violence in movies, videos
and TV shows Wednesday and warned entertainment industry executives
to clean up material aimed at children or face federal regulation.
Lynne Cheney, former head of the National Endowment for the
Humanities and wife of Republican vice presidential nominee Dick
Cheney, and Sen. Joseph Lieberman, the Democratic vice presidential
nominee, during testimony Wednesday before the Senate Commerce
Committee. (Susana Raab/The New York Times) -MAGS OUT, NO SALES-
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 13, 2000 -- CONGRESS-HATE-CRIMES --
Armed with more data showing hate crimes often go unreported,
President Clinton on Wednesday appealed to Congress to pass hate
crimes legislation. Clinton walks with Sherialyn Byrdsong, the
widow of Ricky Byrdsong, a former Northwestern University
basketball coach killed in a 1999 hate-motivated shooting rampage,
as they arrive to the White House event, Wednesday. (Justin
Lane/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
