<SLUG> BC-OLY-POSTCARD-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
G'DAY FROM AUSTRALIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
Dear American readers,
<TEXT>
<P>
   You'll find considerably more queues (lines) than kangaroos in
and around Sydney Olympic Park. So when a hotelier in Bondi Beach
lamented in one of the local newspapers that the site of the
Olympic beach-volleyball competition is ``like a ghost town,''
that's straight where I headed.
</P>
<P>
   Bondi Bay is less than 20 miles from Homebush Bay, but the drive
took an hour in midday traffic. No worries; the scene that awaited
me was more soothing than a 60-minute massage.
</P>
<P>
   It was a lovely day for sunbathing, with the temperature
climbing into the 70s. And yet the crowd spread along the mile-long
stretch of beach was tinier than a string bikini. This was so, said
Greg, the lifeguard on duty, not because of any Olympics backlash
but because Sydneysiders are no more conditioned to go to the beach
in September than Summer Olympians are to go for the gold in
September.
</P>
<P>
   In November, when spring is heating up here, ``we'll get 10,000
to 15,000 people a day,'' Greg said. ``Some days you can't see the
sand, there are so many bodies.''
</P>
<P>
   As Greg scanned the sand from his tower, what he mostly saw were
unfamiliar faces. He estimated 80 percent of the sunbathers were
tourists. Who were we to disagree with him? The first person we
randomly picked to converse with to soak up some local color turned
out to be a tourist from Newport Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The riptide was strong, which explained the ``No Swimming'' sign
that looked so out of place, standing as it was against a backdrop
of surfers meshed in emerald waves.
</P>
<P>
   Bondi Olympic Watch, an environmental activist group, gathered
12,000 signatures opposing the development of the venue, which its
members consider a blight on their shores. I couldn't disagree
more. I think the Olympic volleyball venue blends into the scenery
like a red and orange sunset. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Catch ya' later, &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Karen Crouse &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-00 2315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
