<SLUG> BC-APPLE-MACOS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 APPLE COUNTING ON THE POWER OF 10  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A moment Macintosh fans and developers have
awaited for more than a decade finally arrived Wednesday: Apple
Computer released, if only in beta-test form, a thoroughly modern
version of the 16-year-old Mac operating system.
</P>
<P>
   As long ago as 1988, Apple's then-chief executive officer, John
Sculley, said Apple engineers were rewriting the Mac system
software from the ground up, to put it on a more-stable foundation
that would support future growth.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Apple has delivered a variety of compelling
improvements, but it never quite delivered on Sculley's promise.
</P>
<P>
   Until Wednesday. Ironically, it was Steve Jobs _ the man who
co-founded Apple, got pushed out by Sculley in 1985, took charge
again in 1997 and since then has spearheaded the company's
remarkable recovery _ who had the honor of introducing the radical
rewrite his former-friend-turned-nemesis had promised so long ago.
</P>
<P>
   In a keynote address to a Paris trade show called Apple Expo,
Jobs proclaimed the new system, called Mac OS X (pronounced
``ten''), ``the future of Apple.'' The test version is available on
CD-ROM for $29.95 at Apple's online store (www.apple.com/store).
The official 1.0 is slated for release sometime in ``early 2001.''
</P>
<P>
   The lowest levels of Mac OS X are based on Unix, the
``industrial-strength'' operating system used on most servers and
workstations. That will make Mac OS X, unlike any previous version,
what industry insiders jokingly call ``buzzword-compliant.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it is based on principles of operating-system
design such as pre-emptive multitasking, protected memory and
symmetrical multitasking. Clearly, only a minority of Apple's
customers can define those terms, but they will translate into
something all users are bound to appreciate: more stable, powerful
and responsive computers.
</P>
<P>
   Apple's not counting just on new plumbing, however, to sell Mac
OS X. The system also boasts powerful new graphics capabilities _
based largely on industry standards like Adobe's .pdf (Acrobat)
format and the OpenGL 3D technology relied on by many game
developers.
</P>
<P>
   On top of all this, Apple has endowed Mac OS X with a slick and
streamlined new look it calls Aqua. The interface borrows heavily
from the software developed at NeXT, the failed computer company
Jobs ran during his exile from Apple, and it will require the Mac
faithful to forsake some core elements of the traditional Mac look
and feel in favor of NeXT-derived widgets.
</P>
<P>
   Mac users who want to try all this out will need up-to-date
hardware and plenty of memory. The system will run, according to
Apple, only on Macs with factory-installed PowerPC G3 and G4
processors _ in other words, not on Mac clones or even most
Apple-branded models made before mid-1998, even if they since have
had processor upgrades.
</P>
<P>
   Even one G3-based model, the original PowerBook G3, didn't quite
make the cutoff. But the new system will run on all versions of the
iMac, the popular consumer model Apple introduced two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Many iMacs, though _ among other qualifying models _ will need a
memory upgrade to handle the new system. The beta version requires
128 megabytes of RAM, twice as much as Apple had previously said
would be needed.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials said Wednesday that they still hope to make
the final Mac OS X run on 64 megabytes of RAM.
</P>
<P>
   Making the transition to the new system smooth for developers
and customers is the toughest technical challenge Apple has faced
since it adopted a new processor _ the PowerPC _ in 1993 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts agree that Apple did a remarkable job in that case, by
providing software that enabled programs written for older chips to
run, with only minimal slowdown, on PowerPC-based Macs.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the company is trying to pull off a similar trick:
Mac OS X can run most existing Mac applications in what Apple calls
the ``Classic'' environment, a version of the older Mac OS that
loads automatically inside the new one when users launch an older
application.
</P>
<P>
   The Classic environment, though, offers no clear advantage over
Mac OS 9, so the long-run success of Mac OS X will be determined by
how many developers invest in updating their applications to take
full advantage of the new system.
</P>
<P>
   So far, only a handful has done so. Mac OS X CD comes with a
beta version of Microsoft's Internet Explorer that fully exploits
the new system, but Office 2001, an updated productivity suite the
Redmond, Wash., company plans to release next month, will run only
in the Classic mode.
</P>
<P>
   Adobe, Quark and other developers that are key to the Mac's
professional market also have promised but not yet delivered Mac OS
X-optimized versions of their products.
</P>
<P>
   In other news, Apple updated its iBook portable line Wednesday,
introducing faster chips, larger drives, FireWire ports, a DVD
option and new colors. One new model, available in indigo and key
lime, will sell for $1,499. The iBook Special Edition, equipped
with a DVD-ROM drive, will go for $1,799 in lime or graphite.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Henry Norr at hnorr(AT)sfchronicle.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-00 2316EDT &QL; 
