<SLUG> BC-INKTOMI-WEBCAST-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 INKTOMI BETS BIG ON WEBCASTING  &HT;     By VERNE KOPYTOFF 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Inktomi Corp. leaped into the emerging Internet
broadcasting industry Wednesday by disclosing the acquisition of
FastForward Networks, a San Francisco maker of Webcasting software,
in a deal valued at $1.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition will give Foster City, Calif.'s Inktomi
technology to distribute and monitor live Internet broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   That market is expected to grow dramatically with increasing
broadcasts of concerts, conferences and sporting events, now
notorious for jerky images and poor sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are seeing the Internet as a new channel capable of
delivering new experiences,'' said Dick Pierce, an executive vice
president at Inktomi. ``This could be a significant chunk of
Inktomi's revenues in a couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   FastForward's clients include Digital Island, an online content
delivery company, and RealNetworks, which sells multimedia software
for the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce said he expects many more clients as technology improves.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Elstein, an analyst who specializes in multimedia for the
Aberdeen Group, a market research firm in Boston, said Inktomi's
acquisition is a significant addition to the company's arsenal of
software.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted that Internet broadcasting will become increasingly
prevalent and profitable but added that there are many technical
hurdles to overcome before most consumers will get high-resolution
images.
</P>
<P>
   ``Television quality is still a few years away,'' Elstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Inktomi's acquisition underscores the firm's continuing
transformation from a Internet search engine provider to a Internet
infrastructure business. Search now accounts for only 30 percent of
Inktomi's revenue, versus 70 percent for services like data caching
and Internet content delivery software.
</P>
<P>
   For the third quarter of this year, Inktomi reported that it had
$61.5 million in revenue. The company had a profit of $4.5 million
(4 cents per share).
</P>
<P>
   Inktomi's image suffered in June when Yahoo dropped the firm's
search engine on its portal in favor of Google, the Internet
upstart from Mountain View. The loss for Inktomi was not big in
terms of revenue, but it caused the company's stock to decline
dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   Inktomi's last acquisition was in June, when the company bought
the Ultraseek software division of the Go Network, Disney's online
properties. The $344.7 million deal gave Inktomi a search engine
for corporations.
</P>
<P>
   The deal with FastForward, a private firm with 75 employees, is
an all-stock transaction. Inktomi will exchange nearly 11.9 million
shares of its common stock, which closed at $111 a share on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Inktomi's stock was down $2.25 to $108.75 in regular
trading.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Verne Kopytoff at vkopytoff(AT)sfchronicle.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
