 NAPSTER SAYS RECORD FIRMS OUT TO `KILL'  &HT;     By BENNY EVANGELISTA 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In its final legal pleading before going to
court, Napster Inc. argued the record industry is trying to kill
new technology to keep control over music distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the San Mateo, Calif., firm late Tuesday filed a
36-page brief with the U.S. Court of Appeals in San Francisco,
which will decide next month whether to overturn a lower court's
preliminary injunction against Napster, creator of a popular online
music-sharing program.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case is about whether plaintiffs (major record companies)
can use their control over music copyrights to achieve control over
Napster's decentralized technology and prevent it from transforming
the Internet in ways that might undermine their present chokehold
on music promotion and distribution,'' according to the brief filed
by Napster's legal team, headed by high-powered attorney David
Boies.
</P>
<P>
   Napster also contends the record industry, which is trying to
stop the the company on grounds that it violates federal copyright
laws, has refused Napster's offers to negotiate a ``reasonable
license'' to the music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plaintiffs seek not fair compensation for what they own, but
to kill or control a technology that is not theirs,'' the brief
says.
</P>
<P>
   Napster's brief was in response to a 94-page brief filed Friday
by the Recording Industry Association of America. The RIAA argues
that U.S. District Court Judge Marilyn Hall Patel was correct when
she issued a preliminary injunction against Napster in July to
prevent users from downloading copyright-protected songs.
</P>
<P>
   The next step is scheduled for Oct. 2, when the appeals court
will hear lawyers for both sides argue the case in court.
</P>
<P>
   The record companies said the injunction was needed to stop the
copyright infringement of 12 million to 30 million songs per day.
Napster officials argued the injunction would unfairly shut down
their business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Napster's business strategy from the inception was to use
plaintiff's music to usurp and undermine the record industry, to
take over, or at least threaten, plaintiff's role in the promotion
and distribution of music,'' the RIAA brief said.
</P>
<P>
   The RIAA also rebuffed Napster's argument that instead of an
injunction, Patel could have ordered Napster to pay royalties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Napster never explains how the court could set rates or terms
of a royalty, how such a royalty would be calculated or supervised
or how it possibly could pay a royalty for the millions of songs
unlawfully copied,'' the RIAA brief said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Benny Evangelista at bevangelista(AT)sfchronicle.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
