<SLUG> BC-COMPUTING-EINSTEIN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 COMPUTING Q&AMP;A (COLUMN): FILTERS CAN CUT SPAM  &HT;     By DAVID EINSTEIN 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: I'm getting more junk e-mail than ever these days. Mostly it
falls into two categories: get-rich-quick schemes, like how to make
$10,000 a month working at home, and solicitations from sexually
oriented Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   I can delete unwanted messages easily enough, but now my
12-year-old daughter wants to send e-mail to her friends. I'd like
to give her a separate e-mail account, but my guess is that the
junk mailers would find her, too. Any suggestions for how I can
keep her safe from this seamy side of the Internet?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: You're right _ giving your daughter her own e-mail account
wouldn't protect her from junk mail (also known as spam). But you
can take steps to reduce how much of the stuff actually reaches her
_ or you, for that matter. Your e-mail software, whether it's
Outlook Express, Eudora, Netscape or some other program, has
filters that let you block incoming messages whose subject lines
and text fields contain words commonly associated with junk mail.
And you can block mail from spammers if you know their e-mail
address.
</P>
<P>
   You can also get additional software that does a fair job of
keeping junk mail out of your inbox. Some of the more popular
programs include SpamKiller ($29.95 from Novasoft at
www.spamkiller.com) and Spam Buster ($19.95 from Contact Plus at
www.contactplus.com). If you use America Online, there's Garbage
Man ($8 from WaveOp at www.waveop.com).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
PC Blackout
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: I bought my IBM Aptiva PC with Windows 98 a little more than a
year ago. Here's my problem: Whenever the computer isn't used for
15 minutes or so, the screen goes dark. I am supposed to hit any
key to reactivate it, but that doesn't work. The only way to get
any action is to turn the computer off and then turn it on again.
And that initiates the scan process because Windows doesn't like to
be shut down that way. Do you have any clues or suggestions for
solving this dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: Sounds like your PC is having a hard time with its energy-saving
feature (something that all newer PCs have). I'll bet the monitor
is set to turn off after 15 minutes, and it's just not able to
power back up. This is a pretty common problem, and there's an easy
fix. Right-click your mouse on an empty area of your Windows
desktop to bring up the Display Properties dialog box. Click
Settings, then select ``Never'' in the Turn off Monitor option.
</P>
<P>
   You can always activate a screen saver if you plan to leave the
PC on when you're not using it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Text Where You Want It
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: I'm doing a project in Microsoft Excel and would like to insert
some text in a worksheet. I know I can type words into the cells,
but that's awkward and imprecise. Is there an easier way to enter
text that I could position anywhere on the page?
</P>
<P>
   &LR; a  &LR;  A: Indeed there is. What you want to do is create a text
box, which lays on top of the spreadsheet's grid. To create a text
box, right-click on an unused area of the Excel menu bar, then
select Drawing. This will display the Drawing toolbar, probably
along the bottom of the screen. One of the icons on the toolbar
looks like a page of text with an ``A'' at the top. That's the Text
Box icon. Click it, then position your mouse pointer where you want
the text box to be and drag the mouse to create the box as big as
you like.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've created a text box, you can use the mouse to resize
or move it to a different spot on the page. You can also change the
type style, size and attributes of the text in the box as you would
for any document.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Computer Fatigue
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: Sometimes my computer slows down after I've been using it for a
long time _ say, several hours. What's causing this, and what can I
do about it?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: It could be that you have too many programs open at the same
time, or perhaps some temporary files have stayed in the PC's
memory even after programs have been closed. The result is a
reduction in the amount of ``system resources'' that are available
to the PC. Next time you experience a slowdown, do this:
Right-click the My Computer icon on your desktop, choose Properties
and tab over to Performance to see how much of your System
Resources are free. If it's less than 70 percent, try closing some
programs. If that doesn't work, I'd restart the computer to bring
the resources back up to snuff.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
David Einstein is a columnist for Forbes Digital Tool. E-mail him
at computers(AT)sfchronicle.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
