<HEADLINE>
GALAXY MUST FACE TOP DUO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The Tampa Bay Mutiny isn't much more than a
couple of players, but Colombia's Carlos Valderrama and the
Senegal's Mamadou Diallo might be all Tampa needs.
</P>
<P>
   Valderrama, with a Major League Soccer-record 26 assists, and
Diallo, with an MLS-best 26 goals, could go down as the best
one-two punch in MLS history. After a forgettable two losses in the
final week of the regular season, this is the Galaxy's punishment
for dropping to the fifth seed.
</P>
<P>
   After losing home-field advantage, the Galaxy opens the
first-round, best-of-three playoff series against the Mutiny
tonight at Raymond James Stadium. In two meetings this season, each
team has won at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Valderrama is like Magic Johnson,'' Galaxy defender Paul
Caligiuri said. ``He's confusing and hard to read. He can be
looking one way, then pass the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   And what of Diallo, the 6-foot-2, 190-pound bulldozer?
</P>
<P>
   ``Valderrama is the key to Diallo, but Diallo does his own
work,'' Galaxy goalkeeper Kevin Hartman said. ``He doesn't beat you
with his pace, he beats you by knocking you around and bumping you
off the ball with his intimidating frame.''
</P>
<P>
   You can imagine Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid's concern. Normally,
Danny Pena would mark Valderrama, but he's out after undergoing
season-ending knee surgery. With Pena down, Schmid figured he could
rely on Peter Vagenas to stop the Colombian wizard, but Vagenas is
with the Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's containment by committee. Midfielders Brian Kelly and
Simon Elliott will take turns on Valderrama.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be tough,'' said Schmid. ``You can't take your
eye off of (Carlos) for a second. We will have our hands full, but
if our concentration level is high, we should find a way to manage
him.''
</P>
<P>
   The responsibility of tracking Diallo falls on Caligiuri, 35,
who steps in for Olympian Danny Califf.
</P>
<P>
   When asked how he might contain Diallo, Caligiuri didn't
hesitate.
</P>
<P>
   ``With brains,'' he said. ``It's mind over matter, there isn't
anyone in this league I don't think I can't shut down. But to do
it, it's all in your head. You have to be prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   A veteran of the U.S. National team and former player in the
German Bundesliga, Caligiuri realizes he's going to have to rely on
his years of experience.
</P>
<P>
   To stop Diallo, it doesn't matter where you position your body.
He has enough size and quickness to physically punish defenders,
and he's mobile enough to turn and free himself for quick shots.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are many players who think Diallo is nothing more
than a cheap-shot artist. A month ago, Diallo crashed into New
York/New Jersey goalkeeper Mike Ammann, ending Ammann's season with
punctured lungs, broken ribs and a scratched face.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't the first time I've played against cheap and dirty
players,'' Caligiuri said. ``I've played internationally so many
times that you encounter this everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Caligiuri can't get involved in Diallo's tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to use my control and experience to not get sucked into
his style of play,'' Caligiuri said. ``He isn't going to change the
way he plays so I just have to stand in there and match what he
brings.''
</P>
</TEXT>
