<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINDOWSME-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 REVIEW: WINDOWS ME BRINGS MOVIES HOME  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It's difficult to resist the temptation to poke
fun at Microsoft's claim that Windows Millennium Edition, the new
version that goes on sale Thursday, is ``a simpler, more robust and
more useful operating system'' for home users.
</P>
<P>
   You could, for example, point to plenty of ``enhancements'' that
hardly seem worth the price of admission ($59.95 if you upgrade
from Windows 98 by Jan. 15, 2001, around $90 thereafter, or if you
are starting from an earlier version of Windows).
</P>
<P>
   Is networking any easier now that the former Network
Neighborhood has been rechristened My Network Places? Whose
experience was improved by changing the Start menu's Find command
to Search or by replacing the radio buttons in the Shutdown dialog
(the ones for Shutdown, Restart and other available options) with a
pop-up menu offering similar choices?
</P>
<P>
   More seriously, it probably won't be long, if you make ME yours,
before you are forced to acknowledge that ``more robust'' is
strictly a relative term _ it might be true, but it doesn't
actually mean stable and reliable.
</P>
<P>
   As I was typing this text into Microsoft Word, with no other
applications open and no third-party gizmos to blame for messing up
a fresh ME installation, I suddenly found myself staring at a
feature that hasn't changed at all _ the infamous ``blue screen of
death.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's hibernation. For years, makes of notebook PCs have
offered their own software that lets users power down temporarily
without closing all of their applications and documents.
Unfortunately, these Standby or Hibernate features were notoriously
unreliable _ they never worked consistently on any notebook I have
used, and many corporate IT managers (including The Chronicle's)
warn users not to try these features because they often result in
serious disk corruption.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Crashing While Sleeping
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft promised to address the problem in Windows ME, and
indeed it did, with a new option in that Shutdown dialog called
Hibernate. Now, instead of the frozen black screen I usually faced
when I tried to wake up from hibernation in Windows 95 and 98, ME
on my Compaq Armada produces a spectacular display of alternating,
pulsating pink, lime and black quarter-inch blocks, with a
smattering of asterisks and parentheses visible in the background
like so many twinkling stars and crescent moons.
</P>
<P>
   As with the previous versions of Windows, the only way out was
to force a restart. But after this happened three or four times, I
got to experience another way ME leaves its predecessors in the
dust: A dialog popped up noting that the last few times I'd tried
hibernation, it hadn't worked properly and asking if I'd like to
have the feature disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Windows 95 and 98 were never so polite.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The Inside Story
</P>
<P>
   Behind all these glitches and tweaks to Windows' facade is a
painful reality: Even though much of the 500-odd megabytes of code
that Windows ME installs on your hard drive is relatively new, it
all rests on an ancient foundation never designed to carry such a
load.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, ME is still built on DOS, the primitive operating
system that put Microsoft on the map 20 years ago, when IBM (to its
enduring regret) adopted it for the original PC. DOS is hidden a
little deeper than in previous Windows releases _ you can no longer
boot your machine into it, except from your emergency startup
floppy, and the MS-DOS Prompt command has been moved off the main
Programs menu to the Accessories submenu _ but most of it is still
there.
</P>
<P>
   Except, that is, the code that lets DOS programs work in a state
known as ``real mode.'' Microsoft has finally removed it, which
means that starting up your PC is now marginally faster (perhaps 10
percent) but also that old games and applications that require real
mode will no longer work. In theory, however, most DOS software can
still be used. But when I tried, just for old times' sake, to peek
at the C: prompt, Windows informed me, in its inimitable way, that
the program had ``performed an illegal operation and (would) be
terminated.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Still Using DOS
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't supposed to be this way. A couple of years ago, when
it announced Windows 98, Microsoft said that would be the last
DOS-based version; what has now become ME was to be based on the
relatively modern and robust core code of Windows NT/2000.
</P>
<P>
   But the company soon dropped that plan, apparently because there
were too many popular Windows games, plus driver software for many
peripherals, that wouldn't work on NT. For home users, the
transition is now scheduled for the next release of Windows, a
combined business-and-consumer version code-named Whistler, that is
expected late next year.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Windows ME is really just a stopgap product,
designed to give Bill Gates et al. something fresh to peddle while
their programmers work on Whistler.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Goodies Galore
</P>
<P>
   Subject to all those limitations, Windows ME does include some
potentially worthwhile new features and enhancements.
</P>
<P>
   -- Behavior modification. The most valuable of these,
considering the fundamental instability of Windows, are several
Microsoft classified under the rubric ``PC Health.''
</P>
<P>
   A feature called System File Protection, borrowed from Windows
2000, prevents newly installed programs from overwriting critical
system files with outdated or nonstandard versions, thus reducing
the odds of crashes or other odd behavior from other programs.
</P>
<P>
   A new Help and Support Center provides a single, consistent
point of access to tips, tours and tutorials from both Microsoft
and, in the future, third-party developers. A link in this center
takes you to a new feature called System Restore, which lets you
roll your system back to a previous state in case corruption or
newly installed software cause problems.
</P>
<P>
   By default, it takes a ``snapshot'' of your setup after every 10
hours of computing, but you can make a new one at any time _ a good
idea before you install a new program or make any other major
changes to your system.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, I failed to do that before I let someone modify
my laptop's networking configuration last week. And now, for
reasons I don't understand, the only snapshot available is one
taken after those changes.
</P>
<P>
   In short, it sounds nifty, and I'm sure it will be helpful to
some people some of the time, but so far, the one time I could
actually have used its help, it failed me.
</P>
<P>
   A popular utility called GoBack, now published by Adaptec,
offers a similar function. If you're using it, though, be sure you
have the latest version before installing Windows ME _ older ones
are not compatible.
</P>
<P>
   -- Internet integration. Windows ME comes with Internet Explorer
5.5, a recent version that differs from 5.0 mainly by the addition
of a Print Preview feature, which can help you avoid wasting lots
of time, toner and paper if you print often from the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, as soon as you get your Windows ME online _ a
process that went remarkably smoothly with all four PCs where I
installed the new system _ another new feature will let you know
that your version of IE is no longer the latest and greatest.
</P>
<P>
   The feature, called AutoUpdate, checks the Microsoft Web site
for updates in the background while you're online but your modem or
network connection isn't active. You can customize its behavior (or
shut it off altogether), but at its default settings, it
automatically downloads any relevant updates it finds, then asks
you if you want them installed.
</P>
<P>
   (The new software that AutoUpdate recommends is a beta test
version of IE with new cookie-management features.)
</P>
<P>
   Under the hood, ME replaces the TCP/IP ``stack'' _ the Internet
plumbing software _ from Windows 98 with a newer version borrowed
from Windows 2000. It's supposed to be more stable and secure; all
I can say is that I got all four of the PCs on which I installed ME
online without incident. The only downside: Most of the popular
personal firewall software packages, including Network ICE's
BlackICE Defender and Symantec's Norton Internet Security (but not
Zone Labs' ZoneAlarm), require updates.
</P>
<P>
   Another new feature in ME is a ``wizard'' that is supposed to
make it much easier to create a home network, particularly to
enable multiple machines to share Internet access. I didn't test it
_ my home network has worked fine for years, and I wasn't about to
jeopardize its stability even for the sake of science _ but by all
accounts it works well.
</P>
<P>
   The influence of the Net is apparent in lots of smaller ways,
too. The new Help center and even ordinary desktop windows, for
example, now have forward and back buttons, History and Favorites
menus and other browser-style features. And from the Help center
lists you can go with a single click to online support sites, just
as easily, if not quite as quickly, as you can jump to help files
on your own hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   Last but, for gamers, not least, Windows ME includes five new
games _ versions of backgammon, checkers, hearts, Reversi and
spades _ designed to be played against online opponents.
</P>
<P>
   -- Digital media. Included with ME is the latest version of the
Windows Media Player, a slick and versatile, though somewhat
unstable, program for playing and managing digital audio and video
in several formats, including MP3 (but not RealAudio or RealVideo).
Like most competing products, it lets you choose among a variety of
``skins,'' or onscreen interfaces.
</P>
<P>
   The Media Player doesn't require Windows ME, and it is freely
downloadable from Microsoft's Web site (www.microsoft.com/windows
/windowsmedia/en/software /Playerv7.asp). But that's not the case
with several other digital-media programs in the new Windows.
</P>
<P>
   One is Windows Movie Maker, which lets you edit digital videos,
then share them via e-mail or posting to the Web. Like iMovie, the
video application Apple now ships with nearly all Macs, the program
automatically divides video sequences into separate scenes, which
makes it relatively easy to get rid of those you don't want and
reorganize what's left.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Apple program, Movie Maker works with clips imported
from conventional analog video cameras as well as the newer (and
pricier) digital kind. But because very few PCs ship with the
hardware needed to import video _ either a FireWire/i.Link/1394
port for digital camcorders, or a PCI card or external device for
digitizing and capturing analog video _ you will probably still
need to spend additional time and money before you can start
editing.
</P>
<P>
   And because most if not all such hardware add-ons come with
their own editing software, even aspiring Spielbergs may never need
Movie Maker.
</P>
<P>
   Another new media feature in ME, carrying the catchy name
Windows Image Acquisition, simplifies the process of downloading
still images from a digital camera or scanner via Universal Serial
Bus or a conventional serial connection _ provided your images are
coming from a new, WIA-compatible device.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all digital cameras and scanners already come with
download software for Windows, but some of these programs are
clunky, whereas WIA seems to work smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; The Bottom Line
</P>
<P>
   Windows ME requires, at a minimum, a 150-megahertz processor and
32 megabytes of memory, but I wouldn't even consider it unless you
already have or are willing to get at least 64 megabytes of memory.
Microsoft says a typical installation requires about 295 megabytes
of available space on your hard drive, including about 100
megabytes for backup files created during installation. When I
installed it on a freshly formatted drive, however, it filled a
whopping 513 megabytes.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you meet the technical requirements, there's some risk
of hassles if you install ME on an older PC. When I tried it on a
5-year-old Dell Pentium Pro system, Windows ME couldn't find
software for either my NumberNine video card or my Kingston network
adapter. (The latter worked fine anyway; the former, though, worked
only in 640-by-480-pixel mode.)
</P>
<P>
   But suppose you have a relatively up-to-date PC with plenty of
disk space and memory, and you aren't bothered by any of the
relatively few incompatibilities that have turned up thus far _
should you upgrade to Windows ME?
</P>
<P>
   The question to ask, I think, is whether any of the system's new
features sounds like something you really don't want to be without.
If so, you probably don't have a lot to lose except the hour or so
the installation will take; at $60 _ no more than many popular
utilities _ it's difficult to argue that ME isn't worth the price
if you actually expect to use new features like Movie Maker or the
online games, or if you now frequently run into issues, like DLL
conflicts, that the new PC health features might prevent or
resolve.
</P>
<P>
   For most people, though, my advice is to wait, either until you
get a new machine with ME already installed or until Whistler
arrives. At its roots, despite some welcome improvements, ME is
clearly last-millennium software. Whatever you think about
Microsoft, it's a shame that despite all its riches and talent, it
couldn't deliver a Millennium Edition that deserves to be called
21st century technology.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Henry Norr at hnorr(AT)sfchronicle.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
