<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3748 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-HILLARY-DEBATE0914-CO     09-13 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-DEBATE0914-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton and Lazio spar in televised debate
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. &Cx1f;  _ A Senate campaign that began as a polite
listening tour 14 months ago turned into an old-fashioned New
York-style political brawl Wednesday night as first lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton and Republican congressman Rick Lazio held their
first debate.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates started out trading accusations of chutzpah and
ended up pointedly not shaking hands after practically
arm-wrestling at midstage over the subject of soft money. In
between, things occasionally verged on mudslinging as Mrs. Clinton
kept trying to link Lazio to the worst aspects of Newt Gingrich's
congressional leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, when moderator Tim Russert brought up the subject of
Monica Lewinsky, Lazio was only too happy to help tie Mrs. Clinton
to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that, frankly, what's so troubling here with respect
to what my opponent just said is somehow that it only matters what
you say when you get caught,'' Lazio said after Mrs. Clinton had
been forced to watch a long-ago ``Today'' show clip in which she
blamed her husband's Lewinsky problems on a ``vast right wing
conspiracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Lazio: ``Blaming others every time you have responsibility,
unfortunately that's become a pattern, I think, for my opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Lazio was only giving as good as he'd already gotten.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mentioned trust,'' Mrs. Clinton told Russert just before
turning to look in Lazio's direction. ``I didn't cast the votes
that Newt Gingrich asked me to cast.''
</P>
<P>
   There was even a bit of telecast showmanship on Lazio's part for
the millions of viewers watching the live broadcast on all the NBC
affiliates in New York. Near the end of the debate, Lazio walked
over to Mrs. Clinton's podium and tried to induce her to sign a
copy of what he called his ``New York Freedom from Soft Money
Agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I admire that,'' Mrs. Clinton laughingly told him, just after
saying she would sign the agreement if and when he produced signed
letters from outside groups she said were creating so-called ``soft
money'' ads on Lazio's behalf. ``That was a wonderful
performance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not asking you to admire it,'' Lazio cut in, while Russert
essentially told them to break it up because the debate was nearly
over. ``I'm asking you to sign it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only didn't they sign it. They didn't even shake hands
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The somewhat tense standoff was symbolic of a race in which the
stakes are high and every vote literally counts. Two polls released
Tuesday showed Mrs. Clinton barely leading by under 5 points. The
outcome likely will be decided by a small bloc of undecided voters,
some of whom say that Mrs. Clinton hasn't made a case for herself
as a representative New Yorker and that Lazio is running on little
else but his local roots.
</P>
<P>
   Going into the debate, many New Yorkers had complained that they
didn't yet know enough about the two candidates. That may explain
why four of five likely voters polled this past week said they
intended to watch.
</P>
<P>
   While it's too soon to say if the hourlong encounter made up
many voters' minds in this neck-and-neck race, history undeniably
was made the moment the debate began inside Buffalo's public
television station WNED.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton is the first presidential spouse to run for public
office while still living in the White House. And for all her
attempts to sound like an average, albeit incredibly well-informed
New Yorker _ at one point getting specific about overcrowding in
one Queens school and wiring problems in another in Buffalo _ it
was impossible to ignore the Secret Service agents or international
press corps of approximately 150 her presence attracted.
</P>
<P>
   Or the range of public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hillary's only here so she can run for president someday!'' a
Lazio supporter yelled outside the studio where some 150 boosters
of both candidates mingled behind yellow police crime tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you're only here so you can get on TV!'' a Clinton
supporter yelled back while a half-dozen TV news crews taped the
scene.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio only entered the race in late May, when Mrs. Clinton's
colorful Republican opponent, New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani,
dropped out due to prostate cancer and marital difficulties. Since
then, however, the relatively unknown four-term congressman from
suburban Long Island has raised nearly as much money as Mrs.
Clinton _ $19.2 million to her $21.9 million. Meanwhile, his public
profile has soared as a result of campaign ads featuring the likes
of Sen. John McCain and his repeated comparisons of his own
elective experience and lifelong New York residency to that of Mrs.
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Or as Lazio said in his first remarks during Wednesday's debate,
commenting on Mrs. Clinton's failed 1994 efforts at health care
reform:
</P>
<P>
   ``A New Yorker never would have made that proposal!''
</P>
<P>
   She may be a first lady, but the next time she got a chance to
talk, Mrs. Clinton fired right back:
</P>
<P>
   ``Listening to the congressman's response,'' she told Russert
with a smile, ``reminds me of a word I've heard a lot this year.
Chutzpah.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
