A3749 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-MLK0914-COX     09-13 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MLK0914-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. firm wins competition to design MLK monument on the Mall
 &HT;    By Melanie Eversley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A San Francisco architectural firm won a worldwide
competition Wednesday to design a memorial to the Rev. Martin
Luther King Jr. on the National Mall with a plan for an open-air
stone structure highlighted by curtains of water and the words of
the late civil rights leader.
</P>
<P>
   Coordinators for the Martin Luther King Jr. National Memorial
Project presented the Roma Design Group with a check for $20,000
and the opportunity to design the edifice. The announcement was
made during a one-hour ceremony at a Washington hotel Wednesday
night. The firm beat out 900 other entrants for the chance to
design the first memorial to an individual African American on the
National Mall.
</P>
<P>
   Boris Dramov, a principal partner of Roma, said the structure is
intended to serve as an uplifting tribute to a man who hoped beyond
hope, not a dismal reminder of the pain of the civil rights
struggles. King, who grew up in Atlanta, was gunned down in April
1968 while standing on the porch of a Memphis motel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to create a place . . . for all people to come, to
be exposed to the civil rights movement, and to give a proper
honoring for the man, the movement and the message,'' Dramov said.
</P>
<P>
   Coretta Scott King, who attended the ceremony with her daughter,
Bernice, said her late husband knew a perfect world is elusive, but
people must continue to strive for that perfect world. The striving
is what makes for social change, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In that vein, she added she felt the memorial design was one
that acknowledged the pain of segregation and racism, but also
recognized her late husband's vision of hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that Martin was concerned that freedom never stopped.
He realized the dream is always becoming,'' she said. ``I think
this will continue to motivate people. I think it will continue to
inspire generations.''
</P>
<P>
   Three commissions in Washington must approve the structure
design before it can become reality, but coordinators said they
hope to break ground by November 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial will be an open-air design, much like the one
dedicated to Franklin Delano Roosevelt, also overlooking the Tidal
Basin. It will feature walls of water inscribed with the words of
King, as well as a towering stone structure at the entrance, in
which King's profile will be sculpted as well as the words from his
``promissory note'' passage, in which he declares America owes
black Americans freedom and fairness. King's profile will face the
memorial to Thomas Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial, which coordinators anticipate will draw admirers
from around the world, had a very simple genesis. Five members of
the Alpha Phi Alpha fraternity were sitting around a kitchen table
in 1983 when they came up with the idea. In 1998, Congress passed
legislation authorizing creation of the foundation, which is headed
by Alpha Phi Alpha President Adrian Wallace. Wallace and other
members of the 94-year-old fraternity, based in Baltimore, hosted
the event.
</P>
<P>
   Clothing designer Tommy Hilfiger, who has vowed to donate at
least $5 million toward the project, also was on hand. He said he
learned of the project just as he had created a new foundation he
hoped he could devote to honoring America's diversity.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Andrew Young, a King aide who later served as Atlanta
mayor and ambassador to the United Nations, also attended
Wednesday's ceremony, leading the event with a prayer of thanks for
King and his spirit of hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are here to raise a stone of hope, a beacon of
understanding, a ray of warmth and nonviolence that might give
additional life to those yet unborn,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   After the event, Young said he was touched by the design.
</P>
<P>
   ``This seems to be a really powerful statement of what the
movement was all about because it represents the images of hope,''
Young said. ``I think of this not as a statue to a black American,
but as a tribute to non-violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
