<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3751 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBC-DREW-BREES-TEX     09-13 1223
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-DREW-BREES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPLICATED OFFENSE NO PROBLEM FOR PURDUE'S DREW BREES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST LAFAYETTE, Ind. _ Here's why Purdue quarterback Drew Brees
is one of the leading candidates for the Heisman Trophy: 69
touchdown passes, 8,857 passing yards, .617 completion percentage.
</P>
<P>
   Here is one way how: Fox Right Gun Red 74 X Z Under
</P>
<P>
   That is one of a hundred or so different calls Brees might make
in the huddle Saturday during the 13th-ranked Boilermakers' game at
No. 21 Notre Dame. And that one mouthful of a play call does not
take into account the possibility he calls an audible at the line
of scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good decision-maker,'' Purdue coach Joe Tiller said.
``Here, so many things happen after you're at the line of scrimmage
as opposed to what's in the huddle.''
</P>
<P>
   Brees, a senior, is on pace to become the most prolific passer
in Big Ten Conference history. The former Austin Westlake High
School star is the major reason that Tiller's pass-intensive
offense _ one that critics said would not work in the
brass-knuckled Big Ten _ is now accepted as dangerous and
legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   Brees faces the same game-day challenges and difficulties as
other high-profile quarterbacks, though he works in a more
complicated scheme than most. To an outside observer, the
information he processes in the 25 seconds from calling the play to
executing it appears comparable to assembling a 1,000-piece jigsaw
puzzle in half a minute.
</P>
<P>
   Here is what it is like to be Drew Brees: \Nsubheds:Intense
study In preparing for a game like Notre Dame, Brees often watches
two to three hours of film per day. That is in addition to the two
hours of daily practice. And then there is the little challenge of
learning the game plan, backward, forward, inside out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a restricted number of plays that are run out of an
unrestricted number of formations,'' Tiller said. ``How many plays
do we have? I don't know. We have an infinite number.''
</P>
<P>
   But the challenge is not just for Brees to know which plays to
call in the huddle or which audibles will work. The other 10
offensive players need to be able to quickly adjust to whatever
change Brees orders. Each game plan provides two specific options
for Brees to call audibles out of the plays that Purdue has
packaged for that opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are quarterbacks who can't keep it in the right order
sequentially,'' Tiller said. ``They know they want to audible, but
they take you to the wrong audible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other quarterbacks are robotic. They think the blitz is
coming, they get ready to make a `hot' throw to beat the blitz and
then the blitz isn't there and it's `Oh, ... Drew goes from A to E
on the checklist; other quarterbacks have trouble going from A to
B.''
</P>
<P>
   And all the plays and all the audibles go against a defense
trying to disguise coverage and confuse the quarterback. Like a
veteran comedian who can pull the right joke out of his mental card
file, Brees can call the right play in a moment's notice. It is as
if his quarterback's mind is equipped with a Pentium III processor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to fool him every now and then \Rbut\S if you tip
your hand, he'll be 100 percent on his decisions,'' Tiller said.
``He's going to get the ball to the right guy, then it's a matter
of us catching it.'' \Nsubheds:Chess game For Brees, the perfect
scenario for each play gives him 15 seconds at the line of
scrimmage to assess the defense, see if the play called will work
and if he should audible. And never mind the television cameras,
the 70,000 screaming fans, the late-game pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I do is look at the play clock,'' said Brees,
who must decide which of Tiller's 22 offensive commandments he must
check off on any given play. ``If there's less than 10 seconds,
I'll yell, `Alert, alert.' That tells our guys there's not much
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Depending on where he lines up _ under center or in the shotgun
_ Brees' next challenge is scouting the defense. His eyes sweep the
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at the safeties, glance to the cornerbacks, come along
to the linebackers, the defensive line,'' he said. ``It's kind of a
circle I make with my eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   This is where football turns into a rapid-fire chess game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every coverage has either one safety or two,'' Brees said, his
hands moving to add to his narrative. ``If there's one safety
playing back and the corners are playing soft, I know it's one of
two coverages _ `man free' or `cover three.' \RThe first is
man-to-man, the second is a three-deep zone played by the safety
and the two cornerbacks.\S
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of teams play a soft man-to-man with the safety back. It
looks like zone, but it's man-to-man.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look at the linebackers, if they're lined up outside
and aren't looking at me, I know it's a zone. If they're head up on
the receivers, I know it's man. I look at the inside linebackers. I
can usually tell by how they're lined up or their body lean whether
or not they're blitzing.''
</P>
<P>
   Brees paused and smiled. ``Sure, sure, Drew, this is all so easy
to understand; right there with ya, pal.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense might drop eight men in coverage _ or blitz any of
eight players. Beyond the disguised coverages _ is it man or is it
zone? _ zone blitzes add to the confusion. That is when a
linebacker blitzes, but a defensive lineman drops into coverage.
Very tricky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't worry if they're trying to fool me,'' the 6-foot-1,
220-pound Brees said. ``If I can see a safety, I know there's no
way they can bring more guys than we can block, unless they want to
leave one of our receivers open. If a guy comes free untouched,
I've got about 1.5 seconds to get a pass off. That's enough for
me.'' \Nsubheds:No sweat OK, Mr. Brees, please explain that play
call. What the heck is ``Fox Right Gun Red 74 X Z Under''?
</P>
<P>
   Fox: Number of receivers (five)
</P>
<P>
   Right: Which side of the formation the tight end starts.
</P>
<P>
   Gun: Shotgun formation
</P>
<P>
   Red: Type of pass protection.
</P>
<P>
   74 X Z Under: The type of the routes. The receivers (labeled A,
F, X, Y and Z in Purdue lingo) all know what routes they are
supposed to run. In this case, the outside receivers run hitch
patterns, the inside receivers run fade patterns, the tight end
runs up the hash mark (down the middle of the field).
</P>
<P>
   ``All the receivers have to know what the other receivers are
doing on each play,'' Brees said. ``They've all got
responsibilities on each play, even if they're not the main
receiver. We've all got to be doing our jobs right for it to
work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fox Right Gun Red 74 X Z Under'' is just one play. In the roar
of competition, with blitzes flying and receivers digging and
cornerbacks bumping, making all the pieces fit into a play that
gains yardage is ... Oh, never mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``All defenses have a man in all areas of the field,'' said
Brees, who has a 3.41 grade point average in Purdue's School of
Management. ``How can an offense move against that? That's where
the quarterback comes in. You have two receivers go where just one
defender is. The quarterback uses his eyes to move the defender,
the receiver reads where the opening is and you throw it to where
the defender isn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all makes sense and it becomes simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Easy for him to say.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
