<HEADLINE>
YEAR OF CHANGE APPARENT IN MLS PLAYOFFS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BLANE BACHELOR 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Changes have been the story for the Major League Soccer's fifth
season. The season began with a new commissioner, Don Garber in his
first full year. Taking a look at the playoff picture shows plenty
else that's new this year: from coaching changes, to first-year
impact players, to teams that have made impressive turnarounds.
</P>
<P>
   The most glaring absence in this year's playoffs is D.C. United.
The three-time MLS champion inexplicably fizzled this season,
despite returning the bulk of a team that had never missed the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Contrasting United's fall from the top is the rise of two
cellar-d wellers _ Kansas City and the MetroStars. Under former
Galaxy coach Octavio Zambrano, New York/New Jersey captured the
franchise's first division title. Bob Gansler orchestrated another
reversal of fortunes in his first full season with Kansas City,
guiding the Wizards to the Western Division title after Kansas City
had missed the playoffs the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   MLS also moved from two to three divisions and, under the new
format, playoff races came down to the final game. Colorado
clinched a berth with an overtime goal, and the Burn jumped from
eighth to sixth place with a last-gasp victory against San Jose,
shuffling the order in the bottom of the standings.
</P>
<P>
   The playoffs should be just as exciting. Chicago is the only
other team besides United to have won a title, but that could
change with D.C. out of the picture.
\Nsubheds:The lowdown A look at the best in this year's playoffs:
</P>
<P>
   Goalie: Tony Meola, Kansas City Wizards.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Meola battled injuries, but this year he has a
league-record 16 shutouts and registered a league-best 0.89
goals-against average.
</P>
<P>
   Midfielder: Carlos Valderrama, Tampa Bay Mutiny.
</P>
<P>
   The orange-haired Colombian may be 39, but he set a league
record with 26 assists and has veteran experience to draw on for
the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Defender: Mike Petke, MetroStars.
</P>
<P>
   The blond-haired Petke is one of the most fiery players in the
league, and his ability to frustrate strikers could be a major
sticking point for opponents in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Forward: Mamadou Diallo, Tampa Bay Mutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Diallo was one goal short of tying the league record of 27 goals
in a season, and paired with Valderrama, he should continue to be a
major threat.
</P>
<P>
   Coach: Bob Gansler, Kansas City Wizards.
</P>
<P>
   In his first full season with the Wizards, Gansler has utilized
the experience of his veterans and the contributions of his
rookies.
</P>
<P>
   Series: Chicago vs. Dallas in the second round. These teams have
already met 17 times in only three seasons, and last year's
first-round series _ which the Burn won in three _ set the stage
for a heated rematch.
</P>
<P>
   Cup finalists: Chicago vs. Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The Wizards will the ride momentum of their best season to the
Cup final, and Chicago will make up for some absences in its
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   2000 Champion: Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The experience of winning the Cup in 1998 as an expansion team
should propel the Fire back to the top. \Nsubheds:First-round
matchups 1. Kansas City Wizards vs. 8. Colorado Rapids
</P>
<P>
   Records: Wizards 16-7-9, Rapids 13-15-4 Game 1: Saturday, 7:30
p.m., Arrowhead Stadium Game 2: Wednesday, 8:30 p.m.; Mile High
Stadium Game 3: Sunday, Sept. 24, 7:30 p.m., Arrowhead Stadium; .
The superstar: Wizards GK Tony Meola. His resurgence as one of the
league's best keepers is one of the key reasons for Kansas City's
leap to the top. The scoop: The Rapids managed to cap an
injury-plagued season with a miraculous berth into the playoffs,
thanks to an overtime goal from Paul Bravo in their season-ending
victory against the Galaxy. But Colorado's luck could run out
against a powerful Kansas City squad, which will be looking to
avenge the '97 playoffs when it was bumped by the Rapids. The pick:
Kansas City in two games. 2. Chicago Fire vs. 7. New England
Revolution
</P>
<P>
   Records: Fire 17-9-6, Revolution 13-13-6 Game 1: Friday, 7:30
p.m., at Soldier Field; Game 2: Tuesday, 7:30 p.m.; at Foxboro
Stadium; Game 3: Friday, Sept. 22, 7:30 p.m. at Soldier Field; The
superstar: Chicago midfielder Hristo Stoitchov. The fiery Bulgarian
standout is brash, athletic and outspoken. He brings a flair to the
game that is worth more than the price of admission. The scoop: The
Revolution is the only MLS team not to suffer a loss to Chicago
this season, but Chicago is on a late-season tear, averaging three
goals a game during its four-game winning streak. Nevertheless,
Chicago has several key players out of the lineup (midfielder Chris
Armas and defender Lubos Kubik with injuries; forward Josh Wolff
and midfielder Evan Whitfield, with the U.S. Olympic team), which
could offer the Revs some hope to advance. The pick: Chicago in two
games.
</P>
<P>
   3. New York/New Jersey MetroStars vs. 6. Dallas Burn
</P>
<P>
   Records: MetroStars 17-12-3, Burn 14-14-4 Game 1: Friday at
Giants Stadium, 7 p.m.; KSTR/Ch. 49 Game 2: Wednesday at the Cotton
Bowl; 7:30 p.m.; KSTR/Ch. 49 Game 3: Saturday, Sept. 23 at Giants
Stadium, 2:30 p.m.; ESPN2. The superstar: MetroStars M/F Clint
Mathis. MVP candidate has six goals in two games against the Burn
this season. The scoop: A rivalry that is getting fiercer by the
game, this first postseason meeting won't lack in physical play _
or goals. The Burn will be looking to exact some revenge after
losing the last meeting, 6-4, at the Cotton Bowl. A hotly contested
penalty kick from Mathis proved to be the game-winner. The
MetroStars' biggest weakness is in the net, where they will have to
use third-string goalkeeper Paul Grafer. Usual starter, Mike Ammann
is out with season-ending rib and lung injuries after a tackle from
Mamadou Diallo, and backup Tim Howard is playing in Australia with
the U.S. Olympic team. The pick: The Burn in three games.
</P>
<P>
   4. Tampa Bay Mutiny vs. 5. Los Angeles Galaxy
</P>
<P>
   Records: Mutiny 16-12-4, Galaxy 14-10-8. Game 1: Tonight,
Raymond James Stadium at 7 p.m.; ESPN2. Game 2: Wednesday at the
Rose Bowl, 9:30 p.m.; TBA Game 3: Saturday, Sept. 23, at Raymond
James Stadium, TBD; The superstar: Tampa Bay striker Mamadou
Diallo. The Senegalese striker, nicknamed ``Big Mama,'' might have
a controversial physical style, but he always manages to find the
back of the net. The scoop: Another budding rivalry, this closely
matched series has the promise of a thriller. The Galaxy has held
Diallo to only one goal in two meetings this season. Home-field
advantage could be the difference for the Mutiny, but Tampa Bay has
a history of stalling in the postseason, losing its past six
playoff games. The pick: Tampa Bay in three games. _if necessary
nn
</P>
