<SLUG> BC-PROSECUTORS-UNION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON COUNTY ASSISTANT PROSECUTORS VOTE TO JOIN FIREFIGHTERS
UNION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE LAMBE  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Hoping to address longstanding concerns about
low pay, Jackson County assistant prosecutors announced Wednesday
they had voted to join one of the most politically powerful unions
in the metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   More than 90 percent of about 70 assistant prosecutors have
voted to join Local 42 of the International Association of Fire
Fighters, assistant prosecutor Bryan Krantz said.
</P>
<P>
   He said assistant prosecutors chose the union, which represents
Kansas City firefighters, over seven others, because ``the only
card we have is political pressure, and we felt they had the most
clout.''
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Jackson County prosecutors are the lowest-paid in the
metropolitan area and deal with the most crime, he said.
</P>
<P>
   With starting pay of $32,000, several assistant prosecutors take
second jobs to make ends meet and pay off student loans.
</P>
<P>
   Aimee Riederer, niece of a former three-term Jackson County
prosecutor, serves the Jackson County Drug Court in the day and
serves food at a Country Club Plaza restaurant in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   She has $56,000 in student loans, Riederer said, and needs the
waitress work several nights a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can make more in five hours there than I do in a day at the
courthouse,'' she said. Riederer, 30, voted for the union.
</P>
<P>
   More prosecutors are joining unions nationally, but lawyers say
they know of no other prosecutors in Missouri or Kansas who have
done so. They are the first such white-collar professional group to
join Local 42.
</P>
<P>
   Louie A. Wright, president of Local 42, said unions across the
United States were signing more professional workers.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would like to start contract negotiations with
Jackson County within weeks, before a budget is approved in
December.
</P>
<P>
   The firefighters union soon will ask the Jackson County
Legislature and the county executive to accept it as the assistant
prosecutors' bargaining agent, Wright said. The county could
approve the request quickly or ask for another vote by assistant
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative Chairman Victor Callahan said he would not oppose
the union. County Executive Katheryn Shields could not be reached
for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson County Prosecutor Bob Beaird said his staff should be
paid more, adding he did not try to influence them on the union
decision.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, Krantz said, Jackson County assistant
prosecutors ``would like to not be the worst-paid attorneys in
town.'' They will seek more money in contract negotiations, Krantz
said.
</P>
<P>
   Local 42 has won good raises from the Kansas City Council but
sometimes with hard-nosed tactics. Firefighters struck twice in the
1970s and threatened to strike in 1998 pay negotiations, even
though it is illegal for public workers to strike in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant prosecutors will never strike, Krantz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take an oath to uphold the law,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant prosecutors get few raises, Krantz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only do we start low,'' he said, ``we stay low.''
</P>
<P>
   Assistant prosecutor Carol Quinn is an 11-year veteran who makes
$40,000 a year. She works up to 16 evening hours a week, she said,
making calls to verify insurance information. She voted union.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figure I can't do any worse,'' she said. ``When we go to the
well to ask for more money, they just pat us on the head and send
us away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
