<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Sept. 13, 2000 -- CHINESE-ANTIQUES-2 -- Since
the late 19th century, when Westerners began trading with China,
there have been collectors who sought Chinese antiques. But in the
past 10 years, a group of younger, less wealthy collectors has
emerged. When Tish Durkin went to Beijing in 1995 to cover the
World Conference on Women, she went to the Chao Wei antiques market
in search of a souvenir. Instead, she bought a chicken
coop-vegetable bin made of camphor wood; it stood six feet all, and
was 39 inches wide. Durkin next to her find. (Fred R. Conrad/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Sept. 13, 2000 -- CHINESE-ANTIQUES-1 -- Since
the late 19th century, when Westerners began trading with China,
there have been collectors who sought Chinese antiques. But in the
past 10 years, a group of younger, less wealthy collectors has
emerged. Mary Peng, who sells $50 Chinese wedding baskets and
$3,500 Chinese antiques out of her Manhattan loft, says ``The
younger collectors are seasoned travelers in their 20's, coming
back to the United States, who want to purchase the furniture they
had seen overseas, and who know that antiques don't have to be
$10,000 to start.'' (Fred R. Conrad/The New York Times)
</P>
