<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Fla., Wash.)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS
</P>
<P>
   BUSH EXPANDS MESSAGE TEAM
</P>
<P>
   With the presidential race now a dead heat, Gov. George W. Bush
has added a Washington-based Republican consultant, Ed Gillespie,
to his communications team to help sharpen his campaign message.
Gillespie, 39, has been senior adviser to the House majority
leader, Rep. Dick Armey of Texas, director of policy and
communications for the House Republican Conference and a senior
staff member at the Republican National Committee. He was one of
six Washington advisers named by the Bush campaign earlier this
year when national Republicans complained that the Austin-based
Bush campaign was too insular. His hiring for the new job, which
Bush advisers called a natural extension of his earlier role, comes
at a time when Vice President Al Gore has caught Bush in the polls
and some Republicans have been urging Bush to sharpen his campaign
themes.
</P>
<P>
   A REUNION FOR CHENEY AND FORD
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney paid a call Wednesday on his old boss, former
President Gerald Ford, in a campaign swing through Grand Rapids,
Mich. Twenty-five years ago, Cheney, then 34, became Ford's White
House chief of staff. Warmly greeted by Ford and his wife, Betty,
outside the Gerald R. Ford Museum, on the banks of the Grand River,
Cheney said: ``It's fun just to come back and spend some time with
the president, get words of wisdom from somebody who has been where
I'm trying to go, as vice president.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford called his old protege ``a very dear friend and a person
who did a superb job for me when I was in the White House.'' And
what advice and wisdom did Cheney get during the 10-minute meeting?
Cheney proved that he could still keep his old boss' confidences.
``I've always kept my conversations with him private over the
years,'' he said, adding that Ford was ``looking much better''
since his minor stroke last month at the Republican National
Convention in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN FINANCE ATTACK ON SOFT MONEY
</P>
<P>
   Three advocates of stronger campaign finance laws asked a
federal court in Washington Wednesday to rule that coordination of
advertising and other expenditures between a presidential candidate
and a political party represents an illegal campaign contribution.
The trio _ Fred Wertheimer, president of Democracy 21; Scott
Harshbarger, president of Common Cause, and Archibald Cox, the
former Watergate special prosecutor _ argued that the use of
so-called soft money by the Democratic National Committee and
Republican National Committee on behalf of Vice President Al Gore
and Gov. George W. Bush constitutes a ``massive'' violation of
current election law.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Gore have accepted $68 million in public funds for the
general election and are not supposed to receive any other direct
contributions. But using soft funds raised in large amounts from
corporations, unions and rich contributors, the two parties are
spending tens of millions on television ads that, in effect,
promote their candidates and attack their opponents. Under federal
law, soft money ads are not supposed to advocate the election or
defeat of a specific candidate, and the ad campaigns are not
supposed to be coordinated with candidates.
</P>
<P>
   THE STATES
</P>
<P>
   CLOSE RACES IN FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   Two new polls indicate that Vice President Al Gore's support
among voters in Florida has surged and that he now is neck and neck
with Gov. George W. Bush, who once appeared to have a lock on the
state's 25 electoral votes. The first poll, conducted by the
Mason-Dixon survey group for several Florida media outlets, found
Bush only two percentage points ahead; the second poll, conducted
by the University of Connecticut's polling organization, showed the
contest dead even.
</P>
<P>
   Florida's governor, Jeb Bush, is Bush's brother, and Republicans
have been gaining strength in the state in recent years. The
university poll also found that in the race for the Florida's open
Senate seat, Rep. Bill McCollum, a Republican, and state Insurance
Commissioner Bill Nelson, a Democrat, were in a dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   THE PRIMARIES
</P>
<P>
   FINAL DEBATE IN WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates for the Democratic nomination for senator
from Washington clashed Wednesday at their final scheduled debate
before next Tuesday's primary. Speaking before the Rotary Club of
Seattle, the state insurance commissioner, Deborah Senn, and former
Rep. Maria Cantwell traded barbs over their records, Internet
privacy issues and Cantwell's largely self-financed and more lavish
campaign spending. But they also spent time criticizing the record
of the Republican incumbent, Slade Gorton, whom the winner of the
primary will take on in the general election. Senn identified
protecting prescription drug coverage for older Americans as her
top legislative priority, while Cantwell, a millionaire high-tech
executive, singled out campaign finance reform. Compiled by B.
Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
