<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: KURSK WILL BE RAISED
</P>
<P>
   Russia is not reconsidering its decision to raise the submarine
Kursk from the Barents Sea, said Deputy Prime Minister Ilya
Klebanov. He added that he was surprised by remarks by the minister
for atomic energy, Yevgeny Adamov, who suggested that it might be
safer to leave the Kursk and its twin-reactor power plant on the
seabed indefinitely. Klebanov, who heads the commission looking
into the disaster, said the sub would be raised after the dead are
recovered this fall.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: TREATY SIGNED
</P>
<P>
   Russia became the 112th country to sign the treaty setting up an
international criminal court to try those accused of war crimes,
genocide and crimes against humanity. Nineteen countries have also
ratified the treaty, of the 60 ratifications needed for the court
to begin functioning. The United States has not signed, and is
demanding an exemption for U.S. soldiers and officials.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: REBEL ACTION
</P>
<P>
   A mortar fired from a van on a hotel building site damaged a
Royal Ulster Constabulary station in Armagh, and two bombs were
deactivated before they could go off at a British army training
center near Londonderry. No one was hurt in the incidents, which
were attributed to the dissident group the Real IRA.
</P>
<P>
   BELGIUM: UNION SLAYINGS
</P>
<P>
   At least 140 union activists were killed last year, mostly in
Latin America and Asia, and organizing efforts were not adequately
protected in industrialized economies, the International
Confederation of Free Trade Unions said in its annual survey.
Rights of union organizers were violated around the world, the
Brussels-based group said, ranging from union busting to ``ruthless
repression.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: JOURNALIST SHOT
</P>
<P>
   A columnist for Quebec's largest selling paper, Journal de
Montreal, was shot in what a police spokesman called an
assassination attempt. Michel Auger, 56, an expert on organized
crime, was in stable condition. Paule Beaugrand-Champagne, the
newspaper's editor in chief, noted that the attack came a day after
a column by Auger detailed a drug turf war between Quebec's biker
gangs and Mafia groups.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA: WAR ON VIGILANTES
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials said South Africa is at war with the
vigilante group suspected of orchestrating a string of bombings in
and around Cape Town for two years. The statement came hours after
a bomb exploded near a community center where the provincial
premier was about to speak. Several people were hurt.
</P>
<P>
   BURUNDI: TUTSI TO SIGN PACT
</P>
<P>
   The last three holdout Tutsi parties have agreed to sign an
accord aimed at ending the country's civil war, Nelson Mandela, the
mediator in the civil war, said after meeting with the leaders of
the three groups at his home in Johannesburg. All 19 parties to the
accord have now signed it, but two Hutu rebel groups continue to
oppose the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN: CLINTON ORDERS SANCTIONS
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton ordered the first sanctions against Japan for
expanding its hunting of whales, ordering that Japanese fishermen
will be prohibited from fishing in United States waters if they are
opened to foreign fleets this year. He acted after the Commerce
Department ruled that Japan is undermining efforts to protect
whales, saying he would consider more sanctions in the next 60
days.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: SURGERY FOR PREMIER
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee will have surgery on his
left knee after returning from his current visit to the United
States, a government spokesman said. Vajpayee's health has been the
cause of great speculation recently, but the prime minister has
insisted that his ailments begin and end with a bad knee.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: CHANGING DESIRES
</P>
<P>
   Under the headline ``The Jewish Mother No Longer Wants Her Son
to Be a Doctor,'' the Yediot Ahronot published results of a poll of
Israeli mothers. It showed that 40 percent want their children to
go into the high-tech industry, 15 percent want them to become
doctors, and only 2 percent want them to be rabbis.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: SLOW JUSTICE
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli-Arab family that won a landmark Supreme Court case
this year, earning the right to settle in the Jewish community of
Katzir, has still not been able to move into the town. The
Association for Civil Rights in Israel petitioned the state
attorney to comply with the court's decision and allocate land to
the family.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY: EX-PREMIER'S JAILING DELAYED
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors agreed to a four-month delay in jailing former Prime
Minister Necmettin Erbakan for remarks he made in 1994. A warrant
was issued for Erbakan, 73, after he failed to show up to start
serving a one-year sentence for telling a political rally Turkey
had abandoned its Islamic roots and politicians had divided Kurds
from other Turks. Erbakan's lawyers said his jailing would prevent
him from defending two other cases.
</P>
