<TEXT>
<P>
   FEWER BRITISH JOBLESS
</P>
<P>
   Britain said the number of unemployed fell to a 25-year low of
3.6 percent in August from 3.7 percent in July as a further 18,000
people found work. The figures reflect the contrast between Britain
and continental Europe, where the average unemployment rate is
almost three times as high, but the fall is causing problems for
manufacturers unable to find skilled workers. Other figures showed
wage increases also fell in the three months through July to an
annualized 3.9 percent, down from 4.1 percent in the previous
quarter, reducing worries about the likely impact of inflation on
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ANOTHER INFUSION FOR DOME
</P>
<P>
   British authorities acknowledged that more public financing
would be given in subsidies to keep the ill-starred Millennium Dome
open until the end of the year. A spokeswoman said the grant _ the
sixth this year _ would total around $110 million, including funds
previously announced and new money to compensate for the collapse
this week of a $157 million deal for the project to be sold to a
division of Nomura, the Japanese investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   QUEBEC CABLE DEAL
</P>
<P>
   The Quebec government's pension fund and a private-sector
partner, Quebecor Inc., have won control of the province's largest
cable television company, Groupe Videotron Ltd., with a $3.3
billion all-cash offer. The two topped a bid by Rogers
Communications Inc. of Toronto. Rogers withdrew its bid Wednesday
and will be paid a $163 million breakup fee. The value of its offer
had fallen below the all-cash counter-bid of about 4.9 billion
Canadian dollars from the Caisse de Depot et Placement du Quebec,
the provincial pension fund, and Quebecor, a Montreal media
company.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-GERMAN INTERNET ALLIANCE
</P>
<P>
   Japan's leading Internet service provider, the Nifty Corp.,
agreed to a cooperative alliance with T-Online International AG of
Germany, Europe's largest Internet service provider. Nifty, owned
by Fujitsu Ltd., and T-Online, owned by Deutsche Telekom AG, will
make available to each other's customers access points in Japan and
Europe. Nifty has 3.9 million subscribers, while T-Online has 6
million spread through Germany, France and Austria.
</P>
<P>
   CADBURY IN PEPSI DEAL
</P>
<P>
   Cadbury Schweppes PLC of Britain will buy Pepsi Cola Bottlers
Australia to increase its market share in carbonated soft drinks.
Terms were not disclosed. The deal will make Cadbury, through its
Australian subsidiary, Schweppes Cottee's, the exclusive bottler of
such brands as Pepsi, Diet Pepsi, 7 Up and Mountain Dew. John
Sunderland, Cadbury's chief executive, said the expansion would
enhance the efficiency and profitability of Schweppes Cottee in the
$2.5 billion (Australian) soft-drink market and nearly double its
market share to 25 percent. &QL;
</P>
