<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILE-CIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE TO REVISIT CHILE FILES THAT CIA WANTS TO BLOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER MARQUIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House ordered a new look Wednesday at
several hundred files that the CIA intends to withhold when it
releases American documents about the 1973 military coup in Chile.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to concerns that the agency is overly protective of
its secrets, Sandy Berger, national security adviser, postponed the
governmentwide release of documents and asked aides to review the
CIA papers and seek the ``fullest possible disclosure.''
</P>
<P>
   The move appeared to signal a victory for Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright and other advocates of a broad disclosure of the
American role in the overthrow of the socialist government of
President Salvador Allende and in the ensuing 17-year dictatorship
of Gen. Augusto Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
   And it could be read as a rebuke to CIA Director George Tenet,
who last month overruled his own declassification experts and
announced that he would withhold certain files on the ground that
they would compromise intelligence techniques still in use.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lockhart, the White House spokesman, said the re-examination
of the CIA papers would take ``no more than a few weeks.'' In two
previous releases of about 7,500 documents, there has been no
explicit evidence of a CIA role in destabilizing the Allende
government, archivists say.
</P>
<P>
   The declassification effort was ordered last year by President
Clinton to shed light on rights abuses, terrorism and other acts of
political violence in Chile from 1968 to 1990.
</P>
<P>
   A Senate committee reported in 1975 on CIA efforts to prevent
Allende from taking office. But the official record remains
somewhat murky on whether American intelligence operatives had a
direct role in the 1973 coup, and on what the American government
knew about the murders of thousands of Chileans _ and some
Americans _ under Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Tenet told members of Congress that some of the
documents in question had to be withheld because they presented ``a
pattern of activity that had the effect of revealing intelligence
methods that have been employed worldwide.''
</P>
<P>
   Tenet insisted that he was not trying to shield his agency or
the United States from embarrassment.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-00 2336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000913.0454 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 23:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3783 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-BOEING-RUDDER-NYT &LR;      09-13 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-RUDDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAA WILL REQUIRE CHANGES FOR RUDDERS ON BOEING 737'S 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Aviation Administration plans to
announce on Thursday that it will require replacement of the rudder
control system on the Boeing 737, the most widely used airliner in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   The agency concluded that safety improvements were still needed,
even after three orders were issued to airlines in recent years to
change hardware and emergency procedures were developed for pilots
to use if the rudders failed.
</P>
<P>
   A rudder malfunction was blamed for the crash of USAir Flight
427, which flipped over and plunged to earth on approach to
Pittsburgh International Airport six years ago this month, killing
all 132 people on board. It is also suspected in the crash of a
United Airlines Boeing 737 on approach to the airport in Colorado
Springs, Colo., in 1991 that killed all 25 on board. But aviation
experts continue to characterize rudder problems on the plane as
rare.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA intends to issue an order by next July that will specify
precisely what changes will be needed and will require finishing
the changes within three to five years. Planes coming off the
assembly line will have to comply sooner.
</P>
<P>
   The decision is a reversal for the agency, which had previously
argued that smaller changes in hardware and procedures would
suffice. Even after the flaw that caused the Pittsburgh crash was
demonstrated, senior agency officials had argued that the existing
system was quite reliable and that a new system could conceivably
have a higher failure rate.
</P>
<P>
   The roughly 1,500 737s registered in this country would be
covered directly by the order and most of the 2,000 registered in
other countries would also be covered, because regulators abroad
typically adopt the same rules as the FAA for American-built
planes. The number of planes in service and the expected scope of
the work are likely to make this one of the biggest orders
affecting planes already in service, aviation officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But the design of the new system is ``still a work in
progress,'' said Diane Spitaliere, a spokeswoman for the FAA. And
even when the new system is completed, the agency will take some
time to approve it, aviation officials said.
</P>
<P>
   It is also unclear what the changes will cost, ``other than the
fact that it's going to be expensive,'' said David Fuscus, a
spokesman for the Air Transport Association, the trade group of the
major airlines. In such cases the cost is typically shared by
airlines and the aircraft manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   In the Pittsburgh case, investigators believe that a malfunction
in the hydraulic system made the rudder swing all the way to one
side and stick there. When the plane's design was first approved,
engineers believed that the control system was redundant, meaning
that there were two separate control systems and one would take
over if the other failed. The system used two valves, one sliding
back and forth within the other.
</P>
<P>
   But after years of investigation, engineers concluded that they
were wrong. One sliding valve could fail without any sign and that
if it did so in one particular position, the other half could later
fail and produce ``rudder reversal,'' which would swing the rudder
hard to the opposite side from what the pilot intended.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-00 2337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
