u w BC-PILOT-SLEEP-NYT &LR;      09-13 0421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PILOT-SLEEP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLINES CALL FOR TIGHTER LIMIT ON PILOTS' DAILY WORK HOURS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The nation's major airlines said Wednesday that the
Federal Aviation Administration should tighten restrictions on how
many hours a day a pilot could work. They also said the agency
should repeal a ``regulatory loophole'' allowing crews to ferry
empty airplanes at the end of the day without regard to how many
hours a pilot had already flown.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest pilots' union said the airlines' proposals were ``a
delaying tactic'' in implementing new regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA has been trying since 1995 to rewrite the rules on how
long pilots can work, but its proposal attracted 2,000 comments
from airlines, pilots and others, and the agency is still
considering those comments. Without a consensus, it is not certain
that the agency will be able to write a new rule.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots now are limited to 16 scheduled hours a day, but the
aviation agency said in 1995 that it would like to shorten that to
14. As air traffic delays have worsened, pilots' workdays have
stretched, even if the number of miles they fly has stayed
constant.
</P>
<P>
   The major airlines' trade group, the Air Transport Association,
which made the announcement Wednesday, called for tightening
certain exceptions to the 16-hour rule; in 1995 it opposed a
14-hour limit as too short.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, a DC-8 cargo plane on a ferry flight crashed on
approach to Guantanamo Bay, the American military base on the Cuban
coast; all three cockpit crew members were sleepy, the National
Transportation Safety Board found.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an example of something that should simply not
happen,'' said Carol Hallett, the executive director of the Air
Transport Association, a trade association made up of 23 airlines.
The member airlines have agreed to stop using a rule that lets them
conduct such flights regardless of how long the crew has worked,
Hallett said.
</P>
<P>
   The association wants the FAA to impose the same restriction on
smaller carriers. Hallett acknowledged, however, that most, if not
all, members of the group had stopped such flights before the
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   But the president of the Air Line Pilots Association, Capt.
Duane Woerth, said Wednesday that the airlines' announcement fell
short of what was required. The pilots have been complaining about
short turnarounds that they say leave them too little time for rest
between workdays.
</P>
<P>
   But pilots themselves are divided over the limits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
