A3793 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w BC-GAMBLING-BILL-KAN &LR;      09-13 0465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMBLING-BILL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE COMMITTEE PASSES MEASURE THAT WOULD BAN BETTING ON AMATEUR
SPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Efforts advanced Wednesday to outlaw legalized
betting on college, high school and Olympic sports..MDSD/.MDNM/
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee passed a bill to make betting on
amateur sports illegal, which already is the case virtually
everywhere in the country, except Nevada. A Senate panel took
similar action in June, saying it would protect the integrity of
amateur athletics.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a chance for Congress in the last hours of this
session to do something for a cause many Americans really love and
appreciate, and that is college sports,'' said Rep. Lindsey Graham,
a South Carolina Republican and bill sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Sam Brownback, a Kansas Republican who sponsored a similar
bill passed in June by the Senate Commerce Committee, said he was
glad there was support in both houses of Congress for the
prohibition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should not gamble with the integrity of the Olympic Games,
our colleges or the future of college athletics,'' Brownback said.
``Gambling has become a black eye on too many of our colleges and
universities.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham said that betting on amateur sports was a $1 billion
annual enterprise in Nevada and that betting can influence young
athletes and teams.
</P>
<P>
   But critics said the bill did nothing to curb widespread illegal
betting on college sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to make a bit of difference in the real
world,'' said Rep. William Delahunt, a Massachusetts Democrat who
is on the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Betting is common on college campuses, in workplaces, on the
Internet and through bookmaking operations, some lawmakers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me trying to focus on Nevada as a way of stamping
out illegal betting is a little bit overdone,'' said Rep. John
Conyers of Michigan, the ranking Democrat on the Judiciary
Committee. ``We are really ignoring illegal gambling in the other
49 states.''
</P>
<P>
   Conyers, who spoke favorably of the bill when it first was
introduced, suggested that a task force be appointed to study the
issue. The committee rejected that idea and voted 17-11 for the
bill, mostly along party lines, with Republicans in support of the
measure. ``It's been studied to death,'' Graham said. ``We don't
need another study.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Fahrenkopf Jr., president and chief executive of the
American Gaming Association, said he was encouraged that there were
numerous votes against the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we have been saying all along, when people start focusing
on the facts, they would recognize this bill for what it is: a
cosmetic response to serious campus gambling problems,'' he said in
a news release.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
