<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BREWERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAYTON PUTS END TO DRAMA WITH 10TH-INNING HOMER
</HEADLINE>
  By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Mets' 4-1 victory over the Milwaukee
Brewers Wednesday was a Jay Payton production in three acts. Mixing
tragicomedy with suspense, Payton presented the Brewers with a gift
run in the first inning, then wrote himself award-winning parts in
the ninth and 10th innings.
</P>
<P>
   Critics in the Mets' clubhouse applauded Payton's second- and
third-act performances because they turned another potentially
devastating loss attributed to the missing-offense malady into an
uplifting victory that strengthened the Mets' hold on the National
League wild-card spot and let the Atlanta Braves know they
shouldn't celebrate the East division championship yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was offering steak dinners for anybody who got a run back
for us,'' Payton said of his first-inning play that allowed the
certain third out to become a run-scoring error.
</P>
<P>
   On the 11-game road trip that begins Thursday night, Payton can
take himself and Robin Ventura to dinner. Their doubles produced
the tying run in the ninth, and Payton lined a two-out, three-run
home run over the left-center-field fence in the 10th.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the third in the Mets' last four games, and even
though they aren't scoring tons of runs consistently, at this
juncture of the season, a victory is a victory, however it is
achieved.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared that a missed fly ball in the first inning would
decide the outcome. Angel Echevarria walked with two out, and
Richie Sexson hit an eminently catchable fly to right-center. Lenny
Harris, starting in right for the first time this season, called
for the ball. But so did center fielder Payton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both could have caught it,'' Payton said. ``Lenny probably
could have caught it easier than me. But when I'm in center, I'm
aggressive. I go after the ball, and I'm going to call for it. I
want my corner outfielders to get behind me. But Lenny was probably
there before me. I'm just coming over. He heard me at the last
second and bailed. I wasn't sure he was going to bail, so we both
bailed. It was my fault. It's my responsibility to catch that
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The ball fell between the outfielders _ Harris was charged with
the error _ and Echevarria raced home with the unearned run.
</P>
<P>
   Payton's first-inning play was not far from his thoughts. ``I
was thinking about that the whole game,'' he said. ``We haven't
been scoring runs and I didn't want us to go down because of a ball
that was misplayed in the first inning.''
</P>
<P>
   The right-handed-hitting Payton lined the fourth pitch to right
field for a double.
</P>
<P>
   Payton moved to third as Edgardo Alfonzo bounced out. After Mike
Piazza swung at a high fastball well out of the strike zone and sat
down with strikeout No. 4, Ventura swung at the first pitch and
lined a double to left, driving in Payton with the steak-producing
run.
</P>
<P>
   Payton's Act III came not much later. With one out in the 10th,
Mike Bordick singled. Joe McEwing then lofted a high pop-up into
short center, and the Brewers proceeded to reprise the Mets'
first-inning farce.
</P>
<P>
   As McEwing slammed his bat to the ground, shortstop Mark Loretta
went back and center fielder Marquis Grissom came in. It appeared
that either could catch the ball. But Grissom called for it,
Loretta fell to the ground to get out of his way and Grissom, like
Payton, did not make the catch. It fell for a single, giving the
Mets runners at first and second.
</P>
<P>
   Bubba Trammell popped up for the second out, but Payton lashed a
line drive to left-center that Lou Collier pursued.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I thought it probably was going to be caught,''
Payton said. ``I didn't think I hit it that good. It was a slider,
and I stayed back and I put a good swing on it, but I thought I got
out in front of it just a little bit. I was running hard watching
the left fielder. I thought the way he was running he would go back
and make a play on it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the ball took off and sailed over the fence. ``I got some
new bats today,'' the jubilant Payton said, ``so maybe the wood's a
little better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets felt much better when Payton reached his place at home
plate and his play was over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
