u k BC-EDIT-MORGAN-CHASE-NYT     09-13 0404
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MORGAN-CHASE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: GIGANTIC BANKS, EVOCATIVE NAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Sept. 14:
</P>
<P>
   The proposed takeover of J.P. Morgan by Chase Manhattan to form
the country's third-largest financial services institution is the
latest in a series of mergers that have wiped out many of New York
City's great banks of the past. Gone as independent banks are
Manufacturers Hanover Trust, Bankers Trust and Guaranty Trust.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some of the great banks survive in name only. Once
Chemical took over Chase in 1996, an independent Chase ceased to
exist. But Chemical ditched its own name in favor of one that
evoked images of Abraham Lincoln's Treasury secretary, after whom
Chase Bank was named, and the Rockefeller family.
</P>
<P>
   After this latest takeover, an independent J.P. Morgan will also
cease to exist, though the merged corporation will be called J.P.
Morgan Chase. That sounds more impressive than Chemical.
</P>
<P>
   As mergers swallow one bank after another, the survivors grow
gargantuan. J.P. Morgan Chase rolls the former Chemical, Chase,
Manufacturers Hanover and J.P. Morgan banks into one financial
goliath controlling more than $650 billion in assets. That leaves
it behind only Citigroup and Bank of America. Chase and J.P. Morgan
together account for more than 90,000 employees and $17 billion in
revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The reigning theory says banks can survive only as part of
global conglomerates that offer corporate customers every
conceivable financial product. International markets may
accommodate only a few conglomerates. The likely survivors include
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, Goldman Sachs and Merrill Lynch.
Standing alone, neither Chase nor J.P. Morgan would make the cut.
Together, they might.
</P>
<P>
   Size may not, however, prove to be a magic elixir. Citigroup,
which combined Citibank and Travelers Group two years ago, appears
to be doing well. But huge Japanese banks and European banks have
stumbled. Shareholders have a lot to fear if gigantism proves a
failure. But the general public does not. There are plenty of banks
and securities firms to compete for customers' business.
</P>
<P>
   For New York City, the merger threatens to produce layoffs in
the short term. But if the merger puts J.P. Morgan Chase on the
short list of corporate survivors, it will help keep New York at
the center of the financial world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-00 2339EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000913.0460 </DOCNO>
