<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-US-BASKETBALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREAM TEAM SEEKS A CHALLENGE; SUPPORT FOR KNIGHT; HOUSTON SPRAINS
WRIST 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PENRITH, Australia _ Alonzo Mourning acknowledged Wednesday what
his teammates already knew: getting motivated to annihilate
inferior basketball nations is hard work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really difficult to get yourself up to play against
international competition because, first of all, you know you're
superior to them,'' Mourning said Wednesday as the U.S. men's
basketball team prepared for its opening game of the 2000 Olympics
against China on Sunday (Saturday Eastern time).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we're competing against the guys we compete
against in the league,'' Mourning said. ``It's like Gary Payton
says, `We're getting ready for the Clippers.'''
</P>
<P>
   The American men are a lock to capture a third consecutive gold
medal. With a 40-0 mark in international play since National
Basketball Association players were allowed to compete in 1992, the
pressure is not merely to win. They have to win by astronomical
scores to keep up with distant Dream Team cousins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each one of those Dream Teams are different,'' Mourning said.
``International competition has gotten better and better. They've
improved from back when Jordan was playing eight years ago. It's
improved dramatically.''
</P>
<P>
   Mourning will miss two games next week to return home to be with
his wife, Tracy Wilson-Mourning, who is expected to give birth to a
baby daughter, Myka Sydney. He will travel 9,330 miles roundtrip
over four days.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's rousing half-court scrimmage in a community center
gymnasium about an hour's drive west of Sydney may be the best
competition Mourning and his teammates face.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we're here, we've got to get something out of this, even
if it's in practice against ourselves,'' he said. ``Execute, work
and let our talents take over. We do that, this thing will care of
itself. We want to put on a show for the world and let everybody
know that USA Basketball is still the best.''
</P>
<P>
   They did not endear themselves to Australians during an
exhibition in Melbourne last Saturday night that featured an
altercation between Vince Carter and Andrew Gaze and as much
physical play as a Heat-Knicks series. The crowd, ready to embrace
the NBA All-Stars before the game began, chanted derisively at
Carter in the second half of an 89-64 victory by the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Several players admitted that playing the dual role of
international good sportsman and dominant gold-medal favorite can
be a chore. The talking and shoving on Saturday night was more than
excessive.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't go and tell Tim Hardaway not to play the way he's
been playing for 25 years,'' Payton said. ``Off the court, we're
great people. But on the court, we're trying to get a job done and
win. And if it comes across bad, we've got to be that way. As long
as we don't do anything to really embarrass our country or team _
like a big altercation or fight _ then it's great.''
</P>
<P>
   Allan Houston said: ``We're worried about winning. Who we are is
who we are. We don't have any knuckleheads on this team that's
going to misrepresent the United States anyway. We're not going out
there to do anything crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Mourning also divulged another badly kept secret. The Americans
have no chance of losing, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not worried about that,'' he said. ``If we played five
players the whole game, I couldn't see us losing. We might not win
by a big margin, but I still can't see us losing.''
</P>
<P>
   Support for Knight
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 10,000 miles from Bloomington, Ind., one of Bobby
Knight's longtime rivals and the point guard on his first national
championship team was surprised and disappointed over the Indiana
coach's firing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed for basketball because he's a great mind,''
said Quinn Buckner, USA Basketball's vice president, who won a
national championship with Knight. ``I'm disappointed for the
university because they lose a great coach. I'm obviously
disappointed for him because he loses not just a job but also a
program that he built. Indiana basketball was Bob Knight
basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Buckner, who started on the last undefeated team in men's
Division I basketball, in 1976, added: ``I still remember when we
won the championship. I hadn't seen him happy before that. His hair
was mussed; he used to wear those ugly checked suits. But he was
finally happy when we won.''
</P>
<P>
   Gene Keady, an assistant coach with the men's team and a fixture
at Purdue for two decades, said he was stunned by the news
delivered to him by an assistant coach in his hotel room on Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Even though they were fierce rivals in the Big Ten Conference,
Keady, who has been involved with USA Basketball for 21 years,
helped Knight select the 1984 Olympic team. He conceded that
calling Knight to express his condolences would probably not be a
good idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never done much of that because we've always just played
each other,'' Keady said. ``I don't think Coach Knight would return
a call to me. It'd be wasted money. He's got more important things
to worry about. I'll miss mostly the competition and what it took
to prepare for his teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston Sprains Wrist
</P>
<P>
   Allan Houston sat out most of practice after spraining his right
wrist as he was driving to the basket against Shareef-Abdur Rahim.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels like I kind of jammed it,'' Houston said of his
shooting hand, which was surgically repaired after the 1996-97
season. ``I don't feel like I did anything serious, but hopefully
by tomorrow I can shoot the ball. If I can shoot, I'm all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston said he would put off any decision on X-rays until
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I worried? If I can't practice, it's going to worry me a
little,'' he said. ``I want to be able to play in practice and in
the Games.''
</P>
</TEXT>
