<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CAP-AVOIDANCE-970&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMITH'S SECRET PACT UNDERCUTS NBA CAP
</HEADLINE>
  By JAMES C. McKINLEY Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Joe Smith signed with the Minnesota Timberwolves in January
1999, he accepted a one-year contract worth only $1.75 million, a
small sum for a 6-foot-10-inch forward with immense potential who
had been the first pick in the 1995 draft.
</P>
<P>
   The deal raised a few eyebrows around the NBA. Smith, who is 25,
should have been worth between three to five times as much on the
open market, league officials say. Indeed, he had earned $2.5
million his rookie year with the Golden State Warriors.
</P>
<P>
   The skeptics, it turns out, had reason to doubt. Smith signed
two agreements with the Timberwolves: The first was the one-year
contract that the team sent to the league office in New York. But
the second was an extensive secret agreement in which the team's
owner promised Smith, in writing, a seven-year deal worth as much
as $86 million after he had worked for three years under less
lucrative, one-year contracts, said several people who have seen
both documents.
</P>
<P>
   The tactics of the Timberwolves, Smith and his agent, Eric
Fleisher, reflect a widespread problem in professional basketball
that has undercut the effectiveness of the NBA's salary-cap rules.
Those rules, league officials say, are intended to keep rich teams
from hoarding the best talent.
</P>
<P>
   For years, there have been allegations that some agents and
owners were circumventing the salary cap, using a loophole that
lets a team re-sign its own free agents after three years even if
the new contract exceeds the cap. Known as the Larry Bird rule, the
provision was originally meant to protect owners from being forced
to break up a great team just to remain under the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   But some owners and agents have been exploiting the loophole,
agents and officials from the league and the players union say.
Teams who cannot afford an expensive player because of the salary
cap sometimes sign him first to a series of low-paying, one-year
contracts, while promising, with a wink and a nod, to give him a
lucrative multiyear deal three years later, when he gets what are
known as his ``Bird rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Some officials in the NFL have also been concerned about teams
doing an end run around salary-cap restrictions. The league's
management council has been investigating whether Carmen Policy,
the former president of the San Francisco 49ers, violated
salary-cap rules in contracts in the 1990s with Steve Young, a
former quarterback, and Brent Jones, a former tight end.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the NBA has made fruitless attempts to investigate
allegations of secret deals to circumvent the salary cap. The
league's lawyers have always failed to find a paper trail proving
that secret agreements existed.
</P>
<P>
   In Smith's case, however, the league has obtained copies of the
two agreements, which show that in early 1999 Smith and his agent,
Fleisher, negotiated not only a standard one-year contract, which
was filed with the league, but also an extensive separate pact with
the Timberwolves' owner, Glen Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   That secret agreement was never shown to the NBA, league
officials said. People who have read the second agreement said it
laid out a 10-year arrangement under which Taylor agreed to sign
Smith to three one-year contracts, of $1.75 million, $2.1 million
and $3.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor also agreed that he would give Smith, before the 2001-2
season, two additional contracts that cumulatively over seven years
would be worth between $40.6 million and $86.6 million. The final
value of the deal depended on whether Smith became an All-Star or
led the team to a championship, several people who have read the
documents said. The secret agreement is dated Jan. 22, 1999, a day
before the one-year contract for $1.75 million was signed,
notarized and sent by the team to the league's offices.
</P>
<P>
   In the one-year contract filed with the league, Fleisher signed
an oath, under penalty of perjury, saying that ``there are no
undisclosed agreements of any kind, express or implied, oral or
written.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the secret agreement, signed by Smith and Taylor the
previous day, said its provisions would override any other
contracts the parties had signed. ``The terms of this agreement
shall control,'' the document says, people who have read it said.
</P>
<P>
   Fleisher did not return telephone calls left Wednesday at his
office.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith's new agent, Daniel Fegan, portrayed his client as a
victim of an unscrupulous agent. He said the secret agreements were
unnecessary and ``were designed to protect the interests of the
player agent, not the player.'' He also said Smith had never asked
Fleisher or the team to draft the documents, and that the agent had
advised Smith to sign them without explaining that they violated
the salary-cap rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe for a minute that he understood exactly what
he was signing,'' Fegan said. ``And I don't believe it was ever
explained to him or that he understood what he was risking.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor declined a request to be interviewed for this article. In
an article last weekend in The Minneapolis Star Tribune, he
acknowledged the secret agreement, but stopped short of admitting
that he had violated the salary-cap provisions in the collective
bargaining agreement between the NBA and the players association.
</P>
<P>
   ``The agreement called for a number of things to be phased in
each year,'' Taylor said. ``We agreed on different scenarios of
what his market value would be.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it basically just said that we had to conform with the
collective bargaining rules; it would be an agreement that we would
send into the commissioner for his approval. There were no side
deals or anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   NBA officials do not see it that way. In a news release, league
officials called the existence of a secret agreement ``the most
serious salary-cap offense that can be committed by teams, players
or agents.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   An arbitrator, Kenneth Dam, a University of Chicago professor,
has been hired to hold private hearings into the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are alleging that there is a written undisclosed agreement
between Joe Smith and the Timberwolves,'' Joel Litvin, the NBA
executive vice president for legal and business affairs, said.
``The agreement, which is set forth in writing, calls for future
payments to Smith of tens of millions of dollars and was
deliberately hidden from the league by the parties involved.''
</P>
<P>
   The arbitrator could order several penalties against the team,
including a fine of up to $3.5 million, the forfeiture of draft
picks and the suspension of team officials for up to a year.
</P>
<P>
   Fleisher could face severe sanctions from the player's union,
which certifies agents. The union's committee on agent regulation
could strip him of his license to represent NBA players. As a
lawyer, he also runs a risk of being sanctioned by the bar
association if it is shown he committed perjury. As a player, Smith
faces a less severe penalty. His pacts with the team could be
voided, leaving him once more a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   In the NBA, the Larry Bird loophole has made the cap easy to
override. In most cases, league officials have been powerless
because they have been unable to prove the existence of secret
agreements.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time we've got them dead to rights,'' one league official
said, speaking on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
