<HEADLINE>
ARCHITECTS SUBMIT FOUR PROPOSALS FOR NEW HEADQUARTERS FOR THE
TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Conn., Calif., Britain)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT42 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID W. DUNLAP   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Plans by The New York Times to build a new
headquarters on Eighth Avenue took intriguing form this week with
the submission of competing proposals by some of the world's most
renowned architects.
</P>
<P>
   Prismatic, polymorphous, scintillating and starkly angular, they
defy the conventional idea of a boxy or stepped New York
skyscraper.
</P>
<P>
   Though Times executives were quick to say that the architects'
visions would bear little or no relation to the final design of the
building, if such a building is even constructed, the models offer
a tantalizing glimpse of the company's ambitious aspirations for
the site, between 40th and 41st streets.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the four entrants have won the Pritzker Architecture
Prize, widely considered the platinum bar of the profession. They
are Renzo Piano, Norman Foster and Frank Gehry, who is allied in
his submission with Skidmore, Owings &AMP; Merrill. The other entrant,
Cesar Pelli, has been a Pritzker juror.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Golden, the vice chairman and senior vice president of
The New York Times Co., said Wednesday that he hoped the final
choice could be made next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said we wanted this to be a difficult decision, and boy, is
it,'' he said after the four presentations concluded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want a building that is an icon,'' Golden said, ``that
speaks to our heritage and also speaks to our future.'' New York
City, he said, is already rich in architecture. ``We want to make
it richer.''
</P>
<P>
   The Times Co. and its development partner, Forest City Ratner
Companies, are planning a tower about 650 feet high, with 1.3
million square feet of space, across Eighth Avenue from the Port
Authority Bus Terminal. The Times would occupy a little more than
half the building, including the larger floors at its base. The
rest would be leased to commercial and retail tenants.
</P>
<P>
   Although the 200-by-400-foot site is part of the Times Square
redevelopment area, it is still in the hands of 11 different
owners. The 42nd Street Development Project, a subsidiary of the
Empire State Development Corp., would acquire the properties
through eminent domain and lease the land to the Times Co. and
Forest City Ratner.
</P>
<P>
   Construction might begin late next year or early in 2002, Golden
said, with occupancy of the new building about two years later. The
Times would probably sell the building at 229 W. 43rd St., which it
has occupied since 1913, Golden said.
</P>
<P>
   But he cautioned that the Times board had not yet decided to
make the move and declined to estimate the cost of the project,
saying it was too early to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should warn you that what you see won't be what you get,''
Golden told Times employees in a memo about the architectural
presentations. ``The models represent the architects' design
concepts at this point in time. The architect that is chosen will
then embark upon a yearlong, detailed and complex process to design
the building we will ultimately occupy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   That said, each concept is arresting.
</P>
<P>
   A towering right triangle has been proposed by Foster &AMP; Partners
of London. The high point would be on Eighth Avenue and the
inclined facade on the east, with tree-filled terraces every seven
stories. The sides would be crisscrossed with bold X bracing. The
top of the building would be illuminated and could, the architect
said, be assigned to an artist as a ``cultural billboard.''
</P>
<P>
   Foster's projects have included the Hong Kong and Shanghai Bank
in Hong Kong and the reconstruction of the Reichstag in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   From Frank O. Gehry &AMP; Associates of Santa Monica, Calif., has
come a proposal for a tower with an undulating facade, wrapped in
twisting, sinewy planes that blossom at the top and bustle at the
bottom; not unlike pappardelle pasta on a colossal scale. At the
top of the building would appear an ``N'' and ``Y'' in the
black-letter typeface from the newspaper's nameplate.
</P>
<P>
   Gehry, who astonished the world with the sinuous,
titanium-roofed Guggenheim Museum in Bilbao, Spain, has more
recently designed a proposal for a new Guggenheim Museum on the
Lower Manhattan waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   He is associated with Skidmore, Owings &AMP; Merrill, whose current
projects include Columbus Center, soon to rise on the site of the
New York Coliseum; the new Pennsylvania Station; and the new New
York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Cesar Pelli &AMP; Associates of New Haven is probably best known in
New York as the architect of the World Financial Center at Battery
Park City and the Carnegie Hall Tower. But its proposal for the
Times building is nothing like those.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than four square walls, Pelli calls for a series of
suave, tapered, intersecting planes, each at a slightly different
angle, topped by a slanting roof. There would be tree-filled
atriums at either end of the building, which would rise out of a
low base covering the entire site.
</P>
<P>
   Piano has proposed an irregular, rectangular tower whose facade
consists of layers of diaphanous glass screens that almost seem to
float in the air around the building. There would be a five-story
atrium in the base, opening from Eighth Avenue, and a roof garden.
</P>
<P>
   In a caption accompanying his presentation, Piano said the Times
building ``should introduce new qualities: lightness, vibration,
transparency and immateriality.''
</P>
<P>
   Piano attracted world attention in the 1970s with the
startlingly exoskeletal Pompidou Center in Paris, designed with
Richard Rogers. Recent projects include the redevelopment of
Potsdamer Platz in Berlin. The Renzo Piano Building Workshop is
based in Paris and in Genoa, Italy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
