<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MEGAPLEXES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MOVIE THEATERS SEEK HAPPY ENDING 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Sept. 14:
</P>
<P>
   If it were a Hollywood production, ``The Plight of the
Megaplex'' would be a tear-jerker starring companies brought to
ruin because they sought to bring hourly show times, reclining seat
backs, retractable armrests and stadium seating to every last
corner of America.
</P>
<P>
   Movie theater chains have been building plush, massive
``megaplexes'' since 1995, when a 24-screen theater went up in
Dallas. Customers seem to love them. While ``stadium seating'' may
conjure up images of freezing temperatures, hard seats and
fistfights at a professional football game, it actually means
building theaters so as to enable all moviegoers to see the screen
instead of only the back of someone's cranium. It is the most
revolutionary film-exhibiting development to come along since the
cup holder, which took the industry by storm in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is, these new facilities have been taking business
away from the same operators' older screens, often located at mere
``multiplexes.'' There simply aren't enough customers to go around.
Although the number of movie screens in the United States has more
than doubled over the past two decades _ from 17,675 in 1980 to
37,185 in 1999 _ only 50 percent more tickets were sold last year
than in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Also, because theaters take a smaller slice of the box office in
a movie's first weeks, putting the hottest movies on five screens
with staggered starting hours may turn out to be a poor business
strategy, insofar as it shortens a film's life span.
</P>
<P>
   The casualties are mounting. This year United Artists, Carmike
Cinemas, Edwards Cinemas and Silver Cinemas have filed Chapter 11
bankruptcy petitions. Loews Cineplex said on Aug. 25 that it might
default on debt payments. Not even $5 bags of popcorn can stem the
tide of red ink that resulted when these companies overbuilt to
protect market share. The summer of 2000, short on blockbuster
hits, proved little relief, with box office receipts down $210
million from last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Once the crisis is past, surviving movie theater chains will be
left to confront the question haunting the 500-channel cable TV
universe: Is there enough good material to put on all those
screens?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-00 2342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
