<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-DEBATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK COMMENTARY: TWO CANDIDATES WHO DIFFER MEAN A CHOICE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOYCE PURNICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It would not have seemed possible before Wednesday
night's Senate debate, not remotely possible that you could feel
sympathy for Hillary Rodham Clinton _ tough-as-nails, implacable
Hillary, of the Rose Law Firm and Travelgate and Whitewater and the
Vast Right-Wing Conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   But when Tim Russert ran that tape of her from January 1998,
defending her husband on the ``Today'' program against charges of
sexual impropriety; and her opponent, Rep. Rick Lazio, hammered
away at  &UR; the issues &LR;  of ``character and trust''; and then he
marched over to her, demanding, like a Long Island Joe McCarthy,
that she sign a pledge saying she never again would spend soft
money, let's face it. The first lady was getting beaten up and
except for the entrenched Hillary-haters, more than a few viewers
probably felt a twinge of sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   We shouldn't. That's politics. Clinton gets no more protection
than any other candidate, should and probably does not expect
special treatment as a woman or first lady, nor should voters take
umbrage when she takes her knocks. Campaigns get nasty. Indeed,
many times Wednesday night, Clinton let Lazio have it, accusing him
of ``chutzpah,'' and linking him time and again to Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   But this had a different quality to it. This was harsh and
personal, this was wince-making, especially to hear her hesitate
and watch her look down at her hands and reach for words, repeating
``you know'' over and over again as she tried to answer Russert
about the ``Today'' program, saying ``Well, you know, Tim, that was
a very, a very painful time for me, for my family and for our
country.'' To his question about whether she would apologize for
misleading the country, she said she didn't know the truth about
her husband, which maybe was true, maybe was not.
</P>
<P>
   But you had to wish she would tell Russert: enough, it's none of
your business. Except candidates, especially women, cannot lose
their tempers with impunity.
</P>
<P>
   What does this all have to do with being a senator? With who won
this debate? Probably very little. But extraordinary things happen
in campaigns that reveal a great deal about this country and our
politics, and this was one of those moments.
</P>
<P>
   It was a reminder that the playing field is not level and that
there are unwritten rules for women in politics, still. Just as an
aggressive female politician will be labeled shrill and unappealing
while an aggressive man will be, well, manly and tough, a male
candidate can't be too harsh toward a female opponent because he
will come across as a bully. Same for the reporters. Russert was
doing his job and did it well. But his style made this viewer, and
surely others, cringe. Same for Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   Not fair, absolutely. Not fair. But that's how it is and that is
why, we predict, the Russert-Clinton moment, followed by the Lazio
paper-signing act, will be what most viewers take away from
Wednesday night's debate in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   As for the less-laden question of who won, who knows? We do know
that New Yorkers should feel pretty good about the debate. It
showed that they have two significant candidates with real
differences between them. A choice.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, who had to prove Wednesday night that he wasn't New
York's Dan Quayle, held his own and then some, deflecting charges
that he was a puppet of the Republican leadership and staking out
positions on key issues. Clinton, who had to show she wasn't Lady
Macbeth, stuck to substance and was, if not relaxed and
comfortable, prepared and in command.
</P>
<P>
   They disagreed on health care, education and fiscal policy. He's
for vouchers, she isn't. He opposes casino gambling, she would
support it if the community wanted it. Both object to the teachers
strike in Buffalo, he more assertively than Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   They linked each other to other politicians: Clinton aligning
Lazio with Gingrich; Lazio blaming Clinton for some of President
Clinton's policies. And each played games with soft money. Lazio
pushed his pledge, Clinton said she'd tried to get a mutual soft
money ban early on, and of course both are raising and spending all
they can get.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio even tried to sound like the New York equivalent of a good
old boy, quoting _ that is, misquoting _ Casey Stengel. ``I've
delivered for New York,'' said the congressman. ``And as that old
Yankee manager, Casey Stengel, used to say, `You can check it
out.''' Actually, the line attributed to Casey Stengel is, ``You
could look it up.''
</P>
<P>
   For an hour Wednesday night, New York was treated to a good
political debate. Standard politics. Except for what was not,
which, we suspect, is what we will remember.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
