<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: TWO COUNTRIES UNDER ONE BANNER 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Athletes from North and South Korea will march into Sydney's
Olympic Stadium as one nation Friday, in what should prove one of
the emotional highlights of the Games' opening ceremony. Though the
two nations will compete separately, their decision to march
together under a single white flag with a blue depiction of an
undivided peninsula should be greeted as another significant step
toward reconciliation. The joint march will also be a tribute to
the Olympic aspiration that sports can break down barriers between
people.
</P>
<P>
   Koreans have experienced a perceptible thaw in relations ever
since the June meeting in Pyongyang between South Korea's
president, Kim Dae-jung, and the North Korean leader, Kim Jong Il.
Wednesday, Kim Jong Il agreed to visit Seoul next spring. An
exchange of family visits last month that brought together
relatives who had not heard from each other in a half-century
transfixed South Korea and served as a reminder to the rest of the
world of the lingering tragedy that Korea's division represents.
More such family visits are planned, and South Korea has agreed to
import grain to provide to its hunger-stricken communist neighbor.
Both countries, still technically at war since their conflict ended
with a mere truce in 1953, have also agreed to rebuild the rail
link between them.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the Olympics, South Korea is to play host, along with
Japan, to the other major global sporting event, soccer's 2002
World Cup. Organizers are already discussing the possibility of
holding one or two matches in reclusive North Korea. That would be
another valuable step toward reconciliation brought about by
sports.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-00 2343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
