<HEADLINE>
FISHER COULD MISS ENTIRE SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ Already lacking in muscle and depth, the
Los Angeles Lakers are soon to face a deficit in heart and sweat as
well as they prepare to defend their NBA title.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Fisher, a spot starter and key reserve for the defending
NBA champions, is out for at least three months _ and potentially
the entire season _ because of a stress fracture in his right foot.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers open training camp in three weeks and, at the moment,
retain just two healthy guards from their championship team _ Kobe
Bryant and 35-year-old Ron Harper.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, a four-year veteran, injured the foot last season and
played in pain throughout the playoffs and the Finals. Yet the
6-foot-1 Fisher played a major role in stopping opponents' smaller
guards, from Portland's Damon Stoudamire to Indiana's Travis Best.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, who has been working out with teammates at the Lakers'
training facility, probably aggravated the injury while playing
pickup games this summer, but a Lakers spokesman said the team does
not know all the details yet.
</P>
<P>
   Although not among the Lakers' top scorers, Fisher is a
hard-nosed defender, unselfish playmaker and one of the
hardest-working members of the team. He has earned minutes and
popularity with his frequent dives across the court and into the
seats to save loose balls.
</P>
<P>
   Without Fisher, the Lakers will be even more reliant on the
recently acquired and tempestuous Isaiah Rider. They also are
likely to increase efforts to re-sign free agent Brian Shaw. But if
the season opened today, the Lakers' fourth guard would be
little-used Tyronn Lue.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher received the diagnosis Tuesday from team orthopedist Dr.
Stephen Lombardo and was given two options: rest and therapy, with
the hope of returning in three months, or surgery, which would
knock him out for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher flew to his hometown of Little Rock, Ark. on Wednesday to
get a second opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers general manager Mitch Kupchak and coach Phil Jackson were
unavailable for comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Last season Fisher played in 78 games, averaging a career-high
6.3 points in 23.1 minutes per game. He averaged 6.0 points and 3.8
assists during the Finals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
