<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBATE-PAPERS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL HOT POTATO RECEIVED AND LET GO BY GORE CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (INSERTS grafs 8-14 with quotes from press conference with Bush's
spokeswoman)  
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A close adviser to Vice President Al Gore said he
had received an anonymously mailed package on Wednesday that
involved material designed to prepare Gov. George W. Bush for his
debates with Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The adviser, former Rep. Tom Downey of New York, said he
examined the materials briefly before giving them to his lawyer,
who turned them over to the FBI on Wednesday afternoon. Downey, who
has been helping Gore prepare for the Bush debates and was standing
in for Bush in mock debates, also said he would recuse himself from
any further debate preparation.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush and Gore campaigns are to meet on Thursday to negotiate
the debate schedule. If the candidates adhere to a plan set up by a
bipartisan commission, the first debate will be on Oct. 3 in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign officials said they did not know if the materials sent
to Downey had been stolen from the Bush campaign or were meant to
trap the Gore adviser in some sort of dirty trick. Downey's lawyer,
Marc Miller, said the material _ a videotape and a sheaf of papers
_ arrived in an envelope postmarked Austin, Texas, where the Bush
campaign has its headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign was eager to dissociate itself quickly from
the incident. After Miller called the FBI, campaign officials
alerted The Associated Press that the packet had arrived and
provided a detailed time line of Downey's actions.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Fabiani, a spokesman for Gore, said of Downey: ``He's being
very careful and very prudent. He's handled this exactly right. No
one can raise any questions about how it's being handled. What to
make of it, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Ari Fleischer, a spokesman for the Bush campaign, said: ``We
don't know what the Gore campaign claims to have in their
possession, but we take it very seriously. We have asked our
attorneys to review it to try to determine what they have.''
</P>
<P>
   At an impromptu news conference Wednesday in Westminster,
Calif., the chief spokeswoman for the Bush campaign, Karen Hughes,
said that his campaign had not yet determined whether the materials
Downey received were legitimate, but that she was not aware of any
missing materials like the videotape or briefing papers.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said that the campaign had asked the FBI for permission
to review the materials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking this seriously,'' Hughes said. ``We think the
first step is to find out what the materials are, and if in fact
they are legitimate.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that Bush and a small group senior advisers had begun
debate preparations last May. She said that while the earliest
sessions were not videotaped, some later ones were. She said that
only Bush and a few senior advisers _ including herself; the
campaign's manager, Joe Allbaugh; Karl Rove, the campaign's chief
strategist; Donald L. Evans, the campaign's chairman, and Mark
McKinnon, the chief media adviser _ had legitimate access to the
videotapes.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hughes said that William M. Daley of the Gore campaign had
called Evans Wednesday to tell him that they had received the
materials. ``He was fairly vague about what materials,'' she said.
Asked whether the Gore campaign had handled the situation well, she
said she had so few details that it was impossible to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was right for them to send them over to
authorities,'' she said of the videotapes.
</P>
<P>
   Of the materials, she stressed: ``We have not seen it and we
really have not had a very detailed description at all given to
us.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason the Gore campaign was eager to get the story out in a
hurry was a fear that Gore's current political momentum might
suffer from a perception of any improperly gained advantage. Ronald
Reagan's presidential campaign was criticized in 1980 after it
obtained secret briefing papers on the debate strategy of President
Jimmy Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Those papers, made public in 1983, revealed that Carter planned
to expose Reagan's ``flip-flops'' on various issues when the two
debated on Oct. 28, 1980. Reagan aides said that the information
was mostly conventional wisdom, and Reagan himself said that the
material had simply saved his team the trouble of ``having to go
out and dig up'' widely known information. But Carter aides said
that it had given Reagan a significant advantage.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, when the package arrived at Downey's office, he
happened to be preparing debate materials for Gore. ``It looked
like our debate material,'' Downey said.
</P>
<P>
   Downey said he watched 60 to 90 seconds of the video, and saw
Bush and Sen. Judd Gregg of New Hampshire, who is playing Gore in
the mock debates, and another person he did not know.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at it, and I said, `I shouldn't have this and
shouldn't be looking at this,''' he said. ``I knew that it was
serious stuff. I know what ours looks like.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
